<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. GENERAL PROLOGUE. LANSDOWNE MS. 851. Incipit prologus fabularum Cantuariensium.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE>[Note: after very many final c, e, f, g, k, r, s, t, there is a stroke or a tag. The number is so great, sometimes 6 or 7 in 1 line, that I am obliged to disregard all.]</HEADNOTE>
<MILESTONE N="2a" UNIT="folio">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHan &thorn;at Aprille wy&thorn;e his schoures soote.</L>
<L>&thorn;e drought of Marche ha&thorn;e perced to &thorn;e roote.</L>
<L>And ba&thorn;es euery veyne in suche lycoure.</L>
<L N="4">Of whiche vertue engender is &thorn;e floure.</L>
<L>Whan &yogh;ephirus eke with his swete bre&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Inspired ha&thorn;e in euery holte and hethe.</L>
<L>The tendre croppes and &thorn;e &yogh;onge sonne.</L>
<L N="8">Ha&thorn;e in &thorn;e Ramme his half cours ronne.</L>
<L>And Smal foules maken melodye.</L>
<L>&thorn;at slepen al nyht wi&thorn; open. yhe.</L>
<L>So prikke&thorn; hem nature in her corages.</L>
<L N="12">Than longen folke to gone one pilgrimages.</L>
<L>And palmeres for to seeke straungere strondes.</L>
<L>To ferne halowes cow&thorn;e in sundre londes.</L>
<L>And specialy from euery schyres ende.</L>
<L N="16">Of Ingelonde to Canterburi &thorn;ei wende</L>
<L>The holy blisful Martir for to seke</L>
<L>That hem ha&thorn; holpen whan &thorn;ei were seke</L>
<L>It be-fel &thorn;an in &thorn;at sesone vpon a daie</L>
<L N="20">In Suthewerke att &thorn;e tabard as .I. laie</L>
<L>Redi to wende on my pilgremage.</L>
<L>To Canterburie wi&thorn; ful deuoute Corage.</L>
<L>At nyhte was come in-to &thorn;at hostelleric</L>
<L N="24">Wel Nyne and twente on a companye</L>
<L>Of sondre folke be auenture yfalle</L>
<L>In felauschipe and Pilgrimes were &thorn;ei alle</L>
<L>To-warde Canterburi &thorn;at wolde ride
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="2"></L>
<L N="28">The Chambres and stables weren wyde</L>
<L>And wele weren esede at &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>An schortly whan &thorn;e son was to reste</L>
<L>So had .I. spoken with hem euerychone</L>
<L N="32">&thorn;at .I. was of her felawschep anone</L>
<L>And maade forwarde erly for to rise</L>
<L>To take owre waie &thorn;are as .I. &yogh;owe deuise</L>
<L>Bot na&thorn;eles while .I. haue time and space</L>
<L N="36">Er &thorn;at .I. for&thorn;er in &thorn;is tale pace.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enke&thorn; it accordant to resone</L>
<L>To tell &yogh;owe alle &thorn;e condicione</L>
<L>Of iche of hem so as it semed me</L>
<L N="40">And whiche &thorn;ei were and of whate degre</L>
<L>And eke in whatte araie &thorn;at &thorn;ei were inne</L>
<L>And att a knyhte &thorn;an wold .I. furst be-ginne.</L>
<L>A Knyght &thorn;ere was and &thorn;at a wor&thorn;i manne<MILESTONE N="2b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="44">That fro &thorn;e time &thorn;at he first be-ganne</L>
<L>To ryden owte he loued cheualrie</L>
<L>Treu&thorn;e and honoure fredome and curtesie</L>
<L>fful wor&thorn;i was he in his lordes werre</L>
<L N="48">And &thorn;ar-to had he riden no man so ferre</L>
<L>As wele in Cristendom as in hey&thorn;ennesse</L>
<L>And euere honoured for his wor&thorn;inesse.</L>
<L>Att Alisander he was wh&amacr;n it was wonne</L>
<L N="52">fful oft time he had &thorn;e borde be-gonne</L>
<L>Aboue al nacions in Pruce</L>
<L>In Lettowe had he reysed and in Ruce</L>
<L>No Cristeneman so oft of his degre</L>
<L N="56">In Gernade att &thorn;e sege eke had he be</L>
<L>Of Algezire and riden had in Belmarye</L>
<L>Att Leyes was he and att Satilye</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei were wonne. and in &thorn;e grete see</L>
<L N="60">Att mony a noble Arme had he bee</L>
<L>Att Mortel Batailles had he be fiftene</L>
<L>And fowhten for owre fei&thorn;e att Tramessene.</L>
<L>In listes &thorn;ries and ay sleyne his foo
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="3"></L>
<L N="64">This ilke wor&thorn;i knyhte hade bene also</L>
<L>Some tim wi&thorn;e &thorn;e lorde of Palatye</L>
<L>A&yogh;eine ano&thorn;er hei&thorn;en in Turkye</L>
<L>And euer more he had a souereine prise</L>
<L N="68">And &thorn;oughe &thorn;at he was wor&thorn;i he was wise</L>
<L>And of his porte as meke as is a maide</L>
<L>He neuer &yogh;it no velany seide</L>
<L>In al his life til no maner wyght</L>
<L N="72">He was a verrey perfite gentil knyht</L>
<L>ffor to tel &yogh;owe of his araye</L>
<L>His hors was goode bot he was nouhte gaye</L>
<L>Off ffustion he werede a Gepon</L>
<L N="76">All be-smoterde wi&thorn; his haburgen.</L>
<L>ffor he was late come fro his viage</L>
<L>And went for to done his Pilgrimage</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hime &thorn;are was his sonne a &yogh;onge swiere</L>
<L N="80">A louyer and a lusti bachellere</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; lokkes crulle as &thorn;ei were leide in presse</L>
<L>Of .xx. &yogh;eres of age he was .I. gesse.</L>
<L>Of his stature he was of euen lenge&thorn;e</L>
<L N="84">And wonderly deliuer. and grete of strenke&thorn;e</L>
<L>And he had be sume time in cheualrie<MILESTONE N="3a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In fflandres in Artoys and in Pykardie</L>
<L>And borne him wele as of so litel space</L>
<L N="88">In hope to stonden in his lady grace</L>
<L>Embrowded was he as it were a mede</L>
<L>Al ful of frissche flowres white and rede</L>
<L>Singeinge he was or flowteinge al &thorn;e daie</L>
<L N="92">He was al so fresche as is &thorn;e mone&thorn; of maie.</L>
<L>Schort was his goune with sleues longe and wide</L>
<L>Wele cou&thorn;e he sitte on an horse and faire ride</L>
<L>He cou&thorn;e songes make and wele endite</L>
<L N="96">Iuste and eke daunce and wele purtreie and write</L>
<L>So hote he loued &thorn;at be nyghter tale</L>
<L>He slepete no more &thorn;an do&thorn;e &thorn;e nyhtegale</L>
<L>Corteis he was lowly and seruisable
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="4"></L>
<L N="100">And karf to-for his fader att &thorn;e table</L>
<L>A &yogh;oman had he and seruantes no moo</L>
<L>Att &thorn;at time for him liste ride soo</L>
<L>And he was cladde in cote and hoode of grene</L>
<L N="104">A scheef of pokoke arwes briht and kene</L>
<L>Vnder his belte he bare ful &thorn;reftelie</L>
<L>Wele cou&thorn;e he drese his takel &yogh;emonlie</L>
<L>His arwes drouped nouht wi&thorn; fe&thorn;eres lowe</L>
<L N="108">And in his honde he bare a myhti bowe</L>
<L>A notte hede had he wi&thorn; a broune visage</L>
<L>Of wodecraft wele cou&thorn;e he al &thorn;e vsage</L>
<L>Vpon his arme he bare a gaie brasere</L>
<L N="112">And be his side a swerde and a bokelere</L>
<L>And on &thorn;at o&thorn;ere side a gaie daggere.</L>
<L>Herneyste wele and scharpe as &thorn;e pointe of a spere.</L>
<L>A christofur on his breste of siluer schene.</L>
<L N="116">An horne he bare &thorn;e bawdrik was of grene</L>
<L>A forster was he so&thorn;elye as .I. gesse.</L>
<L>&para; Thare was also a Nonne a Prioresse</L>
<L>That of hir smyleynge was ful simple and coye</L>
<L N="120">Her grettest o&thorn;e was bot be seint Loye.</L>
<L>And sche was cleped Madame Englentyne</L>
<L>fful wele sche songe &thorn;e seruise deuine</L>
<L>Entuned in hir nose ful semely.</L>
<L N="124">And franche sche spake ful faire and fetisly</L>
<L>After &thorn;e scole att Stretford att Bowe</L>
<L>ffor frenche of Paris was to hire vnknowe</L>
<L>Att mete wele ytauhte was sche with-all<MILESTONE N="3b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="128">Sche lete no morsel fro hir lippes fall</L>
<L>Ne wete hir fingeres in hir sauce depe</L>
<L>Wele cou&thorn;e sche cary a morsel and wel kepe</L>
<L>&thorn;at no drope ne fel vpon hir breste</L>
<L N="132">In curtesie was sette ful muchel her leste</L>
<L>Hir ouere-lippe sche wyped so clene</L>
<L>That in hir coppe &thorn;er was no fat &thorn;inge sene</L>
<L>Of grece whan sche had dronken hir drawhte
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="5"></L>
<L N="136">fful semelye after hir mete sche rawhte.</L>
<L>And sekerly sche was of grete disporte.</L>
<L>And ful plesant and ful amyable of porte</L>
<L>And peyned hir to counterfet chere</L>
<L N="140">Of Courte and to be stalyche of Manere</L>
<L>And to be holden digne of reuerence</L>
<L>Bot for to speke of hire Conscience</L>
<L>Sche was so charitable and so pytous.</L>
<L N="144">Sche wolde wepe &yogh;if &thorn;at sche sawe a mouse</L>
<L>Kauht in a trape if it ware dede or bledde</L>
<L>Of smale houndes had sche &thorn;at sche fedde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; rostede flesche or melke or wastel brede</L>
<L N="148">Bot sore wepped sche if one of hem were dede</L>
<L>Or if men smote it wi&thorn; a &yogh;erde smart</L>
<L>And al was conscience and tendur herte</L>
<L>fful semely hir wympul pinched was</L>
<L N="152">Hire nose was streihte her yhen was grei as glas</L>
<L>Hire mou&thorn;e ful smal. and &thorn;ere-to soft and rede</L>
<L>Bot sekurly sche had a faire forhede</L>
<L>It was al-moste a spanne brode .I. trowe</L>
<L N="156">ffor hardely sche was nouhte vnder growe</L>
<L>fful fetis was hir cloke as .I. was war</L>
<L>Of smale coral aboute hir harme sche bar</L>
<L>A peire of Bedes gauded al wi&thorn; grene</L>
<L N="160">And &thorn;ere-one honge a broche of golde ful schene</L>
<L>On whiche &thorn;are was firste wreten wi&thorn; a crowned .A.</L>
<L>And After Amor vincit omnia.</L>
<L>&para; A no&thorn;er nonne wy&thorn; hir had sche</L>
<L N="164">&thorn;at was hir Chapeleyne and prestes &thorn;re</L>
<L>A monke &thorn;ere was a faire for &thorn;e maistre</L>
<L>An owte-rider &thorn;at loued venere</L>
<L>A manly man to bene an Abbot Able</L>
<L N="168">fful mony a daynte hors hade he in stable</L>
<L>And whanne he rode men myht his bridele here<MILESTONE N="4a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Gyngelinge in a whistelinge wynde al so clere</L>
<L>And eke as lowde as do&thorn;e &thorn;e chapel belle
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="6"></L>
<L N="172">There as &thorn;is lorde was keper of &thorn;e selle</L>
<L>The rewle of seint Maure or of seint Beneyte</L>
<L>Be cause &thorn;at it was olde and somdele streyte</L>
<L>This ilke monke lete olde &thorn;inges pace</L>
<L N="176">And helde after &thorn;e newe werde &thorn;e pace</L>
<L>He &yogh;af nouht of &thorn;e text a pulled henne</L>
<L>&thorn;at sei&thorn;e &thorn;at hunteres be&thorn;e nouht holy menne</L>
<L>Ne that a monke whan he is recheles</L>
<L N="180">Is likkened til a fische &thorn;at is waterles.</L>
<L>That is to seie A monke oute of his cloistre</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ilke text held he nouht wor&thorn;e an hoistre</L>
<L>And .I. seide his opinione was goode</L>
<L N="184">Whatt scholde he stodie and make him selfe wode</L>
<L>Vpon a boke in cloister al-weie to powre</L>
<L>Or swynke wi&thorn; his hondes and laboure</L>
<L>As Austine bite howe schal &thorn;e werld be serued</L>
<L N="188">Latte Austine haue his swynke to him rese[r]ued</L>
<L>Thare-for he was a prikasoure a right</L>
<L>Grehoundes he had as swift as foules in flyht</L>
<L>Of Prikinge and of huntynge for &thorn;e hare.</L>
<L N="192">Was al his lust for no cost wolde he spare.</L>
<L>.I. seighe his sleues purfiled att &thorn;e honde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Gryse and &thorn;at &thorn;e fynest of a londe</L>
<L>And for to festen &thorn;e hode vnder his chynne</L>
<L N="196">He had of golde wrought a ful coriouse pinne</L>
<L>A loue knotte on &thorn;e gretter hende &thorn;ere was</L>
<L>His hede was balled &thorn;at schone as any glas</L>
<L>And eke his face as he had be anoynte</L>
<L N="200">He was a lorde ful fatte and in goode pointe.</L>
<L>His yhen stepe and rollinge in his hede</L>
<L>That stemed as a furneis of a lede</L>
<L>His botes souple his hors in grete astate</L>
<L N="204">Nowe certeynely he was a faire prelate.</L>
<L>He nas nouht pale as a forpyned goste</L>
<L>A fatte swanne loued he best of any roste</L>
<L>His Palfrei was as broune as is a burye
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="7"></L>
<L N="208">&para; A frere &thorn;are was a wanton and murye.</L>
<L>A lymitur a ful solempne manne</L>
<L>In all &thorn;e orderes foure is none &thorn;at canne.</L>
<L>So muche of daliance and faire langage<MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="212">He had maade ful mony a mariage.</L>
<L>Of &yogh;onge wemmen att his owen cost</L>
<L>Vn-to his order he was a nobel post</L>
<L>fful wele be-loued and famulier was he.</L>
<L N="216">With frankeleyns ouer al in his contre.</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; wor&thorn;e wemmen of &thorn;e toune</L>
<L>ffor he had power of confessione</L>
<L>As seide him selfe more &thorn;an a curate</L>
<L N="220">ffor [of] his order he was licenciate</L>
<L>fful swetely herde he confessi&omacr;n</L>
<L>And plesant was his absoluci&omacr;n.</L>
<L>He was an hesy man to &yogh;ef pen&amacr;nce</L>
<L N="224">Ther as he wiste to haue a goode pet&amacr;nce</L>
<L>ffor vn-to a poure order for to &yogh;eue</L>
<L>Is singne &thorn;at a man is wel yschriue</L>
<L>ffor if he &yogh;af he dorst make avaunt</L>
<L N="228">He wist &thorn;at a man was repentaunt</L>
<L>ffor mony a man so harde is of his herte</L>
<L>He maie nouht wepe al &thorn;ouhe he sore smerte</L>
<L>There-for in stede of wepeynge and preyeres</L>
<L N="232">Men mote &yogh;iue siluer to &thorn;e poure freres</L>
<L>His tepet was ay farset ful of knyues</L>
<L>And pinnes for to &yogh;eue faire wyues</L>
<L>And certeinli he had a mery note</L>
<L N="236">Wele cou&thorn;e he singen and pleine on a rote</L>
<L>Of &yogh;eddinges he bare witterli &thorn;e pris</L>
<L>His neke white was as &thorn;e floure delis</L>
<L>Ther-to he was also stronge as a champioune</L>
<L N="240">He knewe &thorn;e tauernes wele in euery towne.</L>
<L>And eueryche hosteler or a tapestere</L>
<L>Better &thorn;an a la&yogh;ar or a Begger</L>
<L>ffor vn-to suche a wor&thorn;i man as he
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="8"></L>
<L N="244">Accorded nouht as be his faculte</L>
<L>To haue wi&thorn; suche seke lazerz acquayntance</L>
<L>It is nouht honest it maie nouht avaunce</L>
<L>ffor to dele wi&thorn; suche poraile</L>
<L N="248">Bot al wi&thorn; riche and seller of vitaile</L>
<L>And ouere al &thorn;are as profet schold arise</L>
<L>Curteise he was and lowly of seruyse</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas no man noghwere so vertuous</L>
<L N="252">He was &thorn;e best begger in his hous</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inter">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ouhe a widowe had nouht a scho<MILESTONE N="5a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So plesande was his in principio.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it wolde he haue a fer&thorn;inge ar he wente</L>
<L N="256">His purchas was wel better &thorn;an his rent</L>
<L>And rage he cou&thorn;e riht as it were a whelpe</L>
<L>In louedaies &thorn;are cou&thorn;e he muchel helpe</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ere he was not liche a cloistrere</L>
<L N="260">Wi&thorn; a &thorn;rede-bare cope as a pouer scolere</L>
<L>Bot he was lyke a Maistre or a Pope</L>
<L>Of dowble worstede was his semy-cope</L>
<L>&THORN;at rounde as a bell out &thorn;e presse</L>
<L N="264">Somwhat he lisped for his wantonesse</L>
<L>To make his yngelische swete vpon his tonge</L>
<L>And in his harpeinge whan he had songe</L>
<L>His yhen twynkeled in his heued ariht</L>
<L N="268">As do&thorn;e &thorn;e sterres in &thorn;e froste nyht</L>
<L>This wor&thorn;e Limetour was cleped Huberd</L>
<L>&para; A marchant was &thorn;ere with a forked berde</L>
<L>In motteley. and hye on hors he satte</L>
<L N="272">Vpon his heued a fflaundrisshe beuere hatte</L>
<L>His botes clasped faire and fetislye</L>
<L>His resons he spake ful solemplye</L>
<L>Scheweynge alwey &thorn;encres of his wynynge</L>
<L N="276">He wolde &thorn;e se were keppede for any &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Be-twyx Middelburgh. and Orewelle
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="9"></L>
