<L>In &yogh;ow&thorn;e he had lerned a good mistere</L>
<L>He was a wel goode wriht a carpentere</L>
<L>This satt vpon a fol goode stot</L>
<L N="616">That was a pomely greye and hihte Scot</L>
<L>A longe surcote of peers vpon he hadde</L>
<L>And be his side he bare a rusti blade</L>
<L>Of Nor&thorn;efolk was &thorn;is reue whiche .I. tell</L>
<L N="620">Be-siden a towne men clepen it baldeswell</L>
<L>Tukked he was as is a frere abowte</L>
<L>And euere he rode hinderest of owre Rowte</L>
<L>&para; A Somynour was &thorn;er wi&thorn; vs in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="624">&THORN;at had a firy Cherubynnes face</L>
<L>ffor sausefleme he was with yhen narowe</L>
<L>Als hote he was and licherous as a sparowe</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; scalled browes blake and a pilled berde</L>
<L N="628">Of his vesage childerne were aferde</L>
<L>Ther nas whike-siluer litarge or bremstone</L>
<L>Boras orsure ne oyle of tartre none</L>
<L>Ne oyment &thorn;at wolde clense and bite<MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="632">That him myht helpe of his whelkes white</L>
<L>Nere of &thorn;e knobbes sittinge in his chekes</L>
<L>Wele loued he garlike onyons and &yogh;ite lekes</L>
<L>And for to drinke stronge wyne rede as blode</L>
<L N="636">Than wold he speke and crie as he ware wode</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he wele drongen had &thorn;e wyne
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="19"></L>
<L>&thorn;an wold he speke no worde bot latyne</L>
<L>A fewe terems had he two or thre</L>
<L N="640">That he had lerned owte of sum decre</L>
<L>No wonder is he herd it al &thorn;e daie</L>
<L>And eke &yogh;e knowen it wele howe &thorn;at a Iaie</L>
<L>Kan clepe watt as wele as kan &thorn;e pope</L>
<L N="644">Bot who so cou&thorn;e in o&thorn;er &thorn;inge him grope</L>
<L>&THORN;an had he spent al his philosophie</L>
<L>Ay Questio quid Iuris wold he crie</L>
<L>He was a gentil harlot and a kynde</L>
<L N="648">A better felawe scholde men nouht finde</L>
<L>He wolde suffer for a whart of wyne</L>
<L>A good felaw to haue his concubyne</L>
<L>A twelmou&thorn;e and excuse him att fulle</L>
<L N="652">And priuely eke a finche cou&thorn;e he pulle</L>
<L>And. if he fonde owhere a goode felawe</L>
<L>He wolde techen him to haue none awe</L>
<L>In suche cas of &thorn;e Archedekenes Curse</L>
<L N="656">Bot if [a] mannes soule were in his purse</L>
<L>ffor in his purs he scholde punyschede be</L>
<L>The purse es &thorn;e Archedekenes hell seide he</L>
<L>Bot wele .I. wote he lyede riht in dede</L>
<L N="660">Of curssinge owht yche gilty man him drede</L>
<L>ffor curs wil sle riht as a-soyleynge sauy&thorn;e</L>
<L>And also war him of a significauit</L>
<L>In dawngere had he att his owen gise</L>
<L N="664">The &yogh;onge girles of &thorn;e diocise</L>
<L>And knewe her consel and what was al here rede</L>
<L>A garland had he sett vpon his hede</L>
<L>As grete as it were for an Alestake</L>
<L N="668">A bokelere had he made him of a kake</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn;e him &thorn;ere rode a gentil pardonere</L>
<L>Of Rouncyual his frende and his comper</L>
<L>&thorn;at streyhte was comme fro &thorn;e courte of Rome</L>
<L N="672">fful loude he songe come hider loue to me.</L>
<L>This Somenoure bare to him a stif burdoune<MILESTONE N="10a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>Was neuer trompe of halfe so grete a soune</L>
<L>This pardonere had here as &yogh;alowe as wax.</L>
<L N="676">Bot smothe it henge as do&thorn; a strike of flax.</L>
<L>Bi ounces henge his lokkes &thorn;at he hadde</L>
<L>And &thorn;er wi&thorn; he his scholdres ouer spradde</L>
<L>But &thorn;inne it leie be culpones one and one</L>
<L N="680">But hode for Iolyte wered he none</L>
<L>ffor it was trussed vp in his walet</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ouht he rode al of &thorn;e newe get</L>
<L>Discheuele saue his cape he rode al bare</L>
<L N="684">Suche glayringe yhen had he as it were an hare</L>
<L>A vernicle had he sewe vpon his cape</L>
<L>His walet [lay] to forne him in his lappe</L>
<L>Bret ful of pardon comen from Rome al hote</L>
<L N="688">A voyce he had also smale as it were a gote</L>
<L>No berde had he ne neuer schuld haue</L>
<L>As smo&thorn;e it was as it were late schaue</L>
<L>.I. trowe he were a geldinge or a mare</L>
<L N="692">Bot of his craft fro Berwike in to ware</L>
<L>Ne was &thorn;ere suche ano&thorn;er pardonere</L>
<L>ffor in his male he hadde a pylowbere</L>
<L>Whiche that he seide was owre lady veyle</L>
<L N="696">He seide he had a gobet of &thorn;e seile</L>
<L>That seint Peter had whan &thorn;at he wente</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e see till ihesu crist him hente</L>
<L>He had a croyce of Laton ful of stones</L>
<L N="700">And in a glasse he hadde Pygges bones</L>
<L>Bot wi&thorn;e &thorn;es relikes whan &thorn;at he fonde</L>
<L>A pouer person dwellynge vpon londe</L>
<L>Vppon a daie he gat him more moneye</L>
<L N="704">Than &thorn;at &thorn;e person gatte in &thorn;e Monethes tweye</L>
<L>And &thorn;us wi&thorn; feyned flaterynge and Iapes</L>
<L>He Maade &thorn;e persone and &thorn;e peple his Apes</L>
<L>Bot trewly to tellen att &thorn;e laste</L>
<L N="708">He was in &thorn;e cherche a noble ecclesiaste</L>
<L>Wele cou&thorn;e he rede a lesson or a story
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>Bot al&thorn;er best he songe a offertory</L>
<L>fful wele he wist whan &thorn;at songe was songe</L>
<L N="712">He moste preche and wele affile his tonge</L>
<L>To wynne siluer as he wele cowde</L>
<L>&THORN;ere-fore he songe so merely and loude</L>
<L>&para; Nowe haue .I. tolde &yogh;owe so&thorn;ely in a clause<MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="716">The estate. &thorn;e arraye. &thorn;e Nombre and eke &thorn;e cause</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;at assembled was &thorn;is companye</L>
<L>In Suthewerke att &thorn;is gentil Hosterie</L>
<L>&thorn;at hiht &thorn;e taberd fast be &thorn;e belle</L>
<L N="720">Bot nowe is time to &yogh;owe for to telle</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at we beren vs &thorn;at ilke nyhte</L>
<L>Whan we were in &thorn;at Osterye alyhte</L>
<L>And after wil .I. tell of owre viage</L>
<L N="724">And al &thorn;e remenant of owre pilgrenage</L>
<L>Bot first .I. preye &yogh;owe of &yogh;oure curtesie</L>
<L>That &yogh;e ne ret it nowht my velenye</L>
<L>Thoughe &thorn;at .I. pleinly speke in &thorn;is matier</L>
<L N="728">To telle &yogh;owe her wordes and eke her chere</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ouhe .I. speke here wordes propurly</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is &yogh;e knowen as wele as .I.</L>
<L>Who so sal tellen a tale after a m&amacr;n</L>
<L N="732">He mote reherce as nyhe as euer he c&amacr;n</L>
<L>Eueryche a worde if it be in his charge</L>
<L>Al speke he neuer so rudeli and so large.</L>
<L>Or elles he most tel his tale vntrewe</L>
<L N="736">Or feyne &thorn;inges. or fynde wordes Newe</L>
<L>He may nouht spare al-&thorn;ouhe he ware his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>He mot also wele seie o worde as a-nother</L>
<L>Criste spak him self ful brode in holy writte</L>
<L N="740">And wele &yogh;e wote no velany is itte</L>
<L>Eke plato sei&thorn;e who so kan him rede</L>
<L>The wordes most be Cosin to &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>&para; Also .I. preie &yogh;owe for-&yogh;if it me</L>
<L N="744">Al haue .I. not sett folke in her degre</L>
<L>Here in &thorn;is tale as &thorn;at &thorn;ei scholde stonde
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="22"></L>
<L>My witte is schorte &yogh;e maie wele vnderstonde</L>
<L>Grete chere maade owre oste vs euerychone</L>
<L N="748">And to &thorn;e soper sett he vs anone</L>
<L>He serued vs wi&thorn;e vitailles att &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>Stronge was &thorn;e wyne and wele drinke vs leste</L>
<L>A semely man owre ost was wi&thorn; all</L>
<L N="752">ffor to bene a marschal in a lordes hall</L>
<L>A large man he was wi&thorn; ey&yogh;en stepe</L>
<L>A fairer burgeis is none none in chepe</L>
<L>Bolde of his speche and wyse and wele y-tawht</L>
<L N="756">And of manhode him lakked riht nouht</L>
<L>Eke &thorn;ere-to he was riht a mery man<MILESTONE N="11a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And after soper pley&yogh;en he be-gan</L>
<L>And spak of Mir&thorn;e amonge o&thorn;ere &thorn;inges</L>
<L N="760">Whan &thorn;at we had maade owre rekenynges</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;us Now lordeynges trewly</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bene to me welcome riht hertly</L>
<L>ffor be my trou&thorn;e if &thorn;at .I. schal notte lye</L>
<L N="764">.I. sawe nouht &thorn;is &yogh;ere so mery a companye</L>
<L>Att ones in &thorn;is herburhe as is nowe</L>
<L>ffayne wolde .I. done &yogh;owe mer&thorn;e wist .I. howe</L>
<L>And of a mer&thorn;e .I. am riht nowe be-&thorn;ouhte</L>
<L N="768">To done &yogh;owe ese and it schal cost nowhte</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;e gone to Canterbury god &yogh;owe spede</L>
<L>The blisful Martir white &yogh;ow &yogh;owre mede</L>
<L>And wele .I. wote as &yogh;e gone be &thorn;e weye</L>
<L N="772">Sche schapen &yogh;owe to talen and to pleye</L>
<L>ffor trewly comfor&thorn;e and mer&thorn;e is none</L>
<L>To riden be &thorn;e waie dom as any stone</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-for wil .I. maken &yogh;owe disporte</L>
<L N="776">As .I. seide arst and do &yogh;ow som comforte</L>
<L>And if &yogh;owe like&thorn; all be on assente</L>
<L>ffor to stonden at My Iuggemente</L>
<L>And for to werken as .I. schal &yogh;owe seie</L>
<L N="780">To morwen whan we riden be &thorn;e weie</L>
<L>Nowe be Mi fader sow[l]e &thorn;at is dede
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>But &yogh;e bue Merie .I. &yogh;eue &yogh;owe Mine hede</L>
<L>Holde vpe &yogh;owre hondes wi&thorn;-owte more speche</L>
<L N="784">&para; Owre consell was not longe for to seche</L>
<L>Vs &thorn;ouhte it was not wor&thorn;e to make it wise</L>
<L>And graunted him wi&thorn;-oute more avise</L>
<L>And bad him seie his verdite as him liste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="788">Lordynges quod he now herkene&thorn; for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>Bot tak it nowhte .I. pray &yogh;owe in disdeyne</L>
<L>This is &thorn;e pointe to speke schort and pleine</L>
<L>That iche of &yogh;owe to schort wi&thorn; owre weie</L>
<L N="792">In &thorn;is viage schal tel tales tweye</L>
<L>To Kanterbury warde .I. mene it so</L>
<L>And homward he schal tellen o&thorn;ere two</L>
<L>Of aventures whilome &thorn;at hane be-fall</L>
<L N="796">And whiche of &yogh;owe &thorn;at bere&thorn; him best of all</L>
<L>That is to seyne &thorn;at telle&thorn; in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>Tales of best sentence. and most solas</L>
<L>Schall haue a soper at owre aller cost<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="800">Here in &thorn;is place sittinge be &thorn;e post</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at we comen a-geine fro Canturbury</L>
<L>And for to make &yogh;ow &thorn;e more mery</L>
<L>.I. wil my seluen goodely wi&thorn; &yogh;ow ride</L>
<L N="804">Riht att myne oune coste and be &yogh;owre gide</L>
<L>And who so wil my Iuggement wi&thorn;-seie</L>
<L>Schal paie al &thorn;at we spende be &thorn;e weie</L>
<L>And if &yogh;e vouche saue &thorn;at it be so</L>
<L N="808">Tel me anone wi&thorn;-owten wordes mo</L>
<L>And .I. wil erly schape me &thorn;ere-fore</L>
<L>&para; This &thorn;inge was graunted and owre o&thorn;es swore</L>
<L>With ful glad hert and praieyng him also</L>
<L N="812">&thorn;at he wolde vouche saue for to do so</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he wolde be owre gouernowre</L>
<L>And of owre tales Iugge and reporture</L>
<L>And sett a soper att a serteine pris</L>
<L N="816">And we wil rewled bene att his deuis</L>
<L>In hihe and in lowhe and &thorn;us be one assent
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>We bene accorded to &thorn;e Iuggement</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-vpon &thorn;e wyne was fett anone</L>
<L N="820">We dronken and to rest went ichone</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-owten any longer taryinge</L>
<L>An morwe whan &thorn;e daie gan to springe</L>
<L>Vp roos owre ost and was owre alder cok</L>
<L N="824">And gederd vs to-geder in a floke</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e we reden a litel mor &thorn;an pas</L>
<L>Vnto [&thorn;e] wateringe of seint Thomas</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere owre oste gan his hors areste</L>
<L N="828">And seide lordes herkene&thorn; if &yogh;owe leste</L>
<L>&YOGH;e wote &yogh;owre forward. and .I. it &yogh;owe recorde</L>
<L>If &thorn;at Euynsonge. and Morwsonge accorde</L>
<L>Lat se nowe who schal tel &thorn;e first tale</L>
<L N="832">As euer mot .I. drinke wine or ale</L>
<L>Who so be rebel to my Iuggement</L>
<L>Schal paie for al &thorn;at be &thorn;e waie is spent</L>
<L>Now drawe&thorn; cut or &thorn;at we fer&thorn;er wynne</L>
<L N="836">Whiche &thorn;at ha&thorn;e &thorn;e schortest schal be-ginne</L>
<L>&para; Sir knyht quod he my maister and my lorde</L>
<L>Now drawe&thorn; Cut for &thorn;at is Myne accorde</L>
<L>Comme&thorn; nere quod he Mi ladi prioresse</L>
<L N="840">And &yogh;e sire clerke lat be &yogh;owre schamefastnesse</L>
<L>Ne studiethe nowht leie honde to euery man<MILESTONE N="12a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Anone to drawe euery wight began</L>
<L>And schortly for to tellen riht as it was</L>
<L N="844">Were it be aventure or sort or cas</L>
<L>The so&thorn;e is &thorn;is &thorn;e Cut fel on &thorn;e knyht</L>
<L>Of whiche ful bli&thorn;e and glad was euery whit</L>
<L>And tellen he most his tale as it was res&omacr;n</L>
<L N="848">Bi forward and be composici&omacr;n.</L>
<L>As &yogh;e haue herde what nede&thorn; wordes moo</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is good man sawhe &thorn;at it was so</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at wise was and obedient</L>
<L N="852">To kepen his forward be his fre assent</L>
<L>He seide se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;at .I. schal beginne &thorn;e game
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>What welcome be &thorn;e cut one goddes name</L>
<L>Now lat vs ride and herkene&thorn; what .I. seie</L>
<L N="856">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde we riden for&thorn;e owre weie</L>
<L>And he be-gan wi&thorn; riht a mery chere</L>
<L>His tale anone and seide as &yogh;e mai here<NOTE PLACE="end">No gap in the MS.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000054.tif" N="26">
<EPIGRAPH><Q>Iam que domos patrias scitice post aspera gentis Prelia Laurigero, &amp;c.</Q></EPIGRAPH>
<HEAD> Incipit fabula Militis</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="859">Whilome was as holde stories tellen vs</L>
<L>There was a Duke<NOTE PLACE="marg">Boccaccio calls <I>Teseo</I> 'duca di Atene' (I. 13), and says that his father <I>Egeo</I> was 're d'Atene' (I. 6).</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Athenes he was lorde and gouernoure</L>
<L>And in his time suche a conqueroure</L>
<L>That gretter was none vndere &thorn;e sonne</L>
<L N="864">fful Mony a riche Contre had he wonne.</L>
<L>What wi&thorn; wisdome and his Chiualrie<NOTE PLACE="marg">Books I-II.</NOTE></L>
<L>He conquered al &thorn;e Regne of ffemynye.</L>
<L>That whilom cleped was Scithia</L>
<L N="868">And wedded &thorn;e qwene ypolita</L>
<L>An browht hire home wi&thorn;e him in to his contre</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; muche glorie and grete solempnite</L>
<L>And eke hire &yogh;onge sustere Emelye</L>
<L N="872">And &thorn;us wi&thorn; victori and melodie</L>
<L>Latt .I. &thorn;is nobul Duc to Athenes ride</L>
<L>And all his hoste in aremes be his side</L>
<L>And certes if it nere to longe to here</L>
<L N="876">.I. wold haue told fully &thorn;e manere</L>
<L>How wonnen was &thorn;e Reigne of ffemynye</L>
<L>By Theus and be his Chiualrrye</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e grete Bataile for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L N="880">Be-twixen Athenes and Ama&yogh;ones</L>
<L>And how asseged was ypolyta<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The faire hardie quene of Scithia</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e fest &thorn;at was att hir weddeynge</L>
<L N="884">And of &thorn;e tempest at hire home comynge.</L>
<L>Bot al &thorn;at &thorn;inge .I. mot at nowe for-bere</L>
<L>.I. haue gode wote a large felde to ere</L>
<L>And weike bene &thorn;e Oxen in my plouhe</L>
<L N="888">The remenant of &thorn;e tale is longe y-nouhe</L>
<L>I. wil not letten eke none of &thorn;is route
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>Latt euery felawe tel his tale aboute</L>
<L>And latt see nowe who schal &thorn;e soper winne</L>
<L N="892">And &thorn;ere .I. laft .I. wil a&yogh;eine beginne</L>
<L>&para; This Duc of whome .I. make mensioune<NOTE PLACE="marg">II. 2-5.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan he was comen al-most to &thorn;e toune</L>
<L>In all his wele and his most pride</L>
<L N="896">He was ware as he kast his yhe a side</L>
<L>Where &thorn;at &thorn;ere kneled in &thorn;e hihe waie</L>
<L>A company of ladyes twey. and twaie</L>
<L>Iche after o&thorn;er cladde in clo&thorn;es blake</L>
<L N="900">Bot suche a crye and suche a woo &thorn;ei make</L>
<L>That in &thorn;is werlde is creature lyueynge</L>
<L>&thorn;at herd suche a no&thorn;er weymentynge</L>
<L>And of &thorn;is crie &thorn;ei nolde neuer stenten<NOTE PLACE="marg">II. 25. (before the car.)</NOTE></L>
<L N="904">Till &thorn;ei &thorn;e reynes of his bridel henten</L>
<L>What folke bene &yogh;e &thorn;at att myne home comynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">II. 26.</NOTE></L>
<L>Perturbe so my fest with cryinge</L>
<L>Quod Theus haue &yogh;e so grete envie.</L>
<L N="908">Of myne honour &thorn;at &thorn;us compleigne and crie</L>
<L>Or who ha&thorn; &yogh;ow mysboden or offended</L>
<L>And telle&thorn; me if it maie bene amended</L>
<L>And whi &thorn;at &yogh;e bene clo&thorn;ed &thorn;us in blake</L>
<L N="912">The eldest lady of hem al spake</L>
<L>Whan sche had swowned wi&thorn; a dedely chere</L>
<L>That it was rew&thorn;e for to seen and here</L>
<L>&para; Sche seide lorde to whome ffortune ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen</L>
<L N="916">Victorie and as a conqueroure to lyuen</L>
