<L>A worthi Duc &thorn;at hiht. Perotheus<NOTE PLACE="marg">III. 47.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1192">That felowe was vn-to Duc Theseus</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;ilke daie &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren childern lite</L>
<L>Was commen to Athenes his felawe to visite</L>
<L>And for to pleie as he was wont to do</L>
<L N="1196">ffor in &thorn;is werlde he louede no man so</L>
<L>And he loue him also as tendrely a-&yogh;eine</L>
<L>So wele &thorn;ey loued as olde bokes seine</L>
<L>That whanne &thorn;at one was dede sothely to tell</L>
<L N="1200">His felaw went and sowht him downe in hell</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;at stori leste me nouht to write</L>
<L>Duc Perotheus louede wel Arcite<NOTE PLACE="marg">III. 51-4</NOTE></L>
<L>And him knowe att Thebes &yogh;ere be &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="1204">And ffinally . att request . and prayere</L>
<L>Of Perotheus wi&thorn;-owten any Raunson.</L>
<L>Duc Theseus him lete owte of prison</L>
<L>ffrely to gone where &thorn;at him list ouer all</L>
<L N="1208">In suche a gise as .I. &yogh;owe telle schall</L>
<L>This was &thorn;e forward pleinly to endite</L>
<L>Be-twex Theseus and him Arcite</L>
<L>That if so were &thorn;at Arcite was fownde</L>
<L N="1212">Euere in his lif be daie or nyht or stownde</L>
<L>In any Contre of &thorn;is Theseus
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="36"></L>
<L>And war cauht it was accorded &thorn;us</L>
<L>That wi&thorn;e a swerde he scholde lese his hede<NOTE PLACE="marg">III. 54.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1216">Ther nas none o&thorn;ere remedye ne rede</L>
<L>Bot take&thorn;e his leue and homwarde he him spedde</L>
<L>Lat him be war his nek li&thorn;e to wedde</L>
<L>How grete a sorwe suffur&thorn;e nowe arcite<MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1220">The de&thorn;e he fele&thorn; &thorn;oruhe his hert smite</L>
<L>He wepe&thorn;e he weyle&thorn; and crie&thorn; pitously</L>
<L>To slene him self he waite&thorn; priuely</L>
<L>He seide alas &thorn;at .I. was borne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Gen. resembl. See III. 75, &amp;c.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1224">Nowe is my prison werse &thorn;an be-forne</L>
<L>Nowe is me schape eternalie to dwelle</L>
<L>Nouht in purgatorie Bot in helle</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;at euer .I. knewe Perotheus</L>
<L N="1228">ffor elles had .I. dwelled wi&thorn; Theseus</L>
<L>Ifetterd in his prison euer mo</L>
<L>Than had .I. bene in blisse and nowht in woo</L>
<L>Onely &thorn;e siht of hire whome &thorn;at .I. serue</L>
<L N="1232">Thouhe &thorn;at .I. neuere hir grace miht deserue</L>
<L>Wholde haue ysuffised riht .I.-nowhe for me</L>
<L>&para; O dere Cosine Palamon quod he</L>
<L>Thine is &thorn;e victorie of &thorn;is auenture</L>
<L N="1236">fful blisfully in pris&omacr;n mayght &thorn;ou dure</L>
<L>In prison sertes naye bot Paradise</L>
<L>Wele ha&thorn; fortune turned &thorn;e dise</L>
<L>That ha&thorn;e &thorn;e siht of hire and .I. &thorn;e absence</L>
<L N="1240">ffor possible is se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou hast hir presence</L>
<L>And art a kny[ght] a wor&thorn;i and an able</L>
<L>That be som caas fortune is chaungeable</L>
<L>Thou maiste to &thorn;i desire somtime ateigne</L>
<L N="1244">Bot .I. &thorn;at am exiled and bareigne</L>
<L>Of al grace and in so grete dispeire</L>
<L>That &thorn;er nys er&thorn;e water fire ne ayre</L>
<L>Ne creature &thorn;at of hem Maked is</L>
<L N="1248">That may me helpe ne do me comford in &thorn;is</L>
<L>Wele owht .I. sterue In wanhope and distris
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="37"></L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">line out: no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alas why pleine men so in Comune</L>
<L N="1252">On purueance of god or of fortune</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;eue&thorn;e hem ful of in many a gise</L>
<L>Wele bet &thorn;an &thorn;ei can hem self deuise</L>
<L>Som man desire&thorn; for to haue richesse</L>
<L N="1256">&thorn;at cause is of his mordre or grete sekenesse</L>
<L>And som man wolde owte of his prison fayne</L>
<L>That in his house is of his meine sleyne.</L>
<L>Infinite harmes bene in &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L N="1260">We wote nowht what &thorn;inge we praien hiere</L>
<L>We faren as he &thorn;at dronken is as a mouse</L>
<L>A dronken man wote wele he ha&thorn;e an house</L>
<L>Bot he note whiche &thorn;e riht waie is &thorn;edere<MILESTONE N="17a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1264">And to a dronken man &thorn;e waie is scle&thorn;ere</L>
<L>And certes in &thorn;is werlde so faren we</L>
<L>We seken fast after felicite.</L>
<L>Bot we gone wronge oft ful trewli</L>
<L N="1268">Thus maie we seine all and namelyche .I.</L>
<L>That wende and had a grete opinione</L>
<L>That if .I. myht scippe fro prisone</L>
<L>Than had .I. b[e]ne in Ioye and parfit hele</L>
<L N="1272">There nowe .I. am exiled fro my wele</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;at .I. may not sene &yogh;owe Emelye<NOTE PLACE="marg">III. 75.</NOTE></L>
<L>.I. am bot dede &thorn;er nyse no remedie</L>
<L>&para; Vpon &thorn;at o&thorn;ere side Palamon</L>
<L N="1276">Whan &thorn;at he wiste &thorn;at Arcite was agone</L>
<L>Suche sorwe he make&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e grete toure</L>
<L>Resoune&thorn; of his &yogh;ellinge and clamour</L>
<L>The pore fettres on his schinnes grete</L>
<L N="1280">Were of his bitter salte teres wete</L>
<L>Alas quod he Arcita Cosyn myne</L>
<L>Of al oure strif god wote &thorn;e fruyt is &thorn;ine</L>
<L>Thow walkes now in Thebes att &thorn;i large</L>
<L N="1284">And of my woo &thorn;ou &yogh;euest litel charge</L>
<L>Thou maiste sinne &thorn;ou hast wisdome and manhede
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>Assemble al &thorn;e folke of &yogh;oure kinrede</L>
<L>And Maake a werre so scharpe on &thorn;is Cite</L>
<L N="1288">That be som auenture or sum trete</L>
<L>Thou maiste haue to lady and to wife</L>
<L>ffor whome &thorn;at .I. most nedes lese my life</L>
<L>ffor as be weie of Possibilite</L>
<L N="1292">Sethe &thorn;ou art att &thorn;i large of prison fre</L>
<L>An art a lorde grete is &thorn;ine avantage</L>
<L>More &thorn;an is myne &thorn;at sterue&thorn;e here in a cage</L>
<L>&para; ffor .I. mote wepe and waile wil &thorn;at .I. leue</L>
<L N="1296">With al &thorn;e wo &thorn;at prison maie me &yogh;eue</L>
<L>Ande eke wi&thorn;e peine &thorn;at loue me &yogh;eueth also</L>
<L>That dowble&thorn; al my turment and my wo</L>
<L>Thare-wi&thorn;e &thorn;e fire of Ielousie vp sterte</L>
<L N="1300">With-inne his breste and hente him be &thorn;e herte</L>
<L>So woodly &thorn;at he like was to be-holde</L>
<L>The box tree or &thorn;e asshen dede or colde.</L>
<L>&para; Than seide he O cruel goddes &thorn;at gouern</L>
<L N="1304">This werlde wi&thorn; byndeinge of &yogh;owre worde eterne</L>
<L>And wreten in &thorn;e table of Atthamaunt<MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;owre parlement and &yogh;owre eterne graunt</L>
<L>What is Mankinde More vn-to &yogh;o holde</L>
<L N="1308">Than is &thorn;e schepe &thorn;at rowke&thorn; in &thorn;e folde</L>
<L>ffor sleine is man riht as ano&thorn;ere beste</L>
<L>And duelle&thorn;e eke in prison and in areste</L>
<L>And ha&thorn;e sekenesse and grete aduersite</L>
<L N="1312">And ofte time giltles parde</L>
<L>&para; What gouernance is in &thorn;is prescience</L>
<L>That giltles tormente&thorn; Innocence</L>
<L>And encrese&thorn; &thorn;us al my penaunce</L>
<L N="1316">That man is bounde to his obseruaunce</L>
<L>ffor goddes saake to letten of his will</L>
<L>&thorn;ere as a beste maie al his lust fulfill</L>
<L>And whan a beste is dede it ha&thorn;e no peine</L>
<L N="1320">Bot after his de&thorn;e man moste wepe and pleyne.</L>
<L>Thouhe in &thorn;is werlde he haue care and woo
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="39"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-owten doute it maie stonden soo</L>
<L>The ansewere of &thorn;is lette .I. to dyuines</L>
<L N="1324">Bot wele .I. wote &thorn;at in &thorn;is werlde grete peine es</L>
<L>Alas .I. see a serpent or a &thorn;ef</L>
<L>That mony a trewman ha&thorn; done meschief</L>
<L>Gone att his large and where him list maie turne</L>
<L N="1328">Bot .I. most be in prison &thorn;oruhe Saturne</L>
<L>An eke &thorn;oruhe Iuno Ialous and eke wode</L>
<L>That ha&thorn;e destruyde nyhe al &thorn;e blode</L>
<L>Of Thebes wi&thorn; his waste walles wide</L>
<L N="1332">And venus flie&thorn; me on &thorn;at o&thorn;ere side</L>
<L>ffor Ialousie and fere of him Arcite<NOTE PLACE="marg">"paurosa gelosia" V. 2</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Nowe wil .I. stinte of Palamon a lite</L>
<L>And lat him in his prisone stille dwelle</L>
<L N="1336">And of Arcite for&thorn;e .I. will &yogh;owe telle</L>
<L>The somer passe&thorn; and &thorn;e nihtes longe</L>
<L>Encreseth dowble wise &thorn;e peynes stronge</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of &thorn;e louere and &thorn;e prisonere</L>
<L N="1340">.I. note wiche ha&thorn;e &thorn;e wofuller myster</L>
<L>ffor schortelye for to seine &thorn;is Palamon</L>
<L>Perpetuely is dampned to prison</L>
<L>In chynes and fettres to &thorn;e dede</L>
<L N="1344">And Arcit is ercilede vpon his hede</L>
<L>ffor euere more as oute of &thorn;at Cuntre</L>
<L>Ne neuere ne schal his lady see.</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;owe louiers .I. aske &thorn;is questi&omacr;ne<MILESTONE N="18a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1348">Who ha&thorn; &thorn;e wers Arcite or Palam&omacr;ne</L>
<L>The one maie se his lady . daie be daie</L>
<L>Bot in prison he most dwel alweie</L>
<L>The to&thorn;ere where him liste Maie ride or goo</L>
<L N="1352">Bote sene his lady schal he neuer moo</L>
<L>Nowe deme&thorn; as &yogh;owe liste &thorn;at &yogh;e canne</L>
<L>ffor .I. wil tel for&thorn;e as .I. be-ganne<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000068.tif" N="40">
<HEAD>[PART II. No gap in the MS.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;at Arcite to Thebes commen was</L>
<L N="1356">fful often adaie he swelte and seide alas</L>
<L>ffor seen his ladi schal he neuer moo</L>
<L>And schortly to concluden al his woo</L>
<L>So muche sorwe had neuer creature</L>
<L N="1360">That is or schall whil &thorn;at &thorn;e werde mai dure</L>
<L>His slepe his mete his drinke is be-raft<NOTE PLACE="marg">IV. 26, 27.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at lene he wex and drie as is a schaft</L>
<L>His yhe hollowe and grisely to be-holde<NOTE PLACE="marg">IV. 28.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1364">His hiew falowe and pale as asshe colde<NOTE PLACE="marg">IV. 27.</NOTE></L>
<L>And solitarie he was. and euer a lone</L>
<L>And weyleynge al &thorn;e nyht makinge his mone.</L>
<L>And if he herde songe or instrument</L>
<L N="1368">Than wolde he wepe he myht nouht be stent</L>
<L>So feble eke were his spretes and he lowe<NOTE PLACE="marg">IV. 29.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Chaungede so &thorn;at noman cou&thorn;e knowe</L>
<L>His speche nor his voice &thorn;ouhe men hit herde</L>
<L N="1372">And in his gere for al &thorn;e werlde he ferde</L>
<L>Not comly lyke to louers maledye</L>
<L>Of heres bot ra&thorn;er like manye</L>
<L>Engenderd of humor malancolike</L>
<L N="1376">Be-forne his celle ffantastike</L>
<L>And scortly torned was al vp and downe</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Abite and disposicioune</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;is woful louer dame Arcite</L>
<L N="1380">&para; Wat schold .I. al daie of his wo endite</L>
<L>Whan he endured had a &yogh;ere or two</L>
<L>This cruel torment and &thorn;is peine and woo</L>
<L>As Thebes in his Contre as .I. seide</L>
<L N="1384">Vpon a nyhte on slepe as he him leide.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ouht howe &thorn;at venged god Mercurie</L>
<L>Be-forne him stode and bad him to be merie</L>
<L>His slepi &yogh;erde in honde he bar vp riht</L>
<L N="1388">An hatte he werede vpon his heres briht
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>Arraide was &thorn;is god as as he toke kepe</L>
<L>As he was whan &thorn;at Argus toke his slepe</L>
<L>And seide him &thorn;us to Athenes &thorn;ow schalt wende<MILESTONE N="18b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1392">Where is &thorn;e schapen of &thorn;i woo an ende</L>
<L>&para; And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde Arcite woke and sterte</L>
<L>Now trewli how sore &thorn;at me smerte</L>
<L>Quod he to Athenes riht nowe wil .I. fare</L>
<L N="1396">Ne for &thorn;e drede of de&thorn;e schal .I. nouht spare</L>
<L>To se my lady &thorn;at .I. loue and serue</L>
<L>In hire presence .I. reche not to sterue</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde he cauht a grete Mirroure</L>
<L N="1400">And sauhe &thorn;at chaunged was al his coloure</L>
<L>And sauhe his vesage al in ano&thorn;er kinde</L>
<L>And riht anone it ran him in his mynde<NOTE PLACE="marg">IV. 38.</NOTE></L>
<L>That se&thorn; his face was so disfigurede</L>
<L N="1404">Of &thorn;e Maledy whiche he had endurede</L>
<L>He myht wele if &thorn;at he bare him lowe</L>
<L>Leue in Athenes euer more vnknowe</L>
<L>An seen his lady wel ny day be daye</L>
<L N="1408">And riht anone he chaunged his Araye</L>
<L>And clad him as poure laborere<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>pover valletto</I>, IV. 22.</NOTE></L>
<L>An al alone saue onely o swiere<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>umil garzone</I>, IV. 22.</NOTE></L>
<L>That knewe his priuete and al his case<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>povero valletto</I> IV. 40.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1412">Whiche was disgised pouerly as he was</L>
<L>To Athenes is gone &thorn;e next waye</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e courte he went vpon a daye</L>
<L>And att &thorn;e gate he proferd his seruyse</L>
<L N="1416">To drugge and drawe what so men wil deuise</L>
<L>And schortly of &thorn;is mater for to seine</L>
<L>He fel in office wi&thorn; a chamburleine</L>
<L>The whiche &thorn;at was dwellinge wi&thorn; Emelye</L>
<L N="1420">ffor he was wise and sone cou&thorn;e aspye</L>
<L>ffor euery seruant whiche &thorn;at serue&thorn; here</L>
<L>Wele cou&thorn;e he hewen wode and water bere</L>
<L>ffor he was &yogh;onge and myhti for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L N="1424">And &thorn;er-to he was stronge and briht of bones
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>To done &thorn;at any whit him can devise</L>
<L>A &yogh;ere or two he was in &thorn;is seruise</L>
<L>Page of &thorn;e chambere of Emely &thorn;e briht</L>
<L N="1428">And Philostrat he seide &thorn;at he hiht<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>Penteo</I> IV. 3, &amp;c.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot halfe so wele be-loued a man as he</L>
<L>Ne was &thorn;ere neuer in Courte of his degre</L>
<L>He was so gentil of condicioune</L>
<L N="1432">That &thorn;oruhe-owte al &thorn;e courte was his renoune</L>
<L>Thei seide &thorn;at it were a charite<MILESTONE N="19a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That Theseus wolde en-haunse his degre</L>
<L>And putten him in worschip-ful seruise</L>
<L N="1436">There as he myht his vertue exercise</L>
<L>And &thorn;us wi&thorn;-inne a while his name is spronge<NOTE PLACE="marg">IV. 59.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of his dede and his good tonge</L>
<L>That Theseus ha&thorn;e taken him so nere</L>
<L N="1440">That of his chambre he maade him a swiere</L>
<L>And &yogh;aue him gold to mainteigne his degre</L>
<L>And eke men brouht him oute of his contre</L>
<L>ffro &yogh;ere to &yogh;ere so priuely his rente</L>
<L N="1444">But onestly and sleyhtly . he it spente</L>
<L>&thorn;at noman wondred howe &thorn;at he it hadde</L>
<L>And &thorn;rei &yogh;ere in &thorn;is wise his lif he ladde</L>
<L>And bare him so in pees and eke in werre</L>
<L N="1448">There was no man &thorn;at Theseus hathe derre<NOTE PLACE="marg">IV. 59.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in &thorn;is blisse let .I. nowe Arcite</L>
<L>And speke .I. will of Palamon a lite</L>
<L>&para; In derkenes and horrible and stronge prisone<NOTE PLACE="marg">V. 1.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1452">&THORN;is seuen &yogh;ere ha&thorn;e siten Palamone</L>
<L>ffor-pined whate for wo and for destresse</L>
<L>Who fele&thorn; double sore and heuinesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">V. 3.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot Palamon &thorn;at loue destreyne&thorn; so</L>
<L N="1456">That woode owte of his witte he go&thorn; for wo</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;ere-to he is a prisoner</L>
<L>Perpetuelly not onely for a &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Who cou&thorn;e rime in Englisshe propurly</L>
<L N="1460">His martirdome for so&thorn;e it am not .I.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>There-fore .I. passe al so lihtly as .I. maye</L>
<L>&para; It fel &thorn;at in &thorn;e seuent &yogh;ere of maie</L>
<L>The &thorn;ridde nyhte as holde bokes seine</L>
<L N="1464">That all &thorn;is story telle&thorn; more pleine</L>
<L>Were it be aventure or destanye</L>
<L>As whan a &thorn;inge is schape it schal bye</L>
<L>&THORN;at sone after &thorn;e mydenyht Palamon<NOTE PLACE="marg">V. 25-7.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1468">Be helpinge of a frende brake prison</L>
<L>And fleeth &thorn;e Cite fast as he mai goo</L>
<L>ffor he had gif his Gailer drinke soo<NOTE PLACE="marg">V. 24.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of a clarre maade of a certein wyne</L>
<L N="1472">Wi&thorn; nercotiks and opie of Thebes fyne</L>
<L>That al &thorn;at nyht &thorn;ouhe &thorn;at men wold him schake</L>
<L>The Gaillere slepe he myht nouht awake.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he flie&thorn; as fast as euere he maie<MILESTONE N="19b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1476">The nyht was schort and fast be &thorn;e daie</L>
<L>That nedes coste he most him self hiden</L>
<L>And til a groue faste fast &thorn;ere be-siden<NOTE PLACE="marg">V. 33.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; dredful fote &thorn;an stalke&thorn; Palamon</L>
<L N="1480">ffor schort &thorn;is was his opinion</L>
<L>That in &thorn;at groue he wolde him hide aldaie</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e nyht &thorn;an wolde he take his waie</L>
<L>To Thebes-warde his frendes for to praye</L>
<L N="1484">On Theseus to helpe him to werreie</L>
<L>Or schortly he wolde lese his lif</L>
<L>Ore wynnen Emely to his louely wif</L>
<L>This is &thorn;efecte and his entente pleine</L>
<L N="1488">&para; Now whiles turne we to Arcite a&yogh;eine</L>
