<L>As sende me him &thorn;at most desire&thorn; me</L>
<L>Be-holde goddes of clene chastite</L>
<L>The bitter teres &thorn;at on my cheke falle<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 78.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2328">Sen &thorn;ou art Maiden and keper of vs alle</L>
<L>My maidenhede &thorn;ou kepe and wele conserue</L>
<L>And wile .I. leue a maide .I. wil &yogh;owe serue</L>
<L>The fires berne vpon &thorn;e auter clere<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 88.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2332">While emely was &thorn;us in hir preiere</L>
<L>Bot sodanly sche sawe a siht queynte</L>
<L>ffor rihte a-none on of &thorn;e fires queynte<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 91.</NOTE></L>
<L>An quyked a&yogh;eine and after &thorn;at anone</L>
<L N="2336">That o&thorn;er fire was queynte and al agone</L>
<L>And as it queynte it maad a whistelynge</L>
<L>As done &thorn;es wete brondes in her brenynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 92.</NOTE></L>
<L>And att &thorn;e brondes ende oute ran anone</L>
<L N="2340">As it were blodi dropes many one</L>
<L>ffor whiche so sore agaste was Emelye</L>
<L>That sche was nyhe mad and gan to crie</L>
<L>ffor sche ne wist what it signified<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 92.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2344">Bot onely for &thorn;e fere &thorn;us ha&thorn; sche cried</L>
<L>And wepe &thorn;at Pite was to here</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere wi&thorn; all Diane gan a-pere<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 88.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bowe in honde riht as an hunteresse</L>
<L N="2348">And seide douhter stinte &thorn;ine heuinesse</L>
<L>Amonge &thorn;e goddes on hihe it is affermede<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 89.</NOTE></L>
<L>And be eterne worde wreten and confermede<NOTE PLACE="marg">['con eterna pa|rola,' VII. 85.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thou schalt be wedded vn to one of &thorn;oo<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 89.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2352">That haue for &thorn;e so muche care and woo</L>
<L>Bot vnto whiche of hem .I. maie nouht telle<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 89.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffare wele for .I. ne maie no longer dwelle</L>
<L>The fires whiche &thorn;at on myn auter berne<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 89.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2356">Schole &yogh;e declaren arr &thorn;at &yogh;e gon henne</L>
<L>&para; Thyne auentur of loue as in &thorn;is caas
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde &thorn;e Arwes in &thorn;e caas</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e goddes claterne fast and ringe<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 90.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2360">And for&thorn;e sche wente and made a vanyssinge</L>
<L>ffor whiche &thorn;i[ng] emely astoned was<MILESTONE N="30a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And seide what a-mounte&thorn; &thorn;is alas</L>
<L>.I. pute me in &thorn;i protectione</L>
<L N="2364">Diane and in &thorn;ine dispocicion</L>
<L>And home sche go&thorn;e a-none &thorn;e next weye<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 93.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is is &thorn;effecte &thorn;ere is nomore to seie</L>
<L>&para; The next houre of Mars folwynge &thorn;is</L>
<L N="2368">Arcite vnto &thorn;e temple walke is</L>
<L>Of fires Mars to don his sacrifice</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; all &thorn;e rihtes of his payen wise</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;e pitous hert and hihe deuocione<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 23.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2372">Riht &thorn;us to mars he sent his orison</L>
<L>&para; O stronge good &thorn;at in &thorn;e regne colde<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 24.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Trace honoured erte and lorde .I.-holde</L>
<L>And hast in euery regne and in euery londe</L>
<L N="2376">Of armes al &thorn;e bridel in &thorn;in honde</L>
<L>And hem fortunest as &thorn;e liste deuyse</L>
<L>Accepte of me my pitous sacrifise</L>
<L>If so be &thorn;at my &yogh;ou&thorn;e mai deserue<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 25.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2380">And &thorn;at .I. myht be wor&thorn;i for to serue</L>
<L>Thi godhede &thorn;at .I. maie bene one of &thorn;ine</L>
<L>&THORN;at praie .I. to &thorn;e to rewe vpon my pine</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ilke pine and &thorn;ilke hote fire</L>
<L N="2384">In whiche &thorn;ou whilome berneste for desire</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ou vsedest &thorn;i beaute<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 25.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of faire &yogh;onge fressche venus fre</L>
<L>And haddest hir in armes att &thorn;i will</L>
<L N="2388">Al-&thorn;ouhe &yogh;e ones on a time mysfell</L>
<L>Whane vulcanus hadde cauht &thorn;e in his laas<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 25.</NOTE></L>
<L>And fonde &thorn;e liggynge be his wif alaas</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ilke sorwe &thorn;at was in &thorn;in herte</L>
<L N="2392">Haue reu&thorn;e as wele vpon my peines smerte</L>
<L>.I. am &yogh;onge and vnkunynge as &thorn;ou woste<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 26.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="69"></L>
<L>And as .I. trowe wi&thorn; loue offendude moste</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer was any liues creature<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 26.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2396">ffor sche &thorn;at do&thorn;e me al &thorn;is woo endure</L>
<L>Ne recche&thorn; neuer whe&thorn;er .I. sinke or flete</L>
<L>And wele .I. wote ar sche me merci hete</L>
<L>.I. moste wi&thorn; strenke&thorn; winne hir in &thorn;e place</L>
<L N="2400">And wele .I. wote wi&thorn;-owten helpe or grace<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 26.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e; ne maie my strenke&thorn; nouht aveile</L>
<L>Than helpe me lorde to-morne in my bataile.<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII 27.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ilke fire &thorn;at whilom brente &thorn;e<MILESTONE N="30b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2404">As wele as &thorn;ilke fire nowe brenne&thorn; me</L>
<L>An do &thorn;at .I. to-morne haue &thorn;e victorie</L>
<L>Myne be &thorn;e trauayle and &thorn;ine be &thorn;e glorie<NOTE PLACE="marg">'Io il diletto, e tu n' abbia l' onore.' VII. 27.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thi souereyne temple wele most .I honouren</L>
<L N="2408">Of any place and al-wey moste labouren.</L>
<L>In &thorn;i pesauntez and in &thorn;i craftes stronge</L>
<L>And in &thorn;i temple .I. will Mi baner honge<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 28.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al &thorn;e armes of my compaignye</L>
<L N="2412">And euer more vntil &thorn;at .I. dye</L>
<L>Eterne fire .I. will be-for &thorn;e finde<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 28.</NOTE></L>
<L>And eke to &thorn;is a-vowe .I. wil me binde</L>
<L>Mine Mine here &thorn;at honge&thorn; longe a doune<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 28.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2416">That neuer &yogh;ite ne felte offensione</L>
<L>Of Rasoure ne of schere .I. wil &thorn;e &yogh;eue</L>
<L>And bene &thorn;i treu seruant while .I. leue.</L>
<L>Now lorde haue reu&thorn;e vpon my sorous sore</L>
<L N="2420">&YOGH;if me &thorn;e victorie .I. ax &thorn;e no more</L>
<L>&para; The preier stinte of Arcita &thorn;e stronge</L>
<L>The ringe on &thorn;e temple dore &thorn;at honge.</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;e dores claterden ful fast<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 39.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2424">Of whiche arcita sumwhat him a-gaste</L>
<L>The fires brenten vpon &thorn;e auteres brihte<NOTE PLACE="marg">VI. 40.</NOTE></L>
<L>That it gan al &thorn;e temple for to lihte</L>
<L>And swete smelle &thorn;e gronde anone vp &yogh;afe</L>
<L N="2428">And Arcita a-none his hand vp hafe<NOTE PLACE="marg">See VII. 40.</NOTE></L>
<L>And More encence in to &thorn;e fire he caste
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; o&thorn;ere rihtes moo and at &thorn;e laste</L>
<L>The Statue of Marc&yogh; began his hauberk ringe<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 40.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2432">And wi&thorn; &thorn;e sounde he herde a memorynge</L>
<L>fful lowe and dimme &thorn;at seide &thorn;us victorie</L>
<L>ffor whiche he &yogh;afe to mars honour and glorie</L>
<L>And &thorn;us wi&thorn; Ioy and hope wele to fare<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 41.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2436">Arcite a-none vn to his Inne he is fare</L>
<L>As feine as fowle is of &thorn;e briht sonne</L>
<L>And riht anone ffrissche strife is be-gunne<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 67.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ilke grauntynge in &thorn;e heuen a-boue</L>
<L N="2440">Be-twix venus &thorn;e goddes of loue</L>
<L>And marce &thorn;e steren god Armipotentent</L>
<L>That Iubiter was besie it to stent</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e pale Saturnus &thorn;e colde</L>
<L N="2444">&thorn;at knewe so mony of aventures olde</L>
<L>ffond in his olde experiens an arte<MILESTONE N="31a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That ful sone ha&thorn;e pleside euery parte</L>
<L>A so&thorn;e is seide Elde ha&thorn; grete auantage</L>
<L N="2448">In Elde is bo&thorn;e wisdome and vsage</L>
<L>Men Maie &thorn;e olde att-renne and nouht atrede</L>
<L>Saturne a-none to stint strif and drede</L>
<L>Al be it &thorn;at it is a&yogh;eines his kinde</L>
<L N="2452">Of Al &thorn;is st[r]if he gan remedi finde</L>
<L>Mi dere Douhter venus quod Saturne</L>
<L>Mi course &thorn;at ha&thorn;e so wide for to turne</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; more powere &thorn;an ha&thorn; any manne</L>
<L N="2456">Mine is &thorn;e drynchinge in &thorn;e see so wanne</L>
<L>Mine is &thorn;e prisone in &thorn;e derke cote</L>
<L>Mine is &thorn;e strangle and hongeinge by &thorn;e &thorn;rote</L>
<L>The murmure and &thorn;e cheles rebellinge</L>
<L N="2460">The groneynge and &thorn;e priue enprisoneinge</L>
<L>.I. do vengeance and pleine correctione</L>
<L>Wil .I. dwelle in &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e leone</L>
<L>Myne is &thorn;e ruyne of &thorn;e hihe halles</L>
<L N="2464">The fallynge of &thorn;e toures and of &thorn;e walles</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e minor and &thorn;e Carpenter
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="71"></L>
<L>I slowhe Sampson schakinge &thorn;e piler</L>
<L>And myne bene &thorn;e Maladies colde</L>
<L N="2468">The derke tresoures and &thorn;e Costes olde</L>
<L>My lokeynge is &thorn;e fader of pestelence</L>
<L>Nowe wepe nomore .I. schal do diligence</L>
<L>&THORN;at palamon &thorn;at is &thorn;ine owen knyht</L>
<L N="2472">Schal haue his lady as &thorn;ou him hihte</L>
<L>Mars schal helpe his knyht na&thorn;eles</L>
<L>Be-twix &yogh;owe &thorn;ere mot be sum time pes</L>
<L>Al be nouht bo&thorn;e of on complexione</L>
<L N="2476">&THORN;at cause&thorn; al daie suche diuisione</L>
<L>.I. am &thorn;in ayell rede att &thorn;i will</L>
<L>Wepe nowe no more &thorn;i lust .I. wil fulfill</L>
<L>Nowe will .I. stente of &thorn;e goddes aboue</L>
<L N="2480">Of Mars and of venus goddes of loue</L>
<L>And tell &thorn;owe also pleinely as .I. can</L>
<L>&THORN;e gret effecte of whiche that .I. be-gan</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART IV. No gap in the MS.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Grete was &thorn;e feste in Athenes &thorn;at daie</L>
<L N="2484">And eke &thorn;at lusti seson of &thorn;at maye</L>
<L>Maade euery knyht to bene in suche plesaunce</L>
<L>That al &thorn;at monday Iousten &thorn;ei and daunce.</L>
<L>And spende it in hihe venus seruise<MILESTONE N="31b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2488">Bot be &thorn;e cause &thorn;at &thorn;ei scholde rise</L>
<L>Erly for to seen &thorn;e grete fighte</L>
<L>Vnto her reste went &thorn;ei att nihte</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morwe whan &thorn;e dai gan springe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[General imita|tion of VII. 95-99.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2492">Of hors and herneys noyse and clateringe</L>
<L>There was in hostries al a-boute</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Paleys rode &thorn;er mony a route</L>
<L>Of lordes vpon stedes and palfreis</L>
<L N="2496">There maist &thorn;ou seen diuiseinge of harneys</L>
<L>So vnkou&thorn;e and so riche and wrouhte so wele</L>
<L>Of gold smy&thorn;erie of brondeinge and of stele
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="72"></L>
<L>The Scheldes briht testeres and trappures</L>
<L N="2500">Gold hewen helmes hawberkes cote armures</L>
<L>Lordes in paramentes on hir courseres</L>
<L>Knyhtes of Retenu and eke swieres</L>
<L>Naillinge &thorn;e speres and helmes bokelynge</L>
<L N="2504">Gideinge of scheldes wi&thorn; layners lasinge</L>
<L>There as nede is &thorn;ei were no &thorn;inge ydel</L>
<L>The fomy stedes on &thorn;e golden bridel<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 97.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gnawen and faste &thorn;e armureres also</L>
<L N="2508">Wi&thorn; file and hamur prikinge to and fro</L>
<L>&YOGH;omen on fote and comune mony one</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; schort staues riht as &thorn;ei mai gone</L>
<L>Pipes trompes nakers clarions</L>
<L N="2512">&thorn;at in &thorn;e retaile blewe blodi sownes</L>
<L>The Paleis ful of peple vp and doune<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 99.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here &thorn;re &thorn;er ten holdeinge her questioune<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 98.</NOTE></L>
<L>Deuyneinge of &thorn;is thebane knyhtes tuo</L>
<L N="2516">Som seide &thorn;us sum seide it schal be so</L>
<L>Some holden wi&thorn; him wi&thorn; &thorn;e blake berde</L>
<L>Some wi&thorn; &thorn;e balle some wi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ikke herede</L>
<L>Some seide he loked grimme and he wolde fihte</L>
<L N="2520">He ha&thorn; a spar&thorn;e of .xx. pounde of wihte</L>
<L>Thus was &thorn;e hal ful of diuineinge</L>
<L>Longe after &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne gan to springe</L>
<L>The grete Theseus &thorn;at of his slepe awaked<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 96.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2524">Wi&thorn; mynstralcye and noys &thorn;at was maked</L>
<L>Held &yogh;ite &thorn;e Chambres of his palays riche</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e Thebanes knyhtes bo&thorn;en yliche</L>
<L>Honorable weren in to &thorn;e Palays ffette</L>
<L N="2528">Duc Theseus is att &thorn;e window sette</L>
<L>Arraide riht as he were a god in Throne<MILESTONE N="32a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The peple presed &thorn;ederwarde ful sone</L>
<L>Him for to seyn and done hihe reuerence</L>
<L N="2532">And eke to herken his heste and his sentence</L>
<L>An heraude on a scafold maad an hoo</L>
<L>Til all &thorn;e noys of &thorn;e peple was . y-doo
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="73"></L>
<L>And whan he sawe &thorn;e peple of noyse al still</L>
<L N="2536">Thus schewed he &thorn;e myhty dukes will</L>
<L>&para; The lorde ha&thorn; of his hihe discrecione<NOTE PLACE="marg">See VII. 7-13.</NOTE></L>
<L>Considered &thorn;at it were destructione</L>
<L>To gentil blode to fihten in &thorn;is gise</L>
<L N="2540">Of Mortaile bataile nowe in &thorn;is emprise<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 7.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whare-for to schapen &thorn;at &thorn;ei schal not deye</L>
<L>He will his first purpos modefye</L>
<L>No man &thorn;ar-fore vpon peine on his lif<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 12. [<I>no</I> lances allowed in Boccaccio]</NOTE></L>
<L N="2544">No manere schotte ne polax ne schorte knyfe</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e listes sende ne &thorn;eder bringe</L>
<L>Ne schort swerde for to stoke wi&thorn; pointe biteinge.</L>
<L>No man ne drauhe ne bere it be his side</L>
<L N="2548">Noman schal vn to his felawe ride</L>
<L>Bot oo cours wi&thorn; a scharpe ygrounde spere</L>
<L>ffoyne if him list on fote him self to were</L>
<L>And [he] &thorn;at is att Meschef schal be take<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 131-132.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2552">And nouht sleine bot be brouht vnto &thorn;e stake</L>
<L>That schal bene ordeined on ey&thorn;er side</L>
<L>But &thorn;ider he schal be force and &thorn;are abide</L>
<L>And if so fal &thorn;e Cheftaigne be take</L>
<L N="2556">On ey&thorn;er side or elles sleine his make</L>
<L>No longer schal &thorn;e tornynge last</L>
<L>God sped &yogh;ow go for&thorn;e and laie on fast</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; longe swerdes and wi&thorn; maces fihten &yogh;oure fill<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 12 [and with 'bipenne'].</NOTE></L>
<L N="2560">Go nowe &yogh;oure weie &thorn;is is &thorn;e lordes will</L>
<L>The voice of &thorn;e peple touched heuen<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 14.</NOTE></L>
<L>So loude cried &thorn;ei wi&thorn; mery steuene</L>
<L>God saue suche a lorde &thorn;at is so goode</L>
<L N="2564">He wilne&thorn; no destruction of mannes blode</L>
<L>Vp go&thorn;e &thorn;e trompes and &thorn;e melodie</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e listes ryde&thorn; &thorn;e compaignie</L>
<L>Be ordinance &thorn;oruhe oute &thorn;e Cite large</L>
<L N="2568">Honged wi&thorn; clo&thorn;e of golde and nouht wi&thorn; sarge</L>
<L>fful like a lorde &thorn;is noble Duc gan ride<NOTE PLACE="marg">See VII. 100-102.</NOTE></L>
<L>The tuo Thebanes vpon ey&thorn;er side.
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>And aftere rode &thorn;e queene and Emely<MILESTONE N="32b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2572">And after &thorn;at an o&thorn;er compaignie<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 113-4.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of one and o&thorn;er after here degre</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;ei passen &thorn;urgh oute &thorn;e Citee</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e listes come &thorn;ei be time</L>
<L N="2576">It was nouht of &thorn;e daie &yogh;it fulliche prime</L>
<L>&para; Whan sette was Theseus ful riche and hihe</L>
<L>Ipolita &thorn;e queene and Emelye</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er ladyes in degres a-boute</L>
<L N="2580">Vn-to &thorn;e setes prese&thorn; all &thorn;e route.</L>
<L>And westwa &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e gates vnder Marte<NOTE PLACE="marg">Arcita (in Boccaccio) comes from the quarter of 'Euro' (VII. 114): Pale|mone comes 'Dall' altra parte' (VII. 118). No mention is made by Boccaccio of their banners being <I>red</I> and <I>white</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 114.</NOTE></L>
<L>Arcite and eke &thorn;e hundre&thorn; of his parte</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; baner rede is entred riht anone</L>
<L N="2584">And in &thorn;at selfe moment Palamon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 118.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is vnder venus est-warde in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; banere white and hardy chere and face</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e werlde to seken vpe and doune<NOTE PLACE="marg">VII. 19.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2588">So euen wi&thorn;-oute variacioune</L>
<L>&thorn;er ner suche companyes tweye</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ere was none so wise &thorn;at cou&thorn;e seye</L>
<L>&THORN;at any had of o&thorn;ere auantage</L>
<L N="2592">Of wor&thorn;inesse ne of state of age;</L>
<L>So euen were &thorn;ei Chosen for to gesse</L>
