<L>In culpons wele arraide for to berne<MILESTONE N="36a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2868">His officers wi&thorn; swift foote &thorn;ei renne</L>
<L>And ride a-none att his commaundement</L>
<L>And aftere &thorn;is Theseus ha&thorn; .I.-sent<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 15.</NOTE></L>
<L>After a bere a bere and it al ouere spradde</L>
<L N="2872">Wi&thorn; clo&thorn;e of golde &thorn;e richest &thorn;at he hadde</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e same suyte he cladde Arcite</L>
<L>Vpon his hondes his gloues white</L>
<L>Eke on his hede a coroune of Laurel grene</L>
<L N="2876">And in his honde a swerde brihte and kene</L>
<L>He laide him bare / &thorn;e visage on &thorn;e bere</L>
<L>There-wi&thorn;e he weppe &thorn;at pite was to here</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e peple schold seen him all<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 16.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2880">Whan it was daie he brouhte hem in to &thorn;e hall</L>
<L>That rore&thorn; of &thorn;e crie and &thorn;e soune<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 30.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Tho come &thorn;is woful Palamone</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; flotery berde and ruggy asshi heres</L>
<L N="2884">In clo&thorn;es blakke dropped al wi&thorn; teres</L>
<L>And passinge o&thorn;ere of wepeinge Emelye<NOTE PLACE="marg"><Q><L>'Non men dolente, Emilia pur piangea,</L><L>. . . . .</L><L>I circostanti pi&ugrave; pianger facea' (XI. 31).</L></Q></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 31.</NOTE></L>
<L>The reufulleste of al &thorn;is compaignie</L>
<L>In as mulche &thorn;at &thorn;e seruise schold be</L>
<L N="2888">The more noble and riche in his degre</L>
<L>Duc Theseus lete for&thorn;e &thorn;rei stedes bringe<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 35.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at trappede were in stele al gleteringe</L>
<L>And couerde wi&thorn; &thorn;e armes of Dan Arcite</L>
<L N="2892">Vpon &thorn;ese stedes grete and white</L>
<L>There sitten folke of whiche on bar his schelde</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ere his spere vppon his hondes helde
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="83"></L>
<L>The &thorn;rede bare him wi&thorn; his bowe turkeys</L>
<L N="2896">Of brente golde was &thorn;e caas and eke &thorn;e herneys<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 35.</NOTE></L>
<L>And riden for&thorn;e a pas wi&thorn; sorweful chere</L>
<L>To-warde &thorn;e groue as &yogh;e schol after here</L>
<L>The noblest of &thorn;e grekes &thorn;at &thorn;ere were<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 38.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2900">Vpon her scholdres Cariden &thorn;e bere</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; slake paas and y&yogh;en rede and wete</L>
<L>&THORN;oruhe-oute &thorn;e Cite be &thorn;e maistre strete</L>
<L>&THORN;at sprad was al wi&thorn; blake and wonder hihe</L>
<L N="2904">Riht of &thorn;e same is &thorn;e strete y-wrye</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e rihte honde went olde Egeus<NOTE PLACE="marg">Right and left of Palemone (XI. 40).</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 40.</NOTE></L>
<L>And on &thorn;at o&thorn;er side Duc Theseus</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; vesseles in hir honde of gold ful fine<NOTE PLACE="marg">In the hands of the noblest of the Greeks (XI. 37).</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 37.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2908">Al ful of hony melke and blode and wyne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 40.</NOTE></L>
<L>Eke Palamon wi&thorn; full grete compaignye<MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And efter &thorn;at cam woofull Emelye</L>
<L>With fire in honde as was &thorn;at time &thorn;e gise</L>
<L N="2912">ffor to done &thorn;e Office of funerale seruise</L>
<L>Hihe Laboure and full apparaillinge<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 18.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whas att &thorn;e seruise and att &thorn;e fire makeinge</L>
<L>That whi&thorn;e his grene top &thorn;e heuen rauhte<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 26.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2916">And twenty fa&thorn;ome on brede &thorn;e armes strauhte</L>
<L>This to seine &thorn;e bowes were so brode</L>
<L>Of stre first &thorn;er was leide mony a lode<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 27.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot howe &thorn;e fire was maked vp on hihte<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 22-25.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2920">Ne eke &thorn;e names howe &thorn;e trees hihte</L>
<L>As oke. fir. beche. aspe. alder holme popelere</L>
<L>Wylowe. elme. plane. asshe. Box. chasteine Binde Laurere</L>
<L>Mapul. &thorn;orne. berche. hasul. ewe. whipiltre</L>
<L N="2924">Howe &thorn;ei were felde schal nouht be tolde for me</L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;e goddes ronnen vp and doune.</L>
<L>Disherited of here habitacioune</L>
<L>In whiche &thorn;e wonden in rest and pes</L>
<L N="2928">Nimphes faunes and amadries</L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;e bestes and &thorn;e birdes all<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 21.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffledden for ferde whan &thorn;e [wood] was fall
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;e grounde agast was for &thorn;e liht</L>
<L N="2932">That was nouht wonte to se &thorn;e sonne briht<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 21.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;e fire was cowched first wi&thorn; stree<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 27.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;an wi&thorn; drye stikkes clouen a three</L>
<L>And &thorn;an wi&thorn; grene wode . and spicerie</L>
<L N="2936">And &thorn;an wi&thorn; clo&thorn;e of golde and of Perrye<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 29.</NOTE></L>
<L>And garlondes hongeinge wi&thorn; ful mony a floure<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 27.</NOTE></L>
<L>The mirre Thensens wi&thorn; also swete odoure<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 28.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne howe Arcite lay amonge al &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 30.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2940">Ne what riches abowte his body is</L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;at Emelye as was &thorn;e gyse<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 40.</NOTE></L>
<L>Putte in &thorn;e fire of funeral seruise</L>
<L>Ne howe sche swownede whan maade was &thorn;e fire<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 41-46.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2944">Ne what sche spak ne what was hir desire</L>
<L>Ne what Iuels men in &thorn;e fire cast<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 48, 50.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e fire was grete and brende fast</L>
<L>Ne howe som kast hir schelde and som hir spere<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 56.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2948">And of her vestementes which &thorn;at &thorn;ei were<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 50.</NOTE></L>
<L>And coppes ful of melke wyne and blode<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 50, 51.</NOTE></L>
<L>In to &thorn;e fire &thorn;at brente as it were wode</L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;e Grekes wi&thorn; an huge route<MILESTONE N="37a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 52.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2952">Thries riden al &thorn;e fire aboute<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 53.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e lefte hand . wi&thorn; a bowe scheteinge</L>
<L>And &thorn;ries wi&thorn; here speres Clateringe</L>
<L>And &thorn;rie howe &thorn;e ladies gan crye<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 54.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2956">Ne howe &thorn;at ladde was homward Emelye</L>
<L>Ne howe Arcite is bernte to asshe colde<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 57, 58.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne howe &thorn;at liche wake was yholde<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 59-67.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;ilke nyht . ne howe &thorn;e grekes pleie</L>
<L N="2960">The wake playes ne kepe .I. nouht to seie</L>
<L>Who werstele&thorn; beste nakede wi&thorn; oile anoynte</L>
<L>Ne who &thorn;at bar him best in no disioynte</L>
<L>.I. wil nouht tellen al howe &thorn;ei gone</L>
<L N="2964">Home til Athenes whan &thorn;e pleie was done</L>
<L>Bot schortly to &thorn;e point &thorn;an wil .I. wende</L>
<L>And maken of myne longe tale an ende
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>&para; Be proces and be lengthe of certein &yogh;eres</L>
<L N="2968">Al stinte is &thorn;e morneynge and &thorn;e teres<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 3, '<I>giorni</I>,' instead of <I>years</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Greges be one general assent</L>
<L>Than semede &thorn;are was A parlement</L>
<L>Att Athenes vppon a certeine pointe and caas</L>
<L N="2972">A-monge &thorn;e whiche poyntes spoken was</L>
<L>To haue wi&thorn; certein crontres alliaunce</L>
<L>And haue fully of Thebane obeisaunce</L>
<L>ffor whiche &thorn;is noble Theseus a-none</L>
<L N="2976">Lete sende after gentil Palamone<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 4.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnwiste of him whatt was &thorn;e cause and whie</L>
<L>Bot in his blake clo&thorn;es sorwfully</L>
<L>He came att his commandement in hye.</L>
<L N="2980">Tho sente Theseus for faire Emelye</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei were sett and huyst was in &thorn;e place<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Theseus abiden ha&thorn; a space</L>
<L>Or any worde cam fro his wise breste</L>
<L N="2984">His ey&yogh;en sett he &thorn;ere as was his leste</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; a sadde visage he siked stille</L>
<L>And af[t]erward riht &thorn;us his wille</L>
<L>&para; The firste mouere of &thorn;e cause aboue<NOTE PLACE="marg">IX. 51.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2988">Whan he first maade &thorn;e faire cheine of loue<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>mondo</I>, for cheine of loue.'</NOTE></L>
<L>Grete was &thorn;effect . and hihe was his entente</L>
<L>Wele wiste he whi . and what &thorn;ere-of he mente<NOTE PLACE="marg">IX. 51.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor wi&thorn; &thorn;at faire cheine of loue he bonde</L>
<L N="2992">The fire &thorn;e Aire . &thorn;e watere and &thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>In certeine boundes &thorn;at &thorn;ei maie nouht fle<MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That same prince and &thorn;at meuer quod he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[See IX. 51, 52, and XII. 6.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ha&thorn; stabled in &thorn;is wrechede werlde a-doun</L>
<L N="2996">Certeine daies and d[omi]nacioun</L>
<L>To al &thorn;at ben engrendred in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Ouere &thorn;e whiche daie &thorn;ei maie nouht pace</L>
<L>All mowe &thorn;ei &yogh;ute &thorn;o daies a-brugge</L>
<L N="3000">There nede&thorn; none auctorite to lugge.</L>
<L>ffor it is proued be experience</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at me lust declaren my sentence
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>Than maie men wele by &thorn;is order discerne</L>
<L N="3004">That &thorn;ilke mouere stable is and eterne</L>
<L>Wele maie men knowe bot it be foole</L>
<L>That euery partie darrained fromme his hoole</L>
<L>ffor nature ha&thorn;e nou&yogh;t take his begynnynge</L>
<L N="3008">Of no partie nor of cantel of a thinge</L>
<L>Bot of a thinge &thorn;at parfite is and stable</L>
<L>Descendeinge so to it be corrumpable</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-for for . his wise purueance</L>
<L N="3012">He ha&thorn; so wele be-sette his ordenance</L>
<L>That specie of &thorn;inges and progressions</L>
<L>Schullen endure be successions</L>
<L>And nouht eterne wi&thorn;-oute any lye</L>
<L N="3016">&THORN;is maystowe vnderstonden and seen att eye</L>
<L>Lo &thorn;e oke &thorn;at ha&thorn;e so longe a norissheynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 7.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffro &thorn;e time &thorn;at it first biginne&thorn; to springe</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; so longe a lif as &yogh;e maye see</L>
<L N="3020">&YOGH;ut att &thorn;e laste wasted is &thorn;e tree</L>
<L>Considere&thorn; eke howe &thorn;at &thorn;e harde stone</L>
<L>Vnde[r] owre fote on whiche we trede and gone</L>
<L>&YOGH;it waste&thorn; it as it li&thorn;e be &thorn;e weie</L>
<L N="3024">The brode riuer som time waxe&thorn; dreie</L>
<L>The grete townes see we wane and wende</L>
<L>Than &yogh;e see &thorn;at al &thorn;is &thorn;inge ha&thorn; ende</L>
<L>Of man and womman see we wele also<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 8.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3028">&THORN;at nede&thorn; in oone of &thorn;e teremes tuo</L>
<L>&THORN;is is to seine in &yogh;ou&thorn;e or elles age</L>
<L>He mote be dede &thorn;e kinge as schal a page</L>
<L>Som in his bede some in &thorn;e depe see.<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 10.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3032">Some in &thorn;e large felde as &yogh;e maie see.</L>
<L>There helpe&thorn; nouht al go&thorn;e &thorn;at ilke weie</L>
<L>&THORN;an may .I. seie &thorn;at al &thorn;is &thorn;inge mote deie</L>
<L>What make&thorn; &thorn;is bot Iubiter &thorn;e kinge<MILESTONE N="38a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3036">That is prince . and cause of al &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Conuertynge all vn-to his propre wille</L>
<L>ffro whiche it is darreyned so&thorn;e to tylle
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>And here a-geynes non creature on lyue</L>
<L N="3040">Of no degre aveile&thorn; for to striue<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 6.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than is it wisdome as &thorn;enkes me<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 11.</NOTE></L>
<L>To make vertue of necessitee</L>
<L>And take it wele &thorn;at we maye nouht eschewe</L>
<L N="3044">And name &thorn;at to vs al is dewe</L>
<L>And who grucche&thorn; ou&yogh;t he do&thorn;e folye<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 13.</NOTE></L>
<L>And rebel is to him &thorn;at al maie guye</L>
<L>And serteinly a man ha&thorn; most honoure<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 9, 12.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3048">To deyen in his excellence and floure</L>
<L>Whan he is seker of his good name</L>
<L>Than ha&thorn;e he done his frendes ne him no schame</L>
<L>And gladder ouhte his frendes bene of his de&thorn;e</L>
<L N="3052">Whan wi&thorn;e honoure is &yogh;olden vp &thorn;e bre&thorn;e</L>
<L>Than whanne his name apalled is for age</L>
<L>ffor al for&yogh;eten is his vessellage</L>
<L>Than is &thorn;e best as for a wor&thorn;i fame</L>
<L N="3056">To dey&yogh;en whan he is best of name</L>
<L>The contrarie of al &thorn;is is wilfulnes<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 13.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whi grucchen we whi haue we heuynes<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 14-17.</NOTE></L>
<L>That good Arcite of chiualrye &thorn;e floure</L>
<L N="3060">Departed is wi&thorn; dewte and wi&thorn; honoure</L>
<L>Owte of &thorn;is foule Prisone of &thorn;is life</L>
<L>Whi grucche&thorn; here his cosine and his wife</L>
<L>Of his welfare &thorn;at loue&thorn; him so wele</L>
<L N="3064">Kanne&thorn; he hem &thorn;onke nay . god wote neuer a dele</L>
<L>That bo&thorn;en his soule and eke him offende</L>
<L>And &yogh;it &thorn;ei mowe her lustes nou&yogh;t amende</L>
<L>What . may .I. conclude of &thorn;is longe serie</L>
<L N="3068">Bot after woo .I. rede vs to be merie<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 19.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;anke Iubiter al his grace</L>
<L>And er we departen frome &thorn;is place</L>
<L>.I. rede we make of sorwes two</L>
<L N="3072">O parfite Ioye lasteinge euermo</L>
<L>And loke&thorn;e nowe whe[r] moste sorwe is inne</L>
<L>Ther wil .I. firste amenden and be-gynne.
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>&para; Suster quod he &thorn;is is my ful assente</L>
<L N="3076">Wi&thorn; al &thorn;au-ys here of my parlemente.</L>
<L>That gentill Palamon &yogh;oure owen knyht<MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That serue&thorn; &yogh;owe wi&thorn; will and herte and myht</L>
<L>And euer ha&thorn;e do se&thorn; firste &yogh;e him knewe</L>
<L N="3080">That &yogh;e schall of &yogh;owere grace vpon him rewe</L>
<L>And taken him for husbonde and for lorde</L>
<L>Lene me &yogh;owre honde for &thorn;is is oure accorde</L>
<L>Lat see nowe of &yogh;owre wommanly pyte</L>
<L N="3084">He is a kinges bro&thorn;er sonne parde</L>
<L>And &thorn;ouhe he weere a pouer bachellere</L>
<L>Sen he ha&thorn;e serued &yogh;owe so mony a &yogh;ere</L>
<L>And had for &yogh;owe so grete aduersite</L>
<L N="3088">It moste be considered leue&thorn; me</L>
<L>ffor gentil mercye oute to passen riht</L>
<L>&THORN;an seide he &thorn;us to Palamon &thorn;e knyht</L>
<L>.I. trowe &thorn;ere nede&thorn;e litul sermonynge</L>
<L N="3092">To make &yogh;owe assente to &thorn;is &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Come&thorn; nere and take&thorn; &yogh;owre lady be &thorn;e honde</L>
<L>Be-twexen hem anone was maade &thorn;e bonde<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 69.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hiht Matrimoigne or mariage</L>
<L N="3096">Be al &thorn;e counsel and &thorn;e Baronage</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; al blis and melodye<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 72.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ha&thorn;e Palamon ywedded Emelye</L>
<L>An god &thorn;at ha&thorn;e al &thorn;is werlde wrouht</L>
<L N="3100">Sende him his loue &thorn;at ha&thorn; it dere bouht</L>
<L>ffor nowe is Palamon in al his wele<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 83.</NOTE></L>
<L>Leueinge in blis richesse and hele</L>
<L>And Emely him loue&thorn; so tenterly</L>
<L N="3104">And he hir se[r]uith so gentilly</L>
<L>That &thorn;ere no worde was hem be-twene</L>
<L>Of Iolousy or any o&thorn;er tene</L>
<L>Thus Ende&thorn; Palamon and Emelye</L>
<L N="3108">And god saue al &thorn;is faire compaignye</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>Explicit fabula</B> mylitis.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="89">
<HEAD>Incipit prologus Melendenarij</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e knyht had &thorn;us . his tale y-tolde</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e company nas &thorn;ere &yogh;onge ne holde</L>
<L>That he ne seide it was noble storye</L>
<L N="3112">And wor&thorn;i for to drawen in memorie</L>
<L>And nameliche &thorn;e gentils euerychone</L>
<L>Owre oste louhe and swore so mot .I. gone</L>
<L>This go&thorn;e ariht vnboklede is &thorn;e male</L>
<L N="3116">Lat see nowe who schal tel ano&thorn;er tale</L>
<L>ffor trewly &thorn;e game is wele be-gunne<MILESTONE N="39a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now telle&thorn; &yogh;e sire monke if &yogh;e kunne</L>
<L>Somewhat to white wi&thorn; &thorn;e knyhtes tale</L>
<L N="3120">&para; The Mellere &thorn;at for-dronken was al pale</L>
<L>So &thorn;at vnne&thorn; vpon his hors he sat</L>
<L>He nolde a-valen ney&thorn;e hode ne hat</L>
<L>Ne abide noman for his curtasie</L>
<L N="3124">Bot in Pilates voice he gan to crie</L>
<L>And swore be armes and be blode and bones</L>
<L>.I. can a noble tale for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; whiche .I. wil nowe qvite &thorn;e knyhtes tale</L>
<L N="3128">Owre oste sauhe &thorn;at he was dronken of ale</L>
<L>And seide abide Robin leue bro&thorn;ere</L>
<L>Som better man schal tel us firste a-no&thorn;er</L>
<L>Abide and late vs werken &thorn;reftely</L>
<L N="3132">Be goddes sowle quod he &thorn;at wil nouht .I.</L>
<L>ffor .I. wil speken or elles go my weye</L>
<L>Oure Oste ansewerd . tell on &thorn;an a deuelweye</L>
<L>Thowe ert a fole &thorn;i witte is ouer come</L>
<L N="3136">Nowe herken quod &thorn;e Mellere al and some</L>
<L>Bot first .I. make a protestacioun</L>
<L>&THORN;at .I. am dronken .I. knowe it be my sowne</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere if .I. speke or mys saie</L>
<L N="3140">Wiyte it &thorn;e ale of Sou&thorn;ewerk I. &yogh;owe praie
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>ffor .I. will tell a legende and a lif</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;en of a carpenter and his wif</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at a clerke ha&thorn;e sette &thorn;e wrihtes cappe</L>
<L N="3144">The reue ansewerde stinte &thorn;i clappe</L>
<L>Latt bue &thorn;i lewed dronken harlotrie</L>
<L>It is a sinne and eke grete folye</L>
<L>To appeiren any man or him defame</L>
<L N="3148">And eke to bringe wiues in suche fame</L>
<L>&THORN;ou maist ynouhe of o&thorn;ere &thorn;inges saine</L>
<L>This dronken Meller spak ful sone a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>And seid leue bro&thorn;er oswolde</L>
<L N="3152">Who ha&thorn;e no wif he is no cokewolde</L>
<L>But .I. seie nou&yogh;t &thorn;ere-fore &thorn;at &thorn;ou art oon</L>
<L>Ther bene ful gode wives Many on</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="3156">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whi ert &thorn;ou angri wi&thorn; my tale nowe</L>
<L>I. haue a wife perde as wele as &thorn;owe</L>
<L>&yogh;ete nolde .I. note for &thorn;e oxen in my plouhe</L>
<L N="3160">Tak vpon me more &thorn;an .I. nowhe</L>
<L>As demen of my self &thorn;at .I. were oone<MILESTONE N="39b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>.I. will beleue &thorn;at .I. am none</L>
<L>An husbonde schal nouht be inquisitif</L>
<L N="3164">Of goddes priuetees ne of his wif</L>
<L>So he may finde goddes foyson &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e remenant nede&thorn; nouht to enquere</L>
<L>What schold .I. more seie; Bot &thorn;is Mellere</L>
<L N="3168">He nolde his wordes for noman forbere</L>
<L>Bot [sayde] his cherles tale in his manere</L>
<L>Me a&thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at .I. schal reherce hem here</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-for euery . gentil whight .I. preie</L>
<L N="3172">Deme&thorn; nouht for goddes loue &thorn;at .I. seie</L>
<L>Of yuel enten bot &thorn;at .I. mot reherce</L>
<L>Her tales al be &thorn;ei better or werse</L>
<L>Or elles falsen somme of my matiere</L>
<L N="3176">And &thorn;ere-fore who so list nouht to here
<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>Torne ouere &thorn;e leue and chese a-no&thorn;er tale</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e schal finde . y-nowe grete and smale</L>
<L>Of storial &thorn;inge &thorn;at touche&thorn; gentillesse</L>
<L N="3180">And eke moralite and holynesse</L>
<L>Blame&thorn; nou&yogh;t me if &thorn;at &yogh;e chesen a-mys</L>
<L>The meller is a cherle &yogh;e knowe wele &thorn;is</L>
<L>So was &thorn;e reue eke and o&thorn;er mo</L>
<L N="3184">And harlotrye &thorn;ei tolden bo&thorn; tuo</L>
<L>Auise&thorn; &yogh;owe and putte me owte of blame</L>
<L>And eke men schal nou&yogh;te make ernest of game<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>Explicit</B> prologus.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="92">
<HEAD>Incipit fabula</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHilom &thorn;ere was dwellyng att Oxenford</L>
<L N="3188">A riche gnof &thorn;at gestis helde to bord</L>
<L>And of his craft he was a Carpentier</L>
<L>With him &thorn;ere was dwellinge a pouer scolier</L>
<L>Hadde lerne arte bot al his fantasie</L>
<L N="3192">Was torned for to leren astrologie</L>
<L>And cou&thorn;e a certeine of conclusions</L>
<L>To demen be interrogaciones</L>
<L>If &thorn;at men axed him in certeine houres</L>
<L N="3196">Whan men schold haue drouht or elles schoures</L>
<L>Or if men axed him what schal be-falle</L>
<L>Of euery &thorn;inge .I. may nouht reken alle</L>
<L>This clerke was cleped hende Nicholas</L>
<L N="3200">Of derne loue he cou&thorn;e and of solas</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-to he was sleight and wele priue</L>
<L>And like a maide meke for to see</L>
<L>A chambre had he in &thorn;at hostellerie<MILESTONE N="40a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3204">Alone wi&thorn;-oute any compaignie</L>
<L>fful fetisly diht wi&thorn; herbes swote</L>
<L>And he him selfe as swete as is &thorn;e rote</L>
<L>Of lycoris or of any settewale</L>
<L N="3208">His almagiste and bokes grete and smale</L>
<L>His Astrelabre longeinge to his arte</L>
<L>His augrim stones leyen faire a parte</L>
<L>On schelues chowched as his beddes hede</L>
<L N="3212">His prisse . ycouerid wi&thorn; a foldeynge rede</L>
<L>And al aboue &thorn;ere leie a gaie sawtrie</L>
<L>On whiche he made a nyht melodie</L>
<L>So swetely &thorn;at al &thorn;e chambre ronge</L>
<L N="3216">And Angelus ad virginem he songe</L>
<L>And after he songe &thorn;e kinges note</L>
<L>fful oft blissed was his mery &thorn;rote
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;e swete clerke his time spente</L>
<L N="3220">Affeter his frendes findeynge and his rente</L>
<L>This Carpenter had wedded newe a wif</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at he loued more &thorn;an his lif</L>
<L>Of .xviij. &yogh;ere sche was of age</L>
<L N="3224">Ielous he was and helde hire narwe in cage</L>
<L>ffor sche was wilde and &yogh;onge and he was holde</L>
<L>And demed him self bene like a cokewolde</L>
<L>He knewe nou&yogh;t Caton for his witte was rude</L>
<L N="3228">That bad men wedde his similitude</L>
<L>Men scholde wedde after hire astate</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;ou&thorn;e and elde is often att debate</L>
<L>Bot se&thorn;en &thorn;at he was fallen in &thorn;e snare</L>
<L N="3232">He moste endure as o&thorn;ere folke his kare</L>
<L>ffaire was &thorn;is &yogh;onge wif and &thorn;erto wi&thorn; al</L>
<L>As any wesel<NOTE PLACE="marg">[l: <I>later</I>]</NOTE> hir bodi gente and smal</L>
<L>A seinte sche wered barred al of silke</L>
<L N="3236">A barmeclo&thorn;e as white as any morwes mylke</L>
<L>Vppon hire lendes fol of mony a gore</L>
<L>White was hire smoke and broude al be-fore</L>
<L>And eke be-hinde on hire colere aboute</L>
<L N="3240">Of cole blak silke within and eke with-oute.</L>
<L>The tapes of hir white volupere</L>
<L>Were of &thorn;e same sute of hire colere</L>
<L>Hire felet broode of silke and sitt ful<NOTE PLACE="marg">[l: <I>later</I>]</NOTE> hihe</L>
<L N="3244">And sekurly sche had a lykuruse eye</L>
<L>fful small y-pulled was hire browes two.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o were bente. and blake as any. slo.</L>
<L>Sche was ful more blisfull for to see<MILESTONE N="40b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3248">Thane is &thorn;e newe perionet tree</L>
<L>And softer &thorn;an wolle is of a we&thorn;er</L>
<L>And be hir gyrdel<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gyrdel: <I>later</I>]</NOTE> hinge a purs of le&thorn;ere</L>
<L>Tassilde wi&thorn; selke a[n]d perlid wi&thorn; laton</L>
<L N="3252">In al &thorn;is werlde to seken vpe and downe</L>
<L>&THORN;ere is noman so wise &thorn;at cou&thorn;e &thorn;enche</L>
<L>So Gaye a popelote or swiche a wenche
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>fful brihter was &thorn;e schineinge of hir hewe</L>
<L N="3256">Than in &thorn;e toure &thorn;e noble forgode newe</L>
<L>Bott of hir songe it was so lowde and &yogh;erne</L>
<L>As any swalowe Chiterynge on a berne</L>
<L>There-to sche cou&thorn;e skippe and make a game</L>
<L N="3260">As any kide or calfe foloweynge his dame</L>
<L>Hir mou&thorn;e was swete as braket or &thorn;e me&thorn;e</L>
<L>Or horde of appeles layde in haye or he&thorn;e</L>
<L>Wynsinge sche was as a Ioli colte</L>
<L N="3264">Longe as a maste and vpriht as a bolte</L>
<L>A broche sche bare on hire loue colere</L>
<L>As brode as is &thorn;e boos of a bokelere</L>
<L>Hir schoes were laced on hir legges hihe</L>
<L N="3268">Sche was a primerol a pigges nye</L>
<L>ffor any lorde to liggen in his bedde</L>
<L>Or &yogh;it for any good &yogh;oman to wedde</L>
<L>&para; Nowe sire and eft sire so be-fell &thorn;e cas</L>
<L N="3272">That on .a. daie &thorn;is hende Nicholas</L>
<L>ffil wi&thorn; &thorn;is &yogh;onge wif to rage and to pleie</L>
<L>While &thorn;at hire husbond was att Osenaye</L>
<L>As clerkes ben ful sotel and ful wheinte</L>
<L N="3276">And priuelye he cauht hire be &thorn;e queynte</L>
<L>And seide. ywis bot if .I. haue my. will.</L>
<L>ffor derne loue of &thorn;e lemman .I. spill</L>
<L>And held hire harde be &thorn;e haunche bones</L>
<L N="3280">And seide lemman loue me wele att ones</L>
<L>Or .I. wille deyen also god me saue</L>
<L>And sche spronge as a colte do&thorn; in &thorn;e traue</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; hire hede sche wried fast a-waie</L>
<L N="3284">Sche seide .I. wil nouht kisse &thorn;e be my. faie</L>
<L>Whi labbe quod iche lat be nycholas</L>
<L>Or .I will crie out harrowe and alas</L>
<L>Do weie &yogh;oure hondes for &yogh;owre curtesie</L>
<L N="3288">This Nicholas gan mercie for to crie.</L>
<L>And spake so faire and proferd him so fast<MILESTONE N="41a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That sche hire loue grauntide him att last
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>And swore an he-o&thorn;e be seinte Thomas of Kent</L>
<L N="3292">That sche wolde be att is commandement</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at sche maie hir leisere wele aspie</L>
<L>Mine husbonde is so ful of Ielousye</L>
<L>That bot .I. weite wele and be priue</L>
<L N="3296">.I. whote riht wele .I. name but dede quod sche</L>
<L>&YOGH;e motte be ful derne as in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>Nay &thorn;ere-of care &thorn;e nouht quod Nicholas</L>
<L>A clerke hadde li&thorn;erli be-sette his while</L>
<L N="3300">Bot if he cou&thorn;e a carpenter begile</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;ei attorden and. y-sworne</L>
<L>To wayte a tyme as .I. haue tolde be-forne</L>
<L>Whan Nicholas hadde &thorn;is euery dele</L>
<L N="3304">And &thorn;akked hire aboute &thorn;e lendes wele</L>
<L>He kiste hire swete and take&thorn; his sautrie</L>
<L>And plaie&thorn; fast and make&thorn; melodie</L>
<L>&para; Than fel it &thorn;us &thorn;at to &thorn;e Parissche cherche</L>
<L N="3308">Cristes owen werke for to werche</L>
<L>This good wife went on an haly daie</L>
<L>Hire forhed schone as briht as any daie</L>
<L>So was it whassche whan sche lete hir werke</L>
<L N="3312">Nowe was &thorn;ere of &thorn;at chirche a parische clerke</L>
<L>The whiche &thorn;at was ycleped Absolon</L>
<L>Crull was his here and as &thorn;e gold it schone</L>
<L>And strouted as a ffan large and brode</L>
<L N="3316">fful streighte and euen lay his Ioly schode</L>
<L>His rud was rede his yen grei as goos</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; poules wyndowe coruen on his schoos</L>
<L>In hoses rede he went fetisly</L>
<L N="3320">Y-cladde he was ful smal and propurly</L>
<L>Al in a kertell of a liht wachett</L>
<L>fful faire and ful &thorn;ike be &thorn;e pointes sett</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere vpon he hadd a gaie surplise</L>
<L N="3324">As white as is &thorn;e blossome on &thorn;e Rise</L>
<L>A mery childe he was as god me saue</L>
<L>And wele cou&thorn;e he laten blode or clippe or schaue
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>And make a charter of londe or on quitance</L>
<L N="3328">In twenti manere quod he trip and daunce</L>
<L>After &thorn;e scole of Oxenforde &thorn;o</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his legges casten to and fro</L>
<L>And pleyen songes in a small rebibe<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3332">Ther-to he songe some time a loude quynyble</L>
<L>And also wele cou&thorn;e he pleie on a geterne</L>
<L>In all &thorn;e toune nas brewes ne tauerne</L>
<L>That he ne viset it wi&thorn; his solas</L>
<L N="3336">There any gailerd tapstere was</L>
<L>Bot so&thorn;e to seine he was sumdele squaymous</L>
<L>Of fartinge and of speche daungerous</L>
<L>&para; This absolon &thorn;at Ioly was and gaie</L>
<L N="3340">Go&thorn;e wi&thorn; a censer on &thorn;e haly daie</L>
<L>Sensynge &thorn;e wyues of &thorn;e parische faste</L>
<L>And many a louely loke on hem caste</L>
<L>And nameli on &thorn;is Carpenteres wif</L>
<L N="3344">To loken on hire him &thorn;ouhte a mery lyf</L>
<L>Sche was so propre and swete and licorous</L>
<L>I dar wele seie if sche hade bue a mous</L>
<L>And he a cat he wolde her hinte anone</L>
<L N="3348">This Pariche clerce. &thorn;is Ioly Absolone</L>
<L>Ha&thorn;e in his herte suche a loue longeinge</L>
<L>That of no wif toke he none offringe</L>
<L>For curtesye he seide he wolde none</L>
<L N="3352">The mone whan it was nyht ful briht schone</L>
<L>And absolon his geterne ha&thorn;e ytake</L>
<L>ffor paramoures he &thorn;ouhte for to wake</L>
<L>And for he go&thorn; Iolif and amorous</L>
<L N="3356">Til he came to &thorn;e Carpenters hous</L>
<L>A litel after cokkes had. ycrowe</L>
<L>And drissed him vp be a schot windowe</L>
<L>That was vp on &thorn;e carpenteres wall</L>
<L N="3360">He singes in his voice gentill and small</L>
<L>Nowe dere lady if &thorn;i willes be</L>
<L>.I. preie &yogh;owe &thorn;at &yogh;e wil rewe on me
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>fful wele accordant to his geterneynge</L>
<L N="3364">This Carpenter awoke and herd him singe</L>
<L>And spake vnto his wif and seide anone</L>
<L>What Alison heres &thorn;ou not Absolone</L>
<L>That chaunte&thorn; &thorn;us vnder oure boures wal</L>
<L N="3368">And sche ansewerde hir husbonde &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-al</L>
<L>&YOGH;is god wote Iohen .I. wote it euery. dele</L>
<L>&THORN;is passe&thorn; for&thorn;e what wil &yogh;e bet &thorn;an wele</L>
<L>ffro daie to daie &thorn;is Ioli Absolon</L>
<L N="3372">So wowe&thorn; hire &thorn;at him is woo be-goon</L>
<L>He wake&thorn; all &thorn;e nyght and al &thorn;e daie<MILESTONE N="42a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He kembed his lokkes brode and maade hem gaie</L>
<L>He wowe&thorn; hire be menes and brocage</L>
<L N="3376">And swore he wolde bene hir owen page</L>
<L>He singe&thorn; brokkinge as a nyhtingale</L>
<L>He sente hir Me&thorn;e and Piment and spyced ale</L>
<L N="3379">And weifres pipeinge hote vnder &thorn;e glede</L>
<L>And for sche was of towne he proferd mede<NOTE PLACE="marg">Vn Ouidius Ictibus agrestes</NOTE></L>
<L>For some folke wil be wonne with richesse</L>
<L>And sum for strokes and somme for gentilnesse</L>
<L>Somtime to schewe his lyhtnesse and Maistre</L>
<L N="3384">He plaie&thorn; Heraude vpon a scafolde hihe</L>
<L>Bot what aveile&thorn; him as in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>Sche loue&thorn; soo &thorn;is hende Nicholas</L>
<L>That absolon maie blowe &thorn;e bokkes horne</L>
<L N="3388">He ne ha&thorn;e for his laboure bot a scorene</L>
<L>And &thorn;us sche Make&thorn; Absolon hire Ape</L>
<L>And al his erneste torne&thorn; till a Iape</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e is &thorn;is prouerbe it is no lye</L>
<L N="3392">Men sein right &thorn;us Alweie &thorn;e neighe Sley&yogh;e</L>
<L>Make&thorn; &thorn;e fer leue to be lo&thorn;e</L>
<L>For &thorn;ouhe &thorn;at Absolon be woode or wro&thorn;e</L>
<L>Be cause &thorn;at he fer was from hir siht</L>
<L N="3396">This nyhe Nicholas stode in his liht</L>
<L>&para; Nowe bere &yogh;owe wele hende Nicholas</L>
<L>ffor Absolon may waile and singe Alas
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="98"></L>
<L>And so be-fell it on a seturdaie</L>
<L N="3400">This Carpentier was gone to Oseneye</L>
<L>And hende Nicholas and Alison</L>
<L>Accorded bue to &thorn;is conclusione</L>
<L>That Nicholas schapen hem a wile</L>
<L N="3404">&THORN;ese sely Ielouse husbonde to be-guyle</L>
<L>And if so be &thorn;e game went ariht</L>
<L>Sche scholde slepen in his arme al nyht</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is was his desire and hire also</L>
<L N="3408">And riht anone wi&thorn;-oute wordes moo</L>
<L>This Nicholas no langere wolde tarye</L>
<L>Bot do&thorn;e soft vn to his chambre Carye</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e mete and drinke for a daie or tweye</L>
<L N="3412">And to hir husbonde bad hire for to seie</L>
<L>If &thorn;at he axede after Nicholas</L>
<L>Sche scholde seie sche nyst where he was</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at daie sche seihe him nou&yogh;t with Eye<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3416">Sche trowed &thorn;at he was in sum Maledye</L>
<L>ffor for no crye hire maide cou&thorn;e him calle</L>
<L>He wolde ansewere for no&thorn;inge &thorn;at myht falle</L>
<L>This passe&thorn; for&thorn;e al &thorn;ilke Saturdaie</L>
<L N="3420">&THORN;at Nicholas stil in his chambur leye</L>
<L>And ete or slepede or dide what him liste</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e sonday &thorn;at &thorn;e sonday go&thorn; to riste</L>
<L>This sely Carpentier ha&thorn;e grete Merveile</L>
<L N="3424">Of Nicholas or what &thorn;inge miht him aile</L>
<L>And seide .I. am adrede be seint Thomas</L>
<L>It stonde&thorn; nouht a-riht wi&thorn; Nicholas</L>
<L>God schelde &thorn;at he deyede sodanly</L>
<L N="3428">This werlde is nowe ful tekel sikurly</L>
<L>.I. sihe to daie a corps borne to cherche</L>
<L>That nowe on Monondaie last .I. sawhe him werche</L>
<L>Go vp quod he vn to [his] knaue anone</L>
<L N="3432">Clepe att his dore or knoke wi&thorn; a stone</L>
<L>Looke howe it is and tel me boldely.</L>
<L>This knaue go&thorn; him vp ful studely
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>And att &thorn;e chambre dore while &thorn;at he stode</L>
<L N="3436">He criede and knokked as &thorn;at he were wode</L>
<L>What howe what do &yogh;e Maister Nicholay</L>
<L>Howe maie &yogh;e slepen al &thorn;e longe daie</L>
<L>Bot al for nouht he herde nouht a worde</L>
<L N="3440">An hole he fonde ful longe vpon a borde</L>
<L>There as &thorn;e catte was wonte inne for to crepe</L>
<L>And att &thorn;at hole he loke in ful depe</L>
