<L>And to him selfe he seide .I. scal &thorn;e qwite</L>
<L>Who rubbeth nowe who frote&thorn; nowe his lippes</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; duste wi&thorn; sonde. wi&thorn; strawe wi&thorn; clo&thorn;e wi&thorn;e chippes</L>
<L>Bot Absolon &thorn;at sei&thorn;e ful ofte Alas</L>
<L>My soule be-take .I. to sathenas</L>
<L>Bot me were leuere &thorn;an al &thorn;is toune quod he</L>
<L N="3752">Of &thorn;is dispite awroken for to be.</L>
<L>Alas quod he alas .I. ne hadde yblente<MILESTONE N="46b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His hote loue is colde and al yquente</L>
<L>ffor fro &thorn;at time &thorn;at he had kissed here ers</L>
<L N="3756">Of paramours he sett nouht a cres</L>
<L>ffor he was helede of his maladye</L>
<L>ffull oft paramours he gan defie</L>
<L>And weppe as do&thorn;e a childe &thorn;at is ybete</L>
<L N="3760">A soft pas he went ouere &thorn;e strete
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="108"></L>
<L>Vnto a smy&thorn;e Men clepen Daun geruays</L>
<L>&thorn;at in his forge smy&thorn;eie&thorn; . plouhe hernays</L>
<L>He scharpe&thorn; schare and culter bisilie</L>
<L N="3764">This Absolon knokke&thorn; al eselye</L>
<L>And seide vn to geruais and &thorn;at anone</L>
<L>What who art &thorn;ou . It am .I. Absolone</L>
<L>What Absolone . What cristes swete tree</L>
<L N="3768">Whi rise &yogh;e so ra&thorn;e . ey benedicite</L>
<L>Whate eyle&thorn; &yogh;owe some gaie gerle god it wote</L>
<L>Ha&thorn;e brouht &yogh;owe &thorn;us on &thorn;e veritote</L>
<L>Be seint note &yogh;e wote wele whatt .I. mene</L>
<L N="3772">This Absolon ne rouht nouht a bene</L>
<L>Of al his pleie no worde a&yogh;eine he &yogh;affe</L>
<L>He had more towe on his distaffe</L>
<L>Than geruays knewe and seide frende so dere</L>
<L N="3776">The hote Culter in &thorn;e chymene here</L>
<L>As lene it me .I. haue &thorn;er-wi&thorn;&thorn;e to done</L>
<L>.I wil bringe it a&yogh;ein ful sone</L>
<L>Gerueys ansewerde Certes were it golde</L>
<L N="3780">Or in a poke nobles al vntolde</L>
<L>Thowe scholdest haue as .I. am trewe smy&thorn;&thorn;e</L>
<L>Ey Cristes foo what will &yogh;e do &thorn;er-wi&thorn;&thorn;e</L>
<L>There-of quod Absolon be as be maye</L>
<L N="3784">I. schal wele telne it &thorn;e to morwe daie</L>
<L>And cauhte &thorn;e Culter be &thorn;e colde stele</L>
<L>fful soft owte att &thorn;e dore he gan stele</L>
<L>And wente vnto &thorn;e Carpentiers wal</L>
<L N="3788">He koughed first and knokked &thorn;er wi&thorn; al</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e wyndowe riht as he dide ere</L>
<L>This Alison ansewarde who his &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&thorn;at knokke&thorn; so .I. warant . it a &thorn;efe</L>
<L N="3792">Whi naye quod he god wote my swete lefe</L>
<L>.I. am &thorn;in Absolon &thorn;in derleinge</L>
<L>Of golde quod he .I. haue &thorn;e browht a ringe</L>
<L>Mi modere &yogh;afe it me so god me saue<MILESTONE N="47a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3796">fful fyne it is and &thorn;arto wel y-graue
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="109"></L>
<L>&thorn;is wil .I &yogh;euen &thorn;e . if &thorn;ou me kisse</L>
<L>&thorn;is Nicholas was resen for to pisse</L>
<L>And &thorn;ouhte he wolde amenden al &thorn;e Iape</L>
<L N="3800">He scholde kisse his ers er &thorn;at he scape</L>
<L>And vpe &thorn;e windowe dede he hastely.</L>
<L>And oute his ers he put priuelye</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e buttok to &thorn;e haunche bone</L>
<L N="3804">And &thorn;er-wi&thorn; spak &thorn;is clerke &thorn;is absolone</L>
<L>Speke swete birde .I. note where &thorn;u ert</L>
<L>This Nicholas anone lete flie a fart</L>
<L>As grete as it had be a &thorn;onder dinte</L>
<L N="3808">That wi&thorn; &thorn;at stroke he was almost yblint</L>
<L>And he was rede wi&thorn; his yren hote</L>
<L>And Nicholas in &thorn;e ers he smote</L>
<L>Of go&thorn;e &thorn;e scynne an handebrode aboute</L>
<L N="3812">The hote culter so brent his toute</L>
<L>&para; And for &thorn;e smerte he wende for to deie</L>
<L>As he were woode for woo he ganne to creie</L>
<L>Helpe water water helpe for goddes herte</L>
<L N="3816">This Carpentier owte of his slomere sterte</L>
<L>And herde one Crie water as he was wode</L>
<L>And &thorn;ouht alas Nowe comme&thorn; Noes flode</L>
<L>And sett him vp with wordes moo</L>
<L N="3820">And wi&thorn;e an ax he spote &thorn;e corde a twoo</L>
<L>And doune go&thorn;e al He fonde Nei&thorn;er to selle</L>
<L>No brede Nor ale til he cam to &thorn;e selle</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e flore and &thorn;er aswowen he laye</L>
<L N="3824">Vp sterte Hire Alison and Nicholaye</L>
<L>And criede oute and harrowe in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>The neyhebores bo&thorn;e smal and grete.</L>
<L>In ronnen for to gauren vpon &thorn;is man</L>
<L N="3828">That on swoune laie bo&thorn;e pale and wan</L>
<L>For wi&thorn; &thorn;at fal he broken ha&thorn; his arme</L>
<L>Bot stonde he moste vn-to his owen harme</L>
<L>For when he spake he was a-none borne doune</L>
<L N="3832">Wi&thorn;e hende Nicholas and Alisoune
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="110"></L>
<L>Thei tolden euery man &thorn;at he was wode</L>
<L>He was a-gast so of &thorn;e Nowels flode</L>
<L>Thurghe fantasie &thorn;at of his vanite</L>
<L N="3836">He had him bouhte knedeyng tubbes &thorn;re</L>
<L>And had hem hongede in &thorn;e roofe aboue<MILESTONE N="47b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at he preide him for goddes loue</L>
<L>To sitten in &thorn;e roof par compaignye</L>
<L N="3840">The folke gan lawhen att his fantasie</L>
<L>An to &thorn;e roofe &thorn;ei keken and &thorn;ei gape</L>
<L>And torned al his harme vnto a Iape.</L>
<L>ffor what so &thorn;is Carpentier ansewerde</L>
<L N="3844">It was for nouht no man his resone herde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;e o&thorn;es grete he was so sworne y-doune</L>
<L>That he was holden woode in all &thorn;e toune</L>
<L>ffor euery clerke anone riht ichone helde wi&thorn; o&thorn;ere</L>
<L N="3848">Thei seide &thorn;e man is wode my leue bro&thorn;ere</L>
<L>And euery white gan lauhen att his strif</L>
<L>Thus swyued was &thorn;e Carpentiers wif</L>
<L>ffor al his kepeinge and his Ielouseie</L>
<L N="3852">And Absolon ha&thorn;e keste hire hir ne&thorn;er eye</L>
<L>And Nicholas is scalded in his toute</L>
<L>This tale is done and god saue al &thorn;e route.<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>Explicit fabula</B> Molendenarii</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="111">
<HEAD>Incipit prologus.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHan folke han lawhen att &thorn;is nyce caas</L>
<L N="3856">Of Absolon and hende Nicholas</L>
<L>Diuers folke diuersely &thorn;ei seide</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;e more parte &thorn;ei lowhe and pleide</L>
<L>Ne att &thorn;is tale I. sauhe no man him greue</L>
<L N="3860">Bot it were onely Oswolde &thorn;e Reue</L>
<L>Be cause he was of Carpenteres craft</L>
<L>A litel ire is in his hert laft</L>
<L>He gan to gruche and blame it a lite</L>
<L N="3864">So &thorn;eyke quod he ful wele cou&thorn; .I. &yogh;ow quyte</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; blerynge of a proude mellers eye</L>
<L>If &thorn;at me liste to speke of ribaudie</L>
<L>Bot ik am olde me list nouht pleie for age</L>
<L N="3868">Gras time is done my foder is forage</L>
<L>This white toppe writes myne olde &yogh;eres</L>
<L>Myne herte is also moulde . as myne heres</L>
<L>Bot if .I. fare as do&thorn;e an openers</L>
<L N="3872">&thorn;at ilke fruyte is euer longe &thorn;e werse</L>
<L>Til it be roten in molloke and in stree</L>
<L>We olde men .I. drede so fare we</L>
<L>Til we be roten can we nouht be ripe</L>
<L N="3876">We hopen al-weie while &thorn;e werld wil pipe</L>
<L>For in owre wille &thorn;ere stike&thorn; euer a naile<MILESTONE N="48a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To haue an hore here and a grene taile</L>
<L>As ha&thorn;e a leke for &thorn;ouhe oure myht be gone</L>
<L N="3880">Owre wille desire&thorn; foly euery in one</L>
<L>ffor whan we maie nouhte done &thorn;an wil we speke</L>
<L>&YOGH;it in owre hasschen olde is fire y-reke</L>
<L>ffoure gledes han we whiche .I. schal deuise</L>
<L N="3884">Auauntynge . lyeinge . Anger . and Couetise</L>
<L>This foure sperlkes longe&thorn; vnto elde</L>
<L>Owre olde limmes Mowe wele bene vnwelde
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>Bot wil<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>h</I> and <I>e</I> have been scratched out to re|duce this word.]</NOTE> ne schal nouht failen &thorn;at is so&thorn;e</L>
<L>And &yogh;it haue .I. alwei a coltes to&thorn;e</L>
<L>As mony a &yogh;ere as it is passed henne</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;at my tap of lif beganne to renne</L>
<L>ffor sekerly whan .I. was borne a-none</L>
<L N="3892">De&thorn;e drowhe &thorn;e tape of lif and lete it gone</L>
<L>And euery si&thorn;&thorn;e ha&thorn;&thorn;e so &thorn;e tap .I.-ronne</L>
<L>Till &thorn;at al-moste al empti is the tonne</L>
<L>The streme of lif nowe droppe&thorn; on &thorn;e chimbe</L>
<L N="3896">The seli tonge maie wele ringe and climbe</L>
<L>Of wrechedenesse &thorn;at passed is ful &yogh;ore</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; olde folke saue dotage is no more</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;at oure oste had herd &thorn;is sermonynge</L>
<L N="3900">He gan to speke as lordly as a kinge</L>
<L>He seide what a-mounte&thorn; al &thorn;is witte</L>
<L>What schal we speke al day of holy writte</L>
<L>The deuel maade a reue for to preche</L>
<L N="3904">Or of souter schipman or a leche</L>
<L>Say for&thorn;e &thorn;i tale and tary nouht &thorn;e time</L>
<L>Loo depford and it is halfe weie prime</L>
<L>Loo grenewiche &thorn;at mony a schrewe is inne.</L>
<L N="3908">It were al time &thorn;i tale for to gynne</L>
<L>&para; Nowe sires quod Oswalde &thorn;e reue</L>
<L>.I preie &yogh;owe al &thorn;at &yogh;e nouht &yogh;owe greue</L>
<L>Thowhe .I. ansewere and sumdel sett his howue</L>
<L N="3912">For leueful it is wi&thorn; force force to schowue</L>
<L>This dronken melle ha&thorn;e .I.-tolde us here</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at be-giled was a carpentier</L>
<L>Parauentur in scoren for .I. am one</L>
<L N="3916">And be &yogh;oure leue .I. schal him quyte anone.</L>
<L>Riht in his cherles termes wil .I. speke</L>
<L>I preie to god his neke mot he breke</L>
<L>He can wele in myne eye seen a stalke</L>
<L N="3920">Bot in his owen he can nouht sene a balke
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000141.tif" N="113">
<HEAD>&thorn;e revese tale / begynne&thorn; here<MILESTONE N="48b" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Trumpyngton nouht fer fro Cambrugge</L>
<L>There go&thorn;e a broke . and ouere &thorn;at a brugge</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e whiche broke &thorn;ere stant a Melle</L>
<L N="3924">And &thorn;is is verrey so&thorn; &thorn;at .I. telle</L>
<L>A meller was &thorn;ere duellinge mony a daie</L>
<L>As any pekok he was proude and gaie</L>
<L>Pipe he cou&thorn;e and fisshen and nettes bete</L>
<L N="3928">And torne coppes and wele wrastel and schete.</L>
<L>Ay be his belte he bare a longe Panade</L>
<L>And of a swerde ful trenchant was &thorn;e blade</L>
<L>A Ioly popper bare he in his puche</L>
<L N="3932">Ther was no man for perile dorst him touche</L>
<L>A scheffeld &thorn;witel bare he in his hose</L>
<L>Rounde was his face and kamuse was his nose</L>
<L>As pilled as an hape was his Sculle</L>
<L N="3936">He was a Market beter att &thorn;e fulle</L>
<L>Ther was no whihte &thorn;at dorst honde on him ligge</L>
<L>Bot if he swore he schole anone abegge</L>
<L>A &thorn;efe he was for so&thorn;e of corne and mele</L>
<L N="3940">And &thorn;at a sleigh . and vsand for to stele</L>
<L>His name was hoten deynous symkyne</L>
<L>A wife he had commen of Noble kinne</L>
<L>The parson of &thorn;e toune hir fadere was</L>
<L N="3944">Wi&thorn;e hire he &yogh;afe mony a panne of bras</L>
<L>For &thorn;at Simkin schold in his blode allye</L>
<L>Sche was yfostrede in a Nonnerye</L>
<L>ffor Simkin wold no wif as he seide</L>
<L N="3948">Bot sche were wele ynorissched and a maide</L>
<L>To saue his astate of &yogh;omanrye</L>
<L>And sche was proude and pert as a pye</L>
<L>A ful faire siht was it vppon hem tuo</L>
<L N="3952">On Halidaies be-forne hire wolde he go
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>With his tepet wonden aboute his hede</L>
<L>And sche cam after in a gide of rede</L>
<L>And simkyn hadd hosen of &thorn;e same</L>
<L N="3956">Thare dorste no whiht clepen hire bot dame</L>
<L>Was none so hardy &thorn;at wente be &thorn;e weie</L>
<L>That dorste with hire ones rage or pleie</L>
<L>Bot if he wolde be sleine of Simkynne</L>
<L N="3960">Wi&thorn; panade or wi&thorn; knyf or wi&thorn; Boydekynne</L>
<L>ffor Ielous folke bene perlous euer mo</L>
<L>Al-gates &thorn;ei wolde here wives wenden so</L>
<L>And eke for sche was somdele smoterliche<MILESTONE N="49a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3964">Sche was as deyne as water in a diche</L>
<L>As ful of Hokere and of bismare</L>
<L>Hir &thorn;ouht &thorn;at a lady schold spare</L>
<L>What for hire kinred and hire Nortelrie</L>
<L N="3968">That sche had lerned in the Nonnerye</L>
<L>A douhter had &thorn;ei be-twexe hem two</L>
<L>Of twenty &yogh;ere wi&thorn;-outen any moo</L>
<L>Saueinge a childe &thorn;at was of halfe &yogh;ere age</L>
<L N="3972">In cradel it ley. and was a propur page</L>
<L>&thorn;is wenche &thorn;ikke and wele y-groue was</L>
<L>wi&thorn; Camois nose and eyen . grei as glasse</L>
<L>wi&thorn; buttokes brode . and brestes rounde and hihe</L>
<L N="3976">Bot rihte faire was hire here .I. wil nouht lye</L>
<L>The parson of &thorn;e toune for sche was so faire</L>
<L>In purpos was to make hire his hayre</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of his Catel and his Mesuage</L>
<L N="3980">And strange he maade it for hire Mariage</L>
<L>His purpos was to be-stowe hire hye</L>
<L>In to somme wor&thorn;i blode of Auncestrie</L>
<L>ffor holy cherche goode mot be despended</L>
<L N="3984">On holy cherche blode &thorn;at is descended</L>
<L>Ther-fore he wolde his holy blode honoure</L>
<L>&thorn;ouhe &thorn;at holy cherche scholde deuoure</L>
<L>Grete soken ha&thorn;e &thorn;is meller oute of doute</L>
<L N="3988">Wi&thorn; wete and malte of al &thorn;e lande aboute
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>And namely &thorn;er was a grete College</L>
<L>Men clepen &thorn;e solier halle att Cantabregge</L>
<L>There was hir whete and eke his malte ygrounde</L>
<L N="3992">And on a daye it happide on a stounde</L>
<L>Seeke laie &thorn;e Maunciple on a Maledye</L>
<L>Men wenden wisly &thorn;at he scholde deye</L>
<L>ffor whiche &thorn;is meller stale bo&thorn;e mele and corne</L>
<L N="3996">An hundre&thorn; time more &thorn;an be-forne</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ere be-forne he stale bot curteysly</L>
<L>Bot nowe he was a &thorn;ef outrageou[s]ly</L>
<L>ffor whiche &thorn;e wardeine chidde and made fare</L>
<L N="4000">Bot &thorn;ere-of sette &thorn;e Meller nouht a tare</L>
<L>He crakke bost and swore it was nouht soo</L>
<L>Than were &thorn;ere &yogh;onge scolers tuo</L>
<L>That dwelten in &thorn;e hal of whiche .I. seye</L>
<L N="4004">Testif &thorn;ei were and lusti for to pleie</L>
<L>And oonely for her mir&thorn;e and reuelrie<MILESTONE N="49b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e wardeine besely &thorn;ei crie</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue hem leue bot a litel stounde</L>
<L N="4008">To goone to melle and seen her corne . y-grounde</L>
<L>And hardely &thorn;ei dorst leine her neke</L>
<L>&thorn;e Meller schold nouht stele hem half a pekke</L>
<L>Of corne ne be sleihte ne be force heme reue</L>
<L N="4012">And att &thorn;e laste &thorn;e wardeine &yogh;af hem leue</L>
<L>Iohn hight &thorn;at one . and Aleyne hiht &thorn;at o&thorn;ere</L>
<L>Of one towne were &thorn;ei borne &thorn;at hiht stro&thorn;ere</L>
<L>ffer in &thorn;e Nor&thorn;e .I. can nouht tel where</L>
<L N="4016">This Aleine Make&thorn; redi all his gere</L>
<L>And one an hors &thorn;is sak he cast anone</L>
<L>ffor&thorn;e go&thorn;e Aleyne &thorn;e clerke and also Ione</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; good swerde and wi&thorn; bokeler be his side</L>
<L N="4020">Iohn knewe &thorn;e weie him nede&thorn; no gide</L>
<L>And att &thorn;e melne &thorn;e sakke adoune he laythe</L>
<L>Alayn spak first . al haile Simonde in fay&thorn;e</L>
<L>Howe fare&thorn; &thorn;i faire douhter and &thorn;i wife</L>
<L N="4024">Alayne welcome quod Simkin be my life
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>And Iohn also howe nowe what do &yogh;e here</L>
<L>Be god quod Iohn . Simond . nede ha&thorn;e no pere</L>
<L>Him be-houe&thorn; serue him self &thorn;at ha&thorn;e no sweyne</L>
<L N="4028">Or elles he is a foole as clerkes seine</L>
<L>Oure Maunciple .I. hope he wil be dede</L>
<L>Swa werkes him &thorn;e wanges in his hede</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-fore es .I. come and alswa Aleine</L>
<L N="4032">To grinde oure corne and carie it ham a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>.I. prei &yogh;owe spede vs he&thorn;en &thorn;at &yogh;e maye</L>
<L>It schal be done quod Simkin be my faye</L>
<L>&para; What will &yogh;e done while &thorn;at it is in hande</L>
<L N="4036">Bed god . riht be &thorn;e hoper will .I. stande</L>
<L>Quod Iohn and see howe &thorn;e corne go&thorn;e Inne</L>
<L>&YOGH;it sawe .I. neuer be my fader kinne</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at &thorn;e hoper wagges till and fra</L>
<L N="4040">Aleyne Ansewerd Iohn wil-tow swa</L>
<L>Than wil .I. be by-ne&thorn;e be my croune</L>
<L>And see howe gates &thorn;e mele falles adowne</L>
<L>In-till &thorn;e troughe &thorn;at schall be my disporte</L>
<L N="4044">Quod Iohn in faa&thorn;e .I. es al of &yogh;owre sorte</L>
<L>.I. es as il a Melnere as es &yogh;e</L>
<L>This Mellere smyled of here Nicite.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ouht al &thorn;is nys done bot for a wyle<MILESTONE N="50a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4048">&thorn;ei weene &thorn;at no man may &thorn;em be-gile</L>
<L>Bot be my &thorn;reft &yogh;it schal .I. blere here eye</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e sleight in hire philosophie</L>
<L>&thorn;e moo qweinte crekes &thorn;at &thorn;ei make</L>
<L N="4052">&thorn;e more wil .I. stele whan .I. take</L>
<L>In stede of flowre &yogh;it will .I. &yogh;eue hem branne</L>
<L>The grettest clerke ne is nou&yogh;t &thorn;e wiseste manne</L>
<L>As whilome to &thorn;e wolfe &thorn;us spak &thorn;e mare</L>
<L N="4056">Of al hire arte counte .I. nouhte a tare</L>
<L>Oute att &thorn;e dore he go&thorn;e ful priuelye</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he sawhe his time softly</L>
<L>He loke&thorn;e vp and doune til he haue founde</L>
<L N="4060">The clerkes hors &thorn;ere as it stode bounde
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>Be-hinde &thorn;e Mille vnder a leuesel</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e hors he go&thorn; him feire and wel</L>
<L>He strepe&thorn; of &thorn;e bridel riht a-none</L>
<L N="4064">Whan &thorn;e hor[s] was laus he ginne&thorn; to gone</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e fenne &thorn;ere wilde mares renne</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e wi&thorn;e wehe &thorn;oruhe &thorn;ikke and &thorn;oruh &thorn;enne</L>
<L>This mellere go&thorn;e a&yogh;ein no worde he seide</L>
<L N="4068">Bot do&thorn; his note and wi&thorn; his clerkes pleide</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at her corne was faire and wele ygrounde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e mele is sakked and ybounde</L>
<L>This Iohn go&thorn;e owte and finde&thorn; his hors aweie</L>
<L N="4072">And gan to crie harrowe and walaweie</L>
<L>Oure hors is loste Aleine for goddes banes</L>
<L>Steppe on &thorn;i fete man come of al att anes</L>
<L>Alas oure wardeine has his palfraie lorne</L>
<L N="4076">This Aleine al for-&yogh;at bo&thorn;e mele and corne</L>
<L>Al was owte of his mynde his hosbandrie</L>
<L>What whilke waye es he gane he gan to crye</L>
<L>The wife cam lepeinge inwarde att a renne</L>
<L N="4080">Sche seide Alas &yogh;oure hors go&thorn;e to &thorn;e fenne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wilde mares as faste as he may go</L>
<L>Vn&thorn;anke com on his hand &thorn;an bonde him so</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at better scholde haue knet &thorn;e Reyne</L>
<L N="4084">Allas quod Iohn Aleine for cristes peine</L>
<L>Lay doune &thorn;i swerde . and I wil myne alswa</L>
<L>.I. es ful swift god wate as is a ra</L>
<L>Be goddes hert he sal not scape vs ba&thorn;e</L>
<L N="4088">Whi ne hadde &thorn;ou putte &thorn;e capel in &thorn;e la&thorn;e</L>
<L>Il a hayle be god aleyne &thorn;ou es a grete fonne<MILESTONE N="50b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thes sely Clerkes han ful fast ronne</L>
<L>To-warde &thorn;e fenn bothen Aleyne and eke Iohn</L>
<L N="4092">And whan &thorn;e Meller sihe &thorn;at &thorn;ei were gone</L>
<L>He half a busschel of her flour ha&thorn;e take</L>
<L>And bad his wife go knede it in a kake</L>
<L>And seide .I. trowe &thorn;e clerkes weren aferd</L>
<L N="4096">&yogh;it can a meller Make a clerkes berde
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>ffor al his arte &yogh;it late hem gone hire weie</L>
<L>Lo where he go&thorn;e &yogh;e latt &thorn;e children pleie</L>
<L>Thei get him nouht so lihtly be my crowne</L>
<L N="4100">&thorn;eis seli clerkes rennen vp and doune</L>
<L>wi&thorn; kepe kepe stande stande .Iossa warderere</L>
<L>Ga whistil &thorn;ou and .I. schal kepe him here</L>
<L>Bot schortly til it was verrei nyht</L>
<L N="4104">&thorn;ei cou&thorn;e nouhte &thorn;ouhe &thorn;ei dide al her myht</L>
<L>Hir caple cache he ran alwei so faste</L>
<L>Til in a diche &thorn;ei cauht him att &thorn;e laste</L>
<L>wery and wete as best is in &thorn;e reine</L>
<L N="4108">Come&thorn; sely Iohn . and with him comme&thorn; Aleine</L>
<L>&para; Alas quod Iohn &thorn;e daie &thorn;at .I. was borne</L>
<L>Nowe er we dreuen til he&thorn;inge and til scoren</L>
<L>Owre corne is stolle Men wil vs foles calle</L>
<L N="4112">Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e wardeine and owre felawes alle</L>
<L>And Namely &thorn;e Meller walewaye</L>
<L>Thus pleyne&thorn; Iohn as he ga&thorn; be &thorn;e weie</L>
<L>Towarde &thorn;e Melle and bayard in his honde</L>
<L N="4116">The meller sittinge be &thorn;e fire he fonde</L>
<L>ffor it was nyht and fer&thorn;er myht he nouht</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;e loue of god &thorn;ei him be-souht</L>
<L>Off herboruhe and of ese as for her penye</L>
<L N="4120">The Mellere seid ageine . if &thorn;ere be anye</L>
<L>Swyche as it is &yogh;ute schal &yogh;e haue &yogh;oure part</L>
<L>Myne hous is streite bot &yogh;e haue lerned arte</L>
<L>&YOGH;e can be argument Make a place</L>
<L N="4124">A Mile brode of twenti foote of space</L>
<L>Latt se nowe if &thorn;is place Maie suffise</L>
<L>Or make it Romer wi&thorn; speche as is &yogh;oure gise</L>
<L>Now Simond seid &thorn;is Iohn be seint Cutberde</L>
<L N="4128">Ay es &thorn;ou Mery and &thorn;at is faire ansewerde</L>
<L>.I. haue herde saye Men sall taken of tua &thorn;inges</L>
<L>Swilke as he fint or swilke as he bringes</L>
<L>Bot specialy .I. praie &thorn;e ooste dere<MILESTONE N="51a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4132">Gete vs sum mete and drinke and make vs chere
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>And we wil payen trewly att fulle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; empti handes men maye nouhte haukes tulle</L>
<L>Lo here owre siluere redy for to spende</L>
<L N="4136">This Meller to &thorn;e toune his douhter sende</L>
<L>ffor al and brede and rosted hem a goos</L>
<L>And bonde her hors it schold no more go loos</L>
<L>And in his owen chambre he maade hem a bede</L>
<L N="4140">Wi&thorn; schetes and wi&thorn; chalons faire y-sprade</L>
<L>Nouht fro his owen bedde ten fote or tuelue</L>
<L>His douhter had a bedde al be hire selue</L>
<L>Riht in &thorn;e same chambre by. and bye</L>
<L N="4144">It myht be no bet and cause whie</L>
<L>Ther was no romer herboruhe in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>Thei soupen and &thorn;ei speken hem to solace</L>
<L>And drenken euer stronge ale att &thorn;e beste</L>
<L N="4148">Aboute mydnyhte wente &thorn;ei to reste</L>
<L>Wele ha&thorn;e &thorn;is Mellere vernysshed his hede</L>
<L>fful pale he was for-dronken and nouht rede</L>
<L>He &yogh;exe&thorn; and he speke&thorn; &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e nose</L>
<L N="4152">As he war on &thorn;e quakke or one &thorn;e pose</L>
<L>To bede he go&thorn;e and wi&thorn; him go&thorn;e his wif</L>
<L>As any Iay he lyht was and Iolif</L>
<L>So was hir Ioly whistel wele y-wette</L>
<L N="4156">The crade att &thorn;e bedes feete is sette</L>
<L>To rokken and to &yogh;eue &thorn;e childe to souke</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at dronken was al in &thorn;e crouke</L>
<L>To bedde wente &thorn;e douhter riht anone</L>
<L N="4160">To bedde go&thorn;e Aleine and also Iohn</L>
<L>There nas no more &thorn;em neded no dwale</L>
<L>This Meller ha&thorn;e so wisly bibbed ale</L>
<L>That as an hors he snowrte&thorn; in his slepe</L>
<L N="4164">Ne of his taile behinde he toke no kepe</L>
<L>His wif bare him a burdon a ful stronge</L>
<L>Men myhten here routeynge halfe a forlonge</L>
<L>The wenche route&thorn;e eke par comopaignye</L>
<L N="4168">Aleyne &thorn;e clerke &thorn;at herde &thorn;is melodye
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>He poukede Ioh&omacr;n and seide slepest &thorn;ou</L>
<L>Herdest &thorn;ou euer slyke a sange or nowe</L>
<L>Lo swilke a compline es be-tuene hem alle.</L>
<L N="4172">A wilde fire on &thorn;eire bodies falle</L>
<L>Wha herde euere slyke a ferly &thorn;inge<MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;ei schal haue &thorn;e floure of il endynge</L>
<L>&para; This lange myhte &thorn;er sal .I. haue na reste</L>
<L N="4176">Bot &yogh;it na force al sal be for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>ffor Iohn seide he as euere mote .I. &thorn;riue</L>
<L>If &thorn;at .I. maye &thorn;e wenche wil .I. swyue</L>
<L>Some esement ha&thorn; &thorn;e lawe schapen vs</L>
<L N="4180">ffor Iohn &thorn;ere is a lawe &thorn;at sei&thorn;e &thorn;us</L>
<L>&thorn;at if a man in o pointe be agreuede</L>
<L>&thorn;at in a-no&thorn;er he sal be releuede</L>
<L>Oure corne is stollen so&thorn;ely it is no naye</L>
<L N="4184">And we haue hade an yuel fitte to daye</L>
<L>And seen .I. schal haue none amendement</L>
<L>Ageyn my losse .I. wil haue esement</L>
<L>Be goddes saule it sal nane o&thorn;ere be</L>
<L N="4188">This Iohn Ansewerde Aleine avise &thorn;e</L>
<L>The Meller is a parlous man he seide</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he oute of his slepe a-breide</L>
<L>He myhte done vs ba&thorn;e a velanye</L>
<L N="4192">Aleyne ansewarde .I. count him nat a flye</L>
<L>And vpe he reste and be &thorn;e wenche he crepte</L>
<L>&thorn;is wenche lay vpriht and fast sche slepte</L>
<L>Tyl he so nyhe was or sche myht spye</L>
<L N="4196">That it hadde bene to late for to crie</L>
<L>And schortly for to seye &thorn;ei were att one</L>
<L>Now plaie Aleine for .I. wil speke of Iohne</L>
<L>This Iohn li&thorn;e still a furlonge waie or two</L>
<L N="4200">And to him selfe he make&thorn; reu&thorn;e and woo</L>
<L>Alas quod he &thorn;is is a wikked Iape</L>
<L>Now may .I. saie &thorn;at .I. es bot an ape</L>
<L>&yogh;it ha&thorn;e my felawe sum what for his harme</L>
<L N="4204">He ha&thorn;e &thorn;e Mellers douhter in his arme
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>He Auntre him and ha&thorn; his nedes spedde</L>
<L>And .I. ly as a draf sakke in my bedde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is Iape is tolde ano&thorn;er daie</L>
<L N="4208">.I. sall be holden a daff a Cokeneye</L>
<L>.I. wil arise and auntre it it be my faithe</L>
<L>Vnhardy is vnsely &thorn;us men sey&thorn;e</L>
<L>And vppe he ros and softly he went</L>
<L N="4212">Vn to &thorn;e cradel and in his honde it hente</L>
<L>And bare it soft vn to his beddes fete</L>
<L>Sone after &thorn;e wife hire routeynge lete</L>
<L>An gan to wake and went hir oute to pisse<MILESTONE N="52a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4216">And cam a-gaine and gan hir cradel Misse</L>
<L>An groped here and &thorn;ere bot sche fonde none</L>
<L>Allas quod sche .I. had almost mys gone</L>
<L>I hadde al-moste gone to &thorn;e clerkes bedde</L>
<L N="4220">Ey benedicite &thorn;an had .I. foule .I.-spedde</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e sche go&thorn;e til sche &thorn;e cradel fonde</L>
<L>Sche grope&thorn; alwey for&thorn;er wi&thorn; hire honde</L>
<L>And fonde &thorn;e bedde and &thorn;ouht nouht bot goode</L>
<L N="4224">Be cause &thorn;at &thorn;e cradel by it stode</L>
<L>And neste where sche was for it was derke</L>
<L>Bot faire and wele sche crepe in to &thorn;e clerke</L>
<L>And li&thorn;e ful still. and wolde haue cauht a slepe</L>
<L N="4228">Wi&thorn;-in a while &thorn;is Iohn &thorn;e clerke vp lepe</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is goode wife he lei&thorn;e on sore</L>
<L>So mery a fitte ne had sche not full &yogh;ore</L>
<L>He prike&thorn; harde and depe as he were madde</L>
<L N="4232">&thorn;is Ioly lif haue &thorn;ese tuo clerkes ladde</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;redde koke be-gan to singe</L>
<L>Aleyne wex wery in &thorn;e dawneinge</L>
<L>ffor he had swonken all &thorn;e longe nyht</L>
<L N="4236">And seide faire wele Malyn swete whight</L>
<L>The daie is come .I. maie no longer bide</L>
<L>Bot euere-mo where-so .I. go or ride</L>
<L>.I. am &thorn;ine owen clerke so haue .I. sele</L>
<L N="4240">Nowe dere lemman quod sche go fare wele.
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>Bot or &thorn;ou go oo &thorn;inge .I. will &thorn;e telle</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ou wendest homwarde be &thorn;e melle</L>
<L>Riht att &thorn;e entre of &thorn;e dore be-hinde</L>
<L N="4244">Thou schalt a cake of halfe a buschell finde</L>
<L>That was ymaked of &thorn;in owen mele</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at .I. helpe my sire for to stele</L>
<L>And goode lemman and god &thorn;e saue and kepe</L>
<L N="4248">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde almost he gan to wepe</L>
<L>Aleine vprist and &thorn;ouht or &thorn;at.It dawe</L>
<L>.I. wil go crepen inne be my felawe</L>
<L>And fonde &thorn;e cradel wi&thorn; his honde anone</L>
<L N="4252">Be god &thorn;ouht [he] al wrange .I. haue mys gone</L>
<L>Myne hede is toty of my swynke to nyhte</L>
<L>&thorn;at make&thorn; me &thorn;at .I. go nouht arihte</L>
<L>.I. wote wele be &thorn;e cradel .I. haue mys go</L>
<L N="4256">Here li&thorn;e &thorn;e mellere and his wif al so</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e he go&thorn;e a twenty deuel weye<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e bedde &thorn;ere as &thorn;e Meller leye</L>
<L>He wende haue cropen be his felawe Ioh&omacr;n</L>
<L N="4260">And by &thorn;e Meller ine he crape a-none</L>
<L>And kauht him be &thorn;e nekke and soft he spakke</L>
<L>He seide &thorn;ou Iohn &thorn;ou swineshede awake</L>
<L>ffor cristes soule and here a noble game</L>
<L N="4264">ffor [by] &thorn;at lorde &thorn;at called is seinte Iame</L>
<L>As .I. haue &thorn;ries in &thorn;is schorte nyhte</L>
<L>Swyuede &thorn;e meller douhter bolt vpriht</L>
<L>While &thorn;ou hast as a cowarde bene agaste</L>
<L N="4268">&YOGH;e false harlot quod Meller haste</L>
<L>A false traytur false traitur quod he</L>
<L>Thou schal be dede be goddes dignite</L>
<L>Who dorste be so bolde to disparage</L>
<L N="4272">My douhter &thorn;at is comen of suche lignage</L>
<L>&para; And be &thorn;rote bolle he cauht Aleyne</L>
<L>And he hinte him dispitously a-&yogh;eine</L>
<L>And one &thorn;e nose he smote him wi&thorn; his fiste</L>
<L N="4276">Doune run &thorn;e blode streme vpon his briste
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e flore wi&thorn; nose and mou&thorn;e to-broke</L>
<L>&THORN;ei walowe as tuo pigges in a poke</L>
<L>And vpe &thorn;ei gone and doune a-&yogh;eine anone</L>
<L N="4280">Til &thorn;at &thorn;e meller sporned att a stone</L>
<L>And doune he fel bakwarde vpon his wif</L>
<L>That wist no &thorn;inge of &thorn;is nice strif</L>
<L>ffor sche was fal a slepe a litel wyht</L>
<L N="4284">Wi&thorn; Ioh&omacr;n &thorn;e clerke &thorn;at waked had al &thorn;e nyhte</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e fal oute of here slepe sche braide</L>
<L>Helpe holy cros of bromeholme sche saide</L>
<L>In manus tuas lorde to &thorn;e .I. call</L>
<L N="4288">Awake Simonde &thorn;e fende is on me fall</L>
<L>Myne herte is broken helpe .y. ne am bot dede</L>
<L>There one vp my wombe and vp myne hede</L>
<L>Helpe Simkyn for &thorn;e false clerkes fihte</L>
<L N="4292">&THORN;is Iohn stert vp al so fast as euer he myhte</L>
<L>And grasped be &thorn;e walles to and fro</L>
<L>To finde a staf and sche sterte vp al so</L>
<L>And knewe &thorn;at estres beter &thorn;an dide &thorn;at Iohn</L>
<L N="4296">And by &thorn;e wal a staf sche fande a-none</L>
<L>And sawhe a litel schimeringe of a lyght</L>
<L>ffor att an hole in schone &thorn;e mone briht</L>
<L>And be &thorn;at liht sche seihe hem bo&thorn;e two<MILESTONE N="53a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4300">Bot sekerly sche nyst who wa[s] who</L>
<L>Bot as sche sauhe a white &thorn;inge in hire eye</L>
<L>And whan sche gan &thorn;is white aspie</L>
<L>Sche wende &thorn;e clerke had wered a volupere</L>
<L N="4304">And wi&thorn;e &thorn;e staf sche drowhe ay nere and nere</L>
<L>And wende haue hit &thorn;is Aleine att full</L>
<L>And smote &thorn;e Mellere on &thorn;e pilled scoll</L>
<L>That downe he go&thorn;e and cried harrowe .I. deye</L>
<L N="4308">This Clerkes bet him wele and lete him lye</L>
<L>And grey&thorn;en &thorn;eym and toke her hors a-none</L>
<L>And eke here mele and on &thorn;eire weie &thorn;ei gone</L>
<L>And att Melle &yogh;it &thorn;ei toke her cake</L>
<L N="4312">Of halfe a busschel flowre ful wel y-bake
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>&para; Thus is &thorn;e proude Mellere wele ybete</L>
<L>And ha&thorn;e yloste &thorn;e grindeinge ofe &thorn;e whete</L>
<L>And paiede for &thorn;e sopere euery dele</L>
<L N="4316">Of Aleyne and of Iohn &thorn;at bet him wele</L>
<L>His wif is swyue and his douhte als</L>
<L>Lo swyche it is a mellere to be fals</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to &thorn;is prouerbe is seide ful so&thorn;e</L>
<L N="4320">Him &thorn;ar note wene wele &thorn;at yuel do&thorn;e</L>
<L>A gylour schal him self be-giled be.</L>
<L>And god &thorn;at sitte&thorn; hihe in Maiestee</L>
<L>Saue al &thorn;is compainye grete and smale</L>
<L N="4324">Thus haue .I. quyte &thorn;e Meller in my tale<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit fabula</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="125">
<HEAD>Incipit Prologus Coce.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THe coke of london while &thorn;e reue spakke</L>
<L>For Ioy him &thorn;ouht he clowde him on &thorn;e bakke</L>
<L N="4327">Ha ha quod he for cristes passione</L>
<L>This Mellere ha&thorn;e a scharpe conclusione<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;e koce.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vpon his argument of herbegage</L>
<L>Wele seide Salamon in his langage</L>
<L>Ne bringe nouhte euery man in to &thorn;ine hous</L>
<L N="4332">For herberwynge be nyhte is perilous</L>
<L>Wele ouhte a man avisede for to be</L>
<L>Whome &thorn;at he brouhte in to his priuete</L>
<L>.I. prei to god so &yogh;eue me sorwe and care</L>
<L N="4336">If euer si&thorn;en .I. hight Hogge of ware</L>
<L>Herd .I. mellere better sett a werke</L>
<L>He had a Iape of Males in &thorn;e derke</L>
<L>An &thorn;ere-fore if &yogh;e wowche saue to here<MILESTONE N="53b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4340">Bot god for-bede &thorn;at we stente here</L>
<L>A tale of me &thorn;at am a por man</L>
<L>.I. wil &yogh;owe tel as wele as euer y can</L>
<L>A litel Iape &thorn;at felle in owre Citee</L>
<L N="4344">&para; Owre Oste ansewerde and seide .I. graunt it &thorn;e</L>
<L>Now tell on Roger. loke &thorn;at it be goode</L>
<L>For mony a paste haste &thorn;ou laten blode</L>
<L>And mony a Iak of douere hast &thorn;ou solde</L>
<L N="4348">That ha&thorn; bene twis hote and twis colde</L>
<L>Of Mony a pilgrim hast &thorn;ou cristes curse</L>
<L>For of &thorn;i percelly &yogh;it &thorn;ei fare &thorn;e wrse</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei haue eten wi&thorn; &thorn;e stoble goose</L>
<L N="4352">For in &thorn;i schope is mony a flie lose</L>
<L>Nowe tell on gentil roger be &thorn;i name</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it .I. prey &thorn;e be nouhte wrothe for game</L>
<L>A man maie seie ful lo&thorn;e in game and plaie</L>
<L N="4356">Thou seist ful so&thorn;e quod Roger be my faie
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>Bot so&thorn;e pleie. quade pleie as the flemynge sei&thorn;e</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-fore herry baillif be &thorn;i fei&thorn;e</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou nouht wro&thorn;e er we departen here</L>
<L N="4360">&thorn;ouhe &thorn;at myne tale be of an Ostelere</L>
<L>Bot na&thorn;eles .I. wil nou&yogh;t tel it &yogh;it</L>
<L>Bot or we departe .I.-wis &thorn;ou schalt be quyt</L>
<L>And ther wi&thorn; al he lowhe and made chere</L>
<L N="4364">And seide his tale as &yogh;e schal after here<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit prologus.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="127">
<HEAD>Incipit fabula</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>APrentis whilom duelled in oure Cite</L>
<L>And of a craft of vitaillers was he</L>
<L>Gaillard he was as goldefinche in &thorn;e schawe</L>
<L N="4368">Broune as a bery. a propur schort felawe</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; lokkes blake y-kempt ful fetisly</L>
<L>Daunce he cou&thorn;e so wele. and Iolyly</L>
<L>&thorn;at he was clepede Perkinne reueloure</L>
<L N="4372">He was as ful of loue and paramour</L>
<L>As is &thorn;e hyve ful of hony swete</L>
<L>Wele was &thorn;e wenche wi&thorn; him myht mete</L>
<L>Att euery bridel wolde he singe and hoppe</L>
<L N="4376">He loued bett &thorn;e tauerne &thorn;an his maistier schoppe</L>
<L>For whan &thorn;er any rydeinge was in chepe</L>
<L>Owte of &thorn;e schoppe &thorn;eder wolde he lepe</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at he hadde al &thorn;e siht yseyne</L>
<L N="4380">And daunced wele wolde he nou&yogh;t come a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>And gaderd him a Meyne of his sorte<MILESTONE N="54a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To hoppe and singe and maken swiche disporte</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere &thorn;ei setten steuen for to mete</L>
<L N="4384">To pleine att &thorn;e dys in suche a strete</L>
<L>For in &thorn;e toune was &thorn;ere no prentis</L>
<L>&THORN;at fairer cou&thorn;e cast a paire of dis</L>
<L>Than perkyn cou&thorn;e and &thorn;ere-to he was fre</L>
<L N="4388">Of his dispense in place of priuete</L>
<L>&para; That fonde his Maister wele in his chaffare</L>
<L>For oft time he fonde his box ful bare</L>
<L>For sekurly a prentis reueloure</L>
<L N="4392">&thorn;at haunte&thorn; dis. riot or paramoure</L>
<L>His Maister schal it in his schoppe a-bye</L>
<L>Al haue he not part of &thorn;e menstralcye</L>
<L>For &thorn;eft and ryot &thorn;ei bene conuertible</L>
<L N="4396">Al conne he plaie on geterne or ribible
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>Reuele and treu&thorn;e as in a louhe degre</L>
<L>Thei bene ful wro&thorn;e aldaie as men maie see</L>
<L>This Ioly prentis with his maister bode</L>
<L N="4400">Til he weer nyhe oute of his prentishode</L>
<L>Al were he snybbed bo&thorn;e erly and late</L>
<L>And sum tyme ladde wi&thorn; reuel to newgate</L>
<L>Bot att &thorn;e last his maister him be-&thorn;ought</L>
<L N="4404">Vpon a daie whan he his paper souht</L>
<L>Of a prouerbe &thorn;at sei&thorn;e &thorn;is same worde</L>
<L>Wele better is roten appel oute of horde</L>
<L>Than &thorn;at it rote al &thorn;e remenant</L>
<L N="4408">So fare&thorn; it be a riotous seruant</L>
<L>It is full lasse harme to latt it passe</L>
<L>&THORN;an he schende al &thorn;e seruantes in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>Thare-for his maister &yogh;af him aquitance</L>
<L N="4412">And bad him go wi&thorn; sorwe and wi&thorn; meschaunce</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;is Iolif prentise had his leue</L>
<L>Nowe lat him riote al &thorn;e nyhte or leue</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ere is no &thorn;ef wi&thorn;-owten a lowke</L>
<L N="4416">&THORN;at helpe&thorn; him to wasten and to sowke</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at he bribe can or borwe maye</L>
<L>Anone he sent his bedde and his araie</L>
<L>Vnto a Conper of his owen sorte</L>
<L N="4420">&THORN;at loued dis and reuel and disporte</L>
<L>And had a wife &thorn;at helde for countinance</L>
<L>A schoppe and swyued for his sustenance.<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="link"><PB REF="00000157.tif" N="129">
<HEAD>APPENDIX TO GROUP A. [THE SPURIOUS TALE OF GAMELYN.] [Spurious Link.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fye &thorn;er-one it is so foule .I. will nowe tell no for&thorn;ere<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For schame of &thorn;e harlotrie &thorn;at sewe&thorn; after</L>
<L>A velany it were &thorn;are-of more to spell</L>
<L N="4">Bot of a knyhte and his sonnes My tale .I. wil for&thorn;e tell</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>[THE SPURIOUS TALE OF GAMELYN.] [Tale.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1">And &thorn;ere-fore listene&thorn;. and herkene&thorn; &thorn;is tale ariht.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e schullen here of a douhte knyht</L>
<L>Sir Iohn of Boundys was his name</L>
<L>He cou&thorn;e of nortur and muchel of game</L>
<L>&thorn;re sonnes &thorn;e knyht had and wi&thorn; his body he hem wanne</L>
<L>The eldest was a muche schrewe and sone he beganne</L>
<L>His bre&thorn;erne loued wele here fader and of him were agast</L>
<L N="8">The eldest deserued his fader curs and had it att &thorn;e last</L>
<L>The good knyht his fadere leuede so &yogh;ore</L>
<L>That de&thorn;e was commen him to and handeled him sore</L>
<L>The goode knyht cared sore seke &thorn;er he leye</L>
<L N="12">How his children schold leuen after his deye</L>
<L>He had bue wide where bot no husbonde he was</L>
<L>All &thorn;e londe &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[he <I>later</I>]</NOTE> had was verrey purchas</L>
<L>Fayne he wolde it were y-dressed a-monge hem al</L>
<L N="16">That iche of hem miht have his parte as it wald fal</L>
<L>Tho sente he in-to Contre after wise knyhtes</L>
<L>To helpen delen his londes and drisse hem to rihtes</L>
<L>He sent hem worde by lettres &thorn;ei scholden hihe belyue</L>
<L N="20">If &thorn;ei wolde speke wi&thorn; him if &thorn;ei were on lyue
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>Tho &thorn;e knyhtes herden seek &thorn;at he laye</L>
<L>Had &thorn;ei no reste ney&thorn;er nyht nor daye</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ei cam to hime &thorn;ere he lay stille</L>
<L N="24">On his de&thorn; bede to abide goddes wille</L>
<L>Than seide &thorn;e good knyhte seke &thorn;ere he lay</L>
<L>Lordes .I. &yogh;owe warne so&thorn;e wi&thorn;-owten nay</L>
<L>.I. may no longer leue here on &thorn;is stonde</L>
<L N="28">ffor &thorn;orwhe goddes will de&thorn; draue&thorn; me to grounde.</L>
<L>Ther nas none of hem all &thorn;at herde him a-riht</L>
<L>That &thorn;ei hadden rew&thorn;e of &thorn;at ilke knyht</L>
<L>And seid sir for goddes loue ne dismay &yogh;owe nouht</L>
<L N="32">God maye done bote of bale &thorn;at is nowe ywrouht</L>
<L>Than spake &thorn;e good knyht seeke &thorn;ere he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[he <I>later</I>]</NOTE> laie</L>
<L>Bote of bale god may sende .I. wote it is no naye</L>
<L>Bot .I. be seke &yogh;ow knyhtes for &thorn;e loue of me</L>
<L N="36">Go&thorn; and dresse&thorn; my londes amonge myne sonnes &thorn;re</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e loue of God dele&thorn; hem nouht a-mys</L>
<L>And for-&yogh;ete nouht Gamelyn my yonge son &thorn;at i</L>
<L>Take&thorn; hede to &thorn;at one as wele as to &thorn;e to&thorn;er<MILESTONE N="55a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="40">Selde &yogh;e see any heire helpen his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>Tho lete &thorn;ei &thorn;e knyht lyen &thorn;at was nouht in hele</L>
<L>And wenten in to counseil his londes for to dele</L>
<L>ffor to delen hem al to one &thorn;at was here &thorn;ouhte</L>
<L N="44">And for gamelin was &yogh;ongest he schold haue nouht</L>
<L>All &thorn;e londe &thorn;at &thorn;ere was &thorn;ei dalten it in tuo</L>
<L>And leten Gamelyn &thorn;e &yogh;onge wi&thorn;-owten lande go</L>
<L>And iche of hem seide to o&thorn;ere ful loude</L>
<L>His bre&thorn;erne mow &yogh;euen him londe whan he goode coude</L>
<L N="49">Whan &thorn;ei hadde deled &thorn;e lond att &thorn;eire will</L>
<L>They comen to &thorn;e knyht &thorn;ere he laie ful still</L>
<L>And tolde him a-none howe &thorn;ei had wrouht</L>
<L N="52">And &thorn;e knyht &thorn;ere he laie liked it riht nouht</L>
<L>&para; Than seide &thorn;e knyht be seinte Martine</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;at &yogh;e haue done &yogh;it is &thorn;e londe myne</L>
<L>ffor goddes loue neyboures stonde&thorn; al still</L>
<L N="56">And .I. will delen my londe riht after my will
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>Iohn myne eldest son schal haue ploues fiue</L>
<L>&thorn;at was my faders heritage while he was on lyue</L>
<L>And my Meddelest son fiue plowhes of londe</L>
<L N="60">That .I. helpe for to geten wi&thorn; my riht honde</L>
<L>And al myn o&thorn;ere purchas of londes and of ledes</L>
<L>That .I. be-quethe Gamelyne and al my goode stedes</L>
<L>And .I. be-seeke &yogh;owe good men &thorn;at lawe conne of londe</L>
<L N="64">ffor Gamelyn loue &thorn;at my quest stonde</L>
<L>&para; Thus dalte &thorn;e knyht his londe be his daye</L>
<L>Riht on his de&thorn;e bed seke &thorn;ere he laye</L>
<L>And sone afterward he laye stone still</L>
<L N="68">And deide whan time came as it was cristes will</L>
<L>Anone as he was dede and vnder gars graue</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;e alder bro&thorn;er giled &thorn;e &yogh;onge knaue</L>
<L>And toke in-to his honde his londe and his lede</L>
<L N="72">And Gamelin him selfe to cle and to fede</L>
<L>He clo&thorn;ed him and fedde yuel. and eke wro&thorn;e</L>
<L>And lete his for fare and his house&yogh; bothe</L>
<L>His Parkes and his wodes and dide no &thorn;inge wel</L>
<L N="76">And se&thorn;&thorn;en he it abouhte on his faire fel</L>
<L>So longe was Gamelin in his bro&thorn;ers hall</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e strongest of good will &thorn;ei douten him all</L>
<L>Ne was &thorn;ere none &thorn;er-inne &yogh;onge ne olde</L>
<L N="80">That wold wre&thorn;&thorn;e ware he neuer so bolde</L>
<L>&para; Gamelyn stode vp on a daie in his bro&thorn;ere &yogh;erde<MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And be-gan wi&thorn; his honde to handel his berde</L>
<L>He &thorn;ouhte on his londes &thorn;at layen vnsawe</L>
<L N="84">And his faire Okes &thorn;at doune were drawe</L>
<L>His parkes were broken and his dere reuede</L>
<L>Of all his goode stedes was none him be-leuede</L>
<L>His howses weren vnhelde and ful yuel y-diht</L>
<L N="88">Tho &thorn;ouht Gamelyn it wente nouht a-riht</L>
<L>Afterwarde cam his bro&thorn;er walkinge &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And seide to Gamelin is oure mete &yogh;ere</L>
<L>&thorn;o him wre&thorn;&thorn;ed Gamelyn and suore be goddes boke</L>
<L N="92">Thou schalt go bake &thorn;i selfe .I. wil nou&yogh;t be &thorn;i koke
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="132"></L>
<L>Howe bro&thorn;er Gamelyn howe answeres &thorn;ou nowe</L>
<L>Thou spak neuer suche a worde as &thorn;ou dost nowe</L>
<L>Be my fai&thorn;e seide Gamelin now me &thorn;enke&thorn; nede</L>
<L N="96">Of al &thorn;e harmes that .I. haue .I. toke neuer are hede</L>
<L>My parkes bene broken and myn dere be reuede</L>
<L>Of myne armoure and my stedes nouht is me be-leued</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at my ffader me be-quathe al go&thorn;e to schame</L>
<L N="100">And &thorn;er-for haue &thorn;ou goddes curse bro&thorn;er be &thorn;i name</L>
<L>&para; Than be-spakke his bro&thorn;er &thorn;at rape was of rees</L>
<L>Stond still gedelinge and hold riht &thorn;i pes</L>
<L>Thou schalt be faine for to haue &thorn;i mete and &thorn;i wede</L>
<L N="104">What spekest &thorn;ou gamelin of londe or of lede</L>
<L>Than seide Gameline &thorn;e childe &thorn;at was &yogh;inge</L>
<L>Cristes curs mot he haue &thorn;at clepe&thorn; m[e] gedelinge</L>
<L>.I. am no wers gadelyn ne no wers whyght</L>
<L N="108">Bot borne of lady and geten of a knyht</L>
<L>Ne dorste he nouht to Gamelyin neere a fote go</L>
<L>Bot cleped to him his men and seide to hem &thorn;o</L>
<L>Go&thorn;e and bete &thorn;is boye and reue&thorn; him his witte</L>
<L N="112">And lat him leren a-no&thorn;er time to answere me bitte</L>
<L>Than seide &thorn;e childe &yogh;onge Gamelyn</L>
<L>Cristes curs most &thorn;ou haue bro&thorn;er art &thorn;ou myne.</L>
<L>And if schal algate be beten a-none</L>
<L N="116">Cristes curs must &thorn;ou haue bot &thorn;ou be &thorn;at one</L>
<L>And anon his bro&thorn;er in &thorn;at grete hete</L>
<L>Made his men to fet staues Gamelin for to bete</L>
<L>Whan euery of hem had a staf ynome</L>
<L N="120">Gamely was war &thorn;oo he sey hem comen</L>
<L>Tho Gamelyn seye hem com he loked ouere all</L>
<L>And was ware of a pestel stondeinge vnder a wall</L>
<L>Gamelyn was liht and &thorn;eder gan he lepe<MILESTONE N="56a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="124">And droue al his bre&thorn;es men riht on an hepe</L>
<L>He loked as wilde lyon and leide on good wone</L>
<L>Tho his bro&thorn;er sawhe &thorn;at &thorn;ei be-gan to gone</L>
<L>He fleyhe vpe in-til a lofte and schotte &thorn;e dore fast</L>
<L N="128">Thus Gamelyn with his pestel made hem al a-gast
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="133"></L>
<L>Som for for Gamelines loue and somme for his eye</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ei drouhe be halues whan he be-gan to pleye</L>
<L>What nowe seide Gamelin yeuel mot &yogh;e &thorn;e</L>
<L N="132">Wil &yogh;e beginne contik and so sone flye</L>
<L>Gamelin souht his bro&thorn;ere whider he was flowe</L>
<L>And sawh where &thorn;at he loked oute at a windowe</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er seide Gamelyn come a litel nere</L>
<L N="136">And .I. wil teche a pleie att &thorn;e bokelere</L>
<L>His bro&thorn;er him ansewarde and swore be seint Richere</L>
<L>While &thorn;e pestel is in &thorn;i honde .y. come &thorn;e no nere</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er .I. wil make &thorn;i pees .I. swere be goddes ore</L>
<L N="140">Cast awaie &thorn;i Pestel and wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e nomore</L>
<L>.I. mot nede seide Gamelyne wra&thorn;&thorn;e me att ones</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou wolde make &thorn;i men breke my bones</L>
<L>Ne had .I. had maine and miht in bo&thorn;e myn armes</L>
<L N="144">To fende hem from me &thorn;ei wolde haue done me armes</L>
<L>Gamelin seide his bro&thorn;ere be &thorn;ou nouht wro&thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor to seen &thorn;e haue harme me were riht lo&thorn;e</L>
<L>.I. ne dide it nouht bro&thorn;er but for a fondeinge</L>
<L N="148">ffor to loken if &thorn;oue were stronge and art so &yogh;ynge</L>
<L>Come a-doune &thorn;an to me and graunt me my bone</L>
<L>Of &thorn;inge .I. will &thorn;e axen and we schal sauhte sone</L>
<L>&para; Doune &thorn;an cam his bro&thorn;er &thorn;at fikel was and fel</L>
<L N="152">And was riht sore agast of &thorn;e pestel</L>
<L>He seide bro&thorn;er Gameline ax me &thorn;i bone</L>
<L>And loke &thorn;ou me blame bot .I. it graunt &thorn;e sone</L>
<L>Than seide Gamelyin bro&thorn;e ywis</L>
<L N="156">And we schol bene att one &thorn;ou most me graunt &thorn;is</L>
<L>All &thorn;at my fader me bequa&thorn;e while he was on lyue</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most do me it haue if we scholl nouht striue</L>
<L>That schalt &thorn;ou haue Gamelyn .I. swere be goddes ore</L>
<L N="160">Al &thorn;at &thorn;i fader &thorn;e be-qua&thorn;e &thorn;ouhe &thorn;ou woldest haue more</L>
<L>Thi londe &thorn;at lie&thorn; ley wele it schal be sowe</L>
<L>And &thorn;in house reised vpe &thorn;at ben leide so lowe</L>
<L>Thus seide &thorn;e knyht to Gameline be mow&thorn;e</L>
<L N="164">And &thorn;ouht of falsenes as he wele cou&thorn;e
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="134"></L>
<L>The knyht &thorn;ouht on treson and Gamelin &thorn;ouht none<MILESTONE N="56b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And went and kissed his bro&thorn;er And whan &thorn;ei weren att one</L>
<L>Alas &yogh;onge Gamelyne no &thorn;inge he ne wiste</L>
<L N="168">With suche false treson his bro&thorn;er him kyst</L>
<L>Lysten and lythes and holde&thorn; &yogh;oure tonge.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e schal here talkeinge of Gamelin &thorn;e &yogh;onge</L>
<L>Ther was &thorn;ere be-side cride a wrastlinge</L>
<L N="172">And &thorn;er for &thorn;ere was sette a rame and a ringe</L>
<L>And Gamelyn was in wil to wende &thorn;er to</L>
<L>ffor to prouen his myht what he cou&thorn;e do</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;ere seide Gameline be seint Richere</L>
<L N="176">Thou moste lene me to nyht a litel coursere</L>
<L>&thorn;at is frische to &thorn;e spores on for to ride</L>
