<L>And to his tweine bre&thorn;er ful sone he came</L>
<L>Sir seide sir Ote to &thorn;e Scherref &thorn;oo</L>
<L N="736">We bene bot &thorn;ree bre&thorn;ern schal we neuer be mo</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou hast prisoned &thorn;e best of all</L>
<L>Suche a-no&thorn;er Iuel mot him befall</L>
<L>Sire Ote, seide &thorn;e false knyht lat be &thorn;i curs</L>
<L N="740">Be god for &thorn;i wordes he schal fare &thorn;e wurs
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="150"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e kinges prison he his ynomme</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere he schal abide vnto &thorn;e iustice come</L>
<L>Pardie seide sire Ote Better it schall be</L>
<L N="744">.I. bidde him to mainprise &thorn;at &thorn;ou graunt to me</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e next siteinge of deliuerance</L>
<L>And lat &thorn;at Gamelin stonde to his chaunce</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;e in suche a forward .I. take him to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="748">And be &thorn;i faderes soule &thorn;at be-&yogh;ate &thorn;e and me</L>
<L>Bot he be redi whan &thorn;e Iustice sitte</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt bere &thorn;e Iuggement for all &thorn;i grete witte</L>
<L>.I. graunt wele quod sire ote &thorn;at it so be</L>
<L N="752">Lat do liuer him a-none and tak him to me</L>
<L>Tho was Gameline deliuerde to sir Ote his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>And &thorn;at nyht dwelden &thorn;e tone wi&thorn; &thorn;e to&thorn;ere</L>
<L>On &thorn;e morwe seide Gamelin to sir Ote &thorn;e hende</L>
<L N="756">Bro&thorn;e he seide .I. mot for so&thorn;e fro &thorn;e wende</L>
<L>To loke how my &yogh;onge men leden here lif</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ei leuen in ioye or elles in strif</L>
<L>Be gode seide sir hote &thorn;at is a colde rede</L>
<L N="760">Now .I. see &thorn;at al &thorn;e carke schal fal on myne hede</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;e Iustice sitte and &thorn;ou be nouht yfounde</L>
<L>.I. schal anone be taken and in &thorn;i stede ybounde</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er seide Gamelin dismaie &thorn;e nouht</L>
<L N="764">ffor be seint Iame in Galeis &thorn;at mony men ha&thorn; souht</L>
<L>If &thorn;at god almyhty holde me my lif and witte<MILESTONE N="63b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>.I. wil be &thorn;ere redy whan &thorn;e Iustice sitte</L>
<L>Than seide sir Ote til gamelin god schelde &thorn;e fro schame</L>
<L N="768">Com whan &thorn;ou seest time and bringe vs oute of blame</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Gamelin went &thorn;o vnder wode rise</L>
<L N="772">And fonde &thorn;ere playinge men of prise</L>
<L>Tho was &yogh;onge Gamelin riht glad ynouhe</L>
<L>Whanne he fonde his men vnder woode bouhe</L>
<L>Gamelin and his men talken in fere</L>
<L N="776">And &thorn;ei had good Game here maister to here
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="151"></L>
<L>His men tolden him of aventures &thorn;at &thorn;ei had founde</L>
<L>And Gamelin hem tolde a&yogh;ein howe he was fast bounde</L>
<L>Whan Gamelin was outelawe he hadde no cors</L>
<L N="780">Ther was no man &thorn;at for him ferde &thorn;e wors</L>
<L>Bot Abbotes and priours and monke and chanone</L>
<L>On hem left he nouht whan he myht hem nome</L>
<L>While Gamelin and his men made mer&thorn;es rive</L>
<L N="784">The fals knyht his bro&thorn;er yuel most he &thorn;riue</L>
<L>ffor he was fast aboute bo&thorn;e daie and o&thorn;er</L>
<L>ffor to hire &thorn;e queste for to honge his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>&para; Gamelin stode vpon a daie and he be-helde</L>
<L N="788">&THORN;e wode and &thorn;e schawes in &thorn;e wilde felde</L>
<L>He &thorn;ouht on his bro&thorn;er howe him be-hette</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde be redy whan &thorn;e Iustice sette</L>
<L>He &thorn;ouht wele &thorn;at he wolde wi&thorn;-oute delaie</L>
<L N="792">Com afor &thorn;e Iustice to kepen his daye</L>
<L>And seide to his &yogh;onge men diht &yogh;owe &yogh;are</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;e Iustice sitte we mot be &thorn;are</L>
<L>ffor .I. am vnder borwe til &thorn;at .I. come</L>
<L N="796">And my bro&thorn;er for me to prison schal be nomme</L>
<L>Be seint Iame seide his &yogh;onge men and &thorn;ou reede &thorn;erto</L>
<L>Ordeigne howe it schal be and it schal be do</L>
<L>While Gameline was cominge &thorn;er &thorn;e Iustice satt</L>
<L N="800">The false knyht his bro&thorn;e for-&yogh;ate he nou&yogh;t &thorn;att</L>
<L>To hire men on his queste to hangen his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>&THORN;ouhe &thorn;ei had nouht &thorn;e tone he wolde haue &thorn;at o&thorn;ere</L>
<L>Tho cam Gamelin fro vnder wode rise</L>
<L N="804">And brouht wi&thorn;e hem &yogh;onge men of prise</L>
<L>I se wele saide Gamelin &thorn;e Iustice is sette</L>
<L>Go a-forne Adam and loke how it spette</L>
<L>Adam went in to &thorn;e hall and loke al aboute</L>
<L N="808">He sawhe &thorn;ere stand lordes grete and stoute</L>
<L>And sir Ote his bro&thorn;ere fetterd ful faste<MILESTONE N="64a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Tho went Adam oute as he were agaste</L>
<L>Adam seide to Gamelin and to his felawes all</L>
<L N="812">Sire Ote stant fetterd in &thorn;e mote hall
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="152"></L>
<L>&YOGH;onge men seide Gamelin &thorn;is here &yogh;e alle</L>
<L>Howe sir Ote stant fetterd in &thorn;e mote halle</L>
<L>If god &yogh;ife vs grace wele for to do</L>
<L N="816">He schal it a-bigge &thorn;at brouht it &thorn;er-to</L>
<L>Than seide Adam &thorn;ot lokkes had hore</L>
<L>Cristes curs mot he haue &thorn;at him bonde so sore</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou wilte Gamelin do after my rede</L>
<L N="820">&THORN;are is none in &thorn;e hall schal bere awaie his hede</L>
<L>Adam seide Gamelin we wil nouht do soo</L>
<L>We wil sle &thorn;e Giltif and late &thorn;e o&thorn;ere goo</L>
<L>.I. wil into &thorn;e hall and wi&thorn; &thorn;e Iustice speke</L>
<L N="824">On hem &thorn;at ben Giltif .I. wil bene awreke</L>
<L>Lat none scape att &thorn;e dore take&thorn; &yogh;onge men &yogh;eme</L>
<L>ffor .I. wil be Iustice &thorn;is daie domes to deme</L>
<L>God spede me &thorn;is daye att my newe werke</L>
<L N="828">Adam Com &thorn;ou wi&thorn; me for &thorn;ou schal be my clerke</L>
<L>His men Anseward him and bad him done his best</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou to vs haue ne le &thorn;ou schal finde vs preste</L>
<L>We wil stand wi&thorn; &thorn;e while &thorn;at we maie dure</L>
<L N="832">And bot we wirken manly paie vs non hire</L>
<L>&YOGH;onge men seide Gameline so mote .I. wel &thorn;e</L>
<L>As trusti a maister schal &yogh;e finde on me</L>
<L>Riht &thorn;ere &thorn;e Iustice satte in &thorn;e hall</L>
<L N="836">In went Gamelin a-monge hem all</L>
<L>Gamelin lete vn-fetter his bro&thorn;er oute of bende</L>
<L>Than seide sir Oke his bro&thorn;er &thorn;at was hende</L>
<L>Thou haddest al-most gamelin dwelled to longe</L>
<L N="840">ffor &thorn;e quest is oute for me &thorn;at .I. scholde be honge</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er seide Gamelin so god gif me gode rest</L>
<L>&THORN;is daie &thorn;ei schal be hongede &thorn;at bene on &thorn;i queste</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Iustice bo&thorn;e &thorn;at is &thorn;e Iugge man</L>
<L N="844">And &thorn;e scherreue bo&thorn;e &thorn;oruh him it be-ganne</L>
<L>Than seide Gamelin to &thorn;e Iustice</L>
<L>Nowe is &thorn;i power done &thorn;ou most nedes a-rise</L>
<L>Thou hast &yogh;eue domes &thorn;at bene yuel diht</L>
<L N="848">.I. wil sitten in &thorn;i sette and dressen hem a-riht
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="153"></L>
<L>The Iustice satt still and rose nouht anone</L>
<L>And Gamelin cleue his cheke bone.</L>
<L>Gamelin toke him in his armes and no more spak<MILESTONE N="64b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="852">Bot &thorn;roue him ouer &thorn;e barre and his arme to-brak</L>
<L>Dorst none to Gameline seie bot gode</L>
<L>ffor ferde of &thorn;e compaignie &thorn;at wi&thorn;-oute stode</L>
<L>Gamelin set him doune in &thorn;e Iustice sete</L>
<L N="856">And sir Ote his bro&thorn;er by him and Adam att his fete</L>
<L>Herke of bourde &thorn;at Gamelin dede</L>
<L>He &thorn;ouht for to make hem riht sore adrede</L>
<L>&para; He lete fetter &thorn;e Iustice and his false bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="860">And lete hem come to &thorn;e barre &thorn;e tone wi&thorn; &thorn;e to&thorn;er</L>
<L>Tho Gamelin had &thorn;us done he no rest</L>
<L>To he had enquered who was on &thorn;e quost</L>
<L>ffor to demen his bro&thorn;er sir Ote for to honge</L>
<L N="864">Or he wiste whiche &thorn;ei were he &thorn;ouht ful longe</L>
<L>Bot as son as Gamelin wist where &thorn;ei were</L>
<L>He dide hem euery-chon fetter in fere</L>
<L>And bringe hem to &thorn;e barre and sett hem on rewe</L>
<L N="868">Be my fai&thorn;e seide Iustice &thorn;e scherreue is a schrewe</L>
<L>Than seide Gamelin to &thorn;e Iustice</L>
<L>Thou hast &yogh;eue domes of &thorn;e werst assise</L>
<L>And &thorn;e .xij. sisours &thorn;at weren on &thorn;e queste</L>
<L>Thei schal ben an-hanged &thorn;is daie so haue .I. goode reste</L>
<L N="873">Than seide &thorn;e scherreue to &yogh;onge Gameline</L>
<L>Lorde .I. crie &thorn;e Mercye bro&thorn;e art &thorn;ou myne</L>
<L>Ther-fore seide Gamelin haue &thorn;ou goddes curs</L>
<L N="876">ffor and &thorn;ou were Meister &yogh;it .I. scholde haue wors</L>
<L>ffor to make schort tale and nouht to longe</L>
<L>He ordeyned him a queste of his men so stronge</L>
<L>The Iustice and &thorn;e scherreve bo&thorn; hongede hihe</L>
<L N="880">To veyven wi&thorn;e &thorn;e ropes . and wi&thorn; &thorn;e wynde drye</L>
<L>And &thorn;e .xij. sisours sorwe haue &thorn;ei &thorn;at rekke</L>
<L>All &thorn;ei were hanged fast be &thorn;e nekke</L>
<L>Thus ende&thorn; &thorn;e false knyht wi&thorn; his trecherie</L>
<L N="884">That euer hade ladde his lif in falsnes and in folye
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="154"></L>
<L>He was hongede be &thorn;e nekke. and nouht be &thorn;e purce</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e mede &thorn;at he had for his fader curs</L>
<L>Sire Ote was eldest and Gamelin was &yogh;inge</L>
<L N="888">Wente wi&thorn; here frendes and pesed wi&thorn; &thorn;e kinge</L>
<L>Thei made pes wi&thorn; &thorn;e kinge of &thorn;e best sise</L>
<L>The kinge louede wele sir Ote and maade him Iustice</L>
<L>And after &thorn;e kinge maade Gamelin bo&thorn;e in est and weste</L>
<L N="892">Chief Iustice of his fre forest.</L>
<L>All his whight &yogh;onge men &thorn;e kinke for-&yogh;aue here gelte<MILESTONE N="65a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And si&thorn;en in good Office he ha&thorn;e hem al pelte</L>
<L>Thus wan Gamelin his londe and his lede</L>
<L>And wrake him of his enemys and quyte hem here mede</L>
<L N="897">And sir Ote his Bro&thorn;er maade him hi[s] heire</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e wede Gameline a wif a goode and a feire</L>
<L>Thei leueden to-geder while &thorn;at crist wolde</L>
<L N="900">An sy&thorn;en was Gamelin Grauen vnder molde</L>
<L>And so schal we al maie &thorn;ere none fle</L>
<L>God bringe vs to &thorn;at Ioye &thorn;a euer schal be AmeN.<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit fabula Coci.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="155">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="129">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>B.</B> (&alpha;. FRAGMENT II.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. MAN OF LAW'S HEAD-LINK.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LANSDOWNE MS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Incipit prologus Legis periti.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 65</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OWre Oste sauhe wele &thorn;at &thorn;e briht sonne</L>
<L>The arke of his artificial daie had ronne</L>
<L>The fer&thorn;e part &amp; half an houre &amp; more</L>
<L N="4">And &thorn;ouhe he were nou&yogh;t expert in lore</L>
<L>He wist it was &thorn;e .xviij. daye</L>
<L>Of Aprill &thorn;at is messagiere of maie</L>
<L>And sawhe wele &thorn;at &thorn;e schadow of euery tree</L>
<L N="8">Was as in lenge&thorn; in &thorn;e same quantite</L>
<L>As was &thorn;e body erect &thorn;at caused it</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-for be &thorn;e schadowe he toke his wit</L>
<L>That phebus whiche &thorn;at schone so clere and briht</L>
<L N="12">Degres was .xlv. clome on hiht</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at daie as in &thorn;at latitude</L>
<L>It was .x. att clokke . he gan conclude</L>
<L>And sodenly he piht his hors aboute</L>
<L N="16">Lordeinges quod he .I. warne &yogh;ou al &thorn;is route</L>
<L>The fer&thorn;e party of &thorn;is daie es gone</L>
<L>Nowe for &thorn;e loue of god and seinte Iohn</L>
<L>Lese&thorn; no time as ferfor&thorn; as &yogh;e maie</L>
<L N="20">Lordeinges &thorn;e time it waste&thorn; nyht and daie</L>
<L>And stele&thorn; from vs what priuely slepeinge</L>
<L>And what &thorn;orwhe necligence in oure wakeynge</L>
<L>As do&thorn;e &thorn;e streme &thorn;at turne&thorn; neuer a-&yogh;eine</L>
<L N="24">Descendeinge fro &thorn;e mountaigne in to &thorn;e pleine</L>
<L>Wele cane senec and mony a philosophre</L>
<L>Be-weylein time more &thorn;an golde in Cophre</L>
<L>ffor losse of catell maie recouerd be</L>
<L N="28">Bot losse of time schende&thorn; vs quod he
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="156"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="130"></L>
<L>It wil nouht com a&yogh;ein wi&thorn; oute drede</L>
<L>Ne mor &thorn;an wil Malkins Maidenhede</L>
<L>Whan sche ha&thorn;e lost it in hire wantonnes<MILESTONE N="65b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="32">Lat vs nou&yogh;t moulen &thorn;us in ydelnes</L>
<L>Sir Man come<NOTE PLACE="marg">[later]</NOTE> of quod he so haue &yogh;e blisse</L>
<L>Tel vs a tale nowe as forward is</L>
<L>&YOGH;e be submitted &thorn;orwhe &yogh;oure fre assent</L>
<L N="36">To stonden in &thorn;is caas att my Iuggement</L>
<L>Acquite&thorn;e now &yogh;owe of &yogh;oure beheste</L>
<L>Than haue &yogh;e done &yogh;oure deuer att leste</L>
<L>Ost quod he de par deux iche assent</L>
<L N="40">To breke forwarde is nouht myne entent</L>
<L>Beheste is dette and .I. wil holden faine</L>
<L>Al my byheste .I. can no better seine</L>
<L>ffor suche lawe as a man &yogh;eue&thorn; ano&thorn;er whihte</L>
<L N="44">He scholde him selfe vsen it be riht</L>
<L>Thus wil oure text bot na&thorn;eles certeine</L>
<L>.I. can . riht nowe no trusti tale seine</L>
<L>&THORN;at chaucer &thorn;ouhe he can bot lewdly</L>
<L N="48">On metres and in rymeinge craftely</L>
<L>Ha&thorn;e saide hem in suche ynglysshe as he can</L>
<L>Of Olde time as knowe&thorn; mony a man</L>
<L>And if he haue nouht seide hem leue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="52">In o boke he ha&thorn;e seide in a no&thorn;er</L>
<L>ffor he ha&thorn; tolde of louers vp and doune</L>
<L>Moo &thorn;an Ouide Maade Mencion</L>
<L>In his Episteles &thorn;at been ful olde</L>
<L N="56">What schold .I. tellen hem sen &thorn;ei bu tolde</L>
<L>In &yogh;ou&thorn;e he maade of Ceys and Alcione</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en ha&thorn;e he spoken of euerichone</L>
<L>Thes noble wifes and &thorn;es louers eke</L>
<L N="60">Who so &thorn;at wil his large veloine seke</L>
<L>Cleped &thorn;e seintes Legent of Cupide</L>
<L>There maie he see &thorn;e large woundes wide</L>
<L>Of Lucres and of Babilan Thisbe</L>
<L N="64">The swerde of dido for &thorn;e fals ene
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="157"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="131"></L>
<L>The tree of phillis for hir demefon</L>
<L>The pleinte of Dianyre and of Ermyon</L>
<L>Of Adriane and of ysiphilee</L>
<L N="68">The barayn ysel stondeynge in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>The dreynt leandre for his erro</L>
<L>The teres of Eleyne and eke &thorn;e wo</L>
<L>Of brixseide and of &thorn;e ladomya</L>
<L N="72">The cruelte of quene Medea</L>
<L>The litil childern hongeinge be &thorn;e hals<MILESTONE N="66a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i Iason &thorn;at was of loue fals</L>
<L>Of ypnistra Penelope Alceste</L>
<L N="76">&YOGH;oure wifehode he commende&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>Bot certeynly no worde write&thorn; he</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilke wilke ensample of Canace</L>
<L>&THORN;at loued hir owen bro&thorn;er sinfully</L>
<L N="80">Of suche cursed stories .I. saie fye</L>
<L>Or elles of Tiro Appolonius</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;e cursed kinge Anthiochus</L>
<L>Beraft his douhter of hir maydenhede</L>
<L N="84">That is so orrible a tale for to rede</L>
<L>Whan he hire <NOTE PLACE="marg">[? yrewe]</NOTE>&thorn;rewe &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e pament</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-for he of ful avisement</L>
<L>Nolde neuer write in none of his sermones</L>
<L N="88">Of whiche vnkinde abhominaciones</L>
<L>Ne .I. ne wil none reherce if &thorn;at .I. maie</L>
<L>Bot of my tale . howe schal .I. done &thorn;is daie</L>
<L>Me were lo&thorn;e be likned douteles</L>
<L N="92">To muses &thorn;at men clepen pieriedes</L>
<L>Methamorphoseos woote what .I. mene</L>
<L>Bot natheles .I. recche nou&yogh;t a bene</L>
<L>&THORN;owhe .I. come after him wi&thorn; halve bake</L>
<L N="96">.I. speke in prose and lat him rimes make</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde he wi&thorn; a sobre chere</L>
<L N="98">Began his tale as &yogh;e schal after here.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000186.tif" N="158"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="132">
<HEAD>Hic incipit fabula legis periti.<NOTE PLACE="head">[No breaks in the MS between the stanzas.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="99">O Hateful harme condicione of pouert</L>
<L>With &thorn;urst . with colde . with hungre so confounded</L>
<L>To asken helpe &thorn;ou schame&thorn; in &thorn;ine hert</L>
<L N="102">If &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>a late</I> none <I>inserted</I>]</NOTE> axe with nede &thorn;ou art so wounded</L>
<L>&thorn;at verrei nede vnwrappe&thorn; al &thorn;i wound hid</L>
<L>Maugreue &thorn;in hede &thorn;ou most for indigence</L>
<L N="105">Or steele or begge or borwe &thorn;i despense</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou blamest crist and seist ful bittirly.</L>
<L>He mys departe&thorn; richesse temporal</L>
<L>&THORN;i neiheburghe &thorn;ou witest sinfully</L>
<L N="109">And seiste &thorn;ou haste to litel and he ha&thorn; al</L>
<L>Per fey seys &thorn;ou sum tyme he reken schal</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at his taile schal berne in &thorn;e glede</L>
<L N="112">ffor he nou&yogh;t helpe&thorn; nedeful in here nede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Herken what is &thorn;e meneynge of &thorn;e wise</L>
<L>Better is to dyen &thorn;an to haue indigence<MILESTONE N="66b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;i self neighebore wil &thorn;e dispise</L>
<L N="116">If &thorn;ou be pore fare wele &thorn;i reuerence</L>
<L>&YOGH;it of &thorn;e wiseman take&thorn; &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>All &thorn;e daies of pormen ben wikke</L>
<L N="119">Be war &thorn;ar fore or &thorn;ou com in &thorn;at prikke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; If &thorn;ou be pore &thorn;i bro&thorn;er hate&thorn; &thorn;ee</L>
<L>And al &thorn;i frendes flye fro &thorn;e alas</L>
<L>O riche marchauntes ful of wel be &yogh;e</L>
<L N="123">O noble prudent folke as in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure bagges bene nou&yogh;t filled wi&thorn; ambes aas</L>
<L>Bot wi&thorn; sis sinke &thorn;at renne&thorn; for &yogh;oure chaunce</L>
<L N="126">Att Cristes masse mery maie &yogh;e daunce
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="159"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="133"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &YOGH;e seken londe and see for &yogh;oure wininges</L>
<L>As wise folke &thorn;at knowen al &thorn;e astate</L>
<L>Of regnes &yogh;e bene faders of ti&thorn;inges</L>
<L N="130">And tales bothen of pes and debate</L>
<L>I. was riht nowe of tales desolate</L>
<L>Nar &thorn;at a marchant gone is mony a &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="133">Me tauht a tale whiche as &yogh;e schal here
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000188.tif" N="160"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="134">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In Surre some while dweled a company.</L>
<L>Of chap men riche and &thorn;er-to sadde and trewe</L>
<L>That wide where senten hire spicery</L>
<L N="137">Clo&thorn;es of golde and satine riche of hewe</L>
<L>Here chaffer was so &thorn;refty and so newe</L>
<L>That euery wiht ha&thorn;e deynte to chaffare</L>
<L N="140">Wi&thorn;e hem and eke to sellen hem here ware</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nowe felle &thorn;at &thorn;e maistres of &thorn;at sorte</L>
<L>Hane schapen hem to Rome for to wende</L>
<L>Were it fo chapmanhode or for disporte</L>
<L N="144">None o&thorn;er Messagier wolde &thorn;ei &thorn;eder sende</L>
<L>Bot cam hem selft to rome &thorn;is es &thorn;e ende</L>
<L>And in swyche place as &thorn;ouht hem auantage</L>
<L N="147">ffor here intent &thorn;ei take here herbergage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Soiorne haue &thorn;ese marchantes in &thorn;at toune</L>
<L>A certaine time as fell to here plesaunce</L>
<L>Bot so be-fel &thorn;at &thorn;e excellent renoune</L>
<L N="151">Of &thorn;e Emperoure douhter dame Custance</L>
<L>Reported was wi&thorn; euery circumstance</L>
<L>Vn to &thorn;is surrien Marchantez in suche wise</L>
<L N="154">ffro day to day as .I. schal &yogh;owe deuise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This was &thorn;e comune voyce of euery man</L>
<L>Owre Emperour of Rome Gode him see<MILESTONE N="67a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A douhter he ha&thorn;e &thorn;at sen &thorn;e werlde beganne</L>
<L N="158">To rekken as wele hire goodnes as beaute</L>
<L>Was neuer suche ano&thorn;er as is sche</L>
<L>.I. praie to gode in honoure hire susteigne</L>
<L>And wald sche were of al Europe &thorn;e quene.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Europa est tercia pars mundi.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="161"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In hir is hihe beaute wi&thorn; oute pride</L>
<L>&YOGH;ow&thorn;e wi&thorn; oute greuehode or foly</L>
<L>To al hire werkes vertue is hir gyde</L>
<L N="165">Humblesse ha&thorn;e slayne in &yogh;owe al tyranny</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire herte is verrai chambre of holynesse</L>
<L N="168">Hir hande Ministre of fredam for almesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And al &thorn;is voice was so&thorn;e as god is trewe</L>
<L>Bot nowe to purpos lat vs turne a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>This marchantez han don frauht here schippes newe</L>
<L N="172">And whan &thorn;ei han &thorn;is blisseful Maiden seine</L>
<L>Home to surre be &thorn;ei wente a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>And done here nedes as &thorn;ei han done &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="175">And leuen in wele .I. can say &yogh;ow no more</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nowe fel it &thorn;at &thorn;ese marchantz stoden in grace</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at was Souldan of Surrye</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei cam from any strange place</L>
<L N="179">He wolde of his benigne curtesie</L>
<L>Make hem good chiere and besilye aspye</L>
<L>Thinges of sundre remes for to lere</L>
<L N="182">The wonderes &thorn;at &thorn;ei myht se or here</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Amonges o&thorn;er &thorn;inges specialy</L>
<L>Thos Marchantz hane him tolde of dame Custance</L>
<L>So grete noblesse in erneste curiousely</L>
<L N="186">&THORN;at &thorn;is souldan ha&thorn; kauht so grete plesance</L>
<L>To hane hir figure in his remembrance</L>
<L>And al his lust and al his besy cure</L>
<L N="189">Was for to loue hir while his lif maie dure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Parauenture in &thorn;e large booke</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at cleped &thorn;e heuen y-writen was</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sterres whan &thorn;at he his bir&thorn;e toke</L>
<L N="193">That he for loue schol haue his de&thorn;e alas
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="162"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="136"></L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;e sterres clerer &thorn;an is &thorn;e glas</L>
<L>Is wreten god wote who so cou&thorn;e it rede</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;e de&thorn;e of euery man wi&thorn; outen drede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In sterres mony a winter &thorn;ar be-forne<NOTE PLACE="marg"><Q><L>&para; Ceptra pharonei furtum discordia thebe</L><L>&para; Flammam phetontis deu-calionis aque</L><L>&para; In stellis priami; species audacia turni</L><L>&para; Sensus vlixeus herculeus que vigor.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Was wreten &thorn;e de&thorn;e of Ector and achilles</L>
<L>Off Pompe Iulius or thei were borne<MILESTONE N="67b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="200">The strif of Thebes and of Hercules</L>
<L>Of Sampson turnus and of Socrates</L>
<L>The de&thorn; bot mennus wittes bene so dulle</L>
<L N="203">That no whiht can wel rede it att &thorn;e fulle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Sowldan for his priue conseile sente</L>
<L>And schortly of &thorn;is matier for to passe</L>
<L>He ha&thorn;e to hem declared his entent</L>
<L N="207">And seide hem certeine bot if he myht haue grace</L>
<L>To haue Custance wi&thorn; inne a litel space</L>
<L>He nas bot dede and charged hem in hihe</L>
<L N="210">To schapen for his lif som remedie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Diuers men diuers &thorn;inges saiden</L>
<L>The Argumentz custen vp and doune</L>
<L>Many a sotyl reson for&thorn;e &thorn;ei leyden</L>
<L N="214">Thei speken of Magik and abusion</L>
<L>Bot finalli as in conclusion</L>
<L>Thei can nou&yogh;t seen in &thorn;at none auantage</L>
<L N="217">Ne in none o&thorn;er waie saue Mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Than sauhe &thorn;ere suche difficulte</L>
<L>Be way of Reson for to speke as pleine</L>
<L>Be cause &thorn;at &thorn;ere was suche diuersite</L>
<L N="221">Be twene here bo&thorn;e lawes as &thorn;ei seine</L>
<L>Thai trowe &thorn;at no cristen prince wold feine</L>
<L>Wedden his childe vnder her lawes so swete</L>
<L N="224">That hem was tauht bue Mahoun &thorn;e prophete
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="163"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="137"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And he Ansewarde ra&thorn;er &thorn;an .I. lese</L>
<L>Constance .I. wil be cristened douteles</L>
<L>.I. mot bene hirs .I. maie none o&thorn;er chese</L>
<L N="228">.I. pray &yogh;ow holde &yogh;oure argumentes in pes</L>
<L>Saue&thorn; my lif and be&thorn; nouht recheles</L>
<L>To gete hir &thorn;at ha&thorn; my lif in cure</L>
<L N="231">ffor in &thorn;is woo .I. maie nouht longe endure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; What nede&thorn; gretter dilataci&omacr;n</L>
<L>.I. sey be tretise and embassadrie</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e popes Medeacione</L>
<L N="235">And al &thorn;e cherche and al &thorn;e chiualrie</L>
<L>That in destruccion of Maumetrie</L>
<L>And in encrese of cristes lawe dere</L>
<L N="238">Thei bene accorded so as &yogh;e schal here</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; How &thorn;at &thorn;e Souldan and his Baronage</L>
<L>And alle his leges scholde cristened be</L>
<L>And he scal haue Constance in Mariage<MILESTONE N="68a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="242">And certeigne gold .I. not what quantite</L>
<L>And herto founden sufficiant surtie</L>
<L>This same accorde was swor in ey&thorn;er side</L>
<L N="245">Nowe faire Constance almyhti god &thorn;e gide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nowe wolde sum man waiten as .I. gesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at .I. schol telle al &thorn;e purueance</L>
<L>That &thorn;e Emperour of his noblesse</L>
<L N="249">Ha&thorn; schapen for his douhter Dam Custance.</L>
<L>Wele maie men knowen &thorn;at so grete ordinance.</L>
<L>Maie no man tellen in a litel clause</L>
<L N="252">As was arraied for so hihe a cause</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Cardinals and Bischops bene schapen wi&thorn; hir to wende</L>
<L>Lordes and lades and knyhtes of renoune</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er folke .I.-nowe &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L N="256">And notified is &thorn;oruhe oute &thorn;e toune
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="164"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="138"></L>
<L>That euery whight wi&thorn;e grete deuocione</L>
<L>Schold praie criste &thorn;at &thorn;is Mariage</L>
<L N="259">Resceyue in gree and spede &thorn;is viage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The daie is comen of hire departeinge</L>
<L>.I. say &thorn;at woful daie fatal is come</L>
<L>That &thorn;at &thorn;ere maie be no longer tariynge</L>
<L N="263">Bot for&thorn;warde &thorn;ei hem dresse alle and somme</L>
<L>Constance &thorn;at wi&thorn; sorwe is al ouer-come</L>
<L>fful pale a-rist and drisse&thorn; hire to wend</L>
<L N="266">ffor wele sche see&thorn;e &thorn;ere is none o&thorn;ere ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Allas what wonder is it &thorn;ouhe sche wepete</L>
<L>That schall be sent to so strange nacione</L>
<L>ffro frendes &thorn;at so tendurly hir keppete</L>
<L N="270">And to be boundon vnder subiectione</L>
<L>Of one sehe knowe&thorn; nouht his condicion</L>
<L>Husbondes bene al good and hane bu &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="273">&thorn;at knewen wives .I. dar sei &yogh;ow no more</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffader sche seide . &thorn;i wreched childe Constance</L>
<L>&thorn;i &yogh;onge douhter fostred vp so soft</L>
<L>And &yogh;e my moder my souereigne plesance</L>
<L N="277">Ouer al &thorn;inge oute take criste on loft</L>
<L>Constance &yogh;owre childe hir recommande&thorn; oft</L>
<L>Vn to &yogh;oure grace for .I. schal to Surrye</L>
<L N="280">Ne schal .I. neuer seen &yogh;ow more wi&thorn; eye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alas vn to &thorn;e Barbarie Nacion</L>
<L>.I. most anone se&thorn; it is &yogh;oure wille</L>
<L>Bot crist &thorn;at starf for oure redempcione<MILESTONE N="68b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="284">So &yogh;eue me grace his hestes to fulfille</L>
<L>.I. wriched womman no force &thorn;ou .I. spille</L>
<L>Wemmen arne born to &thorn;raldom and penance</L>
<L N="287">And to bue vnder mannes gouernance
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="165"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="139"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; .I. trowe att troie whan purrus brake &thorn;e wal</L>
<L>Or. ylion &thorn;at brende Thebes &thorn;at Citee</L>
<L>Noute Rome for &thorn;e harme &thorn;orwhe Hanybal</L>
<L N="291">That Romaynes ha&thorn; venquissed times &thorn;re.</L>
<L>Nas herde swiche tender wepeinge for pite</L>
<L>As in &thorn;e chambre for hire departeinge</L>
<L N="294">Bot for&thorn;e sche mote whereso sche wepe or singe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O ferst moueynge cruel firmament</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;i diurnale sweigh &thorn;at croudest aie</L>
<L>And hurlist al fro est to Occident</L>
<L N="298">&THORN;at naturelly wold hold a-no&thorn;er waye</L>
<L>Thi croudeinge sett &thorn;e heuen in suche arraie</L>
<L>Att &thorn;e be-ginnynge of &thorn;is fers viage</L>
<L N="301">That cruel Mars ha&thorn;e slayne &thorn;is mariage<NOTE PLACE="inter">Vnde <B>Tholomeus</B>. libro primo capitulo <B>8.</B> Primi <B>motus Celi duo</B> sunt quorum <B>vnus</B> est <B>qui mouet</B> totum semper <B>ab oriente</B> in occidentem; <B>vno</B> modo super <B>orbes &amp;c</B>. Alter vero motus est qui <B>mouet</B> orbem stellarum currencium <I>contra</I> motum primum videlicet. ab <B>occidente in orientem</B> super <B>alios duos polos &amp;c</B>. Omnes enim sunt concordati quod elecciones <B>sint debiles</B> nisi in diuitibus Habent enim <B>isti</B> licet debilitentur eorum elecciones radicem <B>.i. natiuitates</B> eorum <B>que</B> confortant omnem planetam debilem in itinere Huc. Philoso|phus. [ <I>a quotation in the middle of the text</I>.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Infortunate ascendent tortuous</L>
<L>Of whiche &thorn;e lorde is falle alas</L>
<L>Out of his angle in to &thorn;e derkest house</L>
<L N="305">O mars o.ata&yogh;ir as in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>O feble mone vn-happy bene &thorn;i pas</L>
<L>Thou knettest &thorn;e &thorn;ar &thorn;ou ert nouht receyuede</L>
<L N="308">The &thorn;ou weere wele fro &thorn;ens nowe ert &thorn;ou weyued</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Imprudent emperour of Rome allas</L>
<L>Was &thorn;ere no philosopher in al &thorn;i toune</L>
<L>Is no time bet &thorn;an o&thorn;er in suche cas</L>
<L N="312">Of viage is &thorn;ere none eleccion</L>
<L>Namely to folke of hihe condicion</L>
<L>Nat whan a rote is of a bur&thorn;e y-knowe</L>
<L N="315">Alas &yogh;e bene to lewed or to slowe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The schippe is brouht &thorn;is woful faire maide</L>
<L>Solempnely wi&thorn;e euery circumstance.</L>
<L>Nowe ihesu criste be wi&thorn; &yogh;owe al sche saide<MILESTONE N="69a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="319">There is no more bot fare wele faire Constance
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="166"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="140"></L>
<L>Sche peyne&thorn; hire to make gode continance</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e &thorn;ei lete hir saile in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L N="322">And turne .I. wil a&yogh;eine to my matier</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The moder of &thorn;e Souldan wel of vices</L>
<L>Espied ha&thorn;e hir sones pleine entent</L>
<L>How he wil lete his olde sacrifises</L>
<L N="326">And riht a-none sche for hire conseille sent</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei comen to knowen what sche ment</L>
<L>And whan assembled was &thorn;es folk in fere</L>
<L N="329">Sche sett hire doune and seide as &yogh;e schalle here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lordes quod sche &yogh;e knowen euerychone</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at my sonne in pointe is fo to lete</L>
<L>The holy lawes of owre Akkaron</L>
<L N="333">&YOGH;euen be goddes Messagiere Makomete</L>
<L>Bott on avowe to grete god .I. hete</L>
<L>The lif schal ra&thorn;er oute of my bodi sterte</L>
<L N="336">Or Macometis lawe oute of myne herte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; What schuld vs tiden of &thorn;is newe lawe</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;raldom to oure bodies and penance</L>
<L>And afterward in hel to be drawe</L>
<L N="340">ffor we reneyed Mahon oure creance</L>
<L>Bot lordes wil &yogh;e maken assurance</L>
<L>As .I. schal seine assentinge to my lore</L>
<L N="343">And .I. schal make us sauf for euer more</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thei sworen and assenten euery man</L>
<L>To leue wi&thorn; hire and deye and by hire stande</L>
<L>And eueryche in &thorn;e best wise he can</L>
<L N="347">To streng&thorn;en hir schal al his frendes fonde</L>
<L>And sche ha&thorn;e &thorn;is emprise take on honde</L>
<L>Whiche &yogh;e schal here &thorn;at .I. schal deuise</L>
<L N="350">And to hem al sche spak in &thorn;is wise
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="167"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="141"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; We schol first feyne vs cristendom to take</L>
<L>Colde water schal nouht greue vs bot a lite</L>
<L>And .I. schal suche a fest and a reuel make</L>
<L N="354">&THORN;at as .I. trowe .I. schal &thorn;e sowdan quite</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ouhe his wif be crestened neuer so white</L>
<L>Sche schal haue nede to whasse awaie &thorn;e rede</L>
<L N="357">Thouhe sche a fonte ful of water wi&thorn; hire lede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O sauldanesse rote of iniquite</L>
<L>Virago &thorn;u semiram &thorn;e seconde.</L>
<L>O serpent vnder femenyte<MILESTONE N="69b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="361">Like to &thorn;e serpente depe in helle bownde</L>
<L>O feyned womman alle &thorn;at may confounde</L>
<L>Vertue and innocence &thorn;oruhe &thorn;i Malice</L>
<L N="364">Is bred in &thorn;e as nest of euery vice.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O Sathan envious sen &thorn;ilk daie</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou were chased from owre heritage</L>
<L>Wele knowes &thorn;ou to wemmen &thorn;e olde waie</L>
<L N="368">&THORN;ou madest Eua to bringe in seruage</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wilt for-done cristen Mariage</L>
<L>&THORN;ine instrument so welawaie &thorn;e while</L>
<L N="371">Makeste &thorn;ou of whan &thorn;u wilte begile</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Souldanesse wham .I. &thorn;us blame and wery.</L>
<L>Lete priuely hire consielle gon here waye</L>
<L>What schold .I. in &thorn;is tale longer tary</L>
<L N="375">Sche ride&thorn; to &thorn;e souldan on a daye</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at sche wold reney hir laye</L>
<L>And cristendome of prestes hondes fonge</L>
<L N="378">Repentynge sche he&thorn;en was so longe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Besekeinge him to done hir &thorn;at honoure</L>
<L>&THORN;at miht haue &thorn;e cresten folke to feste</L>
<L>To plese hem .I. wil do my laboure</L>
<L N="382">The souldan sei&thorn;e .I. wil done at &yogh;oure heste
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="168"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="142"></L>
<L>And knelynge &thorn;onke&thorn; hire of &thorn;at requeste</L>
<L>So glad he was he nyst what to seie</L>
<L N="385">Sche kist hire sonne and home sche go&thorn;e hir waie</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART II.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Arriued bene &thorn;is cresten folk to londe</L>
<L>In Surry wi&thorn;&thorn;e a grete solempne route</L>
<L>And hastely &thorn;is Souldan sent his sonde</L>
<L N="389">ffirst to his Moder and al &thorn;e regne aboute</L>
<L>And seide his wif was commen oute of doute</L>
<L>And praide hir for to riden a&yogh;ein &thorn;e qwene</L>
<L N="392">The honoure of his regne to suteigne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Grete was &thorn;e pres and riche was &thorn;e raie</L>
<L>Of Surrys and Romeyns mette .I.-fere</L>
<L>The Moder of &thorn;e souldan riche and gaie</L>
<L N="396">Reseiue&thorn; hire wi&thorn; also glad a chere</L>
<L>As any moder myht hire douhter dere</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e next Cite &thorn;ere beside</L>
<L N="399">A soft pas solempnyeli &thorn;ei ride</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nouht trowe .I. &thorn;e triumphe of Iulius</L>
<L>Of whiche &thorn;at lukan maade suche a boste</L>
<L>Was Roialer ne more corious<MILESTONE N="70a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="403">Than was &thorn;assemble of &thorn;is blisful oste</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is Scorpion &thorn;is wikked goste</L>
<L>This Sauldanesse for al hir flateringe</L>
<L N="406">Kast vnder &thorn;is mortali to stinge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Souldan come&thorn; himself sone after &thorn;is</L>
<L>So Roialy &thorn;at wonder is to tel</L>
<L>He welcome&thorn; hire wi&thorn; al Ioy and blis</L>
<L N="410">And &thorn;us in mer&thorn;e and Ioye .I. lete hem duel
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="169"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="143"></L>
<L>&THORN;e fruyte of &thorn;is matier &thorn;at .I. tel</L>
<L>Whan tim com men &thorn;ouht it for &thorn;e best</L>
<L N="413">That Reuel stinte and men gon to rest</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The time come &thorn;is olde Souldanesse</L>
<L>Ordeined &thorn;e fest ha&thorn; of wich .I. tolde</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e feste Cristenten folke hem dresse</L>
<L N="417">In generale bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge and olde</L>
<L>He may men feste and Roialte beholde</L>
<L>And deynte&thorn;s mo &thorn;an .I. can &yogh;ou deuyse</L>
<L N="420">Bot al to der &thorn;ei bouht it er &thorn;ei rise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O Sodan woo &thorn;at euer art succesour</L>
<L>To werldly blisse spreynde is wi&thorn; bitternes</L>
<L>The ende of &thorn;e ioye of oure werldly labour</L>
<L N="424">Woo occupie&thorn; &thorn;e fine of oure gladnes</L>
<L>Herke &thorn;is conseile for &thorn;i securnes</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;i glad daie haue in mynde</L>
<L N="427">The vnwar wo or harme &thorn;at come&thorn; be-hinde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor schortly for to telle att o worde</L>
<L>The souldan and &thorn;e cristen euerychone</L>
<L>Be al to-hewe and stiken att &thorn;e borde</L>
<L N="431">Bot it war only Dam Custance alone</L>
<L>Thys olde Sauldanes cursed crone</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; wi&thorn; hir frendes don &thorn;is cursed dede</L>
<L N="434">ffor sche hir selfe wolde &thorn;e contrei lede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ne &thorn;ere was Surreyne ne none &thorn;at was conuertede</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e counsel of &thorn;e souldan wote</L>
<L>That he ne es alto-hewen or he astert-it</L>
<L N="438">And Constance han &thorn;ei take a-none fote hote</L>
<L>And in a schippe al sterles god wote</L>
<L>Thei hane hir sett and beden hire leren to saile</L>
<L N="441">Owte of Surry a&yogh;eine to Itaile
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="170"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="144"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A certeine tresoure &thorn;at sche &thorn;eder ladde</L>
<L>And so&thorn;e to seine vital grete plente</L>
<L>&THORN;ei hane here &yogh;euen and clo&thorn;es eke sche hadde<MILESTONE N="70b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="445">And for&thorn; sche saile&thorn; in &thorn;e salte see</L>
<L>O my Custance fful of benignite</L>
<L>O . Emperours &yogh;onge douhter dere</L>
<L N="448">He &thorn;at is lorde ouere fortune he &thorn;e steere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sche blisse&thorn; and wi&thorn; ful pitous voyce</L>
<L>Vn to &thorn;e croys of crist &thorn;us seide sche</L>
<L>O clere o welful auter holy croyce</L>
<L N="452">Rede of &thorn;e lambes blode ful of pite</L>
<L>&THORN;at whisse &thorn;e werlde fro &thorn;e olde iniquite</L>
<L>Me fro &thorn;e fende and fro his clowes kepe</L>
<L N="455">&thorn;at daie &thorn;at .I. schal drenchen in &thorn;e depe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Victorious tree proteccion of trewe</L>
<L>&THORN;at oonely wor&thorn;i war for to bere</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinge of heuen wi&thorn; his wondes newe</L>
<L N="459">&THORN;e wyght lambe &thorn;at hurt was wi&thorn; a spere</L>
<L>fflemer of frendes oute of him and here</L>
<L>On whiche &thorn;i lynes fai&thorn;fuly extenden</L>
<L N="462">Me kep and &yogh;ife me myht my lyf to amenden</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &YOGH;eres and dayes flete&thorn; &thorn;is creature</L>
<L>&THORN;oruhe owte &thorn;e see of grece vnto &thorn;e streite</L>
<L>Of Marrok as it as it was hir auenture</L>
<L N="466">O many a sory mele noue maie sche baite</L>
<L>Affter her de&thorn; ful oft mai sche waite</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at &thorn;e wilde wawes wil hir drive</L>
<L N="469">Vn to &thorn;e place &thorn;are sche schal ariue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Men myht axen whi sche was nou&yogh;t sleine</L>
<L>Eke att &thorn;e feste who myht hir body saue</L>
<L>.I. answere to &thorn;at demande a&yogh;eine</L>
<L N="473">Who saue Danyel in &thorn;e horrible caue
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="171"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="145"></L>
<L>&THORN;ere euery saue he Maister or knaue</L>
<L>Was wi&thorn; &thorn;e lyons frete in a sterte</L>
<L N="476">No whight bot god &thorn;a he bare in his hert</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; God luste to schewe his wonderful miracle</L>
<L>In hire for sche schold see his myhty werkes</L>
<L>Crist whiche &thorn;at is to euery harme treacle</L>
<L N="480">Be certeine Menes oft as knowen clerkes</L>
<L>Do&thorn; &thorn;inge for certein ende &thorn;at ful derke is</L>
<L>To mannes witte &thorn;at for owre ignorance</L>
<L N="483">Ne conne knowe his prodent purueance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nowe se&thorn; sche was not at &thorn;e fest slawe</L>
<L>Who kepped hire fro &thorn;e drencheinge in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>Who keppet Iona in &thorn;e fisches mawe<MILESTONE N="71a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="487">To he was spouted vp att Niniue</L>
<L>Wele maie men knowe it was no whight bot he</L>
<L>&THORN;at keppe &thorn;e peple Ebayk fro drencheinge</L>
<L N="490">Wi&thorn; dri feete &thorn;oruhe oute &thorn;e see passinge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who had &thorn;e foure spirites of tempest</L>
<L>&THORN;at power hane to anoyen londe and see</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e nor&thorn;e and sou&thorn;e and also west and este</L>
<L N="494">Anoye&thorn; ney&thorn;er se ne londe ne tree</L>
<L>So&thorn;e &thorn;e comander of &thorn;at was he</L>
<L>&THORN;at fro &thorn;e tempest ay &thorn;is womman kepet</L>
<L N="497">As wele whan sche woke as wen sche slepet</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whare myht &thorn;is womman mete and drenke haue</L>
<L>Three &yogh;ere and more how laste&thorn; hir vytaile</L>
<L>Who fede &thorn;e Egipciane Marye in &thorn;e caue</L>
<L N="501">Or in desert non bot crist sans faille</L>
<L>ffyve &thorn;ousand folke it was a grete mervaille</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; loues five and ffisches tuo to feede</L>
<L N="504">Gode sente his foyson att her grete nede
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="172"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="146"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sche dryue&thorn; for&thorn; in to owre Occeane</L>
<L>&THORN;oruhe oute &thorn;e wilde see till att &thorn;e last</L>
<L>Vnder an castel &thorn;at neuen .y. ne can</L>
<L N="508">ffor in Nor&thorn;e Humbrelond &thorn;e wawe her caste</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e sonde &thorn;e schippe stikked so fast</L>
<L>That &thorn;ens wold it nouht of al a tyde</L>
<L N="511">The wil of criste was &thorn;at sche scholde abide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Cunstable of &thorn;e Castel doune is fare</L>
<L>To seen &thorn;is wrakke and al &thorn;e schipe he souhte</L>
<L>And fonde &thorn;is wery womman ful of Care</L>
<L N="515">He fonde also tresoure &thorn;at sche brouht</L>
<L>In hir langage Mercie sche be-souht</L>
<L>&THORN;e lif oute of &thorn;e body for to twynne</L>
<L N="518">Hir to deliuer of woo &thorn;at sche was inne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A maner latine corrupte was hir speche</L>
<L>Bot algatez &thorn;ere by was sche vnderstonde</L>
<L>The Constable whan him lust no longer seche</L>
<L N="522">This wooful womman brouht he to &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>Sche knele&thorn; doune and &thorn;onke&thorn; goddes sonde</L>
<L>Bot what sche was sche wolde no man seye</L>
<L N="525">ffor foule ne faire &thorn;ouhe &thorn;at sche scholde deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sche seid sche was so mased in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche for-gat here mynde be hir trou&thorn;e</L>
<L>The constable of hir ha&thorn;e so grete pite<MILESTONE N="71b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="529">And eke his wif &thorn;at &thorn;ei wepen for reu&thorn;e</L>
<L>Sche was so diligent wi&thorn; owten sleu&thorn;e</L>
<L>To serue and plese eueryche in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="532">That al hir louen &thorn;at loken on hir face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Constable and dam Ermenilda his wif</L>
<L>Where payneins and &thorn;at cuntre euery where</L>
<L>Bot Ermenilda loued here riht as hir lif</L>
<L N="536">And custance ha&thorn; so longe soiourned &thorn;ere
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="173"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="147"></L>
<L>In orisons wi&thorn; mony a better tere</L>
<L>Til ihesu ha&thorn;e conuerted &thorn;oruhe his grace</L>
<L N="539">Dam. Ermenilda Constablesse of &thorn;ilke place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In al &thorn;at londe dorst no kersten route</L>
<L>Al cresten folke bene fledde fro &thorn;at contre</L>
<L>&THORN;oruhe payneins &thorn;at conquerden here aboute</L>
<L N="543">The plages of &thorn;e nor&thorn;e be &thorn;e lande and &thorn;e see</L>
<L>To Wales fledd fledde &thorn;e cristeante</L>
<L>Of olde bretons dwelynge in &thorn;is Isle</L>
<L N="546">Ther was hire refute for &thorn;e mene while</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bot &yogh;it was neuer cristen bretons so exiled</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er nas sum in hir priuete</L>
<L>Honoured crist and hey&thorn;en folk be-giled</L>
<L N="550">And nyhe &thorn;e castel &thorn;er dwel &thorn;er dwelden &thorn;re</L>
<L>&THORN;at one of hem was blinde and myht nouht see</L>
<L>Bot it weere wi&thorn;e ilke yen of his mynde</L>
<L N="553">Wi&thorn; wiche men seen after &thorn;at &thorn;ei be blinde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Briht was &thorn;e sonne as in &thorn;e somers daie</L>
<L>ffor whiche &thorn;e Constable and his wif also</L>
<L>And Constance hane ytake &thorn;e riht waie</L>
<L N="557">To-warde &thorn;e se a forlonge way or tuo</L>
<L>To pleyen and to Romen to and fro</L>
<L>And in her waie blende men &thorn;aie mette</L>
<L N="560">Croked and olde wi&thorn; fast eyen schett</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In &thorn;e name of criste cried &thorn;is blinde bretoune</L>
<L>Dame Ermenilda &yogh;eue me my sihte a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>This lady wex affrayde of &thorn;e soune</L>
<L N="564">Lest hir husbonde schortly for to seyne</L>
<L>Wolde hir for ihesu cristes loue haue sleyne</L>
<L>Til Constance made hir bolde and bad hire wirche</L>
<L N="567">The wil of criste as douhter of his chirche
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="174"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="148"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Constable wex abassched of &thorn;at siht</L>
<L>And seide what amounte&thorn; al &thorn;is fare</L>
<L>Custance anseward it is cristes miht<MILESTONE N="72a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="571">&THORN;at helpe&thorn; folke oute of &thorn;e fendes snare</L>
<L>And so ferfor&thorn;e sche gan oure laye declare</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche constable ar &thorn;at it was eue</L>
<L N="574">Conuerte&thorn; and on criste maad him beleue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Constable was nouht lorde of &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Of whiche .I. spak &thorn;are he constance fonde</L>
<L>Bot keped it stronge mony a winter space</L>
<L N="578">Vnder Allea kynge of of Northehumbrelonde</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;ein &thorn;e scottes as men may wele here</L>
<L N="581">Bot torne .I. wil a-&yogh;eine to my matier</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sathan &thorn;at euer waite&thorn; vs to begile</L>
<L>Sauhe of Custance al hir perfeccioun</L>
<L>And kast anone howe he myht white hir while</L>
<L N="585">And maad a &yogh;onge knyht &thorn;at dwelle&thorn; in &thorn;e toune</L>
<L>Loue hire so hote of foule affeccione</L>
<L>&THORN;at verraily him &thorn;ouht &thorn;at he scholde spille</L>
<L N="588">Bote of hir myht ones haue his wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He wowe&thorn;e hir bot it aveile&thorn; nouht</L>
<L>Sche wolde do no sinne be no weie</L>
<L>And for dispite he compassed in his &thorn;ouht</L>
<L N="592">To make hir a schameful de&thorn;e to deye</L>
<L>He waite&thorn; whan &thorn;e Constable was awaie</L>
<L>And priuely on a nyhte he crepte</L>
<L N="595">In Ermenilda scambur whiles &thorn;at sche sleped</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wery for-waked in hire orisons</L>
<L>Slepe&thorn; custance and Ermenilde also</L>
<L>&THORN;is knyht &thorn;ouht to performe sathanas temptacions</L>
<L N="599">Al softly he is to &thorn;e bedde go
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="175"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="149"></L>
<L>And kette &thorn;e &thorn;rote of Ermenylde a tuo</L>
<L>And leide &thorn;e blody knyf be dam Custance</L>
<L N="602">And wente his weie &thorn;ere god &yogh;iue him meschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sone affter come&thorn; &thorn;is Constable a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>And Eke Allea &thorn;e kenge &thorn;at was of &thorn;is lande</L>
<L>And sauhe his wyf dispitously sleyne</L>
<L N="606">ffor whiche ful of oft he wepet and wronge his honde</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e bedde &thorn;e blody knyfe he fonde</L>
<L>Be dam Custance Alas what myht sche seye</L>
<L N="609">ffor verre woo hir witte was al awaie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To Kinge Alla was tolde al &thorn;is meschance</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;e time and where and in what wise</L>
<L>&THORN;at in a schip was founden &thorn;is Constance</L>
<L N="613">As &yogh;e haue herde to-forne devise<MILESTONE N="72b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The kinges herte of pite gan agrise</L>
<L>Whan he se&thorn;e so benyngne a creature</L>
<L N="616">ffal in disese and in mesauenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor as &thorn;e lambe towarde towarde his de&thorn;e is brouht</L>
<L>So stant &thorn;is Innocent be-for &thorn;e kenge</L>
<L>This fals knyht &thorn;at ha&thorn;e &thorn;is treson wrouht</L>
<L N="620">Bere&thorn; hir on honde &thorn;a sche ha&thorn;e don &thorn;is &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Bot na&thorn;eles &thorn;er was grete Morneinge</L>
<L>Amonge &thorn;e peple and sei &thorn;e can not gesse</L>
<L N="623">That sche had done so grete a wikkenesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor &thorn;ei haue sene hir euer so vertuous</L>
<L>And loueinge ermenilde riht as hir lif</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is bare wittenes eueryche in &thorn;at house</L>
<L N="627">saue he &thorn;at Ermenilde slowhe wi&thorn; his knyfe</L>
<L>This Gentil kinge ha&thorn;e cauht a grete motif</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is wittenes And &thorn;ouht he wolde enquere</L>
<L N="630">Depper in &thorn;is caas he troue&thorn; for to lere
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="176"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="150"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alas Constance &thorn;ou naste no champioun</L>
<L>Ne fiht cans tow nouht so walawaie</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at for oure redempcioun</L>
<L N="634">And bonde Sathan. and lythe &yogh;it &thorn;ere he laye</L>
<L>So be &thorn;i stronge champion &thorn;is daie</L>
<L>ffor bot if criste oopen myracle ky&thorn;e</L>
<L N="637">Wi&thorn;e outen gilt &thorn;ou schalt be sleyne also swy&thorn;e</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sche Sett hir doune on knes and &thorn;us sche seyde</L>
<L>Immortale god &thorn;at sauedest Susan</L>
<L>ffrom false blam and &thorn;ou mercyful mayde</L>
<L N="641">Mary .I. mene douhter of seint Anne</L>
<L>Beforne whos childe Angels singe osanne</L>
<L>If .I. be giltles of &thorn;is felonye</L>
<L N="644">Mi soker be. for elles schal .I. deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Haue &yogh;e nouht seen sum tyme a pale face</L>
<L>Amonge a pres of him &thorn;at ha&thorn;e be lad</L>
<L>To wardes his de&thorn; where him gat no grace</L>
<L N="648">And suche a colour in his face ha&thorn; hadde</L>
<L>&thorn;at men miht knowe his face &thorn;at was be-stadde</L>
<L>Amonge al &thorn;e faces in &thorn;at route</L>
<L N="651">So stant Custance and loke&thorn; hire aboute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O queens leueinge in prosperite</L>
<L>Duchesses and ladies euerychon</L>
<L>Haue some reu&thorn;e of his aduersite</L>
<L N="655">An Emperour douhter stant alone<MILESTONE N="73a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sche ha&thorn;e no whihte to whome to make hire mone</L>
<L>O blode Roial &thorn;at standest in &thorn;is drede</L>
<L N="658">ffer bue &thorn;in frendes att &thorn;i grete nede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This allea kinge ha&thorn; suche compassioun</L>
<L>As gentil hert is fulfilled of pete</L>
<L>&THORN;at from his yen ran &thorn;e water doune</L>
<L N="662">Nowe hastely do feche a boke quod he
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="177"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="151"></L>
<L>And if &thorn;is knyht wil swere howe &thorn;at sche</L>
<L>This womman slowhe &yogh;it wil we vs avise</L>
<L N="665">Whome &thorn;at we wolde &thorn;at schal be oure Iustice</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A breton boke wreten wi&thorn; &thorn;e euangelies</L>
<L>Was fett and on &thorn;is boke he swore anone</L>
<L>Sche giltif was in &thorn;e mene whiles</L>
<L N="669">An hande him smote vpon &thorn;e nekke bone</L>
<L>&THORN;at doune he fel att ones as a stone</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e his ey&yogh;en borst oute of his face</L>
<L N="672">In siht of euery body in &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A voice was herde in general audience</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;ou haste disclaundred giltles</L>
<L>The douhter of holy cherche in hiehe presence</L>
<L N="676">Thus hast &thorn;ou done and &yogh;it .I. mot hold my pes</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is Merueile a-gast was al &thorn;e pres</L>
<L>As Mased folke &thorn;ei stoden euerychone</L>
<L N="679">ffor drede of wreche saue Constance alone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Grete was &thorn;e dede and eke &thorn;e repentance</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at hadden wronge suspecione</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;is cely Innocent constance</L>
<L N="683">And for &thorn;is miracle in conclusione</L>
<L>And by Constance Mediacione</L>
<L>The kinge and mony a-no&thorn;er in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="686">Conuerted was &thorn;onked be cristes grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This fals knyht was sleyne for his vntrew&thorn;e</L>
<L>Be Iuggement of Allea Hastelye</L>
<L>And Constance ha&thorn;e of his de&thorn;e grete rew&thorn;e</L>
<L N="690">And after &thorn;is ihesus of his mercy</L>
<L>Maade Alla wedden ful solempnely.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holy mayden &thorn;at is briht and schene</L>
<L N="693">And &thorn;us ha&thorn;e criste maad Constance a queene
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="178"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="152"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bot who was woful. If .I. schal not lye</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is wedynge bot Domylda and no mo</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinges moder ful of Tiranny.</L>
<L N="697">Hire &thorn;ouht hir cursed hert braste a two<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sche wolde nouht her sonne had don so</L>
<L>Hir &thorn;ouht a dispite &thorn;at he scholde take</L>
<L N="700">So straunge a creature vnto his maake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Me list nouht of &thorn;e chaf ne of &thorn;e stre</L>
<L>Maake so longe a tale as of &thorn;e corne</L>
<L>What scholde .I. tellen of &thorn;e royalte</L>
<L N="704">Of &thorn;e Mariage or whiche cours go&thorn; to forne</L>
<L>Who blowe&thorn; in a trompe or in an horne</L>
<L>The fruyte of euery tale is for to seie</L>
<L N="707">Thei ete. and drinke and dance. and singe and pleie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thei gone to bed as it was skill and riht</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ouhe &thorn;at wyues bene holy &thorn;inges</L>
<L>Thei must take a pacience a nyht</L>
<L N="711">Suche maner necessaries as biene plesinges</L>
<L>To folke &thorn;at hane ywedded hem wi&thorn; ringes</L>
<L>And laie a lite hire holines a side</L>
<L N="714">As for &thorn;e time it maie non o&thorn;er betide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; On hire he gate a knaue childe anone</L>
<L>And to a bischop and his Cunstabule eke</L>
<L>He toke his wif to kepe whan he is gone</L>
<L N="718">To scotelande ward his fomen for to seke</L>
<L>Nowe faire Custance &thorn;at is so humble and meke</L>
<L>So longe is gone wi&thorn; childe til &thorn;at still</L>
<L N="721">Sche halt hir chambure abideinge att cristes will</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The time is come a knaue childe sche bare</L>
<L>Mauricius att &thorn;e font &thorn;ei him calle</L>
<L>This Constable do&thorn; for&thorn;e come a Messagier</L>
<L N="725">And wrote to his kinge &thorn;at cleped was Alle
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="179"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="153"></L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at &thorn;is blisful ti&thorn;inge was be-falle</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er ti&thorn;inge spedful for to seie</L>
<L N="728">He take&thorn; &thorn;e letter and for&thorn;e he go&thorn; his weie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Messagier to done his auantage</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e kinges moder ride&thorn; swy&thorn;e</L>
<L>And salue&thorn; hire ful faire in his langage</L>
<L N="732">Madame quod he he &yogh;e maye glad and bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>And &thorn;onke&thorn; god an hundre&thorn; &thorn;ousand si&thorn;e</L>
<L>My lady queene ha&thorn; childe wi&thorn; oute doute</L>
<L N="735">To Ioy and blisse of al &thorn;is regne a-boute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lo here &thorn;e lettres selede of &thorn;e ti&thorn;inge</L>
<L>&thorn;at .I. mote bere wi&thorn; al &thorn;e hast .I. maie</L>
<L>If &yogh;e wille ouht vn to &yogh;owre sone &thorn;e kinge.</L>
<L N="739">I am &yogh;oure seruant bo&thorn;e niht and daie<MILESTONE N="74a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Domilda anseward as nowe at &thorn;is time</L>
<L>Bot here al niht .I. wil &thorn;at &thorn;ou take &thorn;i rest</L>
<L N="742">To morwe will .I. saie what me lest</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Messagier dranke sadly ale and wyne</L>
<L>And stollne was his lettres priuely</L>
<L>Out off his box while he slepe as a swyne</L>
<L N="746">And Conterfet was ful sotely</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er lettres wrouht ful sinfuly.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e kinge direct of &thorn;is matier</L>
<L N="749">ffro his Constable as &yogh;e schal after here</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The lettre spak howe &thorn;e queene deliuerd was</L>
<L>Of so horrible fendelyche creature</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e Castel none so hardy was</L>
<L N="753">That any while dorst &thorn;er in endure</L>
<L>The moder was an elfe be aventure</L>
<L>Ycome be charmes or be sorceri</L>
<L N="756">And euery whitte hate&thorn;e hir company
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="180"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="154"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Woo was &thorn;is kinge whan he &thorn;is lettre had seyne</L>
<L>Bot to no white he tolde &thorn;is sorwe sore</L>
<L>Bot of his owen he wrote ageyne</L>
<L N="760">Welcome be &thorn;e sonde of criste for euer more</L>
<L>To me &thorn;at am nowe lerend in his lore</L>
<L>Lord welcom be &thorn;i lust and &thorn;i plesance</L>
<L N="763">Mi lust is put al in &thorn;ine ordinance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Kepe&thorn; &thorn;is childe al be it foule or faire</L>
<L>And eke my wif vnto myne home comynge</L>
<L>Criste whan him liste maie sende me an heire</L>
<L N="767">More Agreable &thorn;an this to my likinge</L>
<L>This letter he sele&thorn; priuely wepeinge</L>
<L>Whiche to &thorn;e Messagier was take sone</L>
<L N="770">And for&thorn;e he go&thorn;e &thorn;are is nomore to done</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O Messagier fulfilde of dronkennesse</L>
<L>Stronge is &thorn;i bre&thorn;e &thorn;i limmes faltern aye</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou be-wreyest al sekurnesse</L>
<L N="774">Thi mynde is lorne &thorn;u Iangelest as a Iaye</L>
<L>Thi face is turned in a newe arraie</L>
<L>There drunkennesse reygne&thorn; in any route</L>
<L N="777">&THORN;ere is no counsel hidde wi&thorn; outen doute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O domilda. I ne haue non englisshe digne</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;i malice and &thorn;i tirannye</L>
<L>An &thorn;er-for to &thorn;e fende .I. &thorn;e resigne.</L>
<L N="781">Lat him endite &thorn;i traitery<MILESTONE N="74b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffy mannysshe fy. o nay be god .I. lye</L>
<L>ffy fendlyche spirit for .I. dare wele telle</L>
<L N="784">Thouhe &thorn;ou here walke &thorn;i spirit is in helle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Messagier come&thorn; fro &thorn;e kinge a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>And att &thorn;e kinges moder courte he li&thorn;e</L>
<L>And sche was of &thorn;is Messagier ful faine</L>
<L N="788">And plesed him in al &thorn;at euer sche myht
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="181"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="155"></L>
<L>He dranke and wele his girdel vnder pyht</L>
<L>He slepe&thorn; and he fronte&thorn; in his gise</L>
<L N="791">Alle nyht til &thorn;e son gan rise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Eft was his letters stollen euerych&omacr;n</L>
<L>And Conterfet lettres in &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>The kinge Commande&thorn; his constable a none</L>
<L N="795">Vppeyne of hangeynge or an hihe Iewys</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne schold suffur in no wise</L>
<L>Constance inwi&thorn;e his regne to Abide</L>
<L N="798">Thre daies and a quarter of a tide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bot in &thorn;e same schippe as he hir fonde</L>
<L>Hire and hire &yogh;onge sone and hir gere</L>
<L>He schold putte and croude fro &thorn;e londe</L>
<L N="802">And Charger &thorn;at sche neuer eft com &thorn;ere</L>
<L>O my Constance wele may &thorn;i goste haue fere</L>
<L>And slepeinge in &thorn;i dreme be in penance</L>
<L N="805">Whan Domilda cast al &thorn;is ordinance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Messagier on morwe whan he woke</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e castel halt &thorn;e next waie</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Constable he &thorn;e letter toke</L>
<L N="809">And whan &thorn;at he &thorn;is pitous lettre saye</L>
<L>fful oft he seide alas and walawaie</L>
<L>Lord criste quod he howe maie &thorn;is lettre endure</L>
<L N="812">So wooful of synne is mony a creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O myhti god. if &thorn;at it be &thorn;i wille</L>
<L>Sethe &thorn;owe is riht-ful Iugge howe maie it be</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou wilt suffur Innocent to spille</L>
<L N="816">An wikked folk reigne in prosperite</L>
<L>O good Constance alas so woo is me</L>
<L>&THORN;at .I. mot be &thorn;i tormentour or deye</L>
<L N="819">On schames de&thorn; &thorn;ere is none o&thorn;er weie
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="182"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="156"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wepen bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge and olde in al &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e kinge &thorn;is cursede letter sent</L>
<L>And Custance wi&thorn; a dedly pale face</L>
<L N="823">&THORN;e fer&thorn;e daie to warde &thorn;e schippe sche wente<MILESTONE N="75a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot Na&thorn;eles sche take&thorn; in goode entente</L>
<L>&THORN;e will of criste and kneleinge att &thorn;e stronde</L>
<L N="826">Sche seide lorde ay welcome be &thorn;i sonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He &thorn;at me keppet fro &thorn;e fals blame</L>
<L>While .y. was in &thorn;e londe amonges &yogh;owe</L>
<L>He can me kepe from arme and eke frome schame</L>
<L N="830">In salt see al-&thorn;ouhe .I. see nou&yogh;t howe</L>
<L>As stronge as euer he was he is riht nowe</L>
<L>In him trust .I. and in his moder dere</L>
<L N="833">&THORN;at is to me my saile and eke my stere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hire litel childe laie wepeinge in hir arme</L>
<L>And knelynge pitusly to him sche seide</L>
<L>Pees litel son .I. will do &thorn;e none harme</L>
<L N="837">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e kerchef of hir hede sche braide</L>
<L>And ouer his litel yen sche it leide</L>
<L>And in hir arme sche lulle&thorn; it ful fast</L>
<L N="840">And in to heuen her yen vp sche cast</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Moder quod sche and Maiden briht Marie</L>
<L>So&thorn;e is &thorn;at &thorn;oruh wommannes egment</L>
<L>Man kinde was lorne and dampned aye to deye</L>
<L N="844">ffor whiche &thorn;i childe was on a crois rente</L>
<L>&THORN;i blisfully yen sawhe all his tornement</L>
<L>Than is &thorn;ere no comparison be-twene</L>
<L N="847">&THORN;i woo and any woo man may susteigne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thowe sawhe &thorn;i sonne slayne to for &thorn;in ey&yogh;ene</L>
<L>And &yogh;it leue&thorn; now my childe parfaie</L>
<L>Now lady to whome al woful cry&yogh;en</L>
<L N="851">Thow glorie of wommanhode &thorn;ou faire maie
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="183"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="157"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou haven of refute briht sterre of daie</L>
<L>Rew on my childe &thorn;at of &thorn;i gentillesse</L>
<L N="854">Rewest on euery rewful in destrisse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O litel childe alas what is &thorn;i gilte</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer wrouhtest sinne as &yogh;it parde</L>
<L>Whi wil &thorn;i hard fader haue &thorn;e spilte</L>
<L N="858">O merci dere constable quod sche</L>
<L>As lat my litel childe dwel here wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou darst nouht saue him frome blame</L>
<L N="861">So kesse him ones in his faders name</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ther-wi&thorn; sche loked bakward to &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>And seide fare wel husbonde rew&thorn;eles</L>
<L>And vp sche rise&thorn; and walke&thorn; doune &thorn;e stronde</L>
<L>To warde &thorn;e schippe hir folowe&thorn; al &thorn;e prees<MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And euer sche praie&thorn; her childe to holde his pees</L>
<L>And take&thorn; hire leue and wi&thorn; an holy entent</L>
<L N="868">Sche blisse&thorn; hir and in to schippe sche went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vitailled was &thorn;e schip it is no drede</L>
<L>Abundantly for hire ful longe space</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere necessaries &thorn;at schold nede</L>
<L N="872">Sche had .I.-nowhe heried be goddes grace</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bringe hire home .I. can no better saie</L>
<L N="875">Bot in &thorn;e see sche driue&thorn; for&thorn; hire waie</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART III.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alla &thorn;e kinge come&thorn; home sone after &thorn;is</L>
<L>Vnto his Castel of &thorn;e whiche .I. tolde</L>
<L>And axe&thorn; where his wif and his childe is</L>
<L N="879">The Constable gan aboute his hert colde
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="184"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="158"></L>
<L>And pleinly al &thorn;e maner he him tolde</L>
<L>As &yogh;e hane herde .I. kan tel it no better</L>
<L N="882">And schewe&thorn; &thorn;e kinge his seal and his letter</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And seide lorde as &yogh;e commaunded me</L>
<L>Vp peine of de&thorn; so haue .I. done certeine</L>
<L>This Messagier tumended was til he</L>
<L N="886">Most be-knowen and tellen plat and pleine</L>
<L>ffrom nyht to nyht where &thorn;at he had leine</L>
<L>And &thorn;us be witte and soubtile enquereinge</L>
<L N="889">Imagened was be wham &thorn;is harme gan springe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The hande was knowe &thorn;at &thorn;e lettre wrote</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e venym of &thorn;is cursed dede</L>
<L>Bot in what wise certeinli .I. note</L>
<L N="893">&thorn;e effecte is &thorn;is &thorn;at oute of drede</L>
<L>His moder he slowhe &thorn;at mai men pleinli rede</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at sche traitour was to hire legance</L>
<L N="896">Thus ende&thorn; olde Domylda wi&thorn; meschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The sorwe &thorn;at &thorn;is Alla nyht and daye</L>
<L>Make&thorn; for his wif and his childe also</L>
<L>Ther is no tunge &thorn;at it telle maie</L>
<L N="900">Bot now wil .I. vnto Custance go</L>
<L>&THORN;at flete&thorn; in &thorn;e se in peine and wo</L>
<L>&THORN;re &yogh;ere and more as liked crist sonde</L>
<L N="903">Or &thorn;at hir schip approched vnto &thorn;e londe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vnder an hey&thorn;en castel att &thorn;e last</L>
<L>Of whiche &thorn;e name in my text not .I. finde</L>
<L>Custance and eke hir childe &thorn;e see vpkast</L>
<L N="907">Al myhti &thorn;at saue&thorn; al mankinde</L>
<L>Haue on Constance and hire childe sum mynde<MILESTONE N="76a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That fallen is in hey&thorn;e honde eft sone.</L>
<L N="910">In pointe to spille as .I. scall tel &yogh;owe sone
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="185"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="159"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Done fro &thorn;e Castel comme&thorn; &thorn;ere mony a whihte</L>
<L>To gauren on &thorn;is schep and on Constance</L>
<L>Bot schortly fro &thorn;e castel on a nyht</L>
<L N="914">The lord steweard god &yogh;iue him meschance</L>
<L>A &thorn;ef &thorn;at had reneyde oure creance</L>
<L>Com vn schip alon and seide he schold</L>
<L N="917">Hir lemman be where sche wolde or nolde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Woo was &thorn;is wreched womman woo be gone</L>
<L>Hir Childe cride and sche cried pitously</L>
<L>Bot blisse-ful Marye helped hir a none</L>
<L N="921">ffor wi&thorn;&thorn;e hir strogelinge wele and myhtily</L>
<L>The &thorn;ef fel ouere &thorn;e borde al sodanly.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e se he drenched for vengance</L>
<L N="924">And &thorn;us ha&thorn; crist vnvenemed keped Custance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O foule lust of luxurie lo &thorn;ine ende</L>
<L>Not onely &thorn;at &thorn;ou faintest mannes mynde</L>
<L>Bot verraili &thorn;ou wilt his body schende</L>
<L N="928">The ende of &thorn;i werk or of &thorn;i lust-is blinde</L>
<L>Is compleigneinge howe many oone men maie finde</L>
<L>&THORN;at not for werke sum time bot for &thorn;e entente</L>
<L N="931">To done &thorn;is sinne bene ey&thorn;er sleyne or schente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Howe maie &thorn;is wayko womman haue &thorn;e strenke&thorn;</L>
<L>Hir to dofende a&yogh;eine &thorn;is renegate</L>
<L>O golyas vnmesurable of lenge&thorn;e</L>
<L N="935">Howe myht dauid make &thorn;e so mate</L>
<L>So &yogh;onge and of Armour so desolate</L>
<L>Howe dorst he loke vpon &thorn;i dredeful face</L>
<L N="938">Wele maie men seen it is bot goddes grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who &yogh;af Iudith. Corage or hardinesse</L>
<L>To slene him Olefernus in his tent</L>
<L>And to deliuer oute of wrechednesse</L>
<L N="942">&THORN;e peple of god .I. seide for &thorn;is entente
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="186"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="160"></L>
<L>&THORN;at riht as god spiret and vigor sente</L>
<L>To heme and saued hem out of meschance</L>
<L N="945">So sent he myht and vigor to Constance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor go&thorn;e hir schipe &thorn;oruhe oute &thorn;e narow mou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Of Iubalter and &thorn;ens driueinge aye</L>
<L>Sum tim west and sum tim nor&thorn;e and sou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="949">And som time est ful mony a wery daie.</L>
<L>Til cristes moder blissed be sche aye<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ha&thorn; schapen &thorn;oruhe hire endeles goodenes</L>
<L N="952">To make an hende of al her heuenes</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now latte vs stent of Constance bot a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>An speke we of &thorn;e Romaine Emperour</L>
<L>That oute of Surry ha&thorn;e be letters knowe</L>
<L N="956">The slawhte of Cristen folk and dishonour</L>
<L>Done to his douhter be a fals traitour</L>
<L>.I. mene &thorn;e Curssed wikked Sawdanesse</L>
<L N="959">&THORN;at att &thorn;e fest le slen bo&thorn;e more and lesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor whiche &thorn;is Emperour ha&thorn; sent anone</L>
<L>His Senatour wi&thorn; roial ordinance</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er lordes god wote manyone</L>
<L N="963">On Surriens to taken hir vengeance</L>
<L>Thei brennen slene and bringen hem to meschance</L>
<L>ffol mony a day bot schortly &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L N="966">Homwarde to Rome &thorn;ei schapen hem to wende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Senator repaire&thorn; wi&thorn; vittorie</L>
<L>To Romewarde seileinge ful Roialy</L>
<L>And mette &thorn;e schippe driueynge as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e storie</L>
<L N="970">In whiche Constance sitte ful pitously.</L>
<L>No &thorn;inge ne knewe he what sche was ne whi</L>
<L>Sche was in Suche aray ne sche wil seye</L>
<L N="973">Of hir estate &thorn;ouhe sche schold deie
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="187"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="161"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He bringe&thorn; hir to Rome And to his wif</L>
<L>He &yogh;af hire and hire &yogh;onge sone also</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e Senatur sche led hir lif</L>
<L N="977">Thus can owre lady bringen oute of wo</L>
<L>Woful Constance and mony ano&thorn;ere mo</L>
<L>And longe time dwelled sche in &thorn;is place</L>
<L N="980">In holy werkes euer as was hire grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Senatour wif hire <NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS <I>corrected</I>]</NOTE>Aunte was</L>
<L>Bot for al&thorn;at sche knewe hire neuere more</L>
<L>.I. wil no longer tarien in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L N="984">Bot to kinge Alla whiche .I. spake of &yogh;ore</L>
<L>That for his wif wepe&thorn; and sike&thorn; sore</L>
<L>.I. wil retorne and lete .I. wil Constance</L>
<L N="987">Vnder &thorn;e Senatour gouernance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Kinge Alla whiche &thorn;at had his moder sleyne</L>
<L>Vppon a daie fel in suche repentance</L>
<L>&THORN;at . if .I. schortly tellen schall and pleyne</L>
<L N="991">To Rome he come&thorn; to receyuen his penance</L>
<L>And put him in &thorn;e popes ordinan[c]e<MILESTONE N="77a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In hihe and lowe and ihesu crist be-souht</L>
<L N="994">ffor-&yogh;eue his wikked werke &thorn;at he wrouht</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The fame anone &thorn;orwhe Rome toune is borne</L>
<L>Howe alla kinge scha com in pilgrenage</L>
<L>Be herberioures &thorn;at went him be forne</L>
<L N="998">ffor whiche &thorn;e Senatour as was &thorn;e vsage</L>
<L>Rode him a&yogh;eine and mony of his lignage</L>
<L>Als wele to schewe his magnificence</L>
<L N="1001">As to done any kenge a reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Grete chiere do&thorn;e &thorn;is noble Senatour</L>
<L>To kinge Alla and he to him also</L>
<L>Eueriche of hem do&thorn; to o&thorn;ere grete honour</L>
<L N="1005">And so be-fel &thorn;at on a daie or two
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="188"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="162"></L>
<L>This Senatur is to kinge Alla go</L>
<L>To feste and schortly if .I. schal nouht lye</L>
<L N="1008">Costance sone in his companye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Som men wald seine att &thorn;e request of Custance</L>
<L>This Senatour ha&thorn;e ledde &thorn;is childe to fest</L>
<L>.I. maie not tel euery Circumstance</L>
<L N="1012">Be as be may &thorn;ere he was at lest</L>
<L>Bot so&thorn; &thorn;is is &thorn;at att his moder hest</L>
<L>Be-forne Alla dureinge &thorn;e mete space</L>
<L N="1015">The childe stode lokeinge in &thorn;e kinges face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Alla kinge ha&thorn; of &thorn;is childe grete wonder</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Senator he seide a none</L>
<L>Whos is &thorn;at faire childe &thorn;at stonde&thorn; &yogh;onder</L>
<L N="1019">.I. note quod he be god and be seinte Iohn</L>
<L>A moder he ha&thorn;e bot fader ha&thorn;e he none</L>
<L>&THORN;at .I. of wote and schortly schortly in a stounde</L>
<L N="1022">He tolde Alla howe &thorn;at &thorn;is childe was founde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bot god woote quod &thorn;is Senatour also</L>
<L>So vertuouse a leuere in my lyf</L>
<L>Sawhe .I. neuer as sche . ne herd of moo</L>
<L N="1026">Of werldly wemmen . Maiden or wif</L>
<L>.I. dar wele saie sche had leuer a knyf</L>
<L>Thoruhe hir breste &thorn;an bene a womman wik</L>
<L N="1029">There is no man cou&thorn;e bringe hire to &thorn;at prik</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nowe was &thorn;is childe as like vn to custance</L>
<L>As possible as is a creature to be</L>
<L>This Alla ha&thorn;e &thorn;e face in remembrance</L>
<L N="1033">Of Dame Custance and &thorn;ere-on mused he</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;e childes moder weer ouht sche<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That is wif and priuely he siht</L>
<L N="1036">And sped him fro &thorn;e table &thorn;at he myht
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="189"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="163"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Par faye &thorn;ouht he &thorn;e fantome is in myn hede</L>
<L>.I. hauht demen of skilful Iuggement</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e salt se my wif is dede</L>
<L N="1040">And afterward he maade his Argument</L>
<L>What wote .I. if &thorn;at crist hire ha&thorn; hider sent</L>
<L>.Mi. wyf be see as wele as he hire sent</L>
<L N="1043">To my contre from &thorn;ens &thorn;at sche was went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And after none home wi&thorn; &thorn;e Senatour</L>
<L>Go&thorn;e Alla for to seen &thorn;is wonder chaunce</L>
<L>This Senatour do&thorn; alla a grete honoure</L>
<L N="1047">And hastely sent after Custance</L>
<L>Truste&thorn; wele hire liste nouht to daunce</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at sche wiste where for was &thorn;at sonde</L>
<L N="1050">Vnne&thorn;e vp vpon hire feete sche myht stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whan Alla sauhe his wif faire he hire grete</L>
<L>And wepped &thorn;at it was reu&thorn;e for to see</L>
<L>ffor att &thorn;e first loke he on hire sette</L>
<L N="1054">He knewe wele verraile &thorn;at it was sche</L>
<L>And for sorwe as dombe stant as a tre</L>
<L>So was hir hert schette in hire distresse</L>
<L N="1057">When sche remembred his vnkindenesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Twys sche swownede in his owen siht</L>
<L>He wepe and him excuse&thorn; pitusly</L>
<L>God quod he and his Halowes briht</L>
<L N="1061">So wisly of my soule as haue mercy</L>
<L>That of &yogh;oure harme as gelteles am .I.</L>
<L>As. is Moris my sone so like &yogh;owre face</L>
<L N="1064">Elles &thorn;e fende me feche out of &thorn;is place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Longe was &thorn;e sobynge and &thorn;e bitter peine</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at hir woful hertes myht cesse</L>
<L>Grete was was &thorn;e pite for to here hem pleine</L>
<L N="1068">Thoruhe whiche pleintes gan her woo encres
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="190"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="164"></L>
<L>I. pray &yogh;ow al my labour to relese</L>
<L>.I. maie nouht tel hir woo vn-to to morwe</L>
<L N="1071">.I. am so wery to speke of hir sorwe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bot fynally whan &thorn;at &thorn;e so&thorn;e is wist</L>
<L>That Alla gilteles was of hir woo</L>
<L>.I. trowe. an .C. times bene &thorn;ei kist</L>
<L N="1075">And suche a blisse is &thorn;ere be-tuex hem two</L>
<L>That saue&thorn; &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at laste&thorn; euer mo<MILESTONE N="78a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>There is none like &thorn;at any creature</L>
<L N="1078">Ha&thorn; seen or schal while &thorn;e werlde maye dure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Tho praide sche hir husbond mekly</L>
<L>In releueinge of hir longe pitous pyne</L>
<L>&THORN;a he wolde praie hir fader s[p]ecialy</L>
<L N="1082">That he of his hihe Magestee enclyne</L>
<L>To vowchesaue som day wi&thorn; him to dyne</L>
<L>Sche praide him eke he scholde be no weie</L>
<L N="1085">Vnto hire fader no worde of hir seie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Som men wold sey howe &thorn;at &thorn;e Childe morice</L>
<L>Do&thorn; &thorn;is Message vn-to &thorn;is Emperour</L>
<L>Bot as .I. gesse Alla was nouht so nyce</L>
<L N="1089">To him &thorn;at was of so souereigne honoure</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at is of cristen folke &thorn;e floure</L>
<L>Sent any Childe but it is bet to deme</L>
<L N="1092">He went him selfe and so it maie wele seme</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Emperoure ha&thorn; graunted gentilly</L>
<L>To come to denere as he him besouht</L>
<L>And wele rede .I. he loked besyly.</L>
<L N="1096">Vpon &thorn;is child. and on his douhter &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>Alla go&thorn;e to his Inne as him ouhte</L>
<L>And array for &thorn;is feste in euery wise</L>
<L N="1099">As ferfor&thorn;e as his comynge maie suffise
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="191"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="165"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The morwe cam and Alla gan him dresse</L>
<L>And eke his wif &thorn;is emperour for to mete</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e &thorn;ei redde in Ioy. and in gladnesse</L>
<L N="1103">And whan sche seyhe hire fader in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>Sche lihte&thorn; adoune and falle&thorn; him to fete</L>
<L>ffader quod sche &yogh;oure &yogh;onge childe Constance</L>
<L N="1106">Is nowe ful clene oute of &yogh;oure remembrance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; .I. am &yogh;oure douhter Constance quod sche</L>
<L>That whilome &yogh;e sente vnto Surrye</L>
<L>It am .I. fader &thorn;at in salt see</L>
<L N="1110">Was put alone and dampned for to dye</L>
<L>Goode fader to &yogh;owe .I. crye</L>
<L>Sende me no more<NOTE PLACE="marg">[re <I>interlined in red</I>]</NOTE> in to hey&thorn;ennesse</L>
<L N="1113">Bot &thorn;onke my lorde here of his kindenesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who kan &thorn;e pytous Ioy tellen all</L>
<L>Be-twixe hem &thorn;ree se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ei bue &thorn;us ymett</L>
<L>Bot of my tale make an ende .I. schall</L>
<L N="1117">The day go&thorn;e fast .I. wil no longer lette</L>
<L>This gladde folke to denere &thorn;ei hem sette<MILESTONE N="78b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In Ioy and blisse att &thorn;e mete .I. lete hem dwelle</L>
<L N="1120">A. &thorn;ousand folde wel mor &thorn;an .I. can telle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;is Childe Moris was si&thorn;en Emperour</L>
<L>Maade be &thorn;e pope an leued Cristienly</L>
<L>To Cristes chirche he dide grete honoure</L>
<L N="1124">Bot I. lat al his storie passen bie</L>
<L>Of Constance is my tale sekerlie</L>
<L>In olde Romeyne gestes men mai finde</L>
<L N="1127">Moris lif .I. bere it nouht in mynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This kinge Alla whan he his time seie</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his Custance his holy wif so swete</L>
<L>To Ingelonde bue &thorn;ei comen &thorn;e riht weie</L>
<L N="1131">Where as &thorn;ei leue in Ioy and in quyete
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="192"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="166"></L>
<L>Bot litel while it laste&thorn; .I. &yogh;owe hete</L>
<L>Ioy of &thorn;is werlde for time wil nou&yogh;t abide</L>
<L N="1134">ffro day to nyht it chaunge&thorn; as &thorn;e tide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who so leue&thorn; euer in suche delite a daie</L>
<L>&thorn;at ne meued ey&thorn;er conscience</L>
<L>Or ire or talent or sumkin afraie</L>
<L N="1138">Envie or pride or passion or offense</L>
<L>.I. ne saie bot &thorn;is ende &thorn;is sentense</L>
<L>&thorn;at litel while in Ioy or in plesance</L>
<L N="1141">Laste&thorn; &thorn;e blisse of alla wi&thorn; Constance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor de&thorn; &thorn;at take&thorn; of hihe and louhe his rent</L>
<L>Whan passed was a &yogh;ere euen as .I. gesse</L>
<L>Oute of &thorn;is werlde kinge Alla he hente</L>
<L N="1145">ffore whome Constance ha&thorn;e ful grete heuinesse</L>
<L>Now latt vs preyne God his soule blisse</L>
<L>And dam Constance fynally to seye</L>
<L N="1148">To warde &thorn;e toune of Rome go&thorn;e hire weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To Rome is comen is comen &thorn;is holy creature</L>
<L>And fynde&thorn;e here frendes hole and sounde</L>
<L>Now is sche scaped al hir a-venture</L>
<L N="1152">Whan sche hir fader ha&thorn; founde</L>
<L>Doune on hir knees falle&thorn; sche to grounde</L>
<L>Wepeinge for tendurnesse in hert bli&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1155">Sche herie&thorn; god a .C. &thorn;ousand si&thorn;e</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In vertu and holy almosdede</L>
<L>Thei leuen al. and neuer a sonder wende</L>
<L>Til de&thorn;e depart hem &thorn;is lif &thorn;ei lede</L>
<L N="1159">An fare nowe wele my tale is att an ende</L>
<L>Nowe ihesu criste &thorn;at of his myht maye sende<MILESTONE N="79a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ioy after woo gouerne vs in his grace</L>
<L N="1162">And kepe vs al &thorn;at bene in &thorn;is place</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER><B>Explicit fabula</B> legis periti.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="193">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="167">
<HEAD>Incipit prologus Armigeri.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 79</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OWre Ost vpon his stereps stode anone</L>
<L>And seide goode men herkene&thorn; euerychone</L>
<L>This was a &thorn;refty tale for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L N="1166">Sir pariche preste quod he for goddes bones</L>
<L>Tel vs a tale as was &thorn;i forward &yogh;ore</L>
<L>.I. se welee &thorn;at &yogh;e lerned men in lore</L>
<L>Can muchel goode be goddes dignite</L>
<L N="1170">The person him anseward benedicite</L>
<L>What eyley &thorn;e man so sinfuly to swere</L>
<L>Owr oste anseward Iankin be &yogh;e &thorn;ere</L>
<L>.I. smel a loller in &thorn;e wynde quod he</L>
<L N="1174">How good men quod oure oste herkene&thorn; me</L>
<L>Abide&thorn; for goddes deyne passione</L>
<L>ffor we schal haue a predicacione</L>
<L>This loller will prechen her sumwhat</L>
<L N="1178">Nay be my fader sowle &thorn;at sal he nat</L>
<L>Seid &thorn;e swyere her schal he nouht preche</L>
<L>He schal no gospel glosen here ne teche</L>
<L>He leue&thorn; al in &thorn;e grete god he</L>
<L N="1182">He wolde sowen sum difficulte</L>
<L>Or sprengen cokel in oure clene corne</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-for oste .I. warne &thorn;e be-forne</L>
<L>Mi Ioly body . schal a tale tell</L>
<L N="1186">And .I. schal klynken &yogh;ow so mery a bell</L>
<L>&THORN;at .I. schal waken al &thorn;is compaignie</L>
<L>Bot it schal not bien of philosophie</L>
<L>Ne fisleas ne turnies queynte of lawe</L>
<L N="1190">There is bot litel latine in my mawe<NOTE PLACE="end">[The Squire's Tale follows in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit prologus.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="F" TYPE="group">


<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000222.tif" N="194">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="479">
<HEAD>Incipit fabula.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 79</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Att Sarray in &thorn;e londe o Tartary .</L>
<L>Ther dwelled a kinge &thorn;at werred Russy</L>
<L>&thorn;oruhe whiche &thorn;ere deyed mony a douhti man .</L>
<L N="12">&thorn;is nobil kinge was cleped Kambynskan</L>
<L>Whiche of his time whas of so grete renone</L>
