<L N="1472">&yogh;e wife quod he lat slepe &thorn;at is still</L>
<L>It maie be wele &yogh;it perauentur to seie</L>
<L>Sche schol &yogh;oure trou&thorn;e holden be my faie</L>
<L>For god so wisly helpe me</L>
<L N="1476">.I. hadde well leuer ystiked for to be</L>
<L>For verrei loue whiche &thorn;at .I. to &yogh;oue haue</L>
<L>Bot if &yogh;e scholde &yogh;oure trou&thorn;e saue</L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e is &thorn;e hiest &thorn;inge &thorn;at man maie kepe</L>
<L N="1480">Bot wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde he brast anone to wepe</L>
<L>And seide .I. &yogh;oue for-bede vpon peyne of de&thorn;e</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer whiles &yogh;e last lif ne bre&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Til no wihte telle howe &thorn;at &thorn;is matier<MILESTONE N="150b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1484">As .I. maye kepe .I. wil me wo endure</L>
<L>Ne make no countenance of heuynesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at folke of &yogh;owe maie deme harme or gesse</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e he cleped a swyer and a maide</L>
<L N="1488">Go&thorn;e for&thorn;e anone wi&thorn; Dorogen he saide
<PB REF="00000401.tif" N="373"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="522"></L>
<L>And bringe&thorn;e hir to suche a place anone</L>
<L>&thorn;ei toke her leue and on &thorn;eire wei &thorn;ei gone</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ei ne wist whie sche &thorn;edere went</L>
<L N="1492">He nold no whiht telle hire entent</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="marg">[These lines known only in the Ellesmere MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="1496">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>This Swyere whiche &thorn;at hiht Aurelius</L>
<L N="1500">On dorigen whiche &thorn;at was so amerous</L>
<L>Of aduenture happed. hire to mete</L>
<L>A-mydde &thorn;e toune riht in &thorn;e quek strete</L>
<L>As sche was boune to gone &thorn;e waie for&thorn; riht</L>
<L N="1504">To-warde &thorn;ere as sche had hiht</L>
<L>And he was to &thorn;e Gardeine ward also</L>
<L>For wele he spiede whan sche wold go</L>
<L>Owte of hire hous to any maner place</L>
<L N="1508">Bot &thorn;us &thorn;ei mette of aduenture or of grace</L>
<L>And he saluyd hire wi&thorn; glad entente</L>
<L>And axed of hire wheder &thorn;at sche wente</L>
<L>And sche ansewarde half as sche was madde</L>
<L>[Vnto the gardyn as my husbonde bad<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane 1686 folio" N="205b">]</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e for to holde alas alas</L>
<L>Aurelius gan wonder of &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>And in his hert had grete compassione</L>
<L N="1516">Of hire and of hire lamentacione</L>
<L>And of Arnaragus &thorn;e wor&thorn;i knyht</L>
<L>&thorn;at bad hire holde al &thorn;at sche hiht</L>
<L>So lo&thorn;e he was his wif schold breke hir trou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1520">And in his herte he kest of &thorn;is grete rou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Consideringe &thorn;e beste on euery side</L>
<L>&thorn;at fro his luste were him better abide</L>
<L>&thorn;an done so hihe a cherles wrechednesse</L>
<L N="1524">A&yogh;eines ffraunchis and a&yogh;eynes al gentillesse
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="374"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="523"></L>
<L>For whiche in fewe wordes seide he &thorn;us</L>
<L>Madame sei&thorn;e to &yogh;oure lorde Arneragus</L>
<L>&thorn;at se&thorn;in .I. see &thorn;is grete gentillesse</L>
<L N="1528">To &yogh;owe. and eke .I. see wele &yogh;oure destresse</L>
<L N="1530">&thorn;an &yogh;e to me &thorn;us scholde breke &yogh;oure trou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Sertes me &thorn;inke&thorn; it were riht grete rou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>spurious</I> 1529]</NOTE></L>
<L>.I. haue wele leuer euer to suffre woo<MILESTONE N="151a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1532">Then .I. departe &thorn;e loue be-tuex &yogh;ow tuoo</L>
<L>.I. &yogh;owe reles ma dame in to &yogh;oure honde</L>
<L>Quyte euery surement and euery bonde</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e haue maade to me as here be-forne</L>
<L N="1536">Se&thorn;yns &thorn;ilke time &thorn;at &yogh;e were borne</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e .I. plihte .I. schal &yogh;owe neuer repreue</L>
<L>Of no by-heste and here .I. take my leue</L>
<L>As of &thorn;e trewest and &thorn;e best wif</L>
<L N="1540">&thorn;at euere &yogh;it knewe .I. in al my lyf</L>
<L>Bot euer y wyht bewar of hire behest</L>
<L>On dorigen remembre&thorn; att &thorn;e lest</L>
<L>&thorn;us can a swyer done a gentil dede</L>
<L N="1544">As wele as kan a knyht wi&thorn; outen drede</L>
<L>Sche &thorn;onke him vppon hire knees al bare</L>
<L>And home vnto hire housebonde is sche fare</L>
<L>And told him all &yogh;e haue herde me seide</L>
<L N="1548">And be &yogh;e seker he was so wele apaide</L>
<L>&thorn;at it were impossible to write</L>
<L>What schold .I. longer of &thorn;is cas endite</L>
<L>Arueragus and Dorigene his wif</L>
<L N="1552">In seuereigne blisse leden for&thorn;e here lyfe</L>
<L>Neuer eft ne was &thorn;ere anger hem be-twene</L>
<L>He chirise&thorn; hire as &thorn;ouhe sche where a quene</L>
<L N="1555">And sche was to him treue for euer more</L>
<L N="1557">Aurelius &thorn;at his cost ha&thorn;e Al forlore</L>
<L N="1558">Curse&thorn; &thorn;e time &thorn;at euer he was borne</L>
<L>For certes he sei&thorn; .I. am for-lorne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spurious]</NOTE></L>
<L>Alas quod he alas &thorn;at I be-hiht</L>
<L N="1560">O pured gold .a. &thorn;ousand pou[n]de of wyht
<PB REF="00000403.tif" N="375"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="524"></L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;is Philofre howe schal .I. do</L>
<L>.I. se no more bot &thorn;at .I. am for-do</L>
<L>Myne heritage most .I. nedes sell</L>
<L N="1564">And buen a begger here may .I. no longer dwell</L>
<L>And schamen al &thorn;is kinrede in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Bot .I. of him maie gette &thorn;e better grace</L>
<L>[But netheles I wolle of him assay</L>
<L>At Certeyne yeeris and dayes to pay<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 7333 folio" N="86a:2"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[ <I>Also in Reg.</I> 17 <I>D</I> 15, <I>leaf</I> 190, <I>and Harl.</I> 1758, <I>leaf</I> 136. <I>Not in Sloane</I> 1686, <I>leaf</I> 206, <I>back.</I>]</NOTE>]</L>
<L>.I. wil &thorn;onke him of his grete curtesie</L>
<L>Myne trou&thorn;e wil .I. kepe .I. wil nouht lye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hert sore he go&thorn;e vnto his cofre</L>
<L N="1572">And brouht golde vnto his philosofre</L>
<L>The valewe of .vj.<SUP>C</SUP> pounde .I. gesse</L>
<L>And him beseche&thorn; of his gentillesse</L>
<L>To graunt him daies of &thorn;e remenant<MILESTONE N="151b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1576">And maistere .I. dare wele make auaunt</L>
<L>.I. failed neuer my trou&thorn;e as &yogh;ite</L>
<L>For sekurly my dettes schal .I. quyte</L>
<L>To-warde &yogh;owe howe euer &thorn;at .I. fare</L>
<L N="1580">To gone abigged in my kirtel bare</L>
<L>Bot wold &yogh;e vouche sauf vpon suyrte</L>
<L>Two &yogh;ere o&thorn;er &thorn;re te respite me</L>
<L>Then ware .I. wele for elles most. I sell</L>
<L N="1584">Myne heritage &thorn;er nys no more to tell</L>
<L>Thi[s] philosophre soburly ansewerd</L>
<L>And seid &thorn;us whan he &thorn;es wordes herde</L>
<L>Haue .I. nouht holden couenant vnto &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1588">&yogh;is certes wele and treuly quod he</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou not had &thorn;i lady as &thorn;e lyke&thorn;</L>
<L>No no quod he and sorwfully he sike&thorn;</L>
<L>Whatt was &thorn;e cause tel me if &thorn;ou can</L>
<L N="1592">Aurelius his tale a-none be-gan</L>
<L>And tolde him al as &yogh;e han herde be-fore</L>
<L>It nede&thorn; nouht to rehersen no more</L>
<L>[He seide Arneragus/ of gentilnesse.<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 1758 folio" N="136b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[ <I>Also in Harl.</I> 7333, <I>lf</I> 86, <I>back, col.</I> 1,<I>and Reg.</I> 17 <I>D</I> 15, <I>leaf</I> 136, <I>back.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Had leuyr/ dye in sorow &amp; distresse.
<PB REF="00000404.tif" N="376"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="525"></L>
<L>Than his/ wif were of hir/ trouthe fals/.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Harl. 1758. <I>Not in Sloane</I> 1686, <I>leaf</I> 207.</NOTE></L>
<L>The sorow of Dorigen he tolde hym als/.</L>
<L>How loth hir/ was/ to ben a wickid wif.</L>
<L N="1600">And that sche leuyr/ had that day lost hir/ lif.</L>
<L>And that hir/ trouthe sche swore thorogh ynnocence.</L>
<L>Sche neuyr/ erst/ herd speke of apparence<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. <I>extr. ends</I>]</NOTE>]</L>
<L N="1604">And riht as frely as he sent hire to me</L>
<L N="1603">&thorn;at maad me haue of hire so grete pite</L>
<L>As frely sent .I. hire to hime a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>This is al and somme &thorn;ere nys no more to seine</L>
<L>This philofre Ansewerde leue bro&thorn;ere</L>
<L N="1608">Euer-iche of &yogh;owe ded gentlyche to o&thorn;ere</L>
<L>&thorn;ou ert a swyere and he is a knyht</L>
<L>Bot god for-bede for his blisful myht</L>
<L>Bot if a clerke cou&thorn;e do as gentil a dede</L>
<L N="1612">As wele as any of &yogh;owe it is no drede</L>
<L>Sire .I. reles &thorn;e &thorn;i &thorn;ousand pounde</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou riht nowe were crepe out of &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>Ne neuere or nowe ne haddest knowe me</L>
<L N="1616">For sir .I. wil nou&yogh;t take a peny of &thorn;e</L>
<L>For al my craft ne nou&yogh;t for my trauaile</L>
<L>&thorn;ou haste y-paiede wele for my vitaile</L>
<L>It is ynowhe and fare wele and haue good daie</L>
<L N="1620">He toke his hors and for&thorn;e he go&thorn;e his waie</L>
<L>//Lordinges &thorn;is question &thorn;an wald .I. ax nowe</L>
<L>Whyche was &thorn;e most fre as &thorn;enke&thorn; &yogh;owe</L>
<L>Nowe telle&thorn; me or &thorn;at .I. for&thorn;e wende</L>
<L N="1624">.I. can no more my tale is att an ende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>Explicit Liber /</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<MILESTONE N="152a" UNIT="folio">
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="G" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000405.tif" N="377">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="527">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>G.</B> FRAGMENT VIII.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> THE SECOND NUN'S TALE. LANSDOWNE MS. [THE PROEM.]<NOTE PLACE="head">[No breaks between the stanzas in the MS.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEAD>Incipit prologus .2<SUP>e</SUP>. Monyalys <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="152"></HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">THe Ministre of &thorn;e Norice vn-to vices</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at men clepen in englisshe ydelnesse</L>
<L>The porter of &thorn;e gate is of delices</L>
<L N="4">To eschiewe. And bu hir contrarie hire oppresse</L>
<L>That is to seine be leful besinesse</L>
<L>Wele ouhte we to done oure entent</L>
<L N="7">Lest &thorn;at &thorn;e fende &thorn;oruhe .Idelnesse vs schent</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">&para; For he &thorn;at wi&thorn; his &thorn;ousand cordes sly&yogh;e</L>
<L>Contenuely vs wayte&thorn; to be-clappe</L>
<L>Whan he maie man in Idelnesse aspi&yogh;e</L>
<L N="11">He can so lihtly cache him in his trappe</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at a man be hente riht be &thorn;e lappe</L>
<L>He is not waree &thorn;e fende ha&thorn;e him in honde</L>
<L N="14">Wele ouhte vs werche and ydelnesse wi&thorn; stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">&para; And &thorn;ouhe men dradden neuer for to deye</L>
<L>&YOGH;it seen men wele be reson douteles</L>
<L>&thorn;at ydelnesse is rotin slogardye</L>
<L N="18">Of &thorn;ere come&thorn; neuere none encrese</L>
<L>And se&thorn;ens &thorn;at slou&thorn;e hir halde&thorn; in a lese</L>
<L>Onely to slepe and for to ete and drinke</L>
<L N="21">And to deuowren al &thorn;at o&thorn;er swynke
<PB REF="00000406.tif" N="378"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="528"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">&para; And for to putt vs fro suche Idelnesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at cause is of &thorn;e grete confusione</L>
<L>.I. haue here done my fei&thorn;eful besinesse</L>
<L N="25">After &thorn;e legent in translacione</L>
<L>Riht of &thorn;e glorious lif and passione</L>
<L>&thorn;ou with &thorn;i garlonde wrouht wi&thorn; rosus and lylie</L>
<L N="28">The mene .I. a maide and Martire seint Cecile</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">&para; And &thorn;ou &thorn;at floure of virgines art al</L>
<L>Of whome &thorn;at Bernarde lust so wele to write</L>
<L>To &thorn;e att my begynynge first .I. call</L>
<L N="32">&thorn;ou comfort of vs wreches do me endite</L>
<L>&thorn;i maydens de&thorn; &thorn;at was &thorn;oruhe hir merite</L>
<L>&thorn;e eternale lif and of &thorn;e fende victorie</L>
<L N="35">As men maie after reden in hir storie</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">&para; Thou maiden and moder douhte of &thorn;i sonne</L>
<L>Thou well of Mercy sinful soules cure</L>
<L>In whome &thorn;at god for bounte chees to wonne</L>
<L N="39">&thorn;ou humble and hihe ouer euery creature</L>
<L>&thorn;at no desdeyne &thorn;e Maker had of kinde</L>
<L>&thorn;ou noblest so fere oure nature</L>
<L>His sonne in blode and flessche to clo&thorn;e and winde<MILESTONE N="152b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">&para; Wi&thorn;-inne &thorn;e cloister blisful of &thorn;i sides</L>
<L>Toke mannes schap eterne loue and pees</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;e trine compas lorde and gide es</L>
<L N="46">Whome heuen and see and er&thorn;e out reles</L>
<L>Ay herien. and &thorn;ou virgine wemles</L>
<L>Bare of &thorn;ine body and dueldist maide pure</L>
<L N="49">The creatore of euery creature
<PB REF="00000407.tif" N="379"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="529"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="50">&para; Assembled is in &thorn;e magnificence</L>
<L>With mercy goodnesse and wi&thorn; suche pite</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou ert &thorn;e sonne of excellence</L>
<L N="53">Nouht only helpest hem &thorn;at preyen &thorn;e</L>
<L>But oft time of &thorn;i benignite</L>
<L>Ful frely er &thorn;at men &thorn;in helpe beseche</L>
<L N="56">&thorn;ou gost be-forne and ert her lyues leche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="57">&para; Nowe help &thorn;ou meke and blisful faire maid</L>
<L>Me flemed wriche in &thorn;is desert of gal</L>
<L>&thorn;enke on &thorn;e womman Canan &thorn;at seide</L>
<L N="60">&thorn;at whelpes eten somme of &thorn;e crommes al</L>
<L>&thorn;at from her lordes table buen yfal&middot;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ouhe &thorn;at .I. &thorn;e vnwor&thorn;e douhter of Eue</L>
<L N="63">Be synful &yogh;it accept my be-leue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="64">&para; And for &thorn;at fei&thorn; is dede wi&thorn;outen werkes</L>
<L>So for to worchene &yogh;eue me witte and space</L>
<L>&thorn;at .I. be qwyte frome &thorn;e place &thorn;at most derke is</L>
<L N="67">O &thorn;ou &thorn;at art so faire and so ful of grace</L>
<L>Be myne aduocate in so hihe a place</L>
<L>There as wi&thorn; outen eende is songe Osanna</L>
<L N="70">Thou cristes moder and douhter of Anna</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="71">&para; And of &thorn;ine lyht &thorn;ou graunt my self haue parte</L>
<L>&thorn;at triblide is be &thorn;e cogitacione</L>
<L>[Of my body / and also by &thorn;e weyght</L>
<L N="74">Of erthely lust and fals effeccion<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 7333 folio" N="86b:2">]</L>
<L>O heuen o refute o saluacione</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at buen in sorwe and destresse</L>
<L N="77">Nowe helpe for vnto my werke .I. wil me redresse
<PB REF="00000408.tif" N="380"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="530"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="78">&para; &YOGH;et praie .I. &yogh;owe &thorn;at reden &thorn;at .I. write</L>
<L>For-&yogh;eue&thorn; me &thorn;at .I. do no diligence</L>
<L>&thorn;is ilke storie subtely to endyte</L>
<L N="81">For bo&thorn;e haue .I. &thorn;e wordes and &thorn;e sentence</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at att &thorn;e seintes reuerence</L>
<L>&thorn;e stori wrote and folowen here legende</L>
<L N="84">And praien &yogh;owe &thorn;at &yogh;e woll my werk amende</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13) [THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<L N="85">&para; ffirste will .I. &yogh;owe &thorn;e name of sein Cecile</L>
<L>Expounde as men maie in here stories see<MILESTONE N="153a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>It is to seyen on Englisshe heuenes lylye</L>
<L N="88">For pure chastenesse of virginitee</L>
<L>O&thorn;er for sche witnesse hadde of honeste</L>
<L>Of grene of conscience and of good fame</L>
<L N="91">The swete sauoure lylye was hir name</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="92">O&thorn;ere Cecely. is to seie &thorn;e waie to blinde</L>
<L>For sche ensample was be gode techeinge</L>
<L>Or elles Cicily is as .I. writen fynde</L>
<L N="95">Is Ioyned be a maner conioyneinge</L>
<L>Of heuen and lya. and hire in fygureinge</L>
<L>&thorn;e heuen is sette for &thorn;ouht of holynesse</L>
<L N="98">And lya for hire lasteinge besinesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="99">Cecile eke mai be seide in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Wanteynge of blindenesse for hire grete liht</L>
<L>Of Sapiens and for hire &thorn;ewes clere</L>
<L N="102">Or elles lo &thorn;is maydens name briht</L>
<L>[Off heuen and leos commyth ffor which bi riht<MILESTONE UNIT="Addit. 5140 folio" N="285a">]</L>
<L>Men myht &thorn;e heuen of &thorn;e peple hir call</L>
<L N="105">Ensample of goode and wise werkes all
<PB REF="00000409.tif" N="381"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="531"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="106">For leos peple in ynglissle is to seie</L>
<L>And riht as men may in &thorn;is heuen see</L>
<L>The sonne and mone and &thorn;e sterres euery weye</L>
<L N="109">Riht so gostly in &thorn;is mayden fre</L>
<L>Seyen &thorn;e fai&thorn;e of Manificence</L>
<L>And eke of hel&thorn;e and of sapiens</L>
<L N="112">And sondre werkes briht of excellence</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="113">An[d] riht as &thorn;es philosofers write</L>
<L>&thorn;at heuen is swift rounde and berneinge</L>
<L>Riht so was faire Cecile &thorn;e white</L>
<L N="116">Ful sweft and besi euer in good workinge</L>
<L>And rounde and hole in goode perseueringe</L>
<L>And bernede euer in charite liht</L>
<L N="119">Nowe haue .I. declared &yogh;ow what sche hiht</L>
<TRAILER><B>Explicit</B> Prologus</TRAILER>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD> <B>Incipit fabula.</B></HEAD>
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L N="120">This maiden hiht Cecile as hire lif sei&thorn;e</L>
<L>Was comen of Romeyns and of noble kinde</L>
<L>And so for&thorn;e fostred vp in &thorn;e fei&thorn;e</L>
<L N="123">Of Crist and bare his gospell in hir mynde</L>
<L>Sche neuer cesede as .I. wreten finde</L>
<L>Of hire praier and god to loue and drede</L>
<L N="126">Besecheinge him to kepe hire Maidenhede</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="127">And whan &thorn;is maiden scholde vnto a man</L>
<L>Iwedded be &thorn;at was ful &yogh;onge of Age<MILESTONE N="153b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at ycleped was Waleriane</L>
<L N="130">And &thorn;e daie was commen of his Mariage</L>
<L>Sche fel deuoute and homble in hire Corage</L>
<L>Vnder hire robe of golde &thorn;at satte ful faire</L>
<L N="133">And next hire flesche yclad hire in an haire
<PB REF="00000410.tif" N="382"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="532"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L N="134">&para; And while &thorn;e orgen<SUP>s</SUP> maden melodie</L>
<L>To god alone &thorn;us in hert songe sche</L>
<L>O lorde my soule and eke my bode gie</L>
<L N="137">Vnwemed lest &thorn;at .I. confounded be</L>
<L>And for his loue &thorn;at deied vpon a tree</L>
<L>Euery secunde or &thorn;e &thorn;red daie sche fast</L>
<L N="140">Aie biddi[n]ge in hir orisons ful fast</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="141">&para; The nyht came and to bed sche most gone</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire husbond as often is &thorn;e manere</L>
<L>And priuely sche seide anone</L>
<L N="144">O swete and wel be-loued spouse dere</L>
<L>&thorn;er is a counsel and &yogh;e wold it here</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at riht feine .I. wil vnto seine</L>
<L N="147">So &thorn;at &yogh;e me assured it nou&yogh;t to be-wreine</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L N="148">&para; Valerian gan fast vn to hir swere</L>
<L>&thorn;at for no caas ne &thorn;inge &thorn;at miht be</L>
<L>He scholde for no&thorn;inge neuere be-wrien hire</L>
<L N="151">And &thorn;ann att erst vnto him &thorn;us seid sche</L>
<L>.I. haue an Angel whiche &thorn;at loue&thorn; me</L>
<L>&thorn;at wi&thorn; grete loue whe&thorn;er so y wake or slepe</L>
<L N="154">Is rede ay my bode for to kepe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L N="155">// And &yogh;if &thorn;at he may felen oute of drede</L>
<L>[That ye me touche or love in vilonye</L>
<L>He ry&yogh;t a-non wol slee you with &thorn;e dede</L>
<L N="158">And in your thought &thorn;us schulle ye dye</L>
<L>And yf ye me in clennes gy<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 7333 folio" N="87a:2">]</L>
<L>He wolde &yogh;owe loue as me for &yogh;oure clennesse</L>
<L N="161">And schewen &yogh;owe of his ioye and his brihtnesse
<PB REF="00000411.tif" N="383"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="533"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="162">&para; Valerian correctid as god wolde</L>
<L>Ansewerd a&yogh;eine if .I. schal truste to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Latt me &thorn;at Angel see and him be-holde</L>
<L N="165">And if &thorn;at it a verraie Angel be</L>
<L>&thorn;an wil .I. done as &thorn;ou hast preide me</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou loue a no&thorn;ere man for so&thorn;e</L>
<L N="168">Riht wi&thorn; &thorn;is swerde .I. wil sle &yogh;owe bo&thorn;e</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="169">&para; Cecile ansewerd anone in &thorn;is wis</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &yogh;owe lust &thorn;at Angel schal &yogh;e see</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &yogh;e trowe on criste and &yogh;owe baptize</L>
<L N="172">Go&thorn;e for&thorn;e to via apia quod sche</L>
<L>That frome &thorn;is toune ne stant bot miles &thorn;ree</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pouer folkes &thorn;at &thorn;ere duelle<MILESTONE N="154a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="175">Sei hem riht &thorn;us as &thorn;at .I. schal &yogh;owe telle</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="176">&para; Tel hem. &thorn;at .I. Cecile &yogh;owe to hem sent</L>
<L>To schewen &yogh;owe &thorn;e good vrbane &thorn;e oolde</L>
<L>For secre nedes and for good entent</L>
<L N="179">And whan &thorn;at &yogh;e seint vrban haue be-holde</L>
<L>Tel him &thorn;e wordes whiche &thorn;at .I. &yogh;owe tolde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he ha&thorn; purged &yogh;owe fro sinne</L>
<L N="182">Than schal &yogh;e se &thorn;at angel ar &yogh;e twinne</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="183">&para; Valerian is to &thorn;at place y-goon</L>
<L>And riht as him was tauht be his lerenynge</L>
<L>He fonde &thorn;is holy Vrban anone</L>
<L N="186">Amonge &thorn;e seintes buriels lotiynge.<NOTE PLACE="inter">.i. latitans</NOTE></L>
<L>And he anone wi&thorn;-outen tariynge</L>
<L>Did his Message and whan &thorn;at he hadde tolde</L>
<L N="189">Vrban for Ioye gan his hondes vpholde
<PB REF="00000412.tif" N="384"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="534"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="190">The teres from his yen lete he fall</L>
<L>Almihti god o ihesu Crist quod he</L>
<L>Sewere of Chaste counseil. and herde of vs all</L>
<L N="193">The fruyte of &thorn;ilke seed of chastite</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou hast sowe in Cecile take to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Loo ylike abuse bee wi&thorn; oute gile</L>
<L N="196">&thorn;e serue&thorn; aye &thorn;in owen &thorn;ral Cecile</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L N="197">&para; For &thorn;ilke spouse &thorn;at sche toke bot nowe</L>
<L>Ful like a fers lyon sche sende&thorn; here</L>
<L>As meeke as any lombe was to &yogh;owe</L>
<L N="200">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde anone &thorn;er gan apere</L>
<L>And old man clad wi&thorn; white clo&thorn;es clere</L>
<L>And had a booke wi&thorn; lettres of gold in honde</L>
<L N="203">And gan beforne Valerian stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L N="204">&para; Valerian as dede fel doune for drede</L>
<L>When he him saughe and him vp hent &thorn;oo</L>
<L>And on his booke riht &thorn;us he gan to rede</L>
<L N="207">O lorde .o. fei&thorn;e .o. god wi&thorn; owten mo</L>
<L>Of Cristendome and fader of all also</L>
<L>Aboue all and ouer al euery where</L>
<L N="210">&thorn;is wordes al wi&thorn; golde wreten were</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L N="211">&para; Whan &thorn;is was radde &thorn;an seide &thorn;is olde man</L>
<L>Leuest &thorn;ou &thorn;is &thorn;inge or no sey &yogh;e or naye</L>
<L>.I. leue al &thorn;is &thorn;inge; [quod valerian</L>
<L N="214">ffor sother thing<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 7333 folio" N="87b:1">] &thorn;an &thorn;is .I. dare wele saye</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e heuen no whiht ne &thorn;enke maye</L>
<L>Tho vanysched &thorn;e olde man he nyste wher</L>
<L>An pope Vrbane him cristene riht &thorn;ere<MILESTONE N="154b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000413.tif" N="385"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="535"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L N="218">Valerian go&thorn;e home and sein Cecile</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn;-inne his chambur he sauhe an Aungel stande</L>
<L>&thorn;is Aungel hadde of Roses and of lyle</L>
<L N="221">Corons tuo whiche he bare in hande</L>
<L>And first to Cecile as .I. vnderstande</L>
<L>He &yogh;af &thorn;at one and after gan he take</L>
<L N="224">&thorn;e tother to Valerian hire make</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L N="225">&para; Wi&thorn; body clene and vnwemmed &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>Kepe ay wele &thorn;is Corounes quod he</L>
<L>Frome paradise to &yogh;owe haue .I. hem brouht</L>
<L N="228">Ne neuer more scholl &thorn;ei roten be</L>
<L>Ne lese her swete sauore truste&thorn; me</L>
<L>Ne neuer whight schal seen hem wi&thorn; his ey&yogh;e</L>
<L N="231">Bot he be chaste and hate velanye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L N="232">&para; And &thorn;ou walerian for &thorn;ou sone</L>
<L>Assentest to good counsel alsoo</L>
<L>Sey what &thorn;e lust and &thorn;ou schalt haue &thorn;i bone</L>
<L N="235">.I. haue a bro&thorn;er quod valerian &thorn;oo</L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;is werd .I. loue no man soo</L>
<L>.I. praie &yogh;owe &thorn;at my bro&thorn;er maie haue grace</L>
<L N="238">To knowe &thorn;e trou&thorn;e as .I. do in &thorn;is place</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L N="239">&para; The Angel ansewarde god lyke&thorn; &yogh;oure request</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e wi&thorn; &thorn;e pame of Marterdome</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schol com vnto &thorn;e blisful feste</L>
<L N="242">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde Tiburce his bro&thorn;er come</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he sauoure vnder nome</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e roses and &thorn;e lyles Caste</L>
<L N="245">Wi&thorn; inne his herte he gan to wonder fast
<PB REF="00000414.tif" N="386"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="536"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L N="246">&para; And seide in &thorn;is time .I. wonder of &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Whens &thorn;is suote sauour come&thorn; so</L>
<L>And Roses and lilys it .I. smell here</L>
<L N="249">For &thorn;ouhe .I. had hem in myn hondes tuo</L>
<L>The sauoure in me myht no depper go</L>
<L>The swete smel it in myne here .I. finde</L>
<L N="252">Ha&thorn;e chaunged me al in ano&thorn;er kinde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L N="253">&para; Valerian seide tuo corounes haue we</L>
<L>Snowe white and rose rede &thorn;at schyne&thorn; clere</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ine yen haue no myht to se</L>
<L N="256">And as &thorn;ou smellest hem &thorn;oruhe my preiere</L>
<L>So schalt &thorn;ou seen leue bro&thorn;er dere</L>
<L>If it so be &thorn;at wolte wi&thorn; oute slou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="259">Beleue a riht and knowe verrei trou&thorn;e<MILESTONE N="155a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L N="260">Tiburce answerd saist &thorn;ou &thorn;us to me</L>
<L>In so&thorn;enesse or in dremes herken &yogh;e &thorn;is</L>
<L>In dreme quod Valerian han we bue</L>
<L N="263">Vnto &thorn;is time myn bro&thorn;er ywisse</L>
<L>Bot nowe att erst oure trou&thorn;e dwellyngis</L>
<L>How woost &thorn;ou quod Tiburs and in what wise</L>
<L N="266">Quod Valerian &thorn;at .I. schal deuise</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L N="267">&para; The Aungel of god ha&thorn;e me trew&thorn; ytauht</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt seen if &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolte reneye</L>
<L>&thorn;e ydoles and be clene and elles nouht</L>
<L N="270">And of &thorn;e miracles of &thorn;es corounes tueye</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose in his preface lust to seie</L>
<L>Solempnely &thorn;is noble doctor dere</L>
<L N="273">Commende&thorn; it and sei&thorn; in &thorn;is manere
<PB REF="00000415.tif" N="387"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="537"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L N="274">&para; The palme of marterdome for to receyue</L>
<L>Sein Cecile fulfild of goddes &yogh;ift</L>
<L>&thorn;e werlde and eke here Chambre . gan sche weyue</L>
<L N="277">Wittnesse Tiburce and Cecilez schrift</L>
<L>To whiche god of his bounte wolde schift</L>
<L>Corounes tuo of floures wele smellynge</L>
<L N="280">And maade &thorn;e Angel hem &thorn;e Corounes bringe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L N="281">&para; The maide ha&thorn; brouhte &thorn;es men to blisse a-boue</L>
<L>The werlde ha&thorn; wiste what it was wor&thorn;e certeyne</L>
<L>Deuocione of chastite to loue</L>
<L N="284">Tho schewde him open and pleine</L>
<L>&thorn;at al ydoles nys but &thorn;inge in veine</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei bu domme and &thorn;erto &thorn;ei bue def</L>
<L N="287">And charged him his ydoles for to lef</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L N="288">&para; Who &thorn;at &thorn;is troue&thorn; nouht a beste he is</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;o Tyburce if &thorn;at .I. schal nouht lye</L>
<L>Sche gan &thorn;an kisse his breste and &thorn;at herd &thorn;is</L>
<L N="291">And was ful glad he cou&thorn;e trouthe aspye</L>
<L>&thorn;is daie .I. take &thorn;e for myne a-lye</L>
<L>Seide &thorn;is blisful maide faire and dere</L>
<L N="294">For affter &thorn;at sche seide as &yogh;e maye here</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L N="295">&para; Lo. Riht so as &thorn;e loue of crist quod sche</L>
<L>Maad me &thorn;i bro&thorn;ers wif riht in &thorn;at wyse</L>
<L>Anone for myne Allye here take .I. &thorn;e</L>
<L N="298">Se&thorn;ens &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolde &thorn;in ydoles despise</L>
<L>Go wi&thorn; &thorn;i bro&thorn;er nowe and &thorn;e baptize</L>
<L>And maake &thorn;e clene so &thorn;at &thorn;ou maiste beholde</L>
<L>The aungels face of whiche &thorn;i bro&thorn;er tolde<MILESTONE N="155b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000416.tif" N="388"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="538"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L N="302">Tiburce ansewarde and seide bro&thorn;er dere</L>
<L>&para; First tel me wheder .I. schal and to what man</L>
<L>To whome quod he come for&thorn;e wi&thorn; riht good chier</L>
<L N="305">.I. will &thorn;e leede vn to &thorn;e pope vrban</L>
<L>To vrban bro&thorn;er myne valerian</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;o Tiburce wil &thorn;ou me &thorn;eder lede</L>
<L N="308">Me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at it were a wonder dede</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L N="309">&para; Remenest &thorn;ou nouht vrban quod he &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;at is so of dampned to be dede</L>
<L>And wonne&thorn; in halkes to and fro</L>
<L N="312">And dare nouhte ones put for&thorn;e his heede</L>
<L>Men wolde him berne in a fire so rede</L>
<L>If &thorn;at he were founde and men miht him aspye</L>
<L N="315">And we also &thorn;at bere him companye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<L N="316">&para; And whiles we seken &thorn;ilke diuinitee</L>
<L>&thorn;at is hidde in heuen priuey</L>
<L>Algate y-brent in &thorn;is werld shol we be</L>
<L N="319">To whome Cecily anseward boldely</L>
<L>Men myht drede wele and skilfully</L>
<L>&thorn;is lyf to lese myne owen dere bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="322">If &thorn;is were leueynge only and none o&thorn;ere</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L N="323">&para; Bot &thorn;ere is better lif in o&thorn;er place</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer schal be lost ne drede &thorn;e nouht</L>
<L>Whiche godes sonne vs tolde &thorn;orwhe his grace</L>
<L>[&thorn;at fadres son hathe al &thorn;ing wrou&yogh;t<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 7333 folio" N="88a:1"></L>
<L>And all &thorn;at wrovte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[rov <I>corrected</I>]</NOTE> is with a skylfull &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;e gost that from the fadir gan procede</L>
<L N="329">He souled him with-oute eny drede
<PB REF="00000417.tif" N="389"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="539"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L N="330">By worde &amp; by myracle by goddes son<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. 7333]</NOTE></L>
<L>When he was in this worlde declared her</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er was o&thorn;er lyf &thorn;er men may wene</L>
<L N="333">To whom aunswerd tyburce o systur der</L>
<L>Ne sedest thow ryght now in &thorn;is maner</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas but O. lord god in sothefastnes</L>
<L N="336">And now of thre how maist &thorn;ou bere wytnes</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L>&thorn;at schall I tel quod sche or I goo<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. 7333 <I>extract ends</I>]</NOTE>]</L>
<L>Riht as a man ha&thorn; sapiens &thorn;re</L>
<L>Memorie engyne. and intellect also</L>
<L N="340">Soo moo beynge of diuinite</L>
<L>&thorn;re persones riht wel &thorn;ere maie bee</L>
<L>&para; Tho gan sche him busily preche</L>
<L N="343">Of cristes come and of his peynes teche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L N="344">And mony poyntes of his passione</L>
<L>How goddes son in &thorn;is werld was holde</L>
<L>To do mankinde pleine remissione</L>
<L N="347">&thorn;at was ybonde in sinne and cares colde</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is &thorn;inge sche vnto tyburce tolde</L>
<L>&para; And affter &thorn;is tiburce in good entent</L>
<L N="350">To pope vrban wi&thorn; valerian he went</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L N="351">Whiche &thorn;onked god and wi&thorn; glad hert and liht</L>
<L>He Cristened him and maade him in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Parfite in his leueynge goddes knyht</L>
<L N="354">And aftur &thorn;is Tiburce gat suche grace</L>
<L>That euery daie he sawe in time and space<MILESTONE N="156a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The aungel of god and euery maner bone</L>
<L N="357">&thorn;at he god axed it was sped ful sone
<PB REF="00000418.tif" N="390"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="540"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L N="358">&para; It were ful harde be order for to seyne</L>
<L>Howe mony wonderes ihesu for him wrouht</L>
<L>Bot att &thorn;e last to tel schort and pleine</L>
<L N="361">The seriant of &thorn;e toune of Rome hem souht</L>
<L>And hem be-forne Almache &thorn;e prouost brouht</L>
<L>Whiche hem opposed and knewe all her entente</L>
<L N="364">And to &thorn;e ymage of Iubiter he hem sente</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<L N="365">&para; And seid who so wil nou&yogh;t sacrifice</L>
<L>Swappe of his hede &thorn;is is my sentence here</L>
<L>Anone &thorn;es marters &thorn;at .I. &yogh;owe of deuise</L>
<L N="368">On Maximius &thorn;at was an officere</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e profectes and of Corniculere</L>
<L>Hem hent and when he for&thorn;e &thorn;e seintes ladde</L>
<L N="371">Him selfe he wope for pite &thorn;at he hadde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<L N="372">&para; And whan maximius hadd herd &thorn;e seintes lore</L>
<L>He gatte hem of &thorn;e tormentours leue</L>
<L>And hadde hem in his house wi&thorn; oute more</L>
<L N="375">And wi&thorn; here precheinge ar &thorn;at it were eue</L>
<L>&thorn;ei g&omacr;n fro &thorn;e tormentours to reue</L>
<L>And frome maximius and frome his folke ichone</L>
<L N="378">&thorn;e fals fei&thorn;e to trowe in god a-lone</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55)</HEAD>
<L N="379">&para; Cecele Came whan it was waxen nyht</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; prestes &thorn;at hem cr&edot;stened al in fere</L>
<L>And afterward whan daie was waxen liht</L>
<L N="382">Cecile hem seide wi&thorn; a sobre chere</L>
<L>Nowe cristes owen knyhtes leue and dere</L>
<L>Cast al awaye &thorn;e werkes of derknesse</L>
<L N="385">And arme&thorn; &yogh;owe in armure of lyhtnesse
<PB REF="00000419.tif" N="391"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="541"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56)</HEAD>
<L N="386">&para; &YOGH;e haue for sothe done grete Bataile</L>
<L>And ha&thorn;e &thorn;e victorie &yogh;oure fei&thorn;e &yogh;e haue confermed</L>
<L>Go to &thorn;e croune of lif &thorn;at maie nouht faile</L>
<L N="389">&THORN;e rihtful Iugge whiche &thorn;at &yogh;e haue serued</L>
<L>Will bringe &yogh;owe to his blisse &thorn;at to &yogh;ow ha&thorn; reserued</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is &thorn;inge was seide as .I. devise</L>
<L N="392">Men led hem for&thorn;e to done &thorn;e sacrifise</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57)</HEAD>
<L N="393">&para; Bot whan &thorn;ei were vn-to &thorn;e place ybrouht</L>
<L>To tell schortly &thorn;e conclusioune</L>
<L>Thei nolde encense no sacrifise riht nouht</L>
<L N="396">Bot on her knees &thorn;ei satten hem a doune</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; humble hert and sadde deuocion<MILESTONE N="156b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And losten bo&thorn;e her hedes in &thorn;e place</L>
<L N="399">Here soules went to &thorn;e kenge of grace</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58)</HEAD>
<L N="400">&para; This Maxinius &thorn;at sawe &thorn;is &thorn;inge be-tide</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; pitous tales tolde it a-none riht</L>
<L>&THORN;at he her soules sawhe to heuen glide</L>
<L N="403">Wi&thorn; algels ful of clerenesse and of liht</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his worde conuerted mony a wyht</L>
<L>For whiche almachius dide him so to-bete</L>
<L N="406">Wi&thorn; whippe of leede to he his lif gan lete</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59)</HEAD>
<L N="407">Cecilie him toke and beried him anone</L>
<L>Be tiburce and valeriane softly</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; inne hire heriynge place vnder a stone</L>
<L N="410">And after &thorn;is Almachius hastely.</L>
<L>Badde his Ministres ffecchen openly</L>
<L>Cecile so sche myht in his presence</L>
<L N="413">Do sacrifice and Iubite encense
<PB REF="00000420.tif" N="392"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="542"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60)</HEAD>
<L N="414">&para; Bot &thorn;ei conuerted &thorn;orwhe here wise lore</L>
<L>Wepten sore and &yogh;af credence</L>
<L>Vnto her worde and cryden more and more</L>
<L N="417">Crist god son with outen difference</L>
<L>Is verrey god. &thorn;is is al oure sentence</L>
<L>&thorn;at ha&thorn;e so good a seruant him to serue</L>
<L N="420">&thorn;us wi&thorn; o voice; we trowe &thorn;ei we sterue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61)</HEAD>
<L N="421">Almachius &thorn;at herd al &thorn;is</L>
<L>Bad fecche Cecile &thorn;at he miht hir see</L>
<L>And al&thorn;er ferst lo &thorn;is was his askeinge</L>
<L N="424">What maner womman ert &thorn;ou &thorn;o quod he</L>
<L>.I. am gentill womman borne quod sche</L>
<L>.I. ax quod he &thorn;ouhe it &thorn;e greue</L>
<L N="427">Of &thorn;i religion and of &thorn;i be-leue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62)</HEAD>
<L N="428">Whi &thorn;an be-gan &yogh;oure questione folilye</L>
<L>quod sche &thorn;at woldest &thorn;ou ansewere conclude</L>
<L>In o demande &yogh;e axed lewdly</L>
<L N="431">Almachius anseward to &thorn;at similitude</L>
<L>[Of whens comthe thin Answer so rude<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 7333 folio" N="88b">]</L>
<L>Of whense quod sche when &thorn;at sche was refreynede</L>
<L N="434">Of concience and of good fei&thorn;e vnfeynede</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63)</HEAD>
<L N="435">Almachius seide takest &thorn;ou none hede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;in Ansewere and sche him ansewerd &thorn;us</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure myhte quod sche litel is to drede</L>
<L N="438">For euery mo[r]tel manesse power ne is</L>
<L>Bot y-lyke a bledder ful of wynde y-wis</L>
<L>For wi&thorn; a nedeles point whan &thorn;at is blowe<MILESTONE N="157a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="441">Maie al &thorn;e bost of it be leid ful lowe
<PB REF="00000421.tif" N="393"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="543"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64)</HEAD>
<L N="442">&para; Ful wrongefully began &thorn;ou quod he</L>
<L>And &yogh;ut in wronge is &thorn;i perseuerance</L>
<L>Woste &thorn;ou nouht howe owre mihti princes fre</L>
<L N="445">Bene &thorn;us commanded and maken ordinance</L>
<L>&thorn;at euery cristen whight scha[l] haue penance</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;at he his cristendome wi&thorn; seie</L>
<L N="448">And gone al quyte if he wil it renaye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(65)</HEAD>
<L N="449">&para; &YOGH;oure Princes erren as &yogh;oure noblen do&thorn;e</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;o Cecile and a woode sentence</L>
<L>&yogh;e maake us gilti and it is nouht so&thorn;e</L>
<L N="452">Fore &thorn;at knowen wele oure Innocence</L>
<L>For as muche as we done a reuerence</L>
<L>To criste; and for we bere a cristen name</L>
<L N="455">&yogh;e put on vs a crime and eke a blame</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(66)</HEAD>
<L N="456">&para; Bot we &thorn;at knowen &thorn;elk name so</L>
<L>For vertuous we maie it nou&yogh;t seie</L>
<L>Almachie seide chese one of &thorn;es tuo</L>
<L N="459">Do sacrifice or cristendom reneye</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou mowe skapen be &thorn;at weie</L>
<L>Att whiche &thorn;e holy blisful maide</L>
<L N="462">Gan for to lauhe and to &thorn;e Iuge sche saide</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(67)</HEAD>
<L N="463">&para; O Iuge confuse in &thorn;i nycete</L>
<L>Wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;at .I. reney Innocence</L>
<L>To maken me a wikked wyht quod sche</L>
<L N="466">Lo he dissimule&thorn; here in audience</L>
<L>He stare&thorn; and wode&thorn; in his aduertence</L>
<L>To whome Almachius seide o vncely wrecche</L>
<L N="469">Ne wost &thorn;ou not houe fer my miht mai streche
<PB REF="00000422.tif" N="394"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="544"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(68)</HEAD>
<L N="470">&para; Ha&thorn;e nouht oure myhte prince to me y&yogh;ouen</L>
<L>&yogh;e bothe power and auctorite</L>
<L>To make folke to dey&yogh;en or to leuen.</L>
<L N="473">Whi spekest &thorn;ou so proudely &thorn;an to me</L>
<L>.I. speke it nou&yogh;t bot stedfastly quod sche</L>
<L>Nouht proudly for .I. saie as for my side</L>
<L N="476">.I. hate dedely &thorn;ilke vice of pride</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(69)</HEAD>
<L N="477">&para; And &yogh;if &thorn;ou drede nouht a so&thorn;e to here</L>
<L>&thorn;an wil .I. schewen al openly be riht</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou hast maade a ful grete leseinge here</L>
<L N="480">&thorn;ou seist &thorn;i princes haue &yogh;eue &thorn;e myht</L>
<L>Bothe to slene and for to whikke a wiht</L>
<L>Thou &thorn;at ne maist bot onely lif here be-reue<MILESTONE N="157b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="483">Thou na haste &thorn;erto nei&thorn;er pouer ne leue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(70)</HEAD>
<L N="484">Bot &thorn;ou maist seie &thorn;i Princes han &thorn;e maked</L>
<L>Ministre of de&thorn;e; for if &thorn;ou speke of mo</L>
<L>&thorn;ou liest for &thorn;i pouer is ful naked</L>
<L N="487">Do waie &thorn;i boldenes seide Almachius &thorn;o</L>
<L>Or sacrifice to oure goddes or tuo</L>
<L>.I. reche nouht what wronge &thorn;at &thorn;ou me profer</L>
<L N="490">For .I. can suffre it as a philosofer</L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(71)</HEAD>
<L N="491">Bot &thorn;ilke wronges maie .I. not endure</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou spekest of owre goddes here quod he</L>
<L>Cecile ansewerd .o. nice creature</L>
<L N="494">&thorn;ou seidest no word se&thorn;ens &thorn;ou spak to me</L>
<L>&thorn;at .I. ne knewe &thorn;ere wi&thorn; &thorn;i nicete</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou were in euery maner wise</L>
<L N="497">A lewde Officer and a veine Iustise
<PB REF="00000423.tif" N="395"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="545"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(72)</HEAD>
<L N="498">&thorn;ere lakke&thorn; no &thorn;inge to &thorn;ine vtter y&yogh;en</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou nart blinde for &thorn;inge &thorn;at wee seen all</L>
<L>&thorn;at is a stone &thorn;at men wele maie aspyen</L>
<L N="501">&thorn;at ilke stone a god &thorn;ou wol it call</L>
<L>.I. rede &thorn;e latt &thorn;ine honde vpon hit fall</L>
<L>And tast it wele a stone &thorn;ou schalt it finde</L>
<L N="504">Sens &thorn;at &thorn;ou sixt it not wi&thorn; &thorn;ine y&yogh;en blinde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(73)</HEAD>
<L N="505">It is a schame &thorn;at &thorn;e peple schal</L>
<L>Schal scoren &thorn;e and lauhe att &thorn;i folye</L>
<L>For communly wemmen wote it wele ouere al</L>
<L N="508">&thorn;at myhte goddes is in his heuenes hihe</L>
<L>And &thorn;es ymages wele &thorn;an maistowe aspie</L>
<L>To &thorn;e ne to hem self ne maie &thorn;ei profit</L>
<L N="511">For in hire effecte &thorn;ei bue nouht wor&thorn;e a myte</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(74)</HEAD>
<L N="512">&thorn;us and suche o&thorn;ere wordes seide sche</L>
<L>And he wex wro&thorn;e and badde sche scholde be ledde</L>
<L>Home to hire hous and in hir hous quod he</L>
<L N="515">Birne hire riht in a fire wi&thorn; flammes rede</L>
<L>And as he bad riht so was done &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>And in a bathe &thorn;ei gan hir fast schetten</L>
<L N="518">And nyht and daie grete fire vnder &thorn;ei maden</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(75)</HEAD>
<L N="519">Al &thorn;e longe niht and &thorn;e daie also</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e fire and eke &thorn;e ba&thorn;es hete</L>
<L>Sche satt al colde and felt of it no wo</L>
<L N="522">Ne maade hire nou&yogh;t a drope for to swete</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;at ba&thorn;e hir lif sche moste lete.</L>
<L>For he Almachius wi&thorn; ful wekked entent<MILESTONE N="158a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="525">To sleene hir in &thorn;e ba&thorn;e his sonde sent
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="396"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="546"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(76)</HEAD>
<L N="526">&thorn;ree strokes in &thorn;e nekke he smote hir &thorn;o</L>
<L>The tormentour bot for no maner chaunce</L>
<L>He myhte nouhte smyte al here nek y tuo</L>
<L N="529">And for &thorn;ere was &thorn;at time an ordinance</L>
<L>That no man schold do to man suche penance</L>
<L>The fer&thorn;e stroke to smyten soft or sore</L>
<L N="532">&thorn;is tormentour ne dorste no more</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(77)</HEAD>
<L N="533">Bot half dede wi&thorn; hire nek y-coruen &thorn;ere</L>
<L>He left hire lye and in his weie he wente</L>
<L>The cristen folke whiche abowten hire were</L>
<L N="536">Wi&thorn; schetes home ful feire here hente</L>
<L>&thorn;ree daies leued sche in &thorn;is torment</L>
<L>And neuer cesed hem &thorn;e fei&thorn;e to teche</L>
<L N="539">&thorn;at sche had fostred hame sche gan to preche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(78)</HEAD>
<L N="540">And hem sche &yogh;aue here mebles and her &thorn;inge</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Pope vrban be-toke hem &thorn;o</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;us axed &thorn;is of heuen kinge</L>
<L N="543">To haue respite &thorn;rei daies and no mo</L>
<L>To recommande to &yogh;owe er &thorn;at .I. go</L>
<L>&thorn;es sowles loo and &thorn;at .I. miht do wirche</L>
<L N="546">Here of myne house perpetuelly a cherche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(79)</HEAD>
<L N="547">Seint vrban wi&thorn; his dekenes priuelye</L>
<L>The lady fette and beried it be nyht</L>
<L>Amonge his o&thorn;ere seintes honestly</L>
<L N="550">Here house &thorn;e cherche of seinte cecely hiht</L>
<L>Seinte vrban halowed it as he wel myht</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whiche in to &thorn;is daie in noble wise</L>
<L N="553">Men done to criste and to his seintes seruise.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>Explicit vita</B> sancte <B>Cecilie.</B></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000425.tif" N="397">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="547">
<HEAD>Incipit prologus .Canonice.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 158</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan ended was &thorn;e lif of seint Cecile</L>
<L>Er we had reden fulli. fiue myle</L>
<L>Att bouhton vnder &thorn;e ble vs gan a take</L>
<L N="557">A man &thorn;at clo&thorn;ed was in clo&thorn;es blake</L>
<L>And vnder &thorn;at he hadde a white surplis</L>
<L>His Hakenay &thorn;at was al pomel gris</L>
<L>So swete &thorn;at it wonder was to see</L>
<L N="561">It semed he had priked myles &thorn;re</L>
<L>&thorn;e hors eke &thorn;at &yogh;oman rode vpone</L>
<L>So swet &thorn;at vnne&thorn; myht he gone</L>
<L>Aboue &thorn;e paitrel stode &thorn;e fome ful hy&yogh;e</L>
<L N="565">He was of fome al flekked as a pye<MILESTONE N="158b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A male tweyfold on his cropur leye</L>
<L>It semed &thorn;at he Caride litel araye</L>
<L>Al liht for somere rode &thorn;is wor&thorn;e man</L>
<L N="569">And in myn herte wonder .I. be-gan</L>
<L>What &thorn;at he was til &thorn;at .I. vnder-stode</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at his cloke was sewed to his hode</L>
<L>For whiche when .I. longe had auysed me</L>
<L N="573">.I. demed him sum chanon for to be</L>
<L>His hatte honge doune be-hinde his be a lace</L>
<L>For he had ridde more &thorn;an a trote or a pace</L>
<L>It hadde ay priked lyke as he ware wode</L>
<L N="577">A clote lef he had vnder his hode</L>
<L>For suote and for to kepe his hed from hete</L>
<L>Bot it was Ioy for to seen him swete</L>
<L>His fored dropped as a stillatorie</L>
<L N="581">Where ful of pleintein and of peritorie
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="398"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="548"></L>
<L N="582">And whan he come he gan to crye</L>
<L>God saue quod he &thorn;is Iolie companye</L>
<L>Fast haue .I. priked quod he for &yogh;oure sake</L>
<L N="585">Because &thorn;at .I. wold &yogh;owe ouer take</L>
<L>To riden in &thorn;is mery companye</L>
<L>His &yogh;oman eke was ful of curtasie</L>
<L>And sires nowe in morwe tide</L>
<L N="589">Oute of &yogh;oure Ostlery .I. sawe &yogh;owe ride</L>
<L>And warned here my lorde and my souereine</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at to ride wi&thorn;e &yogh;owe is ful feyne</L>
<L>For his disporde he loue&thorn; daliance</L>
<L N="593">Frende for &thorn;i warneyinge god &yogh;eue &thorn;e good chaunce</L>
<L>Seide oure oste sertes it wolde seme</L>
<L>Thi lorde were wise and so .I. maie wele deme</L>
<L>He is ful Iocunde also dar .I. laie</L>
<L N="597">Can he ouht tell a mery tale or tueye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; whiche he glade maie &thorn;is companye</L>
<L>Who sire my lord &yogh;e &yogh;e wi&thorn; oute lye</L>
<L>He kan of mer&thorn;e and eke of Iolyte</L>
<L N="601">Not bot .I.-nowhe also <I>sir</I> treste&thorn; me</L>
<L>And &yogh;e him knewe as wel as do .I.</L>
<L>&yogh;e wold wonder howe wele and &thorn;reftely</L>
<L>He cou&thorn;e werke and &thorn;at in sundre wise</L>
<L N="605">He ha&thorn; tak on him mony sundre aprise</L>
<L>Whiche were ful harde for any &thorn;at is here</L>
<L>To bringe aboute. bot &thorn;ei of him it lere<MILESTONE N="159a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As homely as he ride&thorn; amonges &yogh;owe</L>
<L N="609">If &yogh;e him knewe. it wolde be &yogh;oure prowe</L>
<L>&yogh;e nolde nouht forgone his aqueyntance</L>
<L>For mochel good .I. dare leie in a balance</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at .I. haue in myne <NOTE PLACE="marg">[? <I>for</I> possossione]</NOTE>proossione</L>
<L N="613">He is a man of hihe discrecione</L>
<L>.I. warne &yogh;owe wele he is a passinge man</L>
<L>Wele quod oure oste .I. pray &thorn;e tel me &thorn;an</L>
<L>Is he clerk or none tel what he is</L>
<L N="617">Nay he is gretter &thorn;an a clerke ywis
<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="399"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="549"></L>
<L N="618">Seide &yogh;oman and in wordes fewe</L>
<L>Oste and of his craft sum what .I. wil &yogh;owe schewe</L>
<L>.I. sei my lorde can suche a sutelte</L>
<L N="621">Bot al his craft &yogh;e maie nouht wite att me</L>
<L>And som what help .I. &yogh;it to his worcheinge</L>
<L>&thorn;at al &thorn;is grounde whiche &thorn;at we bien on rideinge</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at we come to Canturbury toune.</L>
<L N="625">He cou&thorn;e al clene torne vp so<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? <I>MS</I> se]</NOTE> doune</L>
<L>And paue it al of siluer and of golde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is &yogh;oman hadde &thorn;us ytolde</L>
<L>Vnto oure hoste he seide benedicite</L>
<L N="629">&thorn;is &thorn;inge is wonder meruelous to me</L>
<L>Se&thorn;ens &thorn;at &thorn;i lorde of so hihe prudence</L>
<L>Be cause of whiche men scholde hem reuerence</L>
<L>&thorn;at of his worschipe reche&thorn; he so lite</L>
<L N="633">His ouere slope is not wor&thorn;e a myte</L>
<L>As in effecte to him so mot .I. go</L>
<L>It is al bawde and to-tore also</L>
<L>Whi is &thorn;i lorde so slottesche .I. &thorn;e preie</L>
<L N="637">And his of pouer better clo&thorn;es to beie</L>
<L>If &thorn;at his dede accorde wi&thorn; &thorn;i speche</L>
<L>Tel me &thorn;at. and &thorn;at .I. &thorn;e beseche</L>
<L>Whie quod &thorn;is &yogh;oman wherto ax &yogh;e me</L>
<L N="641">God helpe me so for he schal neuer &thorn;e</L>
<L>Bot .I. wil nouht avowe &thorn;at .I. seie</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere for kepe it secre .I. &yogh;owe preie</L>
<L>He is to wise in fei&thorn;e as .I. beleue</L>
<L N="645">&thorn;at &thorn;at is ouere done it wil nouht preue</L>
<L>And riht as clerkes seine it is a vice</L>
<L>Where-fore in &thorn;at .I. holde him lewde and nyce</L>
<L>For whan a man ha&thorn; ouere grete a witte</L>
<L N="649">Ful oft it hapne&thorn; to mis vsen it<MILESTONE N="159b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So do&thorn;e my lorde and &thorn;at me greue&thorn; sore</L>
<L>God it amend .I. can seie nowe no more</L>
<L>Thare-of no force good &yogh;oman quod oure Oste</L>
<L N="653">Se&thorn;ens his connynge of &thorn;i lorde &thorn;ou woste
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="400"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="550"></L>
<L N="654">Tel. howe he do&thorn;e .I. praie &thorn;e hertelye</L>
<L>Se&thorn;en &thorn;at he is so craftie and so slye</L>
<L>Where dwellen &yogh;e it to tel be</L>
<L N="657">In &thorn;e subbarbes of a toune quod he</L>
<L>Lurkeinge in Hirnes and in lanes blinde</L>
<L>Where &thorn;es robbers and &thorn;eues be kinde</L>
<L>Holden her priue fereful residence</L>
<L N="661">As &thorn;ei &thorn;at dare nouht schewe her presence</L>
<L>So fare we if .I. schal sey &thorn;e so&thorn;e</L>
<L>&yogh;it quod oure Oste lat me talke to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Whie ert &thorn;ou discoloure in &thorn;i face</L>
<L N="665">Peter quod he god &yogh;if harde grace</L>
<L>I am so vsed in &thorn;e fire to blow</L>
<L>That it ha&thorn;e chaunged my colour as .I. trowe</L>
<L>.I. am nouht wont in no myrrour to prie</L>
<L N="669">Bot swynke sore and leren to multiplie</L>
<L>We blondern euer and pouren in &thorn;e fire</L>
<L>And for al &thorn;at we failen of oure desire</L>
<L>For euere we lakken oure conclusione</L>
<L N="673">To muche folke we bene bot illusione</L>
<L>And borwe golde be it a pounde or tuo</L>
<L>Or ten. or .xij. or mony summes mo</L>
<L>And make hem wene att &thorn;e leste weie</L>
<L N="677">&thorn;at of o pou[n]de we cou&thorn;e maake tweie</L>
<L>&yogh;it is it fals and aye we haue good hope</L>
<L>It forto done and after it we grope</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at science is so fer vs be-forne</L>
<L N="681">We mowe nouhte al-&thorn;ouhe we had it suorne</L>
<L>It ouertake. it slide a-waie so faste</L>
<L>It wil vs make beggers att &thorn;e last</L>
<L>Whiles &thorn;is &yogh;oman was &thorn;us in &thorn;is talkeinge</L>
<L N="685">This Chanon drouhe him nere and herd al &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at &thorn;is &yogh;oman spak for suspecione</L>
<L>Of men speche euer had &thorn;is chanone</L>
<L>For Caton sei&thorn;e he &thorn;at giltif is</L>
<L N="689">Deme&thorn; al &thorn;inge be spoke of him ywys
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="401"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="551"></L>
<L N="690">Because of &thorn;at he gan so nyhe to drawe</L>
<L>His &yogh;oman &thorn;at he herd al his sawe<MILESTONE N="160a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us he seide vnto his &yogh;oman &thorn;o</L>
<L N="693">Holde &thorn;ow &thorn;i pees and speke wordes no mo</L>
<L>For if &thorn;ou do &thorn;ou schalt it dere abye</L>
<L>Tho sklanderst me here in &thorn;is compaignye</L>
<L>And eke diskeuerest &thorn;at &thorn;ou scholdest hide</L>
<L N="697">&yogh;e quod oure Oste tel one what so be-tide</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is &thorn;reteinge reche &thorn;e nouht a myte</L>
<L>In fei&thorn;e quod he no more .I. do bot a lite</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is Chanone sawe it wolde nouht be</L>
<L N="701">Bot his &yogh;oman wolde tel his priuete</L>
<L>He fledde awaie for verrei sorwe and schame</L>
<L>A quod &thorn;is &yogh;oman here schal arise game</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at .I. can anone wil .I. tell</L>
<L N="705">Se&thorn;en he is gone &thorn;e foule fende him quell</L>
<L>For neuer here after wil .I. wi&thorn; him mete</L>
<L>For penye ne for pounde .I. be-hete</L>
<L>He &thorn;at me brouht first vnto &thorn;at game</L>
<L N="709">Er &thorn;at he deie sorwe haue he and schame</L>
<L>For it ernest to me be my fei&thorn;e</L>
<L>&thorn;at fele .I. wele what so any man sei&thorn;e</L>
<L>And &yogh;itte for al my smert and al my greue</L>
<L N="713">For al my sorwe laboure and mescheue</L>
<L>.I. cou&thorn;e neuere leue it in no wise</L>
<L>No wolde god my witte myht suffise</L>
<L>To tellen al &thorn;at longe&thorn; for &thorn;at arte</L>
<L N="717">Bot na&thorn;eles &yogh;it wil .I. tel &yogh;owe parte</L>
<L>Se&thorn;en my lorde is gone .I. wil not spare</L>
<L>Suche &thorn;inge as .I. knowe .I. wil declare</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>Explicit </B>prologus</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="402">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="552">
<HEAD>[THE PREAMBLE.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>Incipit ffabula.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 160</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wythe &thorn;is chanon dwelled haue .I. seuen &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="721">And of his science am .I. neuer &thorn;e nere</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at .I. had .I. haue .I.-lost &thorn;ere by</L>
<L>And god wote so ha&thorn;e mony mo &thorn;an .I.</L>
<L>Ther .I. was wont to be riht frissche and gay</L>
<L N="725">Of clo&thorn;inge and of good arraie</L>
<L>Nowe may .I. were an hose vpon myn hede</L>
<L>And where my coloure was bo&thorn;e freche and rede</L>
<L>Now it is wan and of a lewde hewe</L>
<L N="729">Who so it vse&thorn; sore sc[h]all he rewe</L>
<L>And of my swynke &yogh;it blered is myne ey&yogh;e</L>
<L>Lo whiche avantage is for to multepli&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;at slideinge science ha&thorn; me maade so bare<MILESTONE N="160b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="733">&THORN;at .I. haue no goode where &thorn;at euere y fare</L>
<L>And &yogh;ite .I. am endited &amp; endetted so &thorn;ar bye</L>
<L>Of golde &thorn;at .I. haue borwed trewlye</L>
<L>&thorn;at while .I. leue .I. schal it quite neuer</L>
<L N="737">&thorn;at euery man be war be me for euer</L>
<L>What manere man &thorn;at caste&thorn; him &thorn;er to</L>
<L>If he continue .I. holde his &thorn;reft ydo</L>
<L>For so helpe me god &thorn;ar by schal he nouht wynne</L>
<L N="741">Bot empte his purce and make his wittes &thorn;inne</L>
<L>And whan he &thorn;oruhe his madnes and foly</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; lost his owen goode &thorn;orul Iopardy</L>
<L>&thorn;an he excite&thorn; o&thorn;er men &thorn;erto</L>
<L N="745">To lese here gode as hem self ha&thorn; do</L>
<L>For vnto schrewes Ioye it is an[d] ese</L>
<L>To haue her felowe in peine and disese.
<PB REF="00000431.tif" N="403"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="553"></L>
<L>Thus was .I. lerned ones of a clerk</L>
<L N="749">Of &thorn;at no charge .I. wil speke of o&thorn;er werke</L>
<L>Whan we bene &thorn;are as we schal exercise</L>
<L>Oure eluyssche craft we seme wonder wise</L>
<L>Oure termes buen so clergial and so wheinte</L>
<L N="753">.I. blowe &thorn;e fire til &thorn;at myne hert feinte</L>
<L>What schold .I. tel of suche proporcion</L>
<L>Of &thorn;inges whiche &thorn;at we worche vppon</L>
<L>As .on. v. or .vj. vnce it maie wel be</L>
<L N="757">Of siluer or of sum o&thorn;e[r] quantite</L>
<L>And bise me to tel &yogh;owe &thorn;e names</L>
<L>Of orpement bernt bones yren swames</L>
<L>&thorn;an in to pouder grounde bue ful smal</L>
<L N="761">And in an er&thorn;en potte houe &thorn;at potte is al</L>
<L>And salt put inne and also papere</L>
<L>Be for &thorn;es pouders &thorn;at .I. speke of here</L>
<L>And wele ycouerd wi&thorn; a lampe of glas</L>
<L N="765">And of muche o&thorn;ere &thorn;inge what &thorn;at &thorn;ere was</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e potte and glas engluteinge</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e eyere myht passe no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And of the esye and smarte alsoo</L>
<L N="769">Whiche &thorn;at was maad and of &thorn;e care and woo</L>
<L>&thorn;at we hadde in oure matiers sublimeinge</L>
<L>And amalgamynge and calcenynge</L>
<L>Of whike siluere y-cleped Marcurie crude</L>
<L N="773">For all oure sleytes we can nouht conclude</L>
<L>Oure orpement and sublimed Mercurie<MILESTONE N="161a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Oure grounde litage eke on &thorn;e perorforie</L>
<L>Of yche of &thorn;es vnces a certeine</L>
<L N="777">Nou&yogh;t helpe&thorn; vs oure laboure is in veine</L>
<L>Ne eke owre spirites ascencion</L>
<L>Ne eke oure matiers &thorn;at lien al fix adoune</L>
<L>Mowe in oure werkeinge no&thorn;inge vs aveile</L>
<L N="781">For lost is al oure laboure and traueile</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e cost in .xx. deuel waie</L>
<L>Is loste also whiche we on it leie
<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="404"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="554"></L>
<L>&thorn;ere is also mony ano&thorn;ere &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="785">&thorn;at is to oure crafte or perteineinge</L>
<L>&thorn;ouhe .I. be order hem here ne reherse can</L>
<L>Because &thorn;at .I. am a lewde man</L>
<L>&yogh;it wil .I. tel hem al &thorn;ei come to mynde</L>
<L N="789">&thorn;ouhe .I. ne kan sette hem in her kinde</L>
<L>As bole armonyac verte grece and borace</L>
<L>And sundere vessels maade of er&thorn;e and glasse</L>
<L>Oure Orinales and oure descensories</L>
<L N="793">Viols cresletes and sublimatories</L>
<L>Cocurbites<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? <I>MS</I> Corurbites]</NOTE> and alembekes eke</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er suche dere y-nowhe a leke</L>
<L>Note nede&thorn; it to reherse hem al</L>
<L N="797">Waters rubefinge and boles gall</L>
<L>Arcenyk sal armonyak and bromstone</L>
<L>And herbes cou&thorn;e .I. tel eke many one</L>
<L>As egremoyne valeriane and lunarie</L>
<L N="801">And o&thorn;er suche if &thorn;at me luste to tarye</L>
<L>Oure lampes berneinge bo&thorn;e nyht and daie</L>
<L>To bringen aboute oure craft it &thorn;at we maie</L>
<L>Oure forneys eke of Calcinacione</L>
<L N="805">And of waters albificacione</L>
<L>Vnslekked lyme chalke and gleire and of an aye</L>
<L>Pouders diueres asshes donge pisse and cleie</L>
<L>Ceride poketes Sal peter and vitriol</L>
<L N="809">And diuers fires maad of wode and cole</L>
<L>Sal tarter Alkaly and sal preparate</L>
<L>And combust matiers and coagulate</L>
<L>Cleye made wi&thorn; hors here and oyle</L>
<L N="813">Of tartre Alumglasse berme worte and Argoile</L>
<L>Resalgar and o&thorn;er matiers enbybeynge</L>
<L>And eke of o&thorn;er maters encorperinge</L>
<L>And of siluer citrinacione<MILESTONE N="161b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="817">Oure cementinge and fermentacione</L>
<L>Oure Ingotes testes and mony mo</L>
<L>.I. wil &yogh;owe tell as was me tauht also
<PB REF="00000433.tif" N="405"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="555"></L>
<L>The . foure spirites and &thorn;e bodis seuen</L>
<L N="821">Be order of ofte as .I. herd my lorde neuen</L>
<L>&thorn;e . first spirit whiksiluer cald is</L>
<L>&thorn;e . secunde Orpement &thorn;e &thorn;red .I.-wis</L>
<L>Sal armoniac . and &thorn;e fourt bromstone</L>
<L N="825">The bodis .vij. eke lo hem here anone</L>
<L>Sol . gold . is . and luna . siluer we &thorn;repe</L>
<L>Mars . yren . Mercure . whikseluer we clepe</L>
<L>Saturnus lede . and Iubiter is tynne</L>
<L N="829">And Venus coper be my fader kinne</L>
<L>&thorn;is cursed craft who so wil exercise</L>
<L>He schal no goode hane &thorn;at maie him suffise</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e good he spende&thorn; &thorn;ere aboute</L>
<L N="833">He lese schal &thorn;er-of haue .I. no doute</L>
<L>Who so &thorn;at lust to outen his folie</L>
<L>Lat him com for&thorn;e and leren to multeplie</L>
<L>Ande euery man &thorn;at ouht in his cofre</L>
<L N="837">Lete him appere and wax a philosophre</L>
<L>Ascanse &thorn;at craft is so liht for to lere</L>
<L>Nay nay god it wote al be he monke or frere</L>
<L>Preste or chanone or any o&thorn;er wyht</L>
<L N="841">&thorn;ouhe he sitte att his boke bo&thorn;e daie and nyht</L>
<L>In lerneynge of &thorn;is elvisshe nice lore</L>
<L>Al is in veine and parde muche more</L>
<L>Is to lerne a lewd man &thorn;e sotelte</L>
<L N="845">For fye speke nouht &thorn;ere-of for it wil nouht be</L>
<L>Al cou&thorn;e he letterure or cou&thorn;e he none</L>
<L>As in effect he schal finde it al one</L>
<L>For bo&thorn;e tuo be my saluacione</L>
<L N="849">Concluden in multiplicacione</L>
<L>I-lyche wele whan &thorn;ei haul al y-do</L>
<L>&thorn;is is to seine &thorn;e feile bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>&yogh;it for &thorn;at .I. to muche rehersaill</L>
<L N="853">Of waters Corosif and of lymayle</L>
<L>And of bodis mollificaci&omacr;ne</L>
<L>And also of here induracione
<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="406"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="556"></L>
<L>Oyles ablucione and metale fusible.</L>
<L N="857">To tellen al wald passen any bible.</L>
<L>That ouhwhere is where-for as for &thorn;e best<MILESTONE N="162a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of all &thorn;is names now will .I. me rest</L>
<L>For as .I. troue .I. haue &yogh;owe tolde ynowhe</L>
<L N="861">To Reysen a fende loke he neuer so rouhe</L>
<L>A nay lat be &thorn;e philosophre stone</L>
<L>Elixir cleped we sechen fast ychon</L>
<L>For had we him &thorn;an were we seker ynowhe</L>
<L N="865">Bot vnto god of heuen .I. maak a vowe</L>
<L>For al oure craft whan we haue al y-do</L>
<L>And al oure sleiht he wil nouht com vs to</L>
<L>He ha&thorn;e vs made spend muche good</L>
<L N="869">For sorwe of whiche al-moste we wexen wode</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at goode hope crepe&thorn; in oure herte</L>
<L>Supposeinge euer &thorn;ouhe we sore smert</L>
<L>To be releued be him afterwarde</L>
<L N="873">Supposinge and hope is scharpe and harde</L>
<L>.I. warne &yogh;owe wele it is to seken euer</L>
<L>&thorn;at futur temps ha&thorn; maad men deseuer</L>
<L>In trust &thorn;er-of from al &thorn;at euer &thorn;ei hadde</L>
<L N="877">&YOGH;it of &thorn;at art &thorn;ei cou&thorn; nouht wex sadde</L>
<L>For vn to hem it is a bitter swete</L>
<L>So seme&thorn; it forne had &thorn;ei bot a shete</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;ei miht wrappe in a nyht</L>
<L N="881">And Abak to walken inne be daie liht</L>
<L>Thei wold hem sellen and spenden on &thorn;is craft</L>
<L>Thei can nouht stint til no&thorn;inge be laft</L>
<L>And euer more where &thorn;at euer &thorn;ei gone</L>
<L N="885">Men maye hem knowe be smell of bromstone</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e worlde &thorn;ei stinken as a gote</L>
<L>Hire sauoure is so rammysshe and so hote</L>
<L>That &thorn;ouhe a man from hem a mile be</L>
<L N="889">The sauour wil infecte truste&thorn; me</L>
<L>Lo &thorn;us be smellinge and be &thorn;rede bare arraie</L>
<L>If &thorn;at men lust &thorn;is folke &thorn;ei knowe maie
<PB REF="00000435.tif" N="407"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="557"></L>
<L>And if a man wil ax him priuely</L>
<L N="893">Whi &thorn;ei bue clo&thorn;ed so vnthriftely.</L>
<L>Riht anone &thorn;ei wil roune in his ere</L>
<L>And seie if &thorn;ei espied were</L>
<L>Men wold hem fle be cause of hire science</L>
<L N="897">Lo &thorn;us folke be-trayen Innocence</L>
<L>Passe ouer &thorn;is .I. go my tale vntoo</L>
<L>Er &thorn;at &thorn;e pote be on &thorn;e fire ydoo</L>
<L>Of Metaile wi&thorn; a certeine quantite<MILESTONE N="162b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="901">Mi lorde hem tempre&thorn; and no man bot he</L>
<L>Nowe he is gone .I. dare sei boldely</L>
<L>For as men seine he can do craftely.</L>
<L>Algate .I. wote wele he ha&thorn;e suche a name</L>
<L N="905">And &yogh;itte ful ofte he renne&thorn; in &thorn;e blame</L>
<L>And witte &yogh;e howe ful oft it hapne&thorn; so</L>
<L>&thorn;e potte to-breke&thorn; and fare wele al is goo</L>
<L>&thorn;es metals been of so grete violence</L>
<L N="909">Owre walles maie nouht make hem resistence</L>
<L>Bott if &thorn;ei wrowht of lime and stone</L>
<L>&thorn;ei percen so and &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e wal &thorn;ei gone</L>
<L>And sum of hem sinken in to &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L N="913">&thorn;us haue we lost be times mony a po[u]nd</L>
<L>And somme erne scaterd al &thorn;e flore aboute</L>
<L>Somme lepen in to &thorn;e roof wi&thorn;&thorn;e-outen doute</L>
<L>&thorn;ouhe &thorn;at &thorn;e fende note in oure siht hem schewe</L>
<L N="917">.I. trow &thorn;at he wi&thorn; vs be &thorn;at schrewe</L>
<L>In hell where &thorn;at his lorde and sire</L>
<L>Ne is &thorn;ere no more woo ne angur ne Ire</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at owre potte is broke as .I. haue seide</L>
<L N="921">Euery man Chitte and halt him yuel apaide</L>
<L>Som seide it was longe on &thorn;e fire makeinge</L>
<L>Somme seide nay . it was longe on &thorn;e bloweynge</L>
<L>Than was .I. ferde for &thorn;at was myne office</L>
<L N="925">Strawe quod &thorn;e &thorn;redde &yogh;e be lewde and nyce</L>
<L>It was nouht tempred as it ouhte to be</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e fer&thorn;e stinte and herken me
<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="408"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="558"></L>
<L>Be cause oure fire was nouht maade of beche</L>
<L N="929">&thorn;at is &thorn;e cause none o&thorn;er so &thorn;eeche</L>
<L>.I. can not tell where on it is a-longe</L>
<L>Bot wele .I. wote grete strife is vs amonge</L>
<L>What quod my lord &thorn;ere is no more to done</L>
<L N="933">Of &thorn;es periles .I. wil be ware eft sone</L>
<L>.I. am riht seker &thorn;at &thorn;e pott was crased</L>
<L>Be as be maye be &yogh;e no &thorn;inge amasud</L>
<L>As vsage is late swepe &thorn;e flore as swy&thorn;e</L>
<L N="937">Pluke vpe &yogh;oure herte and be &yogh;e gladde and bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>The mollok on an hepe yswepped was</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e flore cast a canvas</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is mollok in a sif y&thorn;rowe</L>
<L N="941">And ysiftide and yplucked mony a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>Parde quod one summe what of oure metale</L>
<L>&yogh;itt is &thorn;ere here &thorn;ouhe we haue nouht al<MILESTONE N="163a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ouhe &thorn;is &thorn;inge mishapped ha&thorn;e as nowe</L>
<L N="945">Ano&thorn;er time it maie be wele ynowhe</L>
<L>Vs most putte oure goode in aduenture</L>
<L>A marchant parde maie nouht aie endure</L>
<L>Tristne&thorn; me wele in his prosperite</L>
<L N="949">Som time is goode is drowned in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>And sum time it comme&thorn; sauf vnto &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>Pes quod my lorde &thorn;e next time .I. wil fonde</L>
<L>To bringe oure crafte al in ano&thorn;ere plite</L>
<L N="953">And bote .I. do sires latt me haue &thorn;e wite</L>
<L>There was defaute in sum what wele .I. wote</L>
<L>An o&thorn;ere seide &thorn;e fire was ouere hote</L>
<L>Bot be hit hote or colde .I. dar sei &thorn;is</L>
<L N="957">&thorn;at we concluden euermore amys</L>
<L>We failen of &thorn;at whiche &thorn;at we wolde haue</L>
<L>And oure madnesse euer more we raue</L>
<L>And whan we bue to-geder euerychon</L>
<L N="961">Euery man seme&thorn; as wise as salomon</L>
<L>Bot al &thorn;inge whiche &thorn;at schyne&thorn; as &thorn;e gold</L>
<L>Is not golde as .I. haue herde it tolde
<PB REF="00000437.tif" N="409"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="559"></L>
<L>Ne euery appel &thorn;at is faire att ey&yogh;e</L>
<L N="965">Ne is not good whatt so men clappe or crie</L>
<L>Riht so loo farith it amongus vs</L>
<L>He &thorn;at seme&thorn; &thorn;e wisest be ihesus<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS ihc]</NOTE></L>
<L>Is most foole whan it comme&thorn; to &thorn;e prefe</L>
<L N="969">And he &thorn;at seme&thorn; trewest is a &thorn;efe</L>
<L>&thorn;at schol &yogh;e knowe er &thorn;at .I. fromme &yogh;owe wende</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at .I. of my tale haue maade an ende<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000438.tif" N="410"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="560">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THer is a chanon of religion<NOTE PLACE="marg">.ij<SUP>a</SUP>. pars</NOTE></L>
<L N="973">Amonges vs wolde enfecte al a toune</L>
<L>&thorn;ouhe it as grete were as nynyue</L>
<L>Rome Alisander . Troy . and o&thorn;er &thorn;re</L>
<L>His sleihtes and his infinite falsenesse</L>
<L N="977">There cou&thorn;e no man writen as .I. gesse</L>
<L>&thorn;ouhe &thorn;at he myht leuen a . &thorn;owsande &yogh;ere</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is of fals-nesse ne is his pere</L>
<L>For in his termes he wil him so winde</L>
<L N="981">And speke his wordes in so slyhe a kynde</L>
<L>Whan he comun schal wi&thorn; any wiht</L>
<L>What he wil make him dote anone riht</L>
<L>Bot it &thorn;e fende be as his seluen is</L>
<L N="985">Ful mony a man ha&thorn;e he bigiled ar &thorn;is<MILESTONE N="163b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And will if &thorn;at he maie leue a while</L>
<L>And &yogh;it men riden and gon ful mony a myle</L>
<L>Him for to seeke and haue acqueyntance</L>
<L N="989">Nat knoweinge of his fals gouernance</L>
<L>And if &thorn;e luste to &yogh;eue me audience</L>
<L>.I. will it tellen here in &yogh;oure presence</L>
<L>Bot worschipful chanon religious</L>
<L N="993">Ne deme&thorn; nouht &thorn;at .I. sclander &yogh;oure house</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ouhe my tale of chanon be</L>
<L>Of euery order some schrewe is parde</L>
<L>And god for-bede &thorn;at al a companye</L>
<L N="997">Sholde rewe a singuler mannes folye</L>
<L>To sclander &yogh;owe is not myne entente</L>
<L>Bot to Corretten &thorn;at mys yment
<PB REF="00000439.tif" N="411"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="561"></L>
<L>This tale was nou&yogh;t onely tolde for &yogh;owe</L>
<L N="1001">Bot eke for o&thorn;ere mo &yogh;e woote wele howe</L>
<L>&thorn;at amonge cristes posteles twelue</L>
<L>&THORN;ere nas no traytur bot Iudas him selue</L>
<L>Than whi scholde &thorn;e remenant al haue blame</L>
<L N="1005">That giltles were . by &yogh;owe say .I. &thorn;e same</L>
<L>Sauf only &thorn;is if &yogh;e wil herken me</L>
<L>If any Iudas in &yogh;oure Couent be</L>
<L>Remoue&thorn; him be time .I. &yogh;owe rede</L>
<L N="1009">If schame or losse maie causen any drede</L>
<L>And bu&thorn;e no&thorn;inge displesed .I. &yogh;owe preie</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;is caas herkene&thorn; what .I. wil seie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN Londen was a preste an annuellere</L>
<L N="1013">&thorn;at &thorn;er-inne dwelled had mony a &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Whiche was so plesant and so seruisable</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e wiff where he was att table</L>
<L>That sche wolde suffur him no &thorn;inge for to paye</L>
<L>For borde ne for clo&thorn;einge wente he neuer so gaye</L>
<L>And spendinge siluer hadde he riht ynouhe</L>
<L>&thorn;ere-of no force .I. wol procede as nowhe</L>
<L>And tel for&thorn;e my tale of &thorn;e Chanon</L>
<L N="1021">&thorn;at brouht &thorn;is prest to confusion</L>
<L>This fals chanon cam vppon a daye</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e prestes chambre &thorn;er he laye</L>
<L>Besecheinge him to lene him a certeine</L>
<L N="1025">Of golde and he wolde white him a-&yogh;eine</L>
<L>Lene me a marke quod he bot daies &thorn;re</L>
<L>And att my daie .I. wil it quyte &thorn;e<MILESTONE N="164a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And it so be &thorn;ou finde me fals</L>
<L N="1029">Ano&thorn;er daie honge me be &thorn;e hals</L>
<L>This preste him toke a marke and &thorn;at als swi&thorn;e</L>
<L>And &thorn;is chanon him &thorn;onked oft si&thorn;e</L>
<L>And toke his leue and went for&thorn;e his weie</L>
<L N="1033">And att &thorn;e &thorn;ered daie brouht his monye</L>
<L>And to &thorn;is preste he toke &thorn;is golde a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>There-of &thorn;is prest was glad and feine
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="412"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="562"></L>
<L>Certes quod he no &thorn;inge anoye&thorn; me</L>
<L N="1037">To lene a man a noble or tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L>Or what &thorn;inge were in myn possessione</L>
<L>Whan he so trewe is of condicione</L>
<L>&thorn;at in no wise breke wil his daie</L>
<L N="1041">To suche a man .I. can neuer saie naye</L>
<L>What quod &thorn;is chanon schold .I. be vntrewe</L>
<L>Naye it were &thorn;inge fallen al of &thorn;e newe</L>
<L>Treu&thorn;e is a &thorn;inge &thorn;at .I. wil euer kepe</L>
<L N="1045">In to &thorn;e daie in whiche &thorn;at [I] schal crepe</L>
<L>In to my graue and elles god for-bede</L>
<L>Beleue&thorn; &thorn;is as seker as is &yogh;oure crede</L>
<L>God &thorn;onke .I. and in goode time be it seide</L>
<L N="1049">&thorn;at &thorn;er was neuer man &yogh;it yuel appaide</L>
<L>For golde ne siluer &thorn;at he to me lent</L>
<L>And neuer falsed in myne herte y ment</L>
<L>And sir quod he nowe of my priuete</L>
<L N="1053">And se&thorn;en . &yogh;e so goodly haue bue to me</L>
<L>And ki&thorn;ed to me so grete gentillesse</L>
<L>Som whatte to whiten wi&thorn; &yogh;oure kindenesse</L>
<L>.I. wil &yogh;owe schewe .&amp;. if &yogh;owe lust to lere</L>
<L N="1057">.I. schal it schewe to &yogh;owe anone riht here</L>
<L>Howe .I. kan worchen in filosophie</L>
<L>Take&thorn; goode hede &yogh;e scholn sene wele att ye</L>
<L>&thorn;at .I. wil do a maistre ar .I. goo</L>
<L N="1061">&YOGH;e sir quod &thorn;e preste . &yogh;e sire and wil &yogh;e so</L>
<L>Mary &thorn;ere-of .I. praie &yogh;owe hertely</L>
<L>Att &yogh;oure commandement sir treuly</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e chanon and elles god for-bede</L>
<L N="1065">Lo how &thorn;is &thorn;ef cou&thorn;e . his seruise bede</L>
<L>Ful so&thorn;e it is &thorn;at suche proferd seruise</L>
<L>Stinke&thorn;e as wittenes &thorn;is olde wyse</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ful sone .I. wil . it verifie</L>
<L N="1069">In &thorn;is chanone is rote of al trecherie<MILESTONE N="164b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That euermore delite ha&thorn;e and gladnesse</L>
<L>Suche fendely &thorn;ouhtes in his hert empresse
<PB REF="00000441.tif" N="413"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="563"></L>
<L>Howe cristes peple he maie to meschief bringe</L>
<L N="1073">God kepe vs fromme his fals discimulinge</L>
<L>What wist &thorn;is preste wi&thorn; whome he delte</L>
<L>Ne of his harme comynge no&thorn;inge he felte</L>
<L>O cele preste o celi Innocent</L>
<L N="1077">Wi&thorn; Couetise anone &thorn;ou schalt be blent</L>
<L>O graceles ful blinde is &thorn;i conceite</L>
<L>No &thorn;inge ert &thorn;ow war of &thorn;i deceit</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at &thorn;is fox schapen ha&thorn; to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1081">His wyle wrenches &thorn;ou maiste nouht flyhe</L>
<L>Wher-fore to go to &thorn;e conclusion</L>
<L>&thorn;at referre&thorn; to &thorn;i confusion</L>
<L>Vnhappe man anone .I. wil me hihe</L>
<L N="1085">To tellen &thorn;in vnwitte and &thorn;i folye</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;e falsenesse of &thorn;at o&thorn;er wreche</L>
<L>As ferfor as my connynge wil streche</L>
<L>&thorn;is chanon was my lorde &yogh;e wolde wene</L>
<L N="1089">Sir oft in fai&thorn;e and bue &thorn;e heuen quene</L>
<L>It was ano&thorn;er chanon and nouht he</L>
<L>&thorn;at can an .C. folde more sotelte</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; be-traied folke mony a time</L>
<L N="1093">Of his falsnesse it delite&thorn; me to rime</L>
<L>Euer whan .I. speke of his falsede</L>
<L>For schame of him my cheke waxen rede</L>
<L>Al gates &thorn;ei be-gon for to glowe</L>
<L N="1097">For redenes haue .I. riht nowe wele .I. knowe</L>
<L>In my vesage for sinnes diuers</L>
<L>Of Metals whiche &yogh;e haue herd me reherce</L>
<L>Consumed and wastede ha&thorn;e myne redenesse</L>
<L N="1101">Now take&thorn; hede of my chanons cursednesse</L>
<L>Sir quod he to &thorn;e preste lat &yogh;oure man gone</L>
<L>Fo[r] whiksiluer &thorn;at we is had anone</L>
<L>And latte him bringe vnces tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L N="1105">And whan he comme&thorn; als fast schal we se</L>
<L>A wonder &thorn;inge whiche &yogh;e sawe neuer ar &thorn;is</L>
<L>Sir quod &thorn;e preste it schal be done ywisse
<PB REF="00000442.tif" N="414"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="564"></L>
<L>He bad his seruant fechen him his &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="1109">And he al rede was at his bedynge</L>
<L>And went him for and cam anon a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;is whike siluer schortly for to seyne<MILESTONE N="165a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And toke &thorn;es vnces &thorn;re to &thorn;e chanone</L>
<L N="1113">And he it leide faire and wele adoune</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;e seruant coles for to bringe</L>
<L>&thorn;at he anone myht go to his wirkeinge</L>
<L>&thorn;e coles riht anone weren yfet</L>
<L N="1117">And &thorn;is chanon toke oute a croselet</L>
<L>Of his bosome and schewe it &thorn;e prest</L>
<L>This quod he whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ou sest</L>
<L>Take in &thorn;ine hande and put &thorn;i self &thorn;ere inne</L>
<L N="1121">Of &thorn;is whike siluere an vnce and here beginne</L>
<L>In &thorn;e name of crist to wex a philosofer</L>
<L>Ther bene ful fewe whiche &thorn;at .I. wil profer</L>
<L>To schewe hem &thorn;us muche of my science</L>
<L N="1125">For &yogh;e schol seen here be experience</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is siluer .I. wil mortifie</L>
<L>Riht in &yogh;oure siht anone wi&thorn; oute lye</L>
<L>And maak it as god siluer and als fyne</L>
<L N="1129">As &thorn;er is any in &yogh;oure porce or in myne</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto als doulcete and malliable</L>
<L>And elles holde me fals and vn-able</L>
<L>Amonge folk euer to appere</L>
<L N="1133">.I. haue a pouder here . it cost me dere</L>
<L>Schal make al good for it is cause of al</L>
<L>Mi konnynge whiche . &thorn;at .I. &yogh;owe schew shall</L>
<L>Voide&thorn; &yogh;oure man and lat him be &thorn;er oute</L>
<L N="1137">An schette &thorn;e dore whiles we bene aboute</L>
<L>Oure priuete &thorn;at no man vs aspie</L>
<L>Whiles we werken in &thorn;is philosophie</L>
<L>Al as he bad ffulfilled was in dede</L>
<L N="1141">&thorn;is ilke seruant anon riht oute &yogh;ede</L>
<L>And his maister schett &thorn;e dore anone</L>
<L>An to her laboure spedely &thorn;ei gone
<PB REF="00000443.tif" N="415"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="565"></L>
<L>&thorn;es preste att &thorn;is cursed chanons bydynge</L>
<L N="1145">Vpon &thorn;e fire a-none sett &thorn;is &thorn;inge</L>
<L>And blewe &thorn;e fire and besid him ful fast</L>
<L>And &thorn;is chanon in to &thorn;is croselett cast</L>
<L>A pouder note .I. wher-of it was</L>
<L N="1149">.y.-maade of chalk o&thorn;ere of glas</L>
<L>Or sum whatte elles was nouht wor&thorn;e a flie</L>
<L>To blinde wi&thorn;e &thorn;is preste and badd him hihe</L>
<L>&thorn;es coles for to cowchen al aboue</L>
<L N="1153">This Croslet for in token &thorn;at .I. &thorn;e loue<MILESTONE N="165b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Quod &thorn;is chanon &thorn;ine hondes tuoo</L>
<L>Schal worche al &thorn;inge whiche as schal be doo</L>
<L>Gremercy quod &thorn;e preste and was ful gladde</L>
<L N="1157">And couched coles as &thorn;e Chanon badd</L>
<L>And whiles he besy was &thorn;is fendely wrecche</L>
<L>&thorn;is fals chanon &thorn;e foule fende him fecche</L>
<L>Oute of his bosom toke a bechen cole</L>
<L N="1161">In whiche ful sotelly was maad an hole</L>
<L>And &thorn;ereinne pitt was of siluer limaile</L>
<L>An vnce and stopped was wi&thorn; oute faile</L>
<L>This hole wi&thorn; wex to kepe the limal inne</L>
<L N="1165">An[d] vnderstonde&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;is false gynne</L>
<L>Was not maade &thorn;ere bot it was maade to fore</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er &thorn;inges .I. schal tel more</L>
<L>Here after warde whiche &thorn;at he wi&thorn; him brouht</L>
<L N="1169">Ar he com &thorn;ere to begile him he &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>And so he dide are he went a twynne</L>
<L>Til he had tornyd him kou&thorn;e he not blinne</L>
<L>It dulle&thorn; me whan &thorn;at .I. of him speke</L>
<L N="1173">On his fals hede faine wolde .I. me awreke</L>
<L>If .I. wist howe bot he is here and &thorn;ere</L>
<L>He is so variant he bide&thorn; no where</L>
<L>Bo[t] take&thorn; hede nowe sires for goddes loue</L>
<L N="1177">He toke his cole of whiche .I. spak aboue</L>
<L>And in his honde he bare it priuely</L>
<L>And whiles &thorn;e priste couched besili
<PB REF="00000444.tif" N="416"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="566"></L>
<L>&thorn;e coles as .I. tolde &yogh;ow er &thorn;is</L>
<L N="1181">&thorn;is Chanon seide frende &yogh;e done amys</L>
<L>&thorn;is is nouht couched as it ouht to be</L>
<L>Bot sone .I. schal amend it quod he</L>
<L>Nowe lat me medel &thorn;ere-wi&thorn; bot a while</L>
<L N="1185">For of &yogh;oue haue .I. pete be sein gile</L>
<L>&yogh;e been riht hote .I. see wele how &yogh;e swete</L>
<L>Haue here a clo&thorn;e and wype aweie &thorn;e wete</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e prest him wyped haas</L>
<L N="1189">This Chanon toke his cole .I. schrewe his face</L>
<L>And leid it vpon abouen &thorn;e Midward</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e croselett . And blewe wele afterward</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e Coles gan fast berne</L>
<L N="1193">Now &yogh;if vs drinke quod &thorn;e Chanone &thorn;ann</L>
<L>Als swi&thorn;e al schal be wele .I. vndertake.</L>
<L>Sit we doune and lete vs mery make<MILESTONE N="166a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And whann &thorn;e chanons bechen cole</L>
<L N="1197">Was brente al &thorn;e limal oute of the hole</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e croselet anone fel adoune</L>
<L>And so it mot nedes be resoune</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en it so heuen aboue couched was</L>
<L N="1201">Bot &thorn;ere-of wist no &thorn;inge &thorn;e preste alas</L>
<L>He demed al &thorn;e coles ylyche goode</L>
