<L>And borwed him large botels &thorn;re</L>
<L N="872">And in &thorn;e tueyne &thorn;is poyson poured he</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;redde he keped clen for his drinke</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e nyht he schop him to swynke</L>
<L>In cariynge of &thorn;e golde out [of] &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="876">And whan &thorn;is ryetoure wi&thorn; sory grace</L>
<L>Hadde filled wi&thorn; him his grete boteles &thorn;re</L>
<L>To his felawes a&yogh;eine repaire&thorn; he</L>
<L>What nede&thorn; it to sermon &thorn;er-of more</L>
<L N="880">For riht as &thorn;ei had kast his de&thorn;e to-fore</L>
<L>Riht so &thorn;ei haue him sleyne and &thorn;at anone</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at &thorn;is was done &thorn;an spak &thorn;e tone</L>
<L>Nowe lat vs drinke and sitte and make vs merye</L>
<L N="884">And afterward we wollen his body berye
<PB REF="00000481.tif" N="453"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="330"></L>
<L>And efteward it happed him percas</L>
<L>To take &thorn;e botel &thorn;er-in &thorn;e poyson was</L>
<L>And drange and &yogh;aue his felawe drinke also</L>
<L N="888">For whiche anone &thorn;ei storuen bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>Bott certes .I. suppose &thorn;at Aucyenne</L>
<L>Wrote neuer in no canon ne in no fenne</L>
<L>No wonder sorwes of enpoysonynge.</L>
<L N="892">Thus hadde &thorn;es wriches tuo here endeinge<MILESTONE N="180a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thus ended buen &thorn;es homicides tuo.</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;e false empoysonere also</L>
<L>O cursede sinne ful of cursednesse</L>
<L N="896">O traitoures homicideres o wikkednesse</L>
<L>O . glotony . o luxurye o hasardye</L>
<L>&THORN;ou blasphemer of crist wi&thorn; velanye</L>
<L>And o&thorn;es grete of vsage and of pride</L>
<L N="900">Alas mankinde howe may it betide</L>
<L>Thereto &thorn;ine Creatour whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e wrouht</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his precious blode &thorn;e bouhte</L>
<L>Thowe ert so fals and so vnkinde alas</L>
<L N="904">Nowe good men god for-&yogh;eue &yogh;owe &yogh;oure trespas</L>
<L>And war &yogh;owe fro &thorn;e sinne of Auarice</L>
<L>Myne holy pardon may &yogh;ow al warissche</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &yogh;e ofer nobles o&thorn;er sterlinges</L>
<L N="908">O&thorn;ere elles siluer spones broches or ringes</L>
<L>Bowe&thorn; &yogh;owre heued vnder &thorn;is holy bulles</L>
<L>Comme&thorn; vpe &yogh;e wives and offer &yogh;oure wolles</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure name .I. entre here in my rolle anone</L>
<L N="912">In-to &thorn;e blisse of heuen schole &yogh;e gone</L>
<L>.I. &yogh;owe assoile be myne hihe pouere</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at wollen offere as clene and eke as clere</L>
<L>As &yogh;e weer borne and sires lo &thorn;us .I. preche</L>
<L N="916">And ihesu crist &thorn;at is oure sowles leche</L>
<L>So graunt &yogh;owe his pardon to receyve</L>
<L>For &thorn;at is best .I. wil &yogh;owe nouht deceyve</L>
<L>Bot sires o worde for-gat .I. in my tale</L>
<L N="920">.I. haue Reliques and pardon in my male
<PB REF="00000482.tif" N="454"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="331"></L>
<L>As faire as any man of yngelonde</L>
<L>Whiche were me y&yogh;eue be &thorn;e popes honde</L>
<L>If any of &yogh;ow wil of deuocione</L>
<L N="924">Offerne and haue myne absolucione</L>
<L>Comme&thorn; for anone and knele&thorn; adowne here</L>
<L>And &yogh;e schal haue my pardon &thorn;at is dere</L>
<L>Or elles take&thorn; pardon as &yogh;e wende</L>
<L N="928">All newe and frishe att euery tounes ende</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &yogh;e offren alwei newe and newe</L>
<L>Nobles and pens whiche &thorn;at bien good and trewe</L>
<L>It is an honur to eueryche &thorn;at is here</L>
<L N="932">&thorn;at &yogh;e maye haue a suffisaunt pardonere</L>
<L>To assoile &yogh;ow in contre as .I. ride</L>
<L>For aventures whiche &thorn;at mai be-tide</L>
<L>For paraduenture &thorn;ere maie fal on or tuo<MILESTONE N="180b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="936">Doune of his hors and breke his nekke a two</L>
<L>Looke whiche a surte it is to &yogh;owe al</L>
<L>&THORN;at .I. am in &yogh;oure felischipe yfal</L>
<L>&THORN;at maie assoile &yogh;owe bo&thorn;e more and lasse</L>
<L N="940">Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e soule fro &thorn;e body passe</L>
<L>.I. rede &thorn;at oure oste schal beginne</L>
<L>For he is most envolupte in sinne</L>
<L>Comme&thorn; for&thorn;e sire oste and offer first anone</L>
<L N="944">And &thorn;ou schalt kisse re relikes euerychone</L>
<L>&YOGH;e for a grote vnbokel anone &thorn;i purce</L>
<L>Nay nay . haue .I. &thorn;an quod he cristes curce</L>
<L>Lat be quod he it schal not be so &thorn;eiche</L>
<L N="948">&thorn;ou woldests make me kisse &thorn;ine olde breche</L>
<L>And swere it were a relike of a seint</L>
<L>&THORN;ouhe it were wi&thorn; &thorn;i foundement depeint</L>
<L>Bot be cros &thorn;at seint Elyne fonde</L>
<L N="952">.I. wold .I. had &thorn;i coylons in myne honde</L>
<L>In stede of relikes o&thorn;er of seyntuarie</L>
<L>Let cutt hem of .I. wil &thorn;e helpe hem carie</L>
<L>Thei scholl be schryned in an hogges torde</L>
<L N="956">This pardoner answerd nouht a worde
<PB REF="00000483.tif" N="455"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="332"></L>
<L>So wro&thorn;e he was he nold no worde seie</L>
<L>Nowe quod oure oste .I. wil no longer pleie</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e no wi&thorn; none o&thorn;er angre man</L>
<L N="960">Bott riht anone &thorn;e wor&thorn;i knyht be-gan</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he sawhe &thorn;at al &thorn;e peple louhe</L>
<L>No more of &thorn;is for it is riht y-nouhe</L>
<L>Sire pardoner be meri and glad of chere</L>
<L N="964">And &yogh;e sire oste &thorn;at bene to me so dere</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;owe &thorn;at &yogh;e kisse &thorn;e pardonere</L>
<L>And pardoner .I. praie &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou drau &thorn;e nere</L>
<L>And as we dide now late vs lauhe and pleie</L>
<L N="968">Anone &thorn;ei kisse and reden for&thorn;e &thorn;eire weye</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit fabula questoris;</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000484.tif" N="456">
<HEAD>Incipit prologus<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 180, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BOt &thorn;an spak oure Oste vnto Maister schipman</L>
<L>Maister quod he to vs summe tale tel &yogh;e can</L>
<L>Where-withe &yogh;e myht glad al &thorn;is company</L>
<L N="4">If it were &yogh;oure pleseinge .I. wote wele sekurlye</L>
<L>Sertes quod &thorn;is Schipman a tale .I. can tell</L>
<L>And &thorn;e[r]-fore herkene&thorn; hyderward how &thorn;at .I. wil spell</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit prologus.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000485.tif" N="457">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="168">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>B.</B> (&beta;. FRAGMENT III.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 4. THE SHIPMAN'S TALE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Incipit fabula Naute</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Marchant whilom dwelled att sein Denys<MILESTONE N="181a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That riche was for whiche men helde him wys.</L>
<L>A wif he hadde of excellent beaute.</L>
<L>And compinable and reuerent was sche</L>
<L>Whiche is a &thorn;inge &thorn;at cause&thorn; more dispence</L>
<L N="1196">Then wor&thorn;e is al &thorn;e chier and reuerence.</L>
<L>That men haue done att festes or at daunces</L>
<L>Suche Salutacions and countenaunces</L>
<L>Passe&thorn; as do&thorn;e &thorn;e schadowe on a wall</L>
<L N="1200">Bot woo is him &thorn;at paie most for all</L>
<L>The Cely husbonde algates he must paye</L>
<L>He moste vs clo&thorn;e and vs araie</L>
<L>Al for his owen wo[r]schip richelye</L>
<L N="1204">In whiche araie we dauncen Iolylye</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he nouht maie paraduenture</L>
<L>Or elles luste no suche to endure</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;enke&thorn; it is waste and yloste</L>
<L N="1208">&thorn;at mot ano&thorn;ere payen for owre coste</L>
<L>Or leue vs golde and &thorn;at is parilous</L>
<L>This noble marchant helde a noble hous</L>
<L>ffor whiche he had al daye grete repaire</L>
<L N="1212">ffor his largenesse and for his wif was faire</L>
<L>That wonder is? bot herkene&thorn; to my tale</L>
<L>Amonges al his gestes grete and smale</L>
<L>Ther was a monke a faire man and a bolde</L>
<L N="1216">.I. trowe . a &thorn;erte wynter he was of olde</L>
<L>That euere in one was draweinge to &thorn;e place</L>
<L>This &yogh;onge monke &thorn;at was so faire of face
<PB REF="00000486.tif" N="458"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="169"></L>
<L>Aqweynted was so wi&thorn; &thorn;is goodman</L>
<L N="1220">Se&thorn;en &thorn;att her first knowleche began</L>
<L>That in his hous as famylier was he</L>
<L>As it is possible any frende to be</L>
<L>And for als muchel as &thorn;e good manne.</L>
<L N="1224">And eke &thorn;is monke of whiche &thorn;at .I. be-ganne.</L>
<L>Were bo&thorn;e tuo borne in o vilage</L>
<L>&thorn;e monke him clayme as for cosinage</L>
<L>And he a&yogh;eine he sei&thorn; nouht ones naye</L>
<L N="1228">Bot was as glad &thorn;ere-of as foule of daye</L>
<L>ffor to his herte it was a grete plesaunce</L>
<L>Thus bene &thorn;ei knytt wi&thorn; eterne alliaunce</L>
<L>And ilke of hem gan o&thorn;er to assure</L>
<L N="1232">Of bro&thorn;erhed whiles &thorn;at &thorn;eire lyue maie endure.</L>
<L>ffre was dan Iohn and namely of dispense<MILESTONE N="181b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As in &thorn;at hous and ful of diligence</L>
<L>To do plasance and also grete Costage</L>
<L N="1236">He nouht for&yogh;ate to &yogh;eue &thorn;e lest page</L>
<L>In al &thorn;at hous bot after here degre</L>
<L>He &yogh;af &thorn;e lorde and se&thorn;en al &thorn;e meyne</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he cam sum maner honest &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="1240">ffor whiche &thorn;ei were al gladd of his comynge</L>
<L>As foule is feine whan sonne vprise&thorn;</L>
<L>No more of &thorn;is as now for it suffise&thorn;</L>
<L>Bot so be-fel &thorn;is marchant vpon a daie</L>
<L N="1244">Schope him to make rede his araie</L>
<L>Towarde &thorn;e toune of Brugges for to fare</L>
<L>To byen &thorn;ere a porcion of ware</L>
<L>ffor whiche he ha&thorn;e to parische sent anone</L>
<L N="1248">A messagier and preide ha&thorn;e dan Iohn</L>
<L>Thas he scholde come to seinte Denys and pleye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him and wi&thorn; his wif a dai or tweye</L>
<L>Are he to brugges wente in al wise</L>
<L N="1252">&thorn;is noble Monke of whiche .I. &yogh;owe deuise</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; of his Abbot as him lust lycenc</L>
<L>Be-cause he was a man of hihe prudence
<PB REF="00000487.tif" N="459"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="170"></L>
<L>And eke an Oficere oute for to ride</L>
<L N="1256">To se here graunges and her bernes wide</L>
<L>And vnto Seint Denys he come&thorn; anone</L>
<L>Who was so welcom as my lorde dan Iohne</L>
<L>Oure dere Cosyn ful of Curtasye</L>
<L N="1260">With him brouht a Iubbe of Maluese</L>
<L>And eke ano&thorn;er ful of goode vernage</L>
<L>And volatile as aie was his vsage</L>
<L>And &thorn;us .I. lete hem ete and dringe and pleie</L>
<L N="1264">&thorn;is marchant and his monke a daie or tweie</L>
<L>The &thorn;red daie &thorn;is Marchant vp he rise&thorn;</L>
<L>And on his nedes sadly him a-vise&thorn;</L>
<L>And vp in-to his counte hous go&thorn;e he</L>
<L N="1268">To reken wi&thorn; him-self wel maie be</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilke &yogh;ere howe &thorn;at wi&thorn; him stode</L>
<L>And howe &thorn;at he despended had his goode</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he encresed were or none</L>
<L N="1272">His bokes and his bagges many one</L>
<L>He ley&thorn;e be-for him on his counteingborde</L>
<L>fful riche was his tresore and his horde</L>
<L>ffor whiche ful fast his counterhous dore he schette<MILESTONE N="182a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1276">And eke he nolde no man schold him lette</L>
<L>Of his accomptes for &thorn;e mene time</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he sitte til it was passed prime</L>
<L>Dan Iohn was resen in &thorn;e morne also</L>
<L N="1280">And in gardyn wakke&thorn; to and fro</L>
<L>And ha&thorn;e his &thorn;inges seide deuoutly</L>
<L>This good wif cam walkinge priuely</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e Gardeine &thorn;er he walke&thorn; soft</L>
<L N="1284">And him Salue&thorn; as sche ha&thorn; done oft</L>
<L>A maiden childe cam in hire compaignie</L>
<L>Whiche att hir lust maie gouerne and gye</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;it vnder &thorn;e &yogh;erde was &thorn;e maide</L>
<L N="1288">O dere Cosyn myne dan Iohn sche saide</L>
<L>What eyley&thorn;e &yogh;owe so ra&thorn;e to rise</L>
<L>Nece quod he hit ouht ynouhe suffise
<PB REF="00000488.tif" N="460"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="171"></L>
<L>.V. houres to slepe on a nyht</L>
<L N="1292">Bot it were for an olde palled knyht</L>
<L>As ben &thorn;es wedded men &thorn;at ly and dare</L>
<L>As in a forme sitt alweie an hare</L>
<L>Were al for-strauht wi&thorn; houndes grete and smale</L>
<L N="1296">Bot dere nece whi be &yogh;e so pale</L>
<L>.I. trowe certes &thorn;at oure good man</L>
<L>Ha&thorn;e &yogh;owe labourde se&thorn;en &thorn;e niht be-gan</L>
<L>That &yogh;owe were nede to resten hastelye</L>
<L N="1300">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde he louhe ful merelye</L>
<L>And of owen &thorn;ouht he wex rede</L>
<L>&THORN;is faire wif gan to sake hire hede</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;us? &yogh;e god wote al quod sche</L>
<L N="1304">Nay cosyne myne it stant nouht so wi&thorn; me</L>
<L>ffor be &thorn;at god &thorn;at &yogh;af me soule and life</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e reme of fraunce is &thorn;ere no wif</L>
<L>&thorn;at lesse lust ha&thorn;e to &thorn;at sori pleie</L>
<L N="1308">ffor .I. maie singe alace and weilewaie</L>
<L>&thorn;at .I. was borne bot to no whight quod sche</L>
<L>Dare .I. nouht tell howe it stant wi&thorn; me</L>
<L>Wherefore .I. &thorn;enke oute of &thorn;is londe to wende</L>
<L N="1312">Or elles of my-selfe to make an ende</L>
<L>So fol am .I. of drede and of care</L>
<L>This monke be-gan vpon &thorn;is wif to stare</L>
<L>And seide alace my nece god for-bede</L>
<L N="1316">That &yogh;e for any sorwe or for any drede</L>
<L>ffor-do &yogh;owre self. bot telle&thorn; for&thorn;e &yogh;oure greffe<MILESTONE N="182b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Paraduenture .I. maie in &yogh;oure meschieffe</L>
<L>Counsel or helpe and &thorn;er-fore telle&thorn; me</L>
<L N="1320">All &yogh;owre annoy&yogh;e for it schall be secre</L>
<L>ffor on my portos .I. make an oothe</L>
<L>&thorn;att neuer in my lif for leue ne lothe</L>
<L>Ne schal .I. of no counsel &yogh;owe be-wreye</L>
<L N="1324">The same a&yogh;eine to &yogh;owe .I. seye</L>
<L>Be god and be &thorn;is portos .I. swere</L>
<L>&THORN;ouhe men wolde me al to peces tere
<PB REF="00000489.tif" N="461"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="172"></L>
<L>Ne schal .I. neuere for to go in-to hell</L>
<L N="1328">Be-wreye a worde of &thorn;inge &thorn;at me tell</L>
<L>Not for no Cosinage ne alliance</L>
<L>Bot verreyly for loue and affiance</L>
<L>Thus bue &thorn;e sworne and here vpon kist</L>
<L N="1332">And ekke of hem tolde o&thorn;ere what hem lust</L>
<L>Cosine quod sche if .I. had a space</L>
<L>As .I. haue none and namely in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>&thorn;an wolde .I. tel a legent of my lyue</L>
<L N="1336">What I haue sufferd se&thorn;en .I. was a wive</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;e myne husbande al&thorn;eihe he be &yogh;oure cosine</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;is monke be god and be seint Martine</L>
<L>He nys no more cosine vn-to me</L>
<L N="1340">Than is &thorn;e leue &thorn;at hange&thorn; on &thorn;is tre</L>
<L>.I. clepe him so be seinte denise in fraunce</L>
<L>To haue &thorn;e mor cause of acqueyntance</L>
<L>Of &yogh;owe whiche .I. haue loued specialye</L>
<L N="1344">Abouen al wemmen sekurlye</L>
<L>This swere .I. nowe on my professioun</L>
<L>Telle&thorn; &yogh;oure greue lest &thorn;at he come a-doun</L>
<L>And haste&thorn; &yogh;owe and go &yogh;oure weie anone</L>
<L N="1348">My dere loue quod sche o Doun Iohn</L>
<L>fful leue me were &thorn;is counsel to hide</L>
<L>Bot out it mot it maie longer abide</L>
<L>Myne husband is to me &thorn;e werst man</L>
<L N="1352">&THORN;at euer was se&thorn;en &thorn;e werlde began</L>
<L>Bot se&thorn;en .I. am a wif it sitte nouht me</L>
<L>To telle no wyght of oure priuete</L>
<L>Ney&thorn;er a bedde ne in none o&thorn;er place</L>
<L N="1356">God schelde .I. scholde tel it for his grace</L>
<L>A wif ne schal nou&yogh;t seine of hire husbande</L>
<L>Bot all honoure as .I. kan vnder-stonde.</L>
<L>Saue vn-to &yogh;owe &thorn;us muche tel .I. schall<MILESTONE N="183a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1360">As helpe me god he ne is nouht wor&thorn;e att all</L>
<L>In no degre &thorn;e value of a flie</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it me greue&thorn; most his Nygardrye
<PB REF="00000490.tif" N="462"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="173"></L>
<L>And wele &yogh;e wote &thorn;at wemmen naturellye</L>
<L N="1364">Desiren &thorn;inges seven as wel as .I.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey wolden &thorn;at husbondes scholden be</L>
<L>Hardy. and wyse. riche. and &thorn;er-to fre</L>
<L>And buxum to his wif and fresche a bedde</L>
<L N="1368">Bot be &thorn;at ilke lorde &thorn;at for vs bledde</L>
<L>ffor his honour miself to araie</L>
<L>A sonday next .I. must paye</L>
<L>And hundre&thorn; frankes or elles .I. am lorne</L>
<L N="1372">&YOGH;it were me leuer &thorn;at .I. were vnborne</L>
<L>The me were done a sclander or velanye</L>
<L>And if myn husbonde eke myht a-spye</L>
<L>.I. were bot lost and &thorn;erefore .I. &yogh;owe preye</L>
<L N="1376">Lene me &thorn;is somme and elles mot .I. deye</L>
<L>Dan Iohn .I. seie lene me &thorn;is hundre&thorn; frankes</L>
<L>Parde .I. wil nouht fail &thorn;e my &thorn;onkes</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &yogh;ow lust to do &thorn;at .I. &yogh;owe preye</L>
<L N="1380">ffor att a certeyne daye .I. wil &yogh;owe peye</L>
<L>And do to &yogh;owe what plesance and seruise</L>
<L>&THORN;at .I. maie do riht as &yogh;owe lost deuise</L>
<L>And bot .I. do god take on me vengeaunce</L>
<L N="1384">As foule as hadde Genylon of fraunce</L>
<L>This gentil monke ansewerd in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Nowe trewly myne owen ladi dere</L>
<L>.I. haue quod he on &yogh;owe so grete a row&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1388">&THORN;at .I. &yogh;owe swere and pliht &yogh;owe my trou&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at whan &yogh;oure husbond is to flaundres fare</L>
<L>.I. wil deliuer &yogh;owe owet of &thorn;is werldes care</L>
<L>ffor .I. wil bringen &yogh;owe an hundre&thorn; frankes</L>
<L N="1392">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at he cauht hire be &thorn;e schankes</L>
<L>And here enbraced harde and kissed ofte</L>
<L>Go&thorn;e nowe &yogh;oure weie quod he al stil and soft</L>
<L>And latt us deyne as sone as euer we maie</L>
<L N="1396">ffor be my chilinder it is prime of &thorn;e daie</L>
<L>Go&thorn;e nowe and be as trewe as .I. schal be</L>
<L>Nowe elles god for-bede sir quod sche
<PB REF="00000491.tif" N="463"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="174"></L>
<L>And for&thorn;e sche go&thorn;e as gelous as a pye</L>
<L N="1400">And badde &thorn;e cokes &thorn;at &thorn;ei scholde hem hihe</L>
<L>So &thorn;at men myht dyne and &thorn;at anone<MILESTONE N="183b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vp to hir husbond is &thorn;is wif gone</L>
<L>And knokke&thorn; att his Counter boldely</L>
<L N="1404">Que la quod he peter it am .I.</L>
<L>Quod sche whatte howe longe wil &yogh;e fast</L>
<L>Howe longe time wil &yogh;e reken and kast</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure sommes &yogh;oure bokes and &yogh;oure &thorn;inges</L>
<L N="1408">The deuel haue part on al suche rekenynges</L>
<L>&YOGH;e haue y-nowhe parde of goddes sonde</L>
<L>Comme doune to daie and latte &yogh;oure bagge stonde</L>
<L>Ne be &yogh;e nouht aschamed &thorn;a[t] dan Iohn</L>
<L N="1412">Schal fastinge al &thorn;is daye Elenge gone</L>
<L>What latt vs here Masse go we dyne</L>
<L>Wif quod &thorn;is man litel canstowe deuyne</L>
<L>The Corious besines &thorn;at we haue</L>
<L N="1416">ffor of vs chapmen so god me saue</L>
<L>And be &thorn;at lorde &thorn;at called is seinte Ive</L>
<L>Scarsely amonges tuelue tweyne schollen &thorn;riue</L>
<L>Continuly lasteynge vnto oure age</L>
<L N="1420">We maye wele make chiere and good visag</L>
<L>And driue for&thorn;e &thorn;e werld as it maie be</L>
<L>And kepen oure estate in priuete</L>
<L>Til we be dede or elles &thorn;at we pleie</L>
<L N="1424">On pilgrenage or gone out of &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-fore haue .I. grete necessite</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;is qweinte werlde to avise me</L>
<L>ffor euer more we must stonde in drede</L>
<L N="1428">Of happe and fortune in myne chapmanhede</L>
<L>To flandres wil .I. go to morwe att daye</L>
<L>And Come a&yogh;eine as sone as euer y maye</L>
<L>ffor whiche my dere wif .I. &thorn;e be-seke</L>
<L N="1432">As be to euery wyht buxum and meke</L>
<L>And for to kepe oure goode be curiouse</L>
<L>And honestly gouerne wele oure house
<PB REF="00000492.tif" N="464"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="175"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast ynouhe in euery manere wyse</L>
<L N="1436">&THORN;at to a &thorn;refte husbonde may . suffise</L>
<L>&THORN;e lakke&thorn; none array . ne no vitaile</L>
<L>Of siluer in &thorn;i purce &thorn;ou maist nou&yogh;ht faile</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde his counter dore he schett</L>
<L N="1440">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hastely a messe was &thorn;ere seide</L>
<L>And spedely &thorn;e tables wer ylaide</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e dener fast &thorn;ei hem spedde</L>
<L N="1444">And richely &thorn;is monke &thorn;is chapman fedde<MILESTONE N="184a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And after dener Dan Iohn Soburlye</L>
<L>This chapman tok aparte al priuely</L>
<L>He seide him &thorn;us Cosyn it stande&thorn; so</L>
<L N="1448">&THORN;at wele .I. se to brugges wil &yogh;e go</L>
<L>God and seinte Austine spede &yogh;owe and guyde</L>
<L>.I. praie &yogh;owe Cosin wisly &thorn;at &yogh;e ride</L>
<L>Gouerne&thorn; &yogh;owe also of &yogh;owre dyette</L>
<L N="1452">And temparaly. and namely in &thorn;is hete</L>
<L>Be-tuex vx tuo nede&thorn; no strange fare</L>
<L>ffare wel cosin god schilde &yogh;owe fro care</L>
<L>If any &thorn;inge &thorn;ere be be daye or be nyht</L>
<L N="1456">If it lye in my power and my myht</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e me wil command in any wyse</L>
<L>It shal be done riht as &yogh;e wil devise</L>
<L>O &thorn;inge er &thorn;at &yogh;e go if &thorn;at it maie be</L>
<L N="1460">.I. wolde praie &yogh;ow for to lene me</L>
<L>An .C. frankes for a weke or tweyne</L>
<L>ffor certeine bestes &thorn;at .I. most bye</L>
<L>To store wi&thorn; a palas &thorn;at is owres</L>
<L N="1464">God helpe me so .I. wolde &thorn;at it were &yogh;oures</L>
<L>.I. schal nou&yogh;ht fail surely of my daie</L>
<L>Note for .a .M. frankes a myle waye</L>
<L>Bot lat &thorn;is &thorn;inge be secre .I. &yogh;owe preie</L>
<L N="1468">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And fare nowe wele myne owen Cosine dere</L>
<L>Graunt Mercy of &yogh;oure cost and of &yogh;oure chere
<PB REF="00000493.tif" N="465"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="176"></L>
<L>This noble Marchant gentilli anone</L>
<L N="1472">Ansewarde and seide o kosine Dan Iohne.</L>
<L>Nowe sekerly &thorn;is is a small request</L>
<L>Mi golde is &yogh;oures whan &thorn;at &yogh;ou lest</L>
<L>And Nouht onely my golde bot my Chaffare</L>
<L N="1476">Take&thorn; what &yogh;owe lest god scheld &thorn;at &yogh;e spare</L>
<L>Bot o &thorn;inge is &yogh;e knowe it wele y-nowhe</L>
<L>Of chappemen &thorn;at her mony is hir plouhe</L>
<L>We may creance whiles we haue a name</L>
<L N="1480">Bott goldelesse for to be is no game</L>
<L>Paye&thorn;e it a&yogh;eine whan it li&thorn;e in &yogh;oure ese</L>
<L>After my myht ful feine wod .I. &yogh;ow plese</L>
<L>&THORN;es .C. frankes he fette for&thorn; anone</L>
<L N="1484">And priuely he toke it to dan Iohn</L>
<L>No wyght of al &thorn;is werlde ne wiste of &thorn;is lone</L>
<L>Saueynge &thorn;is Marchant and dan Iohn alone.</L>
<L>Thei dranken and Romen<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> Roiuen]</NOTE> and pleye<MILESTONE N="184b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1488">Til &thorn;at Dan Iohn Ride&thorn; to his Abbei</L>
<L>The morwe cam and for&thorn;e &thorn;is marchant Ride&thorn;</L>
<L>To flanders-ward his prentis wele him gyde&thorn;</L>
<L>Til he cam in-to brugge merily.</L>
<L N="1492">Now go-&thorn;e &thorn;is marchant fast and besily</L>
<L>Aboute his nedes and bi&thorn;e and creaunce&thorn;</L>
<L>He ney&thorn;er pley&thorn;e att &thorn;e dyes ne daunce&thorn;</L>
<L>Bot as a Marchant schortly for to tell</L>
<L N="1496">He lete&thorn; his lyf and &thorn;ere .I. late him duell</L>
<L>The sonday next &thorn;is marschant was agone</L>
<L>To seinte Denys y-commen was Dan Ione</L>
<L>Whiche crowe and berde fresche and newe schaue</L>
<L N="1500">In al &thorn;e house &thorn;er nas so litel a knaue</L>
<L>Ne no wyght elles &thorn;at he nas feyne</L>
<L>ffor my lorde Dan Iohne was comen a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>And schortly to her pointe for to gone</L>
<L N="1504">&THORN;is faire wif accorde&thorn; to dan Iohn</L>
<L>And for &thorn;is .C. frankes he scholde al nyht</L>
<L>Haue hire in his armes bolte vpriht
<PB REF="00000494.tif" N="466"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="177"></L>
<L>And &thorn;is accorde parformed was in dede</L>
<L N="1508">In mer&thorn;e al nyht a besi lif &thorn;ei lede</L>
<L>Til it was daie &thorn;at Dan Iohn went his weie</L>
<L>And badde &thorn;e meny&yogh;e fare wele and haue good daie</L>
<L>ffor none of heme no wight in &thorn;e toune</L>
<L N="1512">Ha&thorn;e of dan Iohn riht none suspecione</L>
<L>And for&thorn;e he ride&thorn; home to his abbeie</L>
<L>Or wher him list no more of him .I. seye</L>
<L>This Marchant whan &thorn;at ended was &thorn;e faire</L>
<L N="1516">To seint Denyse he gan to repaire</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his wif he make&thorn; fest and chere</L>
<L>And telle&thorn; hire &thorn;at chaffer is so dere</L>
<L>&THORN;at nedes most he maake a cheuesance</L>
<L N="1520">ffor he was bounden in a requenysance</L>
<L>To paye .xx. M. schildes anone</L>
<L>ffor whiche &thorn;is marchant is wont to gone</L>
<L>To borwe of certeine frendes &thorn;at he hadde</L>
<L N="1524">A certeine and somme wi&thorn; him he ladde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he was comen into &thorn;e toune</L>
<L>ffor grete chere and grete affeccione</L>
<L>Vn-to Dan Iohn him first go&thorn;e to pleie</L>
<L N="1528">Nouht for to borwe of him no moneye</L>
<L>Bot for [to] wite and see of his welfare<MILESTONE N="185a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And for to tellen him of his chaffare</L>
<L>As frendes done whan &thorn;ei be mette in fere</L>
<L N="1532">Dan Iohn. him Make&thorn; fest and mery chiere</L>
<L>And him tolde a&yogh;eine ful specially</L>
<L>Howe he hadde bouht ful wele and graciously</L>
<L>Thonked he god al hole his Marchandise</L>
<L N="1536">Saue &thorn;at he must in al maner wise</L>
<L>Maken a cheuesans as for his best</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he scholde be in Ioye and rest</L>
<L>Dan. Anseward certes .I. am feyne</L>
<L N="1540">&THORN;at &yogh;e in hele be comme home a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at .I. were riche as haue .I. blisse</L>
<L>Off .xx. M. scheldes schold &yogh;e nouht mysse
<PB REF="00000495.tif" N="467"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="178"></L>
<L>ffor. &yogh;e so kindely &thorn;is o&thorn;ere daie</L>
<L N="1544">Lent me gold and as .I. kan. and maie</L>
<L>.I. &thorn;onke &yogh;owe be god and be seint Iame</L>
<L>Bot. na&thorn;eles .I. toke vn-to owre dame</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure wif att home &thorn;e same golde a&yogh;eine</L>
<L N="1548">Vpon &yogh;oure benche sche woote. it wele certeine</L>
<L>Be certeyne tokenes &thorn;at .I. can hire tell</L>
<L>Nowe be &yogh;oure leue .I. maie no longer duell</L>
<L>Oure Abbote will oute of &thorn;is toune anone</L>
<L N="1552">And on his company most .I. gone</L>
<L>Grete wele oure dame myne owen nece swete</L>
<L>And faire wele dere cosine til we mete</L>
<L>This Marchant wi&thorn; &thorn;at was ful war and wise</L>
<L N="1556">Creanced ha&thorn;e and eke paide in parisshe</L>
<L>To certeyne lombardes rede in hire hande</L>
<L>The summe of golde and gatte of hem &thorn;e bande</L>
<L>And home he go&thorn;e mery as a papenioye</L>
<L N="1560">ffor wele he knewe he stode in suche araie</L>
<L>&thorn;at nedes most he winne in suche a viage</L>
<L>A .M. frankes aboue al his costage</L>
<L>It wif ful rede mett him att &thorn;e gate</L>
<L N="1564">As sche was wonte of olde vsage algate</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at nyht in mer&thorn;e &thorn;ei be sette</L>
<L>ffor he was riche and clerely oute of dette</L>
<L>Whane it was daye &thorn;is Marchant gan embrace</L>
<L N="1568">His wife al newe and kist hir on hire face</L>
<L>And vpe he go&thorn;e and make&thorn;e it wonder touhe</L>
<L>No more quod sche be god &yogh;e haue ynowhe.</L>
<L>And wantonly a&yogh;eine wi&thorn; him sche pleide<MILESTONE N="185b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1572">Til att &thorn;e last &thorn;is Marchant seide</L>
<L>Be god quod he .I. am a litel wro&thorn;e</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &yogh;owe my wif al-&thorn;ouhe it be me lo&thorn;e</L>
<L>And wote &yogh;e whye be god as &thorn;at .I. gesse</L>
<L N="1576">ffor &yogh;e haue maade a maner strangenesse</L>
<L>Be-twex me and my Cosyne Dan Iohn</L>
<L>&YOGH;e scholde haue warned me ar .I. hadde gone
<PB REF="00000496.tif" N="468"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="179"></L>
<L>That he had &yogh;owe an .C. frankes payede</L>
<L N="1580">Be rede token and he him helde yuel apaide</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at .I. to him spake of cheuesaunce</L>
<L>Me semed soo as be his countenaunce</L>
<L>Bot na&thorn;eles be god heuen kinge</L>
<L N="1584">.I. &thorn;ouht nouht to axe of him no &thorn;inge</L>
<L>.I. praie &thorn;e wif ne do no more soo</L>
<L>Til me alweie are &thorn;at .I. fro &thorn;e goo</L>
<L>If any dettour ha&thorn;e in myne absence</L>
<L N="1588">Ypayde &thorn;e lest &thorn;oruhe &thorn;i necligence</L>
<L>I myht him axe a &thorn;inge &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e paide</L>
<L>This wif was nouht aferde ne affraide</L>
<L>But boldely sche seide and &thorn;at anone</L>
<L N="1592">Mary. y dify &thorn;at fals monke dan Ione</L>
<L>.I. kepe nouht of his tokenes neuer a dele</L>
<L>He toke me certeine golde &thorn;is wote .I. wele</L>
<L>&THORN;at ivel &thorn;edom on his monkes snowte</L>
<L N="1596">ffor god it wote .I. wende wi&thorn;-outen doute</L>
<L>&THORN;at he it had y&yogh;eue me be cause of &yogh;owe</L>
<L>To do &thorn;ere-wi&thorn;e myn honure and my prowe</L>
<L>ffor Cosinage eke and for bele chere</L>
<L N="1600">&THORN;at he ha&thorn; hadde ful often time here</L>
<L>Bot se&thorn;en .I. see .I. stonde in suche disioynte</L>
<L>.I. wil answere &yogh;oue to &thorn;e poynte</L>
<L>&YOGH;e haue mo slakker dettores &thorn;an am .I.</L>
<L N="1604">ffor .I. wil paie &yogh;owe wele and redelye</L>
<L>ffro daye to day and if so be. &thorn;at .I. faile</L>
<L>.I. am &yogh;oure wif score it on my taile</L>
<L>And .I. schal paie as sone as euer y maie</L>
<L N="1608">ffor be my trou&thorn;e .I. haue on myne araye</L>
<L>And nouht on waste bestouede euerydele</L>
<L>And for .I. haue bestowed it so wele</L>
<L>To &yogh;oure honoure for goddes sake .I. saie</L>
<L N="1612">As be nouht wro&thorn;e bot lat vs hauhe and pleye.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schollen my. Ioly body haue to wedde<MILESTONE N="186a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Be godde .I. wil nouht paie &yogh;owe bot in bedde
<PB REF="00000497.tif" N="469"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="180"></L>
<L>ffor-&yogh;eue it me myne owen spouse dere</L>
<L N="1616">Turne&thorn;e hider-warde and make&thorn; better chiere</L>
<L>This Marchant seyhe &thorn;er was no better remedye</L>
<L>And for to chide it nere bot folye</L>
<L>Se&thorn;en &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;inge maie nouht amended be</L>
<L N="1620">Nowe wif he seide and .I. for-&yogh;eue it &thorn;e</L>
<L>Bot be &thorn;i life ne be no more so large</L>
<L>Kepe bette my goode &thorn;is &yogh;eue .I. &thorn;e in charge</L>
<L>Thus ende&thorn; nowe my tale and god vs sende</L>
<L N="1624">Toyleynge ynouhe vnto oure lyues ende</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit fabula Naute.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000498.tif" N="470">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="181">
<HEAD>Incipit prologus Priorisse<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 186</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wele saide be corpus dampnus seide oure Oste</L>
<L>Nowe longe mot &thorn;ou seile be &thorn;is coste</L>
<L>Sire gentil Maister gentil marinere</L>
<L N="1628">God &yogh;eue &thorn;e monke a .M. last quade &yogh;ere</L>
<L>A ha felaus be&thorn;e war of suche a Iape</L>
<L>The monke put in &thorn;e mannes hode an ape</L>
<L>And in his wives eke be seint Austine</L>
<L N="1632">Draue&thorn; no monkes more vnto &yogh;oure inne</L>
<L>Bot nowe passe ouere &amp; lat vs seke aboute</L>
<L>Who schal nowe telle first of al &thorn;is route</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er tale and wi&thorn; &thorn;at worde he seide</L>
<L N="1636">As curteysly as it hadde bue a maide</L>
<L>My lady Prioresse be &yogh;oure leue</L>
<L>So &thorn;at .I. wist .I. scholde &yogh;ow not greue</L>
<L>.I. wolde deme &thorn;at &yogh;e telle scholde</L>
<L N="1640">A tale next if so were &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde</L>
<L>Now wil &yogh;e vouche-saue my lady dere</L>
<L>Gladly quod sche and seide in &thorn;is manere
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000499.tif" N="471"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="182">
<HEAD>Incipit Priorisse ffabula<NOTE PLACE="head">[No breaks in the MS between the stanzas.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[The Prologue.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Olorde oure lorde &thorn;i name howe mervelouse</L>
<L>Is in &thorn;is large werlde y-spredde quod sche</L>
<L>ffor nou&yogh;t onely &thorn;i loude preciouse</L>
<L N="1646">Parformed is be men of dignite</L>
<L>Bot be &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of childern &thorn;i bounte</L>
<L>Parformed is for on oure breste soukeinge</L>
<L N="1649">Some time schewen &thorn;ei &thorn;ine heriinge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Where-fore in loude as .I. kan beste or maie</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e and of &thorn;e white lylye floure</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e bare and is a maide alweie</L>
<L N="1653">To tel a storye .I. wil do my labour<MILESTONE N="186b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nouhte &thorn;at .I. maie encrese hir honour</L>
<L>ffor sche hir self is honour and &thorn;er-to Rote</L>
<L N="1656">Of bounte next hire sonne of soules bote</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O moder maide o maide moder fre</L>
<L>O busche vnbernde bernynge in Moyses siht</L>
<L>&THORN;at rauisched doune fro &thorn;e deite</L>
<L N="1660">&THORN;oruhe &thorn;ine humblesse &thorn;e gost &thorn;at in &thorn;e aliht</L>
<L>Of whos verteu whan he in &thorn;ine hert aliht</L>
<L>Conceyued was &thorn;e faders Sapiens</L>
<L N="1663">Helpe me to tel it in &thorn;i reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lady &thorn;ine bounte and &thorn;ine Magnificence</L>
<L>&THORN;ine vertue and &thorn;i grete humilite</L>
<L>&THORN;ere maie no tunge expresse in no science</L>
<L N="1667">ffor sum time ladi ar men preye to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Thou gost be-forne of &thorn;ine benyngnyte</L>
<L>And getest vs &thorn;e liht &thorn;oruhe &thorn;i praiere</L>
<L N="1670">To guyden vs vnto &thorn;i son so clere
<PB REF="00000500.tif" N="472"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="183"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; My konnynge is to wayke o blisful qweene</L>
<L>ffor to declare &thorn;i grete wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at .I. ne may &thorn;e weyht nouht sustene</L>
<L N="1674">Bot as a childe of twelmo&thorn;e age or lesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at can vnne&thorn; any worde expresse</L>
<L>Riht so fare .I. and &thorn;erefore .I. &yogh;owe preye</L>
<L N="1677">Gyde&thorn; my songe &thorn;at .I. schal of &yogh;owe seye</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther was a Ce in a grete Cite</L>
<L>Amonge cristen folk and Iewre</L>
<L>Su[s]teynde be a lorde of &thorn;at contre</L>
<L N="1681">ffor foule vser and locre of velany</L>
<L>Hatteful to criste and to his compaignye</L>
<L>And &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e strete men miht ride or wende</L>
<L N="1684">ffor it was and open at euere ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A litel folke of cristen folke &thorn;ere stode</L>
<L>Doune att &thorn;e fer&thorn;er ende in whiche &thorn;ere were</L>
<L>Childern an hepe commen of cristes blode</L>
<L N="1688">&thorn;at in &thorn;at scole &yogh;ere be &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Lerned &thorn;e doctrine as men vsed &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&thorn;is is to seie to singen and to rede</L>
<L N="1691">As smale childern done in here childehede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Amonge &thorn;es childern was a wedow sonne</L>
<L>A litel clergeon vj. &yogh;ere of age</L>
<L>&THORN;at daye be daie to scole was his wonne</L>
<L N="1695">And eke also where he sawe &thorn;e ymage<MILESTONE N="187a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of cristes modere had he in vsage</L>
<L>As him was tauht to knele adoune and saie</L>
<L N="1698">His Aue marie as he go&thorn;e be &thorn;e weie
<PB REF="00000501.tif" N="473"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="184"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thus ha&thorn;e &thorn;is wedowe hire lytel childe tauht</L>
<L>Oure blisfol lady cristes modere dere</L>
<L>To worschipe aie and he for-&yogh;at it nouht</L>
<L N="1702">ffe Cely childe wil al daie sone lere</L>
<L>Bot aie whan .y. remembre me on &thorn;is Matere</L>
<L>Seint Nicholas stant euer in my presence</L>
<L N="1705">ffor he so &yogh;onge to criste dide reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This childe is&middot;litel booke lerenynge</L>
<L>As he satt in &thorn;e scole att his primere</L>
<L>He alma redemptoris herd singe</L>
<L N="1709">As childern lerned hir Antiphanere</L>
<L>And as he durste he drouhe him nere and nere</L>
<L>And erkened aye &thorn;e wordes and &thorn;e note</L>
<L N="1712">Til he &thorn;e first vers cou&thorn; al be rote</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nouht wyste he what &thorn;e latine was to seie</L>
<L>ffor he so &yogh;onge and tender was of age</L>
<L>Bott on a daie his felawe he gan preie</L>
<L N="1716">To expounen &thorn;is songe in his langage</L>
<L>Or tellen whi &thorn;is songe was in vsage</L>
<L>This preide he him to constrewe and declare</L>
<L N="1719">fful oft time vpon his knees bare</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His felawe whiche &thorn;at elder was &thorn;an he</L>
<L>Ansewarde his &thorn;us &thorn;is songe .I. haue herd seie</L>
<L>Was maked of oure blissed ladi fre</L>
<L N="1723">Hir to salue and eke hir to preie</L>
<L>To bene oure helpe and socour whane we deye</L>
<L>.I. can no more expounde in &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L N="1726">.I. leren songe .I. can bott small gramere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And is &thorn;is songe maad in reuerence</L>
<L>Of cristes moder seide &thorn;is Innocent</L>
<L>Nowe certes .I. wil do my diligence</L>
<L N="1730">To konne it ar cristenmes be went
<PB REF="00000502.tif" N="474"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="185"></L>
<L>&THORN;ouhe &thorn;at .I. for my primer schal be schent</L>
<L>And schal be beten &thorn;ries in an oure</L>
<L N="1733">.I. will. it conne oure lady for to honoure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His felawe tauht him homward priuely</L>
<L>fro day to day til he cou&thorn;e it be rote.</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne he songe it wele and boldely</L>
<L N="1737">ffro warde to warde accordeinge to &thorn;e note<MILESTONE N="187b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;reys on a daye it passed &thorn;oruhe his &thorn;rote</L>
<L>To scoleward and homwarde when he went</L>
<L N="1740">On cristes moder sette was his entent</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; As I haue seide &thorn;oruhe oute &thorn;e Iewrye</L>
<L>This litel Childe as he cam to and fro</L>
<L>fful merily &thorn;an wolde singe and crye</L>
<L N="1744">On alma redemptoris euer mo</L>
<L>The swettnesse ha&thorn;e his herte perced so</L>
<L>Of cristes moder &thorn;at to hire to preie</L>
<L N="1747">He can nouht stinte of singinge be &thorn;e waie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Owre ferst foo &thorn;e serpent Satanas</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn;e in Iewes his waspes neste</L>
<L>Vp swal and seide O Ebrayke peple alas</L>
<L N="1751">Is &thorn;is a &thorn;inge to &yogh;owe &thorn;at is honest</L>
<L>&THORN;at suche a boye schal walken as him lest</L>
<L>In &yogh;oure and singen of suche sentence</L>
<L N="1754">Whiche is a&yogh;eines &yogh;oure lawes reuerence.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffro &thorn;ens for&thorn; &thorn;e Iewes han conspirede</L>
<L>This Innocent of &thorn;is werlde to chace</L>
<L>In homicide haunt &thorn;ei &thorn;ere-to huyrede</L>
<L N="1758">one That in a leye hadde a priue place</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e childe gan forby for to pace</L>
<L>This cursed Iewe him hente and helde fast</L>
<L N="1761">And kutte his &thorn;rote and in a pute him cast
<PB REF="00000503.tif" N="475"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="186"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I sey &thorn;at in a wardrope &thorn;ei him drewe</L>
<L>Where as &thorn;is Iewes purgen entraile</L>
<L>O cursed folke o herodes al newe</L>
<L N="1765">What may &yogh;oure yuel tent &yogh;oue availe</L>
<L>Morder wil oute certein. it wil nouht faile</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;ere honure of god schold sprede</L>
<L N="1768">The blode oute crie&thorn; on &yogh;oure cursed dede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O martire soundede to virginite</L>
<L>Now maiste &thorn;ou singe folowinge euer in on</L>
<L>The white lombe Celestial quod he</L>
<L N="1772">Of whiche &thorn;e grete euaungelist seint Iohn</L>
<L>In Pathmos wrote whiche sei&thorn;e &thorn;ei &thorn;at gone</L>
<L>Be-forne his lombe and singe a songe of new</L>
<L N="1775">Thet neuere flexly wemmen &thorn;ei knewe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This pouer wedowe wayte&thorn; al &thorn;at nyht</L>
<L>Affter &thorn;is litel Childe bot home cam he nouht</L>
<L>for whome alsoune as it was daies liht</L>
<L N="1779">Wi&thorn; face pale for drede and besy &thorn;ouht<MILESTONE N="188a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sche ha&thorn;e att scole and elles where him souht</L>
<L>Til finally sche gan so fer asspye</L>
<L N="1782">&THORN;at he was sey&yogh;en last in &thorn;e Iewrye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; moders pyte in hir breste enclosede</L>
<L>Sche go&thorn;e as sche were halue oute of mynde</L>
<L>To euery place where sche ha&thorn; supposed</L>
<L N="1786">Be liklyhed hire childe to finde</L>
<L>And euer on cr[i]stes moder meke and kinde</L>
<L>Sche cried and att &thorn;e last &thorn;us sche wrouht</L>
<L N="1789">Amonge &thorn;e cursed Iewes sche him souht</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sche freyne&thorn; and sche prei&thorn;e pitously</L>
<L>To euery Iewe &thorn;at duelled in &thorn;ilk place</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1793">Thei saiden naie bot ihesus of his grace
<PB REF="00000504.tif" N="476"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="187"></L>
<L>&YOGH;aue in her &thorn;ouht in wi&thorn; a litel space</L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;at place after her sonne sche cried</L>
<L N="1796">Thare he was cast in a putte be side</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O grete god &thorn;at parfourmed &thorn;in laude</L>
<L>Be mou&thorn;e of Innocence Lo here &thorn;i myht</L>
<L>This gemme of chastite &thorn;is emeraude</L>
<L N="1800">And eke of Marterdom &thorn;e ruby briht</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he wi&thorn; &thorn;rote ycorue leie vpriht</L>
<L>He Alma redemptoris gan to singe</L>
<L N="1803">So longe &thorn;at al &thorn;e place gan to ringe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The cristen folke &thorn;at &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e strete wente</L>
<L>In Camyne to wonderne of &thorn;is &thorn;inge</L>
<L>And hastely &thorn;ei for &thorn;e prouost sente</L>
<L N="1807">He cam anone wi&thorn;-outen any taryinge</L>
<L>And herie&thorn; crist &thorn;at is heuen kinge</L>
<L>And eke his moder honoure of mankinde</L>
<L N="1810">And after &thorn;e Iewes lete he binde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This childe wi&thorn; pitous lamentacioune</L>
<L>Vp taken singeinge his songe al weye</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; honoure of grete processioune</L>
<L N="1814">Thei Carien him to &thorn;e next Abbeye</L>
<L>His modere swoneynge be &thorn;e bere laye</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn; myhte &thorn;e peple &thorn;at was &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="1817">This newe rachel bringe fro his bere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; torment and wi&thorn; schamful de&thorn;e ilkone</L>
<L>This prouost do&thorn;e &thorn;es Iewes for to sterue</L>
<L>That of &thorn;is morder wist and &thorn;at anane</L>
<L N="1821">He nolde none suche cursednesse obsirue.</L>
<L>Euel schal haue &thorn;at yuel wil deserue<MILESTONE N="188b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>There-fore wi&thorn; wilde hors he did him drawe</L>
<L N="1824">And after &thorn;at he hinge him be &thorn;e lawe
<PB REF="00000505.tif" N="477"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="188"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vpon &thorn;is bere ay lye&thorn; &thorn;is Innocent</L>
<L>Be-forne &thorn;e chief autter whiles Masse last</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;e Abbot wi&thorn; his Couent</L>
<L N="1828">Hadde spedde hem for to burye him fast</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ei haly water on him cast</L>
<L>And &yogh;it spakke &thorn;e childe whan spreynt was &thorn;e holy water</L>
<L N="1831">And songe O alma redemptoris mater</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Abbot whiche &thorn;at was an holy man</L>
<L>As monkes be or elles ouhten to bee</L>
<L>&THORN;is &yogh;onge childe to coniure he gan</L>
<L N="1835">And seide o dere childe .I. hailese &thorn;e</L>
<L>Be vertue of &thorn;e holy Trinite</L>
<L>Tel me what is &thorn;i cause for to singe</L>
<L N="1838">Sethen &thorn;i &thorn;rote is kette att myn semeinge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; My &thorn;rot is cutte vnto my nekke bone</L>
<L>Saide &thorn;is childe and as be waie of kinde</L>
<L>.I. scholde haue deyed longe time agone</L>
<L N="1842">Bott ihesu criste as &yogh;e in bokes finde</L>
<L>Wil &thorn;at his glori last and bue in mynde</L>
<L>And for worschipe of his moder dere</L>
<L N="1845">&YOGH;ette may .I. singe O Alma loude and cle[re]</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This wel of Mercie cristes moder swete</L>
<L>.I. loued alweie as after my coninge</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at .I. my lif scholde lete</L>
<L N="1849">To me sche camme and badd me for to singe</L>
<L>&THORN;is Antime verrely in my mynde deynge</L>
<L>As &yogh;e haue herd and whan &thorn;at .I. had songe</L>
<L N="1852">Me &thorn;ouht sche laide a greyne vpon my tonge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wher-for .I. saie and singe most certeigne</L>
<L>In honour of cristes moder fre</L>
<L>Til of my tonge of taken is &thorn;e greyne</L>
<L N="1856">And after &thorn;at seide sche &thorn;us to me
<PB REF="00000506.tif" N="478"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="189"></L>
<L>My litel childe nowe wil .I. feche &thorn;e</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e greine. is fro &thorn;i tonge ytake</L>
<L N="1859">Be nouht agast .I. wil &thorn;e nouht for-saake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Holy monke &thorn;is Abbot him mene .I.</L>
<L>His tonge oute cauht and toke awey &thorn;e greyne</L>
<L>And he &yogh;af vpe &thorn;e gost ful softly</L>
<L N="1863">And whan &thorn;e Abbotte hadde &thorn;is wondere seyne</L>
<L>His salte teres strikled doune as reyne<MILESTONE N="189a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And gruffe he fel al platte to &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L N="1866">And still he laie as he had bene ybounde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The [Couent] Eke ley vpon &thorn;e pament</L>
<L>Wepeinge and heriinge Cristes moder dere</L>
<L>And after &thorn;ei rise and for&thorn;e been went</L>
<L N="1870">And toke aweie &thorn;is marter fro his bere</L>
<L>And in a tombe of Marble stones clere</L>
<L>Enclosen &thorn;ei his lytel body swete</L>
<L N="1873">There he is nowe god lene vs for to mete</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O &yogh;onge hewe of Lincolne sleyne also</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; cursed Iewes as it is notable</L>
<L>ffor it nys bot a litel while a-goo</L>
<L N="1877">Preye eke for vs we sinful folke vnstable</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his Mercie god so merciable</L>
<L>On vs his grete mercie multiplye</L>
<L N="1880">ffor reuerence of his moder Marye</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>Explicit fabula priorisse.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000507.tif" N="479">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="190">
<HEAD>Incipit prologus de Thopas.<NOTE PLACE="head">[No breaks in the MS between the stanzas.]</NOTE> <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="189"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan seide was &thorn;is tale euery man</L>
<L>As sober was &thorn;at wonder was to se</L>
<L>Ti &thorn;at oure Oste Iape beganne</L>
<L>And &thorn;an att erst he loked vpon me.<NOTE PLACE="marg">.id <I>est</I>. Chaucer</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide &thorn;us what man ert &thorn;ou quod he</L>
<L>Thou lokest as &thorn;ou woldest finde an hare</L>
<L N="1887">ffor euer vpon &thorn;e grounde .I. se &thorn;e stare</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Appr[o]che nere and loke merely</L>
<L>Nowe ware &yogh;owe sires and latt &thorn;is man haue place</L>
<L>He in &thorn;e waste is schapen as wele as .I.</L>
<L N="1891">This were a popet in armes to enbrace</L>
<L>ffor any womman smal and faire of face</L>
<L>He seme&thorn;e eluysche be his countenance</L>
<L N="1894">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Say nowe sumwhat se&thorn;en o&thorn;ere folke ha&thorn;e seide</L>
<L>Tel vs a tale of mer&thorn;e and &thorn;at anone</L>
<L>Oste quod .I. ne be nouht yuel apaide</L>
<L N="1898">ffor o&thorn;er tale certes can I. none</L>
<L>Bot of a rime .I. lerned longe agone</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at is good quod he shal we here</L>
<L N="1901">Summe deynte&thorn; &thorn;inge me &thorn;enke&thorn; be his chiere</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit prologus.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000508.tif" N="480">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="191">
<HEAD>Incipit fabula.<NOTE PLACE="head">[No breaks in the MS between the stanzas.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Fitte I.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LEstene&thorn;e lordes in goo[d] entent</L>
<L>And .I. wil tel verraiment</L>
<L N="1904">Of Miracle and of solace.</L>
<L>Al of a knyht was faire and gent<MILESTONE N="189b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In Bataile and in turnament</L>
<L N="1907">His name was. sir Thopas</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>.I.-borne he was in fer contre</L>
<L>In flaundre al be&yogh;onde &thorn;e see</L>
<L N="1910">Att Poperinge in &thorn;e place.</L>
<L>His fader was a man ful fre</L>
<L>And lord he was of &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L N="1913">As it was goddes grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Thopas was douhty swayne</L>
<L>White was his face as a peyndemayne</L>
<L N="1916">His lippes reede as roose</L>
<L>His rode is like scarlet in greyne</L>
<L>And .I. &yogh;owe tell in goode certeyne</L>
<L N="1919">He hadde a semely nose.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His here his berde was lyke safroun</L>
<L>&THORN;at to his gerdel rauht a doune</L>
<L N="1922">His schone of cordeweyne</L>
<L>Of brugges was his hosen broune</L>
<L>His roob was of Ciclatoune</L>
<L N="1925">&THORN;at cost mony a Iayne
<PB REF="00000509.tif" N="481"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="192"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He cou&thorn;e hunt att wilde dere</L>
<L>And ride on haukeinge for &thorn;e reuer</L>
<L N="1928">Wi&thorn; grey goshauke on honde</L>
<L>Therto he was a good archere</L>
<L>To werstelynge was &thorn;er none his pere</L>
<L N="1931">&THORN;ere any man scholde stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>fful mony a maide briht in boure</L>
<L>&THORN;ei morne for his paramoure</L>
<L N="1934">whane &thorn;ei were bette to slepe</L>
<L>Bot he was chast and no lichoure</L>
<L>As swete as is &thorn;e brembel floure</L>
