<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000518.tif" N="490"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="201">
<HEAD>Hic incipit fabula de Mellybeo per Chaucer.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[There are no line-numbers or breaks between the paragraphs in the MS. Tyrwhitt's breaks are kept here to prevent slight differences in the Six Texts throwing out many lines.]</P><P>[<I>Lansdowne MS</I> 851, <I>on leaf</I> 192.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<P>[2157] A &yogh;onge man whilom called Mellibe. Mihte. &amp; riche be-gate vpon his wyf. &thorn;at called was. Prudence. a douhter which was cleped Sapience.//</P>
<P>[2158] vpon a daie fel &thorn;at he for his disporte is went in to &thorn;e feldes him to pley; [2159] His wife &amp; eke his douhter ha&thorn;e he laft wi&thorn;-in his hous. of whiche &thorn;e dores were fast yschett. [2160] Foure of his olde foos haue it aspied. And setten ledders to &thorn;e walles of his hous. &amp; be &thorn;e wyndows entred [2161] &amp; beten his wif &amp; wounded his douhter with .v. mortale woundes in .v. sundre places [2162] &para; This is to seye. in here fete in hire hondes in hire eres &amp; in hire nose &amp; in hire mou&thorn;e. And laften hir for dede &amp; wenten here wey.</P>
<P>[2163] &para; Whan. Mellibeus returned was a&yogh;ein in to his hous. &amp; sauhe al &thorn;is meschief &para; He ylike a mad man rentynge his clo&thorn;es gan to wepe &amp; crye.</P>
<P>[2164] Prudens his. <MILESTONE N="192b" UNIT="folio">&para; Prudence his wif as ferfor&thorn; as sche dorst. be-souht him of his wepeinge for to stinte [2165] &para; Bot not for-&thorn;i he gan to wepe &amp; crie. euer &thorn;e lengeer &thorn;e more.</P>
<P>[2166] &thorn;is noble wif prudence remembre&thorn; her on &thorn;e sentence of Ouide. In his boke &thorn;at cleped is &thorn;e remedie of loue. where he sei&thorn;e. [2167] He is a. foole &thorn;at distorble&thorn; &thorn;e modere for to wepe in &thorn;e de&thorn;e of hir childe. til sche haue wepped hire fil as for certeine time. [2168] Than schal a man done his diligence wi&thorn; amyable wordes. hir to recomford. &amp; to preier her of 
<PB REF="00000519.tif" N="491"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="202"> here wepeinge for to stinte [2169] &para; For whiche resone &thorn;is noble prudence suffurd hir husbond for to wepe &amp; crie for a certeine space. [2170] &para; And whan sche sauhe hire time sche seide him in &thorn;is wyse /./ Alas my. lorde quod sche. whie maake &yogh;oure self for to be like a fole. [2171] &para; For sothe it aperteigne&thorn; not to a wiseman. To maak suche a sorwe [2172] &para; &YOGH;oure douhter wi&thorn; &thorn;e grace of god schal be warissched &amp; ascape &Verbar; [2173] And al were it so riht nowe sche were dede. &yogh;e ouht not as for hire de&thorn;e &yogh;oure self to destruye. [2174] &para; Senec.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Senec.</NOTE> sei&thorn;e. &thorn;e wiseman schal nouht tak to grete discomford for &thorn;e de&thorn;e of his childer. [2175] bot certe he scholde suffere it in pacience. As wele as he Abide&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> de&thorn; of his owen propre person.</P>
<P>[2176] &para; &THORN;is Millibeus ansewarde a-none &amp; seide &para; What man quod he scholde of his wepeinge stinte &thorn;at ha&thorn;e so grete a cause for to wepe. [2177] Ihesu criste owre lorde him self wepped for &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> de&thorn; of Lazarus his frende [2178] &para; Prudence anseward; certez wele .I. wote atempre wepeinge is nouht defended vnto him &thorn;at sorwful is a-monge folk of sorwe. Bot it is ra&thorn;er graunted him to wepe [2179] &para; &thorn;e Apostle paule vn to &thorn;e Romaynes write&thorn;. // Man schal reioyse wi&thorn; hem &thorn;at hem &thorn;at maken ioye; &amp; wepe wi&thorn; suche folke as wepen. [2180] &para; Bot &thorn;ouhe atempre wepeinge be graunted; Outrageous wepeinge certes is defended. [2181] &para; Mesurable wepeinge schold be considered after &thorn;e lore &thorn;at teche&thorn; vs Senec [2182] &para; Whan &thorn;at &thorn;i frende is ded lat nouht &thorn;ine yen to moiste bien of teres; ne to muche drye &para; Al &thorn;ouhe &thorn;e teres commen of &thorn;ine yen. lat hem nouht fallen [2183] &para; And whan. &thorn;ou hast for-gone &thorn;i frende .I. rede &thorn;ou do &thorn;i diligence to gette &thorn;e a nother. And &thorn;is is more wysere &thorn;an to wepe for &thorn;i frende &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast lorne; For &thorn;er inne is no boote [2184] &para; And &thorn;erfore if &thorn;e lust to gouerne &thorn;e be Sapience Putte awaie sorwe fro &yogh;oure hert. [2185] Remembre&thorn; &yogh;owe &thorn;at. Ihesu Sirak. sai&thorn;e; 
<PB REF="00000520.tif" N="492"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="203"> A man &thorn;at is ioyus &amp; gladde in hert; it him con|serue&thorn; florischeinge in his Age. Bot so&thorn;ely Sorweful hert Make&thorn; his bones drye [2186] &para; He sei&thorn;e eke &thorn;us; &thorn;at sorwe in hert. slee&thorn;e mony a man. [2187] Sa|lamon sei&thorn;e &thorn;at riht as mouhtes in &thorn;e schepes fles anoye&thorn; to &thorn;e clo&thorn;es An &thorn;e smale wermes on &thorn;e tres vn to &thorn;e fruyte; Riht so anoy&thorn;e sorwe vnto &thorn;e hert /./ [2188] Wherfore we ouht as wele in &thorn;e de&thorn;e of oure childerne; as in &thorn;e losse of oure godes temperel; &para; Haue pacience.</P>
<P>[2189] Remembre &yogh;owe vp&omacr;n &thorn;e pacient &para; Iob. whan he hadde lost his children &amp; his temperel sub|stance. And in his <MILESTONE N="193a" UNIT="folio">bodi endured &amp; suffred mony a greuous temptacionz; &YOGH;it seid he &thorn;us. [2190] &para; Owre lorde quod he &yogh;aue it me. oure lorde ha&thorn; be-raft it me. Riht so as oure lorde ha&thorn;e wolde; riht so be it done. y|blissed be &thorn;e name of oure lorde [2191] &para; To &thorn;is afor &thorn;inges Melibius ansewerd to his wif Dame prudence. Al &thorn;i wordes quod he bien so&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;er-to pro|fitable. Bot trewely Min hert is trobled wi&thorn; &thorn;is sorwe so greuously &thorn;at .I. note what to done. [2192] &para; Late cal quod prudence &thorn;ine trewe frendes al; &amp; &thorn;in lignage whiche &thorn;at bien wise; telle hem &thorn;in caas &amp; herken what &thorn;ei seine in conseilinge; And &yogh;owe gouerne &thorn;ere after here sentence /./ [2193] Salomon sei&thorn;e &para; worche al &thorn;i &thorn;inge be counsel; &amp; &thorn;ou schal neuer repent.</P>
<P>[2194] Than be &thorn;e conseil of his wif dame Prudence. Melibeus lete callen a grete congregacione of folke [2195] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> olde &amp; &yogh;onge. And somme of his olde ennemys reconsiled as be her semblant in to his loue &amp; in to his grace. [2196] And &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-al cam somme of his neihbours &thorn;at dide him reuerence more for drede &thorn;an for loue as it happe&thorn; oft [2197] &para; &thorn;are commeth also ful mony a subtile flatreres and wise aduocates lerned in &thorn;e lawe.</P>
<P>[2198] And whan &thorn;is folk togeder assembled were This Mellibeus in sorwful wise schewde hem &thorn;is cas. 
<PB REF="00000521.tif" N="493"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="204"> [2199] And by &thorn;e manere of speche he bare in his herte a cruel ire rede to do venge|ance vpon his foos; // And sodanly desired &thorn;at werre schold / beginne [2200] &para; Bot na&thorn;eles &yogh;it axed he counseile vpon &thorn;is mate[re] [2201] &para; A Surgeane / be licence / &amp; assent of suche as were wise vp rose vn to Melibeus &amp; seide as &yogh;e maie here.</P>
<P>[2202] Sir quod he as to vs surgeans apperteyne&thorn; to euery whight &thorn;e best &thorn;at we can where as we be wi&thorn; - holde &amp; to oure pacience &thorn;at we do no damage. [2203] Ther-for it happe&thorn; mony time &amp; oft. &thorn;at whan tuo men ha&thorn;e eueryche wounded o&thorn;ere one same surgean hele&thorn; hem bo&thorn;e. [2204] Wherefor vnto oure arte it is nouht pertinent; to norische werre ne parties to supporte [2205] Bot certes as to &thorn;e warissheinge of &yogh;oure douhtere be it so &thorn;at sche is perilously. wounded. we shold done so entenfully be signes fro daie to nyht &thorn;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e grace of god sche schal be sounde &amp; hole as sone as it is possible [2206] &para; Al men in &thorn;e same wise ansewarden &amp;. &thorn;e Phesiciens. saue &thorn;ei seiden a fewe wordes more [2207] &para; That riht as Maladise bene heled be hire contraries /./ Riht so schal men warisshe werre be vengeance [2208] his neyh|bour ful of envye; // His feyned frendes &thorn;at semed reconsiled. his flatrers [2209] maden semblant of wepeinge empaired &amp; engreged muche of his matiere in preiseinge gretely /./ Melibeus of myht of pouere of riches &amp; of frende. Dispiseinge &thorn;e powere of his aduersaries. [2210] &amp; seiden outerly &thorn;at he anone scholde wreken him on his ennemys &amp; be-ginne werre</P>
<P>[2211] Vp rose &thorn;an an Aduocate &thorn;at was wise &amp; seide be leue &amp; be counseile of o&thorn;er &thorn;at were wise. &amp; seide. [2212] Lordeinges &thorn;e nedes for whiche we bene assembled in &thorn;is place is a ful heuy &thorn;inge. &amp; an hihe matiere [2213] because of &thorn;e wronge &amp; of &thorn;e wikkenesse &thorn;at ha&thorn;e be done. And eke be reson of &thorn;e grete. damage 
<PB REF="00000522.tif" N="494"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="205"> in time comynge. bien possible to fal for &thorn;is same cause. [2214] &amp; eke <MILESTONE N="193b" UNIT="folio">be reson of &thorn;e grete richesse &amp; power of &thorn;e parties bo&thorn;e. [2215] For whiche resouns it were a grete perile for to erren in &thorn;is matiere [2216] &para; Where-fore Milebeus &thorn;is is oure sentence; We counsel &yogh;owe a-boue al &thorn;inges &thorn;at riht anone &thorn;ou do &thorn;i diligence in kepeinge of &thorn;i propre persone in suche [a wise] &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne wante none aspie. ne to wache &thorn;ine bodie for to saue. [2217] &para; And after &thorn;at we counseile &thorn;at &thorn;ou setten in &thorn;ine hous sufficeant garnyson so &thorn;at &thorn;ei maie &thorn;i body also wele as &thorn;ine hous defende. [2218] &para; Botte certes for to meve werre ne sodanly to done vengeance we maie nouht deme in so litel time &thorn;at it were profit|able. [2219] wherefore we Axen leyser &amp; space to haue deliberacion in &thorn;is caas to deme [2220] &para; For &thorn;e comune prouerbe sei&thorn; &thorn;us &para; He &thorn;at sone deme&thorn; sone schal repent [2221] &para; And eke men seine &thorn;us &para; That ilke Iugge is wise &thorn;at sone vnderstonde&thorn; a matier; &amp; Iuge&thorn;e b[y] leyser [2222] &para; For al-be-it so; &thorn;at a tariinge be a-noyeful. Algates it is not to reproue in &yogh;eueinge of Iuggement ne in vengeance takeinge. whan it is suffisant &amp; resonable; [2223] &para; And &thorn;at schwde oure lorde ihesu criste be en|sample. For whan &thorn;at womman was taken in aduoutre &amp; was browhte in his presence to knowe what schal be done wi&thorn; hire persone &para; Albeit so &thorn;at he wist wele him selfe what &thorn;at he wold onsewere. &yogh;ete ne wolde he ansewere sodanly bot he wold haue deliberacione. And in &thorn;e grounde he wrote twyes. [2224] And be &thorn;is cause we axen deliberacione. And we schal &thorn;an by &thorn;e grace of god counseile &thorn;e &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at schallen be profitable</P>
