<P>[2227] Vprose one of &thorn;e olde wise. &amp; wi&thorn; his honde he maade a countenance &thorn;at &thorn;ei schold holde hem stil; and &yogh;euen hem audience [2228] &para; lordeinge quod he &thorn;ere is ful mony a man &thorn;at crie&thorn; werre. werre. &thorn;at woote ful lytel what &thorn;at werre amounte&thorn; // [2229] Werre att his beginynge ha&thorn; so grete an entringe &amp; so large; &thorn;at euery wight maie entren whan him like&thorn; And lyhtly finde werre. [2230] Bot certes to whatt ende &thorn;at schal &thorn;ere-of be-fal; it is note lyhtly to knowe [2231] &para; Whan &thorn;at werre is ones begonne. &thorn;er is ful mony a childe vnborne of his moder &thorn;at schal sterue &yogh;onge be cause of &thorn;ilke werre. O&thorn;ere elles leue in sorwe &amp; deye in wrechednesse, [2232] &para; And &thorn;ere-fore or &thorn;at any werre be-ginne men most haue grete conseile &amp; goode deliberacion. [2233] &para; And whan &thorn;is olde man wende to enforcen his tale be resoun. welnyhe al att ones bygonne for to rise to breken his tale. &amp; biden him ful oft of his wordes to abrigge //. [2234] For so&thorn;ely he &thorn;at preche&thorn; to hem &thorn;at lust nouht his wordes ne his sermon hem he anoye&thorn;. [2235] For ihesus Sirak sei&thorn;e. That Musike in wepeinge is anoyus &thorn;inge. Thus muche it is to seine As much anoye&thorn; to spek to-forne folke to wiche his speche annoye&thorn; as <MILESTONE N="194a" UNIT="folio">it is for to singen be-forne him &thorn;at wepe&thorn;. [2236] &para; And whan &thorn;is wiseman sawhe &thorn;at him wanted audience al schamfast he sett him doune a-&yogh;eine [2237] For Salomon sei&thorn;e &thorn;ere as &thorn;u mai haue none audience enforce &thorn;e nouht to speke. [2238] I. see wele quod &thorn;is wiseman &thorn;at &thorn;e comen prouerbe is so&thorn;e; &thorn;at good counseile wante&thorn; whan it is most nede.</P>
<P>[2239] &para; &YOGH;itte hadde &thorn;is Melebeus in his conseile many folke &thorn;at . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> conseilled him priue &thorn;inge. An counseld him &thorn;e contrarie in general audience.</P>
<P>[2240] Whan mellibeus hadde herde &thorn;e grettest 
<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="496"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="207"> partie of his counseile were accorded &thorn;at he schold make werre. A-none he consentid to here counselynge. And full affermed to he[re] sentence [2241] &para; Than dame Prudence sauhe howe &thorn;at hire hosband schope hime for to wreke him on his foos; &amp; to be-ginne werre Sche in full humble wise whan sche sauhe hire time Saide him in &thorn;is wordes [2242] &para; Mi lorde quod sche .I. &yogh;owe beseche as hertly as .I. dar &amp; can / ne haste &yogh;owe nouht to fast And Afore al guerdouns &yogh;euef me audience. [2243] For Pers Amphons sai&thorn;e .O. who so do&thorn;e &thorn;e goode o&thorn;er harme haste &thorn;e nouht to qwyten it. For in &thorn;is wise &thorn;i frende wil abide And &thorn;ine ennemy schal &thorn;e langere leue in drede; [2244] The prouerbe sei&thorn;e &thorn;at he haste&thorn;e him wele &thorn;atte wele can abide. And in wikked hast is no profite.</P>
<P>[2245] This Melibe ansewerd to his wyf prudence; I. purpos nouht quod he to wirke be &thorn;i counseile ffor mony causes &amp; resons; For certes euery wight wold hold me &thorn;an a foole; [2246] &para; This is for soothe. If .y. for &thorn;in counsellynge wolde chaunge &thorn;inges &thorn;at buen ordeined &amp; affermed be so mony a wyse; [2247] Sec|undly .I. saie &thorn;at al wemmen bien &thorn;ikke &amp; none goode of hem alle. ffor of a. &thorn;ousand men as sei&thorn;e Salomon<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon</NOTE> .I. fonde o good man bot certes of alle wemmen fonde .I. neuere good womman [2248] &para; And Also certes if .I. gouerned me be &thorn;i counseile it schold seme &thorn;at .I. hadde .y.-&yogh;if to &thorn;e ouer me &thorn;e maistre. And god forbede &thorn;at it so were [2249] &para; For Ihesus Sirake. sei&thorn;e. If &thorn;e wif ha&thorn;e &thorn;e maistre sche is contrarius to hir husbonde. [2250] &para; And Salomon. sei&thorn;e. neuere in &thorn;i lif. to &thorn;i wif ne to &thorn;i childe ne to &thorn;i frende ne &yogh;eue none powere ouer. &thorn;ine selfe; For better it were &thorn;at &thorn;ine childern asken of &thorn;ine persone &thorn;inges &thorn;at hem nede&thorn;. &thorn;an &thorn;ou &thorn;i self in &thorn;e handes of &thorn;ine childerne. [2251] And also if .I. wil worche be &thorn;i conseillynge. Certes my conseil most som time be secre til it wer time &thorn;at it must be 
<PB REF="00000525.tif" N="497"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="208"> knowe; And &thorn;is ne may nouht be do; [2252. For it is written, '&thorn;e Ianglerye of wemmen can hide [only] &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ei wote nought' [2253] Furthermore, the philo|sopher saith, 'in wiked counsel, wemmen venquyse&thorn; men;' and for these reasons I ought not to make use of thy counsel. (<I>See Prudence's answers to Reasons</I> 4 &amp; 5, <I>below</I>.)]</P>
<P>[2254] &para; Whan dam pruden ful debonarly &amp; [with] al pacience hadde herd al &thorn;at hire husbond lyked for to seye./ Than axe sche of him licence for to speke. And seide in &thorn;is wise. [2255] Mi lorde quod sche; as to &yogh;oure first reson it maie lyhtly bne ansewerd. ffor .I. seie. it ne is folye to chaunge counseil. whan &thorn;e &thorn;inge is chaungede or elles whan &thorn;e &thorn;inge seme&thorn; o&thorn;erewise &thorn;an it semed a-forne [2256] And more ouere .I. saie. &thorn;eihe &thorn;at &yogh;e haue sworne &amp; behi&yogh;t to performe &yogh;oure emprise. [and natheless ye weyve to performe that same emprise] Be Iuste cause men schold nouht seine &thorn;erefore &thorn;at &yogh;e were a lyere ne for-sworne [2257] &para; ffor &thorn;e booke sei&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;e wise man make&thorn; no leseinge when he torne&thorn; his corage to &thorn;e bettere [2258] &para; An if it so be &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="194b" UNIT="folio">&yogh;oure emprise be establisshet &amp; ordeined be grete multitude of folke &yogh;it &thorn;arre &thorn;e nouht accomplise &thorn;ilke ordinance bot &yogh;owe like&thorn;; [2259] &para; For &thorn;e treu&thorn;e of &thorn;inges &amp; &thorn;e profit bene rather y-founde in fewe folke &thorn;at bien wise and ful of resoune &thorn;an be grete multitude of folke &thorn;ere euery man crie&thorn; &amp; clatere&thorn; what hem like&thorn;; Suche multitude is nouht honest. [2260] And as to &thorn;e secund reson. Where as &yogh;e seine &thorn;at al wemmen bene wikke. saue &yogh;oure grace; for certes &yogh;e dispisen al wemmen in &thorn;is wise. And he &thorn;at all despise&thorn;. all &thorn;inge him despise&thorn; as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e boke.// [2261] And Seneca. sei&thorn;e who &thorn;at woll haue sapience schall no man despise. Bot he schal gladly teche &thorn;e science &thorn;at .I. kan. wi&thorn;-oute presumpcion or pride. [2262] And suche &thorn;inges as nou&yogh; can he schal not be ascamed to leren hem; &amp; to enqueren of lesse 
<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="498"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="209"> folke &thorn;an of him self; [2263] And sire &thorn;at &thorn;are ha&thorn; bue many a goode womman maie lihtly be proued [2264] &para; Certes sire oure lorde ihesu crist nold neuere haue descended to be borne of womman if al wemmen hadde be wikke. [2265] And after &thorn;at for &thorn;e grete bounte &thorn;at is in wemmen oure lorde ihesus whan he was resen fro de&thorn;e to lyf; he appered ra&thorn;er to wemmen &thorn;an he dide to his aposteles [2266] And &thorn;ouhe &thorn;at Salomon sei&thorn;. he ne fonde neuer womman goode. It foulowe&thorn; nouht &thorn;ere-fore &thorn;at al wemmen be wikke [2267] &para; For &thorn;ouhe &thorn;at he no fonde no good womman. Certes mony a no&thorn;er man ha&thorn; founden many a womman ful goode &amp; trewe. [2268] Or elles perauenture &thorn;e entente of Salomon was &thorn;us; That as in souereine bounte he fonde no womman [2269] &para; &thorn;is is to seie &thorn;at &thorn;ere is no wight &thorn;at ha&thorn;e parfite bounte saue god alone; as he him self recorde&thorn; in his euaun|geliste; [2270] ffor &thorn;ere ne is no creture &thorn;at him ne wante&thorn; sumwhat of &thorn;e perfeccion of god &thorn;at is his maker [2271] &para; The &thorn;red reson is &thorn;is &para; &yogh;e seie &thorn;at if &yogh;e gouern &yogh;oue be my counsel; it scholde seme &thorn;at &yogh;e hadde &yogh;eue to me &thorn;e maistre. &amp; &thorn;e lordeschipe of &yogh;oure persone; [2272] Sire; saue &yogh;oure grace it is nouht so &para; For if so were &thorn;at noman scholde be conseiled bot only of hem &thorn;at hadd lordeschip &amp; Meistre of his person. Men nold nou&yogh;t be counceilled so oft. [2273] For so&thorn;ely &thorn;ilke man &thorn;at axe&thorn; counsel of a purpos; &yogh;it ha&thorn;e frewill we&thorn;er he wil do after &thorn;at counseil or no; [2274] &para; And as to &yogh;oure fer&thorn;e reson. &thorn;ere as &yogh;e seine &thorn;at &thorn;e Ianglerye of wemmen can hide &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ei wote nouht. As who sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at a womman kan nouht hide &thorn;at sche wote; [2275] sire &thorn;es wordes buen vnder|stonde of wemmen &thorn;at bien Ianglers &amp; wikked; [2276] of whiche wemmen Men seine &thorn;at &thorn;re &thorn;inges driue&thorn; a man oute of his house &para; &thorn;at is to seie. Smoke. dropeinge of Reine? &amp; wikked wyues. [2277] &para; And 
<PB REF="00000527.tif" N="499"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="210"> of suche wemmen sei&thorn;e Salomon . &thorn;at him were better duelle in desert. &thorn;an wi&thorn; a womman &thorn;at is reyetous. [2278] And sire be &yogh;oure leue &thorn;at am nouht .I. [2279] For &yogh;e haue ful oft assaide my grete silence &amp; my grete pacience. And eke howe wele &thorn;at .I. can hide. &amp; hele &thorn;inges &thorn;at men ouhten sekerly to hiden; [2280] &para; And for&thorn;e as to &yogh;oure fift resone; wher as &yogh;e seie &thorn;at in wiked coun|sel wemmen venquyse&thorn; men; Gode wote &thorn;ilke <MILESTONE N="195a" UNIT="folio">reson stonde&thorn; here in no stede; [2281] &para; For vnder-stonde&thorn; nowe &yogh;e ax conseil for to do wikkednesse. [2282] And if &yogh;e wil wirke wikkenesse; &amp; &yogh;oure wife restreyne&thorn; &thorn;ilke wikked purpos; And ouere-comme &yogh;owe be reson &amp; be goode counsel. [2283] Certes &yogh;owe wif ouht ra&thorn;er to be preised &thorn;an to be blamed. [2284] This schold &yogh;e vnder|stande &thorn;e Philosofre &thorn;at sai&thorn;e. In wikked conseile wemmen venquisched her husbondes. [2285] And &thorn;ere as &yogh;e blame al wemmen &amp; here resons .I. schal schew &yogh;oue be monye ensamples &thorn;at mony wemmen han bien ful goode &amp; &yogh;ut buen. &para; An here consel holsome &amp; profitable [2286] eke: Sommen haue seid &thorn;at counselinge of wemmen es ei&thorn;er to dere or elles to lite of prise [2287] &para; Bot al be it so &thorn;at ful mony a womman is badde. &amp; hire consel vile &amp; not wor&thorn;e. &yogh;it ha&thorn;e men founden mony a goode womman. &amp; ful discrete &amp; wise in counselinge. [2288] &para; Lo Iacob &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e good counsel of his moder Rebec /./ whan he hadde. &thorn;e benyson of his fader. &amp; &thorn;e lordschip ouere al his bre&thorn;er. [2289] &para; Iudi&thorn;e &thorn;oruhe hire goode counsel deliuerd &thorn;e Cite of Bu&thorn;hilie in whiche sche duelte oute of &thorn;e hande of Olifernce &thorn;at hit beseged; &amp; wolde haue al destruyed it. [2290] &para; Abegayle deliuer Nabal hire husbonde fro dauid &thorn;e kinge &thorn;at wold haue sleyne him &amp; apesed &thorn;e ire of &thorn;e kinge be hire witte &amp; be hire good counseil|inge. [2291] Ester be hire counseile enchauncede gretlye &thorn;e peple of god in &thorn;e reigne of Assur [2292] &para; And &thorn;e same bounte in goode conselinge of 
<PB REF="00000528.tif" N="500"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="211"> mony wemmen mai men tell [2293] &para; And for&thorn;ere more whan &thorn;at owre lorde hadde created Adam oure forme fadere. he seide in &thorn;is wise [2294] it is nouht good to bue a man alone Maake we an helpere semblable to him self; [2295] Here maie &yogh;e see &thorn;at if &thorn;at wemmen were nouht goode &amp; here counseile goode &amp; profitable; [2296] oure lorde god of heuen ne wold ney&thorn;er haue wrouht hem ne called hem &thorn;e helper of man. [. . . . .] [2297] &para; And &thorn;ere seide ones a clerk in tuo vers. What is better &thorn;an golde. Iasper; what is better &thorn;an Iasper. wisdome. [2298] And what is better &thorn;an wisdome Womman /./ And whatt is bester &thorn;an womman. &thorn;at is a good womman. no&thorn;inge. [2299] &para; And sire be monye of o&thorn;ere resons may &yogh;e seen &thorn;at mony wemmen ben goode. &amp; eke here conseile goode &amp; profitable also [2300] &para; And &thorn;erfor sire if &yogh;e wil trust vnto mi counsel .I. schal restore &yogh;oure douhter hole &amp; sounde. [2301] and eke &thorn;at .I. wil done to &yogh;owe so muche &thorn;at &yogh;e schal haue honoure in &thorn;is caas</P>
<P>[2302] &para; whan Melibe hadde herde &thorn;e wordes of his wif Prudence. he seide &thorn;us; [2303] That &thorn;e wordes of salomon is so&thorn;e; for he sei&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at buen spoken discretelye be ordinance bien honye combes; For &thorn;ei &yogh;eue swetnesse to &thorn;e soule &amp; holesomenesse to &thorn;e bodye; [2304] And wif be cause of &thorn;i swete wordes &amp; eke for .I. haue prouede &amp; assaide &thorn;i grete sapience &amp; &thorn;i grete trew&thorn;e .I. wil gouerne me be &thorn;i consel in al &thorn;inge</P>
<P>[2305] &para; Nowe. sire quod Dam Prudence &amp; se&thorn;en &yogh;e vouche sauf to be gouernde be my counsel .I. wil en|forme &yogh;owe how &thorn;at &yogh;e schal gouerne &yogh;oure selue In cheseinge of &yogh;oure counselours. [2306] &para; &YOGH;e schol first forme al &yogh;oure werkes mekely. besecheinge to &thorn;e hihe gode &thorn;at he wolde be &yogh;oure. <MILESTONE N="195b" UNIT="folio">consellour. [2307] And schape&thorn; &yogh;owe to suche entent &thorn;at he &yogh;eue &yogh;owe consel &amp; comforte as tauht Thobe to his son [2308] Att all times &thorn;ou schalt blisse 
<PB REF="00000529.tif" N="501"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="212"> god &amp; prei him to dressen &thorn;ine weies. And loke also &thorn;at &thorn;i counsele ben in him for euermore. [2309] &para; Seint Iame sei&thorn;e if any of &yogh;owe haue nede of sapiens aske it of god [2310] &para; And afterward &thorn;an scholne &yogh;e take counsel in &yogh;oure self And examine wele &yogh;oure owen wittes of suche &thorn;inges as &yogh;owe &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at is beste for &yogh;oure profit [2311] &para; And &thorn;an schal &yogh;e driue fro &yogh;oure hert &thorn;enges &thorn;at bene contrarious to good consell. [2312] &thorn;at is to so seie. Ire. couetise. &amp; hastenesse.</P>
<P>[2313] &para; First he &thorn;at aske&thorn; counsel of him self certes he most be wi&thorn;-outen ire . . . . .[2314] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &amp; wrathe in him-self; He wene&thorn; al waie &thorn;at he maie do &thorn;inge &thorn;at he maie nouht do; [2315] And secundly he &thorn;at is yrous &amp; wro&thorn;e he may nouht wel . . . [2316] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> counsel [2317] &para; &thorn;e &thorn;redde is &thorn;is; &thorn;at he &thorn;at is Irous &amp; wro&thorn;e as sei&thorn;e Senec ne maie nou&yogh;t speke bot blame-ful &thorn;inges. [2318] And wi&thorn; &thorn;ilke vicious wordes; he stire&thorn; o&thorn;ere folke to angur. &amp; to Ire. [2319] &para; And eke sir &yogh;owe most drede couetise &amp; put it oute of &yogh;oure hert. [2320] &para; For &thorn;e Apostel sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at Couetise is &thorn;e rote of al harmes [2321] &para; And truste&thorn; riht wele &thorn;at a couetouse man can nou&yogh;t deme ne &thorn;inke bot only to fulfil &thorn;e ende of his couetise; [2322] And certes &thorn;at mai neuer be acomplised &para; For euer &thorn;e mo abundance &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e of riches &thorn;e more he desire&thorn;. [2323] &para; And sir &yogh;oue most also driue oute of &yogh;oure herte hastifnesse [2324] For certes &yogh;e maie not deme for &yogh;e best A sodan &thorn;ouht &thorn;at falle&thorn; in &yogh;oure herte Bot &yogh;ow mot avise on it ful oft. [2325] For as &yogh;e haue herde here-be-forne; &thorn;e commune prouerbe is &thorn;is. That he &thorn;at son deme sone repente&thorn;.</P>
<P>[2326] &para; Sire &yogh;e be not alweie in like disposicione. [2327] For certes some &thorn;inge &thorn;at some time seme&thorn; to &yogh;owe goode for to do; Ano&thorn;er time it seme&thorn; to &yogh;owe &thorn;e contrarie<NOTE PLACE="marg">[A great bit is now omitted in Lansdowne.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000530.tif" N="502"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="213"></P>
<P>[2328] [Whan ye han taken counseil vnto youre self and<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 17 D xv folio" N="246b"> han demed bi goode deliberacioun suche thyng as yow semyth best [2329] than rede I yow that ye kepe it secre [2330] bewry youre counseil to no persone. but if so be that ye wene sikerly that thurgh yowre be-wreyeng your condicion shalbe to youre more profitable [2331] ffor Ihesus Syrak seyth neyther to thy foo ne to thy friend discouere nat thi secree ne thi folye [2332] for they wil yeve the audience and lokyng and supportacioun in thi presence and scorn in thy absence [2333] Another clerk seyth that scarsly thow shalt fynde any persone that may kepe thy counsaile secretly [2334] The booke seyth while that thow kepest thy coun|seil in thyn hert thow kepist it in thy prison [2335] and when thow bewryest thy counseil to any wight he holdith the in his snare [2336] And therfor yow is better to hide youre counseile in yowre hert than pray hym to whom ye have bewreyed youre counseil that he wil kepe it close and stille [2337] ffor Senek seyth if so be that thow ne mayst thyn owne counseil hide / how darstow pray any other wight thy counseil secretely to kepe / [2338] But natheles if thow wene sikerly that thy bewreyeng of thi counseil to a persone wil make thy condicion to stande in the better plite than shalt thow telle hym thy counseyl in this wise [2339] ffirst thow shalt make no semblaunt whether the were leuere pes than werre or this or that ne shewe hym nat thy wil and thyn entent. [2340] for trust wele that comunely thise counsellours bien flaterers [2341] namely the counseillours of grete lordes [2342] for they enforcen hem alwey rather to speke plesaunt wordis enclyneng to the lord his lust. than wordis that bien trewe or profitable [2343] and therfor men <MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 17 D xv folio" N="247a">seyn that the riche man hath sielde goode coun|seil. but if he have it of hym self [2344] and after that thow shalt considre thy friendis and thyn enemyes [2345] And as towchyng thy friendis thow shalt con|sidre 
<PB REF="00000531.tif" N="503"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="214"> whiche of hem bien most feythful and most<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Reg.]</NOTE> wise and most eldest and most appreved in counseillyng [2346] and of hem shalt thow axe thi counseil as the caas requirith</P>
<P>[2347] I sey that first ye shul clepe to yowre coun|seil yowre friendis that bien triewe [2348] ffor Salamon saith for right as the hert of man delitith in savour that is swete right so the counseil of thy friendis yevith swetnesse to the soule [2349] he seyth also ther may nothyng be lykned to the true friende [2350] ffor certes gold ne siluer be nat so moche worth as the goode wille of a triewe friend [2351] And he seyth that a triewe friend is a stronge defence who so that it fyndith certis he fyndith a grete tresour [2352] than shul ye eke considre if that yowre triewe friendis bien discrete and wise for the booke seyth aske alwey thy counseil of hem that bien wise [2353] And be this same reason ye mow clepe to youre counseil of yowre friendis that bien of age [<I>qui assez ont veu</I>] and bien expert in many thynges and han ben appreved in counseillynges [2354] ffor the booke seyth in old men is al the sapience and in long tyme the prudence [2355] As Tullius seyth that grete thynges ne be nat acompliced bi strength ne be delyuer|nesse of body. but by goode counseile and bi auctorite of persones and bi science The whiche .iij. thynges ne be nat fiebled bi age but certes they enforcen and en|cresen day bi day [2356] And than shul ye kepe this for a general rewle ffirst ye shul clepe to your counseil a fewe of youre friendis that bien especial [2357] ffor Salamon saith many friendis have thow. but among a M<SUP>1</SUP>. chese the oon in especial to be thy coun|seillour [2358] for albe it so that thow first ne telle thy counseill but to a fewe thow mayst after-warde tel it to mo folk if it be nede [2359] but loke alwey that thy counseillours have thylk .iij. condicions that I have seyde 
<PB REF="00000532.tif" N="504"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="215"> before. that is to sey that they be triewe wise and old experience [2360] and werk nat alwey in euery nede be oo counseillour alone for somtyme behovith it to be counseiled be many [2361] ffor Salamon seyth saluacion of thynges is where as there bien many counseillours<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Reg. <I>extract ends</I>]</NOTE>]</P>
<P>[2362] &para; Now haue .I. tolde &yogh;owe of whiche folke<NOTE PLACE="marg">Lansdowne MS, <I>on leaf</I> 195, <I>back</I></NOTE> &yogh;e scholde be counseled Nowe wil .I. teche &yogh;owe whiche counsell &yogh;e owe to eschewe [2363] &para; ffirst &yogh;e scholne eschewe &thorn;e counseillinge of foles. Salomon sei&thorn;e; Take&thorn; no coun|sell of no foole for he wil counsel bot after his owen lust and his affeccions; [2364] &para; The booke sei&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;e properte of a foole is &thorn;is. He troue&thorn; lyhtly harme of euery whight; &amp; lyhtly troue&thorn; a bounte in him self [2365] &para; Thou schalt eke eschewe &thorn;e counseileinge of al flaterers whiche enforcen hem ra&thorn;er to preysen &yogh;oure persone by flatry &thorn;an for to tel &yogh;ow &thorn;e so&thorn;e|fastnesse of &thorn;e &thorn;inge.</P>
<P>[2366] Wherefore tullius. sei&thorn;e Amonge al &thorn;e pestelence &thorn;at ben in frenschip &thorn;e grettest is flaterie; And &thorn;er-fore is it more nede &thorn;at &thorn;oue eschewe &amp; drede flatrers &thorn;an any o&thorn;er peple. [2367] The boke sei&thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt ra&thorn;er [drede and] fle fro &thorn;e swete wordes of flateringe &amp; preiseinge &thorn;at from &thorn;e egre wordes of &thorn;ine frende &thorn;at sei&thorn;e &thorn;e &thorn;i so&thorn;es; [2368] Salomon. sei&thorn;e; The wordes of a flaterer is a snare to cache innocence. [2369] &para; He sei&thorn;e also; He &thorn;at speke&thorn; to his frendes wordes of swettnesse; &amp; al plesance; sette&thorn; a nette to for his fete to cache him; [2370] And &thorn;erefor tullius sei&thorn;e Enclyne nou&yogh;t &thorn;ine eres to flatere[r]s ne take no counsel of wordes of flaterye; [2371] And Caton&middot; Avise &thorn;e wele &amp; eschewe &thorn;e wordes of <MILESTONE N="196a" UNIT="folio">swetenesse &amp; of plesance; [2372] &para; And eke &thorn;ou schalt eschewe &thorn;e counsellinge of &thorn;ine olde enmys &thorn;at be reconsiled [2373] &para; The boke sei&thorn;e &thorn;at no whiht retorne&thorn; safly in to &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000533.tif" N="505"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="216"> grace of his olde enmye. [2374] And. Isope. sei&thorn;e. Ne trust nouht to hem to whiche some time &thorn;ou hast hadd werre or enemete; ne tell hem nouht &thorn;ine counsell. [2375] &para; And Senec telle&thorn; &thorn;e cause whi; It maie nouht be sei&thorn; he &thorn;at where longe time fire ha&thorn;e endured &thorn;at &thorn;ere dwelle&thorn; som tyme vapoure of hete; [2376] &para; And &thorn;erefor sei&thorn; Salomon. In &thorn;ine olde foo truste &thorn;ou neuere. [2377] ffor sekerly &thorn;ouhe &thorn;ine enmye be reconsilede &amp; make&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ere of humylite &amp; loute&thorn; to &thorn;e wi&thorn; his hede ne trust him neuere. [2378] ffor certes he make&thorn; &thorn;ilke feyned humylite more for his profit &thorn;an for any humylite. or for any loue of &thorn;in persone . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> be suche feyned countenance. The whiche victorie. he myht haue be strif of werre. [2379] &para; And Peter alfons sei&thorn;e Maake no felaweschepe wi&thorn; &thorn;ine olde enmys; ffor if &thorn;ou done hem bounte &thorn;ei willen peruerten it to wikkednesse; [2380] &para; And eke &thorn;ou most eschiewe &thorn;e counselinge of &thorn;ine seruant&yogh; &thorn;at beren &thorn;e grete reuerence; ffor parauenture &thorn;ei seine it more for drede &thorn;an for loue [2381] And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn;e a philosofer in &thorn;is wise. Ther is no wyght parfitly trewe to hime &thorn;at he to sore drede&thorn;; [2382] And Tullius sei&thorn;e There is no wight so grete of any emperoure&yogh; &thorn;at longe maie endure bot if he haue loue of &thorn;e peple &amp; drede [2383] &para; &thorn;ou schalt eschewe also &thorn;e counselinge of folke &thorn;at bien dronkenlewe for &thorn;ei ne can no counsell hide. [2384] Salomon. sei&thorn;e. &thorn;ere nys no priuete &thorn;ere as regne&thorn; drunkennesse [2385] &para; &yogh;e scholne haue also in suspecte to &thorn;e counselinge of suche folke as counsel &yogh;owe a &thorn;inge priuely &amp; counsel &yogh;owe a thinge &thorn;at is contrarye openly [2386] &para; ffor Cassidorie. sei&thorn;e &thorn;at it is a maner sleihte to hindren his enmye whan he schewe&thorn; to done a &thorn;inge openlye &amp; wirke&thorn; priuely &thorn;e contrarie. [2387] &para; &thorn;ou schalt haue also in &thorn;i suspecte &thorn;e counselinge of wikked folke . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;at is alweie ful 
<PB REF="00000534.tif" N="506"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="217"> of fraude; [2388] And Dauid sei&thorn;e &thorn;at blisful is &thorn;e man &thorn;at ha&thorn;e nouht foulowed &thorn;e counse[l] of schrewes. [2389] &para; Tho schalt also eschewe &thorn;e counselinge of &yogh;onge folke; ffor here counselinge is nouht ripe as Salomon sei&thorn;e</P>
<P>[2390] &para; Nowe sire se&thorn;ens .I. haue schewde &yogh;oue of whiche folke &yogh;e scholne take counseile &amp; of whiche folke &yogh;e schollen folowe &thorn;e counsell [2391] &para; Now wil .I. techeche howe &yogh;e scholne examyne &yogh;oure counsele after &thorn;e doctrine of tullius [2392] &para; In &thorn;e examenynge &thorn;an of &yogh;oure conseloure &yogh;e scholne considere many &thorn;inges [2393] Al&thorn;ere first &thorn;ou schalt considere &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge &thorn;at &thorn;ou purposed; and vpon what &thorn;inge &thorn;ou wolte haue counsel &thorn;at verrey treu&thorn;e be seide &amp; conseruede. &thorn;is to seie; Tel treuly &thorn;in tale. [2394] For he &thorn;at sei&thorn;e fals maye wele be counseled in &thorn;at caas; . . . . .] [2395] &para; And after &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt consideren &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at accorden to &thorn;at &thorn;ou purposest for to be by &thorn;ine counsel|loures if reson accorde&thorn; &thorn;ere to /./ [2396] And eke if &thorn;i myht maie atteigne &thorn;ere to; &para; And if &thorn;e more part &amp; &thorn;e bettere parte of &yogh;oure counsellours accorden &thorn;er-to or no [2397] &thorn;enne schal &thorn;ou considere whatt &thorn;inge schal folowe of hire counselinge. As hate pees. werre. grace profit o&thorn;er Damage or many o&thorn;ir &thorn;inges; [2398] And in al &thorn;inges &thorn;ou schalt schese &thorn;e best and. And <MILESTONE N="196b" UNIT="folio">weife al o&thorn;ere &thorn;inges [2399] &para; Than schalt &thorn;ou considered of what rote it is engenderd &thorn;e matier of &thorn;ine counsel &amp; what fruyte it maie conceive &amp; engendre. [2400] &thorn;ou schalt eke considerer al &thorn;es causes for whiche &thorn;ei bue spronge; [2401] &para; And whan &yogh;e haue examyne &yogh;oure counsel as .I. haue seide and whiche partye is better &amp; more profitable; &amp; hast approued it be mony wise folke &amp; olde; [2402] &thorn;an schalt &thorn;ou considere. if &thorn;ou maist performe it &amp; make a good ende. [2403] For certes reson wil nouht &thorn;at any man schall beginne a &thorn;inge bot if he myht performe it as him ouht; [2404] Ne no wight schol 
<PB REF="00000535.tif" N="507"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="218"> taken vpon him so heuy a charge &thorn;at he ne myht bere it. [2405] &para; For &thorn;e prouerbe sei&thorn;; He &thorn;at to muche enbracet distreyne&thorn; litul. [2406] And Caton sei&thorn;e Asseie suche &thorn;inge as &thorn;ou hast pouere to done lest &thorn;e charge oppresse &thorn;e to sore; &thorn;at &thorn;e be-houe&thorn; to weyve &thorn;inge &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast begonne [2407] &para; And if so be &thorn;ou be in doute whe&thorn;e &thorn;ou maiste performe a &thorn;inge or none; chese ra&thorn;er for to suffur &thorn;an for to beginne [2408] &para; And Peter Alphon sey&thorn;e. If &thorn;ou hast myht to done a &thorn;inge of whiche &thorn;ou most repent. . . . .[2409] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> It is better to hold &thorn;ine tonge still; &thorn;an for to speke [2410] &para; Then may .I. vnder-stonde be stronger resones &thorn;at if &thorn;ou hast power to performe a werke of whiche &thorn;ou schalt repent &thorn;e. Than is it better &thorn;at &thorn;ou suffur &thorn;an begynne; [2411] wele seyne &thorn;ei &thorn;at defenden euery whight to assaie a thinge of whiche he is in doute where he mai performe it or none; [2412] And after whan &yogh;e haue examined &yogh;oure counsell; as .I. haue seide be-forne; And knowe&thorn;e wele &thorn;at &yogh;e maie per|forme &yogh;oure emprise conferme it &thorn;an sadly til it be att an ende.</P>
<P>[2413] &para; Nowe is it reson &amp; time &thorn;at .I. schewe &yogh;owe whenne &amp; where; for &thorn;at &yogh;e maie chaunge &yogh;oure counsel|lours wi&thorn;-outen &yogh;oure reproue [2414] &para; So&thorn;ely a man maie chaunge his purpos &amp; his counsel if &thorn;e cause sese&thorn;; or whan a newe caas be-tide&thorn;; [2415] ffor &thorn;e lawe sei&thorn; vpon &thorn;inges &thorn;at newly be-tyden be-houe&thorn; new counsel; [2416] And senec sai&thorn;e. If &thorn;i counsell come to &thorn;e heres of &thorn;ine ennemys chaunge &thorn;i counsel. [2417] . . . . .] if so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou finde &thorn;at be errour or be any o&thorn;ere cause harme or damage may betide [2418] &para; Also if &thorn;i counsel be dishoneste. or elles come of dishonest cause change &thorn;ine counsel. [2419] For &thorn;e lawe sei&thorn;e &thorn;at al behestes &thorn;at bene dishonest ne biene of no valew; 
<PB REF="00000536.tif" N="508"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="219"> [2420] &para; And eke if it so be &thorn;at it be impossible or maie no&yogh;t gladly be perfourmed or kepet</P>
<P>[2421] &para; And take &thorn;is for a general rewle. That euery counsel &thorn;at is enformed so strongely &thorn;at it maie not be chaunged for no condicion &thorn;at maie be tide; I. saie &thorn;at ilke counsel is wykked;</P>
<P>[2422] &para; Mellibeus whan he hadde herde &thorn;e doctrine of his wif Dame Prudence. he anseward in &thorn;is wise. [2423] Dame quod he as &yogh;it vnto &thorn;is time &yogh;e haue wele tauht me as in general howe .I. schal gouerne me. &amp; in &thorn;e cheseinge. &amp; in wi&thorn;holdeinge of my counsellours. [2424] &para; Bott nowe wolde .I. faine &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde condescende in speciale; [2425] and telle&thorn; me howe &thorn;at like&thorn; &yogh;owe or howe &thorn;at seme&thorn; &yogh;ow be owre coun|sellours &thorn;at we haue chose in &thorn;is present nede</P>
<P>[2426] &para; Mi lorde quod sche .I. beseche &yogh;owe in al hum|blesse &thorn;at &yogh;o wold nouht wilfully reprouen a&yogh;eine myn resouns ne distemper &yogh;oure herte &thorn;eihe .I. speke &thorn;inge &thorn;at &yogh;owe displese [2427] &para; ffor god wote as in myne entent .I. speke it as for &thorn;e best; for &yogh;oure honoure &amp; for &yogh;oure profit eke; [2428] And so&thorn;ely .I. hope &thorn;at &yogh;oure <MILESTONE N="197a" UNIT="folio">be|nignite wil tak it in pacience // [2429] And truste&thorn; to me wele &thorn;at &yogh;oure consel in &thorn;is ne schold nou&yogh;t as to speke properly be called a counsellinge; bot A mocion or ameueinge of folye. [2430] &para; In whiche counsel &yogh;e haue herde in mony a sondre wyse;</P>
<P>[2431] first &amp; forwarde &yogh;e haue herde in &thorn;e assem|blinge of &yogh;oure counsellours; [2432] ffor first &yogh;e schold haue cleped a fewe folk to &yogh;oure counsell. &para; And after &thorn;at &yogh;e myht haue schewde it to mo folke if it hadd be nede; // [2433] Bot certes sodanly &yogh;e haue cleped to &yogh;oure coun|sel a grete multitude of peple ful chargeaunt &amp; ful annoyus for to here; [2434] &para; And also &yogh;e haue herde for|&thorn;er as &yogh;e scholde onely haue cleped to &yogh;oure counsel &yogh;oure trewe frendes olde &amp; wise; [2435] &para; &yogh;e haue cleped also strange folk &yogh;onge folke false flateres &amp; ennemys 
<PB REF="00000537.tif" N="509"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="220"> reconsiled. And folke &thorn;at do &yogh;owe reuerence wi&thorn;e outen loue [2436] And eke also &yogh;e haue herde for &yogh;e haue brouht wi&thorn; &yogh;ou to &yogh;oure counsell. Ire. couetise./ &amp; hastinesse./ [2437] &para; &thorn;e whiche &thorn;re &thorn;inges be con|trarie to euery good consell &amp; honest. &amp; profitable; [2438] The whiche &thorn;re &thorn;inge &yogh;e haue nouht anentisched o&thorn;er de|struyde hem ney &thorn;ere in &yogh;oure self ne in &yogh;oure counsellours as &yogh;owe auht [2439] &para; &yogh;e haue herde also for &yogh;e haue schewde to &yogh;oure consellours &yogh;oure talent. &yogh;our affeccion anone for to do vengeance; [2440] And &thorn;ei haue aspide be &yogh;oure wordes to what &thorn;inge &yogh;e be enclyned; [2441] And &thorn;ere fore haue &thorn;ei ra&thorn;er counseld &yogh;owere talent; &thorn;an to &yogh;oure profitte.// [2442] &yogh;e haue herd also for &yogh;owe seme&thorn; it suffice&thorn; to haue be coun|seld be &thorn;is counsellours onely &amp; be lytil avise; [2443] where as in so grete &amp; in so hihe a nede it hadde bue necessarie mo counsellours &amp; mo delib[er]aciones to performe &yogh;oure emprise. [2444] &para; Also &yogh;e haue nou&yogh;t herde &yogh;oure counsell in &thorn;e forseid manere ne in dieu manere as &thorn;e caas require&thorn;. [2445] &para; &yogh;e haue herde also for &yogh;e haue maade no diuision be tuex . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &yogh;oure trewe frendes &amp; &yogh;oure feyned counselloures [2446] Ne &yogh;e haue nouht knowe &thorn;e will of &yogh;oure trew frendes olde &amp; wise. [2447] Bot &yogh;e haue cast al here wordes in an hoche poche &amp; enclyned &yogh;oure hert to &thorn;e more part and to &thorn;e gretter nombre [and there be ye condescended [2448] <I>Et tu scez bien que les fols sont tousjours en plus grant nombre que les sages</I>,] of foles &thorn;an of wise men; [2449] And &thorn;are for &thorn;e counsellinge &thorn;at ben at congregacioun &amp; mul|titude of folk; &thorn;ere as men tak more rewarde to &thorn;e nombre &thorn;an to &thorn;e Sapience. of persones. [2450] &para; &yogh;e se wele &thorn;at in suche consellinge &thorn;e foles haue &thorn;e maistre. [2451] &para; Mellibe anseward &amp; seide a&yogh;eine .I. graunt wele &thorn;at .I. haue herde [2452] Bot &thorn;ere as &thorn;ou hast tolde me here beforne. That he nys nouht to blame to chaunge his con|sellours 
<PB REF="00000538.tif" N="510"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="221"> for certeine caas &amp; for certeine &amp; iust cause; [2453] .I. am al rede to chaunge my consellours riht as &thorn;ou woldest deuise.// [2454] for &thorn;e prouerbe sei&thorn;e ffor to do synne is manysshe Bot certes for to perseuere longe &thorn;ere in is werkes of &thorn;e deuel.</P>
<P>[2455] &para; To &thorn;is sentence anseward anone dame Pru|dence &amp; seide [2456] examyne&thorn; quod sche &yogh;oure coun|sel. &amp; lat vs see whiche of hem ha&thorn; spoken most resonablelye; &amp; tauht &yogh;oue best consell. [2457] &para; And for als muche &thorn;at examinacions is necessarie Lat vs beginne att surgiens &amp; att phiciens &thorn;at first spaken of &thorn;is matiere [2458] &para; .I. seie &thorn;at Phesiciens &amp; sirurgiens haue seide &yogh;owe in &yogh;oure counsel discretely as hem ouht [2459] in here speche &amp; ful wisely; As to &thorn;e office of hem <MILESTONE N="197b" UNIT="folio">appartene&thorn; to done to euery whiht honour &amp; profit &amp; nouht for to annoye [2460] And after her craft to done grete diligence vn to &thorn;e cure of hem whiche &thorn;at haue in here gouern|ance [2461] &para; And sir riht as &thorn;ei haue anseward wisely &amp; discretly. [2462] riht so rede .I. &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben hihelye &amp; souereingly guerdount for here noble speche. [2463] &amp; eke for &thorn;ei scholne more do &thorn;e ententif bisenesse in &thorn;e curacione of &thorn;ine douhter dere; [2464] ffor albe-it so &thorn;at &thorn;ei be &yogh;oure frendes &thorn;ere for schal &yogh;e nouht suffre &thorn;at &thorn;ei serue &yogh;oue for nouht; [2465] bot &yogh;e auht &thorn;ere after guerdon hem &amp; payen hem here largesse [2466] &para; And as toucheinge &thorn;e proporcion whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e phecisiens encresseden in &thorn;is caas. &para; This is to seine [2467] &thorn;at in maladies is &thorn;at a contrarie is waressched be ano&thorn;er contrarie [2468] &para; I. wolde faine k[n]owe howe &yogh;e vnderstode &thorn;ilke text &amp; what is &yogh;oure sentence [2469] &para; Certes quod Millibeus .I. vnderstonde it in &thorn;is wise; [2470] Riht as &thorn;ei haue done to me a contrarie. So scholde .I. do hem ano&thorn;ere; [2471] ffor riht as &thorn;ei haue venged hem vpon me &amp; done me wronge; Riht so wil .I. venge me vpon hem 
<PB REF="00000539.tif" N="511"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="222"> &amp; done hem wronge; [2472] &amp; &thorn;an haue .I. cured a contrary wi&thorn; ano&thorn;er contrarie</P>
<P>[2473] &para; Lo lo quod dame Prudence. howe lihtly is euery man enclined to his owen desire &amp; to his plesance. [2474] Certes quod sche &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e Phisiciens ne schold nouht be vnderstande in &thorn;at wise. [2475] &para; ffor certes wykkednesse is not contrarie to wikkedenesse. ne ve[n]gaunce is nouht contrari to veng|aunce. ne wronge to wronge; [<I>mais sont semblables</I> [2476] <I>Et pour ce, vengence par vengence, ne injure par injure n'est pas cur&eacute;</I>] [2477] bote euery of hem encrese&thorn; &amp; grege&thorn; o&thorn;ere [2478] Bot certes &thorn;e wordes of phesiciens scholde be vnderstonde in &thorn;is wise; [2479] ffor goode &amp; wykked|nesse bene tuo contraries; &amp; pes &amp; werre. venge|ance &amp; suffrance. discord &amp; accord. &amp; mony o&thorn;ere &thorn;inges [2480] &para; Bot certes wikkednesse schal be warisched be goodenesse. discorde be acorde. werre. be pes. &amp; so for&thorn; &amp; o&thorn;ere &thorn;inges. [2481] &para; And here to &thorn;e Apostel sein Paule in mony place; [2482] He sei&thorn;e ne &yogh;elde&thorn; nouht harm for harme ne wikked speche. [<I>pour maudit</I>] [2483] Bot do wele to hem &thorn;at done &thorn;e harme. &amp; blesse hem &thorn;at sei&thorn; to &thorn;e harme. [2484] &para; And in monye o&thorn;ere places he amoneste&thorn; pees &amp; accorde [2485] &para; Bot now wil .I. speke of &thorn;e coun|sel whiche was y&yogh;eue to &yogh;owe be men of lawe &thorn;e wyse folke &amp; &thorn;e olde folke [2486] &thorn;at seiden al be one accorde as &yogh;e herde beforne. [2487] &para; That ouer al &thorn;inges &yogh;e scholne do &yogh;oure diligence to kepe &yogh;oure persone &amp; to warnyssche &yogh;oure hous [2488] &para; And &thorn;ei seiden also &thorn;at in &thorn;is caas &yogh;owe ouhten to wirchen ful aviselie &amp; with grete deliberacione. [2489] &para; And sir. as to &thorn;e first pointe &thorn;at touche&thorn; vn to &thorn;e kepeinge of &yogh;oure persone [2490] &para; &yogh;e schul vnderstonde &thorn;at he &thorn;at ha&thorn;e werre schal euermore deuoutly &amp; mekely preyen befor al &thorn;inges [2491] &thorn;at ihesus crist of his merci wil 
<PB REF="00000540.tif" N="512"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="223"> haue him in protectione &amp; bien his souereigne helpeinge at his nede; [2492] ffor certes in &thorn;is werlde &thorn;ere nys no wiht &thorn;at mai be counseld ne kepped sufficiantly with|outen &thorn;e kepeinge of oure lor[d] ihesu crist; [2493] To &thorn;is sentence accorde&thorn; &thorn;e profet dauid &thorn;at sei&thorn;e. [2494] If god ne kepe &thorn;e Citee. in Idel wake&thorn; he &thorn;at it kepe&thorn; [2495] &para; Now sir &thorn;an scholne &yogh;e qwite &thorn;e kepeinge of &yogh;oure person to &yogh;oure trewe frendes &thorn;at bene aproued &amp; yknowe; [2496] &amp; of hem schol &yogh;e axen <MILESTONE N="198a" UNIT="folio">helpe &yogh;oure persone for to kepe &para; For Caton sei&thorn;e if &thorn;ou hast nede of helpe ax it of &thorn;i frendes. [2497] For &thorn;ere is none so good a fesicien as is &thorn;i trew frende [2498] &para; And after &thorn;is schal &yogh;e kepe &yogh;owe frome al strange folke &amp; fro lyers; And alweye haue in suspect here companye [2499] &para; For Pers Alphon sei&thorn;e Ne take no company be&thorn;e were of a straunge man bot it so be &thorn;ou haue knowe him of longer time; [2500] And if it so be &thorn;at he fal into &thorn;i compaigne per|aduenture wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;ine assent; [2501] enquere &thorn;an as sotelly as &thorn;ou canste of his conuersacion &amp; of his lif be-fore; &amp; feyneinge &thorn;ine weie seyinge &thorn;ou woldest go &thorn;eder as &thorn;ou woldest not go; [2502] If he bere a spere hold &thorn;e on &thorn;e riht side of him. &amp; if he bere a swerde holde on &thorn;e left side of him. [2503] &amp; &thorn;an schal &yogh;e kepe &yogh;owe wislye fro al suche manere of peple as .I. haue seide &yogh;owe here be-fore. &amp; hem &amp; here coun|sell eschewe. [2504] And after &thorn;is &thorn;an schal &yogh;e kepe &yogh;owe in suche manere [2505] &thorn;at for any presumpcion of &yogh;oure bodely strenge&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;e dispise nouht ne acompte&thorn; nou&yogh;t &thorn;e miht of &yogh;oure aduersarie so lit &thorn;at &yogh;e lette &thorn;e kepeinge of &yogh;oure person for &yogh;oure presumpcion. [2506] For euery wiseman drede&thorn; his enemye; [2507] &para; And Salomon sei&thorn;e. welfull is he &thorn;at of al ha&thorn;e drede [2508] For certes he &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;oruhe hardenesse of his herte; and &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e hardinesse of him self ha&thorn; so grete presumpcion him schal yuel betide; [2509] And &thorn;an 
<PB REF="00000541.tif" N="513"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="224"> schal &yogh;e euer more enconterewaite en-buschementez and al espyaile [2510] &para; ffor as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e wiseman. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap.</NOTE> [2511] he ne falle&thorn; in no perile &thorn;at perilousnes eschewe&thorn; [2512] &para; And al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ou seme &thorn;at &thorn;ou be in secrete place &yogh;it schalt &thorn;ou alweie done &thorn;i diligence in &thorn;e kepeinge of &thorn;i per|son; [2513] &thorn;is is to seie be nouht necligent to kepe &thorn;i person Nouht onely fro &thorn;i grettest enemye bot only fro &thorn;i leste enmye. [2514] Senec. sei&thorn;e. A man &thorn;at is wele a-vised he drede&thorn; his lest enemye; [2515] Ouide. sei&thorn;. &thorn;at &thorn;e litel wesel wil sle &thorn;e grete bull &amp; &thorn;e wilde hert. [2516] And &thorn;e prouerbe sei&thorn;e a litel &thorn;orne mai greue a kinge ful sore &amp; a lite hunde wil holde &thorn;e wilde bore [2517] bot na&thorn;elesse .I. seie nouht &thorn;ou schal nouht be so grete a cowarde &thorn;at &thorn;ou doute where as is no drede [2518] &para; The book sei&thorn;e: &thorn;at somme men haue grete lust to deceyue; Bot &thorn;ei dred to be de|ceyued; [2519] [<I>Apr&egrave;s, tu te dois garder de venin</I>] And kepe &thorn;e from &thorn;e company of scoreners; [2520] for &thorn;e boke sei&thorn;e &thorn;at scorners make&thorn; no company. bot fle here word as venum.</P>
<P>[2521] &para; Nowe as to &thorn;e secunde point. &thorn;ere as &yogh;oure counsellours consell &yogh;ow to warnystor &yogh;oure houses with grete diligence.// [2522] I. wold fein knowe howe &thorn;at &yogh;e vnderstonde &thorn;ilke wordes &amp; what is &yogh;oure sentence</P>
<P>[2523] &para; Millebeus ansewarde &amp; seide; certes .I. vnder|stonde in &thorn;is wise &thorn;at .I. schal warnstore myne house wi&thorn; toures suche as ha&thorn;e casteles &amp; o&thorn;ere manere edifices; &amp; armour &amp; archers [2524] be whiche &thorn;inge. If .I. maie my person &amp; my hous so kepe. &amp; defende &thorn;at myne enemys schal be in drede my hous to aproche</P>
<P>[2525] &para; To &thorn;is sentence anseward a-none dame Prudens warnyscheinge quod sche of hihe toures &amp; of hihe edifices apparteined som time to pride; [2526] And eke men make hihe toures. [<I>et les edifices a grant traueil et a grans</I> 
<PB REF="00000542.tif" N="514"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="225"> <I>despens / Et quant elles sont</I> faites <I>elles ne valent rien se elles ne sont deffendues par saiges et par loyaulz amiz &amp; grans missions</I><MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 19 C xi folio" N="58a:2">] [2527] And vnderstand wele &thorn;at &thorn;e grettest &amp; &thorn;e strangest garison &thorn;at a riche man maie haue. <MILESTONE N="198b" UNIT="folio">As wele to kepen his person &amp; his goodes is [2528] &thorn;at he be byloued wi&thorn; his subiectes &amp; wi&thorn; his nei&yogh;bours // [2529] ffor &thorn;us sei&thorn; Tullius; Thet &thorn;ere is a manere Garnyson &thorn;at man maie venquysschen ne discomfite And &thorn;at is [2530] a lord to be loued of his Cite&yogh;eines And of his peple</P>
<P>[2531] &para; Nowe sir as to &thorn;e &thorn;red pointe; Where as &yogh;oure olde &amp; wise counsellours seiden; &thorn;at &yogh;ow nouht not sodenly ne hastely proceden in &thorn;is nede; [2532] Bot &thorn;at &yogh;owe ouhten purveye &amp; apparel &yogh;owe in &thorn;is caas; wi&thorn; grete diligence &amp; grete deliberacion; [2533] Trewly .I. trowe &thorn;at &thorn;ei seiden riht wisly &amp; riht so&thorn;e; [2534] &para; ffor. Tullius; sei&thorn;e; In euery nede er &thorn;ou be-ginne it; apparel &thorn;e with grete diligence. [2535] Than seie .I. &thorn;at in vengeance takeinge in werre. in Bataile &amp; in warnestoringe. [2536] er &thorn;ou beginne .I. reede &thorn;at &thorn;ou appareile &thorn;e &thorn;ere to; and do it wi&thorn; gode deliberacion [2537] &para; ffor Tullius sei&thorn;e; &thorn;e longe apparaileinge beforne &thorn;e Bataile Make&thorn; schort victorie. [2538] And Cassidorus sei&thorn;e; The garnyson is strongere whan it is longe time avisede.</P>
<P>[2539] &para; Bot nowe lat vs speke of &thorn;e counsel &thorn;at was acorded be oure neihbours suche as done &yogh;owe reuerence wi&thorn;-outen loue [2540] &yogh;oure olde enemyes recon|silede; &para; &YOGH;oure flaterers [2541] &thorn;at counseiled &yogh;owe cer|teine &thorn;inges priuely; &amp; openlye counseled &yogh;owe &thorn;e contrarie; [2542] &para; The &yogh;onge folke also &thorn;at counseld &yogh;owe to do vengeance and to make werre anone; [2543] &para; And certe sir as .I. haue seide be-forne &yogh;e haue gretly erred to haue cleped suche manere of folke to &yogh;oure counsell; [2544] wiche counsellours buene ynowhe repreuede be &thorn;e resons a-forne seide [2545] &para; Bot na&thorn;eles late vs nowe descende to 
<PB REF="00000543.tif" N="515"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="226"> &thorn;e speciale; &para; &YOGH;e schollen first procede after &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> doctrine. of Tullius. [2546] Certes &thorn;e treu&thorn;e of &thorn;is Matier ei&thorn;ere of &thorn;is counsell nede&thorn; nouht diligently enquiren; [2547] For it is wele wist whiche &thorn;ei bien; &thorn;at haue do &yogh;ow &thorn;is trispas &amp; velany; [2548] &amp; howe many trespassours &amp; in what manere &thorn;ei haue done to &yogh;owe al &thorn;is wronge &amp; all &thorn;is velanye [2549] &para; And after &thorn;is; &thorn;an schal &yogh;e examyne &thorn;e secunde condicion; &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at Tullius hadde&thorn; in &thorn;is matiere. [2550] &para; For tullius. putte&thorn; a &thorn;inge whiche att he clepe&thorn; consentynge; &thorn;is is to seie; [2551] who buen &thorn;ei &amp; whiche buen &thorn;ei &amp; houe mony &thorn;at consenten to &thorn;i counsell in &thorn;i wilfulnes to done hasti vengeance; // [2552] And lat vs consider also who bien &thorn;ei. &amp; how mony bien &thorn;ei [<I>et quelz</I> (MS Reg. 19 C xi, lf 58, col. 4)] &thorn;at &thorn;at consenten to &yogh;oure aduersaries [2553] &para; And certes as to &thorn;e first pointe it is wele knowen whiche be &thorn;ei &thorn;at consentine to &yogh;oure hastif wilful|nes; [2554] For treuly al &thorn;o &thorn;at counsel &yogh;oue to maken sodein werre ne bien nou&yogh;t &yogh;oure frendes [2555] &para; Lete se nowe whiche bien &thorn;ei &thorn;at &yogh;e holde so gretely &yogh;oure frendes as to &yogh;oure person; [2556] For al be it so &thorn;at &yogh;e bene myhte &amp; riche; certes &yogh;e bue bot alone. [2557] ffor certes &yogh;e haue no childe bot a douhtere; [2558] ne &yogh;e haue no bre&thorn;ern ne cosins germayns ne none o&thorn;ere nyhe kinred; [2559] where-for &yogh;oure enmys scholden stint to plete wi&thorn; &yogh;owe ne to destruyen &yogh;oure person; [2560] &para; &YOGH;e knowen also &thorn;at &yogh;oure riches most be dispended in diuerse parties; [2561] And what &thorn;at euery whight <MILESTONE N="199a" UNIT="folio">ha&thorn; his parte &thorn;ei wolne tak litel rewarde to vengen &thorn;i de&thorn; [2562] &para; Bot &thorn;ine enemys bien &thorn;re; &amp; &thorn;ei haue many childerne. bre&thorn;ern; cosins; &amp; o&thorn;ere nyhe kinrede [2563] &para; And &thorn;ouhe so were &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddest sleine of hem tuo or &thorn;re; &YOGH;it dwellen &thorn;ere y-nowe to awreken here de&thorn;e; &amp; to sle &thorn;ine persone [2564] &amp; &thorn;eihe so be &thorn;at &yogh;oure kinred be more sikere &amp; stedfast &thorn;an 
<PB REF="00000544.tif" N="516"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="227"> &thorn;e kinrede of &yogh;oure aduersarie; [2565] &yogh;it neuer &thorn;e les &yogh;oure kinred is bot after kinrede &thorn;at bien bot litil sibbe to &yogh;owe [2566] &para; And &thorn;e kine of &yogh;oure ennemys bue nyhe sibbe to hem; And certes as in &thorn;at her condicion is better &thorn;at is &yogh;oures [2567] &para; Than latt vs consideren also of &thorn;e counsellinge of hem &thorn;at counseleden &yogh;ow to taken sodein vengeance; we&thorn;ere it accorde&thorn; to reson or none; [2568] And certes &yogh;e knowen wele naye; [2569] &para; For as be riht &amp; reson &thorn;ere maie no man take vengeance of no wyht bot &thorn;e Iuge &thorn;at ha&thorn;e Iurdiction of it [2570] whan it is graunted him to take &thorn;ilke vengeance hastelye or at|temperellye as &thorn;e lawe require&thorn; [2571] &para; And &yogh;it more ouere of &thorn;ilke worde &thorn;at Tullius clepe&thorn; consentinge; [2572] &thorn;ou schalt consent if &thorn;i myht &amp; &thorn;i power maie consent; And suffice&thorn; to &thorn;i wilfulnesse &amp; to &thorn;ine counsellours; [2573] And certes &thorn;ou maist wele seie &thorn;at naie; [2574] For sekerly as for to speken propurlye we maie do no &thorn;inge bot onely suche &thorn;inge as we may done rihtfully [2575] &para; And certes rihtfully ne maie &yogh;e take no vengeance as of &yogh;oure propre Auctorite; [2576] &para; &thorn;an maie &yogh;e seen &thorn;at &yogh;oue pouer ne consente&thorn; nou&yogh;t ne accorde&thorn; nou&yogh;t wi&thorn; &yogh;oure wilfulnesse. [2577] &para; Nowe latte vs examyne &thorn;e &thorn;rede pointe &thorn;at tullius clepe&thorn; &thorn;e consequent; [2578] &para; &thorn;ou schalt vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e vengeance &thorn;at &thorn;ou purposest for to take his conse|quent; [2579] And &thorn;er-for falle&thorn; ano&thorn;ere vegeance. Perill. werre. &amp; o&thorn;ere damage wi&thorn;-outen nombre of whiche be nouht war as att &thorn;is time; [2580] And as toucheinge &thorn;e fer&thorn;e pointe; &thorn;at Tullius clepe&thorn; en|genderinge [2581] &para; Thou schalt consider &thorn;at &thorn;is wronge whiche &thorn;at is done to &thorn;e; is engenderd of &thorn;e hate of &thorn;ine enmys; [2582] And of &thorn;e vengeance takeing; And vpon &thorn;at wolde engender ano&thorn;er vengance &amp; muchel sorwe &amp; wastinge of richesse as .I. seide ere</P>
<P>[2583] Now sir as toucheinge &thorn;e pointe &thorn;at tullius clepe&thorn; causes. whiche. &thorn;at is &thorn;e last pointe. [2584] &para; &thorn;ou 
<PB REF="00000545.tif" N="517"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="228"> schalt vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e wronge &thorn;at &thorn;u hast receyued ha&thorn; certeine causes [2585] whiche &thorn;at clerkes clepen. Oriens &amp; officiens &amp; causa longinqua &amp; causa propinqua. &thorn;is to seine &thorn;e ferre cause [<I>et la proch|aine</I> [2586] <I>La longtaine est dieu qui est cause de toutes choses</I> / [2587] <I>La prochaine sont ces</I> iij. <I>ennemiz</I> [2588] <I>La cause</I> (Reg. 19 C xi)] Accidentale. was hate. [2589] The causes Material bene &thorn;e .v. wondes of &thorn;ine douhter; [2590] The cause formale is &thorn;e manere of here wercheinge &thorn;at brouht ledders And clomben in att &thorn;ine wyndows. [2591] &thorn;e cause finale was for to sle &thorn;i douhter. It lakked nouht in as muche as in hem was [2592] &para; Bot for to speken of &thorn;e ferre cause as to what ende &thorn;eie scholne come; or what schal be-tiden of hem in &thorn;is caas ne can .I. nouht deme bot be coniectinge &amp; be supposeinge; [2593] &para; For we scholne supp[os]e [<I>que Ilz en vendront</I>] to a wikked ende; [2594] Be cause &thorn;e booke of decrees sei&thorn;e &para; Seldome or wi&thorn; grete peine bene causes / <MILESTONE N="199b" UNIT="folio">brouhte to an hende whan &thorn;ei bene badly be-gonne.</P>
<P>[2595] &para; Nowe sir if men axed me; whi &thorn;at &yogh;e suffer men to done &yogh;owe &thorn;is velanye; certes .I. can not wele ansewer as for no so&thorn;fastnesse [2596] &para; For &thorn;e Apostele sei&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;e science &amp; &thorn;e Iuggement of oure lorde god bene myhty &amp; depe; [2597] &thorn;ere maie no man comprehende ne serche ham sufficeantly; [2598] Nare&thorn;eles be serteine presumpciouns &amp; coniettinges .I. holde &amp; beleue [2599] &thorn;at god &thorn;at is ful of Iustice &amp; rihtwisnes Ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;is be-tide be Iust cause resonable;</P>
<P>[2600] &para; &thorn;i name is Melibe. &thorn;is is to seie a man &thorn;at drinke&thorn; honye; [2601] Thow hast ydronken so muche hony of &thorn;i swete temperal riches &amp; delices &amp; hon|ours of &thorn;is werlde [2602] &thorn;at &thorn;ou art dronken; &amp; hast for&yogh;eten oure lorde ihesu criste &thorn;i creatour; [2603] &thorn;ou hast no&yogh;t done to him suche honour as &thorn;e ouhte; [2604] ne &thorn;ou hast nouht wele take hede to 
<PB REF="00000546.tif" N="518"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="229"> &thorn;e wordes of Ovide &thorn;at seide; [2605] vnder &thorn;e hony of &thorn;e goodes of &thorn;i bodi; is hidde &thorn;e venym &thorn;at sle&thorn; &thorn;i soule; [2606] And Salomon sei&thorn;e; If &thorn;ou hast found Hony; ete of it what suffici&thorn;e; [2607] For if &thorn;ou ete of it oute of mesure; &THORN;ou schalt spewe &amp; be nedy &amp; pouere; [2608] And peraduenture criste ha&thorn;e in despite &amp; ha&thorn; torne awaie fro &thorn;e his face; &amp; his heres of Misericorde; [2609] And also he ha&thorn;e suffred &thorn;at &thorn;ou haste biene ypunysched in &thorn;e maner &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast trespast [2610] &para; Thou hast done sinne a&yogh;eines oure lorde ihesu criste; [2611] for certes &thorn;e &thorn;re enemys of mankinde &thorn;at is to seie. &thorn;e flesche. &thorn;e fende. &amp; &thorn;e werlde. [2612] Thou hast suffurde hem entre in to &thorn;ine [soule] wilfully be &thorn;e windowes of &thorn;i bodye [2613] And hast nouht defended &thorn;e sufficiantly a&yogh;eines here defautes &amp; temptaciouns; So &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue wounded &thorn;i soule in .v. place; [2614] &thorn;is is to seine. &para; &thorn;e dedely sinnes &thorn;at biene entred in to &thorn;ine hert be &thorn;i .v. wittes. [2615] And in &thorn;e same manere oure lorde ihesu crist; ha&thorn;e suffred &thorn;at &thorn;ine &thorn;ree enemys be entrede in to &thorn;ine house be &thorn;e windowes; [2616] And han wounde &thorn;i douhter in &thorn;e same manere;</P>
<P>[2617] &para; Certes quod Mellibe .I. see &thorn;at &yogh;e en|force &yogh;owe mechel be wordes to ouer-come me. In suche manere &thorn;at schal nou&yogh;t avenge me of myne enmye [2618] scheweinge me &thorn;e perils &amp; &thorn;e yueles &thorn;at myhten fal of &thorn;is vengeance [2619] &para; Bot [who]so wolde consider in al vengeance &thorn;e perils &amp; &thorn;e yuels &thorn;at miht sewe of vengancez takeinge [2620] a man wold neuere take veniance; And &thorn;at were harme; [2621] for be &thorn;e venge|ance takeinge buen &thorn;e wikked men deseuerd fro &thorn;e good men; [2622] &para; And &thorn;o &thorn;at han wil to done wikked|nesse; restreyne here wikked purpos; Whan &thorn;ei seen &thorn;e punyssheinge and &thorn;e chastesinge of trespassours</P>
<P>[2623] [And to this answered dame Prudence: 'Certes,' said she, 'I grant you that from vengeance come many 
<PB REF="00000547.tif" N="519"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="230"> benefits as well as many evils; [2624] yet vengeance be|longeth not to "a singulere person," but only to the judges, and to those who have jurisdiction over evil-doers.'] [2625] &para; An &yogh;ite saie .I. more; &thorn;at riht as a singulere person sinne&thorn;e In takeinge vengeance of ano&thorn;er manne. [2626] Riht so sinne&thorn; &thorn;e Iugge if he take no vengeance of hem &thorn;at hit haue deseruede; [2627] ffor Senec sei&thorn;e. That maistere is good &thorn;at reproue&thorn; schrewes; [2628] And as Cassidorye sei&thorn;e A man drede&thorn; to done outrages whan he wote &amp; knoe&thorn; &thorn;at it displese &thorn;e Iuge &amp; &thorn;e souereyngnes; [2629] &para; And ano&thorn;ere. The Iuge &thorn;at drede&thorn; to done riht Make&thorn; schrewes. [2630] And seinte Poule &thorn;e Appostle sei&thorn;e in his epistle whan he write&thorn; vn-to &thorn;e Romayns; That &thorn;e Iuge beren nouht &thorn;e spere wi&thorn;-owten cause [2631] bot &thorn;ei beren it to punysshen &thorn;e schrewes &amp; &thorn;e mysdoers &amp; to <MILESTONE N="200a" UNIT="folio">defende &thorn;e goode men; [2632] If &yogh;e wilne &thorn;an take vengeance of &yogh;oure enemys &yogh;e schol retourne or haue &yogh;oure recours to &thorn;e Iuge &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e Iurdiccioun vpon hem. [2633] &amp; he schal punysshe hem as &thorn;e lawe axe&thorn; &amp; require&thorn;;</P>
<P>[2634] &para; A quod Mellibe; &thorn;is vengeance lyke&thorn; me no &thorn;inge; [2635] I be-&thorn;inke me nowe howe fortone ha&thorn;e norisched me fro my childhode And ha&thorn; holpen me to passe mony a strange place; [2636] Now .I. will assayene here troweinge wi&thorn; goddes grace &amp; helpe &thorn;at &yogh;e schal helpe me my schame for to venge</P>
<P>[2637] &para; Certes quod prudence if &yogh;e wolne wirche be my counseil; &yogh;e schol nouht assaye fortune be no weye [2638] &para; Ne &yogh;e schol nouht lene or borwe vnto here after &thorn;e worde of Senec. [2639] For &thorn;inges &thorn;at bene folylye done &amp; &thorn;at biene in hope of fortune schal neuer come a good ende [2640] And as &thorn;e same Senec sei&thorn;e; The more clere &amp; &thorn;e more and &thorn;e more schineinge &thorn;at fortune is; &thorn;e more brutel &amp; &thorn;e sonner ybroke sche is; [2641] Triste&thorn; nouht in hire for sche is ney&thorn;ere stedfast ne stable; [2642] &para; For whan &thorn;ou trowest to be most sekere or sure of hire 
<PB REF="00000548.tif" N="520"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="231"> helpe; Sche wil Faile &thorn;e &amp; deceyve &thorn;e; [2643] &para; And where as &yogh;e seine &thorn;at fortone ha&thorn; norissched &yogh;ow fro &yogh;oure child-hode; [2644] I. saie &yogh;oue &thorn;at in so muche schal &yogh;e &thorn;e lasse trust in hire &amp; in hire witte; [2645] &para; For Senec sei&thorn;e. &thorn;at what man is norisched be fortune sche make&thorn; him a grete foole; [2646] &para; Nowe se&thorn;en &yogh;e desire &amp; axen vengeance; And &thorn;e vengeance &thorn;at is done after &thorn;e lawe &amp; be-forne &thorn;e Iuge ne like&thorn; &yogh;owe nou&yogh;t; [2647] And vengeance &thorn;at is done in hope of forton is peril|ous &amp; vncerteine; [2648] Than haue &yogh;e none o&thorn;er remedye; bot for to haue &yogh;oure recours vnto &thorn;e souereyne Iuge &thorn;at venge&thorn; al velanyes &amp; wronges [2649] And he schal venge &yogh;oue after &thorn;at &thorn;i self witnesse&thorn;; . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [2650] Leue&thorn; &thorn;e vengeance to me &amp; .I. schal done it;</P>
<P>[2651] Mellibe anseward; I. ne venge me nouht of &thorn;e wronge &thorn;at men han done to me [2652] .I. schal somne or werne hem &thorn;at haue done &thorn;is velany to me And al o&thorn;ere to done me ano&thorn;ere velanye [2653] &para; For it is wreten if &thorn;ou take no vengeance of an olde velanye; &thorn;ou somp|nest &thorn;ine aduersarie to done &thorn;e a newe velanye; [2654] [<I>Et ainsi par mon</I> serement <I>en souffrant len me fera tant de villenie de toutes pars</I> (Reg. 19 C xi, lf 60, col. 2)] &thorn;at .I. myht ney&thorn;e ber it ne susteinge; [2655] And. so schold .I. be oueresett And halden ouere lowe; [2656] For men seine in muchel suffringe schold mony &thorn;inges falle. vn-to &thorn;e whiche .I. schal nouht suffre</P>
<P>[2657] &para; Certes quod prudence .I. graunte &thorn;at ouer muchel suffrance is nouht good; [2658] &para; Bot &yogh;it ne foulowe&thorn; it nou&yogh;t &thorn;ere-of; &thorn;at euery person to whom men doone velanye take of hit vengeance; [2659] For &thorn;at appar|tene&thorn; &amp; longe&thorn; al only to &thorn;e Iuge. For &thorn;ei schal vengen &thorn;e vilenys &amp; &thorn;e inIuryes [2660] And &thorn;erfore &thorn;o tuo Auctoritees &thorn;at &yogh;e haue seide aboue ben only vnderstonden in &thorn;e Iugges [2661] &para; For whan &thorn;ei suffren ouere mechel &thorn;e wronges &amp; velanys be done 
<PB REF="00000549.tif" N="521"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="232"> with-owten punyschinge; [2662] &thorn;ei sompne not a man onely for to do newe wronges; bot &thorn;e commaunde it [2663] &para; Also a wise man sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at &thorn;e Iuge &thorn;at cor|recte&thorn; nouht &thorn;e sinner; commande&thorn;e &amp; bidde&thorn; him to do sinne [2664] &para; And &thorn;e souereignes &amp; &thorn;e Iuges myhten in her londe so muche suffure of &thorn;e schrewees &amp; &thorn;e mysdoers; [2665] &thorn;at &thorn;ei scholden be <MILESTONE N="200b" UNIT="folio">suffrance be processe of time wexen of suche powere &amp; myht; &thorn;at &thorn;ei scholde put oute &thorn;e Iuges &amp; &thorn;e souereignes fro here places; [2666] &amp; att &thorn;e last maken hem lesen here lordeschippes;</P>
<P>[2667] Bot lat vs nowe put &thorn;at &yogh;e haue leue to vengen &yogh;owe; [2668] If &yogh;e be nouht of myht &amp; powere as nowe to vengen &yogh;owe; [2669] &para; For if &yogh;e willen maake comparison vn-to &thorn;e myht of &yogh;oure aduersaries; ye scholne finde in many &thorn;inges &thorn;at .I. haue schewde &yogh;owe aforne &thorn;is; &thorn;at here condicion is better &thorn;an &yogh;oures; [2670] &para; And &thorn;erefore seie .I. &thorn;at it is good as nowe &thorn;at &yogh;e suffre &amp; be pacient</P>
<P>[2671] &para; For&thorn;ere more &yogh;e knowe. &thorn;at after &thorn;e comune sawe it is a wodenesse a man to striue a&yogh;eines a stronger o&thorn;ere a more myhty man &thorn;an him self [2672] &para; And for striue wi&thorn; a man of euen strenke&thorn;; &thorn;at is to seie wi&thorn; a strange man as he is it is a perile. [2673] And for to striue wi&thorn; a weyker man it is foly; [2674] And &thorn;er-for scholde a man fly&yogh;e striueinge as muche as he miht; [2675] as Salomon sei&thorn;e; It is a grete worschipe a man to kepe him fro noyse &amp; strif [2676] &para; And if it so be-falle or happe &thorn;at a man of gretter myht &amp; strenge&thorn; &thorn;an &thorn;ou ert do &thorn;e greuance [2677] Stodye &amp; besye &thorn;e ra&thorn;ere to stille &thorn;e same greuance &thorn;an for to venge &thorn;e [2678] For Senec sei&thorn;e. &thorn;at he putte&thorn; him in grete perile &thorn;at strive&thorn; wi&thorn; a gretter man &thorn;an he him self is [2679] &para; And Caton sei&thorn;e if a man of hiher astate or degre or more myhte &thorn;an &thorn;ou do &thorn;e anoye or greuance suffre hime. [2680] For he &thorn;at ones ha&thorn;e greued &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000550.tif" N="522"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="233"> maie a-no&thorn;ere time releue &thorn;e &amp; helpe &thorn;e; [2681] &para; &YOGH;itt sett .I. caas &thorn;at &yogh;e haue bo&thorn; myht &amp; licence to venge &yogh;owe; [2682] I. seie &thorn;at &thorn;ere bue mony &thorn;inges &thorn;at schold reteyne &yogh;owe. of vengeance takeinge [2683] And maake &yogh;ow for to encline &amp; for to suffre And for to haue paciens in &thorn;e wronges &thorn;at han be done to &yogh;owe; [2684] first &amp; forwarde yf &yogh;e wolne considere &thorn;e defautes &thorn;at bene in &yogh;oure owen person; [2685] ffor whiche defautes god ha&thorn; suffred &yogh;owe to haue &thorn;is tribulacione as .I. haue seide &yogh;owe here before; [2686] ffor &thorn;e poet sei&thorn;e; That we ouhten pacientlye take &thorn;e tribu|lacions &thorn;at come&thorn; to vs whan we &thorn;inken &amp; consideren &thorn;at we haue deserued to haue hem. [2687] &para; And seint Gregorie sei&thorn; whan a man considere&thorn; wele &thorn;e nombre of his defautes &amp; of his sinnes [2688] &thorn;e peynes &amp; &thorn;e tribulacions &thorn;at he suffre&thorn; semen &thorn;e lasse vn-to hime [2689] &para; And alsomuche as him &thorn;ink|e&thorn; his sinnes &thorn;e more heuy &amp; greuous. [2690] In so muche seme&thorn; his peine. &thorn;e lihter &amp; &thorn;e esier vn-to him; [2691] &para; Also &yogh;e owen to enclyne &amp; to bowen &yogh;oure herte to taken &thorn;e pacience of oure [lord] ihesu crist. As sei&thorn;e seint Peter in his Epistles; [2692] &para; Ihesu crist he sei&thorn; ha&thorn;e suffred for vs &amp; &yogh;euen ensample vn-to euery man for to folowe &amp; to sewe him; [2693] ffor he dide neuer sinne. ne neuere ne came a veleyns worde out of his mou&thorn;e; [2694] &para; Whan men cursed him &middot; he cursed hem nouht. And whan men betene him he manessed hem nouht [2695] &para; Also &thorn;e grete paciens whiche &thorn;e seintez &thorn;at bien in paradise haue hadde in tribulacions &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue sufferd wi&thorn;-outen her desert or gilt [2696] ouht muche to stire. <MILESTONE N="201a" UNIT="folio">&YOGH;owe to pacience; [2697] [<I>Aprez moult te dois encliner a pacience ce</I><MILESTONE UNIT="Reg. 19 C xi folio" N="60b:2">] [2698] consideringe &thorn;at &thorn;e tribulacions of &thorn;is werlde bot litel while endure&thorn;; &amp; sone passed biene &amp; gone; [2699] And &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at man seke&thorn; to haue by pacience in tribulacione is perdurable After &thorn;at &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000551.tif" N="523"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="234"> Apostele sei&thorn;e in &thorn;is epistle [2700] &para; The Ioye of god he sei&thorn;e is perdurable &thorn;at is to seie euer lasteinge /;/ [2701] Also trowe&thorn; &amp; beleue&thorn; stedfastlye &thorn;at is nouht wele y-norisched ne wele y-tauht &thorn;at can nouht haue pacience. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [2702] &para; For Salomon. sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at &thorn;e doctrine of &thorn;e witte of man it knowen be pacience; [2703] And in ano&thorn;ere place he sei&thorn;e. He &thorn;at is pacient gouerne&thorn; him be grete prudence; [2704] And &yogh;ut Salomon sei&thorn;e. &thorn;e Angry &amp; &thorn;e wu&thorn;ful man make&thorn; noys; and &thorn;e pacient man attempre&thorn; him &amp; stille him [2705] &para; He sei&thorn;e also it is more wor&thorn;e to be riht pacient &thorn;at to be riht stronge; [2706] And he &thorn;at may haue &thorn;e lorschip of his owen hert is more to preise; &thorn;an he &thorn;at be his force &amp; strenge&thorn; take&thorn; grete Citees [2707] &para; And &thorn;erfor sei&thorn; seint Iame in his apistle &thorn;at pacience is a grete vertue of perfeccione.</P>
<P>[2708] &para; Certes quod Mellibe .I. graunte &yogh;owe dame prudence. &thorn;at pacience is a grete vertue of Perfeccione. [2709] Bot euery man maie not haue &thorn;e perfeccion &thorn;at &yogh;e sechen [2710] &para; Ne .I. ne am not of &thorn;e nombre of riht per|fite me[n]. [2711] ffor myne herte may neuer bue in pees vnto &thorn;e time it be venged .// [2712] And al be it so &thorn;at it was grete perile to myne enemys to done a velany in takeinge vengeance vpon me. [2713] &yogh;it token &thorn;ei none hede of &thorn;e perile bot fulfilden here wikked wil &amp; here corage [2714] &para; And &thorn;ere-fore me &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at men ouht not to reproue me &thorn;eihe .I. putte me in-to a litel perile for to avenge me; [2715] And &thorn;ouhe .I. do a grete excesse; &thorn;at is to saie; &thorn;at .I. do a vengeance outrage be a-no&thorn;er;</P>
<P>[2716] &para; A quod Dame prudence &yogh;e seyne &yogh;oure wil &amp; as &yogh;oue like&thorn; [2717] &para; Bot in no caas of &thorn;e werlde a man schold nouht done outrage ne excesse for to avengen him [2718] &para; For Cassidori sei&thorn;e; That as yuel do&thorn;e he &thorn;at avenge&thorn; him be outrage; As he &thorn;at do&thorn;e &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000552.tif" N="524"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="235"> outrage; [2719] And &thorn;ere-fore &yogh;e schollen venge &yogh;ow after &thorn;e order of riht; &thorn;at is to seine be &thorn;e lawe; nouht be excesse ne be outrage; [2720] Also If &yogh;e wil venge &yogh;ow of &thorn;e outrage of &yogh;oure aduersaries in o&thorn;ere manere &thorn;an riht commande&thorn; &yogh;e synnen; [2721] &para; Therefore sei&thorn;e Senec That a man schal neuere venge schrewnesse by schrewdnesse; [2722] a[n]d if he seie &thorn;at riht axe&thorn; to defende violence be violence; An feihtinge be feyhtinge; [2723] Certes &yogh;e seie so&thorn;e whan &thorn;e defence is done riht anone wi&thorn;-outen interualle or with-owten tarynge or delaye [2724] for to defenden him &amp; nouht for to vengen him; [2725] And it be-houe&thorn; &thorn;at a man putte suche temperance in his defense [2726] &thorn;at men haue no cause ne Matire to reproue him &thorn;at defende&thorn; him of excesse &amp; outrage. [<I>Car au|trement Ce seroit contre droit et contre raison</I> (Reg. 19 C xi)] [2727] &para; Parde &yogh;e wote wele &thorn;at &yogh;e maake no defense as nowe for to defende &yogh;owe. bot for to venge &yogh;owe [2728] &para; And so sewe&thorn; it &thorn;at &yogh;e haue no wil to &yogh;oure dede attemperally; [2729] And &thorn;ere-for me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at pacience is goode &para; For Salomon sei&thorn;e; he &thorn;at is nouht pa<MILESTONE N="201b" UNIT="folio">cient schal haue grete harme</P>
<P>[2730] &para; Certes quod Mellibe .I. graunt wele &thorn;at whan a man is vnpacient &amp; wro&thorn;e of &thorn;at &thorn;at touche&thorn; him nouht &amp; &thorn;at at apperteigne&thorn; nouht to him; &thorn;ouht it harme him it is no wondere [2731] for &thorn;e lawe sei&thorn;e; he &thorn;at is coupable; &thorn;at entre-mete&thorn; him or medele&thorn; him wi&thorn; suche &thorn;inges as perteigne&thorn; nouht to him; [2732] &para; And Salomon sei&thorn;e. That he &thorn;at entermete&thorn; him of &thorn;e noyse &amp; &thorn;e strif of a-no&thorn;ere man is like to hime &thorn;at take&thorn; an hunde be &thorn;e eres; [2733] ffor riht as he &thorn;at take a strange honde be &thorn;e eres is o&thorn;ere while beten wi&thorn; &thorn;e honde; [2734] riht in &thorn;e same wise it &thorn;e resoun &thorn;at he haue harme. &thorn;at by his inpacience medele&thorn; him of &thorn;e noyce of ano&thorn;ere man; wher as it apperteine&thorn; nouht vnto him [2735] &para; Bot &yogh;e knowen wele &thorn;at &thorn;is dede; &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000553.tif" N="525"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="236"> is to seie my greue &amp; my disese touche&thorn; me riht nyhe. [2736] &para; And &thorn;ere-for &thorn;eih .I. be wro&thorn;e &amp; im|pacient; it is no merveile [2737] &para; And saueinge &yogh;oure grace .I. can nou&yogh;t see &thorn;at it myht gretly harme &thorn;eih. .I. take vengeance [2738] ffor .I. am more Richer &amp; myhte &thorn;an myne enemys biene [2739] &para; And wele knowe &yogh;e &thorn;at be mony &amp; he haueinge grete posses|sions bien al &thorn;inge of &thorn;is werld gouernede; [2740] And Salomon sei&thorn; All &thorn;inges obeyne to money;</P>
<P>[2741] &para; Whan prudence had herd hir husbonde to avaunten him of his riches &amp; of his monye; &amp; dispreyse|inge of &thorn;e pouer of his aduersaries; Sche spak &amp; seide on &thorn;is wise [2742] [<I>Certes</I> treschier <I>sires</I>] .I. graunte &thorn;at &yogh;e be riht riche &amp; myhty; [2743] &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e risches bien goode to hem &thorn;at haue wele geten hem. &amp; &thorn;at wele can vsen hem [2744] &para; For riht as &thorn;e body of man maie no&yogh;t leue withouten soule; ne more may it leue wi&thorn;-outen temperale godes [2745] &para; And be rich|es may a man geten him grace; [2746] &para; And &thorn;er-for sei&thorn;e Pamphilles; If any goddes douhter he sei&thorn;e be riche; sche maie chese he sei&thorn;e of a &thorn;ousand men. [<I>lequel quelle veult pour mary</I> [2747] <I>Et de mil</I><MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 19 C xi folio" N="61b:1">] one wil not for-saken hur ne refuysen hire. [2748] &para; And &thorn;is Pamphiles sei&thorn;e al so if &thorn;ou be riht happe; &thorn;at is to seie if &thorn;ou be riht riche &thorn;ou schalt finde a grete nombre of frendes &amp; felawes [2749] &para; And if &thorn;i fortun chaunche&thorn; &thorn;at if &thorn;ou wex pore; ffare wele frenchipp &amp; phelauschipe; [2750] ffor &thorn;ou schalt be alone wi&thorn;-outen any company. bot if be &thorn;e compaigne of good folke [2751] &para; And &yogh;itte sei&thorn;e &thorn;is Pamphiles more ouere; &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;at bien &thorn;ralle &amp; bonde of lignage scholne be maade wor&thorn;e &amp; noble be richesse; [2752] And riht so as be ryches &thorn;ere comen mony godes; Riht so be pouert come&thorn; mony harmes &amp; yuels; [2753] ffor grete pouerte con|streyne&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000554.tif" N="526"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="237"> a man to done mony yuels [2754] &para; And &thorn;ere|for clepe&thorn; Cassidor. pouert. &thorn;e moder of ruyen. [2755] &thorn;at is to seie &thorn;e moder of ouere &thorn;roweinge. or fallinge doune. [2756] And &thorn;erfor sei&thorn; Pers Alphons. One of &thorn;e grettest aduersarie of &thorn;is werlde is; [2757] whan a fre be kinde or of bir&thorn;e is constreyned be pouert to eten &thorn;e almes of his enemye; [2758] &para; And &thorn;e same sei&thorn;. Innocent In one of his bokes sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e sorwe<MILESTONE N="202a" UNIT="folio"> Ful &amp; &thorn;e mys happe is &thorn;e condicion of a pouer beggere. [2759] ffor if He axe&thorn; nouht his mete he deye&thorn; for hungere; [2760] And if he ax he deye&thorn; for schame; And algates necessite constreine&thorn; him to axe. [2761] And &thorn;er-for sei&thorn; Salomon; &thorn;at better is to deie &thorn;an to haue suche pouert; [2762] &yogh;ut sei&thorn; Salo|mon; &thorn;at better is to deie of bitter de&thorn;e &thorn;an for to leue in suche wise; [2763] Be &thorn;es resouns &thorn;at .I. haue seide vnto &yogh;owe; and be mony o&thorn;ere resons &thorn;at .I cou&thorn;e sei; [2764] I graunt &yogh;owe wele &thorn;at riches bene good to hem &thorn;at geten hem wele; &amp; to hem &thorn;at wele vsen hem. [2765] And &thorn;er-fore wil .I. schewe &yogh;owe howe &yogh;e schall haue &yogh;owe; [<I>en amassant les richesses et en vsant de celles</I> (MS Reg. 19 C xi, lf 61, back, col. 2.)]</P>
<P>2766] &para; First &yogh;e schol geten hem with-oute grete desire be goode leyser so-keingly &amp; nouht ouere Hastely; [2767] ffor a man &thorn;at is to desireinge to gette riches; aboundene&thorn; him first to &thorn;eft; &amp; to all o&thorn;ere yuels; [2768] And &thorn;ere-fore sei&thorn; Salomon. He &thorn;at haste&thorn; him ouere besilye to wax riche schal be none Innocent; [2769] He sei&thorn;e also &thorn;at &thorn;e richesse &thorn;at hastely comme&thorn; to a man. Sone &amp; lyhtly go&thorn;e &amp; passe&thorn; fro a man; [2770] &para; But &thorn;at richesse &thorn;at comme&thorn; litell &amp; lytel wexi&thorn; alweie &amp; multiplie&thorn;; [2771] &para; And sire &yogh;e schal gete richesse ynouhe be &yogh;owre witte &amp; be &yogh;oure trauaile vnto &yogh;oure profite [2772] And &thorn;at wi&thorn;-owten wronge or harme; doinge to any o&thorn;ere person; [2773] &para; For &thorn;e lawe 
<PB REF="00000555.tif" N="527"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="238"> sei&thorn;e &thorn;ere make&thorn; no man him self riche if he do harme to ano&thorn;ere wyght; [2774] [<I>Car la loy dit que droit et nature deffent</I> que <I>nulz ne se face riche au</I> dommaige <I>dautruy</I> (MS Reg. 19 C xi, lf 62, col. 1)] [2775] &para; And Tullius sei&thorn;e &thorn;at no sorwe ne no drede of de&thorn;e ne no &thorn;inge &thorn;at maie fall to a man [2776] is so muche a&yogh;eines nature; As a man to encrese his owen profite to &thorn;e harme of ano&thorn;ere man; [2777] And &thorn;ouhe &thorn;e grete men &amp; &thorn;e riche men geten richesse More lihtly &thorn;an &thorn;ou; [2778] &yogh;it schalt &thorn;ou nouht bien ydel ne slowe to done &thorn;i profitt; ffor &thorn;ou schalt in al wise fli&yogh;e ydelnesse; [2779] &para; For Salomon. sei&thorn;e &thorn;at Idelnesse teche&thorn; a man to done many yuels; [2780] And eke he sei&thorn; &thorn;at he &thorn;at trauaile&thorn; &amp; bysi&thorn; him to tilien his londe schal eten brede [2781] Bot &thorn;at is Idel &amp; caste&thorn; him nouht to do no besines ne occupacioun schal fall in-to pouert &amp; deye for hunger; [2782] And he &thorn;at is ydel &amp; slowhe ne can neuer finde couenable time For to done his profite [2783] &para; For &thorn;ere is a versifiour &thorn;at sei&thorn;e &thorn;e ydel man excuse&thorn; him in winter because of &thorn;e grete colde; and in somer be cause of &thorn;e grete hete; [2784] ffor &thorn;es causez sei&thorn;e Caton; Wake&thorn; &amp; enclyne&thorn; &yogh;ow nou&yogh;t ouere mechel for to slepe For ouere muche rust cause&thorn; &amp; norische&thorn; mony vices [2785] &para; And &thorn;erefore sei&thorn;e seinte Ierome Do&thorn;e some goode dedes &thorn;at &thorn;e deuel whiche is oure enmye ne finde &yogh;owe vn-occupied; [2786] &para; For &thorn;e deuel ne take&thorn; nou&yogh;t lihtly vn-to his worche|inge suche as he finde&thorn; yoccupied in good werkes;</P>
<P>[2787] &para; Than &thorn;us in geteinge riches &yogh;e mot fli&yogh;e ydelnesse; [2788] &amp; afterward &yogh;e scholne vse &thorn;e richesse &thorn;e whiche &yogh;e haue getten be &yogh;oure witte &amp; be &yogh;oure trauayle [2789] In suche a maner &thorn;at men halden &yogh;owe nouht scarce ne to spareinge ne to foole large; &thorn;at is to seie ouere large a spender; [2790] For riht as men blam an auarous man be cause of his scarste; &amp; &thorn;inkeinge [2791] in same wise; he is to blame 
<PB REF="00000556.tif" N="528"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="239"> &thorn;at spende&thorn; ouer largely. [2792] <MILESTONE N="202b" UNIT="folio">&para; An &thorn;er-for sey&thorn;e cat&omacr;n; Vse &thorn;e richesse &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast goten [2793] in suche maner &thorn;at men haue no matier ne cause to clepe &thorn;e wreche ne chinche [2794] For it is grete schame to a man to haue a pouer hert &amp; a riche purce [2795] &para; He sei&thorn;e also &thorn;e goodes &thorn;at &thorn;ou haste goten vse hem be Mesure; &thorn;at is to seine spend mesurablye; [2796] for &thorn;ei &thorn;at folely wasten &amp; dispenden &thorn;e goodes &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue [2797] whan &thorn;ei haue no more propre of hire owen; &thorn;ei schapen hem to tak &thorn;e goodes of a-no&thorn;ere man; [2798] I seie &thorn;an &thorn;at he schal ffle auarice [2799] vseinge &yogh;oure riches in suche manere &thorn;at men seie nouht &thorn;at &yogh;oure richesse bue ybered; [2800] Bot &thorn;at &yogh;e haue hem in &yogh;oure miht &amp; in &yogh;oure weldeinge [2801] &para; ffor a wiseman reproue&thorn; &thorn;e auerouce man; And sei&thorn;e &thorn;us in in tuo vers; [2802] Wher-to &amp; Whi beri&thorn; a man his goodes be his auarice And knowe&thorn;e wele &thorn;at nedes most he deye; [2803] ffor [de&thorn;] is &thorn;e ende offe euery man as in &thorn;is present lif; [2804] and for &thorn;at cause &amp; enchesoune Ioyne&thorn; he him or knytte&thorn; he him so fast vn-to his goodes; [2805] &thorn;at al his wittes mowe nouht deseuern him or departe him fro his goodes; [2806] And knowe&thorn;e wele or ouht to knowe &thorn;at whan he is dede he schal not bere it oute of &thorn;e werlde wi&thorn; him; [2807] And &thorn;ere-for sei&thorn; sein Austine &thorn;at &thorn;e Auerouce man is likkened vn-to hell; [2808] &thorn;at &thorn;e more it desire&thorn;; &thorn;e more it swelowe&thorn; &amp; deuoure&thorn;; [2809] &para; And also wele as &yogh;e wolde eschewe to ben ycleped an averous man or a chinche [2810] As wele scholde &yogh;e gouerne &yogh;owe &amp; kepe &yogh;owe in suche a wise &thorn;at men clepe &yogh;ow nouht to large [2811] &para; &thorn;er-fore Tullius sei&thorn;e; The goodes he sei&thorn;e of &thorn;ine house scholde not be hidde ne kepped in close bot &thorn;at &thorn;ei myht ben opende wi&thorn; pite. &amp; wi&thorn; debonarte; [2812] &para; &thorn;at is to sei &yogh;ef hem parte &thorn;at ha&thorn; grete nede [2813] 
<PB REF="00000557.tif" N="529"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="240"> Ne &thorn;i goodes schal nou&yogh;t be so open to ben euery mannes goodes. [2814] Afterwarde in geteinge of &yogh;oure richesse &amp; in vseinge hem &yogh;e scholne alweie haue &thorn;rei &thorn;inges in &yogh;oure herte; [2815] [<I>Cest assauoir dieu conscience et bonne fame</I> [2816] <I>Tu dois donques auoir dieu eu ton ceur</I> (MS Reg. 19 C xi, lf 62, bk, col. 1)] [2817] And for no richesse &yogh;e scholne do no &thorn;inge &thorn;at maie displesaunce to god [<I>ton createur</I>] [2818] &para; For after &thorn;e worde of Salomon. It is better to haue a litel goode wi&thorn; &thorn;e loue of god; [2819] &thorn;an to haue muche goode &amp; tresor &amp; lese &thorn;e loue of his lorde god; [2820] And &thorn;e prophit sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at better it is to be a good man &amp; haue litel goode &amp; tresour; [2821] &thorn;an to be holden a schrewe &amp; to haue grete richesse [2822] &para; &YOGH;it seye .I. for&thorn;er more; &thorn;at &yogh;e scal done &yogh;oure bisines to geten &yogh;owe rechesse [2823] so &thorn;at &yogh;e geten hem wi&thorn; good conscience [2824] &para; And &thorn;e Apostle sei&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ere is no &thorn;inge in &thorn;is werlde of whiche we scholne haue so grete Ioye as when oure concience bere&thorn; vs good wittenesse; [2825] And &thorn;e wise man sei&thorn;e; The substance of a man is ful good whan sinne is nouht in mannes conscience; [2826] &para; Afterwarde in gettinge of &yogh;oure richesse; And in vsinge of hem [2827] &yogh;ow must haue grete besinesse &amp; grete diligence &thorn;at &yogh;oure good name be al weie kepped &amp; conserued [2828] &para; For Salo|mon sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at better it is &amp; more aveile&thorn; a man to haue goode name &thorn;an to haue grete richesse; [2829] And <MILESTONE N="203a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;erfore he sei&thorn;e in ano&thorn;ere place; Do&thorn; grete diligence sei&thorn;e Salomon; in kepeinge of &thorn;i frende &amp; of &thorn;i goode name [2830] for it schal longer abide wi&thorn; &thorn;e [&thorn;an] any tresor be it neuere so precious; [2831] And certes he scholde not be cleped a gentil man &thorn;at after god &amp; good conscience al &thorn;inges left &thorn;at ne do&thorn;e his besines ne diligence to kepen his goode name [2832] &para; And Cassidorie sei&thorn;e &thorn;at it is signe of a goode hert whan a man loue&thorn; &amp; desire&thorn; to haue a goode name; 
<PB REF="00000558.tif" N="530"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="241"> [2833] An &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; sei&thorn; seint Austine &thorn;at &thorn;ere beene tuo &thorn;inges &thorn;at bien necessarie &amp; nedefull. [2834] And &thorn;at is good conscience [2835] to &thorn;ine owen person inwarde; &amp; good loos of &thorn;in neihbour outewarde [2836] And he &thorn;at trustu&thorn; him so muchel in his goode conscience [2837] &thorn;at he dispise&thorn; his good name or loos and rekke&thorn; nou&yogh;t to kepe his goode name; nys bot a cruel cherlle</P>
<P>[2838] &para; Sire nowe haue .I. schewde &yogh;ow howe &yogh;e schol done in geteinge of richesse &amp; howe &yogh;e scholne vsen hem; [2839] And .I. se wele &thorn;at for &thorn;e trust &thorn;at ye haue in rechesse &yogh;e wol men Bataile &amp; werre; [2840] &para; I counsell &yogh;owe &thorn;at &yogh;e be-gynne no werre in trust of &yogh;oure richesse. For &thorn;ei sufficen nouht werres to main|tene [2841] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; a Philosofre That a man desire&thorn; &amp; wil algates haue werre: schal neuer haue sufficeance. [2842] For &thorn;e richer &thorn;at he is &thorn;e gretter dispence mote he make; If he will haue wor|schippe &amp; victorie; [2843] And Salomon sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at &thorn;e gretter richesse &thorn;at a man ha&thorn;e; &thorn;e more despendoures he ha&thorn;e; [2844] &para; And dere sir al be it so; &thorn;at for &yogh;oure richesse &yogh;e mai haue muche folke; [2845] &yogh;utte behoue&thorn; it nouht ne it is nou&yogh;t goode to beginne werre; where as &yogh;e maie in o&thorn;ere manere haue pees vnto &yogh;oure worschip &amp; prophite; [2846] For &thorn;e victories of batailles &thorn;at bien in &thorn;is werlde ly&thorn;e nou&yogh;t in grete nombre of multitude of peple in &thorn;e vertue of man. [2847] Bot it li&thorn;e in &thorn;e will &amp; in &thorn;e hande of oure lorde ihesu crist; [2848] &para; And &thorn;ere-fore Iudas Machabeus whiche was goddes knyht; [2849] Whan he schold feyhten a&yogh;eines his aduersaries &thorn;at hadd a gretter nombre; &amp; a gretter mul|titude of folke; &amp; stronger &thorn;an was &thorn;e peple of Macha|be; [2850] &yogh;it he comford his litel compaigne &amp; seide riht in &thorn;is wise; [2851] &para; As lihtly quod he may oure lorde god almyhty &yogh;eue victori to fewe folke; 
<PB REF="00000559.tif" N="531"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="242"> as to mony folke [2852] ffor &thorn;e victorie of Bataile comme&thorn; nouht be grete nombre of peple; [2853] Bot it comme&thorn; fro oure lorde of heuen; [2854] And dere sire for also muchel as &thorn;ere is noman certeine; if it be wor&thorn;i &thorn;at god &yogh;if him victorie [<I>neant plus se Il est</I> certain <I>se Il est digne de lamour de dieu</I>] or nou&yogh;t; After &thorn;at Salomon sei&thorn;; [2855] Therfor euery man schold gretely drede werres to be-ginne [2856] &para; And be-cause &thorn;at in Batailes scholne fallen mony periles; [2857] And happe&thorn;e o&thorn;ere while; &thorn;at as sone is &thorn;e grete man sleyne; as &thorn;e lytel man; [2858] &para; And as it [is] wreten in &thorn;e secunde boke of kinges; The dedes of Bataile been aduenterous &amp; vncertein; [2859] ffor as lyhtly as one is hurte wi&thorn; a spere <MILESTONE N="203b" UNIT="folio">as a-no&thorn;er; [2860] And &thorn;ere-fore it is grete perile in werre &para; Ther-fore scholde men flee &amp; eschewe werre in as muchel as a man maie goodly; [2861] &para; For Salomon sei&thorn;e he &thorn;at loue&thorn; perile; schal fal in perile</P>
<P>[2862] &para; After &thorn;at dame Prudence had spoken in &thorn;is manere Mellibe anseward &amp; seide; [2863] &para; I. see wele dame Prudence &thorn;at be &yogh;owre faire wordes &amp; be &yogh;oure resouns &thorn;at [<I>vous mettez</I> auant <I>que</I>] &thorn;e werre like&thorn; &yogh;ow no &thorn;inge; [2864] Bot .I. haue nouht &yogh;it herde &yogh;oure wise counsele how .I. schal do in &thorn;is nede;</P>
<P>[2865] &para; Certes quod sche .I. counseile &yogh;owe to accorde with &yogh;oure aduersaries &amp; &thorn;at &yogh;e haue pees wi&thorn; hem; [2866] &para; For <NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Seneques,</I>, MS Reg. 19 C xi, lf 63, col. 2</NOTE> seinte Iames sei&thorn;e [<I>en ses epistre</I>] &thorn;at be concorde &amp; pees &thorn;at smale Richesse waxen grete [2867] And be debate &amp; discorde grete riches fallen doune; [2868] And &yogh;e knowen &thorn;at of &thorn;e grettest &amp; most souereine &thorn;inge &thorn;at is in &thorn;is werlde is vnite &amp; pees; [2869] &para; And &thorn;erfore seide oure lorde ihesu crist to his Apostles in &thorn;is wise [2870] &para; Wel happy &amp; blissed be &thorn;ei &thorn;at louen &amp; purchasen pees; For &thorn;ei bien cleped &thorn;e childerne of god; [2871] &para; A quod Mellibe; Nowe .I. se wele &yogh;e loue nouht my honour ne my worschippe. [2872] &YOGH;e knowen wele &thorn;at myne 
<PB REF="00000560.tif" N="532"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="243"> aduersaries haue begon &thorn;is debate. [<I>et la brigue par leur oultraige</I>] [2873] And &yogh;e seen wele &thorn;at &thorn;ei neuer queren ne preyne me nouht of pees; ne &thorn;ei axe me nouht to be recon|siled; [2874] Wil &yogh;e &thorn;an &thorn;at .I. go meke me &amp; obeye me to hem &amp; crye hem Mercye; [2875] ffor so&thorn;e &thorn;at were not my worschipe; [2876] ffor riht as men seine &thorn;at ouer grete humblesse engender&thorn; despisinge. So fare&thorn;e it be to grete humilite &amp; mekenesse</P>
<P>[2877] &para; &THORN;an by-gan dam prudence to make sem|blante of wra&thorn;&thorn;e; &amp; seide [2878] certes sire saue &yogh;oure grace; I loue &yogh;oure honour &amp; &yogh;oure profite as .I. do myn owen. &amp; euer haue done [2879] ne &yogh;e ne none o&thorn;ere sawe neuer &thorn;e contrarye; [2880] &para; And. &yogh;it if .I. hadde seide &yogh;e scholde haue purchased &thorn;e pees &amp; &thorn;e reconsiliacion; I. hadde nouht mechel mestaken me ne .I. saide amys; [2881] ffor &thorn;e wise man sei&thorn;e. The dis|cencion be-ginne&thorn; be ano&thorn;ere man; &amp; &thorn;e reconsileinge be-ginne&thorn; be &thorn;i self [2882] &para; An &thorn;e profet sei&thorn;e; fflye schrewdenesse &amp; do goodnesse; [2883] Seche pees &amp; folowe it in al so muche as in &thorn;e is; [2884] &YOGH;it sei&thorn; he nouht &yogh;e schollen &thorn;e ra&thorn;er pursewe to &yogh;oure aduersarie &thorn;an &thorn;ei schollen to &yogh;owe [2885] &para; for .I. knowe wele &yogh;e bene so harde y-herted &thorn;at &yogh;e wil do no &thorn;inge for me. [2886] &para; And Salomon. sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at he &thorn;at ha&thorn;e ouer harde an hert; atte &thorn;e last he schal myshapp &amp; mystide;</P>
<P>[2887] Whan Mellibe had herde dame produce maake semblant of wra&thorn;&thorn;e he seide in &thorn;is wise. [2888] Dame .I. preie &yogh;owe &thorn;at &yogh;e be nouht displesed of &thorn;inges &thorn;at .I. seie &yogh;owe [2889] &para; For &yogh;e knowe wele &thorn;at .I. [am] angry &amp; wro&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;at is no wonder [2890] And &thorn;o &thorn;at been wro&thorn;e weten nouht wele what &thorn;ei done; ne what &thorn;ei seine; [2891] Where-fore &thorn;e prophete sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at troubled eyen haue none clere siht [2892] Bot sitte&thorn;e &amp; counsele&thorn; me riht as &yogh;e list; For; I am redy to done riht as &yogh;e wol desire [2893] &para; And if &yogh;e reproue me of my folye .I. am more holden to loue &yogh;owe &amp; to preise 
<PB REF="00000561.tif" N="533"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="244"> &yogh;owe. [2894] For Salomon sei&thorn;e he &thorn;at reproue&thorn; him &thorn;at do&thorn; folye [2895] he schal finde gretter grace &thorn;an he &thorn;at disceyue&thorn; him be wordes.</P>
<P>[2896] Than seide dame Prudence .I. make no sembland of wra&thorn;&thorn;e ne of anger bot for &yogh;oure owen profit. [2897] For Salomon sei&thorn;e <MILESTONE N="204a" UNIT="folio">&para; He is more wor&thorn;e &thorn;at re|proue&thorn; or chide&thorn; a foole for his foly scheweinge him semblant of wra&thorn;&thorn;e; [2898] &thorn;an he &thorn;at supporte&thorn; him &amp; preise&thorn; him in his mys-doinge &amp; lauhe&thorn; att his folye [2899] &para; And &thorn;is salomon sei&thorn; affterwarde; &thorn;at by &thorn;e sorweful visage of man; &thorn;at is to seye; be &thorn;e sory &amp; &thorn;e heuy countenance of a man [2900] &thorn;e foole correcte&thorn; &amp; amende him selfe</P>
<P>[2901] &para; Than seide Mellibe; &para; I schal nouht kon An|sewere vn-to so mony resons as &yogh;e putte&thorn; to me &amp; schewe&thorn;; [2902] sei&thorn;e schortly &yogh;oure will &amp; &yogh;oure con|seile And .I. am redy . to ffulfille &amp; performe</P>
<P>[2903] &para; Than Dame Prudence discouerd all hire will vn-to him &amp; seide; [2904] I counsel &yogh;owe quod sche abouen all &thorn;inge; &thorn;at &yogh;e maken pes be-twene god &amp; &yogh;owe; [2905] &amp; be&thorn;e reconsilede vn-to him &amp; to his grace [2906] For as .I. haue seide &yogh;owe here be-forne; God ha&thorn;e suffred &yogh;owe to haue &thorn;is tribulacione &amp; disese . for &yogh;oure sinnes; [2907] And if &yogh;e done as .I. seie &yogh;owe god will sende &yogh;owre aduersaries vnto &yogh;owe; [2908] &amp; maaken hem to fallen att &yogh;oure fete rede to done &yogh;oure will &amp; youre com|mandement [2909] &para; For Salomon sei&thorn;e whan &thorn;e con|dicione is plesant &amp; likeande vnto god; [2910] He chaunge&thorn; &thorn;e hertes of mannes aduersaries; &amp; con|streyne&thorn; hem to besechen him of pees &amp; of grace; [2911] &amp; .I. praye &yogh;owe lete me speke wi&thorn; &yogh;oure aduersaries in priue place; [2912] for &thorn;ei schol not knowe &thorn;at it be &yogh;oure will or &yogh;oure assent; [2913] And &thorn;an whan .I. knowe her wil and here assent; I. may counsel &yogh;oue more surely;</P>
<P>[2914] &para; Dame quod Mellibe; do&thorn;e &yogh;oure will &amp; 
<PB REF="00000562.tif" N="534"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="245"> &yogh;oure likeinge . [2915] For .I. putte me holy in &yogh;oure disposicione &amp; ordinance.</P>
<P>[2916] &para; Than dame prudence whan sche sawe &thorn;e good wil of of hire husbonde; Sche delyuerly toke a-vise in her self [2917] &thorn;inkinge howe sche myht bringe &thorn;is neede vnto a good conclusione &amp; to a good ende; [2918] And whan sche sawe hire time; sche sente for &thorn;e aduersaries to come to hire into A priue place; [2919] And schewde wisely vnto hem &thorn;e grete goodenesse &thorn;at comme&thorn; of Pees; [2920] And &thorn;e grete harmes &amp; perils &thorn;at bene in werre; [2921] And seiden to hem in goodely manere howe &thorn;at hem au&yogh;ten to haue grete re|pentance [2922] of &thorn;e iniury &amp; &thorn;e wronge &thorn;at &thorn;ei hadden done to Mellibe here lorde an vnto hire &amp; vnto hire douhtere;</P>
<P>[2923] And whan &thorn;ei herden &thorn;e good wordes of dame prudence; [2924] &thorn;ei weren so supprised &amp; rauysshed &amp; hadden so grete Ioye of hire &thorn;at wonder was to tell; [2925] &para; A lady quod &thorn;ei &yogh;e haue schewde vn-to vs &thorn;e blisse of swettnesse after &thorn;e sawe of dauid &thorn;e profette; [2926] For &thorn;e reconsileinge whiche &thorn;at we ne be not wor&thorn;i to haue in no manere; [2927] &para; Bot we ouhten to require it wi&thorn;e grete contricione &amp; humilite; [2928] &yogh;e of &yogh;oure grete goodnesse haue presented vnto vs; [2929] &para; Nowe see we wele &thorn;at &thorn;e conscience &amp; &thorn;e conynge of Salomon is ful trewe . [2930] For he sei&thorn;e &thorn;at swette wordes multiplien &amp; encresen frendes; And maken schrewes to be debonaire &amp; meke;</P>
<P>[2931] &para; Certe quod &thorn;ei we putte oure dede &amp; al oure matier &amp; cause &amp; holy in-to &yogh;owre good wille; [2932] &amp; bene redy to obeye to &thorn;e speche of &thorn;e commande|ment of my lorde Mellebe; [2933] &para; And &thorn;erfore dere &amp; benyngne lady; we preyne &yogh;owe &amp; be-sechen &yogh;owe as we kon &amp; mowen [2934] &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="204b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at it like vn-to &yogh;oure grete goodnesse to ful-fille in dede &yogh;oure goode wordes [2935] &para; For we considern &amp; knoweleche 
<PB REF="00000563.tif" N="535"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="246"> &thorn;at we haue offended &amp; greued my lorde Mellibe oute of reson &amp; mesure [2936] so fer for&thorn;e &thorn;at we be nouht of pouere to maken him amendes; [2937] And &thorn;ere-fore we oblige vs &amp; oure frendes for to done al his wille &amp; commandement [2938] Bot peraduenture he ha&thorn;e suche heuynesse &amp; suche wra&thorn;&thorn;e to vs warde because of oure offense; [2939] &thorn;at [he] wil enioyne vs suche peyne as we maie nouht bere ne susteine. [2940] &para; And &thorn;er-fore noble lady; we be-sechen &yogh;oure wommanly pyte [2941] to take suche avisemen in &thorn;is nede; &thorn;at we ne oure frendes be nouht disherited [<I>et perdus</I>] &thorn;orwhe oure folye</P>
<P>[2942] &para; Certes quod Prudence it is it is an harde &thorn;inge &amp; riht perilous [2943] &thorn;at a man putte him in &thorn;e arbitracione &amp; Iugement al vtterly; &amp; in &thorn;e myht &amp; pouere of his ennemys; [2944] For Salamon sei&thorn;e; Leue&thorn; me &amp; &yogh;if credence to &thorn;at .I. schal seine; .I. saie [<I>tout peuple et toutes gens et gouuerneurs de gloire</I> (Reg. 19 C xi)] [2945] Ne &yogh;eue neuere &thorn;i sonne ne &thorn;i wif. &thorn;i frende ne &thorn;i self [2946] vn-to &thorn;e hondes ne myht of &thorn;ine ennemye; [2947] And Na&thorn;eles .I. counsel &yogh;owe [<I>Se il a doncques deffendu que on ne donne</I> [<I>puissance</I>] <I>sur soy a</I> frere <I>ne a amy</I><MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 19 C xi folio" N="64a:2">] [2948] By a stronger resone he defende&thorn; &amp; forbede&thorn;e a man to &yogh;eue him selfe vn-to his ennemye; [2949] &para; And na&thorn;eles .I counsel &yogh;owe &thorn;at &yogh;e mistrust nouht my lorde; [2950] for .I. wote wele &amp; knowe wele &thorn;at he is debonaire &amp; meke large &amp; curteise [2951] &amp; no &thorn;inge desirous of good ne Couytous to haue richesse; [2952] ffor &thorn;ere is no &thorn;inge in &thorn;is werlde &thorn;at he desire&thorn; saue worschipe &amp; honour; [2953] For&thorn;ermore .I. knowe wele &amp; .I. am riht sure &thorn;at He schal no &thorn;inge do in &thorn;is nede; wi&thorn;-oute myne counsel; [2954] And .I. schal so werchen in &thorn;is cause be &thorn;e grace of oure lorde god &thorn;at &yogh;e scholne be reconsiled vnto vs/:/</P>
<P>[2955] Then seiden &thorn;ei wi&thorn; o voyce; &para; Worschipful 
<PB REF="00000564.tif" N="536"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="247"> lady we putten vs &amp; oure good al fully in &yogh;oure wille &amp; disposicioun [2956] &amp; bene redy to comme whan it like&thorn; vnto &yogh;oure noblesse; to lemete vs or to assigne vs [2957] for maken oure obligacion; &amp; bynde vs as stronge as it lyke&thorn; vn-to &yogh;oure goodnesse [2958] &thorn;at we maie fulfille &thorn;e wil of &yogh;oue &amp; of my lorde Mellybe.</P>
<P>[2959] &para; Whan dame Prudence had herde &thorn;e on|sewers of &thorn;es men &YOGH;e badde hem gone a&yogh;eine priuely; [2960] &amp; sche retourned a-&yogh;eine to hire lorde Mellibe &middot; And tolde him howe sche fande his aduersaries repentaunt [2961] And knowlecheinge ful reuerently &middot; &amp; lowly her sinnes &amp; tres|pas; &amp; howe &thorn;ei were redy to suffur al peine; [2962] Re|quireinge him &amp; preyinge him of Mercy &amp; pytee</P>
<P>[2963] &para; Then seide Mellibe he is wele wor&thorn;i to haue pardone &amp; for-&yogh;euenesse [<I>qui nexcuse point son pechie</I> [2964] <I>mais recognoist et sen repent et demande indulgence</I> [2965] <I>Car seneque dist la est remission</I> (MS Reg. 19 C xi, lf 64, bk)] wher as confession is; [2966] For confession is neyhbour to Innocence [2967] &para; And &thorn;e wiseman sei&thorn;e in ano&thorn;er place; he &thorn;at ha&thorn; schame of his sinne &amp; knowleche it is wor&thorn;i haue mercy /./ And &thorn;ere-fore .I. assent &amp; conferme to haue pees [2968] &para; Bot it is good &thorn;at we do it nouht wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;e wil &amp; assent of oure frendes;</P>
<P>[2969] &para; &thorn;an was Prudence riht gladde &amp; ioyful &amp; seide; [2970] Certes sir quod sche &yogh;e haue goodely &amp; wele ansewarde [2971] &para; For riht as be counsel. assent &amp; helpeinge of &yogh;oure frendes &yogh;e haue be stired to venge &yogh;owe &amp; maake werre [2972] Riht so wi&thorn;|outen hire counsel schol &yogh;e nouht accor; &thorn;owhe &yogh;e ne haue pees wi&thorn; &yogh;oure aduersa<MILESTONE N="205a" UNIT="folio"> ries; [2973] ffor &thorn;e lawe sey&thorn;e; Ther is no &thorn;inge so good be waie of kinde As &thorn;inge to bene vnbounden by him &thorn;at it was y-boundende;</P>
<P>[2974] And &thorn;an dame Prudence wi&thorn;e-outen delaye or taryinge sent anone Messageres for here kinne &amp; for hire olde frendes &thorn;at were trewe &amp; wise [2975] 
<PB REF="00000565.tif" N="537"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="248"> And tolde hem be order in &thorn;e presence of Mellebe al &thorn;e Matier as it was abouen expressed &amp; declared; [2976] And preyden hem &thorn;at &thorn;e wolde &yogh;euen hire a wise coun|seile what best were to done in &thorn;is matiere; [2977] &para; And whan Millebes counsel hadd taken hire a-vise &amp; goode deliber|acione of &thorn;e forseide matier; [2978] And hadde examyned it be grete besines &amp; grete diligence; [2979] &thorn;ei &yogh;auen ful counseile for to haue pees &amp; rest. [2980] And &thorn;at Mellibe schold receyue it with goode herte of his aduersaries to for-&yogh;euenesse &amp; mercye;</P>
<P>[2981] And whan dame Prudence hadd herde &thorn;e assent of hire lorde Mellibe. And &thorn;e counsel of here frendes [2982] accorded wi&thorn; her wil &amp; entencion [2983] sche was wonderly glad in hert &amp; seide. [2984] &para; There is an olde prouerbe quod sche sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at &thorn;e godnesse &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist do &thorn;is daie do it [2985] &amp; abide it nouht ne delaye it nouht til to morwe [2986] &para; And &thorn;erfore .I. counsel &thorn;at &yogh;e send &yogh;oure messagiers wiche &thorn;at ben discrete &amp; wyse [2987] vn-to &yogh;oure aduersaries tellynge hem on &yogh;oure be-halue [2988] if &thorn;ei wil trete of pes &amp; of accorde; [2989] &thorn;at &thorn;ei schapen hem with-outen de-laie or tariinge to come to vs /./ [2990] whiche &thorn;inge performed was indede [2991] &para; And whan &thorn;es trespassours &amp; repentinge folke of here folyes; &thorn;at is to seie &thorn;e aduersaries of Mellibe. [2992] had herde what &thorn;es messagiers seiden vn-to hem [2993] &thorn;e were ful gladde. &amp; ioyful &amp; anseward ful mekely &amp; beningly; [2994] &yogh;eldeinge graces &amp; &thorn;onkes to her lord Mellibe. &amp; to al his compaigne; [2995] And schopen wi&thorn;-outen delay to gone wi&thorn; &thorn;e messagiers; &amp; obey to &thorn;e commandement of here lord Mellibe</P>
<P>[2996] &para; And riht anone &thorn;e token her weie to Mellibe [2997] &amp; toke &thorn;e somme of here trewe wordes &amp; frendes to maken fei&thorn; for hem; and for to bien her borwes [2998] &para; And whan &thorn;ei camen to 
<PB REF="00000566.tif" N="538"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="249"> &thorn;e presence of Mellibe he seide hem &thorn;es wordes; [2999] It stande&thorn; &thorn;us quod Mellibe; &amp; so&thorn;e it is &thorn;at &yogh;e [3000] causels and wi&thorn;-oute skil &amp; resoun [3001] haue done grete Iniuries &amp; wronges to me &amp; to my wif Dame Prudence; &amp; to my douhter also; [3002] &para; For &yogh;e haue entred in-to myne howse be violence [3003] &amp; haue done suche outrage; &thorn;at all men knowe wele &thorn;at &yogh;e haue deserued &thorn;e de&thorn;e [3004] &para; And &thorn;ere-fore wil .I. knowen &amp; witen of &yogh;owe [3005] we&thorn;er &thorn;at &yogh;e wil putte &thorn;e punysshement &amp; &thorn;e chasteysinge &amp; &thorn;e vengeance of &thorn;is outrage in &thorn;e wil of me &amp; of my wif dame Prudence or &yogh;e wil nouht;</P>
<P>[3006] Than &thorn;e wysest of hem &thorn;re answarde for hem al. &amp; seide. [3007] &para; Sire quod he we knowen wele &thorn;at we bien vnwor&thorn;i to comme to &yogh;oure courte of so grete a lorde &amp; so wor&thorn;e as &yogh;e bien; [3008] And for we haue so gretely mys-taken vs &amp; haue offended &amp; agilte in suche a wise a&yogh;eines &yogh;oure hihe lord-schippe [3009] &thorn;at trewlye we haue deseruede &thorn;e de&thorn;; [3010] Bot &yogh;it for &thorn;e grete goodnesse &amp; debonarte &thorn;at al &thorn;e werlde wittenesse&thorn; of &yogh;oure persoun [3011] <MILESTONE N="205b" UNIT="folio">We submitte vs vn-to &thorn;e hihe excellence &amp; benignite of &yogh;oure gracious lorschip [3012] and bien rede to obeie vn-to al &yogh;oure commandementes [3013] Besecheinge &yogh;owe &thorn;at of &yogh;oure merciable pitee to wylne consider oure grete repentance &amp; lowe submissione; [3014] And to grante vs for-&yogh;efnesse of owre owtrageous trespas &amp; offense; [3015] For wel we knowe &thorn;at &yogh;oure liberale grace &amp; mercye strecchen fer&thorn;er in-to goode|nesse &thorn;an done owre outrageous giltes &amp; trespasses in-to wikkednesse; [3016] albeit &thorn;at cursedly &amp; damp|nablye we haue gilte a&yogh;eines &yogh;owre hihe lordschippe;</P>
<P>[3017] Than Mellibe toke him vpe fro &thorn;e grounde ful benyngly [3018] &amp; receyued here obligacions &amp; here landes by hire o&thorn;es vppon here plegges &amp; her borwes [3019] &amp; assigned hem a certein daie to retorne vn-to his courtes; [3020] for to accepte &amp; receyve &thorn;e sentence &amp; 
<PB REF="00000567.tif" N="539"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="250"> Iuggement &thorn;at Mellibe wold comande to be done on hem be &thorn;e causes aforne seide; [3021] whiche &thorn;inge ordeint; euery man retourned to his hous /;/</P>
<P>[3022] And whan &thorn;at Dam prudence sawhe her time sche f[r]eyned &amp; axed her lord Mellibe; [3023] Whatte vengeance he &thorn;ouht to take on his aduersaris</P>
<P>[3024] &para; To whiche Mellibe anseward &amp; seide; Certes quod [he]; I. &thorn;enke &amp; purpos fully [3025] to dis|herit hem of al &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue; &amp; for to putten hem in exile for euer more</P>
<P>[3026] Certes quod Dame Prudence &thorn;is were a cruel sentence &amp; mechel a&yogh;eines resoun; [3027] For &yogh;e be riche ynowe &amp; haue&thorn; no nede of o&thorn;ere mennes goode; [3028] and &yogh;e myht lyhtly geten &yogh;ow a couetouse name. [3029] whiche is a vicious &thorn;inge &amp; ouhte be eschewed of euery man; [3030] ffor after &thorn;e sawe of &thorn;e Apostle Couetise is rote of al harmes; [3031] &para; And &thorn;ere-fore it were better to lese so muchel goode of &yogh;oure owen; &thorn;an for to tak of here goode in &thorn;is manere. [3032] &para; For better it is to lese goode wi&thorn; worschippe &thorn;an it is goode to wynne worschippe wi&thorn; velanye and schame [3033] &para; And euery man ouhte to done his besinesse to geten him a goode name; [3034] And &yogh;itte schal he nouht onely keppen him in kepinge of his good name; [3055] Bott he schal also enforcen him alweie to done some &thorn;inge be whiche he may renouelle his goode name [3036] For it is y-writte; &thorn;at &thorn;e olde good lose or goode name of a man is sone gone &amp; passed; whan it is nouht newed ne re|nouelled /;/ [3037] And as toucheinge &thorn;at &yogh;e seyne &thorn;at &yogh;e wol exile &yogh;oure aduersaries; [3038] &thorn;at &thorn;enke&thorn; me muchel a&yogh;eines reson &amp; out of mesure; [3039] Con|sider &thorn;e power &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue &yogh;ouen &yogh;owe vpon hem selfe; [3040] And it is wreten &thorn;at he is wor&thorn;e to lesen his priuelege &thorn;at mysvse&thorn;e &thorn;e myht &amp; &thorn;e pouere &thorn;at is &yogh;ouen him; [3041] &para; And .I. sette caas &thorn;at &yogh;e myht annoye hem &thorn;at peyne be riht &amp; lawe. [3042] whiche .I. 
<PB REF="00000568.tif" N="540"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="251"> trowe &yogh;e may not do; [3043] I. seye ne myht not put it to excution; paraduenture [3044] &amp; &thorn;an were it likly to retorne to &thorn;e werre as it was be-forne; [3045] &para; And &thorn;er-fore if &yogh;e will &thorn;at men do &yogh;owe obseruance &amp; obeysaunce; &yogh;e most deme more curteisly; [3046] &thorn;is is to seine &yogh;e most &yogh;eue mor esi sentence &amp; Iuggementz; [3047] for it is wreten &thorn;at he &thorn;at most curtesly commande&thorn;; to him. men most obeyen [3048] &para; And &thorn;er|fore .I. praye &yogh;owe &thorn;at in &thorn;is necessite; &amp; in &thorn;is nede &yogh;e casten &thorn;ere-fore to ouere-come &yogh;oure hert; [3049] &para; For Senec sei&thorn;e he &thorn;at ones ouere-comme&thorn; his hert <MILESTONE N="206a" UNIT="folio">ouer-comme&thorn; twyes; [3050] &para; And Tullius sei&thorn;e; &thorn;er is no&thorn;inge so commendable in a grete lorde &middot; [3051] as whan he is debon|aire &amp; meke &amp; appese&thorn; him mekely; [3052] &para; And .I. preie &yogh;owe &thorn;at &yogh;e wil for-bere nowe to do vengeance [3053] in suche maner &thorn;at &yogh;oure goode name may be kepped &amp; conserued; [3054] and &thorn;at men maie haue cause &amp; matiere to preyse &yogh;owe of pite &amp; of mercye; [3055] And &thorn;at &yogh;e haue no cause to repente &yogh;owe of &thorn;inge &thorn;at &yogh;e done; [3056] &para; For Senec sei&thorn;e; he repente&thorn; him in yuel manere &thorn;at repente&thorn; him of his victorie [3057] where|fore .I. preie &yogh;owe; lete. Mercy be in &yogh;oure herte; [3058] to &thorn;effecte &amp; &thorn;entente &thorn;at god al myhty haue Mercy vpon &yogh;owe in his last Iugement; [3059] [<I>Car saint Iaques dit en lepistre Iugement</I> (19 C xi.)] wi&thorn; outen mercy schal be to him &thorn;at ha&thorn;e no mercye of ano&thorn;ere wyht;</P>
<P>[3060] &para; Whan Mellibe hadde herd &thorn;e grete skils &amp; resons of dame Prudence; and of hire wise informacions &amp; techeinges [3061] his hert gan encline to &thorn;e will of his wif consideringe to &thorn;e trewe entent [3062] con|formed him a-nane; &amp; assented ffully to worchen after hire conseile; [3063] &amp; &thorn;ongede god of whome procede&thorn; al godenesse &thorn;at him sent a wif of so [grete] discrecione; [3064] &para; And whan &thorn;e daie cam &thorn;at his aduer|saries schold appere in his presence. [3065] He spak 
<PB REF="00000569.tif" N="541"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="252"> to hem ful goodly And seide to hem in &thorn;is wise; [3066] Al be it soo; &thorn;at of &yogh;oure pride &amp; be presumcion &amp; foly . &amp; of &yogh;oure necligence &amp; vnkunynge [3067] &yogh;e haue misborne &yogh;owe &amp; trespassed to me; [3068] &yogh;itt for al so muche as .I. see &amp; beholde &yogh;oure gre[te] humilite; [3069] &amp; &thorn;at &yogh;e bene sori &amp; repentant of &yogh;oure giltes [3070] it constreyne me to do &yogh;owe grace &amp; mercye; [3071] wherefore .I. receyve &yogh;owe to my grace; [3072] &amp; for-&yogh;eue &yogh;owe vtterly al &thorn;offences Iniuries &amp; wronges &thorn;at &yogh;e haue done a&yogh;eines me &amp; myne [3073] to &thorn;is affecte &amp; to &thorn;is ende &thorn;at god of his endeles mercy [3074] wole att &thorn;e time of oure deyeinge for&yogh;euen oure gelte &thorn;at we haue trespased vn-to him in &thorn;is wrecched werld; [3075] &para; For doubtelesse &middot; if we bien sory &amp; repentant of &thorn;e sinnes &amp; giltes &thorn;e whiche we haue trespasede in &thorn;e siht of oure lorde gode; [3076] He is so fre &amp; so merci|ful [3077] &thorn;at he wil for-&yogh;euen vs ower giltes [3078] &amp; bringe vs vnto &thorn;ilke blisse &thorn;at neuere ha&thorn; ende; To whiche blisse he vs bringe &thorn;at blod on crosse for vs spreynde. Qui cum patre &amp;c.</P>
<TRAILER>Explicit Fabula Galfridi Chaucer/ de Mellibeo . Milite</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000570.tif" N="542">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="253">
<HEAD>Incipit Prologus de Monacho.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 206</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan endede was &thorn;e tale of Mellibe</L>
<L N="3080">And of Prudence &amp; of hire benygnite</L>
<L>Oure Oste seide as .I. am ffei&thorn;ful man</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e precious corpus madrian</L>
<L>I had leuere &thorn;an a barel ale</L>
<L N="3084">That goo l lef my wif hadde herde &thorn;is tale</L>
<L>For sche nys no &thorn;inge of suche pacience</L>
<L>As was &thorn;is Mellebes wif Prudence</L>
<L>Be goddes bones whan .I. bete my knaues</L>
<L N="3088">Sche bringe&thorn; me &thorn;e grete clobbed staues</L>
<L>And crie&thorn; slee<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> sleo]</NOTE> &thorn;e dogges euerychone</L>
<L>And breke&thorn; bo&thorn;e bak &amp; bone</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at any neigheboruhe of myne<MILESTONE N="206b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3092">Wil nouht in cherche to my wif encline</L>
<L>Or be so hardy to hire to trespas</L>
<L>Whan sche comme&thorn; home sche rumpe&thorn; in my face</L>
<L>And crie&thorn; false cowarde wreke &thorn;ine wife</L>
<L N="3096">By corpus bones; I. wil haue &thorn;i knyf</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt haue myn distaf &amp; go spynne</L>
<L>Fro day to nyht riht &thorn;us wil sche be-ginne</L>
<L>Alas sche sei&thorn;e &thorn;at euer y was schape</L>
<L N="3100">To wedde a mylkesoppe or a coward ape</L>
<L>&THORN;at wil be ouere ladde wi&thorn; euery wight</L>
<L>&thorn;ou darst nou&yogh;t stonde be &thorn;i wif ariht</L>
<L>&thorn;is is my lyf bot &thorn;at .I. wold fiht</L>
<L N="3104">And oute att &thorn;e dore anone .I. mot me diht</L>
<L>Or elles .I. am lost bot if &thorn;at .I.</L>
<L>Bue like a wilde lione foole hardye</L>
<L>.I. wote wele sche wil do me sle sum daie</L>
<L N="3108">Some neihbour; &amp; &thorn;an go my waie</L>
<L>For .I. am perilous with knyf on honde</L>
<L>Albeit &thorn;at .I. dar hir nou&yogh;t wi&thorn;-stonde
<PB REF="00000571.tif" N="543"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="254"></L>
<L>For sche is bigge in armes be my fei&thorn;e</L>
<L N="3112">&THORN;at schal he finde &thorn;at hire misdo&thorn;e or sei&thorn;e</L>
<L>Bot lat vs passe a-weie fro &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L>My lorde sir monke he sei&thorn;e be&thorn;e merye of chere</L>
<L>For &yogh;e schal tel a tale trewly</L>
<L N="3116">Lo Rouchester stant here fast by</L>
<L>Ride for&thorn;e myne owen lorde breke nouht oure game</L>
<L>Bot be my trou&thorn;e .I. knowe nou&yogh;t &yogh;oure name</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er .I. schal cal &yogh;owe my lorde Doune Iohn</L>
<L N="3120">Or dan Thomas or dan Albon</L>
<L>O&thorn;ere of whatt house be &yogh;e be &yogh;oure fader kinne</L>
<L>.I. vowe to good &thorn;ou hast a ful faire skynne</L>
<L>It is a gentil pasture &thorn;ere &thorn;ou goste</L>
<L N="3124">&thorn;ou ert nouht like a penant or a goste</L>
<L>Vpon my fei&thorn; &thorn;ou ert sum officiere</L>
<L>Somme wor&thorn;e sexteyne ey&thorn;ere sum celerere</L>
<L>Fo[r] be my fader soule as to my dome</L>
<L N="3128">&thorn;ou ert a maister whan &thorn;ou ert att home</L>
<L>No pouer cloistrer ne no pouer novise</L>
<L>Bot a gouernoure a wilye &amp; wise</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-wi&thorn;-al of braunes &amp; of bones</L>
<L N="3132">A wele faringe persone for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>.I. preie to god gif him confusione<MILESTONE N="207a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at firste &thorn;e brou&yogh;t in-to religione</L>
<L>&THORN;ou woldest haue be a tredefoule ariht</L>
<L N="3136">Haddest &thorn;ou as grete leue as &thorn;ou hast myht</L>
<L>To performe al &thorn;i luste in gendrure</L>
<L>&thorn;ou hadest be-geten mony a creature</L>
<L>Alas whi weres &thorn;ou so wide a cope</L>
<L N="3140">God &yogh;eue &thorn;e sorwe and .I. were a pope</L>
<L>Nowht onely &thorn;ou bot euery myhty man</L>
<L>Theihe he were schore hihe vpon his panne</L>
<L>Schol haue a wif for al &thorn;is werlde is lorne</L>
<L N="3144">Religion ha&thorn; tak vp al &thorn;e corne</L>
<L>Of tredeinge &amp; we burel men bene schrimpes</L>
<L>Of feble tres &thorn;ere comme feble impes
<PB REF="00000572.tif" N="544"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="255"></L>
<L>&thorn;is make&thorn; &thorn;at oure heires bene so sklender</L>
<L N="3148">And febel &thorn;at &thorn;ei maie nouht wele engender</L>
<L>This make&thorn; &thorn;at oure wifes wil assaie</L>
<L>Religious folke for &thorn;ei maie better paie</L>
<L>Of venus Payment &thorn;an may we</L>
<L N="3152">God woot no lusshbourues paie &yogh;e.</L>
<L>Bot be nou&yogh;t wro&thorn;e my lord &thorn;ouhe &thorn;at .I. pleie</L>
<L>Fol in game a so&thorn;e .I. haue herd seie</L>
<L>This wor&thorn;i monke toke al pacience</L>
<L N="3156">And seid .I. wil do al my diligence</L>
<L>As fere as soune&thorn; vnto honeste</L>
<L>To telle &yogh;oue a tale or tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L>And if &yogh;owe lust herken hiderwarde</L>
<L N="3160">.I. wil &yogh;owe seie &thorn;e lif of seint Edwarde</L>
<L>Or elles Tregedise furst. wil .I. tell</L>
<L>Of whiche .I. haue an hundre&thorn; in my sell</L>
<L>Tregedie is for to tel a certeine storie</L>
<L N="3164">As olde bokes maken memorie</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at stode in grete prosperite</L>
<L>And is yfall oute of hihe degre</L>
<L>In-to myserie &amp; ende&thorn; wricchedlye</L>
<L N="3168">And &thorn;ei bien vesified comunly</L>
<L>Of sex fete wiche &thorn;at men clep exametrone</L>
<L>In prose eke bien endited mony one</L>
<L>And eke in metric in mony a sondre wise</L>
<L N="3172">Lo &thorn;is ouht &yogh;owe .I.-nouhe suffise</L>
<L>Nowe herkene&thorn; if &yogh;ou luste for to here</L>
<L>Bot first .I. &yogh;oue be-seche in &thorn;is matiere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ouhe .I. be order tel nouht &thorn;es &thorn;inges<MILESTONE N="207b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3176">Be it of popes Emperoure or kynges</L>
<L>And affter her age as me wreten finde</L>
<L>Bot tel hem some be-fore some be-hinde</L>
<L>And it comme&thorn; nowe to my remembrance</L>
<L N="3180">Have me excused of myne ignor&amacr;nce.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER><B>Explicit</B> Prologus.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000573.tif" N="545">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="256">
<HEAD>Incipit fabula de Casibus virorum.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 207, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>The illumin|ated</I> Y <I>goes down to line</I> 3203, <I>in the MS.</I>]</NOTE> wil be-weile in maner of tregedrie</L>
<L>&thorn;e maner of him &thorn;at stande&thorn; in hihe degre</L>
<L>And felle so &thorn;at &thorn;er was no remedye</L>
<L N="3184">To bringe hem out of her aduersite</L>
<L>For certeyne whan &thorn;at fortune luste to flye</L>
<L>&THORN;ere maie no man of hire &thorn;e course wi&thorn;-holde</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3188">Be&thorn;e war By &thorn;is ensample &yogh;onge &amp; olde</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Primo de Lucifero</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Lucifer &thorn;ouhe he an angele were</L>
<L>And nouht a man att him .I. wil beginne</L>
<L>For &thorn;eihe fort&omacr;n maie none angel dere</L>
<L N="3192">Frome hihe degre &yogh;it fell he fro his sinne</L>
<L>Doune in-to hell where as he &yogh;itte is inne</L>
<L>O lucifer brihtest of aungeles all</L>
<L>Nowe ert &thorn;ou Sathanas &thorn;at maist not twynne</L>
<L N="3196">Owte of misery in whiche &thorn;ou ert fall</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Adame . primo homine .</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo Adam in &thorn;e felde of Damasene</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; goddes owen fingere wrouht was he</L>
<L>And nouht begeten of mannes sperme vnclene</L>
<L N="3200">And welde al Paradise saueinge o tre</L>
<L>Hadd neuer werldly man so hihe degre</L>
<L>As Adam til he for his gouernance</L>
<L>Was dreven oute of his hihe prosperite</L>
<L N="3204">To labure &amp; to hell &amp; to muschance.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000574.tif" N="546"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="257">
<HEAD>De Sampsone</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo Sampson whiche was annunciate</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e Angel longe ar his natiuite</L>
<L>And was god almyhty consecrate</L>
<L N="3208">And stode in noblesse whiles he myht see</L>
<L>Was neuer suche ano&thorn;er as was he</L>
<L>To speke of strenke&thorn; &amp; &thorn;er-to hardinesse</L>
<L>Bott to his wif told he his secre.</L>
<L N="3212">&thorn;oruhe whiche he slouhe him self &thorn;oruh wrechednesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sampson &thorn;is nobble &amp; myhty champion<MILESTONE N="208a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen wepe saue his hondes tueye</L>
<L>He slowhe and al to-rent &thorn;e lyon</L>
<L N="3216">To-ward his weddynge walkinge be &thorn;e waie</L>
<L>He false wif cou&thorn;e him plese &amp; preie</L>
<L>Til sche his counseile knewe &amp; sche vntrewe</L>
<L>Vn-to his foos his consel gan be-wreye</L>
<L N="3220">And him for-soke &amp; toke a no&thorn;er newe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; An .C. foxes to Sampson for ire</L>
<L>And al her tailes he to-geder bonde</L>
<L>And sette &thorn;e fox tailes al on fire</L>
<L N="3224">For he in euery taile hadde putt a bronde</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei brente al &thorn;e cornes in &thorn;at lande</L>
<L>And al here Oliues &amp; here vines eke</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand men eke he slowhe wi&thorn; his honde</L>
<L N="3228">And hadde ne wepen bot an asse cheke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When &thorn;ei were sleine so &thorn;ersted him &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Was nyhe lorne for whiche he gan to preie</L>
<L>&thorn;at god wolde of his peine sum pite</L>
<L N="3232">And send him drinke or elles most he dye</L>
<L>And of &thorn;is asse cheke &thorn;at was so drye</L>
<L>oute of a wange to&thorn;e spron anone a welle</L>
<L>Of whiche he dranke . ynouhe schortly to seie</L>
<L N="3236">Thus help him god as Iudicum can telle
<PB REF="00000575.tif" N="547"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="258"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Be verrei force att Gasan in a nyhte</L>
<L>Maugre &thorn;e felistiens of &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>The gates of &thorn;e toune he ha&thorn;e vp pliht</L>
<L N="3240">And on his bakke; y-karid hem ha&thorn; he</L>
<L>Hihe on hulle wher as men miht se</L>
<L>O noble almyhty sampson leue &amp; dere</L>
<L>&thorn;at stronge &amp; noble ha&thorn; bue</L>
<L N="3244">In al &thorn;is werlde ne was &thorn;ere neuer &thorn;i pere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Samson neuer si&thorn;er dranke ne wyne</L>
<L>Ne on hi[s] hede cam rasure none ne schere</L>
<L>Be precepte of &thorn;e Messagier diuine</L>
<L N="3248">For al his strenke&thorn; was in his here</L>
<L>And fully tuenty &yogh;ere be &yogh;ere</L>
<L>He hadde of Israel &thorn;e gouernance</L>
<L>Bot after sone schal he wepe mony a tere<MILESTONE N="208b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3252">For womman schal bringe him to meschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vnto his lemman Dalida he tolde</L>
<L>&thorn;at in his heres al his strenke&thorn; laye</L>
<L>And falsly to his fomen sche him solde</L>
<L N="3256">And slepeinge vpon hir berme vpon a daie</L>
<L>Sche maade to clippe or schere his here a-waie</L>
<L>And maade his fomen al his craft to spyen</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ei him fonde in suche araie</L>
<L N="3260">&THORN;ei bonde him fast &amp; put oute his ey&yogh;en</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot er his here was clepped or y-schaue</L>
<L>&thorn;ere was no bonde &thorn;at myht him bynde</L>
<L>Bott now is he in prisone put in a kaue</L>
<L N="3264">Where as &thorn;ei maden him att &thorn;e queren grinde</L>
<L>O noble Sampson stronkest of mankinde</L>
<L>O whilom Iuge in glorie &amp; richesse</L>
<L>Now maist &thorn;ou wepe with &thorn;ine yne blinde</L>
<L N="3268">Se&thorn;en &thorn;ou ert fro wel&thorn;e fal in-to wrechednesse
<PB REF="00000576.tif" N="548"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="259"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The ende of &thorn;is caitifs was as .I. schal seie</L>
<L>His fomen maade a feste vpon a daie</L>
<L>And maden him as her fole to-forne him pleie</L>
<L N="3272">And &thorn;is was [in] a temple of a grete araie</L>
<L>Bot att &thorn;e last he maade a foul affraie</L>
<L>For he tuo postes schoke &amp; maade hem fall</L>
<L>And doune fell &thorn;e temple &amp; al &thorn;er it laie</L>
<L N="3276">And slowe him selfe &amp; eke his fomen all</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This is to seie &thorn;e princes euerychon</L>
<L>And eke a &thorn;ousand bodis was &thorn;ere sleyne</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; fallinge of &thorn;e grete temple of stone</L>
<L N="3280">Of Sampson ne wil .I. no more seyne</L>
<L>Be ware of &thorn;is ensample olde &amp; pleyne</L>
<L>&thorn;at no man tel her counsel til he[r] wyues</L>
<L>Of suche &thorn;inge as &thorn;e wolde haue secre feyne</L>
<L N="3284">If &thorn;at it touche her lymes or her lyues</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Ercule.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of Ercule &thorn;e souereine conqueroure</L>
<L>Syngen his werkes lewde &amp; hihe renonone</L>
<L>For in his time of strenge&thorn; he bare &thorn;e floure</L>
<L N="3288">He slowhe &amp; raft &thorn;e scynne fro &thorn;e lyone.</L>
<L>He of Centaurus leide &thorn;e bost a doune<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<MILESTONE N="209a" UNIT="folio"> <I>It repeats</I> &para; He slouhe &amp; raft &thorn;e skynne fro &thorn;e lyon]</NOTE></L>
<L>He arpies slowhe &thorn;e cruel birdes fell</L>
<L>He golden apelles raft &thorn;e dragoune</L>
<L N="3292">He drouhe oute Serberous &thorn;e hounde of hell</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He slowhe &thorn;e cruel tyrant Buserus</L>
<L>And maade his hors to frete him flesche &amp; bone</L>
<L>He slouhe &thorn;e verrey serpent venemous</L>
<L N="3296">Of Achilles tuo hornes brak he one</L>
<L>And he slowhe Cacus in a kaue of stone</L>
<L>He slowhe &thorn;e Gyant Anteus &thorn;e stronge</L>
<L>He slowhe &thorn;e Grisely bore &amp; &thorn;at anone</L>
<L N="3300">And bare &thorn;e hede vpon his neke longe
<PB REF="00000577.tif" N="549"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="260"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Was neuere whihite sen &thorn;e werlde be-gan</L>
<L>That slouhe so mony monstres as did he</L>
<L>&thorn;oruhe-oute &thorn;is wide werlde his name ranne</L>
<L N="3304">What for his streynke&thorn; &amp; his bounte</L>
<L>And euerye . Realme went he for to see</L>
<L>He was so stronge &thorn;at noman miht him lette</L>
<L>A-boue &thorn;e werldes ende sei&thorn;e trophe</L>
<L N="3308">In stede of bondes he a piler sette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A lemman hadd &thorn;is noble champion</L>
<L>&thorn;at hiht Dianier frische as maie</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e clerkes maade mencione</L>
<L N="3312">Sche ha&thorn; him sent a schert frische &amp; gaie</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;is scherte &amp; walawaie</L>
<L>envenymed was subtily wi&thorn; all</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at he had werde it hafe a daie</L>
<L N="3316">It maad his flesche fro &thorn;e bone fall</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bo na&thorn;elesse s&omacr;me clerkes hir excusen</L>
<L>Be one &thorn;at hiht nescius &thorn;at it Maked</L>
<L>Be as be maye .I. wil hir nouht accusen</L>
<L N="3320">Bon on his bake &thorn;is schert he weres al naked</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at his flesche was for &thorn;e venym blakede</L>
<L>And whan he sauhe none o&thorn;er remedye</L>
<L>In hote coles he ha&thorn; him self rakede</L>
<L N="3324">For wi&thorn; no venym deynede he to deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thus starfe &thorn;is wor&thorn;e myhte ercules<MILESTONE N="209b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Lo who maie trust on fortune any &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>For him &thorn;at folowe&thorn; al &thorn;is werlde of pres</L>
<L N="3328">Er he bewarre is oft y-laide ful lowe</L>
<L>Ful wyse es he &thorn;at him self knowe</L>
<L>Be war for whan &thorn;at fortune lust to glose</L>
<L>Than weyte&thorn; sche hir man downe to &thorn;roue</L>
<L N="3332">Bu suche a weie as he wolde lest suppose
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000578.tif" N="550"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="261">
<HEAD>De Rege Nabugodonosor</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The myhty trone &thorn;e precious tresoure</L>
<L>&thorn;e glorious septre &amp; Roial Maieste</L>
<L>&thorn;at hadde &thorn;e kinge Nabugodonosore</L>
<L N="3336">Wi&thorn; tunge vnne&thorn; maie descriued be</L>
<L>He twyes name iherusalem &thorn;e Cite</L>
<L>The vessel of &thorn;e temple he wi&thorn; him ladde</L>
<L>Att Babiloyne was his souereigne see</L>
<L N="3340">In whiche his glorie &amp; his delyte he had</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e fairest childern of &thorn;e blode Roial</L>
<L>Of iherusalem he dide do gelde anone</L>
<L>And maade eche of hem to bu his clerke</L>
<L N="3344">Amonge al o&thorn;ere Danyel was one</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e wisest childe of euerychone</L>
<L>For he &thorn;e dremes of &thorn;e kenge expounded</L>
<L>Where as in Caldeie clerk was &thorn;ere none</L>
<L N="3348">&thorn;at wist to what fyne his dremes sounded</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This proude kinge lete make a stature of golde</L>
<L>Sexty Cubetes longe &amp; .vij. in brede</L>
<L>To whiche ymage bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge &amp; olde</L>
<L N="3352">Commanded he to loute &amp; haue in drede</L>
<L>Or in a forneys ful of flammes rede</L>
<L>He scholde be bernt &thorn;at wold not obeie</L>
<L>Bot neuer wolde assent to &thorn;at dede</L>
<L N="3356">Danyel ne his &yogh;onge felawes tweye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This kenge of kinges proude &amp; elate</L>
<L>He wende god &thorn;at sitte&thorn; in Mageste</L>
<L>Ne myht him nouht be-reue of &thorn;at estate</L>
<L N="3360">Bot sodanly he lost his dignite</L>
<L>And like a beste him semed for to be</L>
<L>And ete haye as an oxe &amp; leye &thorn;ere oute.</L>
<L>In reyne wi&thorn; wilde bestes walked he<MILESTONE N="210a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3364">Til certein time was comme aboute
<PB REF="00000579.tif" N="551"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="262"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ylike an egle fethers was his heres</L>
<L>His nayles like birdes clowes were</L>
<L>God releued him a certein &yogh;eres</L>
<L N="3368">And &yogh;af him witte &amp; &thorn;an wi&thorn; mony a tere</L>
<L>He &thorn;onked god; and euer his lif in fere</L>
<L>Was; he to done amys or more trespas</L>
<L>And or &thorn;at time leide was on his bere</L>
<L N="3372">He knewe wele &thorn;at god was ful of myht &amp; grace</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Baltazar dicti Regis Nabugodonosor filio.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His sone which &thorn;at hiht Baltazar</L>
<L>That helde &thorn;e regne after his fader daie</L>
<L>He be his fader cou&thorn;e nouht be war</L>
<L N="3376">For proude he was of herte &amp; of araye</L>
<L>And eke an ydolatre was he aye</L>
<L>His hihe astate assured him in pride</L>
<L>Bot fortune kest adoune &amp; &thorn;ere he laye</L>
<L N="3380">And sodanly his regne gan deuide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A feste he maade vn-to his lordes al</L>
<L>vpon a time he maad hem bli&thorn;e be</L>
<L>And &thorn;an his officers gan he call</L>
<L N="3384">Go&thorn;e bringe&thorn; for&thorn;e &thorn;e vesseles quod he</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at my fader in his prosperite</L>
<L>Owte of &thorn;e temple of iherusalem be-rafte</L>
<L>And to oure hihe goddes &thorn;onke we</L>
<L N="3388">Of honour &thorn;at oure helders wi&thorn; vs lafte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His wif his lordes &amp; his concubines</L>
<L>Ay dranken whiles &thorn;eire appetite laste</L>
<L>Oute of &thorn;is noble vessels sondre wynes</L>
<L N="3392">And on a wal &thorn;is kinge his y&yogh;e kaste</L>
<L>And sauhe an hand armelesse &thorn;at wrote ful fast</L>
<L>For fere of whiche he qwoke &amp; sikked sore</L>
<L>This hand &thorn;at baltazar maade so sore agast</L>
<L N="3396">Wrote Mane techel phares; &amp; no more
<PB REF="00000580.tif" N="552"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="263"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In al &thorn;at londe Magecien was &thorn;ere none</L>
<L>&thorn;at cou&thorn;e expoune what &thorn;is lettre meant</L>
<L>Bot Daniel expound it anone</L>
<L N="3400">And seide kynge god to &thorn;i fader sent<MILESTONE N="210b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Glory &amp; Honour Regne tresoure &amp; rent</L>
<L>And he was proude &amp; no &thorn;inge god ne dradde</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-fore god grete wreche vpon him sent</L>
<L N="3404">And him be-raft &thorn;e Regne &thorn;at he hadde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He was oute cast of Mannes compaignye</L>
<L>With asses was his habitacione</L>
<L>And ete hey as a beste in wete &amp; druye</L>
<L N="3408">Til &thorn;at he knowe be grace &amp; be resone</L>
<L>That god of heuen ha&thorn; domynaci&omacr;n</L>
<L>Ouere euery Regne &amp; euery creture</L>
<L>And &thorn;an hadd god of him compassi&omacr;n</L>
<L N="3412">And him restored his Regne &amp; his figure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eke &thorn;ou &thorn;at ert his son is proude also</L>
<L>And knowest al &thorn;is &thorn;inges priuely</L>
<L>And ert Rebel to god &amp; ert his foo</L>
<L N="3416">Thowe dranke eke of his vessels boldely</L>
<L>&thorn;i wif eke &amp; &thorn;i wenches synfully</L>
<L>Dranke of &thorn;e same vessels sondre wynes</L>
<L>And heried fals goddes curssely</L>
<L N="3420">Therefor to &thorn;e schapen grete peine is</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This honde was sent fro god &thorn;at on the wall</L>
<L>&thorn;at wrote Mane techel phares trust me</L>
<L>Thyne Reygne is done &thorn;ou weyest nouht att all</L>
<L N="3424">Dyuided is &thorn;i regne and it schal be</L>
<L>To medes &amp; to perses &yogh;euen quod he</L>
<L>And &thorn;ilke same nyht &thorn;e kinge was slawe</L>
<L>And Darius occupie&thorn; his degre</L>
<L N="3428">&thorn;eyhe he &thorn;ere-to na hadde nei&thorn;ere riht ne lawe
<PB REF="00000581.tif" N="553"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="264"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lordinges here-by ensamples maie &yogh;e take</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at in lordeschippe is no sekernesse</L>
<L>For whan fortune wil a man forsake</L>
<L N="3432">He bere&thorn; awaye his regne &amp; his Rechesse</L>
<L>And eke his frendes bo&thorn; more &amp; lesse</L>
<L>And whan a man ha&thorn;e frende &thorn;oruhe fortune</L>
<L>Mishappe wil make hem ennemys .I. gesse</L>
<L N="3436">This prouerbe is ful so&thorn;e &amp; ful comune.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Cenobia Palmere Regina.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>CEnobia of Palimere &thorn;e quene<MILESTONE N="211a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As writen Persiens of hire noblesse</L>
<L>So wor&thorn;i was in aremes &amp; so kene</L>
<L N="3440">That no wight passed hire in hardinesse</L>
<L>Ne in lignage ne in o&thorn;ere gentillesse</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e kinges blode of perce is sche descended</L>
<L>I seie &thorn;at sche mad nouht most fairnesse</L>
<L N="3444">Bot of hire schappe sche myht bue amended</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fro hire childhede .I. finde &thorn;at sche fledde</L>
<L>Office of wemmen &amp; to wode sche wente</L>
<L>And mony a wilde hertes blode sche schedde</L>
<L N="3448">Wi&thorn; arwes brode &thorn;at sche to hem sente</L>
<L>Sche was so sweft &thorn;at sche a-none hem hente</L>
<L>And whan sche was elder sche wolde kill</L>
<L>Lyons liberdes and beres altorente</L>
<L N="3452">And in hire armes wilde hem att hire will</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche dorst wilde bestes dennes seeke</L>
<L>And rinne in &thorn;e mountain al &thorn;e niht</L>
<L>And slepe vnder a busche &amp; sche cou&thorn;e eke</L>
<L N="3456">Wrastelen be verrey force &amp; verrey myht</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; any &yogh;onge man were he neuere so whight</L>
<L>Ther myht no &thorn;inge in hir armes stonde</L>
<L>Sche kepped hire Maidenhede fro euery whight</L>
<L N="3460">To no man deyned hire to be bonde
<PB REF="00000582.tif" N="554"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="265"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bo att &thorn;e last here frendes haue hire maried</L>
<L>To Odenake a prince of &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>Al were it so &thorn;at sche hem longe taried</L>
<L N="3464">And &yogh;e scholne vnderstande how &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Hadde suche fantasies as hadd sche</L>
<L>Bot na&thorn;eles whan &thorn;ei were knytte in fere</L>
<L>Thei leueden in Ioie &amp; in felicite</L>
<L N="3468">For vche of hem had o&thorn;ere leef &amp; dere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Saue on &thorn;inge &thorn;at sche nolde neuer assent</L>
<L>By no weye &thorn;at by hire scholde he lye</L>
<L>Bot ones for it was hire pleyne entent</L>
<L N="3472">To haue a childe &thorn;e werlde to multeplye</L>
<L>And also sone as sche miht a-spye</L>
<L>&thorn;at sche was not wi&thorn; childe wi&thorn; &thorn;at dede</L>
<L>Than wolde sche suffre him done his fantasy<MILESTONE N="211b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3476">Eft sone and nouht but ones oute of drede<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No breaks henceforth between the stanzas of each Tragedy.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And if sche ware wi&thorn; childe at &thorn;ilke cast</L>
<L>No more scholde he pleie &thorn;ilke game</L>
<L>Til fully fou[r]te dayes were past</L>
<L N="3480">Than wolde sche ones do suffre him &thorn;e same</L>
<L>All were &thorn;is Odenake wilde ore tame</L>
<L>He gatt no more of hire for &thorn;us sche saide</L>
<L>It was to wives lechery &amp; schame</L>
<L N="3484">In o&thorn;ere caas if &thorn;at men wi&thorn; hem pleide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Tuo sonne be &thorn;is Edenok hadde sche</L>
<L>The whiche sche kepped in vertewe &amp; in lettrure</L>
<L>Bot nowe vnto oure tale torne we</L>
<L N="3488">.I. say &thorn;at worschipful creature</L>
<L>And wise &thorn;erwi&thorn; &amp; large wi&thorn; mesure</L>
<L>So penyble in &thorn;e werre &amp; korteyse eke</L>
<L>Ne more laboure miht in werre endure</L>
<L N="3492">Was none &thorn;eihe al &thorn;is werlde men schold seche
<PB REF="00000583.tif" N="555"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="266"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Here riche araye miht nouht be tolde</L>
<L>As wele in vessel as in clo&thorn;inge</L>
<L>Sche was al cladde in perre &amp; in golde</L>
<L N="3496">And eke sche left for none hunteynge</L>
<L>To haue of sundre tonges folk knoweynge</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at sche leyser hadde to entende</L>
<L>To leren bokes was al hire lykeynge</L>
<L N="3500">Howe sche in vertue myht hire lif dispende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And schortly of &thorn;is storie for to entrete</L>
<L>So douhte was hir husbonde as sche</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei conquered mony regnes grete</L>
<L N="3504">In &thorn;e Orient wi&thorn; mony a faire Cete</L>
<L>Apartenaunte vnto &thorn;e Maieste</L>
<L>Of Rome &amp; wi&thorn; stronge honde helde hem fast</L>
<L>Ne neuere myht hire fomen done hem flye</L>
<L N="3508">Aye wile &thorn;at Odenake dayes last</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Her batailles who so lust hem for to rede</L>
<L>A&yogh;eine Sapore &thorn;e kinge &amp; o&thorn;ere moo</L>
<L>And howe &thorn;at al &thorn;is processe fel in dede</L>
<L N="3512">And whie sche conquerde &amp; what title hadd &thorn;ere too</L>
<L>And aftere of hire meschief &amp; hire woo</L>
<L>Ho &thorn;at sche was be-seged &amp; y-take</L>
<L>Late him vnto mi maister Petrak go</L>
<L N="3516">&thorn;at write&thorn; ynouhe of &thorn;is .I. vndertake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; When Odenak was dede sche myhtyly<MILESTONE N="212a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The regnes helde &amp; wi&thorn; hire propre hande</L>
<L>A&yogh;eine hir foos sche fauht trewly</L>
<L N="3520">&thorn;at &thorn;ere nas kinge ne prince in al &thorn;at lande</L>
<L>That he nas gladde if he &thorn;at grace fande</L>
<L>That sche ne wolde vp&omacr;n his lande werrey</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire &thorn;ei maad alliance be bande</L>
<L N="3524">To biene in pees &amp; latt hir ride &amp; pleie
<PB REF="00000584.tif" N="556"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="267"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Emperour of Rome Claudius</L>
<L>Ne him be-forne &thorn;e Romeyne Galiene</L>
<L>Ne dorste neuere be so Coragius</L>
<L N="3528">Ne none Ermyne ne none egipcie[ne]</L>
<L>Ne Surrien; ne none arrabiene</L>
<L>Withe-in &thorn;e felde &thorn;at dost wi&thorn; hir fiht</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;at sche wolde hem wi&thorn; her handes sleyne</L>
<L N="3532">Or wi&thorn; hire meyne to putten hem to fliht</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In Kinges abite went here sones two</L>
<L>As eyres of here Regnes all</L>
<L>And ermanno; and Thimalao</L>
<L N="3536">Here name were as perciens hem call</L>
<L>Botte ffortune ha&thorn;e ay in here hony gall</L>
<L>This myhty qwene maie no while endure</L>
<L>Fortune oute of her Regne maade hire fall</L>
<L N="3540">To wrichednesse &amp; to mysaduenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Aurelyon whan &thorn;at &thorn;e gouernance</L>
<L>Of Rome camme in-to his hondes tweye</L>
<L>He schope vpon &thorn;is qwene to do vengeance</L>
<L N="3544">And wi&thorn; his legions he toke his weie</L>
<L>Toward Cenoby &amp; schortly for to seie</L>
<L>He maade hire flee &amp; att &thorn;e last hire hent</L>
<L>And fetterd hire &amp; eke her children tweye</L>
<L N="3548">And wann &thorn;e londe &amp; home to Rome &thorn;ei went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Amange &thorn;is o&thorn;er &thorn;inge &thorn;at he wanne</L>
<L>Here Chare &thorn;at was wi&thorn; gold wrouht &amp; perre</L>
<L>&THORN;is grete Romaine &thorn;is Aureliane</L>
<L N="3552">Ha&thorn; wi&thorn; him ladde for &thorn;at men scholde see</L>
<L>Be-forne his triumphe walke&thorn; sche</L>
<L>With gilt cheynes on hire nek hangeinge</L>
<L>Corounde sche was as after her degre</L>
<L N="3556">And ful of perre charged hir clo&thorn;inge
<PB REF="00000585.tif" N="557"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="268"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alas fortune sche &thorn;at whilom was</L>
<L>Dredeful to kinges &amp; to emperoures.</L>
<L>Now gaure&thorn; al &thorn;e peple on hire alace<MILESTONE N="212b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3560">And sche &thorn;at elmed was in stark stoures</L>
<L>And wanne be fors tounes stronge &amp; toures</L>
<L>Schal on here nowe were a fitermyte</L>
<L>And sche &thorn;at bare &thorn;e Septer ful of floures</L>
<L N="3564">Schal bere a distaf here cost for to qwyte</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Petro Hispanye Rege.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O noble o wor&thorn;i Petre of spayne</L>
<L>Whome fortune helde so hihe in maieste</L>
<L>Wele ouhte men &thorn;i pitous de&thorn; compleine</L>
<L N="3568">Thi bastard bro&thorn;er maade &thorn;e to fle</L>
<L>And after att a sege be soubtilite</L>
<L>Thowe were betraide &amp; ladde to his tent</L>
<L>Where as he wi&thorn; his owen hand slouhe &thorn;e</L>
<L N="3572">Succedinge in &thorn;i Regne &amp; in &thorn;i Rent</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Betelmewe Claykeynne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Bertrand du Guesclin.]</NOTE>. Oliuer Mawnye</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The felde of snowe wi&thorn; &thorn;e egle blak &thorn;ere-inne</L>
<L>Cauht wi&thorn; &thorn;e lime Rodde colours as &thorn;e glede</L>
<L>He brewe &thorn;is cursednesse and al &thorn;e sinne</L>
<L N="3576">The wykked nest was wirkir of &thorn;is nede</L>
<L>Nouht Charles &amp; Olyuer &thorn;at ay toke goode hede</L>
<L>Of trou&thorn;e &amp; honour bot of Armorekke</L>
<L>Genyloun Olyuer corrupt for mede</L>
<L N="3580">Brouhtest &thorn;is wor&thorn;i kinge in suche brekke.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Petro Rege Cipri</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wor&thorn;e Petre kinge of Cipre also</L>
<L>That Alisander wanne be hihe maistrye</L>
<L>Ful mony an ey&thorn;en wrouhtest &thorn;ou ful wo</L>
<L N="3584">Of whiche &thorn;ine owen leges hadde enuye</L>
<L>And for no &thorn;inge bot for &thorn;i chiualrye</L>
<L>Thei in &thorn;i bedde han sleyne &thorn;e be &thorn;e morwe</L>
<L>Thus gan fortune gouerne &amp; guye</L>
<L N="3588">And out of Ioye bringe men in to sorwe
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000586.tif" N="558"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="269">
<HEAD>De Barnabo vicecomite Mediolano.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of Milane grete Barnabo viscounte</L>
<L>God of delice &amp; scowrge of Lombardie</L>
<L>Whi scholde nouht .I. &thorn;ine fortune a-counte</L>
<L N="3592">Sethen in estate &thorn;ou clome were so hihe</L>
<L>Thine Bro&thorn;er sone &thorn;at was &thorn;ine double allie</L>
<L>For he &thorn;i nevow was &amp; sone in lawe</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-in his prisoun maade &thorn;e to deye</L>
<L N="3596">Bot whie ne howe woote .I. &thorn;at &thorn;ou wer slawe</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; De Hugiline Comyte Pisano.<MILESTONE N="213a" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;e Erle Hugylyne of Pise &thorn;e Langoure</L>
<L>There maie no tunge tel for pite</L>
<L>Bot litel oute of Pise stant a toure</L>
<L N="3600">In wiche toure in prisone put was he</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; him ben his litel childern &thorn;re</L>
<L>&thorn;e eldest scarsly .v. &yogh;ere was of age</L>
<L>Alas fortune it was grete cruelte</L>
<L N="3604">Suche burdes to putte in suche a cage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Dampned he was to deye in &thorn;at prisone</L>
<L>For Roger &thorn;at bischop was of Pise</L>
<L>Hadde on him maade a fals suggestione</L>
<L N="3608">Thorwhe &thorn;e peple gan on him a-rise</L>
<L>And putten him to prison in suche wise</L>
<L>As &yogh;e haue herde &amp; mete &amp; drinke he hadde</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3612">And &thorn;ere-wi&thorn;-all it was ful pore &amp; badde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And one a daie be-fell &thorn;at inne &thorn;at oure</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at his mete was wonte to be brouht</L>
<L>The gayler schette &thorn;e dores of &thorn;e toure</L>
<L N="3616">He herde it wele bot he sawe it nouht</L>
<L>And in his hert anone &thorn;ere fell a &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei for hunger wolde done him deyen</L>
<L>Alas quod he alas &thorn;at .I. was wrouht</L>
<L N="3620">&thorn;er-wi&thorn;e &thorn;e teres fel fro hy&yogh;en
<PB REF="00000587.tif" N="559"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="270"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His &yogh;onge son &thorn;at &thorn;rei &yogh;ere was of age</L>
<L>vnto him seide fader whi do &yogh;e wepe</L>
<L>Whan wil &thorn;e Gayloure bringen oure potage</L>
<L N="3624">Is &thorn;ere no morsel brede &thorn;at &yogh;e do kepe</L>
<L>.I. am so hungry &thorn;at .I. maie nouht [slepe]</L>
<L>Now wolde god &thorn;at .I. myht slepe euer</L>
<L>&thorn;an scholde none hunger in my wombe crepe</L>
<L N="3628">&thorn;are nys no&thorn;inge saue brede &thorn;at me were leuere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;us daie be daye &thorn;is childe gan to crie</L>
<L>Til in his fader berme adoune it leye</L>
<L>And seide fader Fare wele .I. mote deye</L>
<L N="3632">And kissed his fader &amp; deyed &thorn;e same daye</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e woful fader dede him seye</L>
<L>For woo his arme tuo he gan to bite</L>
<L>And seid alas fortune; &amp; walaweye</L>
<L N="3636">&THORN;ine fals whele my woo .I. al wite</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His childern wende &thorn;at it for hungere was</L>
<L>&thorn;at he his arme gnowhe &amp; nout for woo</L>
<L>And seid fader do nouht so alas<MILESTONE N="213b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3640">Bot ra&thorn;er ete &thorn;e flesche vpon vs tuo</L>
<L>Oure flesche &thorn;ou &yogh;af vs tak oure flesche vs fro</L>
<L>And ete ynouhe riht &thorn;us to him &thorn;ei seide</L>
<L>And efter &thorn;at wi&thorn;-inne a daie or tuo</L>
<L N="3644">&thorn;ei leide hem doune in his lappe &amp; deyed</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Him self dispeired eke for hunger starf</L>
<L>&THORN;us endede is &thorn;e mihte Erle of Pise</L>
<L>Fro hihe a state fortune fro him carf</L>
<L N="3648">Of &thorn;is tregedrie it ouht .I.-nouhe suffise</L>
<L>Who so wile here it in a longer wise</L>
<L>Reede &thorn;e grete Poete of Itaile</L>
<L>That hiht Daunte for he can it deuise</L>
<L N="3652">Fro pointe to poynte nouht o worde wil he faile
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000588.tif" N="560"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="271">
<HEAD>De Nero Imperatore.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Al&thorn;ouhe &thorn;at Nero were as vicious</L>
<L>As fende &thorn;at li&thorn;e ful lowe adoune</L>
<L>&YOGH;itte he as telle&thorn; vs swytheneus</L>
<L N="3656">&thorn;is wide werlde hadde in subieccione</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e est &amp; west &amp; septemtrione</L>
<L>Of Rebees safers &amp; of Pereles white</L>
<L>Were al his clo&thorn;es brouded vp &amp; doune</L>
<L N="3660">For he in Gemmis grete gan delite</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; More delicate more Pompus of araie</L>
<L>More proude was neuere Emperoure &thorn;an he</L>
<L>&thorn;at ilke clo&thorn;e &thorn;at he hadde wered a daie</L>
<L N="3664">After &thorn;at time he nold it neuere se</L>
<L>Nettes of gold &thorn;rede hadde he grete plente</L>
<L>To fysshe in tybre whan him luste to pleie</L>
<L>His lustes were as lawe in his degre</L>
<L N="3668">For fortune as his frende wolde him obeye;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He Rome brent for his delicacie</L>
<L>The Senatours he slowhe vpon a daye</L>
<L>To howe &thorn;at men wolde wepe &amp; crye</L>
<L N="3672">And slowhe his bro&thorn;er &amp; by his suster laye</L>
<L>His moder Maade he in pytous araie</L>
<L>For he hir wombe slitte to be-holde</L>
<L>Where he conceyved was so walawaye</L>
<L N="3676">&THORN;at he so litel of his moder tolde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; No tere oute of his eyen for &thorn;at siht</L>
<L>Ne came Bot seide a faire womman was sche</L>
<L>Grete wonder is &thorn;at he cou&thorn;e or miht</L>
<L N="3680">Be domeseman of hire dede bewte<MILESTONE N="214a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The wyne to bringe commaunde he</L>
<L>And dranke anone none o&thorn;ere woo he maade</L>
<L>Whan myht is Ioyned vnto cruelte</L>
<L N="3684">Alas to depe wil &thorn;e venym wade
<PB REF="00000589.tif" N="561"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="272"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In &yogh;ou&thorn;e a maister hadde &thorn;is Emperoure</L>
<L>To teche him letrure &amp; cur[t]esye</L>
<L>For of Moralite he was &thorn;e floure</L>
<L N="3688">As in his time bott if bokes lye</L>
<L>And whiles his maister hadde of him &thorn;e maystre</L>
<L>He maade him so konnynge &amp; so souple</L>
<L>&thorn;at longe time was or tirannye</L>
<L N="3692">Or any vice dorst in him vncouple</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Seneka of whiche .I. devise</L>
<L>Be-cause Nero had of him suche drede</L>
<L>For he for vices wold him chastise</L>
<L N="3696">Discretely as be worde &amp; nouht be drede</L>
<L>Sire wolde he saie an Emperoure mot nede</L>
<L>Be vertuouse &amp; hate tyrantrye</L>
<L>For whiche he him in ba&thorn;e maad to blede</L>
<L N="3700">On bo&thorn;e his armes til he most deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Nero hadde eke of a continuance</L>
<L>In &yogh;ou&thorn;e a&yogh;eine his maister for to rise</L>
<L>Whiche afterward him &thorn;ouht a grete grevance</L>
<L N="3704">There-fore he maade him deye in &thorn;is wyse</L>
<L>Bot na&thorn;eles &thorn;is Senec &thorn;e wise</L>
<L>Chese in a ba&thorn;&thorn;e to deye in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;ere &thorn;an haue a no&thorn;er tormentrie</L>
<L N="3708">And &thorn;us ha&thorn;e Nero sleyne his maister dere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now fel it so &thorn;at fortune lust no longere</L>
<L>The hihe pride of Nero to cherische</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ouhe he were stronge &yogh;itte were sche strenger</L>
<L N="3712">Sche &thorn;ouht &thorn;us be god .I. am to nyce</L>
<L>To sette a man &thorn;at is fulfilled of vice</L>
<L>In hihe degre &amp; Emperour him call</L>
<L>Be god oute of his sete .I. wil him trise</L>
<L N="3716">When he leste wene&thorn;e sonest schal he fall
<PB REF="00000590.tif" N="562"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="273"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e Peple rose vpon him vpon a nyht</L>
<L>For his defaute &amp; whan he hadd it aspiede</L>
<L>Oute of his dore anone he ha&thorn;e him dyht</L>
<L N="3720">Alone &amp; &thorn;ere he wende haue bue alyede</L>
<L>He knokked fast &amp; ay &thorn;e more he cryed</L>
<L>The faster schetten &thorn;ei &thorn;e dores all<MILESTONE N="214b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Tho wist he wele he had him self be-gilede</L>
<L N="3724">And wente his weie no longere dorst he call</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The peple cried &amp; Rombled vpe &amp; doune</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; his eres herde he howe &thorn;ei seide</L>
<L>Where is fals terant &thorn;is Neroune</L>
<L N="3728">For fere al-moste out of his witte braide</L>
<L>And to his goddes pitously he seide</L>
<L>For socoure for it myht nouht be-tide</L>
<L>For drede of &thorn;is him &thorn;ouht &thorn;at he deide</L>
<L N="3732">And ranne in-to a gardeyne him to hide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And in &thorn;is cardyne fonde he cherles tueye</L>
<L>And fatten be a fire ful grete &amp; rede</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e cherles tuey he gan to preye</L>
<L N="3736">To slene him &amp; to girde of his hede</L>
<L>&thorn;at to his body whan &thorn;at he ware dede</L>
<L>Were no despite ydo for his defame</L>
<L>Him selfe he slouhe he cou&thorn;e no better rede</L>
<L N="3740">Of whiche fortune louhe &amp; had a game</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Oliferno principe.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Was Neuere capitaigne vnder a kinge</L>
<L>That Regnes mo putte in subieccione</L>
<L>Ne strenger was in felde of al &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="3744">As in his time none gretter in renoune</L>
<L>Ne more Pompose in hihe presumsione</L>
<L>Than Oliferne whiche fortune ay kyste</L>
<L>So lykerously &amp; ledde him vpe &amp; doune</L>
<L N="3748">Til &thorn;at he heded was er &thorn;at he wiste
<PB REF="00000591.tif" N="563"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="274"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nouht onely &thorn;at &thorn;is werlde hadde of him awe</L>
<L>For leseinge of Richesse &amp; lyberte</L>
<L>Bot he maade euery man Reny his lawe</L>
<L N="3752">Nabugodonosor was lord he seide</L>
<L>None o&thorn;ere god scholde honoured be</L>
<L>A&yogh;eines his hest no whight dar trespas</L>
<L>Saue in Bethulia a stronge cite</L>
<L N="3756">Where Eleachim a preste was of &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bot take kepe of &thorn;e de&thorn;e of Oliferne</L>
<L>Amydde his oste he drunke laye a nyht</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-inne his tent large as is a berne</L>
<L N="3760">And &yogh;it for al his pompe &amp; al his myhte</L>
<L>Iudithe a womman as he laie vp riht</L>
<L>slepeinge his hede of smote &amp; fro his tente</L>
<L>Ful Priuely sche stale fro euery wyght<MILESTONE N="215a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3764">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Antiochio illustri.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; What nede&thorn; it of kynge Antiocheus</L>
<L>To tel his hihe &amp; Roial Maieste</L>
<L>His hihe pride his werke venymmous</L>
<L N="3768">For suche ano&thorn;ere was neuere none as he</L>
<L>Rede&thorn; whiche &thorn;at he was in Macabe</L>
<L>And rede&thorn; &thorn;e proude wordes &thorn;at he seide</L>
<L>And whie he fel fro his prosperite</L>
<L N="3772">And in an hulle howe wrychedly he deyed</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Fortune had him enhaunsed so in pride</L>
<L>&thorn;at verraylye he wende he myhte atteygne</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e sterres vpon euery sidde</L>
<L N="3776">And in a balance to weye iche mounteyne</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e floodes of &thorn;e see restreyne</L>
<L>And goddes peple hadde he moste in hate</L>
<L>Hem wolde he sle in torment &amp; peyne</L>
<L N="3780">Weneynge &thorn;at god myht nouht his pride abate
<PB REF="00000592.tif" N="564"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="275"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And for &thorn;at Nichamoure &amp; Timothee</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Iewes were venqwiste mihtile</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e Iewes suche an hatte hadde he</L>
<L N="3784">That he hadde grey&thorn;ed his chare ful hastelye</L>
<L>An swore &amp; seide ful dispitouslye</L>
<L>Vnto Ierusalem wolde he eft sone</L>
<L>To wreke hire on it ful crouellye</L>
<L N="3788">Bot of his purpose he was lette ful sone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; God for his manasse him so sore smote</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; inne-visible wounde aye vncurable</L>
<L>&thorn;at in his guttes karf so &amp; bote</L>
<L N="3792">&thorn;at his peynes weren importable</L>
<L>And certeinly &thorn;e wreche was resonable</L>
<L>For mony mannes guttes dede he peine</L>
<L>Bot fro his purpos cursed &amp; dampnable</L>
<L N="3796">For al his smert he nold him nouht restreine</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bot Badde anone apparellen his Oste</L>
<L>And sodanly or he was of it warre</L>
<L>God daunted al his pride &amp; al his boste</L>
<L N="3800">For he so sore fel oute of his chare</L>
<L>&thorn;at hurte his limes &amp; his scynne to-tare</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he ne myht go ne Ride</L>
<L>Bot in a chayere men aboute him bare</L>
<L N="3804">Al for-brused bo&thorn;e bakke &amp; side</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The wreche of god him smote so crudelye<MILESTONE N="215b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at in his bode wyked wermes creped</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-all he stanke so orribily</L>
<L N="3808">&thorn;at none of al his meyne &thorn;at him kepped</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;ere so &thorn;at he woke or elles sleped</L>
<L>Ne myht nouht &thorn;e stink of him endure</L>
<L>In &thorn;is Meschef he weiled &amp; eke wepped</L>
<L N="3812">And knowe god lorde of euery creature.
<PB REF="00000593.tif" N="565"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="276"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To al his oste &amp; to him self also</L>
<L>Ful wlatesome was &thorn;e stinke of &thorn;is caren</L>
<L>No man miht him bere to ne fro</L>
<L N="3816">And in his stinke &amp; in his orrible peyne</L>
<L>He starf ful wrecchedly in a mownteyne</L>
<L>Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;is Robboure &amp; &thorn;is homicide</L>
<L>That mony a man maade to wepe &amp; pleyne</L>
<L N="3820">Suche guerdone as belonge&thorn; vnto pride</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Alexandro Magno Philippi Regis Macidonie filio</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The storie of Alexander is so comune</L>
<L>That euery wight &thorn;at ha&thorn;e discrecione</L>
<L>Ha&thorn;e herd sum-whate or al of his fortune</L>
<L N="3824">&THORN;is wilde werlde as in conclusione</L>
<L>He w&amacr;n be strenke&thorn; or for his hihe renoune</L>
<L>Thei weren gladde for pes vnto him sende</L>
<L>The pride of man &amp; beste he laide adoune</L>
<L N="3828">Wher-so he came vn-to &thorn;e werldes ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Comparison myht &yogh;ite neuere be makede</L>
<L>Be-tuex him &amp; ano&thorn;er conqueroure</L>
<L>For al &thorn;is werlde for drede of him ha&thorn;e qwaked</L>
<L N="3832">He was of kny[ht]hede and of fredome floure</L>
<L>Fortune him maade &thorn;e heire of owre honour</L>
<L>Saue wyne &amp; wemmen no &thorn;inge miht aswage</L>
<L>His hihe atente in armes &amp; laboure</L>
<L N="3836">So was he of loueinge corage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; What pite were it to him &thorn;ouhe .I. &yogh;owe tolde</L>
<L>Of .Darius &amp; an. C. M. mo</L>
<L>Of Princes kinges Erles bolde</L>
<L N="3840">Whiche he conquered &amp; brouht hem in-to woo</L>
<L>As fer .I. saie as man mai ride or goo</L>
<L>&thorn;e werlde was his Whatt schold .I. more deuise</L>
<L>For &thorn;ouhe .I. write or tolde &yogh;owe euermo</L>
<L N="3844">Of his knyhthode he miht not suffise
<PB REF="00000594.tif" N="566"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="277"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Twelue &yogh;ere he regned as sei&thorn;e Machabe</L>
<L>Philippus &thorn;e sonne of Macedo he was<MILESTONE N="216a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That first was kynge of grece &thorn;e Contre</L>
<L N="3848">O wor&thorn;i gentil Alisander Alas</L>
<L>&thorn;at euer schold falle suche a cas</L>
<L>Enpoysonde of &thorn;i folke &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>&THORN;in suster fortune ha&thorn;e torne in-to an as</L>
<L N="3852">And &yogh;it for &thorn;e ne wepped sche neuer a tere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; How schal men &yogh;eue teres to compleyne</L>
<L>The de&thorn;e of gentillesse &amp; of frauncheys</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e werlde weldede in his demeygne</L>
<L N="3856">And &yogh;it him &thorn;ouht it myht nouht suffise</L>
<L>So ful was his Corage of hihe emprise</L>
<L>Alace who schal me helpe to endite</L>
<L>Fals fortune &amp; poyson to despise</L>
<L N="3860">The whiche tuo of al &thorn;es wo .I. wite</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Iulio Cesare</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; By wisdom manhede &amp; be labour</L>
<L>Fro humblehede &amp; fro Roial Maieste</L>
<L>Vp rose he Iulius &thorn;e conquerour</L>
<L N="3864">That al &thorn;e Occident be lande &amp; see</L>
<L>Be strenke&thorn;e of hande or elles be trete</L>
<L>And vnto Rome maade hem tributarye</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en of Rome &thorn;an Emperoure was he</L>
<L N="3868">Til &thorn;at fortune wex his aduersarie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O myht Cesar &thorn;at in Thessalye</L>
<L>A&yogh;eines Pompeus fader &thorn;in in lawe</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &thorn;e orient hadde al &thorn;e cheualrie</L>
<L N="3872">As fer as &thorn;e daie beginne&thorn; to dawe</L>
<L>Theime &thorn;oruhe &thorn;i knyhthode hast hem take &amp; slawe</L>
<L>Saue fewe folke &thorn;at wi&thorn; pompeus fledde</L>
<L>&thorn;orwhe whiche &thorn;ou puttest al &thorn;e orient in awe</L>
<L N="3876">&thorn;onke fortune &thorn;at so wele &thorn;e spedde
<PB REF="00000595.tif" N="567"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="278"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bot nowe a litel while .I. wil beweile</L>
<L>&thorn;is Pompeus &thorn;is noble gouernoure</L>
<L>Of Rome whiche &thorn;at flye&thorn; att &thorn;is Batayle</L>
<L N="3880">.I. saye one of his men a fals traiture</L>
<L>His hedde of fmote to wynne him fauoure</L>
<L>Of Iulius &amp; him &thorn;e hede brouht</L>
<L>Alas Pompey of &thorn;e Orient conqueroure</L>
<L N="3884">That fortune vnto suche a de&thorn;e brouht</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To Rome a&yogh;eine Repaire&thorn; Iulius</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his tryumphe laureate ful hihe</L>
<L>Bot on a time Brutus Cassius<MILESTONE N="216b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3888">&thorn;at euere hadde of his hihe astate envie</L>
<L>Ful priuely had maad conspiracye</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes &thorn;is Iulius in subtilite wise</L>
<L>And kest &thorn;e place in whiche he scholde deye</L>
<L N="3892">Wi&thorn; Bodekynnes as .I. schal &yogh;owe devise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Iulius to &thorn;e Capitoile went</L>
<L>vpon a daie as he was wont to goone</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e Capitoile anone him hente</L>
<L N="3896">This falce Brutus on of his foule fone</L>
<L>And stikked him wi&thorn; Bodekinnes anone</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mony a wound &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;e lete him lye</L>
<L>Bot neuere gronte he att no stroke bott one</L>
<L N="3900">Or elles att tuo bot if his story lye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So manly was &thorn;is Iulius of hert</L>
<L>And so wele loued estately honeste</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ouht his dedely woundes so sore smert</L>
<L N="3904">His Mantil ouere his hippes cast he</L>
<L>For no man schol se his priuetee</L>
<L>And as he lay in deynge in a trance</L>
<L>And wist verraily &thorn;at dede was he</L>
<L N="3908">Of honeste &yogh;it hadde he Remembrance
<PB REF="00000596.tif" N="568"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="279"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lucan to &thorn;is story .I. recommende</L>
<L>And to Sweton &amp; to Valerius also</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;is storie write&thorn; worde &amp; ende</L>
<L N="3912">How &thorn;at &thorn;es grete Conquerous two</L>
<L>Fortune was first frende &amp; si&thorn;en foo</L>
<L>No man ne trust vpon his fauour longe</L>
<L>Bot haue hire in awaite for euer mo</L>
<L N="3916">Wittnesse on all &thorn;es conqueroures stronge</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Creso Rege.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Riche Cresus whilom kinge of Lyde</L>
<L>Of whiche Cresus Ciquus sore him dradde</L>
<L>&YOGH;ette was he cauht amydes al his pride</L>
<L N="3920">And to be brent men to &thorn;e fire him ladde</L>
<L>Bot suche a Raine doune fro &thorn;e walkyn schadde</L>
<L>&THORN;at slouhe &thorn;e fire &amp; maade him to eskape</L>
<L>Bot to be warre &yogh;itte no grace he hadde</L>
<L N="3924">Til fortune on &thorn;e galoues maade him gape</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whan he ascaped was he can nouht stinte</L>
<L>For to be-ginne a newe Reyne a&yogh;eine</L>
<L>He wende wele &thorn;at fortune him sente</L>
<L N="3928">Suche happe &thorn;at he ascaped &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e Reine<MILESTONE N="217a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at of his foos he myht nouht be sleine</L>
<L>And suche a sweuen vpon a nyht he mette</L>
<L>Of whiche he was proude &amp; eke feine</L>
<L N="3932">&thorn;at in vengeance he al his hert sette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vpon a tre he was as &thorn;at him &thorn;ouhte</L>
<L>There Iubiter him wessche bo&thorn;e halse &amp; side</L>
<L>And phebus eke a faire towel him brouht</L>
<L N="3936">To drye him wi&thorn; &amp; &thorn;erto wex his pride</L>
<L>And to his douhter &thorn;at stode him be-side</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at he knowe in hihe science abounde</L>
<L>He badd him tel hir what it signified</L>
<L N="3940">And sche his dreme began riht &thorn;us expounde
<PB REF="00000597.tif" N="569"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="280"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The tre quod sche &thorn;e galouse is to mene</L>
<L>And Iubiter be-tokene&thorn; snowe &amp; reyne</L>
<L>And Phebus wi&thorn; his towele so clene</L>
<L N="3944">Is &thorn;e sonne stremes for to seyne</L>
<L>Thou schalt an honged be fader certeine</L>
<L>Reyne schal &thorn;e wassche &amp; sonne schal &thorn;e drye</L>
<L>Thus warned sche him ful platte &amp; pleine</L>
<L N="3948">His douhter &thorn;at called was Phayne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; An honged was Cresus &thorn;e proude kynge</L>
<L>His Roial throne myht him nouht availe</L>
<L>Tregedrye in none o&thorn;ere maner &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="3952">Ne cann in sinynge &middot; crie ne be-weyle</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at fortune al wei wil assaile</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; vnwar stroke &thorn;e Reignes &thorn;at bien proude</L>
<L>For whan men truste&thorn; hir &thorn;an wil sche faile</L>
<L N="3956">And couere hire briht face wi&thorn; a cloude</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>Explicit fabula.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000598.tif" N="570">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="281">
<HEAD>Incipit prologus<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 217</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hoo quod &thorn;e knyht good sir no more of &thorn;is</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e haue saide it is y-nowhe y-wis</L>
<L>And muchel more for litel heuynesse</L>
<L N="3960">Is riht ynouhe to muche folke as .I. gest</L>
<L>.I. seie for me it is a grete disese</L>
<L>Where as men ha&thorn; buen in gre wel&thorn;e &amp; ese</L>
<L>To heren of here sodan fal alas</L>
<L N="3964">And &thorn;e contrarie is Ioye &amp; grete solace</L>
<L>As whan ha&thorn;e bue in pouere astate</L>
<L>And climbe&thorn; vp &amp; waxe&thorn; fortunate</L>
<L>And &thorn;are abide&thorn; in prosperite</L>
<L N="3968">Suche &thorn;inge is glad-some as it &thorn;enke&thorn; me.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ouhe suche were goodely for to telle<MILESTONE N="217b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e quod oure Ost be seint poules belle</L>
<L>&YOGH;e seie riht so&thorn;e &thorn;is monke he clappe&thorn; loude</L>
<L N="3972">He spake howe fortune couerd was wi&thorn; a cloude</L>
<L>.I. note neuer what &amp; also of a tregedrye</L>
<L>Riht nowe &yogh;e herde &amp; parde no Remedye</L>
<L>It is to be-weile ne to compleyne</L>
<L N="3976">That &thorn;at is done and als it is a peine</L>
<L>As &yogh;e haue seide to hire of heuenesse</L>
<L>Sir monke no more of &thorn;is so god &yogh;ow blysse</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure tale anoye&thorn; al &thorn;is Compaignye</L>
<L N="3980">Suche talkeinge is nouht wor&thorn;e a botter flye</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere-inne is no sporte ne game</L>
<L>Where-fore sir Monke Dan Piers be &yogh;oure name</L>
<L>I praie hertely tel vs sumwhatt elles</L>
<L N="3984">For seker ner clynkenge of &yogh;oure belles
<PB REF="00000599.tif" N="571"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="282"></L>
<L>&thorn;at on &yogh;oure bridel honge&thorn; on euery side</L>
<L>Be heven kinge &thorn;at for vs al deide</L>
<L>I schal for &thorn;is fal doune for slepe</L>
<L N="3988">Al-&thorn;ouhe &thorn;e slouhe hadde neuere be so depe</L>
<L>Than hadde &yogh;oure tale be tolde in veyne</L>
<L>For certeynly as &thorn;es clerkes seyne</L>
<L>Where as a man maye haue none audience</L>
<L N="3992">Nowht he[l]pe&thorn; to tellen his sentence</L>
<L>And wele .I. woote &thorn;e substance is in me</L>
<L>If any &thorn;inge schal wele Reported bee</L>
<L>Sire sey sum whatt of hunteinge .I. &yogh;owe preie</L>
<L N="3996">Naye quod &thorn;e monke .I. haue no luste to pleie</L>
<L>Nowe latte a no&thorn;ere tel as .I. haue tolde</L>
<L>Than spak oure Oste wi&thorn; rude speche &amp; bolde</L>
<L>And seide vnto &thorn;e Nones preste anone</L>
<L N="4000">Com nere sir prest come hider sir Iohn</L>
<L>Tel vs suche &thorn;inge as may oure hertes glaade</L>
<L>Be merye &thorn;ouhe &thorn;ou ride vpon a Iade</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ouhe &thorn;ine hors be foule or lene</L>
<L N="4004">If he wil serue &thorn;e rekke &thorn;e nouht a bene</L>
<L>Looke &thorn;at &thorn;ine herte be mere euermo</L>
<L>&YOGH;is oste quod he so mot .I. ride or go</L>
<L>Bot .I. be mery .I.-wisse .I. wil be blamede</L>
<L N="4008">And riht anone he ha&thorn;e his tale tamede</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he seide to vs euerychon</L>
<L>This swete preste &thorn;is goodman sir Iohn
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000600.tif" N="572"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="283">
<HEAD>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> Preste [<I>head-line</I>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Pouer wedowe sumdel stoupe in age<MILESTONE N="218a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4012">was whilom dwellynge in a narwe cotage</L>
<L>Be sides a groue standinge in a dale</L>
<L>&thorn;is wedow whiche .I. tolde &yogh;owe of my tale</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ilke daie sche was last a wif</L>
<L N="4016">In pacience ledde a ful simple lif</L>
<L>For litel was hire catel &amp; hire rent</L>
<L>Be husbandry suche as god hire sent</L>
<L>Sche fant her self &amp; eke her douhtern tuo</L>
<L N="4020">&THORN;e large sewes hadde sche &amp; no mo</L>
<L>&THORN;re kyne &amp; eke a schepe &thorn;at hiht mal</L>
<L>Ful soty was hir boure &amp; eke hire hal</L>
<L>In whiche sche ete mony a sklender mele</L>
<L N="4024">Of poynant sauce her neded neuer a dele</L>
<L>No deynte morsel passed hire &thorn;rote</L>
<L>Hire Dyaut was accordant to hire cote</L>
<L>Replecioun maad hir neuer seke</L>
<L N="4028">Atempre diete was all hire phesike</L>
<L>And exercise &amp; hertes sufficiaunce</L>
<L>The goute lettid hire no &thorn;inge to daunce</L>
<L>&thorn;e Poplexie ne shent nouht hire hede</L>
<L N="4032">Ne wyne dranke sche ney&thorn;ere white ne rede</L>
<L>Hire borde was serued most wi&thorn; white &amp; blakke</L>
<L>Melke &amp; broune brede in whiche sche fande no lakke</L>
<L>Seyned bakon &amp; somtyme a neye or tweye</L>
<L N="4036">For sche was as it were a manere deye</L>
<L>A gardeyne sche hadde closed al aboute</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; stikkes &amp; a drye diche wi&thorn; oute</L>
<L>In whiche sche hadde a kok &thorn;at hiht chauntrell</L>
<L N="4040">In al &thorn;e land of croweinge was his pere
<PB REF="00000601.tif" N="573"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="284"></L>
<L>His voice was merier &thorn;an &thorn;e meri organe</L>
<L>On mesdaies &thorn;at in &thorn;e cherche gone</L>
<L>Wele sukere was his croweinge in his loge</L>
<L N="4044">Than is a kloke or any abbeie orlege</L>
<L>Be nature he knewe iche ascencioune</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e equinoxiale of &thorn;ilk toune</L>
<L>For whanne degrese .xv. were descended</L>
<L N="4048">&THORN;an knewe he &thorn;at it myh not bue a-mended</L>
<L>His kombe was redder &thorn;an &thorn;e fine coralle</L>
<L>Enbateled as it were a castel wall</L>
<L>Ilyke a&yogh;ure was his legges &amp; his tone</L>
<L N="4052">His bille was blakke &amp; as &thorn;e gete it schone.</L>
<L>His nailes whitter &thorn;an &thorn;e lyly floure<MILESTONE N="218b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And ylike burnesshed gold was his colour</L>
<L>This gentil kok hadd in his gouernance</L>
<L N="4056">.Vij. hennes to done him plesance</L>
<L>Whiche weren his susters &amp; his paramours</L>
<L>And wondere ylike to him as of Coloures</L>
<L>Of wiche &thorn;e faire hewe on hire &thorn;rote</L>
<L N="4060">Was cleped faire damysel pertelote</L>
<L>Corteys sche was discrete &amp; debonaire</L>
<L>And companable &amp; bare hire self so faire</L>
<L>Se&thorn;ens &thorn;ilke daie sche was sevenyht olde</L>
<L N="4064">That trewly sche ha&thorn;e &thorn;e hert in holde</L>
<L>Of chaunteclere loken in euery ly&thorn;&thorn;e</L>
<L>He loued hire so &thorn;at wele was him &thorn;ere wi&thorn;</L>
<L>Bot suche a ioye it was to here hem singe</L>
<L N="4068">Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e briht sone be-gan to springe</L>
<L>In swete accorde . My leue is fare in londe</L>
<L>For &thorn;ilke time as .I. have vnderstonde</L>
<L>Bestes &amp; birdes kou&thorn;e speke &amp; singe</L>
<L N="4072">And so befel at in a dawenynge</L>
<L>As chaunteclere amonge his wives all</L>
<L>Satt on his perche &thorn;at was in &thorn;e hall</L>
<L>And next him satt his faire pertelote</L>
<L N="4076">This chaunteclere gan gronen in his &thorn;rote
<PB REF="00000602.tif" N="574"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="285"></L>
<L>As a man &thorn;at in his dreme is drecched sore</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at Pertilote &thorn;us herde him Rore</L>
<L>Sche was agast &amp; seide hert dere</L>
<L N="4080">What eyle&thorn; &yogh;owe to grone in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bue a verrey sleper fye for schame</L>
<L>And he anseward &amp; seide &thorn;us madame</L>
<L>.I. pray &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e take it to no greue</L>
<L N="4084">Be god me mette &thorn;at .I. was in suche mischeue</L>
<L>Riht nowe &thorn;at &yogh;it myne hert is sore afliht</L>
<L>Nowe quod he My sweven rede ariht</L>
<L>And kepe my body oute of foule prisone</L>
<L N="4088">Me mette &thorn;at .I. Romed vpe &amp; doune</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-inne oure &yogh;erd where as .I. sawe a beste</L>
<L>Was like an hunde &amp; wolde haue maad areste</L>
<L>Vpon My body &amp; wolde haue hadde me dede</L>
<L N="4092">His colour was be-twixe white &amp; Rede</L>
<L>And tipped was his taile &amp; bo&thorn; his eres</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; blak vnlyke &thorn;e remenant of his heres.</L>
<L>His snowte smal wi&thorn; gloweinge eyen tweye<MILESTONE N="219a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4096">&YOGH;it of his loke almoste for fere .I. deye</L>
<L>&thorn;is caused me my groneinge douteles</L>
<L>Avoye quod sche Fy on &yogh;owe herteles</L>
<L>Alas quod sche for be &thorn;at god aboue</L>
<L N="4100">Now haue &yogh;e lost my hert &amp; my loue</L>
<L>.I. kan nouht loue a coward be my fei&thorn;e</L>
<L>For certes what so any womman sey&thorn;e</L>
<L>Wil al desiren if it myht be</L>
<L N="4104">To haue husbandes harde wise &amp; fre</L>
<L>And secre ne no nygard ne none fole</L>
<L>Ne him &thorn;at is agast of euery tole</L>
<L>Ne none avauntour be &thorn;at god aboue</L>
<L N="4108">How dorst &yogh;e seye for schame vnto &yogh;oure loue</L>
<L>&thorn;at any &thorn;inge myht maake &yogh;owe aferde</L>
<L>Haue &yogh;e none mannes herte &amp; han berde</L>
<L>Alas &amp; kan &yogh;e be agast of sweue[n]sse</L>
<L>[No thyng god woot/ but vanyte/ in sweuyn is/.<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 1758 folio" N="194b">]
<PB REF="00000603.tif" N="575"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="286"></L>
<L>Sweuens engendur of repleciones</L>
<L>[And ofte of/ fame &amp; of complexions/.<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 1758 folio" N="194b">]</L>
<L>Whan humours bien to aboundant in a whight</L>
<L N="4116">Certes &thorn;is dreme whiche &yogh;e haue herd to nyht</L>
<L>Come&thorn; of &thorn;e grete superfluyte</L>
<L>Of &yogh;oure rede coloure parde</L>
<L>Whiche cause&thorn; folk to dreme hire dremes</L>
<L N="4120">Of Arwes and of fire wi&thorn; rede lemes</L>
<L>Of Rede bestes &thorn;at willen hem bite</L>
<L>Of contek &amp; of whelpes grete &amp; lite</L>
<L>Riht as &thorn;e humore malancolye</L>
<L N="4124">Cause&thorn; many a man in slepe to crye</L>
<L>For fere of beres &amp; boles blake</L>
<L>Or elles blake deueles wi him tak</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;ere humerous cou&thorn; .I. tel also</L>
<L N="4128">&thorn;at werken mony a man in slepe ful wo</L>
<L>Bot .I. wil passe as lihtly as .I. kan</L>
<L>Lo Caton whiche &thorn;at was so wise a man</L>
<L>Seide he not &thorn;us ne do no force of dremes</L>
<L N="4132">Now sir quod sche whan we flye fro &thorn;e bemes</L>
<L>For goddes loue as take sum laxatif</L>
<L>Vpon perile of my soule &amp; of my lyf</L>
<L>.I. counsel &yogh;owe &thorn;e best .I. wil nou&yogh;t lye</L>
<L N="4136">&thorn;at bo&thorn;e of coloure &amp; of Malancolye</L>
<L>&yogh;e pure &yogh;owe; &amp; for &yogh;e scholne nouht tary</L>
<L>&thorn;ouhe &thorn;at in &thorn;is toune is no potecarye</L>
<L>.I. schal my self to erbes techen &yogh;owe<MILESTONE N="219b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4140">&thorn;at schal biene &yogh;oure hele &amp; &yogh;oure prowe</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e gardine &thorn;o erbes schal .I. finde</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche haue of here prop[er]te be kinde</L>
<L>To purgen &yogh;owe be-ne&thorn;e &amp; eke aboue</L>
<L N="4144">For-&yogh;ette&thorn; nouht &thorn;is for goddes owen loue</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bien ful colerik of complexioune</L>
<L>Were &thorn;e sonne in his ascencioune</L>
<L>Ne fynde &yogh;oue replite of &yogh;oure humers hote</L>
<L N="4148">And if it do; I. dare wele leie a grote
<PB REF="00000604.tif" N="576"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="287"></L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e schal haue a feuere terciane</L>
<L>Or an Agwe &thorn;at maie be &yogh;oure bane</L>
<L>A daye or tuo &yogh;e schal haue digestiues</L>
<L N="4152">Of wermes ar &yogh;e take &yogh;oure laxatiues</L>
<L>Of Laureole; Centaure &amp; of fymyter</L>
<L>Or elles of elobore &thorn;at growe&thorn; &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Of Catapuce or of gaitres buryes</L>
<L N="4156">Of herbe yve groinge in owre gardine &thorn;at merery is</L>
<L>Peke hem vp riht as &thorn;ei growe &amp; ete hem inne</L>
<L>Be mery husbande for &yogh;oure faders kinne</L>
<L>Drede&thorn; no dreme .I. can sei &yogh;owe no more</L>
<L N="4160">Madame quod he gremercy of &yogh;oure lore</L>
<L>Bot na&thorn;eles as toucheinge dan Catoune</L>
<L>That ha&thorn; of wisdom suche grete renoune</L>
<L>Be god men maie in olde bokes reede</L>
<L N="4164">One of &thorn;e grettest Auctor oute of drede</L>
<L>And mony a man more of auctorite</L>
<L>Than euer Caton was so mott .I. &thorn;e</L>
<L>That al &thorn;e [re]uerese seine of here sentence</L>
<L N="4168">And haue wele founden be experience</L>
<L>&thorn;at dremes be significacions</L>
<L>As wele of Ioye as of tribulacions</L>
<L>&thorn;at folke enduren in &thorn;is lif present</L>
<L N="4172">The nede&thorn; nouht to make of &thorn;is none argument</L>
<L>&THORN;e verei preue schewe&thorn; it in dede</L>
<L>One of &thorn;e grettest auctor &thorn;at men rede</L>
<L>sei&thorn; &thorn;us &thorn;at whilom tuo felawes &yogh;ede</L>
<L N="4176">On pilgrenage in a ful grete nede</L>
<L>And happed so &thorn;ei cam in to a toune</L>
<L>Where as &thorn;ere was suche congregacione</L>
<L>Of peple and eke of streite herbigage</L>
<L N="4180">&thorn;at &thorn;ei [ne] fande as meche as a cotage.</L>
<L>In whiche &thorn;ei bo&thorn;e myht y-loged be<MILESTONE N="220a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wherfor &thorn;ei myhten of necessite</L>
<L>As for &thorn;at nyht departen of compaignye</L>
<L N="4184">And iche of hem go&thorn;e vntil his ostelerye
<PB REF="00000605.tif" N="577"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="288"></L>
<L>And toke his logeinge as it wolde fal</L>
<L>&thorn;at one of hem was loged in a stal</L>
<L>Ferre in a &yogh;erde wi&thorn; oxen of &thorn;e plouhe</L>
<L N="4188">&thorn;e to&thorn;ere man was loged wele y-nowhe</L>
<L>As was his aduentur or his fortune</L>
<L>That vs gouerne&thorn; all as in comune</L>
<L>And so be-fel longe ar it were daie</L>
<L N="4192">&thorn;is man mette in his bedde &thorn;ere he leye</L>
<L>Howe &thorn;at his felawe gan on him calle</L>
<L>And seid alas for in an oxe stalle</L>
<L>This nyht .I. schal be mordred &thorn;ere .I. lye</L>
<L N="4196">Nowe helpe me dere bro&thorn;ere ar .I. deye;</L>
<L>In al haste come to me he seide.</L>
<L>This man oute of his slepe for fere abraide.</L>
<L>Bot whan &thorn;at he wakened out of his slepe</L>
<L N="4200">He turned him &amp; toke of &thorn;is no kepe</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ouht his drem was nouht bot a vanite</L>
<L>Thus twyes in his slepe dremed he</L>
<L>And att &thorn;e &thorn;redde time &yogh;it his felawe</L>
<L N="4204">Cam as him &thorn;ouht .I. am nowe .I.-slawe</L>
<L>Be-holde my blode wounde depe &amp; wide</L>
<L>Aryse vp erly in &thorn;e morne tyde</L>
<L>And att &thorn;e west gate of &thorn;e toune quod he</L>
<L N="4208">A cart ful of donge &thorn;ere schalt &thorn;ou see</L>
<L>In whiche my body is hidde ful priuelye</L>
<L>Do &thorn;ilke cart areste boldelye</L>
<L>My golde caused my morder so&thorn;e to seyne</L>
<L N="4212">And tolde hym euery poynte howe was sleyne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a ful pytous face pale of hewe</L>
<L>And trust wele his drem he fonde ful trewe</L>
<L>For on &thorn;e morne as sone as it was daie</L>
<L N="4216">To his felawes inne he toke &thorn;e riht waie</L>
<L>And whan he cam to &thorn;is oxe stall</L>
<L>Affeter his felawe he began to call</L>
<L>The Osteler answerd him anone</L>
<L N="4220">And seide sir &yogh;oure felawe is gone
<PB REF="00000606.tif" N="578"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="289"></L>
<L>As sone as dei he went oute of toune</L>
<L>This man gan fal in grete suspeccion</L>
<L>Remembreinge on his dremes &thorn;at he mete</L>
<L N="4224">And for&thorn;e he go&thorn;e no longere wolde he let<MILESTONE N="220b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e west gate of &thorn;e toune &amp; fonde</L>
<L>A donge cart as he went to donge &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>&thorn;at was araide in &thorn;e same wyse</L>
<L N="4228">As &yogh;e haue herde &thorn;e dede man deuise</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; an hardy hert he gan to crie</L>
<L>Vengeance &amp; Iustice of &thorn;is felonye</L>
<L>Myne felawe murdre is &thorn;e same nyht</L>
<L N="4232">And in &thorn;is carte he lie&thorn; gapeinge vpriht</L>
<L>[I cry out on the mynistres quod he<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg 17 D xv folio" N="277b"><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Not in</I> MS Reg. 18 C ii (<I>nor are l.</I> 4112, 4114); <I>not in</I> Harl. 1758.]</NOTE></L>
<L>That shulden kepe. and rule this citee</L>
<L>Harrow allas. hire lith my felaw slayne<MILESTONE N="278a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>What shuld I more. vnto this tale sayne</L>
<L>The peple vp stert. and cast the cart to ground</L>
<L>And in the myddil of the dung. ther they found]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>MS Reg.</B> <I>ex|tract ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>The de[de] man &thorn;at murded was al newe</L>
<L N="4240">O blisful god &thorn;at art so iust &amp; trewe</L>
<L>Lo howe &thorn;ou be-wryest morder al weie</L>
<L>Mordre wil oute &thorn;at se we daie be daie</L>
<L>Mordre is so wlatesome &amp; abomynable</L>
<L N="4244">To god &thorn;at is so Iuste &amp; resonable</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne wil nouht suffre it heled be</L>
<L>&thorn;ei it abide a &yogh;ere or two or &thorn;re</L>
<L>Mordre wil oute &thorn;is es myne conclusioune</L>
<L N="4248">And riht anone Ministres of &thorn;e same toune</L>
<L>And hente &thorn;e carter &amp; sore him pynede</L>
<L>And eke the hostelere so ferre engynede</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei be-knewe here wykkednesse anone</L>
<L N="4252">And weren hanged be &thorn;e nekke bone</L>
<L>Here maie menne see &thorn;at dremes bien to drede</L>
<L>And certes in [the] same book .I. rede</L>
<L>Riht in &thorn;e next chapetre .I. rede of &thorn;is</L>
<L N="4256">.I. gabbe nouht so haue .I. Ioye &amp; blis
<PB REF="00000607.tif" N="579"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="290"></L>
<L>[Two men that wold. han passed the see<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Reg. 17 D xv folio" N="278a">]</L>
<L>For certeyne cause into a fer Contre</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;e wynde ne hadde bue contrarie</L>
<L N="4260">&thorn;at maade hem in a Cite for to tarye</L>
<L>&thorn;at stode ful merie vpon an hauen side</L>
<L>Bot on a daie a&yogh;eines &thorn;e euen tide</L>
<L>The wynde gan chaunge &amp; blew as him lest</L>
<L N="4264">Iolif &amp; gladde &thorn;ei wenten vnto rest</L>
<L>And kesten hem ful erly vnto seile</L>
<L>Bot herken &thorn;at o man fel in grete pereile</L>
<L>The tone of hem in slepeinge as he leye</L>
<L N="4268">Him mett a wonder dreme a&yogh;eines &thorn;e daye</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ouht a man stode be his side</L>
