<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000638.tif" N="606b">

<PB REF="00000639.tif" N="607">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="593">
<HEAD>Incipit sermo.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lansdowne</I> 851, <I>on leaf</I> 230, <I>back</I>.]</P><P>[<I>There are no paragraph-breaks in the MS, but Tyrwhitt's are kept in the print for convenience sake.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<EPIGRAPH><BIBL>Ieremie vj<SUP>to</SUP>.</BIBL>
<Q>State super vias. &amp; videte &amp; interrogate de semitis antiquis que sit via bona; &amp; ambulate in ea &amp; inuenietis refrigerium animabus vestris.</Q></EPIGRAPH>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part">
<P>[75] Owre. swete lord god of heuen; &thorn;at no man wil perisshe; but wil &thorn;at we comme al to &thorn;e knowleche of him; &amp; to &thorn;e blisful lyf &thorn;at is perdurable; [76] amoneste&thorn; vs be &thorn;e prophet Ioromie &thorn;at sei&thorn;e in &thorn;is wise; [77] Stande&thorn; vpon &thorn;e weyes &amp; see&thorn;e &amp; axe&thorn; of olde pa&thorn;es. &thorn;at is to seie of olde sentences; whiche is &thorn;e goode weie; [78] &amp; walke&thorn; in &thorn;at weie; &amp; &yogh;e schal finde refrisscheinge for &yogh;oure soules; &amp;c [79] &para; Many buen &thorn;e weyes spirituele. &thorn;at leden folk to to oure lorde ihesu criste &amp; to &thorn;e regne of glorie [80] &para; Of whiche weyes &thorn;ere is a ful noble weie and ful couenable weie; whiche maye not faile to man ne to womman &thorn;at &thorn;oruhe sinne ha&thorn; mys gone fro &thorn;e riht weie of Ierusalem celestial. [81] And &thorn;is weie is cleped Penitence; of whiche men scholde gladly herken &amp; enquere wi&thorn; al his he [82] to wit what is pen|ance; &amp; whan it is cleped penanc. &amp; in howe many manere bene &thorn;e accionce of worchinge of penance; [83] And howe mony spices &thorn;ere biene of penytence And whiche &thorn;inges appartenen; &amp; be-houen to penitence; &amp; whiche &thorn;inges distourben penitence
<PB REF="00000640.tif" N="608"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="594"></P>
<P>[84] &para; Seint Ambrose sei&thorn;e &thorn;at penitence is &thorn;e pleyneinge of man for &thorn;e gilt &thorn;at he ha&thorn; done; and no more to do any &thorn;inge for whiche we ouhte to pleyne; [85] And s&omacr;m doctour sei&thorn;e; Penitence is &thorn;e weyment|ynge of man &thorn;at sorwe&thorn; for his sinne; an peyne&thorn; him selft for he ha&thorn;e mys done; [86] Penytence wi&thorn; certeyne circumstance is verrey repentance of men &thorn;at halt him self in sorwe; And o&thorn;ere peyne for his giltes [87] For he schal be verreye penitent; he schall first beweilen &thorn;e sinne &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e done; And stedfastly purposen in his herte to haue schrift of mou&thorn;e And to done satisfaccione; [88] And neuer to do &thorn;inge. ffor whiche him ouht to beweile or to complene &amp; to con|tinue in goode werkes; or elles his repentance mai nouht availe [89] &para; For as seint Isider sei&thorn;e. He is a Iaper &amp; a gabbere &amp; no verrei repentant; &thorn;at eft sone do&thorn; &thorn;inge ffor whiche him ouht to repent [90] wepeinge; &amp; nouht for to stinte to do sinne Maie not availe; [91] Bot na&thorn;eles men schol hope; &thorn;at at euery time &thorn;at man falle&thorn; be it neuere so of; &thorn;at he may rise &thorn;orwhe peni|tence if he haue grace &para; Bot certeinly. it is grete doute [92] for as sei&thorn;e seinte gregori. vnne&thorn;es arise&thorn; he oute of his sinne &thorn;at is charged wi&thorn; &thorn;e charde of yuel vsage; [93] &amp; &thorn;er fore repentant folke &thorn;at stinte for to sinne &amp; for-lete sinne. er sinne for-<MILESTONE N="231a" UNIT="folio">lete him. Holy cherche holte hem seker of her sauacione; [94] And he &thorn;at sinne&thorn; &amp; verraly repente&thorn; him in his last ende; Holy cherche &yogh;it hope&thorn; his saluacion be &thorn;e grete mercy of our lorde ihesu for his repentance; &para; Bot take&thorn; &thorn;e seker weye &thorn;at is certeine;</P>
<P>[95] &para; And nowe se&thorn;en .I. haue declared &yogh;owe what &thorn;inge is penitence &para; Now scholne &yogh;e vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;ere bue &thorn;re accions of Penytence; [96] The first is if a man be baptized after &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e sinned [97] &para; Seint Austine sei&thorn;e bot he be penitence for his olde sinful lif; he maie not be-ginne &thorn;e newe 
<PB REF="00000641.tif" N="609"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="595"> clene lif; [98] For certes if he be baptist with oute penitence of his olde gilte; he receyue&thorn; &thorn;e merke of baptime. bot not &thorn;e grace ne &thorn;e remission of his sinnes til he haue repentance verreye. [99] &para; Ano&thorn;ere defaut is &thorn;is; that men done dedely sinne after &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue receyued Baptisme [100] &para; &THORN;e &thorn;redde defaute is; &thorn;at men fallen in venial sinnes after her baptisme; fro daie to daie [101] &para; Ther of sei&thorn; seint Austine; &thorn;at penitence of goode &amp; humble folke is &thorn;e penitence of euery daie;</P>
<P>[102] &para; The spices of penance bien &thorn;re; &thorn;at on of hem is solempne; ano&thorn;ere is comune. .&amp;. &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> &thorn;red is priue [103] &para; &thorn;ilke penance &thorn;at is so|lempne; is in tuo maners. As is to be put oute of holy cherche in lente for slauhter of childerne &amp; suche maner &thorn;inge; [104] Ano&thorn;er is whan man ha&thorn; sinned openly; of whiche sinne &thorn;e fame is openly spoken in &thorn;e contre; &para; And &thorn;an holy cherche be iuge|ment Distreyne&thorn; him for to do penance open. [105] &para; Somme penance is &thorn;at prestes enioynen men comunly in certeine caas as for to gone peraduentur naked in pilgrenage or barfote. [106] &para; Priue penaunce is &thorn;ilk &thorn;at men done al daie ffor priue sinnes of whiche we schryuen vs priuely &amp; receyuen priue penance.</P>
<P>[107] &para; Nowe schalt &thorn;ou vnderstande whas behoue&thorn;; &amp; is necessarie to verrei perfit penitence; An &thorn;es standen on &thorn;re &thorn;inges [108] &para; Contricio of hert. Con|fession of mou&thorn;e; &amp; satisfaccione [109] &para; For whiche sei&thorn; Iohannes Grisostemus. Penytence Distreyne&thorn; man to accepte benyngly euery peine &thorn;at is him enioyned with contricione of hert; &amp; schrift of mou&thorn;e &amp; satis|facione &amp; in wercheinge al manere humylite; [110] &para; And &thorn;is is fruyteful penitence a&yogh;ein &thorn;re &thorn;inges in which. we wre&thorn;&thorn;en our lorde ihesu crist; [111] &thorn;is is to seine; be delite in &thorn;inkinge; be reclischenesse in spekeinge; be wykked sinful wyrcheinge; [112] &para; And a&yogh;eines &thorn;es 
<PB REF="00000642.tif" N="610"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="596"> wikked giltes is penitence; &thorn;at maie be likned vnto a tre.</P>
<P>[113] &para; &thorn;e rote of &thorn;is tree is contricione &thorn;at hide&thorn; him in &thorn;e hert of him &thorn;at is verraie repentant Riht as &thorn;e rote of a tre hide&thorn; him in &thorn;e er&thorn;e; [114] &para; Of &thorn;e rote of contricione springe&thorn; a stalk &thorn;at bere&thorn; braunches &amp; leues of confessis &amp; fruyte of satisfaccione. [115] For whiche crist sei&thorn;e in &thorn;e gospel. Do&thorn;e digne fruyte of penite. For be &thorn;is fruyte men maye knowe &thorn;is tre; &amp; nouht be rote &thorn;at is hide in &thorn;e herte of man; be &thorn;e braunche ne be &thorn;e leues of confessione; [116] And &thorn;ere for oure lorde ihesu crist sei&thorn; &thorn;us; Be &thorn;e fruyte of hem schal &yogh;e knowe hem [117] &para; Of &thorn;is rote springe&thorn; a seede of grace; &thorn;e whiche sede is &thorn;e mode of sekernesse; And &thorn;is seed is egre &amp; hote; [118] &thorn;e grace of &thorn;is seed springe&thorn; of god &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e re|membrance of &thorn;e daie of dome &amp; one &thorn;e peines of helle. [119] &para; Of &thorn;is<MILESTONE N="231b" UNIT="folio"> Matier sei&thorn;e Salomon. That in &thorn;e drede of god man for lete&thorn; his sinne. [120] &para; &thorn;e hete of &thorn;is seede is &thorn;e loue of god. &amp; &thorn;e desire of &thorn;e Ioye perdurable; [121] &thorn;is hete draue&thorn; &thorn;e hert of man to god; &amp; do&thorn;e him hate his sinne; [122] &para; For so&thorn;ely &thorn;ere is no &thorn;inge &thorn;at sauere&thorn; so wele to a childe as &thorn;e myke of his norice; Ne no &thorn;inge is to him more abhom|inable &thorn;at &thorn;ilke melk whan it is menged wi&thorn; o&thorn;ere mete. [123] Riht so &thorn;e sinnful man &thorn;at loue&thorn; his sinne it seme&thorn; &thorn;at it is to him moste swete Of any &thorn;inge; [124] &para; Bot fro &thorn;at time &thorn;at he loue&thorn; sadly oure lorde ihesu criste &amp; desire&thorn; &thorn;e lif perdurable; &thorn;ere nys to hime more abhominable; [125] &para; For so&thorn;e &thorn;e lawe of god is &thorn;e loue of god; For whiche dauid &thorn;e prophete sei&thorn;e; I. haue loued &thorn;i lawe &amp; hated wikkednesse; &amp; haten; He &thorn;at loue&thorn; god kepe&thorn; his lawe &amp; his worde; [126] &para; This tre sawe &thorn;e prophet .Danyel. in spirit vpon &thorn;e auysion of nobugodonosor whan he coun|seled him to do penitence. [127] &para; Penance is &thorn;e tre of lif to hem &thorn;at it receyven; And he &thorn;at holde&thorn; him 
<PB REF="00000643.tif" N="611"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="597"> verrey penytence is blissed after &thorn;e verrey sentence of Salomon.</P>
<P>[128] &para; In &thorn;is penitence or contricion man schal vn|derstonden .iiij. &thorn;inges; &thorn;at is to seine What is contricione; &amp; whiche bien &thorn;e causes &thorn;at meuen a man to con|tricione &amp; howe he schold be contrite; &amp; what con|tricioun availed to &thorn;e soule; [129] &thorn;an is it &thorn;us; &thorn;at contricion is &thorn;e verrei sowe &thorn;at a man receyue&thorn; in his hert for his sinnes with sadde purpos to schriuen him &amp; to do penance And to do neuer more sinne; [130] &para; And &thorn;is sorwe schal bien in &thorn;is manere As sei&thorn;e seinte Bernard. It schal be greuous &amp; heuy &amp; ful scharpe &amp; poynant in herte; [131] ffirst for a man ha&thorn; gult his lord &amp; his makere; &amp; mor scharp &amp; poynant; for he ha&thorn; agilte his fader celestial; [132] &amp; &yogh;it more scharp &amp; poynant; For he ha&thorn;e a-wre&thorn;&thorn;ed &amp; agilte him &thorn;at bouht him; &thorn;at withe his precious blode ha&thorn; deliuerd vs fro &thorn;e bandes of sinne And fro &thorn;e cruelte of &thorn;e deuel. And fro &thorn;e peynes of hell;</P>
<P>[133] &para; The causes &thorn;at ouhte to meue a man to con|tricion bien .vj. &para; First a man schal remembre him of his sinnes; [134] bot loke &thorn;at &thorn;at remem|brance be to him no delite be no weye bot grette schame; &amp; sorwe For his gilte. For Iob sei&thorn;e. Sinfulmen do&thorn; werkes wor&thorn;i of confession [135] &para; And &thorn;ere for sei&thorn;e Ezechiele .I. wil remembre me al &thorn;e &yogh;eres of my lif in bitternesse of myn herte; [136] And god sei&thorn;e in &thorn;e Apocolips. Remembre &yogh;o fro wemmes &thorn;at bue fall; For be forne &thorn;at time &thorn;at &yogh;e sinned &yogh;e weren &thorn;e childern of god. &amp; lyme of &thorn;e Regne of god; [137] &para; Bot for &yogh;oure sinne &yogh;e bien wax &thorn;ral &amp; foule &amp; membres of &thorn;e fende; hate of Angeles Sclaundre of holy cherche. And foode of &thorn;e fals serpent perpetuel matiere of &thorn;e fire of hell. [138] And &thorn;at more foule &amp; abom|inable for &yogh;e trespasen so oft time; as do&thorn;e &thorn;e hounde &thorn;at torne&thorn; to eten his spewynge; [139] And &yogh;it 
<PB REF="00000644.tif" N="612"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="598"> bien &yogh;e fouler for &yogh;oure longe continuinge in sinne; &amp; &yogh;oure sinful vsage; For whiche &yogh;e be roten in &yogh;oure sinne as a beste in his donge [140] &para; Suche manere of &thorn;ouhtes maken a man to haue schame for his sinne &amp; no delite; As god sei&thorn;e be &thorn;e prophete Ezechiele. [141] &yogh;e schol remembre &yogh;owe of &yogh;oure weies; &amp; &thorn;ei schol displesen &yogh;owe so&thorn;ely; &para; Sinnes bien &thorn;e weies &thorn;at leden folk to hell;</P>
<P>[142] &para; &thorn;e secunde cause &thorn;at auhte to make a man to haue disdeyne of sinne is &thorn;is; &para; &thorn;at as sei&thorn;e seint Petre; Who so do&thorn;e sinne is &thorn;rall of <MILESTONE N="232a" UNIT="folio">sinne; &para; And sinne putte&thorn; a man in grete &thorn;raldome; [143] And &thorn;ere for sei&thorn;e &thorn;e prophete Ezechiele; I. went sorweful in disdeine of my selfe; &para; Certes wele ouht a man to haue disdeine of synne &amp; wi&thorn;-drawe him fro &thorn;at &thorn;raldome &amp; velanie; [144] And lo whatte sei&thorn;e Seneea in &thorn;is matiere; &thorn;ouhe .I. wiste &thorn;at god ney&thorn;ere man ne scholde neuer knowe it; &YOGH;it wolde .I. haue disdeine for to do sinne. [145] &para; The same Seneca. sei&thorn;e .I. am borne to gretter &thorn;inges &thorn;an to be &thorn;rall to me bodye. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in MS.</NOTE> . . . . [146] More a &thorn;ralle may no man ne womman make of his bodi &thorn;an &yogh;iue his body to sinne; [147] A were it &thorn;e foulest cherle or &thorn;e foulest womman &thorn;at leue&thorn; &amp; leste of value &yogh;ite is he chaunged &amp; moste foule &amp; more in seruitute; [148] Euer fro &thorn;e hiere degre &thorn;at a man falle&thorn; &thorn;e more he is &thorn;rall; And more vnto god &amp; to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> werlde vile &amp; abomin|able; [149] &para; O good god wele ouht men haue disdeyne of sinne; se&thorn;en &thorn;at &thorn;oruhe sinne &thorn;ere he was fre now is he maked bonde [150] &para; And &thorn;ere for sei&thorn;e seinte Austine. If &thorn;ou haue disdeine of &thorn;i seruant if he a gilte or synne; Haue &thorn;ou &thorn;an disdeine &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i self scholdest do synne; [151] Take rewarde of &thorn;ine value &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne be to foule to &thorn;ine value ne to &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> self [152] &para; Alas wele ouhten &thorn;ei &thorn;an to be 
<PB REF="00000645.tif" N="613"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="599"> seruant &amp; &thorn;rall to sinne &amp; sore biene aschamed of hem self; [153] &thorn;at god of his enles goodenesse ha&thorn; sette hem in hihe astate or &yogh;euen hem wi&thorn; strenke&thorn; of body. hele beaute. prosperite; [154] &amp; bouht hem fro de&thorn; with his hert blode; &thorn;at &thorn;ei so vnkindely a&yogh;eines his gentillesse whiten him so velenslye to slauhter of here owen sowles [155] &para; O goode god. &yogh;e wemmen &thorn;at bien of so grete beaute; remembre&thorn; &yogh;owe of &thorn;e prouerbe of Salomon. he sei&thorn;e [156] A faire womman &thorn;at is a fole of hir body; is like to a ringe of golde &thorn;at were&thorn; in &thorn;e groyne of a sowe [157] &para; For riht as a sowe wrote&thorn; in euery ordure; So wrote&thorn; sche hir beaute in stinkeinge ordur of sinne</P>
<P>[158] &para; The &thorn;red cause &thorn;at ouht to meue a max to contricione is &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> drede of &thorn;e daie of dome &amp; of &thorn;e orribles peynes of hell for as seint Ierom sei&thorn;e. Att euery time &thorn;at me remembre&thorn; of &thorn;e daie of dome .I. quake; [160] For whan .I. ete or drink or do what so .I. do euer seme&thorn; me &thorn;at &thorn;e trompe soune&thorn; in myne ere; [161] Rise&thorn; vpe &thorn;at bien dede &amp; comme&thorn; to &thorn;e Iugement [162] of god; &para; Muche ouht iche man to drede suche a Iugement &thorn;ere as we scholne bue all as sei&thorn; seint Poule Be forne &thorn;e strete of oure lorde ihesu crist. [163] Where as &yogh;e schal maake a general con|gregacioun; Wher as noman mai be absent; [164] For certes &thorn;ere ne availe&thorn; none assoyene ne excusacion; [165] And not onely &thorn;at oure fautes schal bu Iuged; bot eke &thorn;at al oure werkes schal openli be knowe; [166] And as sei&thorn;e seint Bernarde. There ne schal no pledynge availe ne no sleiht; we scholne &yogh;euen Rekenynge of euery Idel worde [167] &para; There schal we haue a Iuge. &thorn;at maie nouht be deceyued ne corruppte; And whi for al oure &thorn;ouhtes biene discouerde as to him; ne for preier ne for meede he wil not be corrupte; [168] And &thorn;erefor sei&thorn;e Salomon. &thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e of god wol nou&yogh;t bue corrupte; And &thorn;erfor sei&thorn; Salomon; The wreche 
<PB REF="00000646.tif" N="614"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="600"> of god ne wil nouht spare no wight for praier ne for &yogh;eft; And &thorn;ere fore att &thorn;e daie of dome &thorn;ere is none hope to escape; [169] wherefore as sei&thorn;e Anselme &para; Ful grete anguysche <MILESTONE N="232b" UNIT="folio">Scholne &thorn;e sinful folke have att &thorn;at time; [170] &para; &THORN;ere schal be &thorn;e steren &amp; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wro&thorn;e Iuge; site aboue; And vnder him &thorn;e orrible putte of hell open to de|strey him &thorn;at mot be knowe his . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> sinnes openly be schewde be forne god &amp; be for euery creature; [171] And one &thorn;e left side mo deueles &thorn;an hert maie &thorn;ink for to harye; &amp; to drawe &thorn;e sinful sowles to &thorn;e peine of hell; [172] and with inne &thorn;e hertes of folke schal be &thorn;e byteinge conscience; And wi&thorn; oute for&thorn; schal be &thorn;e werld al berneynge [173] &para; Wheder schal &thorn;an &thorn;e wriched sinful soule flee to hide hime. Certes he maie nou&yogh;t hide him; he most com for&thorn;e &amp; schewe him [174] For certes as sei&thorn; seint Ierom. The er&thorn;e schal cast him oute of him; &amp; &thorn;e see also &amp; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> eyre also &thorn;at schal be ful of &thorn;onder clappes &amp; lyhtnynges; [175] Nowe so&thorn;ely who so wil remembre of &thorn;is &thorn;inges .I. gesse &thorn;at his sinnes schal nouht turne him into delite; bote to grete sorwe for drede of peyne of hell; [176] And &thorn;ere for sei&thorn; Iob to god; &para; Suffur lorde &thorn;at .I. maie a while be waile &amp; wepe ar .I. go; &amp; wepe withe outen retorneinge to &thorn;e derke lande. couered with &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> derkenesse of de&thorn;e [177] to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> londe of Misese &amp; of derkenesse where as is schadowe of de&thorn;e; where as is none o&thorn;er or|dinance bot grisly drede &thorn;at euer schal last [178] &para; lo here may &yogh;e seen &thorn;at Iob preide respite a while to be-wepe &amp; weile his trespas. For so&thorn;ely o daie of Respite is better &thorn;an al &thorn;e tresoure of &thorn;is werlde. [179] &para; And for alsomuche as a man mai aquite him self beforne god be penitence in &thorn;is werlde &amp; nouht be tresour; &thorn;ere fore scholde he preye to god to &yogh;eue him respite a while to be wepen &amp; be weilen his trespas; [180] ffor certes al &thorn;e sorwe &thorn;at a man myht make fro &thorn;e begynynge 
<PB REF="00000647.tif" N="615"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="601"> of &thorn;e werld is bot a luytel &thorn;inge. att &thorn;e regarde of &thorn;e sorwe of hell [181] &para; The cause whi &thorn;at Iob calle&thorn; hell &thorn;e londe of derknesse; [182] vnderstonde&thorn; &thorn;at he clepe&thorn; it &thorn;e londe of er&thorn;e for it is stable &amp; neuer schal faile dereknesse; ffor he &thorn;at is in hell ha&thorn;e defaute of liht material; [183] ffor certes &thorn;e derk liht &thorn;at schal come oute of &thorn;e fire &thorn;at euer schal berne schal torne him al to peine &thorn;at is in hell; ffor it schewe&thorn; him to &thorn;e orrible deueles &thorn;at him torment. [184] Couerd wi&thorn; &thorn;e derkenesse of de&thorn;e . . . . .[185] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> bien &thorn;e sinnes; &thorn;at &thorn;e wrecched man ha&thorn;e do; Whiche &thorn;at distourben him to see &thorn;e face of god; riht a derke cloude be twex vs &amp; &thorn;e sonne; [186] londe of mysese; because &thorn;at &thorn;ere bue &thorn;re manere of defautes a&yogh;eynes. &thorn;re &thorn;inges; &thorn;at folke in &thorn;is werlde haue in &thorn;is present lif; &thorn;at is to seie; Honours. delices. &amp; Riches. [187] &para; A&yogh;eines honour haue &thorn;ei in hell schame; &amp; confusione; [188] ffor wele &yogh;e weten &thorn;at men clepen honour &thorn;e reuerence &thorn;at men don to man; Bot in hell is none honour ne reuerence; ffor certes no more reuerence schal be do to a kinge &thorn;an to a knaue; [189] &para; For whiche go[d] sei&thorn;e be &thorn;e prophet Ieremye. Thilke folke &thorn;at me dispisen schal bue in dispite [190] &para; Honour is eke cleped grete lod|schipe; Thare schal no wight seruen o&thorn;ere bot of harme &amp; turment; Honour is eke cleped grete dignite &amp; hihe|nesse bot in hel schal &thorn;ei be al for-troden of deuels; [191] As god <MILESTONE N="233a" UNIT="folio">sei&thorn;e; Orrible deuels schal comen &amp; gone vpon &thorn;e heuedes of dampned folk; And &thorn;is is for also muche. &thorn;e hiher &thorn;at &thorn;ei were in &thorn;is present lif; &thorn;e more schal &thorn;ei buen abated &amp; defouled in hell; [192] &para; A&yogh;eine &thorn;e riches of &thorn;is werld schal &thorn;e haue mysese of pouerte; And &thorn;is pouert schal be foure &thorn;inges. [193] in defaute of tresour of whiche 
<PB REF="00000648.tif" N="616"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="602"> dauid sei&thorn;e &thorn;e riche folke &thorn;at enbrasen &amp; coueten in all herte &thorn;e tresoure of &thorn;is werlde; scholne slepe in &thorn;e slepeinge of de&thorn;e As no &thorn;inge schal &thorn;ei finden in al hir handes of hire tresour [194] &para; And more ouere &thorn;e Misese of hell schall ben in defaute of mete &amp; drinke; [195] ffor god sei&thorn; &thorn;us be moyses; Thei scholne be wastede wi&thorn; hunger &amp; &thorn;e berdes of hell schal deuouren him wi&thorn; bitter de&thorn; An &thorn;e gal of &thorn;e dragon . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> hir morsel; [196] And fer&thorn;er ouere hire mysese schal buen in defaute of clo&thorn;einge; for &thorn;ei schal be nake in body as in clo&thorn;inge; saue &thorn;e fire in whiche &thorn;ei birne; &amp; o&thorn;ere fel&thorn;es [197] &amp; naked schal &thorn;ei bien in soule of al manere of vertues; whiche &thorn;at is &thorn;e clo&thorn;einge of soule; // Wher bue &thorn;an &thorn;e gaie Robes &amp; &thorn;e soft schetes &amp; &thorn;e smale schertes; [198] Lo what sei&thorn;e god of hem be &thorn;e prophet Ysaye; &thorn;at vnder hem schal be strewed mouhtes; &amp; here couertours schal be of &thorn;e wermes of hell. [199] And fer&thorn;er ouere hire mysese schalbe in defaute of frendes; For he is nou&yogh;t pouer &thorn;at ha&thorn;e goode frendes bott &thorn;ere is no frende; [200] ffor ney&thorn;ere god ne creature schall be frende to hem; And euery of hem schal haten o&thorn;ere wi&thorn; dedeli hate; [201] &thorn;e sonnes of &thorn;e douhtern schal rebellen a&yogh;eines fader &amp; moder &amp; kinrede a&yogh;eines kinrede; &amp; chiden and dispisen iche of hem o&thorn;ere bo&thorn;e daie &amp; nyght; &para; As god sei&thorn;e be &thorn;e prophete Mechias [202] And &thorn;e loueynge childern &thorn;at whilom loued so fleschely eueryche o&thorn;ere wolden eueryche of hem eten o&thorn;ere if &thorn;ei myht; [203] ffor howe schold &thorn;ei louen hem to geder in &thorn;e peine of hell whan &thorn;ei hateden eueryche of hem o&thorn;ere Ey&thorn;erin &thorn;e prosperite of &thorn;is lif [204] &para; For truste wele here fleschely loue was dedely hate as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e prophete dauid. &para; Wo so &thorn;at loue&thorn; wikked|nesse; he hate&thorn; his soule; [205] And who &thorn;at hate&thorn; his owen soule; certes he may loue none o&thorn;er wight 
<PB REF="00000649.tif" N="617"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="603"> in no manere; [206] And &thorn;erfor in hell is no frenschippe Bot euer &thorn;e more fflessly kinred &thorn;at buen in hell; &thorn;e more curseinge &amp; &thorn;e more chide|inge &thorn;e more dedely hate &thorn;ere is ymonge hem; [207] And fer&thorn;ere ouere &thorn;ei scholen haue defaut of al manere delices; For whi &thorn;e delites bene &thorn;e Appetites of &thorn;e five wittes; as siht; hereynge; Sauereinge; Smel|inge; &amp; toucheinge; [208] Bot in hell here siht schal be ful of derknesse &amp; smoke; &amp; ful of teres; And here hereinge ful of waymentynge &amp; of grontinge of te&thorn;e As sei&thorn; ihesu crist. [209] Her nose|&thorn;relles schal be ful of stinkinge stinke; And as sei&thorn;e ysayas &thorn;e prophete. Here Sauereinge schal be ful of bitter gall; [210] And toucheinge of hire body couerd wi&thorn; fire. &thorn;at neuer schal be quenched; and wi&thorn; wormes &thorn;at neuer schall di&yogh;en. As god seide be &thorn;o mou&thorn;e of Isaye; [211] And for alsomuche as &thorn;ei schol not wene &thorn;at &thorn;ei mei deyen for peyne. &amp; be hire de&thorn; flie fro peyne; &thorn;at maie vnder-stonde be &thorn;e worde of Iobe; &thorn;at sei&thorn; &thorn;ere <MILESTONE N="233b" UNIT="folio">as is &thorn;e schadow of de&thorn;e; [212] Certes a schadowe ha&thorn;e likenesse of &thorn;e &thorn;inge of whiche it is schadow; Bot &thorn;e schadowe is nouht &thorn;e same &thorn;inge of whiche it is schadowe [213] Riht so fare&thorn; &thorn;e peyne of hell; It is like de&thorn;e for &thorn;e angwysshe orrible And whie; ffor it peyne&thorn; hem euere as &thorn;ouhe men schold dyen anone; Bot certes &thorn;ei schol not deye [214] &para; For as sei&thorn;e seint Gregorie to wrecched kaytifes schal be de&thorn;e with owten de&thorn;; And ende wi&thorn; outen ende; And defaute with oute faileinge; [215] ffor here de&thorn; schal alwey lyfe; And here ende schal euermore be ginne; And here defaute schal nouht faile [216] &para; And &thorn;ere fore sei&thorn; seint Iohn &thorn;e Euaungeliste; Thei schal folowen de&thorn; &amp; &thorn;ei schal nouht finden him; And &thorn;ei desiren to deye; And de&thorn; schal flye fro hem; [217] And Eke Iob sei&thorn;; &thorn;at in hell is none order of Reule; [218] &para; And all be it so &thorn;at god ha&thorn;e created al &thorn;inge in riht ordre &amp; no&thorn;inge with 
<PB REF="00000650.tif" N="618"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="604"> outen order; Bot al &thorn;inges bene ordeyned &amp; nom|bred; &yogh;ete na&thorn;eles &thorn;ei &thorn;at bue dampned bien no &thorn;inge in ordre ne holde no &thorn;inge in ordre. [219] ffor &thorn;e er&thorn;e schal bere hem no fruyte. [220] For as &thorn;e prophet sei&thorn;e dauid; God schal destruye &thorn;e fruyte of &thorn;e er&thorn;e as fro hem; ne water schal &yogh;eue hem no moystur. ne &thorn;e eyer no refrissheinge; ne fire no lyht; [221] For as sei&thorn;e seint Basile; The birneinge of &thorn;e fire of &thorn;is werlde schal god gif in hell to hem &thorn;at bu dampned; [222] Bot &thorn;e liht &amp; &thorn;e clerenesse. schal be &yogh;ouen in to heuen to his childerne; Riht as &thorn;e good man giffe&thorn; flesshe to his childerne and bones to his hondes; [223] And for &thorn;ei schol haue none hope to escape sei&thorn;e Iobe; Att &thorn;e laste; &thorn;at &thorn;ere schold orroure &amp; grisely drede dwel wi&thorn; outen ende; [224] Orrour is alwei drede of harme &thorn;at is to comme; And &thorn;is drede schal euer dwell in &thorn;e hertes of hem &thorn;at bu dampned &para; And for &thorn;at haue&thorn; &thorn;ei lorne al here hope for vij. causes; [225] ffirst for god &thorn;at is hire Iuge schal bue wi&thorn; outen mercy to hem. Ne &thorn;ei may not plese him ne none of his halowes ne &thorn;ei maie &yogh;eue no &thorn;inge for hire Raunson; [226] Ne &thorn;ei haue no voice to speke to him; ne &thorn;ei maie not fli&yogh;e fro peine ne &thorn;ei haue no goodenesse in hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei maie schew to deliuer hem fro peine; [227] &para; And &thorn;erefore sei&thorn;e Salomon &thorn;e wykked man deye&thorn;; And whan he is dede he schal haue no hope to ascape fro peyne [228] &para; Who so schame will wele vn|derstonde &thorn;es peynes &amp; be &thorn;inke him wele &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e deserued &thorn;ilke peynes for his sinnes; Certes he schold haue more talent to sike &amp; to wepe; &thorn;an for to singen &amp; to pley; [229] &para; For as sei&thorn; Salomon. Who so &thorn;at hadde &thorn;e science for to knowe; &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at buen &thorn;at ystablisshed for sinne; he wold maake sorwe; [230] &para; &thorn;ilke science as sei&thorn;e seinte Austine. Make&thorn; a man to weyment in his herte;</P>
<P>[231] &para; &thorn;e fer&thorn;e point &thorn;at ouhte maake a man 
<PB REF="00000651.tif" N="619"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="605"> haue contricion is &thorn;e sorweful remembrance of &thorn;e goode &thorn;at he ha&thorn; lost to done here in er&thorn;e; And eke good &thorn;at he ha&thorn; lorne; [232] So&thorn;ely &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; loste; ey&thorn;ere &thorn;ei bien &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; wrouht er he fell in to dedely sinne. or elles &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at he wrouht while he laie in sinne. [233] So&thorn;ely &thorn;e gode werkes &thorn;at he dide beforne &thorn;at he fell in sinne bien al mortified &amp; astoned; &amp; dullede be &thorn;e oft sinynge [234] &para; &thorn;e to&thorn;er goode werke &thorn;at he wrouht whiles he ley in sinne; &thorn;ei bien vtterly dede as to &thorn;e lif perdurable in heuen [235] &para; &thorn;an &thorn;elke goode werke &thorn;at bien <MILESTONE N="234a" UNIT="folio">mortified be oft sinynge; Whiche good werkes he dide whiles he was in charite; ne mowen neuere quyken a&yogh;eine withouten parfite penitence [236] And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn;e god be &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of ezechiel; That is &thorn;e rihtfulman re|torne a&yogh;eine from his rihtwisnesse &amp; to worche wikked|nesse schal he leue [237] naye ffor al &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at ha&thorn; wrouht ne scholne neuer bue in remembraunce; ffor he schal deye in sinne [238] &para; And vpon &thorn;ilke chapeter sei&thorn; seint Gregorie &thorn;us &thorn;at we scholde vnder|stonde &thorn;is principaly. [239] That whanne we do dedely sinne; it is for nouht &thorn;an to reherse or to drawe in to memorie &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at we haue wrouht beforne; [240] &para; For certes in &thorn;e worcheinge of dedely sinne; &thorn;ere is no truste to no good werke &thorn;at we han done to fore; &thorn;at is to seine As for to haue &thorn;ere bye; &thorn;e lif per|durable in heuen; [241] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> whan we haue contricione; [242] Bott so&thorn;ely &