<PB REF="00000654.tif" N="622"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="608"> bounde so &thorn;at &thorn;e blode braste oute att euery nayle of his handes as sei&thorn;e seint Austine [270] &para; And for&thorn;ermore for as muche &thorn;at reson of man wil nou&yogh;t daunte sensu|alite whan it maie; &thorn;erefore is man wor&thorn;i to haue schame; And &thorn;us suffred oure lorde ihesu criste; for man; whan &thorn;ei spitten in his vesage // [271] And fer&thorn;ere ouere for as muche &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;e kaytif body of man/ is rebel bo&thorn;e to resoun / &amp; sensualite; And &thorn;erefore is it wor&thorn;i &thorn;e de&thorn;e; [272] And &thorn;is suffurde oure lorde ihesu criste for man vpon &thorn;e croys where as &thorn;ere was no party of his body fre with owten grete pyne &amp; bitter passion; [273] And al &thorn;is suffred oure lorde ihesu criste &thorn;at neuere for fete [&middot;. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &para; To mechel am .I. peyned for &thorn;e same &thorn;inges &thorn;at .I. neuer deseruede And to muchel defouled for frendschipe &thorn;at man is wor&thorn;i to haue; [274] And &thorn;ere|fore maie &thorn;e sinnful man wele saie. as sei&thorn;e seint Bernard; Acursed be &thorn;e butternesse; . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [275] ffor certes after &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> diuerse discordance of oure wikkednesse was &thorn;e pas|sion of oure lorde ihesu criste. yordeinede in diuerse &thorn;inges [276] as &thorn;us; &para; Certes sinnful mannes soule by-trasede of &thorn;e deuel be couetise of temperile prosperite and scorned be deceyte; Whan he chese&thorn; fleschely delites &para; And &yogh;it is he tormented be impacience of aduersite; &para; And be|spette be seruage in subieccione of sinne; and att &thorn;e last it is sleyne fynaly; [277] ffor &thorn;is disordinance of sinnful man. was ihesu crist first betrayde; And after &thorn;at was he bounde &thorn;at cam for to <MILESTONE N="235a" UNIT="folio">for to vnbynde vs of sinne &amp; of peyne; [278] &thorn;an was he bescorned &thorn;at only scholde be honoured in al &thorn;inges be al &thorn;inges. &amp; of al &thorn;inges; [279] &para; Than was his &thorn;at ouht be desired to be seyne of al man kinde; In whiche Angeles desiren to loken vilansly be-spitte; [280] &thorn;an was he scowrged &thorn;at no &thorn;inge had gulte; &amp; fynally &thorn;an was he crucified And sleyne [281] &para; &thorn;an was he acompliced &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000655.tif" N="623"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="609"> wordes of Ysaye; He was wounded for oure mesdedes &amp; defouled be oure veleynyes; [282] Nowe se&thorn;en. &thorn;at ihesu criste toke vpon him selfe &thorn;e peyne of al oure wikkednesse; Muchel ouht sinful man be-wepe &amp; be-weile &thorn;at for his sinne goddes sonne of heuen schold al &thorn;is peine endure [283] &para; The sext &thorn;inge &thorn;at ouht to meue a man to contricione is &thorn;e hope of &thorn;e &thorn;re &thorn;inges; &thorn;at is to seine for&yogh;euenesse; And &thorn;e &yogh;eft of grace wele for to do; And &thorn;e glory of heuen with &thorn;e whiche god schal guerdon m&amacr;n for his goode dedes; [284] &para; And for as muche as ihesu crist; &yogh;ife&thorn; vs &thorn;is &yogh;eftes of his largesse and of his souereyne bounte; &thorn;er for is he cleped Ihesus nazarenus rex iudeorum; [285] Ihesus ys to seyne saueour or sal|uation on whome men scholne hope to haue for&yogh;euenesse of sinnes whiche &thorn;at is properly saluacione of synnes; [286] And &thorn;erfor seide &thorn;e Angel to Ioseph; &thorn;ou clepest his name ihesus &thorn;at schal saue his peple of her sinnes; [287] And here of sei&thorn; seinte Peter; There nys none o&thorn;ere name vnde heuen &thorn;at is &yogh;oue to any man bot only . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> Ihesus [288] nazarenus. Whiche is as moche to seine As florischeinge in whiche a man schal hope; &thorn;at he &thorn;at &yogh;eue&thorn; him remissioun of sinnes; schal &yogh;eu also him grace wele to do; &para; For in &thorn;e floure is &thorn;e hope of fruyte in tyme cominge And in for&yogh;efnesse of sinnes hope of grace wele to do; [289] &para; .I. was att &thorn;e dore of &thorn;ine herte sei&thorn; ihesus and cleped for to entre &para; He &thorn;at opene&thorn; to me schal haue for-&yogh;euenesse of sinne; [290] I. wil entre in to him be my grace And soupe with him be &thorn;e good werkes &thorn;at he schal done; whiche werkes bene &thorn;e foode of god; &amp; he schal soupe wi&thorn; me; be &thorn;e gret Ioy &thorn;at schal be &yogh;oue to him; [291] Thus man hope for his werkes of penance god scholde &yogh;eue him his regne as he behote&thorn; him in &thorn;e gospel;</P>
<P>[292] &para; Nowe schal man vnderstonde in whiche 
<PB REF="00000656.tif" N="624"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="610"> manere schal be his contricion; .I. say &thorn;at it schal bue vniuersale &amp; totale; &thorn;is is to sei a man schal be verrey repentant for al his sinnes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; done in delite of his &thorn;ouht; ffor delite is ful perilous; [293] ffor &thorn;er bien tuo maners of consentynges; &thorn;at one of hem is cleped consentynge of affeccioune whan a man is meved to do synne &amp; delite&thorn; him longe for to &thorn;inke on &thorn;at sinne; [294] He ha&thorn;e reson &thorn;at perteyne&thorn; wele &thorn;at it is sinne a&yogh;eines &thorn;e lawe of god; . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> Al &thorn;ouhe his reson ne consent no&yogh;t to do &thorn;e sinne in dede; [295] &yogh;ut seine somme doctours &thorn;at suche delite &thorn;at dwelle&thorn; longe is ful perilouse; al be it neuer so lite; [296] And also a man scholde sorwe for al &thorn;at; &thorn;at euer he ha&thorn; desired a&yogh;eines &thorn;e lawe of <MILESTONE N="235b" UNIT="folio">god with perfite consentinge of resoun; ffor &thorn;ere of is no doute &thorn;at it ne is dedely sinne; In &thorn;e consentynge [297] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &amp; in to &thorn;e dede; [298] where for .I. seye &thorn;at many men ne repenten hem neuere of suche &thorn;ouhtes &amp; delices ne neuer schreuen hem of it bot onely of &thorn;e dede of grete sinnes vtwarde. [299] where for .y. saye &thorn;at suche wikked delites &amp; wikked &thorn;ouhtes bien subtile begillours of hem &thorn;at scholne be dampned; [300] More ouere man ouht to sorwen For his wikked wordes; as for his wikked dedes &para; For certes &thorn;e repentance of a singuler sinne and nouhte repent of al his o&thorn;ere sinnes; or elles repent him of al his o&thorn;ere sinnes; &amp; not of singulere sinne maye nouht aveile [301] &para; For certes almyhti god; is al goode. And &thorn;erfor he for-&yogh;eue&thorn; all; or elles riht nouht; [302] And here of sei&thorn;e seint Augustine.I. wote certeinly [303] &thorn;at god is enmy to euery sinner; And howe &thorn;an he &thorn;at obserue&thorn; o synne schal he haue for&yogh;euenesse of &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000657.tif" N="625"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="611"> remenant of his o&thorn;ere sinnes; Nay; [304] &para; And for&thorn;ere ouer. contricion scholde be woundes sorwful; And Ang|uisschous; and &thorn;erfor &yogh;eue&thorn; him god pleynly his mercy And &thorn;erfor whan Mi soule was anguysshous with in me .I. had remembrance of god &thorn;at my preyer myht com to him [305] &para; For&thorn;ere ouere contricion must be continuel; and &thorn;at men haue sted|fast purpos to schriue him; &amp; for to amend him of his lif [306] &para; ffor so&thorn;ely whiles contricion laste&thorn; man maie haue hope of for&yogh;efnesse; And of &thorn;is come&thorn; hate of sinne &thorn;at destruye&thorn; sinne bo&thorn;e in him selfe and eke in o&thorn;ere folke as his power; [307] ffor whiche<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota bene de qui sit amor dei</NOTE> sei&thorn;e dauid; &yogh;e &thorn;at louen god hate&thorn; wikkednesse; For trustu&thorn; wele to loue god; is. for to loue &thorn;at he loue&thorn; &amp; hate &thorn;at he hate&thorn;e</P>
<P>[308] &para; The last &thorn;inge &thorn;at men schal vnderstond is &thorn;is; where of availe&thorn; contricion; I. saie &thorn;at sumtim contricion deliuer&thorn; a man fro sinne [309] of whiche &thorn;at dauid sei&thorn;e; I. saie quod dauid &thorn;at is to saie I purposed firmly to schryue me And &thorn;ou lorde relesed my sinne; [310] &para; And riht so as contricion ne veile&thorn; nou&yogh;t with oute sadd purpos of scrifte . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> or satisfaccione wi&thorn;oute contricione [311] &para; And more contricion distreye&thorn; &thorn;e prison of hell &amp; make&thorn; wayke; And feble&thorn; &thorn;e strenge&thorn;es of &thorn;e deueles; And restori&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;ift of &thorn;e holy goste; And of al vertues [312] &amp; interclense&thorn; &thorn;e soule of sinne; Ande deliuere&thorn; &thorn;e soule fro &thorn;e peyne of hell &amp; fro &thorn;e compaignie of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> deuel; And fro &thorn;e seruage of synne &para; And restore&thorn; to al goodes espiritueles in to &thorn;e compaignie communyoun of holy kirke [313] &para; And for&thorn;ere ouere; it make&thorn; him &thorn;at was whilom son of Ire. to be &thorn;e son of grace; And al &thorn;is &thorn;inges he preue&thorn; be holy writte; [314] And &thorn;erefor he &thorn;at wolde sett his entent to &thorn;ese &thorn;inges he war ful 
<PB REF="00000658.tif" N="626"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="612"> wise; ffor so&thorn;e he scholde nouht &thorn;an in al his lif to haue corage to sinne &para; Bot &thorn;an his body &amp; al his herte to &thorn;e seruise of ihesu criste; And &thorn;ere of done him homoge [315] &para; ffor certes oure swete lorde ihesu criste ha&thorn; spare vs so debonerly in oure folyes; &thorn;at if he ne hadd pite of mannes soule a sori songe miht we al singe;</P>
<TRAILER>Explicit prima pars penitencie</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Incipit secunda pars. eiusdem.</HEAD>
<P>[316] The secunde parte of penitence; is confession &thorn;at is signe of contricione; [317] Now scholne &yogh;e vnder-stande; what is confessioun; And<MILESTONE N="236a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>MS. repeats</I> <SUP>1_2</SUP> And&mdash;none</NOTE>And whe&thorn;er it ouhte nedes to be or none;<SUP>2</SUP> And whiche &thorn;inges bene couenable; to verrey confession;</P>
<P>[318] &para; ffirst schalt &thorn;ou vnderstonde &thorn;at confessioun is verreye scheweinge of sinnes to &thorn;e preste; [319] &thorn;is is to seye verraly; &thorn;at he mote confessen him of all &thorn;e condicions &thorn;at be-longen to his sinne as ferfor&thorn; as he can; [320] Al mote be saide &amp; no&thorn;inge excused; ne hidde ne awrapped And nouht auaunt him of his goode werkes [321] &para; And for&thorn;ere ouere it is necessarie to vnder|stande whense &thorn;at sinnes springen; and howe &thorn;ei encresen; And whiche &thorn;ere biene</P>
<P>[322] of springeinge of sinnes; As sei&thorn;e seint Poule on &thorn;is wise &para; &THORN;at rihte as be a man sinne entred first in to &thorn;is werlde &amp; &thorn;oruht &thorn;at sinne deyede; Riht so &thorn;ilke de&thorn;e entre&thorn; in to al men &thorn;at sinneden; [323] And &thorn;is man was Adam be whome &thorn;at sinne entred into &thorn;is werlde whan &thorn;at he brakke &thorn;e commandement of god [324] &para; And &thorn;ere fore he &thorn;at first was so myhti &thorn;at he scholde not haue deied be-cam suche one &thorn;at him must nedes deie; whe&thorn;er he wolde or none; &amp; al his progenie &thorn;at is in &thorn;is werlde &thorn;at in &thorn;ilke manere synnen [325] &para; Loke &thorn;at in &thorn;e state of innocence whan Adam &amp; Eue 
<PB REF="00000659.tif" N="627"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="613"> nakede weren in paradise; And no&thorn;inge schame ne hadden of here nakednesse. [326] How &thorn;at &thorn;e serpent &thorn;at was most wyly of al o&thorn;ere bestes &thorn;at god had maked seide to &thorn;e womman &para; Commaunded god to &yogh;owe &yogh;e schold nou&yogh;t of euery tre in paradise [327] The womman anseward; Of &thorn;e fruyte quod sche of &thorn;e trees in paradyse we feden vs bot so&thorn;ely of &thorn;e fruyte of &thorn;e tre &thorn;at is in &thorn;e myddel of paradise; God for-bede vs for ete ne for to touche it lest parauentour we schold deyen; [328] &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> serpent seid to &thorn;e womman Nay nay; &yogh;e schol nou&yogh;t deye of de&thorn;e; for so&thorn;e god wote &thorn;at what daie &yogh;e eten &thorn;ereof &yogh;oure ey&yogh;en schal open And &yogh;e scholne bue as goddes knowynge goode &amp; harme; [329] The womman sawhe &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tre was good to fedeinge &amp; faire to &thorn;e y&yogh;e &amp; delitable to &thorn;e sihte Sche toke of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fruyte of &thorn;e tree &amp; ete of it; And &yogh;af it to hir husbonde &amp; he ete; And anone &thorn;e ey&yogh;en of hem bo&thorn;e opened; [330] And when &thorn;at &thorn;ei knewe &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren naked; &thorn;e sowde of fige leues in manere of breches to hiden hir membres; [331] &para; Here maye &yogh;e see &thorn;at dedely sinne ha&thorn; furst suggestion of &thorn;e fende; As schewe&thorn; here be Hadder; And afterward &thorn;e delite of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> flesche as schewe&thorn;e here by Eua; And after &thorn;at &thorn;e consentinge of &thorn;e resoun as schewe&thorn; be adam; [332] For. truste&thorn; wele &thorn;ouhe so were &thorn;at &thorn;e fende tempted one; &thorn;at is to saie &thorn;e flesshe And &thorn;e flesshe hadde delite in &thorn;e beaute of &thorn;e fruyte defended; &yogh;ite certes til &thorn;at resoun; &thorn;at is to seie; Adam consen|tynge to &thorn;e eteynge of &thorn;e fruyte &thorn;at stode hihe in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> state of Innocence [333] &para; Of &thorn;ilke Adam toke we &thorn;ilke sinne of originale for of him flesshely discended bu we all; and engenderd of vile &amp; corrupte matier; [334] And whan &thorn;e soule is put in oure bodye riht anone is con|tracte originale sinne; And &thorn;at was erst bot onely peyne of concupiscence is afterewarde bo&thorn;e peyne &amp; sinne; [335] And &thorn;erefor be we al yborne sonnes of 
<PB REF="00000660.tif" N="628"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="614"> wra&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>; And of dampnacion perdurable; if it nere Baptisme &thorn;at we receyuen; which be-nymme&thorn; vs &thorn;e culpe; Bot for so&thorn;e &thorn;e peyne duelle&thorn; with vs as &thorn;e tempta<MILESTONE N="236b" UNIT="folio"> cione; Whiche peine hiht concupiscence [336] And &thorn;is concupiscence whan it is wrongfully disposed. or ordeinte in man; it make&thorn; him coueyten &thorn;e couetise of flesshly sinne be siht of his ey&yogh;en; As to er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges &para; And eke couetise of hihenesse Be pride of hert;/</P>
<P>[337] Now as for to speke of &thorn;e firste couetise &thorn;at is concupiscence after &thorn;e lawe of owre membres &thorn;at weren lawfulli maked and be rihtful Iugge|ment of god [338] .I. saie for alsomuche &thorn;at man is nouhte obeissant to god &thorn;at is lorde &para; &thorn;are for is flesshe to him disobeisant &thorn;oruhe concupiscence; . . . . .[339] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> It is impossible bot he be distempered sum time and noyde in his flesshe to sinne [340] And &thorn;is &thorn;inge maie nouht faile; as longe as &thorn;at leue&thorn;; It maie wele wex feble &amp; feile be vertu of Baptime &amp; be &thorn;e grace of god &thorn;oruhe penitence; [341] Bot fully schal it neuere quenche; &thorn;at he ne schal som time be meued in himself; Bot he were al refreyned be sekenesse or be malafice of sorcerye or colde drinkes; [342] &para; For whatte sei&thorn; seinte poule; The flesshe coueti&thorn;e a&yogh;eine &thorn;e spirite; And &thorn;e spirite a&yogh;eine &thorn;e flesche. &thorn;ei bien so contrarie; &amp; so striuen &thorn;at a man mai nou&yogh;t done alwei as he wolde; [343] The same sei&thorn;e seinte Poule; After his grete penance in water &amp; in land; In water be nyht &amp; be daye in grete perile And in grete peine in lande; &amp; in famyne &amp; in &thorn;urst; in colde &amp; in clo&thorn;es want|ynge; And ones stormed almoste to &thorn;e de&thorn;e; [344] &yogh;itte seid he Alas .I. keytif man who schal deliuer me fro &thorn;e prison; of my caitif body; [345] &para; And seint Ierom whan he longe time had woned in deserte; Where as he hadd no compaignie bot bestes; Where as he hadde 
<PB REF="00000661.tif" N="629"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="615"> no mete bot erbes; &amp; water to his drink; ne no bedde bot &thorn;e naked er&thorn;e; For whiche his flesshe was blac as an Ethiopen for hete &amp; nyhe destruyed for colde; [346] &yogh;ete seyde he &thorn;e birneynge of lycheri boyled in al his body [347] &para; Where-for .I. wote wele sekurly &thorn;at &thorn;ei bu desceyuede &thorn;at seine &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne bien nou&yogh;t tempted in her body; [348] wittenesse of seint Iame &thorn;e Appostle &thorn;at sei&thorn;e &thorn;at euery whihte is tempted in his owen con|cupiscence; &thorn;at is to seye &thorn;at eueryche of vs ha&thorn;e matier &amp; occasion to be tempted of &thorn;e norissheinge of sinne &thorn;at is in his bodye [349] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; seinte Iohn in &thorn;e euaungeliste; If &thorn;at we seine &thorn;at we be wi&thorn; outen sinne we deceyuen oureself &amp; treu&thorn;e is nouht in vs;</P>
<P>[350] &para; Nowe scholn &yogh;e vnderstonde in what manere sinne waxe&thorn; &amp; encrese&thorn; in man; The first &thorn;inge is &thorn;ilke norischeinge of sinne of whiche .I. spak be forne &thorn;ilke concupiscence; [351] And after &thorn;at comme&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> suggestione of &thorn;e deuel; &thorn;is is to seie &thorn;e deueles belye &thorn;e whiche he blowe&thorn; in man &thorn;e fire of concupiscence [352] &para; And after &thorn;at a man be|&thorn;inke&thorn; him whe&thorn;ere he wil do or none &thorn;ilk &thorn;inge to whiche he is tempted; [353] And &thorn;an if &thorn;at a man wi&thorn;-stande and weife &thorn;e firste entiseinge of his flesshe and of o&thorn;e fende; &thorn;an is it no sinne; And if so be &thorn;at he do not so &thorn;an fele&thorn; he anone a flamme of delite; [354] and &thorn;an it is goode to be ware &amp; to kepe him wele; or elles he wil fall anone in to consentynge of sinne; And <MILESTONE N="237a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;an wil he do it if he maye haue time &amp; space; [355] And of &thorn;is matier sei&thorn; Moyses be &thorn;e deuel in &thorn;is manere; The fende fende sei&thorn;e .I. wil chace &amp; pursewe &thorn;e man be wikked suggestiones; and .I. wil hente him be moveinge or stereinge of sinne &para; And .I. will departe my prise or my preye be de|liberacion &amp; my lust schal bue complised in delice; I. wil drawe my swerde in consentinge; [356] &para; For certes riht as as a swerde departe&thorn; a &thorn;inge in two peces; Riht 
<PB REF="00000662.tif" N="630"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="616"> so consentinge departe&thorn; god fro man. <GAP> And &thorn;an wil .I. sle him with myne honde in de&thorn;e of sinne; &thorn;us sei&thorn;e &thorn;e fende. [357] For certes &thorn;an is a man al dede in soule; And &thorn;us is sinne complised by tempt|acion be delite &amp; be consentynge; And &thorn;an is sinne cleped; a<NOTE PLACE="marg">[au&umacr; <I>for</I> actu]</NOTE>u&umacr;iel;</P>
<P>[358] &para; For so&thorn;e sinne is in two maners; ey&thorn;ere it is veniale sinne or dedely sinne So&thorn;e whan men love&thorn; any creature more &thorn;an ihesu criste oure creatour &thorn;an is it dedely sinne; And venial sinne is if man loue ihesu crist lesse &thorn;an him ouht; [359] The dede for so&thorn;e of &thorn;is venial sinne is ful perilous. For it amenuse&thorn; &thorn;e loue &thorn;at men schold haue to god more &amp; more; [360] &para; And &thorn;erfor if a man charge more him self wi&thorn; suche mony venial sinnes certes bot if it so be &thorn;at he sum tym discharge him be schrift; &thorn;ei maie ful lihtly amenuse in him al &thorn;e loue &thorn;at he ha&thorn; to ihesu criste; [361] And in &thorn;is scippe&thorn;e venial in to dedely sinne &para; For certes &thorn;e more &thorn;at a man charge&thorn; his soule wi&thorn; venial sinnes; &thorn;e more is he enclined to fal in dedely sinne; [362] And &thorn;erfore lat vs not be necligent to discharge vs of veniale sinnes; ffor &thorn;e prouerbe sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at mony a smale make&thorn; a grete; [363] An herken &thorn;is ensample; A grete wawe of &thorn;e see comme&thorn; sum time wi&thorn; so grete a violence; &thorn;at it drenche&thorn; &thorn;e schippe &para; And &thorn;e same harme done som tim &thorn;e smale dropes<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Exemplum</NOTE> of water; &thorn;at entre&thorn; &thorn;oruhe a luytel creuyse in to &thorn;e &thorn;urroke &amp; in to &thorn;e bothom of &thorn;e schippe if men bu so necligent; &thorn;at men ne discharge hem nouht be time; [364] And &thorn;erfore al &thorn;ouhe &thorn;ere bue difference betuex &thorn;es tuo causes of drencheinge; Algate &thorn;e schipe is dreinte; [365] Riht so fare&thorn; it somtyme of dedely sinne; &amp; of anoyous venials sinnes whan &thorn;ei multiplie in a man so gretely; &thorn;at &thorn;ilke werldly &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;oruhe whiche He sinne&thorn; venyaly; ys as grete in his herte as &thorn;e loue of god or more [366] 
<PB REF="00000663.tif" N="631"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="617"> <SUP>1</SUP>And &thorn;ere-for &thorn;e loue of euery &thorn;inge &thorn;at is not be-sette in gode; ne done principale for goddes sake; Al &thorn;ouhe a man loue it lasse &thorn;an god; &yogh;it is it venial sinne; [367] And dedely sinne whan &thorn;e loue of any &thorn;inge weye&thorn;e in &thorn;e hert of a man as muche as &thorn;e loue of god ore<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">[<SUP>1_1</SUP> repeated in MS. at &para;]</NOTE> more [368] &para; more dedely sinne As sei&thorn; seinte Austine; is whan man turne&thorn; his herte fro god whiche &thorn;at is verrey souereyne bounte &thorn;at mai nouht chaunge; &amp; &yogh;ive&thorn; <MILESTONE N="237b" UNIT="folio">his herte to a &thorn;inge &thorn;at mai chaunge &amp; flitte; [369] And certes &thorn;at is euery &thorn;inge saue onely god of heuene; For so&thorn;e is if &thorn;at a man &yogh;iue&thorn; his loue whiche &thorn;at he owe&thorn;e al to god. with al his herte vnto a creature; Certes as muche of loue as he &yogh;eueth to whiche creature so muche bereue&thorn; fro god; [370] And &thorn;er for do&thorn;e he sinne; For he &thorn;at is dettour to god ne &yogh;elde&thorn; nou&yogh; al his dette to god &thorn;at his to seye al &thorn;e loue of his herte</P>
<P>[371] &para; Nowe se&thorn; &thorn;at a man vnderstande&thorn; generaly. Whyche is venyale sinne Than is it couenable to tellen of special sinnes whiche &thorn;at a man peraduenture ne deme&thorn; hem nouht sinnes ne schriue&thorn; hem nouht of &thorn;e same &thorn;inges And &yogh;it na&thorn;eles &thorn;ei bue sinnes; [372] &para; As clerkes writen so&thorn;ly &thorn;is is to seye &thorn;at euery time &thorn;at a man ete&thorn; or drinke&thorn; more &thorn;an suffice&thorn; to &thorn;e sustinance of his body; in certeine he do&thorn;e sinn [373] And eke whane he speke&thorn; more &thorn;an it nede; it is sinne; Eke whan he herkene&thorn; nouht mekely &thorn;e compleinte of &thorn;e pore; [374] eke whan he is in hele of body &amp; wol nouht fast whan o&thorn;ere men fast wi&thorn; outen cause resonable; Eke whenne he slepe&thorn; more &thorn;an him nede&thorn;; or whan he comme&thorn; be &thorn;ilk encheson late to cherche or to o&thorn;ere werkes of charite; [375] Eke whan he vse&thorn; his wif wi&thorn; oute souereine desire of engendrure to &thorn;e honour of god; or for &thorn;entent to &yogh;elde to his wif &thorn;e dette of his body; [376] Eke whan he wil not vesete &thorn;e seke; or prisoners whan he maie; 
<PB REF="00000664.tif" N="632"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="618"> eke if he loue wif or childe or any werldly &thorn;inge more &thorn;an reson require&thorn;; Eke if he flater or blandische more &thorn;an him ouht for any necessite; [377] Eke if he amenuse&thorn; or wi&thorn;drawe&thorn; &thorn;e almos of &thorn;e pore; Eke if he apparele&thorn; his mete mor deliciouly &thorn;an nede is or ete it to hastely be lykurus|nesse; [378] eke if he tel vanitees att &thorn;e cherche or in goddes seruise; or &thorn;at he be a talker of ydel wordes of Folye or of velanye; ffor he schal &yogh;elde acomptes of it att &thorn;e daie of dome; [379] Eke whan he behete&thorn; or assure&thorn; to done &thorn;inges &thorn;at he may not performe; Eke whan &thorn;at be lyhtenesse of foly mysvse&thorn; or scorne&thorn; his neyhboure [380] Eke whan he ha&thorn;e any suspecione of &thorn;inge &thorn;ere he ne wote of it no so&thorn;e|fastnesse; [381] Thes &thorn;inge &amp; mo wi&thorn; owten nombre buen sinnes as sei&thorn; seinte Austine</P>
<P>[382] &para; Now schol&yogh;e vnderstonde &thorn;at albeit so &thorn;at none er&thorn;ely man maye eschewe al veniale sinnes; &yogh;it maie he refreyne him be &thorn;e birneinge loue &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e to oure lorde ihesu criste; And be preyers &amp; be confession &amp; o&thorn;ere good werkes; so &thorn;at it schal bot litel greue; [383] ffor as sei&thorn;e seint austyne; If a man lof god in suche manere &thorn;at al &thorn;at euere he do&thorn;e is in &thorn;e loue of god or for &thorn;e loue of god verreyly; for he birne&thorn; in &thorn;e loue of god; [384] Loke howe muche &thorn;at a drope of water falle&thorn; in a fornayce &amp; fol of fire anoye&thorn; or greue&thorn;e; so muche a venial sinne is vnto a man &thorn;at is parfite in &thorn;e loue of ihesu crist; [385] &para; Men maye also refreine venial sinne; be &thorn;e receyueinge of &thorn;e preciouse body of ihesu crist; [386] be receyueinge eke of holy water; be almusdede/ be general confession of &thorn;e confiteor att &thorn;e masse; Att complyne; &amp; be blissinge of bysschopes &amp; be prestes &amp; by o&thorn;er good werkes;
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000665.tif" N="633"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="619">
<HEAD>De .7. peccatis mortalibus</HEAD>
<HEAD>De Superbia.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[from the side]</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>[387]</P>
<P><MILESTONE N="238a" UNIT="folio">NOWe is it be-houely &thorn;inges to tellen whiche buen. &thorn;e .vij. de[d]ly sinne; &thorn;at is to sey chaytifnesse of sinnes Bot al &thorn;ei renne in Coles; Bot in diuerse manere nowe bue &thorn;ei cleped kaytifs; for alsomuche as &thorn;e bu chef &amp; springen of al o&thorn;ere sinnes [388] of &thorn;e rote of &thorn;es frisynnes; . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> ffor if &thorn;is rote springen certeyne braunches as ire envie accidie. or sleu&thorn;e. auarice; or couetise; to comune vnder-stondeinge Glotony. &amp; lychery; [389] And eueryche of &thorn;ese cheue sinnes ha&thorn; his braunches &amp; his &thorn;inges as schal be declared in here chapeter foloweynge;</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Of the Twigs of Pride.]</HEAD>
<P>[390] And &thorn;ouhe so be &thorn;at noman can tell vtterly &thorn;e nomebre of &thorn;e &thorn;inges &amp; of &thorn;e harmes &thorn;at come&thorn; of pride. &yogh;it wil .I. schewe a party of hem as &yogh;e schol vnder|stonde; [391] &para; There is. Inobedience; Auaunteinge; Ipocrisye Despite. Arrogance. Impudence. Swelinge of hert; Insolence. Elacione; . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> Pertenacie; Veinglorie; And many a no&thorn;er &thorn;inge. &thorn;at; I. kan nouht declare;=[392] Ino|bedience is he &thorn;at disobeye&thorn; for despite to &thorn;e commaunde|ment of god and to his souereygnes &amp; to his gostly fadere [393] &para; Auantour is he &thorn;at boste&thorn; of &thorn;e harme or of &thorn;e bounte &thorn;at he ha&thorn; done; [394] Ypocrise is he &thorn;at hide&thorn; him to schewe him suche as he is; &amp; schewe&thorn; him suche as he not is; [395] &para; Dispitous is he &thorn;at ha&thorn; disdeine of his neyhbours; &thorn;at is to seine of his euencristen; or ha&thorn;e despite to do &thorn;at him ouhte to do; [396] &para; Arrogant. is he &thorn;at &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e &thorn;ilke bountes in him &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e nouht; or 
<PB REF="00000666.tif" N="634"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="620"> wene&thorn; &thorn;at he scholde haue hem be his desire; Or elles &thorn;at he deme&thorn; &thorn;at he be &thorn;at he nys note [397] &para; Im|pudent is he &thorn;at for his pride ha&thorn;e no schame for his sinne; [398] Swellinge of hert is he whan a man reioyse&thorn; him of harme &thorn;at he ha&thorn; done; [399] Inso|lent is he &thorn;at despise&thorn; in his Iuggement al o&thorn;ere folke as to regarde of his value; &amp; of his comuneinge. &amp; of his spekeinge; And of his bereinge. [400] &para; Elacione is whan &thorn;at he maie ney&thorn;er suffur to haue Maister ne felawe; [401] &para; Impacient is he; &thorn;at wil nouht bue ytauht ne vnder|nome of his vice; &amp; be strif werre&thorn; trou&thorn;e witingly; &amp; mayntene&thorn; his folye; [402] &para; Contumace is he &thorn;at &thorn;oruhe his indignacion is a&yogh;eines eueryche auctorite or pouer of hem &thorn;at bien his souereignes [403] &para; Pre|sumpcion is he whan a man take&thorn; an emprise &thorn;at him ouht not to do; or elles he maie it not do; &amp; &thorn;at is called Surquidre; &para; Irreuerence is whan men do nouht honoure; &thorn;ere as hem ouhte to do; An wayte&thorn; to be Reuerenset; [404] &para; Pertinacy whan a man defende&thorn; his folye And truste to muche to his owen witte;=[405] veyne glorie is for to haue pompe &amp; delite in temporile richesse; &amp; glorifie&thorn; hem in worldly estates; [406] Iangelynge; is whan a man speke&thorn;e to muche to for folke An clappe&thorn;e as a mullen &amp; take&thorn; no kepe what he sei&thorn;e;</P>
<P>[407] And &yogh;ite is &thorn;ere a priue spice of pride &thorn;at wayte&thorn; furst to be halowed or he be salute al bue he lesse wor&thorn;e &thorn;an &thorn;e to&thorn;ere is peraduenture; And eke waite&thorn; or desire&thorn;e to site or to go aboue him in &thorn;e weie; or kisse pax or bue encensed or go to offringe to for his neyhboure [408] &para; And suche . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> a proude desire to be magnified; &amp; honoured be for &thorn;e peple;</P>
<P>[409] &para; Nowe bene &thorn;ere tuo maners <MILESTONE N="238b" UNIT="folio">of pride &thorn;at on of hem is wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e herte of man; And &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000667.tif" N="635"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="621"> o&thorn;er is with owte; [410] Of whiche so&thorn;ely &thorn;e for|seide &thorn;inges &amp; mo &thorn;an .I. haue seide apartinent to pride; &THORN;at is in &thorn;e hert of man; &para; And &thorn;er to o&thorn;ere spices of pride buen wi&thorn; oute [411] Bot Na&thorn;elesse one of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> spices of pruyde is signe of &thorn;at o&thorn;ere; Riht as &thorn;e gay leuesal att tauerners is signe of &thorn;e wyne &thorn;at is in &thorn;e seler; [412] And &thorn;is is in mony &thorn;inges as in speche &amp; in countenances; and in outrageous araye of clo&thorn;einge; [413] ffor Certes if it nadde be no sinne in clo&thorn;einge; Crist wold nouht so sone haue noted &amp; spoke of &thorn;e clo&thorn;einge; of &thorn;ilke riche man in &thorn;e gospell [414] &para; And as sei&thorn;e seint Gregorie; &thorn;at precious clo&thorn;e is cou|pable for &thorn;e der&thorn;e of it; And for his so&thorn;enesse &amp; for his strangenesse; &amp; for his disgisinesse; and for &thorn;e super|fluite; Or for &thorn;e ino[r]dinance scantnesse; . . . [415] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></P>
<P>[416] &para; As to &thorn;e firste sinne &thorn;at is in superfluyte of clo&thorn;einge whiche &thorn;at make&thorn; it so dere to harme of &thorn;e pele [417] &thorn;at onely &thorn;e cost of enbrowdeinge; &thorn;e degise endentinge or barringe owndeynge paleinge or bendeinge; And sembla wast of clo&thorn;einge in vanite [418] &para; Bot &thorn;er is also costlewe furringe in hire gounes; so muche pounseinge of cheseles to make holes; so muchel dagynge off scheres [419] for&thorn;e wi&thorn;e &thorn;e superfluyte in lenke&thorn; of &thorn;e forsaid gownes; tray|lein in &thorn;e donge &amp; in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> myre on hors &amp; eke on fote as wele of man as of womman; &thorn;at al &thorn;ilke trayleinge is verraly as in effecte wasted &amp; consumed; &thorn;rede bare &amp; roten wi&thorn; donge; ra&thorn;er &thorn;an it is &yogh;ouen to &thorn;e pouer; to grete damage of &thorn;e forseide pouer folke; [420] &amp; &thorn;at in sondre wyse &para; &thorn;is is to seie &thorn;o more &thorn;at clo&thorn;e is wasted; &thorn;e more mot it cost to &thorn;e peple for &thorn;e scarsenesse [421] And; for&thorn;ere ouer. if it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ei wolde &yogh;eue suche pounsed &amp; 
<PB REF="00000668.tif" N="636"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="622"> dagged clo&thorn;einge to &thorn;e pore folke it is nouht conuenient to were for her astate; ne sufficeant to bete her necessite; to kepe hem fro &thorn;e desperacione of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> colde firmament; [422] &para; On &thorn;at o&thorn;ere side to speke of &thorn;e disordinate scantnesse of clo&thorn;inge; as bien &thorn;is cutted sloppes or hanslynes &thorn;at &thorn;oruh her schortnesse ne couern not &thorn;e schamful membres of a man to wykked entente; [423] Alas sum of hem; somme of hem shewen &thorn;e schappe &amp; &thorn;e boce of &thorn;e orrible swollen membres &thorn;at seme&thorn; ylyke to &thorn;e maladye of hyrnya in &thorn;e wrappeinge of her hoses; [424] And eke &thorn;e buttokkes of hem; &thorn;at fare&thorn; as it war &thorn;e hinder parte of a sche ape in &thorn;e ful of &thorn;e mone; [425] And more ouer &thorn;e wreched swolne membres &thorn;at &thorn;ei schewe &thorn;oruhe disgiseinge in departinge of her hoses white &amp; rede seme&thorn; &thorn;at halue him scham|ful priue membres; weren fleyne; [426] And so be &thorn;at &thorn;ei departen her hoses in o&thorn;ere colours as is white &amp; blak; or white &amp; blewe; or blakke &amp; rede; &amp; so for&thorn;e [427] &para; &thorn;an ne seme&thorn; it as be variance of colour &thorn;a halfe &thorn;e partie of his priue membres been corrupte be &thorn;e fire of seint Antonye; or be Cancre or be suche o&thorn;ere meschaunces [428] &para; &YOGH;it of &thorn;e hinder parte of her buttokes; it is ful orrible for to see; ffor certes in &thorn;at partie of hir bodye &thorn;er as &thorn;ei purgen her stinkinge ordure [429] &thorn;at foule partie schewe &thorn;ei prou<MILESTONE N="239a" UNIT="folio">dely to &thorn;e peple in despite of honeste; Whiche honeste &thorn;at ihu criste &amp; his frendes obserued to schew in his lyf. [430] &para; Now as to owtrageous araye of wemmen; God woote &thorn;ouhe &thorn;e visages of hem semen ful chaste &amp; debonayre. &yogh;it notifien &thorn;ei in here araye of atyre likerousnesse &amp; pruyde [431] &para; I say not &thorn;at honeste in clo&thorn;einge of man; &amp; womman is vncouen|able Bot certes &thorn;e superfluyte or &thorn;e disordinance scantid of clo&thorn;einge is reproueable [432] Also &thorn;e sinne of a-ornement or appareile as in &thorn;inges &thorn;at appartenen to Rideinge; As in to mony delicate horses &thorn;at be holden 
<PB REF="00000669.tif" N="637"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="623"> for delite; &thorn;at &thorn;ei bien so faire fatte &amp; costlewe; [433] And also mony a viciouse knave ymayntende be cause of hem; And in to corious harneyse; as in sadels in cropreres. peytrelles; &amp; bridelles couerd wi&thorn; precious clo&thorn;e &amp; riche Barres; &amp; plates of gold. &amp; of siluere; [434] For whiche god sei&thorn;e by Sacarie &thorn;e prophet; I. wil confounde &thorn;e riders of suche horses; [435] This folke taken litel rewardeinge of &thorn;e rideinge of goddes sonne of heuen and of his harneys . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> bot clo&thorn;es of his pouere disciples Ne we rede nou&yogh;t &thorn;at euer he rode on o&thorn;ere beste; [436] I speke &thorn;us of &thorn;e sinne of superfluyte; And nouht for &thorn;e resonable honeste; whan reson it require&thorn;; [437] &para; And for&thorn;er ouere Certes pride is gretly notified in holdeinge of grete meigne; when &thorn;ei bien of luytel profite or riht of no profite; [438] And namely whan &thorn;at mene&yogh;e is felenous &amp; damage|ous to &thorn;e people by hardynesse of hihe lordeschippe; or be way of office [439] &para; For certes suche lordes; fullen &thorn;an her lorschipe to &thorn;e deuel of hell; whan &thorn;e susteigne &thorn;e wykkednesse of here men&yogh;e; [440] Or elles whan &thorn;is folke of lowe degre; as &thorn;ilke &thorn;at holden hosteleries; And &thorn;at is in mony maner of folke &thorn;at susteyne &thorn;eft for hire ostelers; And &thorn;at is in mony maner of disceytes: [441] &thorn;ilke maner of folke bien &thorn;e flyes &thorn;at folowen &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> hony. Or elle &thorn;e hundes &thorn;at &thorn;at folowen &thorn;e Careyne; Whiche for-seide folke stranglen spirituelye her lordschippes; [442] ffor whiche &thorn;us sei&thorn; dauid &thorn;e prophette; Wikked de&thorn; mot comme on &thorn;ilke lordeschipes; And god &yogh;eue &thorn;at &thorn;ei mote descende adoune in to helle; ffor in hire houses bien iniquitees; And schrewnessis &amp; not god of heuen; [443] And certes bot if &thorn;ei done amende|ment; Riht so as god &yogh;af his blissinge to pharao be &thorn;[e s]eruice of Iacob; And to laban be &thorn;e seruice of Ioseph; Riht so god wol &yogh;eue his malison to suche lordeschips And to susteine &thorn;e wikkednesse of her seruantes; but &thorn;ei 
<PB REF="00000670.tif" N="638"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="624"> comme [444] proudly to &thorn;e table and appere&thorn; eke ful oft; ffor certes riche men bu cleped to festes and pouere folke bien putte aweie; And rebuked [445] in excesse of diuerse metes &amp; drinkes; And namely suche maner of Baken metes . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &amp; of semblable waste so &thorn;at it is abusion for to &thorn;inke; [446] And eke of grete preciousenesse of vessell; &amp; curiosite of mynstralcie; By &thorn;e whiche a man is stered &thorn;e more to delices of luxurie; [447] If so be &thorn;at he sette his herte &thorn;e lasse on oure lorde ihesu criste; certeyne it is a sinne; And certeynly &thorn;e delices myht be so grete in &thorn;e case &thorn;at men myht lyhtly fa by hem in-to dedely sinne; [448] &para; The espices &thorn;at sourden of pruyde; so&thorn;ely whan <MILESTONE N="239b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ei sourden of malice ymagenyd and avised and aforne cast; Or elles of vsage bien dedely sinnes it is no doute [449] &amp; whan &thorn;ei sourden be frelte vn|avised sodanly &amp; sodanly wi&thorn;-drawe a&yogh;eine al be &thorn;ei greuous sinnes .I. gesse &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ei bu nouht dedelye; [450] &para; Nowe might men ax where-of &thorn;at pride sourde&thorn; and springe&thorn;; And .I. sum time it springe&thorn; of goodes of Nature; And somme time of &thorn;e goodes of fortune And sum tim of &thorn;e goodes of grace; [451] Certes &thorn;e godes of nature standen in &thorn;e goodes of bodye or goodes of soule; [452] Certes goodes of body bene hele of bodye; strenke&thorn;; diliuernesse; beaute; genterye; ffraunchises; [453] Godes of Nature of &thorn;e soule bien goode wi&thorn; scharp vndestandinge subtile engyne; vertue naturell. goode memorie; [454] &para; Goode of fortune bien richesse; hihe degrees of lordeschippes &para; Preyseinges of &thorn;e peple [455] Goodes of grace biene sciences powere to suffur spyrituele; traveyle benyngnites; vertuous contemplacione withstondinge of temptacione; And semblable &thorn;inges; [456] of whiche forseide goodes certes it is a ful grete folye a man to pride him in any of hem all [457] 
<PB REF="00000671.tif" N="639"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="625"> &para; Nowe as for to speke of goodes of nature; god wote &thorn;at sum tyme we haue hem in nature; Als muche to oure damage as to oure profite; [458] As for to speke of hele of body; Certes it passet ful lyhtlye; And eke it is ful ofte encheson of &thorn;e sekenesse of &thorn;e soule; ffor god woote &thorn;e flesche is a ful grete enmy to &thorn;e soule; And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e more &thorn;at A body is hole; &thorn;e more be we in peril to falle; [459] Eke for to pride him in &thorn;e strenke&thorn; of his bodie; it is an hyhe foly; For certes &thorn;e flesche coueyte&thorn; a&yogh;eine &thorn;e spirit; And ay &thorn;e more stronge &thorn;e flesche is; &thorn;e sorier maie &thorn;e soule be; [460] and ouere al &thorn;is strenke&thorn; of body; ad werldly hardinesse cause&thorn; oft mony men to perile &amp; meschaunce; [461] Eke for to pride him of his gentire; ys ful grete foly; ffor oftentime &thorn;e genterye of &thorn;e soule; and . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> eke we bene al of o fader and al of o moder; And al we be of o nature roten &amp; corrupte riche &amp; pore; [462] ffor so&thorn;e a manere a maner of gentirie is for to preyse &thorn;at apparele&thorn; mannes corage wi&thorn; vertuse of moralites &amp; make&thorn; him cristes childe; [463] For truste&thorn;e wele &thorn;at ouere what man &thorn;at sinne ha&thorn;e maystre he is verrey cherle to synne</P>
<P>[464] &para; Nowe bien &thorn;ere general &thorn;inges of gentillesse. as eschewynge of vices; or rebaudry &amp; seruage of sinne. In worde in werke &amp; contenance. [465] and vsinge vertue Curtasye &amp; clennesse &amp; to be liberal &thorn;at is to seie large be mesure; for &thorn;ilke &thorn;at passe mesure is foly &amp; synne [466] &para; Ano&thorn;er is to remembre him of bounte &thorn;at he of o&thorn;e folke ha&thorn;e receyuede; [467] Ano&thorn;ere is to be benygne of his sugettet Where fore; as sei&thorn; senec &thorn;er is no &thorn;inge more couenable to a man of hihe astate &thorn;an debonarte &amp; seite; [468] &para; And &thorn;er for . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> bees whan &thorn;ey chese hem a kinge; &thorn;ei chesen him &thorn;at ha&thorn; no &thorn;inge wi&thorn;&thorn;e to stinge; [469] 
<PB REF="00000672.tif" N="640"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="626"> Ano&thorn;ere is a man to haue a noble herte &amp; a diligent to atteigne to hihe vertuous &thorn;inges; [470<SUP>*</SUP> <I>see after</I> 474 <I>and Hengwrt and Petworth MSS</I>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [471] Certes also who &thorn;at pride&thorn; him in &thorn;e goodes of fortune he is a ful grete foole; ffor sometyme is a m&amacr;n a ful grete lorde be &thorn;e morwe; &thorn;at is a wreche &amp; a keytif ar it be nyht.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>a leaf cut out of Lansd. MS.; here supplied from</I> Reg. 18, C. 2, <I>on lf</I> 249, <I>bk.</I> ]</NOTE> [472] [And sumtyme &thorn;e . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline"><I>no gap in Reg.</I> 18, <I>C.</I> 2</NOTE> delytes of a man ben cause of &thorn;e greuous maladye &thorn;oru&yogh; whiche he deyeth [473] Certes &thorn;e Comendacion of &thorn;e peple is sum|tyme ful fals &amp; ful brutel for to triste / &thorn;is day &thorn;ey preise to morn <MILESTONE UNIT="Reg. 18, C. 2 folio" N="250a">&thorn;ey blame // [474] God woot desire to haue comendacion eke of peple hath caused deth to many a besy man // [<SUP>*</SUP>470] Now certes a man to pruyde hym in godes of grace / is eke an outragous folye // for &thorn;ilke &yogh;yftes of grace &thorn;at schulde haue turned hym to goodnesse &amp; to medecyne turnyth hym to venym &amp; to confusion as sai&thorn; seint <I>gregorie</I> / [475] Now sethins &thorn;at so is &thorn;at &yogh;e haue vnderstanden what is pruyde and whiche ben &thorn;e spices of hit &amp; w&emacr;ines pride sourdeth and springe&thorn;</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[The Remedy against Pride.]</HEAD>
<P>[476] Now schul &yogh;e vndirstonde whiche is &thorn;e remedye a&yogh;ayns pruyde &amp; &thorn;at is humylite or meknesse [477] &thorn;at is vertu &thorn;urgh whiche a man hath verray knowelache of hym self And haldeth of hym self no pris / ne deyntee as in regarde of his desertis considerynge euer his freelte / [478] Now ben &thorn;ere iij maners of humylyte / As humylyte in herte ano&thorn;er . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> in mouth &thorn;e iij is in werkes / [479] &thorn;e humylyte in herte is in 4 maners &thorn;at on is when a man holdeth hym self as nou&yogh;t worth by forn god of heuene / Ano&thorn;er is whenne he dispiseth 
<PB REF="00000673.tif" N="641"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="627"> non o&thorn;er man // [480] &thorn;e &thorn;ridde is whenne he rekke&thorn; not &thorn;orw&yogh; men holde hym nou&yogh;t worth // &thorn;e iiij is whenne he nys not sory of hys humilyacion [481] Also &thorn;e humylyte of mouth is in 4 &thorn;inges // In atemprure speche &amp; in humble of speche And whenne he by-houyth wi&thorn; his owen mouth &thorn;at he is suche as hym &thorn;enki&thorn; &thorn;at he is in his herte Ano&thorn;er is whenne he preisi&thorn; &thorn;e bounte of ano&thorn;er man / And no&thorn;ing &thorn;erof amenusi&thorn; [482] humylyte // Eke in werk is in 4 maners / &thorn;e firste is whenne he putti&thorn; o&thorn;er men biforn hym / The secunde is to chese &thorn;e loweste place ouer all / The iij is gladly to assente to good counsel / [483] The 4 is gladly to stande to reward of Souerayn or of hym &thorn;at is heier in degre Certeyn &thorn;is is a gret werke of humylyte</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Inuidia.</HEAD>
<P>[484]</P>
<P>After pruyde wol y speke of &thorn;e foule synne of Enuye whiche &thorn;at is as by &thorn;e worde of &thorn;e philozofre Sorwe of o&thorn;er mannes prosperite and aftir &thorn;e word of Seint Austyn Hit is sorwe of o&thorn;ere mennes wele And ioye of o&thorn;er mannes harme // [485] &thorn;is foule synne is platly a&yogh;ayn &thorn;e holy gost Al be hit so &thorn;at euery synne is a&yogh;ayn &thorn;e holy goste // &yogh;et for asmoche as bounte appertyneth properly to &thorn;e holy gost . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [486] &para; Now ha&thorn; malice 2 spices &thorn;at is to seye hardnesse of herte And wickednesse or elles &thorn;e flesch of a man is so blynde &thorn;at he concidere&thorn; not &thorn;at he is in synne . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> whiche is &thorn;e hardnesse of &thorn;e deuel // [487] That other <MILESTONE UNIT="Reg. 18, C. 2 folio" N="250b">spice of Enuye is whenne &thorn;at a man werreth trouthe when &thorn;at he woot &thorn;at hit is trowthe And eke when &thorn;at he werreieth &thorn;e grace of &thorn;at god hath &yogh;oue to his 
<PB REF="00000674.tif" N="642"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="628"> neighbore &amp; al &thorn;is is by Enuye [488] Certes &thorn;enne is Enuye &thorn;e worste synne &thorn;at is // ffor soothly alle o&thorn;er synnes ben somtyme a&yogh;ayn o special vertu [489] &para; But certez Enuye is a&yogh;ayns alle vertues &amp; of alle goodnesses // ffor hit is sory of alle bountes of neighebore and in &thorn;is manere hit is dyuers from alle o&thorn;er synnes // [490] ffor wel vnnethis is &thorn;er any synne &thorn;at hit ne hath som delyte in hym self safe only enuye &thorn;at euer hath in hym self anguysch and sorwe [491] &para; The spices of enuye ben &thorn;ese &thorn;er is first sorwe of o&thorn;er mennes goodnes and of her pros|perite . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> is kyndly matere of ioye &thorn;&emacr;nne is enuye a synne a&yogh;ayns kynde. // [492] The 2<SUP>e</SUP>. spice is ioye of o&thorn;er mennes harme . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [493] Of &thorn;is 2<SUP>e</SUP>. spice cometh bakbytyng . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> or detraccion hath tweyn spices as &thorn;us / Som men preisi&thorn; his neighboure by a wicked entent [494] for he make&thorn; alwey a wicked knotte at &thorn;e laste ende alwey he make&thorn; a butte at &thorn;e laste ende &para; &thorn;at is digne &amp; more blame &thorn;en wor&thorn; is alle &thorn;e plesynge // [495] The 2<SUP>e</SUP> spice is &thorn;at if a man be good &amp; dooth &amp; saith a &thorn;ing to good entent / &thorn;e bacbyter wol turne alle &thorn;e goodnesse vp so doun to his schrewed entent / [496] &para; &thorn;e .3<SUP>e</SUP>. is to amenuse &thorn;e bountee of his ney&yogh;|bore / [497] &thorn;e 4 spice of bakbytyng is &thorn;is &thorn;at if men speke goodnesse of a man wol &thorn;e bacbyter sayn parfay suche a man &yogh;et is bettere &thorn;en he in dispreisynge of hym &thorn;at men preise / [498] &thorn;e 5. spice is for to consente gladly herkne &thorn;e harme &thorn;at men speke of o&thorn;er folk &thorn;is synne is ful gret and ay encresit after &thorn;e wicked entent of &thorn;e bacbyter [499] &para; After bakbytynge come&thorn; grucchynge or mormuraunce / and somtyme hit sprynge&thorn; of inpacyence a&yogh;ayns god and somtyme a&yogh;ayns man // 
<PB REF="00000675.tif" N="643"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="629"> [500] A&yogh;ayns [god] it is whenne a man grucchi&thorn; a&yogh;ayn &thorn;e payne of helle or a&yogh;ayns pouert or losse of Catell or a&yogh;ayn reyne or tempest or elles grucche&thorn; &thorn;at schrewes han prosperite or elles &thorn;at good men han ad|uersyte [501] and alle &thorn;ese &thorn;inges schulde men suffre paciently for &thorn;ey comyn by &thorn;e ri&yogh;tful Iugement &amp; ordinaunce of god // [502] Somtyme cometh grucchynge of auarice as Iudas grucchyd a&yogh;ayns &thorn;e magdelen when sche ennoynted &thorn;e heued of oure lord ihesu Crist wi&thorn; here preciouse oignement [503] &para; &THORN;is manere of mormure is suche as when men grucchen of goodnesse &amp; &thorn;at men selue doon Or &thorn;at o&thorn;er folk doon of her owen <MILESTONE UNIT="Reg. 18, C. 2 folio" N="251a">Catell [504] Somtyme comyth murmur of pruyde as when Symon &thorn;e Pharisee grucchid a&yogh;ayns Magdaleyn when sche approched to ihesu crist and wepte at his fete for her synnes / [505] And somtyme hit sourdeth of Enuye when men discoueren a mannes harome &thorn;at was prynce or berith him an hand &thorn;ing &thorn;at is fals [506] &para; Murmur is eke ofte amange seruauntz &thorn;at grucched when her soueraignes bidden hem to doon leefful &thorn;inges / [507] And for asmoche as &thorn;ey dar no&yogh;t openly wi&thorn;saye &thorn;e commaundementes of her soueraigne &yogh;et woln &thorn;ey saye harm &amp; grucche &amp; murmur pryuyly for verrey dispyte // [508] wiche wordes men clepe &thorn;e deuels pater noster &thorn;ou&yogh; so be &thorn;at &thorn;e deuell had neuer pater noster but &thorn;at folke &yogh;euen hit suche a name // [509] Somtyme hit come&thorn; of yre or of pryue hate &thorn;at norischeth rancour in herte / as afterward I schal declare / [510] &thorn;enne come&thorn; eke bitternesse of herte &thorn;urgh wiche bitternesse euery good dede of his neighbore seme&thorn; to hym bitter and vnsauery / [511] Then come&thorn; discorde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Reg. 18, C 2, <I>extract, leaf</I> 251, <I>ends</I>]</NOTE>] <MILESTONE N="240a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Lansdowne MS, 851, leaf 240 ]</NOTE>&thorn;at vnbynde&thorn; almaner of frindeschepe; &thorn;at comme&thorn; scorenynge of . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> his neyhe|bore al do he neuer so wele; [512] &thorn;an comme&thorn; accuseinge; as whan a man seke&thorn; occasione to anoyen his 
<PB REF="00000676.tif" N="644"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="630"> neyhboure; Whiche &thorn;at is like &thorn;e crafte of &thorn;e deuel; &thorn;at wayte&thorn; bo&thorn; day &amp; nyht to accusen vs all; [513] &para; &thorn;an comme&thorn; malignite &thorn;orwhe whiche a ma anoye&thorn; his neihbour priuely. if he maie; [514] And if he nouht ne may algates his wikked wil ne schal not wante; as for to birne his house priuely or openly; or slene his bestees; &amp; semblable &thorn;inges;</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[The Remedy against Envy.]</HEAD>
<P>[515] &para; Nowe wil .I. speke of &thorn;e remedye a&yogh;eines &thorn;is foule sinne of Envie; ffirst is &thorn;e loue of god principal &amp; loueinge of him selfe &amp; of his neyhbour. ffor so&thorn;ely &thorn;e tone maie not be withouten &thorn;e to&thorn;ere. [516] And truste&thorn; wele &thorn;at in &thorn;e name of &thorn;i neyhboure &thorn;ou schalt vnderstande &thorn;e name of &thorn;i bro&thorn;ere ffor certes al we haue o fader ffleschely &amp; o moder; &thorn;at is to seye Adam &amp; Eue; &amp; eke o fader spirituele &thorn;at is to seie god of heuen; [517] &thorn;ine neyhbour ert &thorn;ou holden for to loue &amp; wilne him al godenesse; And &thorn;erefor sei&thorn;e god loue &thorn;ine neyhbour as &thorn;i self; &thorn;at is to saluacion bo&thorn; to lyue &amp; to soule; [518] And more ouere &thorn;ou schal loue him in worde &amp; benygne ammonesscheynge; And chastiseinge; And comfort him in his anoyes; And praye for him wi&thorn; al &thorn;ine herte; [519] And in dede &thorn;ou schalt loue him in suche wise &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalte done to him in charite; As &thorn;ou woldest were done to &thorn;ine owen persone; [520] And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou schalte note done him no damage in wykked worde ne harme in his body ne in his catel ne in his soule be entiseinge of wykked ensample. [521] &thorn;ou schalt nouht desire his wyf ne none of his &thorn;inges; vnderstande eke; &thorn;at in &thorn;e name of &thorn;i neyhbour is com|prehended his enmye [522] &para; Certes a man schal loue his enemye for &thorn;e commandementz of god; And so&thorn;ely &thorn;i frende schalt &thorn;ou loue in god; [523] I. sei &thorn;in ennemye schalt &thorn;ou loue for goddes saake by his commande|ment 
<PB REF="00000677.tif" N="645"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="631">; ffor if it were reson. &thorn;at man scholde hate his ennemye; for so&thorn; god wol not receyue vs to his loue &thorn;at bien his enemyes [524] a&yogh;eines &thorn;re manere of of wronges; &thorn;at his Ennemy do&thorn;e to him; He schal do &thorn;re &thorn;inges; As &thorn;us; [525] A&yogh;eines hate &amp; rankour of hert; He schal loue him in Herte a&yogh;eine chideinge &amp; wikkede wordes. he schal praie for his Ennemy. &para; A&yogh;eines &thorn;e wikked dede of his ennemye he schal done him bounte; [526] &para; For Crist sei&thorn;e; loue&thorn; &yogh;oure enemys And preie&thorn; for hem &thorn;at speke&thorn; &yogh;owe harme /./ And eke for hem &thorn;at &yogh;owe chasen; &amp; pursewen; And do&thorn;e bounte to hem &thorn;at &yogh;owe haten; =Lo &thorn;us commande&thorn; vs oure lorde ihesu criste to do to oure enemyes; [527] For so&thorn;ely nature driues vs to loue oure frendes. And parfey oure enemys haue more nede to loue &thorn;an oure frendes; And &thorn;ei &thorn;at mor nede had; to hem schal men do goode|nesse [528] &para; And certes in &thorn;ilke dede haue &thorn;e remem|brance of &thorn;e loue of ihesu criste &thorn;at deyed for his ennemys; [529] &para; And in almuche &thorn;at &thorn;ilke loue is &thorn;e more to performe; So muche is more &thorn;e gre merit; And &thorn;erefore &thorn;e loueinge of oure Enmi; Ha&thorn; confounde &thorn;e venime of &thorn;e deuyll; [530] ffor rih as &thorn;e deuel is dis<MILESTONE N="240b" UNIT="folio">comfite be humilite Riht so is he woundede to to &thorn;e de&thorn;e be &thorn;e loue of oure Enmye; [531] Certes &thorn;an is loue &thorn;e medecyne &thorn;at cache&thorn; oute &thorn;e venym of Envye Fro mannes herte [532] &para; &thorn;e spices of &thorn;is pas scholne bue more largely in here chapetles folowynge;</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>de Ira [<I>from the margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[533]</P>
<P>After Ennevie wil .I. declare &thorn;e sinne of Ire; For so&thorn;ely who &thorn;at ha&thorn;e envy vpon his neyhbour; anone comunly he wil finde him matier of wre&thorn;&thorn;e in worde or in dede a&yogh;eines him to whome he ha&thorn; envie; [534] and as wele come&thorn; Ire of pride 
<PB REF="00000678.tif" N="646"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="632"> as of envie; for so&thorn;ely he &thorn;at is proude or envious; is lyhtly wro&thorn;e</P>
<P>[535] &para; &THORN;is sinne of ire after &thorn;e discriueinge of seinte Austine; Is wikked will to bue avengede be worde or by dede; [536] &para; Ire after &thorn;e Philosofre. Is &thorn;e feruen<SUP>t</SUP> blode of man. ywhiked in his hert &thorn;orwhe whiche he wil harme to him &thorn;at he hate&thorn;; [537] &para; For certes &thorn;e hert of man be enchaufeinge &amp; moueinge of his blode waxe&thorn; so trouble &thorn;at he is out of al Iuggement of Reson; [538] Bot &yogh;e schal vnderstonde &thorn;at Ire is in two maners; &thorn;at on of hem is goode &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;ere is wikked [539] &para; The good Ire is be Ielowsy of goodnesse &thorn;oruhe &thorn;e whiche a man is wro&thorn;e with wikkednesse &amp; a&yogh;eines wykkednesse; And &thorn;ere fore sei&thorn;e &thorn;e wise man; &thorn;at ire is bett &thorn;an pleye; [540] &thorn;is ire is wi&thorn; debonarte; Ant it is wro&thorn;e wi&thorn; outen bitternesse nouht wro&thorn;e a&yogh;eines &thorn;e man bot wro&thorn;e wi&thorn; &thorn;e mysdede of &thorn;e man as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e pro|phet dauid; Irascimini &amp; nolite peccare [541] &para; Nowe vnderstonde &thorn;at wykked yre is in tuo maners; &thorn;at is to seine sodeine Ire wi&thorn;e outen avisement &amp; consentinge of his reson; [542] &thorn;e meneynge &amp; &thorn;e sense of &thorn;is; is &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> reson of a man con|sente&thorn; nouht to &thorn;ilke sodeine Ire; &amp; &thorn;an is venial; [543] &para; Ano&thorn;ere Iire is ful wikked &thorn;at come&thorn; of velany of hert avised &amp; cast before wi&thorn; wikked will to do vengeance; And &thorn;erto his Resoun consente&thorn;; And so so&thorn;ely &thorn;is is dedely synne; [544] This Ire is so dis|plesant to god &thorn;at it trouble&thorn; his hous &amp; chase&thorn;e &thorn;e holy gost oute of mannes soule; . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [545] &amp; put in him &thorn;e lik|nes of &thorn;e deuel; &amp; be-nymme&thorn; &thorn;e man fro god &thorn;at is rihtful lorde [546] &para; This ire is a ful grete plesance to &thorn;e deuel; ffor it is &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> deuel forneys &thorn;at is ychaufed with &thorn;e fire of hell [547] ffor certes 
<PB REF="00000679.tif" N="647"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="633"> as fuyre is more myhtye to distroye er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges &thorn;an ano&thorn;ere Element; Riht so is ire myhty to destreye al sprituel &thorn;inges; [548] Loke howe &thorn;at fuyre of smale gledys &thorn;at bien almost dede vnder asshen wyll qwyken a&yogh;eine whan &thorn;ei whan &thorn;ei bue touched with brimstone; Riht so Ire will qwykene a&yogh;eine whan it is touched be pruide &thorn;at is couerde in mannes herte; [549] ffor certes fire may not comme out of no&thorn;inge bot if were first in &thorn;e same &thorn;inge naturelly; As fire is drawen oute of flintes wi&thorn; stele; [550] And riht so as pride is often matire of Ire; Riht so is Ran|cour norische &amp; kepere of &thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e in &thorn;e mannes hert; [551] &para; Ther is a manere tree as sei&thorn; seint Isodere; &thorn;at wh&amacr;n men make&thorn; fire of &thorn;ilke tre And couere&thorn; &thorn;e coles of it wi&thorn; asshen; So&thorn;ely &thorn;e fire of it wil lasten al a &yogh;ere or more; [552] And riht so fare&thorn; it of Rankoure; Whan he is ones conseyued in &thorn;e hert of sinne man; Certeyne it wil last paraduenture <MILESTONE N="241a" UNIT="folio">Fr&omacr;me one Hester day vnto ano&thorn;ere esterdaie or more; [553] Bot certes &thorn;ilke man is fer fro &thorn;e mercy of god al &thorn;ilke while</P>
<P>[554] in &thorn;is forsaide deuels forneys where forgen .thre schrewes; Pride &thorn;at al blow&thorn;e &amp; encrese&thorn; &thorn;e fire be chideinge &amp; wykked wordes; [555] &thorn;an stande&thorn; envye &amp; holde&thorn; &thorn;e hote yren vpon &thorn;e hertes of man wi&thorn; a peire of longe tonges of longe Rankoure; [556] And &thorn;an stant &thorn;e sinne of contumely or strif &amp; chest; &amp; batere&thorn; &amp; forge&thorn; be veleynes reproueynges; [557] &para; Certes &thorn;is cursed sinne anoye&thorn; bo&thorn;e &thorn;e man him self &amp; eke to his neyhbour; For so&thorn;ely almost al &thorn;e harme &thorn;at any man do&thorn;e to his neyhbour; comme&thorn; of wra&thorn;; [558]. For certes outrageus wra&thorn;&thorn;e do&thorn;e al &thorn;at euer &thorn;e deuel him commande&thorn;; for he ne spare&thorn; ney&thorn;ere crist ne his swete moder; [559] And in his out|rageous Anger &amp; Ire Alas Alas ful mony one fele&thorn; in &thorn;at time ful wikkedly 
<PB REF="00000680.tif" N="648"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="634"> &para; Bo&thorn;e of criste &amp; of al his halowes; [560] is nouht &thorn;is acursed vice . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> his debonaire lif espirituel &thorn;at schold kepen his soule; [561] &para; Certes it be-nymme&thorn; eke goddes dieu lord schippe; &amp; &thorn;at is mannes soule &amp; &thorn;e loue of his neybores; &para; It striue&thorn; eke al day a&yogh;eines trow&thorn;e; it reue&thorn; him to quiete of his herte; And subuerte&thorn; his soule;</P>
<P>[562] &para; Of. Ire comme&thorn; &thorn;es stinkinge engenderoures; ffirst hate &thorn;at is olde wra&thorn;&thorn;e; discorde; &thorn;oruhe whiche a man for-sake&thorn; his olde frende &thorn;at he ha&thorn; loued ful longe; [563] And &thorn;an comme&thorn; werre; And euery maner of wronge &thorn;at man do&thorn; to his neyhebour in body or in Catel; [564] Of &thorn;is cursed sinne of Ire comme&thorn; manslawhter; And vnder stonde&thorn; wele &thorn;at Omycide &thorn;at is man slauhter is in diuerse wyse; Somme manere of Omicide is spirituel; &amp; somme is bodely; [565] Spirituel manneslauhtere is in vj &thorn;inges; ffirst be hate as sei&thorn;e seinte Iohn; &thorn;at he &thorn;at hate&thorn; his bro&thorn;er his Omycide; [566] whiche is be bakbiteinge; Of whiche bakbyters sei&thorn; Salomon; &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue tuo swerdes wi&thorn;&thorn;e whiche &thorn;ei slene here neyhebours &para; For so&thorn;ely also wikked it is to be-nyme hime his goode name as his lif; [567] &para; Homicide is eke in &yogh;eueinge of wikked counsel by fraude as for to &yogh;eue counsel to areyse wrongefully custumes &amp; talliages [568] of whiche sei&thorn;e Salomon; Lyon Roreinge; Bere hungrye bien like to crewel lordschippes in wi&thorn;-haldinge or abrugeinge of &thorn;e schipe or &thorn;e hire of wages; . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> Of &thorn;e almos of &thorn;e pouer folke; [569] ffor whiche &thorn;e wiseman sei&thorn;e; Fede&thorn; him &thorn;at almost deye&thorn; for hunger; ffor so&thorn;ely bot &thorn;ou feede him &thorn;ou sleste him; And all &thorn;es bien dedely sinnes; [570] Bodely manslauhter is whan slest him with &thorn;i tunge &para; In o&thorn;ere manere as whan &thorn;ou commandest to sle a man or elles &yogh;euest him counsell to slene a 
<PB REF="00000681.tif" N="649"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="635"> m&amacr;n. [571] &para; Manslauhtere in dede is in .iiij. maners; &thorn;at on is be lawe; Riht as a Iustice dampne&thorn; him &thorn;at is coupable to &thorn;e de&thorn;e; bot latte &thorn;e Iustice be warre &thorn;at he do it rihtfully; And &thorn;at he do it not for delite to spil blode bot for kepeinge of rihtwis|nesse; [572] &para; Ano&thorn;ere homycide is done for necessite; as whan a manne sle&thorn;e ano&thorn;ere in his defendant; And &thorn;at he ne maye none o&thorn;ere wise eschape fromme his owen de&thorn;; [573] Bot certeynly if he maie eskape with|outen slauhter of his aduersarye &amp; sle&thorn; him he do&thorn; sinne; &amp; he schal bere penance as for dedely sinne; [574] Eke if a man be cas or aduenture schete an arwe or cast a stone; with &thorn;e whiche he sle&thorn;e a man it is homycide. [575] Eke if a womman be necligence ouerely&thorn;e hir childe in slepeinge. <MILESTONE N="241b" UNIT="folio">itt is homicide &amp; dedely sinne; [576] Eke whan a man distrouble&thorn; &thorn;e con|cepcion of a childe or make&thorn; a womman barayne be drinkeinge of venemous herbes &thorn;oruhe whiche sche may nouht conceyue; or sle&thorn;e a childe be drinkes; or elles putte&thorn; inne certein material &thorn;inges in hire secre places to sle &thorn;e childe [577] or elles do&thorn;e vnkinde sinne be whiche man or womman schedi&thorn; his nature in manere or in place &thorn;ere as a childe maie nouht be con|ceyued; or elles if a womman ha&thorn;e conceyued &amp; hurte&thorn; her self &amp; slee&thorn;e here childe; &yogh;it is it homycide; [578] Whatte seye we eke of wemmen &thorn;at mordren her childern; for drede of werldly schame certes an hor|rible homycide; [579] Homycide is eke if a manne aproche&thorn; to a womman be desire be desire of lychery; be &thorn;e whiche &thorn;e child is perisched; or elles smyte&thorn; a womman wityngly &thorn;oruhe whiche sche lese&thorn; his childe; Al &thorn;es ben homy|cides; and dedely orrible sinnes; [580] &para; &yogh;utte comme&thorn; &thorn;ere of Ire mony mo sinnes; as wele in worde as in &thorn;ouhte; and in dede; as he &thorn;at arette&thorn; vppon god or blame&thorn; god of &thorn;inge of whiche he is him selfe gilty; or displese&thorn; god &amp; al his halowes as done &thorn;es cursed hasadours 
<PB REF="00000682.tif" N="650"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="636"> in diuerse contres; [581] &thorn;is cursed sinne done &thorn;ei; when &thorn;ei felen in her hert ful wikkedly of god &amp; his halowes. [582] &para; Also whan &thorn;ei treten vnreuerently &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sacrament of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> auter &para; &thorn;ilke sinnes bien. so grete &thorn;at vnne&thorn; &thorn;ei maie be relest; bot &thorn;at &thorn;e mercye of god passe&thorn; his werkes it is so grete &amp; so benigne; [583] &para; &thorn;an come&thorn; of Ire attrye angur; wh&amacr;n a man scharpely amonesched in his schrift for to lete sinne; [584] &thorn;an wil he hangry And ansewere hokerlye &amp; angerly; or defende &amp; excuse his sinne be vnstedfastnesse of his flesche; or elles he dide it for to holde compaignye with wyse felawes; Or elles he sei&thorn;e &thorn;e fende entised hime; [585] or elles he dide it for his &yogh;ou&thorn;e or elles his complexion is so corageous &thorn;at he mai nouht for bere; or elles it is his destanye as he sei&thorn;e vnto a certeine age; or elles; he sei&thorn;e it comme&thorn; him of gentilles of his auncestres and semblable &thorn;inges [586] &para; All &thorn;ese maner of folke so wrappen hem in her sinnes &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne wol nouht deliueren he self; ffore so&thorn;ely no &thorn;at excuse&thorn; him wilfully; of his sinne; may not be deliuered of his sinne til &thorn;at he mekely be-knowe&thorn; his sinne. [587] &para; After &thorn;at comme&thorn; swereinge &thorn;at is expresse a&yogh;eines &thorn;e commandement of god And &thorn;is befalle&thorn; oft of anger &amp; of ire; [588] God sei&thorn;e; &thorn;ou schalt nouht take &thorn;e name of &thorn;ine lorde god in veyne ne in ydel. Also oure lorde ihesu sei&thorn; be &thorn;e worde of seint Mathewe . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [589] Ne wil &yogh;e nouht swere in al manere Ney&thorn;ere be heuen for it is goddes throne. Ne by er&thorn;e for it is &thorn;e bynche of his feete Ne by iherusalem; For it is &thorn;e Cite of a grete kynge; ne be &thorn;in hede; for &thorn;ou maist nou&yogh;t maake an her white ne blake; [590] Bot sei&thorn;e be &yogh;oure &yogh;e. &yogh;e. &amp; nay. naye; And what &thorn;at is more it is yuel. &thorn;us sei&thorn;e criste; [591] ffor cristes saake ne swere&thorn; nouht so sinfully in dismembringe of criste by soule. 
<PB REF="00000683.tif" N="651"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="637"> hert. bones. &amp; body; ffor certes it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cursed Iewes dismembred him no&yogh;t ynowhe; . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> bot &yogh;e dismembren him more; [592] &para; And if so be &thorn;at &thorn;e lawe com|pell &yogh;ow to swere; &thorn;an rewle&thorn; &yogh;owe after &thorn;e lawe of god in &yogh;oure swereinge as sei&thorn;e Ieremye in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> iiij. capitle. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &thorn;ou schalt kepe &thorn;re condicions; &thorn;ou schalt <MILESTONE N="242a" UNIT="folio">swere in trou&thorn;e in dome &amp; in rihtwisnesse; [593] &thorn;is to seine &thorn;ou schalt swere so&thorn;e; for euery leseinge is a&yogh;eines crist. For crist is verray trou&thorn;e; And &thorn;enke wele &thorn;is &thorn;at euery grete swerer nouht compelled lawfully to swere &thorn;e wounde schal not departe fro his house whiles he vse&thorn; suche vnleful swereinge; [594] &para; &thorn;ou schalt swere eke in dome whan &thorn;ou art constreynede by &thorn;i domes|man to wittnese &thorn;e trew&thorn;e; [595] Eke &thorn;ou schalt nouht swere for envye ne for fauor ne for mede bot for rihtwisnesse for declareinge to worschipe of god; &amp; to helpeinge of &thorn;ine euen cristen; [596] And &thorn;erfore eueryman &thorn;at take&thorn; goddes name in ydel or falsely swere&thorn; wi&thorn; his mou&thorn;e or elles take&thorn; on him &thorn;e name of criste to be called a cristenman; And leue&thorn; a&yogh;eines cristes leueynge &amp; his techeinge al &thorn;ei take goddes name in ydel [597] &para; Loke eke whate sei&thorn;e seint Peter Actuum .iiij<SUP>to</SUP>. Non est aliud nomen sub celo; &thorn;ere is non o&thorn;ere name sei&thorn; seint Peter vnder heuen; y&yogh;ouen to men in whiche &thorn;ei muste be saued; &thorn;at is to seye bot in &thorn;e name of ihesu criste [598] &para; Tak kepe eke how &thorn;at &thorn;e precious name of ihesu criste as sei&thorn; seinte Poule ad Philipenses; xij<SUP>o</SUP>. c<SUP>o</SUP>. In nomine ihesu; &amp;c. &thorn;at in &thorn;e name of ihesu euery kne of heuenly creatures or er&thorn;ely or of hell scholde bowen; ffor it is so hihe &amp; so worschipfull &thorn;at &thorn;e cursed fende in hell scholde tremblen to here it nemened;// [599] &thorn;an seme&thorn; it &thorn;at men &thorn;at sweren so orrible by his 
<PB REF="00000684.tif" N="652"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="638"> blissed name &thorn;at &thorn;ei dispisen it more boldely; &thorn;an diden &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cursed Iewes; or elles &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at tremble&thorn; whan he here&thorn; his name;</P>
<P>[600] Now certez se&thorn;en &thorn;at swereynge bot it be do al lawfully; is so holy defendede meche wers is forswereinge falsly; And &yogh;utte nedeles</P>
<P>[601] what seie we eke of heme . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in MS.</NOTE> in swereinge &amp; holde it a genterye or a manly dede to swere grete o&thorn;es; &para; and of hem &thorn;at of verrei vsage. ne cesen nouht to swere grete o&thorn;es; al &thorn;e cause nouht wor&thorn;e a strawe; Certes &thorn;is is an orrible sinne; [602] Swerynge sodanly wi&thorn; oute avisement is eke a sinne; [603] &para; Nowe late vs go to &thorn;ilke orrible &amp; cursed sweringe of adiuracione &amp; coniuracione as done &thorn;ese fals en|chauntours &amp; nygromansoures; In basins ful of water or in a briht swerde in a serkle; or in a fire or in a scholder|bone of a schepe; [604] I. kanne not seine bot &thorn;at &thorn;ei done corsedly &amp; dampnably a&yogh;eines criste &amp; al &thorn;e fei&thorn;e of holy chir chirche;=</P>
<P>[605] what seye we be hem &thorn;at leuen on deueneyles; as be flyht or be noyse of birdes or of bestes or of sorte by ygromansy; be dremes be chirkeinge of dores; be gnoweinge of rattes or crakkeynge of houses &amp; suche maner of wrichednesse; [606] Certes al &thorn;is &thorn;inge is defended be god &amp; holy cherche; ffor whiche &thorn;ei bien acursed till &thorn;ei come to amendement &thorn;at on suche ful&thorn;e setten hire beleue; [607] Charmes for woundes; &amp; Maledies of men or of bestes if &thorn;ei taken any effecte it may be peraduenture &thorn;at god suffure&thorn; it &thorn;at folke scholde &yogh;iue &thorn;e more fai&thorn;e; and Reuerence to his name;</P>
<P>[608] &para; Nowe wil .I. speke of leseinges whiche gener|aly is fals signifiant; of wordes en entent to deceyuen his heuen cristen; [609] Sum leseynge is of whiche &thorn;ere comme&thorn; none auauntage to no wight; And some lese|inge torne&thorn; to &thorn;ese or &thorn;e profite of a man 
<PB REF="00000685.tif" N="653"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="639"> &amp; to damage of ano&thorn;ere manere; [610] &para; Ano&thorn;ere leseinge for to . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> <MILESTONE N="242b" UNIT="folio">Ano&thorn;ere leseinge comme&thorn; of delite for to lye. In whiche delite &thorn;ei wil forgen a longe tale &amp; peynte it wi&thorn; al circumstance; wher al &thorn;e grounde of &thorn;e tale is fals; [611] Somme leseinge comme&thorn; for he wil susteyine his worde; And sum leseynge cometh of rechelnesse; wi&thorn; outen avisement; &amp; sem|blable &thorn;inges</P>
<P>[612] &para; Lat vs now touche &thorn;e vice of flaterye whiche ne come&thorn; nouht gladly bot for drede or for Couetise; [613] Flatery is generally wrongeful preyseinge &para; Flatrer|es bene &thorn;e deueles norices &thorn;at norischen his childerne wi&thorn; melke of losengrye; [614] ffor so&thorn;e sei&thorn;e Salomon; &thorn;at flatery is wers &thorn;an detraccione; ffor sum tyme de|traccion make&thorn; an haunten m&amacr;n &thorn;e more humble for he drede&thorn; detraccion; &para; Bot certes flatery make&thorn; a man to enhante his herte and his countenance; [615] fflatery bien &thorn;e deuels enchauntour; ffor &thorn;ei maake a man to wene of him self to be like &thorn;at he nys nouht lyke; [616] &thorn;ei bien like to Iudas &thorn;at be-trayed . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> a man to sel him to his ennemye &thorn;at is to &thorn;e deuel [617] &para; Flatereres bien &thorn;e deuel chapelleines &thorn;at singen euer placebo; [618] I. reken flatery in &thorn;e vices of ire; &para; For oft time if a man be wro&thorn;e wi&thorn; ano&thorn;ere; &thorn;en wil he flatere sum wyght to susteine him in his qwerell;</P>
<P>[619] Speke we nowe of suche cursinge as comme&thorn; oute of Irrous herte; Malyson may be seide generallye; euery man power of harme such cursynge bereue&thorn; man fro &thorn;e Regne of god; As sei&thorn;e seint Poule; [620] &thorn;at suche cursinge wrongefully retourne&thorn; oft tyme a&yogh;eine to him &thorn;at curse&thorn;e As a birde retourne&thorn; a&yogh;eine vn to his owen neste; [621] And ouere al&thorn;inge men ouhte eschewe to curse her childern &amp; &yogh;eue to &thorn;e deuel here engendorere as fer for&thorn;e as in hem is &para; Certes it is a grete perile &amp; a grete sinne;
<PB REF="00000686.tif" N="654"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="640"></P>
<P>[622] &para; Lete vs &thorn;an speke of chideinge; And reproche whiche biene grete woundes in mannes herte; for &thorn;e vnsewe &thorn;e semes of frendschippe in mannes herte; [623] ffor certes vnne&thorn;es may a man bue pleynely accorded wi&thorn; him &thorn;at ha&thorn; him openly revilede &amp; reproued &amp; disclaunderde; &thorn;is is a ful grysly sinne; as criste sei&thorn;e in &thorn;e gospell; [624] And take kepe nowe &thorn;at he &thorn;at reproue&thorn; his neyhboure; oy&thorn;ere he reproue&thorn; him be som harme of peyne &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e on his body; as mesel croked harlotte or be somme sinne &thorn;at he do&thorn;e; [625] Nowe if he reproue him be harme of peyne &thorn;an torne&thorn; &thorn;e profete to ihesu criste; for peyne is sent be &thorn;e rihtwise sonde of gode; &amp; be his suffrance; be it Meselrye or mayme; ore maladye; [626] And if he reproue him vncharitablye of synne; As &thorn;ou holoure; &thorn;ou dronken lewde harlote; and so for&thorn;; &thorn;an appartene&thorn; &thorn;at to &thorn;e rejoyseinge of &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at euer ha&thorn;e ioye &thorn;at men doon synne; [627] And certes chidynge may not come bot of velens herte; ffor after &thorn;e abundance of &thorn;e herte speke&thorn;e &thorn;e mou&thorn;e ful oft; [628] And &yogh;e scholne vnderstonde . &thorn;at loke be any . waye whan any man schal chaste ano&thorn;ere ano&thorn;er &thorn;at he be war fro chideinge or reproueinge &para; ffor trewly bot he be war he may ful lyhtly queken &thorn;e fuyre of anger; and of wra&thorn;&thorn;e; whiche &thorn;at he schold qwenche &amp; peraduentur sle&thorn;e him &thorn;at he myht chastise wi&thorn; benyng|nite; [629] ffor as sei&thorn;e Salomon the amyable tonge; is &thorn;e tree of lif; &thorn;at is to seyne of lif espirituele and a dislaue tunge sle&thorn;e &thorn;e spirites of him &thorn;at repreue&thorn; <MILESTONE N="243a" UNIT="folio">And eke of him &thorn;at is repreued; [630] Lo what seinte Austine sei&thorn;e; &thorn;ere is no&thorn;inge ylyke &thorn;e deueles childe as he &thorn;at oft chide&thorn;; Seint poule sei&thorn;e eke .I. seruant of god behoue&thorn; nouht to chide [631] &para; And howe &thorn;at chideinge is a veleyns &thorn;inge betwex al maner folke &yogh;it is it certes most vnkouenable be-twyx a man &amp; his wyf; for &thorn;ere is neuer reste; 
<PB REF="00000687.tif" N="655"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="641"> And &thorn;erfor sei&thorn;e salomon. An house &thorn;at is vnkouerde in reyne &amp; dropinge; &amp; a chideinge wif. bene ylike; [632] a man &thorn;at is in in a dropinge hous in many place; &thorn;eyhe he schewe &thorn;e dropinge in o place it droppe&thorn; in ano&thorn;ere in a no&thorn;ere. So fare&thorn;e it be a chideinge wyf; bot sche chide him in o place sche wil chide him in ano&thorn;ere; [633] And &thorn;erfor is better a morsel of brede with Ioye; &thorn;an an hous ful of delices wi&thorn; chideinge sei&thorn;e Salomon; [634] Poule sei&thorn;e O &yogh;e wemmen be &yogh;e soubiettes to &yogh;oure husbondes as be-houe&thorn;e in god; And &yogh;e men louen &yogh;oure wyves Ad Clonicenses .iij<SUP>o</SUP>.</P>
<P>[635] &para; Afterward speke we of scorenynge whiche is a wikked sinne; And namely whan he scorene&thorn; a man for his goode werkes; [636] ffor certe suche scorners faren y-like &thorn;e foule tode &thorn;at mai not endure to smel &thorn;e swete sauour of &thorn;e vine when it floure&thorn;; &para; [637] &thorn;es scorners bien partinge felawes with &thorn;e deuel; = for &thorn;ei haue Ioy whan &thorn;e deuel wynne&thorn;; &amp; sorwe whan he lese&thorn;; [638] &thorn;ei bene aduersaries to oure lorde ihesu criste; ffor &thorn;ei haten &thorn;at he loue&thorn;e &thorn;at is to sei. sauacion of soule;</P>
<P>[639] &para; Speke we nowe of wikked counsel &para; For he &thorn;at wikked counsel &yogh;eue&thorn; is a traitour; for he distroy&thorn;e him &thorn;at truste&thorn; in him. vt achitofell de Abson&emacr;. But na&thorn;eles &yogh;it is it wikked counsel firste a&yogh;eines him selfe [640] for as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e wiseman; Euery fals leueynge ha&thorn;e &thorn;is properte in him selfe &thorn;at he &thorn;at wil anoye ano&thorn;ere man first anoye&thorn; him self; [641] And men schal vndestande &thorn;at man schal nouht take his counsel of fals folke; ne of to angry folke or greuous folke; ne of folke &thorn;at a loue&thorn; specialy to muche here owen profite; ne to muche werldly folke namely in conseleinge of soules;</P>
<P>[642] &para; Nowe comme&thorn; &thorn;e sinne of hem &thorn;at maken discorde amonges folke whiche is a sinne &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000688.tif" N="656"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="642"> criste hate&thorn; vtterly; And no wonder is; ffor he deyed for to maake concorde; [643] &amp; mor schame done &thorn;ei to criste; &thorn;an dide &thorn;ei &thorn;at him crucified; ffor god loue&thorn; better &thorn;at frenchepe be amonges folke; &thorn;an he dide his owen body; whiche he &yogh;af for vnitees; &thorn;erfore beene &thorn;ei likned to &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at euere is aboute to make discorde</P>
<P>[644] &para; Nowe comme&thorn; &thorn;e sinne of dowble tonge suche as speken faire befor folke; &amp; wikkede be-hynde or elles &thorn;ei maken sembland as &thorn;ouhe &thorn;e spake of goode entencion or elles in game &amp; pleye; And &yogh;it &thorn;e speke of wikked entente;</P>
<P>[645] &para; Now comme&thorn; be-wreynge of counseile &thorn;orwhe whiche a man is defamed; vne&thorn;es maye he restore&thorn; &thorn;e damages;</P>
<P>[646] Nowe comme&thorn; manas &thorn;at is an hopen foly; ffor he &thorn;at manasse&thorn;; he &thorn;rete&thorn; more &thorn;an he maie do ful oft time;</P>
<P>[647] Nowe come&thorn; ydel wordes &thorn;at is wi&thorn;eouten profite of him &thorn;at speke&thorn; &thorn;o wordes &amp; eke of him &thorn;at herkene&thorn; &thorn;e wordes; Or elle ydel wordes bien &thorn;o &thorn;at bien nedelesse or wi&thorn;outen entent of naturely profite; [648] And al be it &thorn;at Idel wordes som|time bien venial sinne &yogh;it schold men doute hem; ffor we scholne &yogh;eue reken<MILESTONE N="243b" UNIT="folio">ynge of hem be-for god;</P>
<P>[649] Nowe comme&thorn; Iangelynge &thorn;at may no&yogh;t come wi&thorn;e|owten sinne as sei&thorn;e Salomon; It is a signe of aperte folye; [650] And &thorn;erefore; a philosophre saide; Whan a man asked hyme howe men schold plese &thorn;e peple; And he answarde; Do goode werkes; &amp; speke fewe Iangelinges;</P>
<P>[651] After &thorn;is come&thorn; &thorn;e sinne of Iapes &thorn;at bien deuels apes ffor &thorn;ei maken folke to lawhe att her Iaperye as folkes done att &thorn;e gaudes of an hape; Suche Iapes defende&thorn; seint Poule; [652] Loke howe &thorn;at vertuouse wordes &amp; holy; conuerten hem 
<PB REF="00000689.tif" N="657"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="643"> &thorn;at traueyle in &thorn;e seruice of crist; Riht so conuerten &thorn;e vilens worde &amp; &thorn;e knakkes of &thorn;e Iapes hem &thorn;at traveylen in &thorn;e seruise of &thorn;e deuel. [653] &para; &thorn;es bien &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sinne &thorn;at comme&thorn; of &thorn;e tonge; &thorn;at comme&thorn; of ire &amp; of o&thorn;ere sinnes;</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[The Remedies against Ire]</HEAD>
<P>[654] The remedes a&yogh;eines Ire is a vertue &thorn;at men clepen mansuetude &thorn;at is debonarte; And eke ano&thorn;ere vertue &thorn;at men clepen pacience; . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></P>
<P>[655] Debanarte wi&thorn; - drawe&thorn; &amp; refreyne&thorn; &thorn;e stringes &amp; &thorn;e meueynges of mannes corage in his herte; in suche maner &thorn;at &thorn;ei scipe nou&yogh;t oute be anger ne be ire; [656] Suffrance suffre&thorn; swetly al &thorn;e anoyance &thorn;at &amp; &thorn;e wronges &thorn;at men done to a man outewarde; [657] &para; Seint Ierom . sei&thorn; &thorn;us of debonarte; &thorn;at it do&thorn;e none harme to no wight ne sei&thorn;e for none harme &thorn;at men him done ne seine; He ne eschaunge&thorn; nou&yogh;t a&yogh;eines his reson; [658] &para; This vertue comme&thorn; some time of Nature; ffor as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e Philosopher; A man is a whike &thorn;inge be nature; debonaire &amp; tretable be goodnesse; Bot whan debonairete is enformed of grace. it is &thorn;e more wor&thorn;e; //</P>
<P>[659] Pacience &thorn;at is ano&thorn;ere remedy a&yogh;eynes ire; it is a vertue &thorn;at suffre&thorn; swetely euery mannes goodnesse; &amp; is no&yogh;t wro&thorn;e for none harme &thorn;at is done vnto her. // [660] The Philosopher sei&thorn;e &thorn;at paciens is &thorn;ilke vertve &thorn;at suffer&thorn; debonarly al &thorn;e outrage of aduersitee &amp; euery wikked worde; [661] &thorn;is vertue make&thorn; a man ylyke to god; And make&thorn; him his owen der childe as sei&thorn;e crist; This vertue discomfor&thorn; &thorn;ine Ennemye; and &thorn;erfore sei&thorn;e &thorn;e wise man. If &thorn;ou wilte venqwys &thorn;in enemye. lerene to suffer; [662] And &thorn;ou schalt vnder-stande &thorn;at a man suffer&thorn;; iiij. manere 
<PB REF="00000690.tif" N="658"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="644"> of greuance in otward &thorn;inges; A&yogh;eines whiche foure he mot haue foure maner of pacience</P>
<P>[663] &thorn;e firste greuance is of wyked wordes; &thorn;ilke gre|uance suffred oure lorde ihesu crist wi&thorn; outen gruccheinge ful paciently; Whan &thorn;e Iewes dispised him &amp; reproued him; ful oft [664] suffur &thorn;ou &thorn;ere fore paciently; for &thorn;e wiseman eke sei&thorn;e; If &thorn;ou strif wi&thorn; a fole &thorn;ouhe &thorn;e fole be wro&thorn;e or &thorn;ouhe he lawhe al gate; &thorn;ou schalt haue no reste [665] &para; &thorn;e to&thorn;ere greuance outeward is to haue damage of &thorn;i catel; &thorn;ere a&yogh;ein suffurd criste ful paciently; whan he was dispoilede of &thorn;at he hadde in &thorn;is life &amp; &thorn;at nas nouht bot &thorn;e clo&thorn;es [666] &para; &thorn;an greuance is to a man haue harme in his bodye; &thorn;at suffred criste ful paciently in al his passion [667] &thorn;e fer&thorn;e greuance is an outrageous laboure in werkes. Wherfor .I. seie &thorn;at folke &thorn;at maken here seruantes to traueyle to greuouslye or oute of time as on halidayes; so&thorn;ely &thorn;ei done grete sinne. / [668] <MILESTONE N="244a" UNIT="folio">Here a&yogh;eine suffred criste ful paciently. And tauht vs pacience whan he bare vpon his blissed scholder &thorn;e cros vpon &thorn;e whiche he scholde suffur a spitous de&thorn;; [669] &para; Here maie men lerne to be pacient; for certes nouht onely cristen men bene pacient for &thorn;e loue of ihesu criste; &amp; for guerdone of &thorn;e blisse of heuen. And of &thorn;e blisful lyf &thorn;at is perdurable; Bot certes &thorn;e olde peyneymes &thorn;at neuer were cristen com|menden &amp; vsen &thorn;e vertue of pacience;</P>
<P>[670] A philosofre vpon a time &thorn;at wolde haue bet his disciple for his grete trespace for whiche he was gretely ameuede; &amp; brouhte a &yogh;erde to scoure &thorn;e childe; [671] And whan &thorn;e childe sawe &thorn;e &yogh;erde He seide to his maister what wil &yogh;e do; I. wil bete quod &thorn;e Maister for &thorn;i correctione. [672] For so&thorn;e sire quod &thorn;e childe &yogh;owe ouhte firste corecte &yogh;oure of &thorn;at &yogh;e haue lost &yogh;oure pacience for &thorn;e gilte of a childe; [673] For so&thorn;e quod &thorn;e Maister al wepeinge &thorn;ou 
<PB REF="00000691.tif" N="659"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="645"> seist so&thorn;e; Haue &thorn;ou &thorn;e &yogh;erde my dere sone; &amp; correcte me for myne impacience; [674] Of paciens comme&thorn;e obedience; of whiche a man is obedient to criste; &amp; to all hem to wiche he ouhte be obedient in criste. [675] And vndestande wele &thorn;at obedience is perfite; whan men done gladly &amp; hastely wi&thorn; good herte enterely al &thorn;at he schold do; [676] Obedience generaly is to performe &thorn;e doctrine of god &amp; of his sovreygnes to whiche him ouhte to be obeissant to al rihtwisnesse</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Accidia.</HEAD>
<P>[677]</P>
<P>After &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sinnes of Enevy . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> .I. wil speke of &thorn;e sinnes of accide; For Enevy blinde&thorn; &thorn;e herte of a man; And ire trouble&thorn; aman; And Accide Make&thorn; him hevye &thorn;ouhtful &amp; wrawe; [678] Enevy &amp; Ire make&thorn; bitternes in hert; whiche bitternes is moder of accidie. &amp; benyme&thorn; him &thorn;e loue of al goodnesse. &thorn;an is accide &thorn;e angwysche of a trowble hert; And seinte. Austeyne sei&thorn;e: It is anoye it is anoy of goodenesse; &amp; anoye of harme; [679] sertes &thorn;is is a dampnable sinne; ffor it do&thorn;e wronge to ihesu criste; in alsomuche &thorn;at he nymme&thorn; &thorn;e seruice &thorn;at men ouhte to do to ihesu criste wi&thorn; al diligence as sei&thorn; Salomon; [680] Bot accide do&thorn;e none suche diligence; he do&thorn;e al &thorn;inge wi&thorn; anoye; &amp; wrawnesse slaknesse &amp; excusacion &amp; wi&thorn; dulnes &amp; vnlust; ffor whiche &thorn;e boke sei&thorn;e acursed be he &thorn;at do&thorn;e &thorn;at do&thorn; &thorn;e seruice of god neclygently; [681] &thorn;en is Accide Enevye to eueryche astate of man; For certes &thorn;e estate of man is in &thorn;re maners; [682] Ey&thorn;ere it is &thorn;e state of Innocence as was &thorn;e state of Adam be-fore he fel in to sinne; In whiche he was holden to worche as in an hereynge; &amp; in adourynge of god; [683] Ano&thorn;ere estate is &thorn;e state of sinfulmen; in whiche estate men bien holden 
<PB REF="00000692.tif" N="660"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="646"> to labour in preyinge to god for amendement of here . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> sinnes; [684] Ano&thorn;ere estate es &thorn;e estate of grace; In whiche estate he is halden to do werkes of penitence; And certes to al &thorn;es &thorn;inges is accide Enemy &amp; con|trarie. for he loue&thorn; no besinesse att al; [685] &para; Nowe certes &thorn;is foule sinne accide; is eke a ful grete enemye til &thorn;e liflode of &thorn;e body; ffor it ha&thorn;e no purueance a&yogh;eine temp[or]ele necessite; for it is for-slew&thorn;ed &amp; for slogge&thorn; &amp; distruye&thorn; al goodes temperelles be rechilnesse;</P>
<P>[686] &para; &thorn;e fourte &thorn;inge is &thorn;at Accide is like hem &thorn;at bien in &thorn;e peyne of hell because of her slou&thorn;e &amp; of her hevinesse; ffor &thorn;ei &thorn;at bien dampned bien so bounde &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne maye wele do; ne wele &thorn;enke; [687] Of accide comme&thorn; first &thorn;at a man is anoyed &amp; encombred. <MILESTONE N="244b" UNIT="folio">to done any goodnesse; &amp; make&thorn; &thorn;at god ha&thorn;e Abomynacioun of suche as sei&thorn; seinte Ioh.</P>
<P>[688] Now comme&thorn; sleu&thorn;e &thorn;at wil not suffre none hardenesse ne none penance; For so&thorn;e slou&thorn;e is so tender &amp; so delicate as sei&thorn;e Salomon; &thorn;at he wil not suffre none hardenesse ne penance &para; And &thorn;erfor he schende&thorn; al &thorn;at he do&thorn;e [689] a&yogh;eines his roten hercid sinne of Accide; And slou&thorn;e sholde men exercise hemself to done good werkes &amp; manly &amp; vertuouslye cachen corage wele to done thenk|inge &thorn;at oure lorde ihesu criste quyte&thorn;e euery goode dede be it neuere so lite; [690] vsage of laboure is grete a &thorn;inge; ffor it make&thorn; as sei&thorn;e seinte Bernard; The laborer to haue stronge harmes &amp; hard synowes; &amp; slow&thorn;e make&thorn; him febel &amp; tendre; [691] &para; &thorn;an comme&thorn; drede to be-ginne for to wirke any goode werke; &para; For certes he &thorn;at is enclined to sinne; him &thorn;inke it is so grete an emprise; for to vndertake to do werkes of goodnesse [692] . . . . .
<PB REF="00000693.tif" N="661"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="647"> . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> as sei&thorn;e seint Gregorie</P>
<P>[693] &para; Nowe; comme&thorn; wanhope &thorn;at is dispeire of &thorn;e mercie of god; &thorn;at comme&thorn; sume time of to myche out|rageous sorwe &para; And some time of muche drede ymagen|ynge; &thorn;at he ha&thorn; done so muche sinne &thorn;at it wil nouht aveile him &thorn;ouhe he wold repent him; &amp; for-saak &amp; do goode; [694] &thorn;oruhe whiche dispeire or drede; he abounde&thorn; his hert to euery manere sinne; As sei&thorn;e seint Auguste; [695] whiche dampnable sinne if &thorn;at it continue vn to his ende; it is cleped sinnynge in &thorn;e holy gost; [696] &thorn;is orrible sinne is so perilous &thorn;at he &thorn;at is despeired; &thorn;ere ne is no sinne &thorn;at he doute&thorn; for to do as schewde wele be Iudas; [697] Certes &thorn;an a-bouen al sinnes &thorn;an is &thorn;is sinne most displesant to crist; &amp; most aduersarie [698] to crist // So&thorn;ely he &thorn;at dispeyre&thorn; him; is like &thorn;e cowarde champeoun recreant; &amp; sei&thorn;e creant; al wi&thorn;outene nede; Alas alas nedeles is he creant; &amp; sei&thorn;e creant nedelesse despeired; // [699] for certes &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> mercy of god is euer redy to &thorn;e penytence; it is aboue al his werkes [700] &para; Alas can not a man be - &thorn;enke him of seint luke; 15<SUP>o</SUP>. where as criste sei&thorn;e &thorn;at as wele schal &thorn;ere be; Ioye in heuen vp&omacr;n a sinful man &thorn;at do&thorn;e penitence; &thorn;an vpon 90 &amp; .19. &thorn;at . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> nede&thorn; no penitente [701] &para; Loke fer&thorn;ermore in &thorn;e gospel; &thorn;e Ioy &amp; &thorn;e festes of &thorn;e good man &thorn;at hadde lost his sone; whan his sone wi&thorn; repentance was retorned to his fader; [702] Can &thorn;ei nou&yogh;t remembre hem eke; &thorn;at as sei&thorn;e seinte luca 13<SUP>o</SUP>. c<SUP>o</SUP>. how &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ef sei&thorn;e &thorn;at was hongede be-side ihesu cristes side; Lorde remembre on me whan &thorn;ou commest vn to &thorn;i kingedome [703] &para; For so&thorn;e seide crist; To daie &thorn;ou schalt be with me in paradise; [704] Certes &thorn;er nys none so orrible sinne of 
<PB REF="00000694.tif" N="662"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="648"> man &thorn;at it ne maye in his lif be destreyde be penitence; &thorn;oruhe vertue of &thorn;e passion &amp; &thorn;e de&thorn; of criste; [705] &para; Alas what nede&thorn;e man to be despeired &thorn;an. se&thorn;en his mercy so redye is; An aske &amp; haue; // [706] &thorn;an comme&thorn; sompnolence &thorn;at is slogge slombre whiche make&thorn; a man heuy &amp; dul in body; &amp; in soule; And &thorn;is sinne comme&thorn; of slew&thorn;e; [707] And certes &thorn;e time &thorn;at be wey of resone men schold nou&yogh;t slepe by &thorn;e morwe bot if &thorn;ere were cause resonable; [708] ffor so&thorn;ely in &thorn;e morwe tide is most couenable a man to seie his preyers &amp; for to &thorn;inken on god &amp; for to honoure god; and to &yogh;euen almos &thorn;atcommen<MILESTONE N="245a" UNIT="folio"> to &thorn;e pore &thorn;at first comen in &thorn;e name of criste; [709] Lo what sei&thorn;e Salomon; who so wil be &thorn;e morne awake to seke me he schal finde [710] &para; &thorn;an comme&thorn;; necligence or rechelnesse &thorn;at rekke&thorn; of no &thorn;inge; &amp; howe &thorn;at ignorance is &thorn;e moder of al harme; Certes necligens is &thorn;e norische to [711] necligentes ne do&thorn;e no force whan he schal done a &thorn;inge whe&thorn;er he do it wele or badly;</P>
<P>[712] Of &thorn;e remedy of &thorn;es two sinnes as sei&thorn; &thorn;e wisman &para; &thorn;at he &thorn;at drede&thorn; god spare&thorn; nouht to done &thorn;at him ouht to done; [713] And he &thorn;at loue&thorn; god wyl do diligence to plese god by his werkes &amp; abounden him self wi&thorn; al his myht wele for to done; [714] &para; &thorn;an comme Idelnese &thorn;at is &thorn;e &yogh;ate of al harmes; An; ydel man is lyke to a place &thorn;at ha&thorn;e no walles; &thorn;e deuel may entre on euery side; or schote att him att discouert be tempacions on euery side; [715] &thorn;is ydelnes is &thorn;e &thorn;orrok of al wikked &amp; veleynes &thorn;ouhtes; &amp; of al Iangles trufles &amp; al ordure; [716] Certes &thorn;e heuen is &yogh;ouen to him &thorn;at wil laboure &amp; nouht to ydel folke; Eke dauid sei&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne be not in &thorn;e laboure of men; ne &thorn;ei ne scholn not be whipped wi&thorn; men; &thorn;at is to seie in purgatorie; 
<PB REF="00000695.tif" N="663"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="649"> [717] Certes &thorn;an seme&thorn; it &thorn;ei schal be tormented wi&thorn; &thorn;e deuel in hel; bot if &thorn;ei done penytence;</P>
<P>[718] &thorn;an comme&thorn; &thorn;e sinne &thorn;at men clepen tarditas; As whan a man is so latred &amp; so tariinge ere he wil torne to god; And certes &thorn;at is a grete folye; He is like him &thorn;at falle&thorn; in &thorn;e diche; And wil nouht arise; [719] And &thorn;is vice comme&thorn;e of fals hope; &thorn;at he &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at he schal leue longe; bot &thorn;at hope faile&thorn; ful oft;</P>
<P>[720] &para; &thorn;an comme&thorn; laches &thorn;at is he &thorn;at whan he beginne&thorn; any goode werke; anone he wil for-lete it &amp; stinte as done &thorn;ei &thorn;at haue any wight to gouerne; &amp; ne taken of him no more kepe; anone as &thorn;ei finde any contrarie or anye anoye / [721] &para; &thorn;es bene &thorn;e now scheperdes &thorn;at laten her schepe renne wyteingly to &thorn;e wolf; &thorn;at is in &thorn;e breres; or done no fors of her owen gouernance; [722] &para; Of &thorn;is comme&thorn; pouerte; &amp; discripcion bot of spirituele &amp; temporal &thorn;inges &para; &thorn;an comme&thorn; a manere of coldenesse; &thorn;at frese&thorn; al &thorn;e herte of man; [723] &para; &thorn;an comme&thorn; vndeuocione &thorn;oruhe; whiche a man his so blonte &para; And as sei&thorn;e seint Bernard. He ha&thorn;e suche langour in soule &thorn;at he maie ney&thorn;ere rede ne singe in holy cherche Ne here ne &thorn;inke of deuocion; ne traueyle wi&thorn; his hondes in no goode werke; &thorn;at it nys to him vnsauerye; &para; And al apalled; [724] &thorn;an waxeth he sore &amp; slowe &amp; slombre; &amp; sone wil be wro&thorn;e; And sone is enclinede to hate &amp; to envye // [725] &thorn;ane comme&thorn; &thorn;e sinne of werldly sorwe; whiche &thorn;at is clepide tristicia; &thorn;at sle&thorn;e a man as sei&thorn;e seint Poule; [726] ffor certes suche sorwe worche&thorn; to &thorn;e de&thorn;e of &thorn;e soule &amp; of &thorn;e body also &para; For &thorn;ere of comme&thorn; &thorn;at a man is anoyed of his owen lif; [727] Where-for suche sorwe; schorte&thorn; ful oft &thorn;e lif of a man er &thorn;at his time comme;
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000696.tif" N="664"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="650">
<HEAD>[The Remedy against Accidie.]</HEAD>
<P>[728] &para; A&yogh;eynes &thorn;is orrible sinne of Accide &amp; &thorn;e braunches of &thorn;e same; &thorn;ere is a vertue &thorn;at is called fortitudo; or strenke&thorn; &thorn;at is an affeccioun &thorn;oruhe whiche a man dispise&thorn;e al noyeus &thorn;inge; [729] &para; &thorn;is vertue is so myhty; &amp; so vigorouse &thorn;at it dar wi&thorn;-stande myhtyly &amp; wrestel a&yogh;eines &thorn;e saule of the deuel; And wisely kepen him selfe frome periles &thorn;at bien wikked; [730] For it enchaunce&thorn; &amp; enfor<MILESTONE N="245b" UNIT="folio">ce&thorn; &thorn;e soule Riht as accide abate&thorn; it make&thorn; febel // for &thorn;is fortitude may longe endure be longe suffrance; &thorn;e traveile &thorn;at bien conuenable;</P>
<P>[731] &thorn;is vertue ha&thorn; mony spyces; &para; &thorn;e first is cleped magnificence; &thorn;at is to seie grete Corage; ffor certes &thorn;er behoue&thorn; grete corage a&yogh;eines accidie; les &thorn;at swolowe &thorn;e sowle be &thorn;e sinne of sorwe; or destruye it be wanhope; [732] &para; &thorn;is vertu make&thorn; folke to vndertake harde &thorn;inges &amp; greuouse &thorn;inges be hire owen wyll wysely &amp; resonably; [733] And for als muche as &thorn;e deuel fihte&thorn; a&yogh;eines man more be queyntise &amp; be sleyht &thorn;an be strenke&thorn;; &para; &thorn;erefore a man schal with-stonde him with witte &amp; with reson &amp; with dis|crecion // [734] &thorn;en bien &thorn;ere &thorn;e vertues of fei&thorn;e &amp; hope in god; &amp; in his seintes to acheuen &amp; accomplise &thorn;e goode werkes; in whiche he purpose fermely to continue; [735] &thorn;an comme&thorn; suerte or sikernesse; &amp; &thorn;at is whan a man . . . . .[736]. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> do&thorn;e; &amp; performe&thorn; grete werkes of goodenesse &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e begonne; And &thorn;at is &thorn;e ende whi &thorn;at men schold do goode werkes; &para; ffor in &thorn;e compliseinge of goode werkes li&thorn;e &thorn;e grete guerdone [737] &para; &thorn;an is &thorn;ere constance &thorn;at is stablenesse of Corage; And &thorn;is scholde be in herte be stedfast fei&thorn;e; &amp; in mou&thorn;e &amp; in 
<PB REF="00000697.tif" N="665"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="651"> bereinge; And in chere; &amp; in dede [738] eke; &para; &thorn;ere bien mo special &thorn;inges &amp; remedy a&yogh;eines accide in diuerse werkes; &amp; in consideracion of &thorn;e peyne of hell &amp; of the Ioy of heuen; &amp; in &thorn;e trust of &thorn;e grace of &thorn;e holy goste &thorn;at wil &yogh;iuen him myht to performe his entente</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Auaricia.<NOTE PLACE="marg">de avaricia</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>[739]</P>
<P>Affter Accidie wil .I. speke of avarice; &amp; of Couetyse // Off whiche sinne sei&thorn; seint Paule; &thorn;at &thorn;e rote of al sinnes is couetise; Ad Thimotheum 6<SUP>o</SUP>. [740] &para; For so&thorn;ely whan &thorn;e herte of a man is confounded in hit selfe &amp; trouble &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e soule ha&thorn;e loste &thorn;e comforte of god; &thorn;an sike&thorn; he ane ydel solace of werldely &thorn;inges;</P>
<P>[741] &para; Auarice after &thorn;e scripcione of seint Austyne; is a lykerousnes in hert to haue er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges; [742] Somme o&thorn;ere folk seyne &thorn;at Auarice is for to purchase mony er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges; &amp; no &thorn;inge &yogh;iue to hem &thorn;at haue nede [743] &para; And vnderstand &thorn;ou wele; &thorn;at auarice nys nouht onelye in lande ne in catell; bot sum time in science and in glorye And in euery manere of outrageous &thorn;inges is aueryce; &amp; couetyse; [744] &para; And &thorn;e difference be-tuex Auarice &amp; couetise is &thorn;is; Couetise is for to coueyte suche &thorn;inges as &thorn;ou haste nouht; = And Auarice is to wi&thorn;-holde &amp; kepe suche &thorn;inges as &thorn;ou hast wi&thorn; outen rihtful nede [745] &para; So&thorn;ely &thorn;is Auarice is a sinne &thorn;at is ful dampnable; ffor al holy writte curse&thorn; it; &amp; speke&thorn; a&yogh;eines it; ffor it do&thorn;e wronge to ihesu criste; [746] for it be-reue&thorn; him &thorn;e loue &thorn;at men to him owen. And turne&thorn; it bakwarde a&yogh;eines al reson; [747] &amp; make&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e Auaricious man ha&thorn;e more hope in his catel &thorn;an in ihesu criste; And . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [748] &thorn;erefor sei&thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000698.tif" N="666"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="652"> seinte poule. Ephecios 5<SUP>o</SUP>. &thorn;at Auarous man is &thorn;ral to ydolatrie;</P>
<P>[749] What difference is betuex an ydolastre &amp; an Auarous man; Bot &thorn;at an ydolatre &amp; an Auaricious man par|aduentur ne ha&thorn;e bot one maumet; or tuo; And &thorn;e Auaricious man ha&thorn; monye; For certes euery floreine in his copher is a mawmet; [750] And certes &thorn;e sinne of Maumatrie is &thorn;at god in &thorn;e ten commandementes; As bere&thorn; <MILESTONE N="246a" UNIT="folio">wittenesse in exodi .capitulo .20. [751] &thorn;ou schalt haue none fals goddes beforne me; Ne &thorn;ou schalt make to &thorn;e no graue &thorn;inge; &thorn;us &thorn;an is an Avaricious man &thorn;at loue&thorn; his tresor a-forne god; And ydolatre [752] &thorn;oruhe his sinne of Auarice &amp; of couetise; be whiche commen &thorn;is harde lordeschipes &thorn;oruhe whiche mene bien streyned be talyage costomes &amp; Cariages More &thorn;an here dewte or reson is And elles take &thorn;ei of her bonde|men amerciament; whiche myht more resonable be cleped extorcions &thorn;an mercymentes; [753] Of whiche mercimentes And raunsons of bonde men somme lorde stewardes sein &thorn;at it is rihtful; for also muche as a cherle ha&thorn;e no temporele &thorn;inge &thorn;at ne is &thorn;e lordes as &thorn;ei seine. [754] Bot certes &thorn;is lordeschipes done wronge &thorn;at bereue&thorn; hir bondefolke &thorn;inges; &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne &yogh;afe hem; Augustinus de Ciuitate dei .li<SUP>o</SUP> .9. [755] So&thorn;e is &thorn;at &thorn;e condicion of &thorn;raldome &amp; &thorn;e first cause of &thorn;raldom is for sinne. Genesis .5.</P>
<P>[756] &thorn;us maye &yogh;e seene &thorn;at &thorn;e gilt deserue&thorn; &thorn;raldome Bot note nature; [757] Where-fore &thorn;es lordes schold nou&yogh;t much glorifie hem in here lordeschipe se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;at bu naturel condicion &thorn;ei bien lordes ouer her &thorn;ralles; Bot for &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;raldom cam firste be desert of sinne; = [758] And fer&thorn;ere ouer; &thorn;ere as &thorn;e lawe sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at temporel goodes of bonde folke bien &thorn;e goodes of here lordeschipes: &yogh;e &thorn;at is for to vnderstande &thorn;e goodes of &thorn;e Emperour To defende hem in here riht; bot not to Robbe hem ne to Reue hem; [759] And &thorn;erfore 
<PB REF="00000699.tif" N="667"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="653"> sei&thorn;e Senec &thorn;i prudence schold leue benyngly with &thorn;i &thorn;rall &para; [760] &thorn;ilke &thorn;at &thorn;ou clepest &thorn;i &thorn;rall bien cristes peple; For humble folke bien criste frendes; &thorn;ei bien contuberniale with &thorn;e lorde</P>
<P>[761] &para; &thorn;enke eke &thorn;at suche sede as cherles springen; of suche seede springen lordes; as wele may &thorn;e cherle be saued as &thorn;e lorde; [762] &thorn;e same de&thorn;e &thorn;at take&thorn; &thorn;e cherle; &thorn;e same de&thorn; take&thorn;e &thorn;e lorde; wherfore I rede do riht so wi&thorn; &thorn;i cherle as &thorn;ou woldest &thorn;i lorde dide with &thorn;e if &thorn;ou were in his plite. [763] &para; Euery sinful man is a cherle to sinne; &para; I rede &thorn;e certes &thorn;at &thorn;ou lorde &thorn;ou wirche in suche wise; &thorn;at &thorn;ine cherles ra&thorn;er loue &thorn;e &thorn;an drede &thorn;e [764] &para; I. wote wele &thorn;er is degre aboue degre as reson is; And scyll is &thorn;at men don here deuere &thorn;ere as it is diewe; Bot certes extorcions &amp; dispites of &yogh;oure vnderlinges is dampnable;</P>
<P>[765] &para; And for&thorn;ere ouere vnderstond wele; &thorn;at conquerours or tirantes maken ful often; &thorn;ralles of hem &thorn;at bien borne of as Roial blode as ben &thorn;ei &thorn;at hem conqueren; [766] This name of &thorn;raldom was neuere knowe erst til &thorn;at Noe seide of his sonne Canaan scholde be &thorn;rale to his bre&thorn;erne for his sinne; [767] what sey we &thorn;an of hem &thorn;at pilen And done extorcions to holy chirche &para; Certes &thorn;e swerde &thorn;at men &yogh;euen first to a knyhte whan he is newe dubbid; signifie&thorn; &thorn;at he scholde defende holy chirche; &amp; nouht rob it; And who so do&thorn;e is a traitour to criste [768] as sei&thorn; seinte Austine; &thorn;ei buen deuels wolues &thorn;at stranglen &thorn;e schepe of ihesu criste; &amp; done wers &thorn;an wolues; [769] &para; ffor so&thorn;ely whan &thorn;e wolfe ha&thorn; ful his wombe He stinte&thorn; to strangel schepe; Bot so&thorn;ely &thorn;e piloures &amp; distrey|ours of goodes of holy chirche done not so; for &thorn;e stint neuer to pilen; [770] &para; Now as .I. <MILESTONE N="246b" UNIT="folio">haue seide; Se&thorn;en so is &thorn;at sinn was first cause of &thorn;raldome; &thorn;an it is 
<PB REF="00000700.tif" N="668"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="654"> &thorn;us &thorn;at &thorn;ilke time &thorn;at al &thorn;e werld was in sinne; &thorn;an was al &thorn;is werlde in &thorn;raldome And in subiectione; = [771] Bot certes Sethins &thorn;e time of grace Cam; god ordeynde &thorn;at somme folke scholde be more hihe in Estate; &amp; hihe degree; And somme folke more lowe; &amp; &thorn;at eueryche schold be serued in his estate &amp; in his degre; [772] And &thorn;erfore in somme contrees &thorn;ere &thorn;ei be &thorn;rales; whan &thorn;ei haue turned hem to &thorn;e fei&thorn;e; &thorn;ei maken here &thorn;ralles fre oute of &thorn;raldome; And &thorn;erfore certes &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lorde owe&thorn; to his manne &thorn;at &thorn;e man owe&thorn; to his lorde &para; [773] &thorn;e Pope clepe&thorn; him self seruant of &thorn;e seruantes of god &para; Bot for as muche as &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> state of holy chirche ne myht nouht haue be kepped; Ne &thorn;e commune profit mi&yogh;t haue be kepped; ne pese &amp; rest in er&thorn;e; bot if god hadde ordeynde &thorn;at sommen haue hier degre &amp; som men lowere; [774] &thorn;erfore was souereygnte ordeyned to kepe &amp; mayntene; &amp; de|fende here vnderlinges or her soubiectes in reson; as fer|for&thorn; as it li&thorn;e in hir pouere; And nouht to destreye hem ne as ferfor&thorn;e confounden; [775] Wher for .I. saye &thorn;at &thorn;ilke lordes &thorn;at bien &thorn;ilke wolves; &thorn;at deuoure &thorn;e possessions or &thorn;e catel of pore folke wrongefully wi&thorn; outen Mercye or Mesore; [776] &thorn;ei schollen receyuen bue &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> same mesure &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue mesured to pore folke &thorn;e mercy of ihesu criste bot it bue amended; [777] &para; Nowe comme&thorn; disceite b[e]tuex Marchant &amp; marchant; &para; And &thorn;ou schalt vnder|stant &thorn;at Marchandise is in mony maners; &thorn;at one is bodely; &amp; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> to&thorn;ere is gostlye &para; &thorn;at one is lefful &amp; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> to&thorn;ere is dishoneste &amp; vnleful; [778] Of &thorn;ilke bodely marchandise &thorn;at is leful &amp; honest is &thorn;is; &thorn;at &thorn;ere as god ha&thorn; ordeigned &thorn;at a regne or a contre is sufficeant him selfe &thorn;an is it honeste &amp; lefull &thorn;at of &thorn;e abundance of &thorn;is contree; &thorn;at men helpe a no&thorn;ere contree &thorn;at is more nedye; [779] And &thorn;ere fore &thorn;ere mote be marchantz to bringen fro &thorn;e to cuntre to &thorn;e to&thorn;ere her march|andise; 
<PB REF="00000701.tif" N="669"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="655"> [780] &thorn;e to&thorn;ere Merchandise &thorn;at men haunte wi&thorn; fraude; &amp; trecherye &amp; disceyte wi&thorn;e lesinges &amp; fals o&thorn;es; is cursed &amp; dampnable [781] &para; Espyrituel marchandise is properely Symony; &thorn;at is ententif desire to by &thorn;inge espirituele; &thorn;at is &thorn;inge &thorn;at appartene&thorn; to &thorn;e seintuarye of god; &amp; to cure of &thorn;e soule; [782] This desire if so be &thorn;at a man do his diligence to performe it al be it &thorn;at his desire ne take none effecte &yogh;it is it to him dedely sinne; And if he be ordrede he is Irregulere; [783] &para; Certes Symonye; is clepid of Simon Magus &thorn;at wolde haue bouht with &thorn;e temporele catell &thorn;e &yogh;eft &thorn;at god had &yogh;ouen by &thorn;e holy goste to seinte Peter; &amp; to &thorn;e Apostoles; [784] And &thorn;erfore vnderstande&thorn;; &thorn;at bo&thorn; he &thorn;at selle&thorn; &amp; he &thorn;at bye&thorn; &thorn;inges espirituels bien cleped Symonyals &para; be it Catel; be it be procureinge; Ore be fleschely preyere of his frendes or of spirituel frendes [785] &para; Flesschely; in tuo maners; as by kinred; or as by o&thorn;ere frendes or of spirituel frendes. &para; So&thorn;ely if &thorn;ei prey for him &thorn;at is not able &amp; wor&thorn;i; it is Symonye; If he take &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> benefice; &amp; if he be wor&thorn;i &amp; able; he nys none; [786] &para; &thorn;e to&thorn;ere maner is whan a man or a womman preye&thorn;e; preye for folke to auaunce hem only for wikked fleschely affeccione; &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue vn to &thorn;e persones; &amp; &thorn;at is in foule Symony; [787] Bot certes in seruices for whiche men &yogh;euen &thorn;inges espirituels vnto her seruantes; It mote bien vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e seruice most be honeste &amp; elles note; And eke &thorn;at it be wi&thorn; outen Barganynge &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e persone be able; [788] ffor as sei&thorn;e seinte Damasye; Al &thorn;e sinnes <MILESTONE N="247a" UNIT="folio">of &thorn;e worlde att &thorn;e regarde of &thorn;is sinne biene as a &thorn;inge of nouht; For it is &thorn;e grestest sinne &thorn;at may be; after; &thorn;e sinne of lucifer &amp; of antecriste; [789] ffor be &thorn;is sinne gor for-lese&thorn; &thorn;e chirche &amp; &thorn;e soule &thorn;at he bouhte wi&thorn; his precious blode; by hem &thorn;at &yogh;eue cherches to hem &thorn;at biene nouht digne; [790] For &thorn;ei putten inn &thorn;eues &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000702.tif" N="670"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="656"> stelen &thorn;e soule of ihesu criste &amp; destruye&thorn; his patri|moigne [791] &para; Be. suche vndigne prestes; &amp; Curates haue men &thorn;e lasse Reuerence of &thorn;e sacramentz of holychirche; &para; And suche &yogh;euers of chirches putten oute &thorn;e childerne of criste; &amp; putten in to &thorn;e cherche &thorn;e deueles owen sone [792] &thorn;ei sellen &thorn;e soules; &thorn;e lombe &thorn;ei kepen to &thorn;e wolf &thorn;at strangelle&thorn; hem; And &thorn;erefore schol &thorn;ei neuer houe parte of &thorn;e pasture of &thorn;e lombes &thorn;at is in &thorn;e blisse of heuen; [793] &para; Nowe comme&thorn; hasardy with his apur|tenance as tables &amp; rawfles of whiche comme&thorn; deceyte &amp; fals o&thorn;es chideinge; &amp; al rauynges; blasphemyinge &amp; reniinge of god &amp; hate of his neybours; wasteinges of goodes myspendinge of time; And sumtyme man|slawhter [794] &para; Certes hasardours nemaye nouht be wi&thorn; oute grete sinne whiles &thorn;ei haunte &thorn;at crafte [795] &para; Of Auarice comme&thorn;e eke leseinges &thorn;eft &amp; false wittenesse; Fals o&thorn;es; And &yogh;e schall vnderstonde; &thorn;at &thorn;es bien grete sinnes &amp; expresse a&yogh;eines &thorn;e commandementes of god as .I. haue seide; [796] &para; Fals wittnesse is in worde &amp; eke in dede. In worde as for to be-reve &thorn;i neyhbours good name By &thorn;ine fals witnesinge. Or be-reue him his Catell; or his heritage be &thorn;ine fals wyttenesinge; &para; whan &thorn;ou for Ire or for meede or for envy berest fals wittenesse or accusest him or excusest him by &thorn;ine fals witnesse; or elles ex|cusest &thorn;i self falsly [797] &para; Ware &yogh;oue qwestmongers &amp; notories &para; Certes for false witnesseinge was Susanna in grete sorwe; &amp; peyne; &amp; mony ano&thorn;er mo [798] &para; The sinne of &thorn;eft is eke expresse a&yogh;eines godes heste; &amp; &thorn;at in tuo maners Corporele &amp; spirituele [799] [Corporele] as for to take &thorn;ine neyhbours Catel a&yogh;eines his will be it be force or be sleyht; be it be mette; or be mesure; [800] By steleinge eke of fals enditementes vpon him; And in borwein of &thorn;in neyhbours Catell; in entent neuere to paye; &amp; semblable &thorn;inges [801] &para; Es|pirituel &thorn;eft is sacrilege &thorn;at is to seye vrt|ynge 
<PB REF="00000703.tif" N="671"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="657"> of holy &thorn;inges; or of &thorn;inges sacred to criste in tue maners by reson. of &thorn;e holy place as chirches or chirche hawes; [802] ffor euery. violence sinne &thorn;at men done in suche place may bue cleped Sacrilege; Or euery violence in &thorn;e semblable place; Also &thorn;ei &thorn;at wi&thorn;-drawen falsly &thorn;e rihtes &thorn;at longen to holy cherche; [803] And pleynely &amp; generaly sacrilege is to &yogh;eue holy &thorn;inge fro holy place; or vnholy &thorn;inge oute of holy place; or holy &thorn;inge oute of vn|holy place;</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[The Remedy against Avarice.]</HEAD>
<P>[804] Nowe scholne &yogh;e vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e releuynge of Auarice is misericorde &amp; pite largely taken &para; And me myht axen whi &thorn;at mysericorde &amp; pite is releueinge of Auarice; [805] Certes &thorn;e Auarice man schewe&thorn; no pite ne misericorde to &thorn;e nedful man; ffor he delite&thorn; him in &thorn;re kepinges of his tresoure; &amp; not in &thorn;e restoreinge ne releueinge of his euen|cristen; &amp; &thorn;erfore spek .I. first of mysericorde; [806] &para; &thorn;an is misericord as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e philosofre a vertue bue whiche &thorn;e Corage of man is stered be &thorn;e corage of him. <MILESTONE N="247b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at is my[s]esede [807] vpon whiche misericorde folowe&thorn; pytee in perfourmynge of charitable werkes of misericorde. [808] And certes &thorn;es meuen man to &thorn;e mysericord of ihesu criste &thorn;at him self for oure gilt suffred de&thorn;e for misericorde; &amp; for&yogh;af vs oure originale sinnes; [809] &amp; &thorn;ere-by relessed vs fro &thorn;e peyne of hell; and amynuse&thorn; &thorn;e peyne of purgatorie be penitence. And &yogh;eue&thorn; grace well to do &amp; att &thorn;e last &thorn;e ioye of heuen; [810] &para; The spices of mysericorde bien as for to lene &amp; for to &yogh;eue; &amp; eke for to for&yogh;eue &amp; relese &amp; haue pyte in herte &amp; to haue compassione of &thorn;e meschef of &thorn;ine 
<PB REF="00000704.tif" N="672"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="658"> euecristene; &amp; eke chastice &thorn;ere as nede is. [811] &para; Ano&thorn;ere manere of Remedie a&yogh;eine avarice is resonable largesse; Bot so&thorn;ely here be-houe&thorn; &thorn;e con|sideracioun of &thorn;e grace of ihesu criste &amp; of his temporil goodes . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> perdurables &thorn;at crist &yogh;aff vs [812] and eke to haue remembrance of &thorn;e de&thorn; &thorn;at he schal receyue he note when; and eke &thorn;at he schal for-gone al &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e; . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></P>
<P>[813] Bot for as muche as summe folke bien vnmesur|able men ouhten eschiewe foole largesse &thorn;at men clepen wast; [814] Certes he &thorn;at is foole large ne &yogh;eue&thorn; nouht his catel bot he lese&thorn; his catel; &para; So&thorn;ely what &thorn;inge &thorn;at he &yogh;eue&thorn; for veineglorie as to menstrals &amp; to folke for to beren his renoune in &thorn;e werlde he ha&thorn;e do synne &amp; none almos [815] Certe&yogh; he lese&thorn; foule his good; &thorn;at he ne seke&thorn; no &thorn;inge of his goode bot sinne [816] He is ylike to an hors &thorn;at seke&thorn; ra&thorn;er to drinke drouy or trouble water &thorn;an of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> clere well; [817] And for as muche as &thorn;ei &yogh;eue &thorn;ere as &thorn;ei schold not &yogh;eue to hem appartene&thorn; &thorn;ilke malyson &thorn;at crist schal lyven att &thorn;e daye of dome to hem &thorn;at schal be dampned.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; De gula.</HEAD>
<P>[818]</P>
<P>After Auarice comme&thorn; glotonye whiche is expresse eke a&yogh;eines &thorn;e commandement of god; Glotonye is vnmesurable appetit to ette or to drinke. or elles to done ynouhe to &thorn;e vnmesurable &amp; discorde couetise to ete &amp; to drinke; [819] &para; &thorn;is sinne cor|rumpe&thorn; al &thorn;is werlde as is wele schewde in &thorn;e sinne of Adam &amp; of Eua &para; lo eke what sei&thorn;e seint Poule of glotonye; [820] Mony folke of whiche 
<PB REF="00000705.tif" N="673"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="659"> .I. haue oft seide to &yogh;owe; &amp; nowe .I. seye it wepeinge; &thorn;at &thorn;ei bien ennemys of &thorn;e croyce of crist of whiche &thorn;ende is de&thorn;e; &amp; of whiche here wombes is hire god &amp; hire glorie in confusione of hem &thorn;at so saueren er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges; [821] &para; He &thorn;at is vsant to &thorn;is sinne of glotonye he ne may no sinne wi&thorn;-stande; He moste bue in seruage of al vices for it is &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> deuels horde &thorn;ere he hide&thorn; him inne &amp; reste&thorn;; [822] &para; This sinne ha&thorn; mony spyces; &thorn;e first is dronkennesse &thorn;at is &thorn;orrible sepulcre of mannes resoun; And &thorn;ere|for whan &thorn;at a man is dronken he ha&thorn;e lost his reson; &amp; &thorn;is is dedely sinne [823] &para; Bot certes whan a man is nouht wonte to straunge drinke; ne peraduenture ne knowe&thorn; not &thorn;e strenke&thorn; of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> drinke; or ha&thorn;e feblesse in his hede; or ha&thorn;e trauailede &thorn;oruhe whiche he drinke&thorn; &thorn;e more Al be he so sodanly cauht wi&thorn; drinke it is no dedely sinne bot veniale; [824] The secunde spice of glotonye is &thorn;at &thorn;e spirit of man waxe&thorn; al trouble for dronkenesse bereue&thorn; him discrecioun of his witte; [825] &para; &thorn;e &thorn;red spice of glotony is; Whan a man devowre&thorn; <MILESTONE N="248a" UNIT="folio">his mete &amp; ha&thorn;e no rihtful manere of etynge; [826] &para; &thorn;e fer&thorn;e is whan &thorn;orwh grete abund|aunce of his mete &thorn;e homours of his body biene dis|temperd [827] &para; &thorn;e .v<SUP>e</SUP>. is for&yogh;etelnesse be to mechel drynkynge for whiche sumtyme aman summe time a man for|&yogh;ete&thorn; be &thorn;e morwe what he dide att eue or att &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> nyhte be-fore;</P>
<P>[828] In o&thorn;ere manere bien distinket of Spices of glotony after seint gregorye. &para; &thorn;e first is for to ete to fortime &para; &thorn;e. secunde is whan a man gete&thorn; him to delicate mete [829] &para; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>. threde; is. whan a man take&thorn; to muchel ouere mesure &para; &thorn;e fer&thorn;e. is &thorn;e coriouste wi&thorn; grete entent to maken &amp; apparell his mete. &thorn;e fifte. is to ete to gredely; [830] &thorn;es bien &thorn;e .v. fyngres of &thorn;e deueles honde be whiche he drawe&thorn; folk to sinne
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000706.tif" N="674"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="660">
<HEAD>[The Remedy against Gluttony.]</HEAD>
<P>[831] &para; A&yogh;eynes glotonye is remedy. &thorn;e abstinence of his bodi; as sei&thorn;e Galienus. Bot &thorn;at hold .I. not meritorie. if &thorn;at he onely it do for &thorn;e hele of his body; &para; Seint Austine wil &thorn;at abstinence be done for vertwe; &amp; wi&thorn; paciens [832] abstinens he sei&thorn; is litel wor&thorn;i bot if a man haue goode wil &thorn;ere to // And bot if it be enforced be pacience &amp; charite; &amp; &thorn;at men do it for goddes saake &amp; in hope to haue &thorn;e blisse of heuen;</P>
<P>[833] &para; &thorn;e felawes of abstynence bien attemper|ance &thorn;at halde&thorn; &thorn;e mene in all &thorn;inges; eke schame &thorn;at eschewe&thorn; al disoneste; sufficeance &thorn;at seke&thorn; no Riche mete ne drinkes ne do&thorn;e no force of no owtrage apparelynge of mete [834] &para; Mesure also &thorn;at distreyne&thorn; bue resoun &thorn;e delavy appetite of eteinge; Sobernesse also &thorn;at restreyne&thorn; &thorn;e outrage of drinke. [835] Sparynge also &thorn;at restreyne&thorn; &thorn;e delicate ese to sitte att his mete softly; where-for summe folke stonden of here owen will &amp; to eten att &thorn;e lasse layser</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; De luxuria.</HEAD>
<P>[836]</P>
<P>After glotony. &thorn;an comme&thorn; lycherye for &thorn;es two sinnes bien so nyhe cosines &thorn;at often tim &thorn;ei wil not departe; = [837] god wote &thorn;is sinne is displesant to god; for he sei&thorn; him selfe do no lychery;// &amp; &thorn;ere-fore he put grete peynes a&yogh;eines &thorn;is sinne. in &thorn;e olde lawe [838] If a wom|man &thorn;rall were taken in &thorn;is sinne sche scholde be beten with stones to &thorn;e de&thorn;; And if sche were a gentil womman sche scholde be sleyne with stones; And if sche wer a bischopes douhtere sche scholde be bernte be goddes commandement; [839] &para; For&thorn;ermore be sinne of licherye god dreynte al &thorn;e werlde att &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000707.tif" N="675"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="661"> diluve; &amp; after he berned .v. Cytes with lyht &amp; sanke hem in to hell</P>
<P>[840] &para; Now latt vs spek of &thorn;ilk foule stinkynge sinne of lichery; &thorn;at men clepen aduoutre of wedded folke; &thorn;at is to sey if &thorn;at one of hem be wedded or elles bo&thorn;e; [841] Seint Iohn sei&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;e advowtrers schal bien in hell in a stinkinge birneinge fire of brimstone for licherye &para; In brimstone for &thorn;e stinkeinge of hire ordure; [842] Certe&yogh; &thorn;e brinynge of &thorn;is sacrament is an horible &thorn;inge; It was maked of god him self in paradise &amp; confermed be ihesu criste as sei&thorn; seinte Mathewe in &thorn;e gospell; A man schal lete fader &amp; moder &amp; take him to his wif. And &thorn;e scholne haue be tuo in one flesche; [843] &para; This sacrament be|tokene&thorn; &thorn;e knyttinge to-geder of criste &amp; of holy chirche [844] &para; And nouht onely &thorn;at god for-badde aduoutre in bedde; Bot eke he commanded<MILESTONE N="248b" UNIT="folio"> &thorn;at &thorn;ou scholdest nouht coueyte &thorn;ine neyhebours wif [845] &para; In &thorn;is hest sei&thorn;e seint Austine is forboden almanere Couetise to done lychery; Lo what sei&thorn;e seint Mathewe .v. c<SUP>o</SUP>. in &thorn;e gospel &thorn;at who so se&thorn;e a womman to couetise of his luste he ha&thorn;e done lycherye wi&thorn; hire in his herte; [846] Here maye &yogh;e see &thorn;at not onelye &thorn;e dede of his sinne is forbode bot eke &thorn;e desire to done &thorn;at sinne [847] &para; &thorn;is cursed sinne anoye&thorn; hem greuously &thorn;at it haunte&thorn;; &amp; first to here soule ffor he oblige&thorn; it to sinne; &amp; to &thorn;e peyne of &thorn;e de&thorn;e &thorn;at is perdurable [848] &para; Vnto &thorn;e body anoye&thorn; it greuously also; ffor it drie&thorn; him &amp; waste&thorn; him; &amp; of his blode he make&thorn; sacrifice vn-to &thorn;e fende of hell &para; It waste&thorn; eke his catel &amp; his substance; [849] &amp; certes if it be a foule &thorn;inge a man to wast his catell one wemmen; &yogh;it is it a fouler &thorn;inge whan &thorn;at for whiche ordure wemmen dispenden vpon men here catel &amp; here substance [850] &para; &thorn;is sinne as sei&thorn;e &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> prophite bereue&thorn; man &amp; womman her goode fame &amp; al her honour; And it is ful plesant to &thorn;e deuel; &amp; &thorn;erby 
<PB REF="00000708.tif" N="676"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="662"> he wynne&thorn; &thorn;e moste party of &thorn;is werlde; [851] &para; And riht as a marchant delite&thorn; him moste in chaffer &thorn;at he ha&thorn; most a-vantage of Riht so delite&thorn; &thorn;e fende &thorn;is ordure;//</P>
<P>[852] &thorn;is is &thorn;e to&thorn;ere honde of &thorn;e deuel with .v. fingeres &thorn;at cacche&thorn; &thorn;e peple to his velany; [853] &thorn;e first finger is &thorn;e foole lokeynge; of &thorn;e foole man; &amp; of &thorn;e foole womman &thorn;at sle&thorn;e Riht as &thorn;e Basilicoc sle&thorn;e folke be &thorn;e venym of his syht; ffor couetise of &thorn;e ey&yogh;en folowe&thorn; &thorn;e couetyse of &thorn;e hert; [854] &thorn;e to&thorn;ere finger his &thorn;e violence toucheinge in wykked manere; And &thorn;erfor sei&thorn; Salomon. &thorn;at who so touche&thorn; &amp; handele&thorn; a womman; he fare&thorn; y-lyke him &thorn;at handele&thorn; &thorn;e scorpion &thorn;at stinge&thorn;e; And sodanly sle&thorn;e &thorn;oruhe his envenymynge; As who so towche&thorn; warme piche &thorn;at foule&thorn; his fingers [855] &para; &thorn;e. &thorn;red is; foule wordes &thorn;at fare&thorn;.y-lyke fire &thorn;at birne&thorn;; &thorn;at riht anone birne&thorn; &thorn;e herte; [856] &para; &thorn;e fer&thorn;e is. kissinge; &amp; trewly he were a grete foole &thorn;at wolde kisse &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of a birneinge houen; or of a forneys;? [857] And more fooles bien &thorn;ei &thorn;at kissen in velanye; ffor &thorn;at mou&thorn;e is &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of hell; &amp; namely &thorn;es holde dotardes hulours; &yogh;it wil &thorn;ei kisse &thorn;ouhe &thorn;ei may nou&yogh;t do &amp; smater hem; [858] Certes &thorn;ei bien ylyke to &thorn;e houndes. For an hounde whan he comme&thorn; be &thorn;e roser or be o&thorn;ere beautees &thorn;ouhe he maie nouht pisse; &yogh;itte will he lift vp his legge &amp; make coun|tenance to pisse. [859] &para; And for &thorn;at; many wene&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ei maie nou&yogh;t sinne for no likerous &thorn;at he do&thorn;e with his wif; Certe&yogh; &thorn;at opynioune is fals; God wote a man maie sle him self with his owen knyf; &amp; maken him dronken with his owen tunne. [860] Certe&yogh; be it wif of childe or any o&thorn;er werldely &thorn;inge &thorn;at he loue&thorn; be-for god; it is a maumet &amp; he is an ydolastre; [861] &para; Man scholde loue his wif be discrecione paciently &amp; temporalye; &amp; &thorn;an is sche as it 
<PB REF="00000709.tif" N="677"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="663"> were his sustere; [862] &para; &thorn;e fift finger of &thorn;e deueles honde is &thorn;e stinkeinge dede of lycherye; [863] Certes &thorn;e .v. fingers of glotonye &thorn;e fende putte&thorn; in &thorn;e wombe of a man; &amp; with &thorn;es .v. fingers of lychery; he gripe&thorn; him be &thorn;e reynes for to &thorn;rowe him into &thorn;e forneyse of hell [864] &thorn;ere as &thorn;ei scholne haue &thorn;e fuyre &amp; &thorn;e wormes &thorn;at euer schal laste; &amp; wepeinge &amp; waileinge scharpe hunger &amp; &thorn;urste griselynesse of deueles &thorn;at schal al to treden <MILESTONE N="249a" UNIT="folio">Hem wi&thorn;-outen respite &amp; with|outen ende [865] of lychery as .I. seide sourden diuerse spyces; as fornicacion. &thorn;at is be-tuex man &amp; womman &thorn;at bien not maried; &amp; &thorn;is is dedely sinne &amp; a&yogh;eines nature; [866] Al &thorn;at is enemy &amp; destruccion to nature is a&yogh;eines nature [867] parfeye &para; &thorn;e resone of a man telle&thorn; him eke wele &thorn;at it is dedely sinne for als muche as god forbad lycherye; = And seint Poule &yogh;eue&thorn;e him &thorn;e regne &thorn;at is dieu to no whight bot to hem &thorn;at done dedely sinne [868] &para; Ano&thorn;ere sinne of lycherye is; for to be-reven a mayden of hire maydenhade; ffor certes he &thorn;at so do&thorn;e he take&thorn; a maiden oute of &thorn;e hiest degre &thorn;at is in &thorn;is present lif; [869] &amp; bereue&thorn; hire &thorn;ilke precious fruyte &thorn;at &thorn;e boke clepe&thorn;e &thorn;e hundre&thorn; fruyte. I. can nouht seye it in none o&thorn;ere weye in ynglische Bot in latine it hiht Centesimus fructus; [870] Certes he &thorn;at so do&thorn;e is cause of mony damage &amp; velanyes mo &thorn;an any man kan reken &para; Riht as he s&umacr;mtyme is cause of al &thorn;e damage &thorn;at bestes done in &thorn;e felde; &thorn;at breke&thorn; &thorn;e hegge of &thorn;e closur &thorn;oruhe whiche he distroye&thorn; &thorn;at may not be restored; [871] ffor certes no more maye maydenhede bue re|stored; &thorn;an an arme &thorn;at is smeten fro &thorn;e body maye retorne a&yogh;eine to wex; [872] Sche maye haue mercye &thorn;is wote .I. wele if sche do penitence; Bot neuer schal it be &thorn;at sche nas corrupte; [873] &para; And albeit so &thorn;at .I. haue spoken sumwhat of aduowtre it is goode to schewen mo periles &thorn;at longen to aduoutre &para; For to eschewe &thorn;e foule 
<PB REF="00000710.tif" N="678"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="664"> sinne of [874] aduoutre; in latine is for to seye; Approcheinge to ano&thorn;ere manes bedde; &thorn;oruhe whiche &thorn;o &thorn;at whilom were first o flesche; abawndon here body to o&thorn;ere persones [875] &para; Of &thorn;is sinne as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e wisman come&thorn; mony harmes; ffirste brekinge of fei&thorn;e; And certes fai&thorn;e. is kaye of cristendome; &para; [876] And whan &thorn;at fei&thorn;e is broke &amp; lorne; so&thorn;ely cristendome stant wi&thorn; outen fruyte; [877] &para; &thorn;is sinne is eke a &thorn;efe; ffor &thorn;eft generaly to speke is for reue a wight his &thorn;inge a&yogh;eines his will; [878] Certes &thorn;is is &thorn;e fouleste &thorn;eft &thorn;at maie bue; whan a womman stele&thorn; hir body fro her husbonde; &amp; &yogh;iue&thorn; it to hire holoure to defoule here &amp; stele&thorn; hire soule fromme criste; &amp; &yogh;eue&thorn; it to &thorn;e deuel. [879] &thorn;is is foulere &thorn;eft; &thorn;an for to breke &amp; stele &thorn;e chalys; ffor &thorn;es aduoutres breken &thorn;e temple of god spyrituelly &amp; stelen &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> vessel of grace; &thorn;at is &thorn;e bodye &amp; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> soule; &para; For whiche criste schal destroyen hem as sei&thorn;e seinte Poule. [880] So&thorn;ely of &thorn;is &thorn;eft douted gretely Iosephe whan &thorn;at his lordes wif preide him of velanye; whan he seide; Lo my lady howe my lorde ha&thorn;e take to me vnder my warde al &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e in &thorn;is werlde ne no&thorn;inge of his oute of my powere bot onely &yogh;e &thorn;at bien his wyf [881] &para; And howe schold .I. &thorn;an do &thorn;is wikkednesse &amp; sinne so orrible a&yogh;eines god; god it for-bede &para; Alas al to litel is suche treu&thorn;e no wey founde; [882] &para; &thorn;e &thorn;redde harme is &thorn;e fel&thorn;e &thorn;oruhe whiche &thorn;ei breken &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> commandement of god. &amp; defoulen &thorn;e autere of here matrimoygne &thorn;at is criste; [883] &para; For certes in so muche &thorn;at &thorn;e sacrament of Mariage is so noble &amp; so digne So muche it is &thorn;e gretter sinne for to breke it; &para; For god maad mariage in paradise; in &thorn;estate of Innocence to multeplie mankynde to &thorn;e seruice <MILESTONE N="249b" UNIT="folio">of god; [884] &amp; &thorn;erfore is &thorn;e brekeinge &thorn;ere-of greuous; Of whiche brekeynge comme&thorn; fals heires often time &thorn;at wrongefully occupien o&thorn;er mennes heritage; And &thorn;ere fore wil criste put 
<PB REF="00000711.tif" N="679"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="665"> hem oute of &thorn;e Regne of heven &thorn;at is &thorn;e herytage to good folke [885] Of &thorn;is brekeinge comme&thorn;e eke oft times &thorn;at folke vnware wedden or sinnen wi&thorn; here owen kynred; &amp; namely &thorn;il harlotes &thorn;at hanten bordels; Of &thorn;es foole wemmen &thorn;at maie bu likned to a comune gonge where as men purgen here ordur; [886] what saie we eke of poytours &thorn;at lyuen bi &thorn;e orrible sinne of puytrye And constreyned wemmen &yogh;e somme time his owen wif; or his childe as done &thorn;es baudes to &yogh;elden hem a serteine rente of her bodely putrye &para; Certes &thorn;es bien cursed sinnes; [887] &para; Vnderstande&thorn; eke &thorn;at aduoutre is sette gladly in &thorn;e ten commandementes; by-tuex &thorn;eft &amp; man|slawhter For it is &thorn;e gretest &thorn;eft &thorn;at may be; For it is &thorn;e &thorn;efte of body &amp; soule; [888] &amp; it is ylike homicide for it kerue&thorn;e a tuo; &amp; breke&thorn; atuo hem &thorn;at first weren ymaked o flesche And &thorn;ere-fore by &thorn;e olde lawe &thorn;ei scholde be sleyne; [889] &para; Bot na&thorn;eles be &thorn;e lawe of ihesu crist &thorn;at is &thorn;e lawe of pite whan he seide to &thorn;e womman &thorn;at was fou[n]den in aduoutre; and scholde haue slawe with stones after &thorn;e will of &thorn;e Iewes as was her lawe; &para; Go quod ihesu criste &amp; haue no more will to do sinne; or willen no more to do sinne; [890] So&thorn;ely &thorn;e vengeance of advoutre is awarded to &thorn;e peyne of hell; bot it bue distroubled be penance. [891] &para; &yogh;ette bien &thorn;ere mo spyces of &thorn;is cursed sinne as whan &thorn;at one of hem is religious or elles bo&thorn;e; Or of folke &thorn;at bien entred vnto order as subdecane &amp; deken; or preste or hospitaleres; And euer &thorn;e hyer &thorn;at he is in ordre &thorn;e gretter is &thorn;e sinne; [892] &para; &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at gretely agregen his sinne is &thorn;e brekeinge of his avowe of chastite whan he receyue&thorn; ordre [893] &para; And for&thorn;ere ouere so&thorn;e is &thorn;at holy holy ordere is chef of al &thorn;e tresoure of god; &amp; his especial sinne &amp; merke of chastite to schewe &thorn;at &thorn;ei bien Ioyned to chastite; whiche &thorn;at is &thorn;e most precious lif &thorn;at is [894] &para; And eke &thorn;es ordred folke bien specialy titlyd to god; = &amp; of &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000712.tif" N="680"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="666"> special meyne of god; = ffor whiche whan &thorn;ei done dedely sinne &thorn;ei bien &thorn;e special traytours of god &amp; of his peple; for &thorn;e leven of &thorn;e peple to preie for &thorn;e peple; &para; And while &thorn;ere biene suche traitours Here preyer&yogh; availe&thorn; nouht to &thorn;e peple [895] &para; Pristes bien as aungels as by &thorn;e dignete of here mysterie; ffor so&thorn;e seint Poule sei&thorn;e; &thorn;at Sathanas transforme&thorn;e him in Angel of lihte; [896] &para; So&thorn;elye &thorn;e preste &thorn;at haunte&thorn; sinne may bue lykned to &thorn;e angel of derkenesse transformed in &thorn;e Angel of lyht; &para; He seme&thorn; an Angel of liht; Bot for so&thorn;e he is an Angell of derknesse [897] &para; Suche prestes bien &thorn;e sonnes of of Belye. As schewe&thorn;e in &thorn;e boke of Kynges &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren &thorn;e sonnes of belial &thorn;at is &thorn;e deuel; [898] Belyall is to seyne withowten Iuge; &amp; so faren &thorn;ei hem &thorn;enken &thorn;ei bien fre &amp; han none Iuge no more &thorn;an ha&thorn;e a fre boll &thorn;at take&thorn; whiche kowe &thorn;at him like&thorn; in &thorn;e toune; [899] so faren &thorn;ei bue wymmen; ffor riht as a fre boll is ynouhe for al a toune <MILESTONE N="250a" UNIT="folio">Riht so is a wykked priste corruped ynowhe for al a parische or al a contre // [900] &thorn;es prestes as seine &thorn;e boke ne konne nouht mynisterye of prestehode to &thorn;e peple; ne god ne knowe&thorn; hem nouht; &thorn;ei ne halde hem not apaide as sei&thorn;e &thorn;e boke of so&thorn;en flesche &thorn;at was to hem offred; &para; Bot &thorn;ei toke be force &thorn;e flesche &thorn;at is rowe; [901] Certes riht so &thorn;es schrewes ne holden hem nou&yogh;t apaiede of Roste flesche &amp; so&thorn;en flesche wi&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> whiche &thorn;e peple fedden hem in grete reuerence; Bot &thorn;ei woll haue rowe flesche as mennes wyves &amp; here douhtern; [902] And certes &thorn;es wemmen &thorn;at consenten to here harlotries done grete wronges to criste &amp; to holy chirche &amp; to all halowes &amp; to al sowels; ffor &thorn;ei be-reven al &thorn;es him &thorn;at schold worschipen criste &amp; holy cherche &amp; pray fo[r] all cristen sowles; [903] And &thorn;erfore haue suche prestes &amp; here lemmans eke &thorn;at consenten to here lycherye &thorn;e malison of &thorn;e courte cristen til &thorn;ei comme to amendement. 
<PB REF="00000713.tif" N="681"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="667"> [904] &para; &thorn;e &thorn;red spice of aduoutre is sumtime betwene a man &amp; his wif &amp; &thorn;at is whan &thorn;ei taken no rewarde in here assemblynge bot onely in his ffleschely delite as sei&thorn; seinte Ierom; [905] &amp; ne reken of no&thorn;inge bot att &thorn;ei bien assembled be cause &thorn;ei bien ymaride; al is good ynouhe as &thorn;inke&thorn; to hem; [906] Bot in suche folk ha&thorn;e &thorn;e deuel pouere as seide &thorn;e Angel Raphael to thobie. = ffor in hire assemblynge &thorn;ei puten oute iheus criste of here hert &amp; &yogh;aff hem self to al ordour [907] &para; &thorn;e fer&thorn;e spice is &thorn;e assemblynge of hem &thorn;at bien of her kinrede or of hem &thorn;at bien of one affinite or elles wi&thorn; hem; with whiche hire fadres or here kinred ha&thorn;e deled wy&thorn;&thorn;e inne &thorn;e sinne of licherie; &thorn;is sinne make&thorn; hem like houndes &thorn;at taken no kepe of kinred; [908] &para; And certes Parentela is in tuo maners ow&thorn;er gostely; o&thorn;ere flesslye; Gostly as for to delen wi&thorn; her gossebes. [909] For riht so as he . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> is his godfader; he is his fader spirituele; For whiche a womman maie in no lesse sinne assemble wi&thorn; hire gossib &thorn;at with hire owen ffleschely bro&thorn;ere; [910] &para; &thorn;e fifte spice is &thorn;ilke abhomynable sinne of whiche &thorn;at no man vnne&thorn;es ouht write or speke; &para; Ne&thorn;eles it is openly rehersed in holy writte; [911] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> to speke of orrible sinne; certes holy writte may not bue defoulede nomore &thorn;an &thorn;e sonne &thorn;at schine&thorn; on a mexen. [912] &para; Ano&thorn;ere sinne &thorn;at pertine&thorn; to licherye &thorn;at comme&thorn; in slepeinge; &amp; &thorn;is sinne comme&thorn; oft to hem &thorn;at biene maydens; And eke to hem &thorn;at bien corrupt &para; &amp; &thorn;is sinne men clepen pollucione &thorn;at comme&thorn; in .iiij. maners; [913] somme time of a languysseinge of bodye for &thorn;e humers bien to rank &amp; abundant in &thorn;e body of a man; Sumtyme for &thorn;e infermete for &thorn;e feblenesse of &thorn;e vertue retentif as phisik make&thorn; mencion; Somtim for forfete of mete &amp; drinke; [914] And sume time for 
<PB REF="00000714.tif" N="682"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="668"> violence &thorn;ouhtes &thorn;at bien enclosed in mannes mynde whan he go&thorn;e to slepe whiche may not bue with outen sinne; For whiche he may no&yogh;t kepe him wiselye; or elles maie men sinne ful greuously</P>
